<HEADLINE>
CHANG BEATS INJURED GAMBILL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By STEVE DILBECK  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- Michael Chang was trying ever so hard to appear
the impassive little warrior, consistent in both game and demeanor.
</P>
<P>
   Yet not even the often-stolid Chang could keep his whirl of
emotions inside after winning his first tournament title in 21
months Sunday when he captured the Mercedes-Benz Cup.
</P>
<P>
   Chang, tennis' one-time boy wonder who almost had fallen into
the ATP netherworld, was comparing tennis to life in overcoming
obstacles during a postgame interview broadcast throughout the Los
Angeles Tennis Center when the facade crumbled.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you're down, you have to pick yourself back up ...''
</P>
<P>
   And then his voice cracked and he grew silent, momentarily
overcome and unable to continue.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's emotional for me,'' he said. ``The last couple of years
have been tough.''
</P>
<P>
   So tough that Chang, 28, ranked third in the world at the end of
the 1997 season had fallen as low as No.76 two years later.
</P>
<P>
   So tough that even winning Sunday 6-7 (2-7), 6-3, ret. - when
Jan-Michael Gambill was forced to retire with a sprained ankle
after they split the first two sets - could not abate his
uncharacteristic momentary lapse of control.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't remember the last time I was that emotional,'' Chang
said later. ``Maybe the '89 French Open.''
</P>
<P>
   That would be when he won his Grand Slam at age 17, announcing
to all that the world's next great tennis phenom had arrived. Chang
would go on to win 33 ATP titles, but it was almost two years
before he found his way to No. 34.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is pretty special for me,'' Chang said.
</P>
<P>
   For the Mercedes-Benz Cup, Gambill's injury default was a
fitting ending to a frustrating week of no-shows, injuries and
ejections that had all but stripped the tournament of the game's
big names.
</P>
<P>
   Gambill was just back from the losing U.S. Davis Cup effort in
Spain and had been playing non-stop tennis for almost three months.
Tendinitis started bothering his left knee this week, flared up
again in his semifinal victory over Arnaud Clement on Saturday
night, and then grew worse later when he returned to play three
sets of doubles.
</P>
<P>
   He frequently appeared in pain during the early going Sunday,
but his booming serve - he had 16 aces in the two sets - kept him
in the opening set, until it overpowered Chang in the tiebreaker
7-6 (7-2).
</P>
<P>
   In the second set, Chang's consistency began to wear Gambill and
his knee down. Chang was leading 3-2 when he broke Gambill for the
only time all afternoon. With Chang up 5-3 in the set's ninth game,
Gambill was leading 40-15 and threatening to return the service
break, when he went high for an overhead smash.
</P>
<P>
   Chang scrambled and returned brilliantly to win the point, while
Gambill collapsed in front of the net with a right ankle sprain.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was favoring the left leg and just came down on (my right)
wrong,'' Gambill said. ``I heard it pop. I'd never heard anything
in my body pop before.''
</P>
<P>
   Gambill took an injury timeout, had the ankle taped and tried to
return, but was suddenly reduced to an arthritic old man at age 23.
The only weapon he had left was his serve, but Chang held on to
take the second set 6-3.
</P>
<P>
   Gambill then limped over to the umpire, and recognizing what all
could already tell, and said he couldn't continue.
</P>
<P>
   Chang had won his first tournament since Shanghai in October of
1998, and back in his old hometown.
</P>
<P>
   ``For me to finally be able to break through here in L.A., is
very special,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   And even emotional.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
