<HEADLINE>
HITTING A HIGH NOTE 
</HEADLINE>
 COLUMN-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN SHAUGHNESSY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   OAKLAND, Calif. _ The pale young girl in the wheelchair was
sobbing uncontrollably, so Nomar Garciaparra came over and gave her
a baseball.
</P>
<P>
   Hardly anyone saw it. And the tiny gift was of no consequence
when the Oakland A's went on to beat the Red Sox, 5-2, Sunday
afternoon. But it was a gesture of infinite grace and kindness.
</P>
<P>
   It was something Ted Williams would have done in his prime. In
fact, I'm beginning to wonder about Nomar and Ted. Same
Mexican-American/Southern California heritage. Same .400
flirtation. Same disdain for the media. Same haircuts. Same
affinity for kids _ especially kids who struggle with sickness and
disability.
</P>
<P>
   Sixteen-year-old Amy Giffin has cerebral palsy. So imagine the
bravery it took for her to stand in front of 29,847 fans and sing
our national anthem a cappella before Sunday's game.
</P>
<P>
   She stood with the aid of a large chrome walker. She hit all the
high notes. After ``our flag was still there,'' the gentle,
supportive Bay Area folk started to applaud and carried her right
through ``the home of the brave.''
</P>
<P>
   Finished with her performance, Amy dissolved into tears and
collapsed into the arms of her mom. Amy's parents helped her into
her wheelchair as fans took their seats and the umpires came out
for the exchange of lineup cards. Relieved it was over, Amy
couldn't stop crying.
</P>
<P>
   Jimy Williams was first to visit Amy from the Sox dugout.
</P>
<P>
   ``You did great,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Amy's parents were set to steer her wheelchair off the field
when a second voice said, ``Wait, wait, wait.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It was Nomar,'' said Amy's dad, Marty. ``He came around from
behind us and gave Amy a baseball and said, `Great job.' ''
</P>
<P>
   There are ceremonial first-ball tossers and anthem singers
almost every day and night at every ballpark in the major leagues.
They are easily ignored in the everyday rush to get ready for a
ballgame. Players are stretching, putting resin on bats, arranging
batting gloves and helmets, and lining their pockets with sunflower
seeds. They are required to stand and remove their hats during the
anthem, but no one says they have to acknowledge the performer when
it's over.
</P>
<P>
   This was special. It was a courageous teen, battling a lifelong
affliction (Amy weighed 2 pounds at birth), needing a lift after an
emotional performance.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was nervous, but once I got out there, I was like, `OK, I
can do this,' '' said Amy. ``Near the end, I didn't realize the
fans were all cheering for me. I was like, `Wait, I'm not done
yet.' Those high notes are brutal. Then people were saying, `Good
job,' and shaking my hand and I kind of blocked out what they were
saying.''
</P>
<P>
   Shaking his head and smiling after the game, Nomar said, ``She
was good, man.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Win or lose, that might have been the most important part of
the day,'' said Williams. ``To see her out there standing with that
roller thing. Then listening to her and seeing what she did
afterward. I think those were tears of happiness.''
</P>
<P>
   The late Tom Dowd, former traveling secretary of the Red Sox,
used to accompany Ted Williams on his countless secret visits to
Children's Hospital in Boston. Offering a description of Williams
and his teammates delivering a ball and chatting up a
cancer-stricken boy, Dowd said, ``In those moments, the kid was
whole again. He was one of them, there with his heroes in a
beautiful world.''
</P>
<P>
   That is the power of fame. Small acts of kindness take on
enormous significance for the recipients.
</P>
<P>
   Early Sunday afternoon, more than an hour after the
nerve-wracking anthem, Amy was sitting in upper deck section 224
with her parents. In the bottom of the fifth inning _ holding her
autographed baseball _ Amy watched as Garciaparra went deep into
the hole, backhanded a hard-hopper by Randy Velarde, and fired a
125-foot throw to first, beating Velarde by a half step.
Garciaparra's momentum carried him almost to the A's bullpen mound.
It was a sensational play.
</P>
<P>
   But it was not the best thing he did all day.
</P>
<P>
   He may hit .400 this year. He may win the Most Valuable Player
Award and lead the Red Sox to their first World Series victory
since 1918. But nothing Nomar does in 2000 will surpass this small
gesture of kindness, which hardly anybody saw, in a pregame
ceremony in Oakland before the 101st game of the Red Sox' regular
season.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
