<HEADLINE>
RED SOX, ARROJO WALK THE PLANK 
</HEADLINE>
 SOX-ATHLETICS-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB HOHLER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   OAKLAND, Calif. _ Ken Burns could narrate this chapter of
baseball lore. A guy making $11 a month to play baseball in Cuba
defects to the United States and becomes a millionaire major
leaguer.
</P>
<P>
   Meet Luis Rolando Arrojo.
</P>
<P>
   Another kid scraps his way out of Chicago, barely makes the
bigs, and hits .219 until Kansas City ships him to Oakland this
spring for a player to be named later and $1.
</P>
<P>
   Meet Salvatore Frank Fasano.
</P>
<P>
   Their journeys brought them 60 feet 6 inches from each other
Sunday, and it was Oakland's dollar-store catcher who spoiled the
millionaire-in-exile's Red Sox debut, as Fasano touched Arrojo for
two home runs, including a grand slam, in Boston's 5-2 loss to the
A's before 29,847 at Network Associates Coliseum.
</P>
<P>
   But Fasano's outburst was not all that separated the teams as
they raced for playoff spots. Arrojo, in his first start since the
Sox acquired him last week in a seven-player swap with Colorado,
hurt his cause by issuing three walks before Fasano's slam. And the
Red Sox again mustered only minuscule production while Carl
Everett, their suspended home run and RBI leader, watched from the
bench.
</P>
<P>
   The Sox are 2-4 with Everett on the sideline. They scored only
three runs in back-to-back losses to the A's after winning the
first two games of the series.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's not many games where we don't miss him,'' said
designated hitter Scott Hatteberg, who homered for one of Boston's
two runs Sunday. ``He's huge. I think we can score runs without
him, but it's tough. A lot of the pressure falls on guys who aren't
used to feeling the pressure.''
</P>
<P>
   Jason Varitek homered for the other Boston run. But the Sox
never waged a serious rally as Oakland's Gil Heredia (13-7) and
three relievers scattered six hits and one walk.
</P>
<P>
   ``For us to win, it has to come from different people,'' Varitek
said. ``Look at what Fasano did for them.'
</P>
<P>
   The unlikeliest of heroes, Fasano is a career .219 hitter who
has never hit more than eight home runs in a season and had a
lifetime batting average against the Sox of .111. What's more, he
had seen Arrojo pitch and wanted no part of him.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's why I was so shocked at what happened,'' Fasano said.
``Because when I've seen him pitch, I've thought, `Man, I don't
want to face this guy.' ''
</P>
<P>
   But with the bases loaded and two outs in the second inning,
Fasano popped an Arrojo slider for his first career grand slam.
``He was trying to throw a nasty and he made a mistake with it,''
Fasano said. ``It's unfortunate for him, but it's good for me.''
</P>
<P>
   The slam was Oakland's 10th of the season, two shy of the major
league record shared by Cleveland and Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Arrojo was less rueful about the homer than he was the walks
that preceded it. ``He doesn't think he lost with the home run,''
said Pedro Martinez, acting as interpreter for the Spanish-speaking
Arrojo. ``He lost with the three bases on balls he gave up.''
</P>
<P>
   Take away the five walks he issued _ and the two homers by
Fasano _ and Arrojo was all Sox general manager Dan Duquette was
seeking. He allowed only one other hit, a harmless single, and
struck out four in 6 1/3 innings.
</P>
<P>
   Relievers Rheal Cormier and Hipolito Pichardo held the A's
hitless the rest of the way.
</P>
<P>
   But the walks, as they say in Pitching 101, will kill you, as
Jeff Fassero was reminded in Saturday night's 12-1 loss. Pitching
coach Joe Kerrigan noted that eight of the 13 A's who drew walks in
the last two games scored. ``And that's it in a nutshell,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Kerrigan said before the game he stressed to Arrojo, through
interpreter Rich Garces, the importance of throwing his first
pitches for strikes. He said the A's, who are second in the
American League in drawing walks, swung at the first pitch only
four times Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the whole series, they had only one hit on the 67
first-pitch strikes we threw,'' Kerrigan said. ``It shows they're
not aggressive on the first pitch, and we tried to use that to our
favor, but . . .''
</P>
<P>
   It didn't happen. Kerrigan said Arrojo's wildness may have
sprung from being nervous in his first Red Sox start. But Arrojo
disagreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``He wasn't nervous,'' Martinez said. ``He was probably rushing
a little bit with his mechanics.''
</P>
<P>
   Arrojo, an All-Star in 1998 when he was 14-12 with Tampa Bay,
went 0-for-July, winless in five starts with the Rockies and one
for Boston. He is 5-10 overall this year. But he said he was proud
to wear the Red Sox uniform.
</P>
<P>
   ``He felt big pitching out there with this team,'' Martinez
said. ``This is a team with a lot of history and it's now his turn
to be part of that history.''
</P>
<P>
   Red Sox fans are hoping it's a good part.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
