<HEADLINE>
BELICHICK, PATRIOTS READY TO RAISE CURTAIN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NICK CAFARDO  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CANTON, Ohio _ Perhaps someone should change the name of this
place to Debut City.
</P>
<P>
   With Monday night's Hall of Fame game between the Patriots and
San Francisco 49ers, Dennis Miller and Dan Fouts debut in the ABC
``Monday Night Football'' broadcast booth; Bill Belichick debuts as
Patriots coach and makes his first return to Ohio as a head coach
since being fired by the Cleveland Browns following the 1995
season; the Patriots debut their new uniforms, road whites with
blue pants; and Jeff Garcia debuts as the first No. 1 quarterback
of the 49ers other than Joe Montana and Steve Young in 21 years.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the overriding concern of Belichick and 49ers coach Steve
Mariucci is that the game be injury-free. Both teams, which already
are banged up, need only look at Saturday night's Jets-Saints game
for an example of how bad it can get. The Saints likely lost
cornerback Steve Israel (broken leg) and tight end Cam Cleeland
(torn Achilles' tendon) for the season, and safety Rob Kelly
(broken leg) for up to six weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to be a little thin, but we're going to get a good
look at our rookies and rookie free agents and get a very good
evaluation of them,'' Mariucci said Sunday night following the
49ers' walk-through practice at Fawcett Stadium. ``This is going to
be a little different for us because we now have probably the
youngest team in the league. We used to have a lot of veterans, and
sure, any coach would love to have Hall of Famers all over the
field, but that's not what we're faced with.''
</P>
<P>
   Belichick was so concerned earlier this week he canceled a
scrimmage against the New York Giants. The concern has been
alleviated slightly because his young, raw offensive linemen have
made steady improvement in practice. But practice is practice. This
is not a ``real'' game, but it's a close facsimile, an exhibition
on national TV in which the players should be motivated to play at
their best.
</P>
<P>
   The pressing questions surround the young offensive line, which
consists of Jason Andersen at left tackle, Derrick Fletcher at left
guard, Damien Woody at center, Adam Davis at right guard, and Greg
Robinson-Randall at right tackle.
</P>
<P>
   Belichick, who put his team through a one-hour walk-through
Sunday &UR;  &LR; night, heaped praise on his young linemen last week. He's
built up Fletcher and Robinson-Randall, both of whom have looked
very poised.
</P>
<P>
   Belichick takes great pride in bringing along young linemen, as
does offensive coordinator Charlie Weis. Last season in New York,
Weis started youngsters Randy Thomas and Jason Fabini. Experienced
defensive linemen will have field days early in the season, as did
the Patriots' Willie McGinest against Fabini in last year's season
opener. The hope is the young linemen develop and eventually win
more battles than they lose.
</P>
<P>
   The Indianapolis Colts certainly experienced this in 1997, when
they started rookies Aaron Meadows and Tarik Glenn. Now the two
tackles protect their quarterback (Peyton Manning) as well as
anyone. Whether the Patriots' young linemen are as talented as
Meadows and Glenn is still very much in question, and the
exhibition games, particularly when they're up against
first-teamers, will tell how far they have to go.
</P>
<P>
   Mariucci will start a defense that will be missing numerous
veterans, including end Anthony Pleasant, left tackle Bryant Young,
right tackle Junior Bryant, left outside linebacker Julian
Peterson, left linebacker Ken Norton Jr., right linebacker Winfred
Tubbs, and strong safety Lance Schulters, all of whom have injury
or practice time concerns.
</P>
<P>
   Patriots backup quarterback Michael Bishop should get a chance
to show his stuff, too. Drew Bledsoe is expected to take only about
a dozen snaps.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's my chance to show people what I can do,'' said Bishop,
taken in the seventh round of last year's draft. ``A lot of guys
have been drafted in front of me, but if I get the chance maybe
people will find out that they made a mistake not taking me. I'd
like to prove people wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   Bishop is exciting because of his scrambling capabilities, but
he's been more contained in practice this year, looking to pass
first. The Patriots have some Bishop-friendly plays, including some
option plays at the goal line.
</P>
<P>
   ``Both teams are in the same boat,'' said Mariucci. ``We're both
trying new players. We both have injury concerns, but I expect a
hard-fought game and hopefully we can put on a good show for the
people who come out here.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
