<SLUG> BC-FBN-49ERS-RICE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RICE ISN'T LOOKING FOR RESTING PLACE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MADDEN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CANTON, Ohio _ Jerry Rice was on the sideline of Fawcett
Stadium, home of the McKinley High School Bulldogs, the Timkin High
School Trojans, and the Glenoak High School Golden Eagles. And Rice
was being mobbed by hundreds and hundreds of fans.
</P>
<P>
   A high school field, yes, but a football field only a large hill
and a hundred yards from the Pro Football Hall of Fame. Rice is
here to play against the Patriots Monday night but his permanent
home in a few years will be down the hillside and in the Hall of
Fame.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone knows it.
</P>
<P>
   The thousands of fans who waited and waited late on a Sunday
afternoon, sitting through a torrential thunderstorm to see Rice,
know it. San Francisco coach Steve Mariucci knows it. All football
fans know it. Jerry Rice knows it.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he could picture himself in the building across the
way, Rice said, ``You'll never get that out of me. Never.''
</P>
<P>
   Jerry Rice is 37 and in his 16th year with the 49ers. His limber
body does not look the part but what can't be escaped is that for
the first time in his career, Rice is starting the exhibition
season without Joe Montana or Steve Young throwing him passes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a big difference not having those guys here,'' Rice said,
``because just having those guys on the field was special for us,
and special for the fans. They're really missed. But I can always
look back at the old times. And I can smile about that.''
</P>
<P>
   Even without Young or Montana at quarterback, Rice insisted on
playing more football for the 49ers. He wasn't sure how it would
feel when he signed a three-year contract during the offseason, but
now that he's taken the field without Young or Montana, Rice feels
the difference.
</P>
<P>
   ``It feels like a different era,'' said Rice. ``And, you know,
it seems like how Joe stated it in his speech Saturday, that now he
has a new team.'' And that's how Rice feels, that he's still a
member of the 49ers but now he has a new team.
</P>
<P>
   But now that camp has started, his approach has not changed,
said Rice. ``I'm approaching camp the way I've always approached
training camp _ and that is to work hard to make the team.''
</P>
<P>
   That's been a given on the great 49er teams of the past and most
certainly a given on this young, green team that faces a grim, grim
season. San Francisco may be battling New Orleans to escape the
cellar of the NFC West.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just a bunch of young guys here and a couple of older
guys,'' Rice said of his team, ``and we're just out there to try
and win some football games.''
</P>
<P>
   Rice, of course, is one of those ``older guys.'' Sixteen years
ago, the Patriots _ among other teams _ passed on drafting the
receiver who had all the huge numbers at little-known Mississippi
Valley State. And if Rice couldn't catch a cold, let alone a pass,
early in his first year with the 49ers, he soon developed into
perhaps the greatest receiver ever.
</P>
<P>
   But Montana was throwing him passes then. And Saturday, Rice
watched on television as Montana was inducted into the Hall of
Fame.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was just enjoying it all, seeing so many people from the
49ers (inducted were former teammates Ronnie Lott and Montana, with
former 49er owner Eddie DeBartolo presenting Montana) and seeing so
many 49er fans. I mean, it was crowded and everybody was really
excited. And it felt really good to see.''
</P>
<P>
   Rice then turned and began a slow march along the stands of the
high school stadium, signing autograph after autograph, the fans in
a constant chorus of ``Jerry, Jerry, Jerry.''
</P>
<P>
   Mariucci was in the middle of the field taking it all in.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jerry loves this, he's good at it, and he deserves it,'' said
the coach. ``Steve (Young) is going in (to the Hall of Fame) next,
just because of the timing, and then Jerry is in. You know that.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course.
</P>
<P>
   And so do the fans.
</P>
<P>
   Once Rice and the 49ers left the high school field, a couple of
Frisbee-catching dogs entertained the crowd until the Patriots took
the field for their practice. By then, about two-thirds of the fans
had left. They had seen Jerry Rice close to the Pro Football Hall
of Fame, a few years before they'll see him enter it.
</P>
<P>
   Mariucci was right. They knew that.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
