<HEADLINE>
M'S MANUFACTURE VICTORY OVER TORONTO 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN HICKEY  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ The Mariners' attempt to trade for Detroit slugger
Juan Gonzalez came crashing down Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners' attempt to win another series, on the other hand,
was a rousing success.
</P>
<P>
   Seattle dipped into its bag of tricks to score 10 runs on just
five hits, getting on base in a manner designed to frustrate and
confound the Blue Jays in a 10-6 win over Toronto. The Mariners
walked 11 times, got hit by a pitch once and turned six of those 12
free trips to first base into runs.
</P>
<P>
   The Tigers and the Mariners talked twice Sunday, and after the
first conversation between Tigers' general manager Randy Smith and
the Mariners' Pat Gillick, the Mariners had reason to believe they
could get a deal done for two-time MVP Gonzalez.
</P>
<P>
   The deal was on solid enough footing that a call went to Class
AAA Tacoma to hold right-handed pitcher Joel Pineiro out of his
scheduled start for the Rainiers last night. But after the second
call, word out of both camps was that the deal had ground to a
halt.
</P>
<P>
   The stumbling block? Gillick said, ``we couldn't come to a
meeting of minds'' with Detroit. From the Tigers' view, however,
the Mariners' reluctance to part with any of Seattle's best talent
torpedoed the trade.
</P>
<P>
   From the first, the Tigers were told that pitchers Freddy
Garcia, Gil Meche and Ryan Anderson were not tradable. When Detroit
asked about infielder Carlos Guillen, the Mariners said he wasn't
available.
</P>
<P>
   Gillick wouldn't move and Smith said he needed more to justify
the trade of Gonzalez. End of deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``You listen to what they say, but they've got to give up what
we think is good value,'' Smith said. ``I don't anticipate talking
to them again (about Gonzalez).''
</P>
<P>
   Sunday's five-hit game underscored why the Mariners feel they
needed a Gonzalez-type slugger. But it also underscored why the
Mariners are in first place in the West, four games in front. The
Mariners worked their way on base with patience and guile, then
manufactured runs without big hits.
</P>
<P>
   True, Jay Buhner had a huge two-run homer in the third and Alex
Rodriguez had a solo shot in the fifth, but the Mariners got one
run home on an infield out, one on an error and two on sacrifice
flies.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first number on the scoreboard (runs) is the only one that
counts,'' center fielder Mike Cameron said. ``Look at us. We always
have a lot of guys on base. Baseball is about what you do with men
in scoring position, and we are patient. We almost always have lots
of men on base.''
</P>
<P>
   Cameron has walked 47 times, including once Sunday. On the Blue
Jays, that would be good for third on the team, behind the Jays'
No. 2 walks man, Jose Cruz Jr. On the Mariners, however, there are
five players with more walks than Cameron _ John Olerud (77), Alex
Rodriguez (62), Mark McLemore (61), Edgar Martinez (57) and Jay
Buhner (51).
</P>
<P>
   And that doesn't even count Rickey Henderson, No. 2 on the
all-time walks list with 2,032, including a Mariners-record-tying
five Sunday. Henderson has 35 for Seattle, but he had 24 with the
Mets before joining Seattle, so he has 59.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you have five or six guys drawing all those walks, it
starts to add up,'' Cameron said. ``All you need then is a couple
of big hits.''
</P>
<P>
   Buhner's was the biggest on this day, coming at the end of a
five-run third. David Bell was hit by a pitch and Henderson had
drawn the second of his walks to open the inning. With one out,
Toronto left fielder Rob Ducey dropped the ball on what would have
been a nice running catch of a Rodriguez fly ball near the line.
That scored one run. Edgar Martinez made it 2-0 with a single and
Olerud's grounder made it 3-0 before Buhner crushed his 19th homer
to deep left.
</P>
<P>
   Three more walks in the seventh loaded the bases and chased
Toronto starter Kelvim Escobar. Olerud delivered an opposite field
double, slipping the ball past third baseman Tony Batista for two
more runs in what would be a three-run inning.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's all about patience at the plate,'' manager Lou Piniella
said. ``We've shown that we have that.''
</P>
<P>
   They have the wins to prove it.
</P>
<P>
   P-I reporter John Hickey can be reached at 206-448-8004
</P>
<P>
   or johnhickey &LR; seattle-pi.com
</P>
