<SLUG> BC-BBA-VECSEY-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHO NEEDS JUAN? BUHNER'S A STEADY POWER SOURCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By LAURA VECSEY  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Jay Buhner and the citizens of Marinerville had barely
come down off the high of Buhner's 300th career homer last Tuesday
when Old Man Bone launched another one Sunday _ No. 19 in a season
he didn't expect to be this darn good.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe Buhner was a dairy farmer in a former life. He's been
cranking at the creamery called Safeco lately.
</P>
<P>
   Creamin' 'em: That's the kind of stroke Buhner said he used the
other day after he took A's closer Jason Isringhausen deep,
crushing a 98-mph fastball to become 86th on baseball's all-time
homer list.
</P>
<P>
   It was an epic accomplishment for one of Seattle's most beloved
stars _ a 36-year-old Texan-turned-Northwesterner who has fought
off bum elbows, shoulders, hamstrings and ankles to return to
steady action this season.
</P>
<P>
   If this is a curtain call, Buhner has hardly lost his sense of
the dramatic.
</P>
<P>
   Then, as if the shackles of achieving this significant career
milestone had come flying off, Buhner rocketed another longball
Sunday, crushing a two-run homer in the third inning to help lead
the Mariners to a 10-5 victory over the Blue Jays.
</P>
<P>
   Just when talk of how much the Mariners need some added punch in
the lineup heats up, Buhner ramps up his power stick, fanning the
flames of love and loyalty for the bald-headed man who is now the
longest-tenured Mariner outside of Edgar Martinez.
</P>
<P>
   The power surge made it a little more ironic that a
rent-a-player outfielder whose services were sought and discussed
by the Mariners Sunday was none other than Juan Gonzalez.
</P>
<P>
   If we scoffed at talk of bringing back David Segui or wondered
about the Royals' willingness to deal Johnny Damon, the name Juan
Gonzalez is enough to inspire.
</P>
<P>
   What price the Mariners are willing to pay for Gonzalez _ or
anyone else still on the block _ remains to be seen, but at least
Buhner knew his price.
</P>
<P>
   The M's and Tigers talked twice Sunday about Gonzalez. By the
time the Mariners had beaten Toronto and were back in their
clubhouse, relaxing and waiting and watching rumors fly on TV,
Buhner had made up his mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not giving him my number, I'll tell you that. I'll give
him some playing time but not the number. They'll have to release
me if they promise him that,'' Buhner said.
</P>
<P>
   The right fielder who wears No. 19 and who has become a Seattle
institution in the 12 years he has played here was at ground zero
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Buhner had to compute the ramifications of the M's possibly
adding another high profile right fielder who wears No. 19 and who
has spent productive seasons winning division titles in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are some things that could be done, I suppose. I know
Rickey (Henderson) bought his number off Turner Ward when he was
traded to the Blue Jays. Rickey bought him a Rolex. I don't need a
Rolex. A fishing boat, maybe. A 22-footer. But I'm not giving him
the number.''
</P>
<P>
   In the trade game, which ends this afternoon when major league
baseball declares its deadline at 1 p.m. PST Monday, there are
always hitches.
</P>
<P>
   The logistics of number swapping are usually minor details,
which Buhner understands and which is why he could afford to
chuckle _ not that he wasn't serious about denying Gonzalez any
access to the beloved No. 19.
</P>
<P>
   Of greater importance, though, is how much fleecing the Mariners
are willing to have done to them in order to bring in a big bopper
like Juan Gone and how will such a move impact the team.
</P>
<P>
   Buhner said he found it curious that the Mets were able to bring
in guys like Bubba Trammell, Rick White and Mike Bordick in a hurry
this weekend while all around baseball, general managers in places
like Kansas City and Detroit are trying to hold up the Mariners for
a fleet of pitching prospects.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe it has to do with the way the Mariners used to trade away
talent to get some hired help for the stretch drive, Buhner
suggested.
</P>
<P>
   ``It makes you wonder sometimes,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But this time, with Pat Gillick calling the shots, the feeling
throughout the Mariners clubhouse is that if a big deal gets done
before tonight's game against the Red Sox, it's going to be for the
right part, for the right reasons, without selling off everyone
named Ryan Anderson, Gil Meche and Carlos Guillen.
</P>
<P>
   For Buhner, there was a twist of fate in all the talk Sunday
about Gonzalez. In his final year or so of action, Buhner would
like to ride all the way to the World Series. What a way to go out,
he said.
</P>
<P>
   If it means that it comes at the expense of his ability to
contribute, Buhner is OK with that.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have to accept it. I don't have to like it. But if it comes
to that, I'll accept. It will never come to be a cancer in the
clubhouse. It would never be like that. I think I'll get my playing
time and have a good season. I'll do whatever it takes for us to
win,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He'll share his position. He'll share his spotlight. The number
is non-negiotiable.
</P>
<P>
   P-I columnist Laura Vecsey can be reached at 206-448-8011
</P>
<P>
   or lauravecsey &LR; seattle-pi.com
</P>
