<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RADIATION-CANCER-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 NEW TECHNIQUES MEAN LESS RADIATION FOR CANCER PATIENTS  &HT;     By TOM ABATE 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Marybelle Riley sat in the hospital waiting room
making small talk, with a patch over one eye _ the one caught in
the grip of a virulent tumor that clutched at her optic nerve.
</P>
<P>
   ``The cancer is way up under here,'' said Riley, 89, brushing
her lower left eyelid.
</P>
<P>
   In a lead-lined room down the hall, technicians prepped the
computer-driven linear accelerator that would soon travel in a wide
arc over Riley's body. Along that path, it would emit hundreds of
high-energy X-ray bursts of varying intensity, following a firing
pattern calculated to disintegrate the tumor without damaging the
eye.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll be 90 in September,'' Riley said. ``I want to live and I
want to have my sight.''
</P>
<P>
   Riley has a fighting chance of getting both wishes, thanks to
the convergence of several advances _ including new ways to
pinpoint tumors, more precise X-ray guns, and computer-driven
treatment plans _ that enable radiation therapists to bombard
cancers while they tiptoe around sensitive nerves.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can now put higher doses of radiation into tumors than ever
before, and cut way down on the dose that hits the tissues you
don't want to affect,'' said Dr. Theodore Phillips, a radiation
oncologist at the University of California at San Francisco, where
Riley is being treated.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're using it in many locations,'' Phillips said. ``Head and
neck, prostate, lung, everywhere you have normal tissue that you
want to protect close to the tumor.''
</P>
<P>
   This new technique, called Intensity Modulated Radiotherapy
(IMRT), has moved from the experimental stage into clinical
practice in the past few years. But the procedure's high price and
complexity have made IMRT relatively rare in hospitals and not well
understood even among cancer professionals.
</P>
<P>
   IMRT will be discussed this week, when 2,700 cancer specialists
assemble in San Francisco for the annual meeting of the American
Head and Neck Society.
</P>
<P>
   Cancer fighters are a specialized breed. In addition to having
tumor specialties, such as head and neck, they take different
treatment approaches. Surgeons cut out tumors. Radiation
oncologists blast them with X-rays. Medical oncologists poison them
with chemotherapy.
</P>
<P>
   Increasingly, all three techniques are used in combination, but
a certain lack of understanding remains among experts in the three
approaches. Dr. Jesus Medina, a cancer surgeon and president of the
Head and Neck Society, said a seminar tomorrow morning will help
explain the new radiation therapies to practitioners of the other
cancer-fighting arts.
</P>
<P>
   Understanding state-of-the-art radiation therapy is complicated
by the fact that the advances are not the result a single
breakthrough, but the convergence of several developments,
beginning with some astonishing improvements in imaging
technologies that peer under the skin.
</P>
<P>
   ``The new imaging technologies allow us to distinguish the
normal tissues from the cancer cells with a precision that wasn't
possible even a few years ago,'' said Geoffrey Dalbow, a physicist
with Varian Medical Systems in Palo Alto, Calif., a leader in
radiation oncology systems.
</P>
<P>
   Dalbow said radiation oncologists use an array of imaging
techniques to get several different views of the tumor. Then they
assemble these data, using software programs, into a treatment plan
that drives the radiation gun.
</P>
<P>
   According to Dalbow, these images typically include CT or MRI
scans, which lay out the basic position of the organs inside the
body, showing the location of sensitive tissues in relation to the
tumor.
</P>
<P>
   To get a more precise fix on the tumor, physicians rely on
several technologies, including MRS scans. An MRS scan is a variant
of an MRI. Scientists have shown that certain molecules are found
in higher concentrations in cancer cells. MRS instruments detect
the magnetic signature of these molecules, and plot areas of
concentration, which equate with cancer hot spots.
</P>
<P>
   Other imaging systems are used to double-check tumor locations.
Because cancer cells are constantly growing and dividing, they
consume more of the body's basic fuel, glucose, than normal cells.
</P>
<P>
   To get a better understanding of the malignant tumor, cancer
specialists give patients a small dose of radioactive glucose and
measure which cells absorb the most of this nutrient. A technology
called SPECT detects the irradiated sugar. High concentrations
indicate tumor cells.
</P>
<P>
   With these imaging clues, radiation oncologists draw a tumor
target area, and decide how large a dose of radiation will be
needed to kill or control the cancer.
</P>
<P>
   These targeting techniques would be useless, however, were it
not for innovations that have improved the accuracy of radiation
guns, and allowed these instruments to be controlled by computer
programs that can plot and execute firing sequences of astonishing
complexity.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Mark Carol, a San Francisco
neurosurgeon-turned-entrepreneur, played a central role in these
advances in the early 1990s. By the time Carol entered the picture,
radiation guns had evolved into powerful instruments, which could
travel over the patient, delivering high-energy X-rays from
different angles.
</P>
<P>
   This swiveling feature was a big innovation because of the way
X-rays kill cancer. As the beams plow through the patient, they
break the DNA of any cell that is about to divide, killing it in
the process.
</P>
<P>
   Radiation treatment is particularly deadly to cancerous cells
because they are constantly dividing.
</P>
<P>
   However, X-rays are indiscriminate. They also kill fast-dividing
normal tissues such as stomach or skin cells. So hitting the cancer
from different angles lessens the damage to innocent cells that
happen to be in the path of the beam.
</P>
<P>
   Carol, who pioneered the IMRT technique, saw what was needed to
improve the previous generation of radiation therapy. There had to
be a way to modulate the intensity of the radiation beam. The
radiation guns of early '90s vintage had only two settings: off or
full-bore. They could not be controlled like a stove, which can be
turned up to boil water, but turned down low to melt butter.
</P>
<P>
   To solve this problem, Carol founded a company called Nomos
Corp., which came up an ingenious system that did two things:
First, it modulated the intensity of the radiation beam and, more
importantly, created a software program that made full use of the
modulation capabilities.
</P>
<P>
   According to Carol, by the early 1990s, radiation sources
already were routinely equipped with special lead shutters that
controlled the shape of the beam to conform to the shape of the
tumor.
</P>
<P>
   Nomos, which is based in Pennsylvania, adapted the shutter to a
new purpose. The company devised a way to open and close the
shutter rapidly. A longer shutter opening meant more radiation, a
brief opening meant a lower dose. In effect, Nomos created a switch
to control intensity.
</P>
<P>
   But the real genius of the system lay in the software Nomos
wrote to marry this intensity control to the targeting data, thus
creating a firing pattern that delivers maximum radiation to the
tumor while minimizing damage to innocent cells.
</P>
<P>
   The software involved some phenomenal calculations at the
crossroads of geometry and biology.
</P>
<P>
   The geometric component was the arc of the radiation gun as it
traveled over the patient. The biological variables were the types
of organs between the X-ray source and the tumor. Doctors have a
good idea how much radiation it takes to kill a tumor. They also
know how much radiation different types of healthy cells can absorb
before they suffer unacceptable harm.
</P>
<P>
   The program's job was to pick out the optimal path, ordering
long shutter openings when the imaging data showed the tumor
shielded by dense bone _ which can absorb more radiation without
undue damage. On the other hand, the program would close the
shutter when the X-ray gun passed over a sensitive spot such as
Marybelle Riley's eye.
</P>
<P>
   The program generated a firing pattern, which is loaded onto a
floppy disk, that could control the radiation gun the way a
perforated music sheet runs a player piano.
</P>
<P>
   Radiation oncologists who have used IMRT technology _ which is
new, expensive and rare _ say the results are worth it.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Richard Hoppe, chairman of the radiation oncology department
at Stanford University, said patients benefit from fewer side
effects. Treating head and neck cancers with radiation often means
killing saliva glands, and causing side-effects such as loss of
taste and tooth decay.
</P>
<P>
   ``With IMRT, you can reduce the dose to the salivary glands,
avoiding these complications,'' Hoppe said.
</P>
<P>
   A scientific paper written by cancer researchers Michael
Zelefsky and Steven Leibel of Memorial Sloan-Kettering Hospital
also suggests IMRT can improve cure rates, by allowing radiation
oncologists to give higher doses to tumors in sensitive spots _
such as the prostate _ with fewer side effects than conventional
therapies.
</P>
<P>
   Since Nomos brought its system through the U.S. Food and Drug
Administration approval process in the mid-1990s, similar systems
have appeared. Some are third-party programs that work with the
radiation guns produced by the Big Three X-ray firms: Varian
Medical in Palo Alto; Siemens Medical Systems in Walnut Creek,
Calif., which is a division of a German multinational; and Elekta,
a Swedish firm. Varian has also developed its own software system
that runs with its own, as well as with competing, X-ray guns.
</P>
<P>
   IMRT systems aren't cheap. If a hospital has a modern radiation
device, it might cost $300,000 to $500,000 to add the IMRT system.
The price tag on the latest X-ray source along with an IMRT package
could be $2 million.
</P>
<P>
   So far, the few dozen IMRT systems used in medical practice are
found mainly in leading-edge medical centers such as UCSF and
Stanford. But financial analyst James Terwilliger, with the Houston
investment bank of Sanders Morris Harris, predicts cancer centers
at most hospitals will buy IMRT systems because radiation therapy _
which can cost $35,000 _ is a profit center and the hospitals won't
want to see patients go elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   ``If this was a drug, it would be a multibillion-dollar
blockbuster,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   At UCSF, meanwhile, Marybelle Riley lay perfectly still as the
radiation gun passed overhead, making a sound like chattering teeth
as the lead shutters quickly opened and shut, opened and shut,
hundreds of times, under orders from the computer-driven treatment
plan.
</P>
<P>
   When the chattering stopped, members of the medical team helped
the elderly patient get ready for the ride home.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to work out,'' Riley said, as a home health nurse
wheeled her down the hall. ``I know it is.''
</P>
<P>
   E-mail Tom Abate at  &LR; abate(AT)sfgate.com &LR; .
</P>
</TEXT>
