<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIOSCOPE-COLUMN-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 BIOSCOPE: HUMAN CLONING COULD BE JUST AROUND THE CORNER  &HT;     By TOM ABATE 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Most people think of cloning as the production
of carbon-copy creatures, a practice that might be acceptable when
it comes to making sheep, but morally suspect when it comes to
making babies.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Eibert, an attorney and cloning advocate in Half Moon Bay,
thinks most people are wrong.
</P>
<P>
   Cloning, says Eibert, isn't about churning out another copy of
you, me or him. In the world according to Eibert, such a mistaken
view assumes that people are completely, or mainly, the product of
their genes, and ignores the huge role the environment plays in
shaping the person. Genes nonwithstanding, the kid raised on
``Beavis and Butthead'' will have a whole different outlook than
the child spawned on ``Leave it to Beaver.''
</P>
<P>
   Correcting ``misconceptions'' about cloning is important to
Eibert, who believes this technology offers thousands of infertile
people _ folks who may have tried in vitro fertilization techniques
and failed _ one last hope for producing a child that is
biologically theirs.
</P>
<P>
   So far, no one has cloned a human, at least no one has taken
credit for it. Even so, shortly after Dolly the sheep was cloned,
President Clinton issued an executive order banning the use of
federal funds for human cloning research.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's edict does not prevent any private entity from
bankrolling such experiments. California and a handful of other
states stepped in to plug this perceived loophole by passing laws
that make human cloning experiments, even by private parties,
illegal.
</P>
<P>
   Eibert, who is mulling a legal challenge to the California law,
first contacted me in January after I wrote about the state
advisory panel that has been asked to recommend whether the ban
should be extended or be allowed to expire in 2003.
</P>
<P>
   He recently sent me a 30-page manifesto laying out his case. It
sat on my desk for a while, until I picked it up and began reading
_ and couldn't put it down. I'm not sure I swallow his arguments,
but he presents a provocative case that deserves to be heard in the
court of public opinion, if not in a court of law.
</P>
<P>
   In essence, Eibert considers the cloning ban unconstitutional,
because the state has no right to prohibit a technology that would
allow a person to have a child. He views infertility as a
disability, according to the definitions of the Americans with
Disabilities Act.
</P>
<P>
   In his view, the cloning ban unconstitutionally prevents a
minority _ infertile people who have failed to benefit from
assisted reproduction technology _ from using a technique that
might ``cure'' their affliction.
</P>
<P>
   Eibert, 44, compares today's attitudes toward cloning with the
suspicion that greeted the birth of the first test-tube baby in
1978. Over time, he says, public opinion has accepted the use of a
wide array of assisted reproduction techniques so that infertile
people can bear children who are their genetic offspring.
</P>
<P>
   But, Eibert argues, the current techniques fail more than half
the time, because they still require the couple to produce a viable
egg and sperm. If one or the other can't deliver, the procedure
ends in disappointment.
</P>
<P>
   And we're not talking about a mere handful of folks, he says.
According to his estimates, upwards of 500,000 Californians fall
into this affected class of infertile persons who cannot have a
child by any current means.
</P>
<P>
   Eibert says cloning has technical advantages that might give
these people an alternative. Although the technique hasn't yet been
proven on humans, we know from animal work that the first
prerequisite for cloning is a viable egg.
</P>
<P>
   If the woman involved in the cloning can't produce a good egg, a
donor egg would be fine because the nucleus of that egg can be
removed and replaced with the nucleus of some cell _ any cell _ of
the person seeking to reproduce by cloning.
</P>
<P>
   This altered egg must then be prompted to develop into an
embryo, and transplanted into any woman who will bear the child.
</P>
<P>
   ``What makes cloning so revolutionary as an infertility
treatment is that it does not require the patient to produce viable
eggs or viable sperm,'' Eibert says. ``It's the only infertility
treatment that should work for everyone.''
</P>
<P>
   Whatever else I may think of Eibert's views, that last assertion
seems, at best, only half true. To begin with, for some people who
can't have a child without assistance, the difficulty lies in the
womb. Although fertilization may occur normally, a chemical
imbalance can dislodge the developing embryo and prevent a woman
from bringing the child to term.
</P>
<P>
   Even for those whose infertility is caused by the unviable sperm
or egg scenario, it seems to me only half of those folks would walk
away from a cloning event with a child that inherited their genes.
</P>
<P>
   You see, there's only room in that donor egg for one nucleus. A
couple making a clone would have to choose whose DNA gets to make
their child.
</P>
<P>
   I can hear the discussion now.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's my womb.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's my money.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's flip a coin.''
</P>
<P>
   Eibert is probably right when he suggests that, whatever you or
I may think about the morality of human cloning, it's just a matter
of time before the first human clone emerges from the womb. New
animals are being cloned all the time, extending our skill at the
process.
</P>
<P>
   As Eibert says: ``I have met infertile physicians, infertile
scientists and infertile biotech executives who have a huge
personal stake in seeing cloning technology developed, and who
already possess the training and skills and resources necessary to
make cloning a reality.''
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, the potential for human cloning will force us to
question whether sexual reproduction should be the only way to
produce a child. I'm speaking now of sex from a biological
perspective, the trading of genes and swapping of traits that
occurs when egg and sperm do their molecular tango.
</P>
<P>
   Cloning would allow the willing parent or parents to make the
birth dance a molecular solo, so long as they had a donor egg, a
willing womb and an assist from biotechnology.
</P>
<P>
   Now I'm relatively certain that some profound evolutionary
advantage gave rise to sexual reproduction in the first place.
Otherwise the birds and the bees would still duplicate by division
like the amoeba.
</P>
<P>
   But I'm also aware that the old verities no longer serve many in
our modern society. Eibert mentions the infertile as one group that
might benefit from cloning. Gays and singles are others who might
see asexual reproduction through cloning as a chance to achieve
biological parenthood.
</P>
<P>
   Such changes may seem frightening. On the way into work the
other day I saw a bumper sticker that took a swipe at gay marriage.
``God made Adam and Eve, not Adam and Steve,'' it said.
</P>
<P>
   I got news for the driver. God ain't necessarily in charge of
marriage any more. But if it's any small consolation, it would seem
Darwin's losing his grip on making babies.
</P>
<P>
   (To read the pro-cloning arguments in their entirety, visit
 &LR; www.humancloning.org &LR; . Key in Eibert's name on the search line to
be taken to his home page.)
</P>
<P>
   E-mail Tom Abate at  &LR; abate(AT)sfgate.com &LR; .
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-31-00 0034EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
