<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-ANGELS-TRADE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANGELS TRADE BOTTENFIELD FOR GANT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ The Anaheim Angels traded pitcher Kent
Bottenfield to the Phillies for outfielder/designated hitter Ron
Gant and cash Sunday, and in the process proclaimed that the club's
future is now.
</P>
<P>
   Trading the veteran Bottenfield, 31, means the Angels must rely
even more on their group of young starters in this season's pennant
race, a risk general manager Bill Stoneman and manager Mike
Scioscia believe is worth taking.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bottenfield was a guy who showed the way for a lot of our
younger starters,'' Stoneman said. ``And now it's time for those
younger guys to step up. We've had a lot of faith in those guys all
year, and maybe this is a way of demonstrating that.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Scioscia: ``These guys are not young in the sense of the
poise they've shown or productivity. There are unique circumstances
that led up to this. Usually, a club in the race is looking for
pitching. But it's a situation where the young guys have done so
well, we had a spare part. And we were able to trade it for
something we needed.''
</P>
<P>
   The risk was one the Angels think they needed to make because of
the lack of production coming from the DH spot and off the bench
from the right side. Gant, 35, hit .254 with 20 homers and 38 RBI
for the Phillies this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're bringing in a right-handed power hitter that is
experienced and capable,'' Stoneman said. ``He's been in a pennant
race before and had success in these situations. And he's had a lot
of success this year.''
</P>
<P>
   Added Scioscia: ``It gives us a veteran bat. He's a guy who
still has an explosive bat. He's very productive and is proven.''
</P>
<P>
   The group of young starters - Jarrod Washburn (25), Seth
Etherton (23), Scott Schoeneweis (26), Brian Cooper (25) and Ramon
Ortiz (24) have combined to go 23-15 with a 4.85 ERA (the American
League composite ERA is 4.98).
</P>
<P>
   Washburn is on the disabled list with a strained biceps muscle,
and Ortiz is at Triple-A Edmonton. Ken Hill is the only pitcher in
the rotation with significant experience, but the club also has
Kent Mercker set to begin a rehab assignment today and will start
him if they need to.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess it means they're giving us the ball,'' Washburn said.
``I love that they have that confidence in us. They know we can
pitch and we've got the stuff. It's a great vote of confidence for
them to say, basically, `you're our guys.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Bottenfield was acquired by the Angels, along with second
baseman Adam Kennedy, in a trade with the Cardinals for Jim Edmonds
on March 23. But after winning 18 games last season, Bottenfield
was a disappointment this year, going 7-8 with a 5.71 ERA in 21
starts.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to stay here,'' Bottenfield said. ``But I knew about
a week ago I wasn't going to be here. I've been in the game a long
time, 15 years. When you've been around that long you know people
around the league and get a good sense of what's going on.''
</P>
<P>
   Bottenfield said he believes he would have been traded even if
here were 10-2, and not 7-8, because the team is committed to the
young pitchers and didn't plan to re-sign him next season. He added
that he believes good things are ahead for this year's team.
</P>
<P>
   ``With or without me, they're going to be in the playoffs,'' he
said. ``Because this team does not give up. ... I hope they win.
I'm not going to be looking in the papers saying, `Ha, ha, you
shouldn't have traded me' if they lose a game. I hope they win the
division.''
</P>
<P>
   Gant, like Bottenfield, is eligible for free agency at the end
of the season. He is making $5.04 million this season, $3 million
of which is being paid by the Cardinals, for whom Gant played
before joining the Phillies. The Phillies were responsible for the
other $2 million, which included about $700,000 owed for the rest
of this season. The Phillies have agreed to pay the Angels a
portion of the $700,000.
</P>
<P>
   Gant will join the Angels in Anaheim today and start against the
Tigers. He started most of the games with the Phillies hitting No.
2 in the batting order.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm willing to take on any role,'' Gant said. ``My bat will
complement their left-hand hitters.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
