<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELNOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR NOW, ANGELS WILL STICK WITH FOUR-MAN ROTATION
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ With the trade of Kent Bottenfield, the
Anaheim Angels are down to a four-man starting rotation of Seth
Etherton, Ken Hill, Scott Schoeneweis and Brian Cooper. Because of
an off-day next Thursday, they won't need a fifth start until Aug.
8.
</P>
<P>
   By that time, Jarrod Washburn will be eligible to come off the
disabled list to start that game against the Red Sox.
</P>
<P>
   Washburn's return could mean the end of Edgard Clemente's place
on the team, if it doesn't happen sooner. Clemente's role will be
filled by Ron Gant, who will join the team today.
</P>
<P>
   ``Edgard is still a part of this club,'' manager Mike Scioscia
said, even though the team is believed to be trying to trade him.
</P>
<P>
   In 44 games as a reserve outfielder/DH, Clemente is hitting .218
with no homers, five RBI, 27 strikeouts and no walks in 78 at-bats.
The Angels can't send him to the minors without first having him
clear waivers because he is out of options.
</P>
<P>
   A sure sign that Scioscia has lost faith in Clemente is that he
has used Benji Gil as the DH the past two games with an opposing
left-hander on the mound. Clemente, the nephew of Hall of Famer
Roberto Clemente, was acquired during spring training from the
Rockies for minor-leaguers Norm Hutchins and Jason Dewey.
</P>
<P>
   The journeyman: Bottenfield learned of the trade early Sunday
morning, but he was still in the clubhouse mingling with his
ex-teammates and saying his goodbyes until gametime. Having been
dealt to the Angels from- the Cardinals on March 23, Bottenfield
will be joining his third team the Phillies - in a four-month span.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a little different leaving here because I was only here
four months, as opposed to a couple of years,'' he said. ``But I
was starting to build relationships with these guys. If this
happened a year from now, it would be extremely difficult. As it
is, it's hard. I respect these guys here very much. By no means is
it easy. I hope they do well.''
</P>
<P>
   Bottenfield was well-respected in the clubhouse by the other
players, particularly the other pitchers.
</P>
<P>
   ``You hate to lose a guy like Bottenfield, he's a great
clubhouse guy,'' closer Troy Percival said. ``He sucks up a lot of
innings, and as a reliever, you like a guy who sucks up a lot of
innings. But we had a chance to do something to get better. And I
think this makes us a better team.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
