<SLUG> BC-OLY-US </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BATTLE OF AGES MOVES TO TRIALS 
</HEADLINE>
 GYMNASTICS CHAMPIONSHIP-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN POWERS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. LOUIS _ It was a showdown between those who can belly up to
the bar and those who need fake IDs. ``A beautiful battle of the
two generations,'' US women's gymnastics team coordinator Bela
Karolyi exulted.
</P>
<P>
   On one side were the Atlanta veterans _ Amy Chow, Dominique
Moceanu (an old 18), Dominique Dawes. On the other were the China
survivors _ Elise Ray, Kristen Maloney, Jamie Dantzscher, Vanessa
Atler. The 20s vs. the teens.
</P>
<P>
   ``The younger generation prevailed this time,'' Karolyi declared
Saturday night, after Ray et al. swept the top five places at the
US Gymnastics Championships at the Kiel Center. ``But it was one of
the most disputed championships in many, many years. So don't think
there won't be some surprises next time.''
</P>
<P>
   Most of the surprises at the Olympic trials, which will be held
Aug. 17-20 at the FleetCenter in Boston, likely will come in the
back room, where Karolyi and three other selectors will choose half
of the six-member team for Sydney.
</P>
<P>
   The top two seem set _ Ray, the new champion, and Maloney, who
had won the last two US all-around titles. After that, it's a
scramble among Dantzscher, Atler, Alyssa Beckerman, Chow, and
Morgan White, who were all within half a point here. Not to mention
Moceanu and Dawes, who shook off enough gold dust to place a
creditable eighth and ninth, respectively, and easily make the
12-woman cut for the trials.
</P>
<P>
   The rogue variable is Shannon Miller, who, like Dawes, is trying
for a third Olympic team at 23. Though she withdrew here after the
prelims to avoid jeopardizing the shinbone she cracked at the
beginning of the month, Miller is seeking an injury waiver into the
trials (as is Magnificent Seven teammate Jaycie Phelps).
</P>
<P>
   ``I would like to see Shannon coming back to claim her place
like she could, she should, and I think she will,'' said Karolyi.
``But I have to tell you, it will not be easy.''
</P>
<P>
   Miller, who didn't get back into the gym until December,
competed in only a token bars routine here, just to show federation
officials that she still knew how to put on a leotard. To get a
ticket to Boston, she'll need to prove she can handle all four
events at a special show-me session at Karolyi's Houston ranch
several days before the trials.
</P>
<P>
   If she can get anywhere close to the form that won her seven
Olympic medals, Miller will probably land one of the specialist
spots, if only to get her marquee name, her maturity, and her
stability onto a team that lacks all three.
</P>
<P>
   Though the younger generation ruled here, their last world-level
appearance was a wobbly sixth at last year's global meet in
Tianjin. ``I did not see them in China,'' said Karolyi, ``but it
was a big difference here.''
</P>
<P>
   The US males, also sixth in China, have no golden oldies to
bring back _ only three of the Atlanta veterans returned. One of
them, Chainey Umphrey, finished 30th in his first nationals since
1997. Another, four-time champ John Roethlisberger, was delighted
to place as high as fifth after falling off the pommel horse and
taking an 8.75 on floor.
</P>
<P>
   That leaves five-time titlist Blaine Wilson, who is so far above
the field that he's already been guaranteed a ticket to Sydney no
matter what he does at the trials. Wilson could win a couple of
medals at Olympus _ he missed the bronze in the world all-around by
a thousandth of a point. All he needs is a team around him.
</P>
<P>
   Sean Townsend, who gave Wilson a spirited go here until he fell
off the horse, looks solid for one spot. So does 17-year-old Paul
Hamm, the best natural talent since Wilson came on the scene seven
years ago. So does world-teamer Stephen McCain.
</P>
<P>
   Had Jason Gatson made it back from the blown-out knee he
suffered at last year's nationals (he was a gutsy 18th here), coach
Peter Kormann would have had another solid block to build on.
Instead, he and the selection committee will have to play
mix-and-match, fiddling with computers and calculators to choose
the final two members of the team. ``If you don't want to be
handpicked,'' Wilson said, ``better finish in the top four.''
</P>
<P>
   Handpicking means closed doors and politics and, invariably,
yelps of protest from those passed over. ``We won't have
controversy,'' insisted Karolyi. ``Or we won't have more
controversy than ever. There will always be some crying, some
praising, some bitching, some moaning. That's the sport.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
