<HEADER>
A7875 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-FBN-LeBRETON-COLUMN-T     07-31 0677
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-LeBRETON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COWBOYS' SUBS TURNED OPENER INTO A NIGHT TO FORGET
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GIL LeBRETON 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ By halftime of the Dave Campo prime-time debut,
it was already 38-10 in Pittsburgh's favor, and a traffic jam was
beginning to form outside of Texas Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing against the Dallas Cowboys' new coach. Campo's backups
had turned a reasonably competitive exhibition scrum into a waste
of a warm summer evening.
</P>
<P>
   The night had its moments. Hopefully, you weren't at the
refrigerator and missed them.
</P>
<P>
   ``We moved the ball well and put it in the end zone,''
quarterback Troy Aikman revealed.
</P>
<P>
   The scoreboard backs him up. In two first-quarter possessions,
Aikman was 6-of-7 for 83 yards. The two big-money receivers, Joey
Galloway and Rocket Ismail, each had compelling pass receptions.
And the Cowboys did, in fact, score their only touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   In his lone ensuing series, an old nemesis from the dark side,
Randall Cunningham, now a Cowboy, scrambled for 21 yards and took
the team to a field goal.
</P>
<P>
   But beyond that, egads.
</P>
<P>
   Aikman, Randall, Rocket and Galloway all retired early for the
night, perhaps to that dallascowboys.com chat room. Loyal Cowboys
fans began flipping the dial, searching for ``Walker, Texas
Ranger'' reruns.
</P>
<P>
   And the visiting Pittsburgh Steelers, like an in-law at a
buffet, rudely piled it on.
</P>
<P>
   The name Paul Justin must be mentioned here. His performance, or
lack thereof, as Campo's third quarterback of the night made
franchise history.
</P>
<P>
   In a little more than 10 minutes, Justin lost one fumble, threw
three intercepted passes and was jeered lustily by the estimated
35,000 in attendance.
</P>
<P>
   Has a quarterback in a Cowboys uniform ever been booed in the
first half of the first exhibition game? I didn't think so.
</P>
<P>
   What's curious is that Justin is no rookie, but a sixth-year
pro, and he was signed by the Cowboys (at a cost of $500,000)
because he spent time with the Super Bowl-winning Rams and has
experience running the Jack Reilly offense.
</P>
<P>
   Yeah, sure.
</P>
<P>
   To be fair, though, Justin's play was symptomatic of how a lot
of the second- and third-team Cowboys _ the ones not named
Cunningham _ performed against the opportunistic Steelers.
</P>
<P>
   Backup receivers dropped passes. Backup cornerbacks were bullied
around by the Steelers' big receivers. Backup offensive linemen
failed to open holes for backup running backs.
</P>
<P>
   It was owner Jerry Jones himself who said that he believes this
team has more roster depth than any of his previous ones.
</P>
<P>
   But young players _ among them, Dwayne Goodrich, Mario Edwards,
Wane McGarity and Chris Brazzell _ appeared to have problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think on the young guys, there will be some individual
performances that were good,'' Campo said. ``But I was disappointed
as a whole. I'm not worried, though, about those young corners
losing any confidence.''
</P>
<P>
   In fairness, receivers Plaxico Burress and Malcolm Johnson, who
caught a combined six passes and scored two of the Pittsburgh
touchdowns, are both 6-5. The Cowboys don't list a single backup
cornerback over six feet. Mismatches abounded.
</P>
<P>
   ``The new guys have a chance to get out there and get a taste of
how it's going to be,'' starting safety George Teague said. ``The
next game will be more important.''
</P>
<P>
   Justin's turnovers at quarterback turned the night into a
debacle, but any crispness that the Cowboys might have displayed
vanished after Cunningham went out.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first quarter was fine,'' new offensive coordinator Reilly
said. ``We should have ended it right there.''
</P>
<P>
   Alas, it doesn't work that well. In the NFL summer, you pay your
money and you take your chances. Which is why it was a dead heat
this week over which was worth more _ two tickets to
Cowboys-Steelers or that Napster stock you bought last Christmas.
</P>
<P>
   Poor Campo. It was no way to introduce himself as the new head
coach.
</P>
<P>
   But that's preseason. He had to stay. You got to watch ``Walker,
Texas Ranger''. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
