<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-31 01:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7876 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-FBN-COWBOYS-GALLOWAY-     07-31 0523
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-COWBOYS-GALLOWAY-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPEEDY NEWCOMER GALLOWAY LIKES POSSIBILITIES OF COWBOYS' OFFENSE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CLARENCE E. HILL JR. 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ On the Dallas Cowboys' first offensive play in
Sunday night's 38-10 blowout loss to the Pittsburgh Steelers,
quarterback Troy Aikman opened the much-publicized ``deep-ball
era'' with a 5-yard pass to fullback Robert Thomas.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys, whose off-season revitalization included a new
stretch-the-field offense and the addition of speedy receiver Joey
Galloway, called a pass on the ensuing play.
</P>
<P>
   This time Aikman was good on a 5-yard pass and 4-yard run _ to
Thomas.
</P>
<P>
   It was enough to make an old fullback proud, while causing many
in the stands at Texas Stadium to wonder what in the name of a $42
million contract was going on.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas' predecessor, radio announcer Daryl ``Moose'' Johnston,
proved prophetic in the Cowboys' broadcast booth when he gushed
that the passes to Thomas ``would open things up'' on the outside
for Galloway and his equally speedy receiving partner, Raghib
Ismail.
</P>
<P>
   Two plays later, Aikman found Galloway for 14 yards.
</P>
<P>
   That drive eventually stalled because of poor pass protection.
But when Aikman trotted back on the field for the Cowboys' next
possession, he went right at Galloway for 25 yards.
</P>
<P>
   Aikman came back to Ismail for 23 yards with a similar route on
the other side of the field, giving the Cowboys a first down at the
Pittsburgh 6.
</P>
<P>
   Running back Chris Warren scored two plays later, ending the
evening for the first-team offense.
</P>
<P>
   Though his stint was an abbreviated 11 plays, Galloway's debut
lived up to advance billing. The Cowboys' offense, which played
without starting running back Emmitt Smith (sprained toe), tight
end David LaFleur and guard Larry Allen, showed deadly potential.
</P>
<P>
   Aikman completed 6 of 7 passes for 83 yards. Thomas had three
receptions for 21 yards, but Aikman's passes to the receivers were
down-field darts. Galloway caught two for 39. Ismail hauled in one
for 23.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were able to throw to Rocket and Joey and get a couple of
good completions,'' Aikman said. ``We moved the ball well in a
short time, which was a good sign. I thought our execution was
good.''
</P>
<P>
   The best part was the inclusion of Galloway, who was given the
megabucks contract to replace the retired Michael Irvin and provide
the juice the offense lacked last season.
</P>
<P>
   Galloway, who is still developing an on-field relationship with
Aikman, said Sunday's results were only the beginning.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was good to finally get in the stadium and play a game,''
Galloway said. ``I also enjoyed getting the opportunity to work the
timing with Troy in a game setting. I think we executed well with
the opportunities we had.''
</P>
<P>
   Backup quarterback Randall Cunningham came away impressed, even
though Galloway was out of the game when Cunningham took the field
with the second-team offense.
</P>
<P>
   ``Joey is just so talented he doesn't look like he has to work
as much as other people ... he can do anything you need as a
player,'' Cunningham said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-31-00 0116EDT &QL; 
