<HEADER>
A7879 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i BC-VENEZUELA-VOTE-1STLD-     07-31 0939
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VENEZUELA-VOTE-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OFFICIALS SAY CHAVEZ WINS VENEZUELA PRESIDENTIAL VOTE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Subs for updating, rewriting throughout)   By LARRY ROHTER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CARACAS, Venezuela _ Rallying to President Hugo Chavez's call
for radical social and political change, Venezuelans on Sunday
granted the former paratrooper a new six-year term with enhanced
powers, top officials said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a day of revolution,'' Chavez, 46, who in 1992 led an
unsuccessful military coup attempt, said after casting his ballot
on Sunday morning at a suburban polling station. ``Today a new
republic is being born.''
</P>
<P>
   The ease with which Chavez will be able to carry out his
revolution, however, depends on the outcome of races to elect 165
members of Congress and 23 state governors.
</P>
<P>
   Results of those races were still being tallied early on Monday.
Supporters of the president are expected to win a majority of the
posts, but polls indicate that Chavez may fall short of the
two-thirds majority he needs in the National Assembly in order to
govern without constraints.
</P>
<P>
   Chavez has promised to use his time in power to sweep away the
last remnants of the traditional political order in this nation of
23 million people that in recent years has been the United States'
top oil-supplier.
</P>
<P>
   Hours after the polls were supposed to close, there were no
official results. However, both the head of the outgoing
legislature and the interior minister, Luis Davila, said on
national television that preliminary official results showed that
Chavez had won handily.
</P>
<P>
   Voter surveys posted by the the newspaper El Nacional gave
Chavez as much as a 20-point margin over his main challenger,
Francisco Arias Cardenas.
</P>
<P>
   In the last 18 months, Venezuela's poor, disillusioned by
decades of corrupt and unresponsive government, have united around
Chavez and his plan for a complete overhaul of society.
</P>
<P>
   The preliminary results, announced late Sunday night, were
quickly followed by fireworks and other celebrations across the
capital. Thousands of jubilant Chavez supporters wearing the red
beret that is the emblem of their movement marched with flags and
banners on the Miraflores presidential palace downtown, demanding
that Chavez appear on ``the people's balcony'' to address them.
</P>
<P>
   When he finally emerged, wearing the same red beret and a
military-style uniform, Chavez called for national ``unity,
persistence and patience.'' But he once again resorted to the
language of conflict and confrontation that has become his
trademark, boasting that ``we have routed the forces of the
adversary'' and warning that ``one battle has ended and another is
beginning.''
</P>
<P>
   The vote on Sunday was the culmination of a contentious process
of sweeping political change that began with Chavez's landslide
victory in a December 1998 presidential vote. As a candidate, he
promised voters a ``peaceful social revolution'' if elected, but
also said he would need a new constitution with expanded powers in
order to carry out the transformation the country needed.
</P>
<P>
   In three elections last year, a constitutional assembly was
first convoked and next selected and then finally it submitted a
new charter to voters for approval last December.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, Chavez's term of office was expanded from five to
six years, and a ban on sitting presidents seeking immediate
re-election for one more term was removed _ creating the
possibility that Chavez could remain in office until 2013.
</P>
<P>
   Even before the changes were approved, though, the Congress,
dominated by discredited opposition parties, and the Supreme Court
were eliminated and replaced by weakened entities that have proven
subservient to Chavez and his leftist Patriotic Pole coalition.
</P>
<P>
   The authority of governors and mayors was also reduced, the role
of the armed forces was vastly expanded and a Chavez loyalist was
placed in charge of the powerful state oil company after it was
purged.
</P>
<P>
   With the new Constitution in hand, Chavez called a vote to elect
a new unicameral congress, as well as governors, mayors and state
and municipal legislators, a total of more than 6,200 elected
posts. In what he described as an attempt to ``relegitimize'' his
rule, he also submitted the presidency to a new vote, anticipating
no real challenge.
</P>
<P>
   But in February, Cardenas, a former army colonel who was
Chavez's second-in-command during the 1992 coup and spent two years
in jail with him afterward, broke ranks and announced his own
candidacy.
</P>
<P>
   Chavez, he charged, was assuming dictatorial powers, tolerating
the corruption he had pledged to eradicate, alienating the United
States and forging an undesirable alliance with President Fidel
Castro of Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   In an unusual last-minute incursion into the campaign, Castro
invited a group of Venezuelan journalists to Cuba on Saturday and
issued a ringing endorsement of Chavez, wishing him ``good luck and
lots of votes'' during a rambling news conference that was
televised live here. ``Hugo, I am sure that nothing or no one can
hold you back,'' the Cuban leader said.
</P>
<P>
   Castro's remarks, which appeared to violate a ban on politicking
here after the formal close of the campaign, came days after a man
turned up claiming to be a Cuban intelligence agent and said that
Castro has sent 1,500 operatives here to infiltrate the Venezuelan
government. As the news conference was taking place, Chavez called
Castro, and the two men discussed baseball before ridiculing the
accusations of a Cuban spy network operating here.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-31-00 0130EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
