<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-COWBOYS-NOTES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEDER GETS A LEG UP ON KICKING JOB
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CHAREAN WILLIAMS AND CLARENCE E. HILL JR. 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ The Dallas Cowboys are hoping to have a kick
this season. And they might if they can find a kicker.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys couldn't buy a field goal of more than 40 yards last
season, which is why they went into this season desperately seeking
a new kicker. Richie Cunningham and Eddie Murray were 4-of-11 on
field goal tries of 40-49 yards.
</P>
<P>
   For one night at least, Ashland University's Tim Seder had no
problem getting it through the upright from long distance.
</P>
<P>
   He made a 48-yarder with room to spare with 12:17 remaining in
the second quarter, capping a seven-play, 40-yard drive directed by
backup quarterback Randall Cunningham.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't too bad,'' Seder said. ``It's just habit. It's nice
to work with (long snapper) Dale (Hellestrae). I don't know if
there is more pressure, but when you make a kick like that, you get
more confident.''
</P>
<P>
   Rian Lindell, Seder's competition for the job, kicked the extra
point after the Cowboys' touchdown in the first quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Punter Barry Cantrell, who is in competition with Micah Knorr
for the vacant punting job, re-aggravated a strained left hamstring
in pregame warmups and did not play. Knorr averaged 40.4 yards on
five punts. SPECTATORS
</P>
<P>
   Four Cowboys starters missed Sunday night's game with injuries.
</P>
<P>
   Running back Emmitt Smith said Sunday that his sprained left toe
was not 100 percent, which prevented him from playing. Left guard
Larry Allen (fractured right hand), tight end David LaFleur (groin)
and free safety George Teague (strained glute) also did not play.
</P>
<P>
   Starting right defensive end Greg Ellis, who still is recovering
from a fractured left tibia and fibula suffered last season,
cornerback Charlie Williams (left knee), linebacker Barron Wortham
(left knee) and receiver Jeff Ogden (right foot) were among other
players who got a sideline view of the game. LUCKY LIKELY OUT FOR
YEAR
</P>
<P>
   The season is likely over for backup tight end Mike Lucky, who
injured his right knee Sunday night.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys won't know for sure until Monday when he undergoes a
magnetic resonance imaging exam. However, the coaching staff is not
optimistic.
</P>
<P>
   Cowboys tight ends coach Les Miles said it doesn't look good for
Lucky, who was battling Brian Roche for the third tight end spot
behind David LaFleur and Jackie Harris.
</P>
<P>
   Also out of the year is free-agent safety Sean Key, who broke
his right tibula and fibula. MEANINGLESS?
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys are 1-10 in the exhibition season since 1998. They
have not had a winning preseason record since 1989 when they went
3-1. That's the same season the Cowboys went 1-15 during the
regular season. HERE TODAY...
</P>
<P>
   The best quarterback for the Steelers was Paul Justin.
</P>
<P>
   Justin played his first game as a Cowboy. Justin, who will make
$500,000 if he makes the team as the third-string quarterback,
completed only 2-of-7 passes for 11 yards, threw three
interceptions that led to three Pittsburgh touchdowns and was booed
every time he walked onto the field.
</P>
<P>
   Dewayne Washington returned a Justin pass 17 yards for a
touchdown with 4:53 left in the second quarter. Justin's next pass
was intercepted by Mike Vrabel, which led to a 29-yard Steelers'
touchdown on the next play.
</P>
<P>
   Just before halftime, a Justin pass was picked off by Deshea
Townsend, and the Steelers needed only five plays for their next
score.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anytime that happens to you, your job is on the line,'' Justin
said. HERE FOR GOOD
</P>
<P>
   Randall Cunningham played only one series. He completed 1-of-4
passes for 7 yards, but two of his incompletions were drops. He
also had a 21-yard scramble as the Cowboys got a field goal out of
the seven-play, 40-yard drive.
</P>
<P>
   ``I did feel comfortable,'' said Cunningham, who signed as a
free agent in the off-season. ``I felt like I knew what I was
doing. When I first got here, and they threw that playbook in front
of me, oh, my goodness. My head was spinning. I was like, `You're
kidding. These aren't really the plays are they?' Coach said,
`Yeah, you just get them down. It'll take time.' Then I went up to
Troy (Aikman), and I said, `Troy, how long did it take you?' He
said, `Man, when I first learning the system, it took me a little
while to call the plays.' That made me feel good. He's really
helped me. I felt comfortable based on I knew it was going to take
some time to get these plays down.'' ROOKIE MISTAKE
</P>
<P>
   Free-agent rookie quarterback Clint Stoerner completed 7 of 12
passes for 67 yards and one interception. It was the interception
that was bothering him after the game.
</P>
<P>
   Stoerner's third pass, which was intended for Wane McGarity, was
picked off by Ainsley Battles in the Steelers' end zone.
</P>
<P>
   ``A rule of thumb for a quarterback is don't throw the ball back
across the field like that anytime, and especially when you're
inside the red zone and you've got a chance for a field goal or a
touchdown,'' Stoerner said. ``As soon as I released it, I knew it
was wrong.'' RANDY MOSS?
</P>
<P>
   It didn't take Steelers beat writers long to start comparing
rookie first-round draft choice Plaxico Burress to Minnesota
Vikings receiver Randy Moss. One exhibition game.
</P>
<P>
   Burress caught four passes _ two of them spectacular _ for 60
yards and one touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's going to be Plaxico Burress,'' Steelers quarterback
Kordell Stewart said. ``Calling him Randy Moss is not giving Randy
Moss any respect, because he earned that title in the sense of a
guy who's out there making great plays and making things happen.
Him going up and making those plays can kind of tease you a little
bit to make you think that way. But he still has some work to do.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-31-00 0131EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
