<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-31 01:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7885 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-BBA-RANGERS-TIGERS-TE     07-31 0693
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-RANGERS-TIGERS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RANGERS' OLIVER ROUGHED UP AGAIN, MIGHT LOSE SPOT IN ROTATION
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SIMON GONZALEZ 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ One bad outing by a pitcher frequently is an
aberration. Two can be put down to misfortune. But do it three
times, and it becomes a disturbing trend.
</P>
<P>
   Darren Oliver allowed seven runs on eight hits in two innings as
the Texas Rangers lost to the Detroit Tigers, 8-7, Sunday night at
The Ballpark in Arlington, his third consecutive poor outing since
returning from the disabled list.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's crazy,'' said Oliver, who allowed six runs in the first
inning, all with two outs. ``I know I can pitch a lot better than
this. It's frustrating.''
</P>
<P>
   Matt Perisho, Jeff Zimmerman and John Wetteland provided seven
innings of stellar relief, collectively holding the Tigers to one
run on three hits and giving the Rangers a chance to get back in
it.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers pecked away with a run here, a couple of runs there.
They even scored two runs off Tigers closer Todd Jones in the
ninth, the first time he has been scored on since May 24.
</P>
<P>
   But just as it was Saturday, when Kenny Rogers gave up six in
the first, the early deficit was too much.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you have back-to-back nights when you get behind 6-0 in
the first, it's hard to keep battling back,'' Rangers manager
Johnny Oates said.
</P>
<P>
   The loss dropped Oliver to 0-2 with an 11.57 ERA in his past
three starts, and 2-6 with a 7.33 ERA overall.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers dropped to three games below .500, and 101/2 games
behind the Seattle Mariners in the American League West.
</P>
<P>
   General manager Doug Melvin said Sunday he isn't inclined to
make a major trade before 3 p.m. Monday, the nonwaiver deadline,
mostly because he hasn't received an attractive offer for closer
John Wetteland but also because he'd like to give the club a chance
to make a run at a playoff berth.
</P>
<P>
   But it will be hard to get back into the race without an
extended winning streak, and it will be hard to put together an
extended winning streak unless Oliver improves.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've just got to do better,'' Oates said. ``Right now, it's
not very pretty. His velocity is there, but location-wise he
stunk.''
</P>
<P>
   Oliver complained of a tired arm after a start May 31 and didn't
pitch for 10 days. He was ineffective when he returned to the
rotation, going 0-1 with a 11.88 earned-run average in his next two
starts.
</P>
<P>
   After further examinations he was diagnosed with tendinitis in
his left shoulder, and placed on the DL.
</P>
<P>
   He went 1-1 with a 0.84 ERA in three starts for Triple-A
Oklahoma on medical-rehabilitation assignment and was activated
June 20, but he has been wretched since returning to the majors.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes it's hard to figure it out out there, and it's a
struggle,'' he said. ``I wish I had the answers, but I don't. I
can't put the ball where I want to.''
</P>
<P>
   Overall, he's 0-3 with a 11.70 ERA in five starts after first
saying his arm hurt, and hasn't pitched past the fifth inning.
</P>
<P>
   Physically, he insists there's nothing wrong.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel fine,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The alternative might be even worse. If Oliver isn't injured,
the pitcher signed to a three-year, $18 million contract as a free
agent in the off-season might merely be ineffective. That's a
possibility, considering he was 2-3 with a 5.98 ERA before the
problems with his arm. His two victories in 16 outings are the
second fewest by an AL pitcher with at least 15 starts. The New
York Yankees' David Cone has one in 19.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's one of those things where you have to keep going out
there and keep battling,'' Oliver said.
</P>
<P>
   Unless he improves, Oliver might not have the chance to go out
there much more. Doug Davis, 8-3 with a 2.84 ERA in 12 starts at
Oklahoma, is in the bullpen awaiting his chance.
</P>
<P>
   Oates didn't rule out a switch.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will announce any changes that I may want to do'' Tuesday,
he said, referring to the day after the trading deadline.
</P>
<P>
   But if the Rangers are to have any chance to getting back in the
race they need better results from that spot in the rotation, from
Oliver or someone else. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
