<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-31 01:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7889 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-FBN-HERSKOWITZCOLUMN-     07-31 0787
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-HERSKOWITZCOLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
49ers owe success to Montana pick
<TEXT>
<P>
   By MICKEY HERSKOWITZ
</P>
<P>
   Houston Chronicle
</P>
<P>
   You shudder to think how one decision, one wrong road taken, can
change a life, a team or a city. It is a matter of record that Bill
Walsh, still a few years away from being hailed as a genius, did
not intend to draft Joe Montana in 1979.
</P>
<P>
   San Francisco had a fairly urgent need for a quarterback with
potential, but Walsh had his eye on Phil Simms, who figured to be
gone by the time the 49ers made their pick, and Steve Dils, who had
played for Walsh at Stanford.
</P>
<P>
   It was John Brodie, the former 49ers quarterback, who urged
Walsh to take the senior from Notre Dame, who at 6-2 and 190 pounds
looked almost frail. What he had going for him was a reputation for
bringing his team from behind. Of course, it helped to have played
under the Golden Dome, attached to the legends of Knute Rockne,
George Gipp, Angelo Bertelli, Johnny Lujack and all of the other
saints who walked forever along the misty banks of the Wabash.
</P>
<P>
   But no one had yet forecast immortality for Joe Montana. The rap
against him at Notre Dame was his casual attitude toward practice
and his inconsistency. Then Walsh watched him work out and was
intrigued by his quick feet and the way he set up to throw. ``If he
can be great for one game,'' Walsh wondered, ``why not two? Or
more? He was willing to learn. That was easy to tell.''
</P>
<P>
   So the 49ers grabbed Montana in the third round, making him the
82nd player selected. Think about it. What if they had indeed
drafted the forgettable Dils, and Joe had wound up with the
Patriots or Jets? Would the 49ers have won four Super Bowls in the
'80s? Would Walsh have kept his job, much less qualified for a
genius badge? Would something called the East Coast offense have
ruled the pros and spread across the land?
</P>
<P>
   We can only guess.
</P>
<P>
   Few quarterbacks were more skilled at taking the guesswork out
of a big game. He had an almost supernatural sense of timing. No
one hurried Joe Montana, standing in the pocket or on the podium of
the Pro Football Hall of Fame at Canton, Ohio. He took his own
sweet time and, mercy, what sweet times they were.
</P>
<P>
   Walsh was patient with Montana, letting him understudy Steve
DeBerg for almost two seasons. Nor was that a new role for the
quiet kid with icy blue eyes. At Notre Dame, he had been ranked
last among the three quarterbacks on the freshman roster. Funny
about football myths. By the time Joe was a certified NFL hero, the
popular version of his college debut had six quarterbacks ahead of
him.
</P>
<P>
   He didn't start for the Irish until the fourth game of his
junior year. Coming off the bench in six games, playing less than a
total of 40 minutes, he brought the Irish from 88 points behind and
won them all.
</P>
<P>
   Over the years, Joe proved more than his greatness. He was
modest and brave and normal, a hero but not without flaws. Marriage
threw him for losses twice, but the third time he got it right.
</P>
<P>
   After the 49ers swamped Miami and Dan Marino in Super Bowl XIX,
he married Jennifer Wallace, an actress-model who filmed a
commercial with him for Schick razors. Jennifer said she had to
pinch Joe's bottom to get him to loosen up enough to complete the
spot. The script ended with Joe asking, ``What am I wanted for now,
Sheriff?''
</P>
<P>
   Her reply was prophetic: ``To take me to the dance, Joe
Montana.'' Quarterbacks and singing cowboys usually get the girl,
but not many marry the Schick sheriff. Mostly, he took the risks
and made his own luck.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, in his last college game _ the Siberia Bowl _ he beat
Houston in the snow in Dallas, passing for a touchdown and a
two-point conversion as time ran out, with no one able to see the
line of scrimmage. And his view was blocked when Dwight Clark made
The Catch that beat the Cowboys, sending the 49ers to their first
Super Bowl and a victory over the Bengals.
</P>
<P>
   So many big plays, so many big games. After Montana had back
surgery in 1986, his doctors doubted he would play again that year,
or any other year. Eight weeks later, he led the 49ers to a rout of
the Cardinals. Decked while throwing a touchdown pass to Jerry
Rice, Montana looked up to see a defensive end standing over him.
``You're a hell of a man,'' said Bubba Baker, who then turned and
walked away.
</P>
<P>
   The Pro Football Hall of Fame moves to Houston on Sunday _ at
least its newest attraction does. Montana will sign autographs at a
collectors show, and you will find him unchanged by immortality.
``I go to the store, buy milk and forget the bread. I try to hammer
a nail and hit my thumb,'' he says. ``Do legends do that?''
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
