<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-HOUSTON-REALIGN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Houston owner wants expansion team in AFC Central
<TEXT>
<P>
   By JOHN McCLAIN
</P>
<P>
   Houston Chronicle
</P>
<P>
   CANTON, Ohio _ Houston owner Bob McNair wants the NFL to place
his expansion franchise in the AFC Central with Pittsburgh,
Cleveland and Cincinnati when the league is realigned into eight
divisions of four teams each for the 2002 season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look at the history of the rivalries between Houston and those
three cities,'' McNair said. ``It just seems like such a natural
thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Realignment is shaping up as perhaps the league's most
controversial issue since the merger between the NFL and AFL in
1970. Although nothing is for certain, and everything is subject to
change, it appears Tennessee definitely will leave the AFC Central
and probably will be placed in a newly created southern division in
the AFC.
</P>
<P>
   In many of the realignment proposals disclosed so far, Houston
has been included in a new southern division with Tennessee,
Jacksonville and Indianapolis, even though the Colts aren't a
natural fit.
</P>
<P>
   The realignment controversy won't explode until the league's
spring meetings in March, but owners and front-office executives
are taking sides.
</P>
<P>
   Cleveland wants Houston rather than Baltimore in the AFC
Central. Pittsburgh wants Baltimore. Cincinnati wants Indianapolis.
</P>
<P>
   The new Browns want the old Browns, the Ravens, out of the
division to sever the historical ties.
</P>
<P>
   Pittsburgh wants to keep Baltimore in the AFC Central for the
same reason Cleveland wants the Ravens out _ because of the natural
rivalry between the old Browns and new Browns.
</P>
<P>
   Cincinnati wants Indianapolis because of the close proximity of
the two teams and the possibility of building a rivalry.
</P>
<P>
   McNair has Cleveland owner Al Lerner and Browns president Carmen
Policy as allies.
</P>
<P>
   ``We feel Houston would be an outstanding addition to our
division,'' says Policy, who is one of the league's most
influential executives. ``Cleveland has history with Houston. In
this part of the country, history means something when it comes to
professional football.
</P>
<P>
   ``Competitively, having Houston in our division would be great.
Think about the great memories of Browns-Oilers games and
Steelers-Oilers games. When you think your way through it, it's
very, very appealing to Al Lerner and myself.''
</P>
<P>
   As the owner of the NFL's newest franchise, McNair doesn't have
a vote. Neither does Ravens owner Art Modell. He surrendered his
vote when the league agreed to let him move to Baltimore.
</P>
<P>
   McNair, Lerner and Policy have to work on Steelers owner Dan
Rooney. No owner is more powerful and influential than Rooney, who
was inducted into the Pro Football Hall of Fame on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I honestly believe that with the proper sales approach, we
might be able to get Dan Rooney to see some of the benefits we
see,'' Policy said.
</P>
<P>
   Rooney has said numerous times how much he likes Houston and how
much respect he has for the city and the team. His belief that the
Ravens should remain in the AFC Central has nothing to do with
Houston.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's (Browns-Ravens) such a great natural rivalry,'' Rooney
said. ``I don't know why you'd want to break it up. I'm not saying
it (his opinion) is etched in stone. I'm trying to be open-minded
about it. Over time, just think about what kind of rivalry that
could become.''
</P>
<P>
   For the same reason he believes the Browns and Ravens should be
in the same division, Rooney thinks Houston would be a natural fit
in a division with Tennessee. Former Steelers defensive tackle Joe
Greene agrees.
</P>
<P>
   Greene, who was Rooney's presenter in Canton and is also a
member of the Hall, played on four Super Bowl champions, including
the two that beat the Oilers in AFC Championship Games during the
Luv Ya Blue era.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Steelers and Oilers had a great rivalry and some great
games, but if you're talking geographically, it makes more sense to
keep Baltimore in the division,'' Greene said. ``Because of what
happened with the Oilers moving, Houston and Tennessee would have
the makings of a great rivalry.''
</P>
<P>
   Although so much can change in two or three years because of the
salary cap and free agency, Houston would appear to have a chance
to be competitive sooner by playing in the AFC Central with the
Steelers, Browns and Bengals rather than in a new division with the
Titans, Jaguars and Colts.
</P>
<P>
   In the AFC Central, Houston, Cleveland, Pittsburgh and
Cincinnati would be playing in new stadiums.
</P>
<P>
   No matter what happens, McNair will have Policy and Lerner on
his side.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Bob's going to build a great organization,'' Policy
said. ``I don't know what the odds are that Houston will end up in
the AFC Central, but I think we can inject some real juice into the
issue and make a compelling argument for it.''
</P>
<P>
   An example of how difficult it is going to be can be found in a
comment by commissioner Paul Tagliabue.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got to look beyond geography,'' Tagliabue said. ``We've
got to look at a mix of things. I really think that when we get the
scheduling formula done in October, it's really going to open up
some possibilities because everyone will be playing everyone in the
league on a rotating basis. And you'll be guaranteed of playing
everyone home and away over a relatively short period. I think
that's really going to help us with realignment.''
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
