<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-astros </SLUG>
 lede-HNS  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Glavine beats Astros for 200th win
</P>
<P>
   By CARLTON THOMPSON
</P>
<P>
   Houston Chronicle
</P>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Fate was in attendance Sunday at Turner Field, and it
might as well have been toting a tomahawk.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta Braves pitcher Tom Glavine chopped up the Astros en
route to the 200th victory of his stellar career. Glavine scattered
seven hits over eight innings, and the Braves played highlight-reel
defense in a 6-3 victory over the backpedaling Astros.
</P>
<P>
   After winning a season-high five consecutive games, the Astros
have dropped three in a row, and they open a four-game series
tonight in Florida, where their all-time record is 14-21.
</P>
<P>
   Glavine became the 96th pitcher in major-league history to reach
200 victories, and he joined Roger Clemens and Greg Maddux as the
only active pitchers to accomplish the feat.
</P>
<P>
   It was an emotional day for the veteran lefthander, who left to
a standing ovation from the crowd of 40,613, which included his
parents and other family members.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always get nervous before I pitch,'' said Glavine, who needs
26 victories to tie Hall of Famer Phil Niekro's franchise record
for the most victories since the team moved to Atlanta. ``Today it
was more excitement than nervousness, though. It felt like a
playoff game.''
</P>
<P>
   The Astros didn't need the reminder. With memories of Walt
Weiss' defensive gem from last year's Division Series still fresh,
the Astros could have done without all of the hit-stealing that
occurred Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   At times, it looked as though the Braves had two or three extra
fielders on the diamond. Then again, center fielder Andruw Jones
and rookie shortstop Rafael Furcal often exhibit the range of two
men each. Meanwhile, the Astros remained in their defensive slump,
committing two errors and allowing a pair of unearned runs.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a stark contrast in the fielding,'' Astros manager
Larry Dierker said. ``We made a lot of errors, and they made some
nice plays. . . . But don't get me wrong. Glavine is a tough guy to
beat. He doesn't throw that many pitches over the middle of the
plate, and he makes pitches where guys can't really drive the ball.
That's why he's won the Cy Young Award, been an All-Star and is on
his way to the Hall of Fame maybe.''
</P>
<P>
   Glavine (13-5) allowed all three Astros runs, and lefthander
Mike Remlinger bailed him out of a ninth-inning jam to notch his
ninth save.
</P>
<P>
   Astros starter Chris Holt (4-12) lost for the sixth time in his
last seven decisions. He allowed six runs (four earned) on nine
hits in five innings.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just wasn't able to pitch out of trouble,'' said Holt. ``It
seems like funny things happen when I'm out there. I don't know
what I can do except to keep battling. Hopefully, things will
change, because this is getting old. I'd like to finish strong.''
</P>
<P>
   Glavine surrendered only two hits over the first five innings _
back-to-back singles to lead off the second. He retired 14 of the
first 17 batters he faced, including 11 in a row at one point.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the Braves did all of their scoring during the first
five innings. Included were two unearned runs in the second, when
Jeff Bagwell's error on a bad-hop grounder kept the inning alive
long enough for the Braves to take an early lead.
</P>
<P>
   Braves second baseman Keith Lockhart doubled home a run in the
fourth, and the Braves scored three more runs in a fifth-inning
spurt highlighted by Javy Lopez's two-run double. Astros relievers
Doug Henry and Joe Slusarski combined for three innings of
scoreless relief after Holt's exit.
</P>
<P>
   Bagwell drove in the Astros' first run with a two-out single in
the sixth, and RBI singles by Moises Alou and Tony Eusebio gave the
Astros hopes of a comeback in the ninth.
</P>
<P>
   The potential tying run was in the on-deck circle when pinch
hitter Bill Spiers sent a grounder toward the middle of the
infield. It looked like a base hit until Lockhart made a diving
stop and flipped the ball to second base for a game-ending
forceout.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those guys made a lot of great plays,'' Astros second baseman
Craig Biggio said. ``When a team plays defense the way they did,
there's not much you can do.''
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
