<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELS-WHITESOX-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANGELS GIVE IT AWAY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ The Anaheim Angels got the bat they needed in
the trade for Ron Gant, but Gant's bat would not have helped Sunday
the way the Angels played defense in an ugly, 11-7, 10-inning loss
to the Chicago White Sox before 27,513 at Edison Field.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels made a season-worst five errors, including two by
third baseman Troy Glaus, but still came within one strike of
winning the game in nine innings. Closer Troy Percival gave up
three runs in the ninth inning, turning a 6-4 lead into a 7-6
deficit.
</P>
<P>
   After the Angels tied the game in the bottom of the ninth on a
sacrifice fly by Garret Anderson, the White Sox scored four more in
the top of the 10th to put the game away and salvage a split in the
four-game series.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was one of the few real poor games we've played
defensively,'' Angels manager Mike Scioscia said. ``Errors are part
of the game but we didn't get it done in a lot of ways.
Cutoff-relay, bunt plays, routine plays. Those were just not there
today. We'll get it together.
</P>
<P>
   ``Long before Percy was in the game, we left a crack in the door
open too far. You can't do that with a club as talented as that.''
</P>
<P>
   A two-run triple by Tim Salmon gave the Angels what seemed was a
comfortable 6-2 lead in the seventh inning. After all, the Angels
began the night 45-3 in games when leading after the seventh
inning. But in the eighth, everything fell apart.
</P>
<P>
   The White Sox got two important runs in the eighth inning, and
both were unearned. With runners on second and third and two out,
Jose Valentin hit a grounder to third, but it went under Glaus'
glove for an error, allowing one run to score. After Mark Petkovsek
replaced Mike Holtz, Frank Thomas' RBI single cut the Angels lead
to 6-4.
</P>
<P>
   That set the stage for the ninth when Percival let the lead slip
away.
</P>
<P>
   The White Sox had a runner on first with two out and Percival
was one strike away from finishing it. But Greg Norton fouled off
five pitches from Percival and eventually drew a walk.
</P>
<P>
   That brought up No. 9 hitter Mark Johnson, who began the game
hitting .223. Johnson lined a 95-mph fastball into the right-center
field gap to score two runs and tie the game at 6. Ray Durham, who
was 0 for 5 at that point, followed with an RBI double to give the
White Sox a 7-6 lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew going into the game I had no off-speed pitch,'' said
Percival, who was pitching in his third consecutive game. ``Tonight
I just didn't throw the ball very good. I was trying to get the
ball down and left it up and out over the plate.''
</P>
<P>
   The Angels rallied in their half of the ninth. Two walks
sandwiched around a single loaded the bases with one out for
Anderson, who hit a line drive to left field that Carlos Lee
snared. Scott Spiezio tagged from third and scored to tie the game.
</P>
<P>
   With a chance to win it, Glaus hit a scorching line drive, but
it went right at third baseman Herbert Perry for the final out.
</P>
<P>
   The White Sox got their four-run rally in the 10th started on a
broken- bat single by Frank Thomas and a ground ball that hit
second base for another hit. Later in the inning, Jeff Abbott and
Lee had two-run singles.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's baseball,'' Scioscia said. ``Hopefully you're going to
get some breaks, but we can't say we didn't get a break here or a
break there. We let this game slip away.''
</P>
<P>
   Because of the trade of Kent Bottenfield, Angels starter Seth
Etherton might have had the added pressure of representing all of
the Angels' young starters Sunday. But he responded with one of his
best starts of the season, giving up two runs and nine hits in 6
innings.
</P>
<P>
   He finished strong, getting Perry on a short fly to center
field, keeping Thomas on third while getting the second out of the
inning and holding an Angels' 3-2 lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll take a 3-2 lead anytime,'' Etherton said. ``Our relievers
have done a great job all year. I'll give the ball to them every
time.''
</P>
</TEXT>
