<SLUG> BC-TEN-CROUSE-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THERE'S NO QUESTIONING GAMBILL'S HEART
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KAREN CROUSE  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Jan-Michael Gambill retired on Sunday? Say it
isn't so! He's too young to call it quits.
</P>
<P>
   Gambill turned 23 last month; goodness knows Jimmy Connors has
grudges older than that. If Gambill is gone, can the Backstreet
Boys be long for the pop charts? Can men's tennis in the U.S. be
long for prosperity?
</P>
<P>
   Oh, wait. What's that you say? Gambill merely retired from the
Mercedes-Benz Cup final after splitting the first two sets with
Michael Chang?
</P>
<P>
   Whew! What a relief to know Gambill has a gimpy left knee and a
gimpy right ankle but nothing that will permanently sideline
America's Gladiator. Because this much was obvious just watching
the wunderkind from Washington state limp through a week of singles
and doubles matches here hard on the heels of taking eventual
champion Pete Sampras to four spandex-tight sets in the
quarterfinals at Wimbledon and going down with the ship, USS Mayday
in a Davis Cup semifinal in Spain:
</P>
<P>
   Professional tennis needs Gambill even more than did the
organizers of the 2000 Tour stop at the L.A. Tennis Center; more
than Hollywood or ``Tiger Beat'' magazine or the baby tigers
Gambill helps care for in his hometown of Spokane.
</P>
<P>
   As he showed Sunday, Gambill is a gamer. That alone makes him a
rarer bird than a finesse player on the ATP Tour, where the only
thing more egregious than the egos are the excuses. We're talking
about a climate so polluted that no one blinked twice earlier this
year when Marcelo Rios, a one-time No. 1, retired from a
first-round match against Tommy Haas with what appeared to be
nothing more serious than a bruised ego after losing the first two
sets in lackluster fashion.
</P>
<P>
   The problem with crying ``Ow'' is that after a while no one
believes it when a player really is hurt. So it was some people
wondered aloud how it could be that Andre Agassi suffered a back
injury in a car accident in his hometown of Las Vegas that was bad
enough to keep him out of this tournament but not bad enough to
warrant filing a police report.
</P>
<P>
   Hey, blame Rios. As long as a single player tanks, the whole
Tour will suffer.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Gambill had his share of second-guessers Sunday.
Everybody but his brother wanted to know why he hadn't defaulted
his semifinals doubles match with partner Scott Humphries. Gambill
and Humphries defeated Wayne Ferreira and Kevin Ullyett 6-4, 6-7
(3-7), 6-3 in a match that didn't end until Saturday had given way
to Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, Gambill's tender knees needed another three-set
match like actor George Hamilton needs more sun. And yet he never
seriously considered pulling out of the match. What comes as second
nature to some players is anathema to this athlete.
</P>
<P>
   As Gambill's younger brother Torrey explained, ``He wasn't going
to screw up his doubles partner. He was worried about him.''
</P>
<P>
   Imagine that, a tennis player ranked in the world's top-100
(with a bullet) who recognizes that other players have feelings
too, who puts someone else's well-being above his own. If Gambill
represents the next breed of superstars, we say hooray for men's
tennis!
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a great effort on his part the whole week,'' said
Humphries, who worried that his doubles partner was over-extending
himself even as the pair was prolonging its run in the tournament.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's always in the back of your mind,'' Humphries said. ``But
then if you know Jan-Michael you know if it's at all possible for
him to play, he will. If Jan-Michael has 10 percent to give, he
going to go out and give 10 percent.''
</P>
<P>
   This year's L.A. Tour stop would have had more star power if
more players had been willing to give whatever they've got, like
Gambill. If the tournament failed to stir the sportsman in you,
blame Rios (and Co.), not the beleaguered tournament officials.
</P>
<P>
   The most terrible transgression Gambill was guilty of on this
week came later rather than sooner. After walking out to the court
to accept his runners-up trophy with a limp more pronounced than
Lakers coach Phil Jackson's, Gambill thanked, among others, the car
dealer who loaned him a Jaguar to drive around L.A. for the week.
Never mind that Mercedes-Benz had spent good money to lend their
regal name to the proceedings.
</P>
<P>
   So Gambill isn't perfect, just perfect for professional tennis.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
