<HEADER>
A7894 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BOX-BOXING-COLUMN-LAD     07-31 1031
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-BOXING-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRIDE GOT IN THE WAY OF REASON
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MICHAEL ROSENTHAL  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ I supported the idea of giving Julio Cesar Chavez
one last shot at glory. I believed he deserved the right to go out
on his own terms after all he's given boxing.
</P>
<P>
   Well, I was wrong: No one deserves what we saw Saturday night
from Phoenix - not Chavez, not the sport, not the fans.
</P>
<P>
   We wince when we think of Muhammad Ali's second-to-last fight,
one for which he worked himself into good shape yet was pummeled by
Larry Holmes.
</P>
<P>
   We wince when we think of Sugar Ray Leonard's last two fights,
pathetic knockout losses to Terry Norris and Hector Camacho.
</P>
<P>
   Now, we'll wince when we think of Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   Chavez, like Ali, had whipped himself into reasonably good
condition. He was near the 140-pound weight limit a month before
the fight and it showed: His body hadn't looked as tight as it was
Saturday in years.
</P>
<P>
   However, he's 38 years old and no amount of preparation could
change that. He no longer has the tools to compete at this level.
He said as much in a television interview immediately after the
fight: ``The body just doesn't have the strength.''
</P>
<P>
   Many had the foresight to say: ``No, this isn't right. This is
what's wrong with boxing.'' For example, Arizona senator John
McCain, a boxing reformer and devoted fan, lobbied against staging
the fight in his state.
</P>
<P>
   Let's hope the rest of us learned a lesson.
</P>
<P>
   The motives of WBC head Jose Sulaiman are suspect. He named
Chavez his No. 1 140-pound contender even though the former
six-time champion was beaten silly in a 10-round loss to journeyman
Willy Wise in October and hadn't faced a decent opponent since he
lost to Oscar De La Hoya in September of 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Sulaiman and Don King, Chavez's promoter, undoubtedly
anticipated a few more big paydays out of Chavez had he somehow
beaten Kostya Tszyu.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, that's not how Chavez should've received his final
opportunity to fight for a world championship. That he was the No.
1 contender in the most respected of boxing's sanctioning bodies is
an indication of how corrupt the sport remains.
</P>
<P>
   The Arizona Athletic Commission was more misguided than
sinister. That group would probably say it had no choice: Chavez
passed all the physical tests required for licensing and he still
has some skills.
</P>
<P>
   However, on Saturday, it was never more clear that a
commission's duties go beyond such elementary criteria. It must
determine - based on the testimony of experts - whether its
matchups are likely to be reasonably competitive to protect the
fighters and the fans. One would think this would be a particularly
high priority in a championship fight.
</P>
<P>
   Obviously, Saturday's bout was anything but competitive. Tszyu
is one of the most talented fighters in the world, Chavez just
another junior welterweight - if that.
</P>
<P>
   Again, some of us had genuine motives. Chavez wanted to go out
with ``pride and dignity'' and we wanted to give him that chance.
</P>
<P>
   The problem was that Chavez hardly looked proud and dignified
when he was on all fours after he was knocked down by Tszyu in an
ugly sixth round. Chavez, who simply grew tired and was unable to
defend himself, was as much embarrassed as he was hurt and we were
embarrassed for him.
</P>
<P>
   No one did him any favors by allowing him to fight Tszyu. Had
those who supported his right to give it one more shot really been
looking out for his best interests, they would've demanded: ``Don't
let this happen.''
</P>
<P>
   The only good that came out of a sad night was Chavez's
proclamation that he has had enough and plans to retire. If only it
could've happened one fight sooner.
</P>
<P>
   Ayala-Campas: What are we to think of Tony Ayala after his
eighth-round loss to Yory Campas on Friday?
</P>
<P>
   If Ayala did break his hand in the second round as he and his
handlers claim - and we'll assume he did - then he gave a
remarkable performance and he shouldn't be dismissed as a contender
at 37 and after 16 years in prison for rape.
</P>
<P>
   If the injury was exaggerated, if that was the best Ayala has to
offer, then he'll probably never be among the elite fighters.
</P>
<P>
   Either way, he doesn't have much time to rebuild after his first
defeat. His best opportunity to spring-board himself to a title
shot might be lost.
</P>
<P>
   Big deal: No one is going to get too excited about heavyweight
Tye Fields of Des Moines, Iowa, until he faces a legitimate
heavyweight, but he sure is intriguing.
</P>
<P>
   Fields, who is 6-foot-9, 285 pounds, has knocked out each of 11
overmatched opponents in the first round. That's the kind of
statistic that piques the interest of money-hungry promoters and
blood-thirsty fans.
</P>
<P>
   Fields apparently is a bit crude but has the physical strength
to overwhelm the type of opponents he meets in the Midwest.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are looking for a quality opponent for Tye's next fight,''
said his manager, Ed Lahart. ``With more training and ring
experience behind him, he will be a contender to be reckoned with
among heavyweight fighters.''
</P>
<P>
   We'll see.
</P>
<P>
   Rabbit punches: Hasim Rahman faces Frankie Swindell in a
10-round heavyweight bout on Friday in Las Vegas on ESPN2. ...
</P>
<P>
   Zab Judah, who hopes to fight Tszyu before the end of the year,
defend his IBF junior welterweight title against Terronn Millett in
Connecticut on Showtime.
</P>
<P>
   Rising lightweight prospect Juan Lazcano faces James Leija in a
10- round lightweight bout on that card. ...
</P>
<P>
   Also on Saturday, WBA flyweight champion Sornpichai Pisnurachank
(19-0,16 KOs) defends his title against U.S. Olympian Eric Morel
(26-0, 16 KOs) on Saturday in Madison, Wisc., on HBO.
</P>
<P>
   And, in one more Saturday bout, hot prospect Alex Trujillo
(17-0, 14 KOs) faces Mark Suarez (17-0, 6 KOs) in a 10-round junior
welterweight bout on Saturday in Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   A tape of that fight, along with a heavyweight bout between
Jorge Luis Gonzalez and Cliff Couser, will be televised Sunday on
Fox Sports Net.
</P>
<P>
   Trujillo, a very aggressive fighter with power in both hands,
came from Puerto Rico to work with Joe Goossen in Van Nuys.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
