<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-31 02:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7895 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r e BC-CONVENTION-COVERAGE-S     07-31 0809
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONVENTION-COVERAGE-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NETWORKS RESIST THE GOP'S PHILADELPHIA STORY
</HEADLINE>
  By JOHN DIAZ 
c.2000, San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Twenty years ago, when the television networks still saw
political conventions as a prime-time showcase for their reporting
talent and dazzling new technologies, NBC's Tom Brokaw cut a bold
fashion statement at Detroit's Joe Louis Arena.
</P>
<P>
   The network's fastest-rising star wore jogging shoes with his
suit to cover the floor action on opening night of the Republican
National Convention.
</P>
<P>
   The next night, it seemed that half the reporters on the floor
had tossed aside their wingtips and loafers to follow Brokaw's
lead. After all, the Big Three networks _ with upstart CNN making
its debut in an arena skybox _ set the tone for convention coverage
in every way.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the biggest development of that convention came not from
the floor or the podium, but from the skybox booths, where Gerald
Ford openly speculated about the prospect of ``a co-presidency.''
His interviews with Walter Cronkite and Barbara Walters caused
delegates and reporters to scramble to find a TV, and ultimately
prompted nominee Ronald Reagan to make a dramatic trip to the
convention hall to announce that George Bush, not Ford, would be
his running mate.
</P>
<P>
   It was the first live convention I covered, and I came away
wondering if the real front-row seats belonged to the millions of
Americans parked in front of the TV.
</P>
<P>
   Not anymore. The parties got smart and drained all remaining
risks of drama out of their convention schedules. By 1980, the
Reagan strategists knew better than to allow the sort of
freewheeling platform debate and 39 vice presidential nominations
(Archie Bunker, Mao Zedong included) that left George McGovern
making his 1972 acceptance speech at 3 a.m. eastern time. These
days, even the vice presidential selections are locked up before
the first thump of the gavel.
</P>
<P>
   Neither George W. Bush nor Al Gore would dare allow any such
substance or frivolity to crash four days of orchestrated pablum.
</P>
<P>
   It might seem odd that anyone would complain about lack of
coverage of an event that has drawn 15,000 credentialed
journalists, but that is exactly what is happening in Philadelphia.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
    &UR; (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL ADD FOLLOWS) &LR;  &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In a hand-wringing session Sunday at Philadelphia's historic
City Hall, Republican Chairman Jim Nicholson and Democratic
Chairman Edward Rendell bemoaned the cost to democracy of the
networks' diminishing convention coverage. The three major networks
averaged more than 40 hours of live telecasts at the 1980
conventions; this year, NBC and CBS are planning on 10 hours at
each convention. ABC will show just five.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything doesn't have to be news,'' Nicholson protested at
the session sponsored by Harvard University's Joan Shorenstein
Center on Press, Politics and Public Policy. He called the GOP
convention a ``national town hall meeting'' with ``important
information'' to convey.
</P>
<P>
   When, in the name of our Founding Fathers, have town hall
meetings become one-way dialogues? A real ``town hall meeting''
among Republicans might _ just might _ generate some discussion of
a platform that opposes civil rights for gays and would outlaw
abortion even in cases of rape and incest. Attention party leaders:
Of all the facts and figures that were tossed about, one of the
most surprising was a study that showed nominees received equally
strong ``bounces'' in the polls from conventions where the
delegates aired their differences.
</P>
<P>
   Even with the proliferation of news-oriented cable channels and
Internet sites that will generate an unprecedented level of readily
available information about this convention, there is still reason
to be concerned about the lack of attention on network airwaves.
</P>
<P>
   Nicholson pointed out that 25 percent of U.S. households do not
subscribe to cable TV, and there is a very real ``digital divide''
when it comes to access to the Internet _ and it falls, he
correctly noted, along racial lines.
</P>
<P>
   The implications of the digital divide, however, go well beyond
Nicholson's concern that low-income minorities will not be able to
see gavel-to-gavel coverage of the GOP convention. The issue cuts
to the core of how early and how extensively young people are
exposed to the marvelous learning tools available online. It is
inseparable from the larger question of how to help those who have
been left behind in the economic boom. These matters do not lend
themselves to easy answers or soft-focus speeches, but this society
ignores them at its long-term peril.
</P>
<P>
   These are the types of difficult issues the parties should be
debating openly and making hard, specific commitments to address.
</P>
<P>
   And guess what? If they did, the networks would cover them.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
