<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-31 08:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7979 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a BC-INTEL-AZR &LR;      07-31 0788
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INTEL-AZR </SLUG>
  
BC-INTEL-AZR(a) 
 &HT;    A MODEL POLLUTION PROGRAM(a) 
 &HT;    (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)(a) 
 &HT;    By BRUNO J. NAVARRO(a) 
 &HT;    c.2000 The Arizona Republic(a) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   (PHOENIX) - The idea was simple: Intel would voluntarily add
pollution controls at its computer chip plant in Chandler in
exchange for less regulatory red tape.
</P>
<P>
   That was four years ago. Now, company officials, government
representatives and at least one environmentalist praise the
federal program as a model that benefits businesses and the
environment.
</P>
<P>
   As a result of the program, Intel has published information on
the Web about its air emissions, has exceeded wastewater treatment
standards and recycled wooden crates used to transport equipment.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even when we're fully built out, the microchip plant will be
the largest in the world, and we're still a minor source for air
emissions,'' said Jim Larsen, manager of strategic programs for
Intel. ``It's phenomenal.''
</P>
<P>
   But critics say the program relies too heavily on the honor
system and leaves open the potential for abuse.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody actually goes out there and does testing,'' said Dave
Matusow, a member of Intel's citizens advisory group. ``Even though
there's technology to do that, it's not actually utilized.''
</P>
<P>
   Intel, which is building the $2 billion Fab-22 computer chip
manufacturing plant in Chandler, was among the first to sign up
with Project XL in November 1996.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton touted the federal program as a way to boost
environmental protections while reducing regulatory burdens on big
business.
</P>
<P>
   Watchdog groups criticized the program before it was
implemented, arguing that it gave too much freedom to large
companies without providing equal benefits to the communities that
would be affected.
</P>
<P>
   Intel's Larsen said Project XL has led to increased
accountability because the company publishes on its Web site
detailed environmental information, ranging from chemical recycling
to emissions of air pollutants.
</P>
<P>
   Company resources, Larsen said, are available to do that because
Intel doesn't constantly have to file paperwork that can climb into
the tens of thousands of pages.
</P>
<P>
   ``Money's going into environmental performance instead of
meeting regulations,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   That's what concerns Matusow, a software programmer who
volunteered to join the Project XL advisory group.
</P>
<P>
   Intel will be allowed to build its 360,000-square-foot facility
- among the world's largest - without seeking any additional
environmental permits, he said.
</P>
<P>
   But Matusow acknowledges that Intel's willingness to publish its
environmental information is ``superior to what had been
required.''
</P>
<P>
   Jo Crumbaker of the Maricopa County Environmental Services
Department said this was one of the program's highlights.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the strongest benefits {hellip} was the presentation of
information in a form the local community can understand,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   Intel has published on the Web vast amounts of detailed
information each quarter about its emissions, making it available
to anyone with access to the Internet. The site is at
www.intel.com/intel/oth er/ehs/projectxl/.
</P>
<P>
   However, Crumbaker joined Matusow in saying the project demanded
a heavy time commitment in its early stages, sometimes involving
four meetings a week, each lasting up to six hours. Plus, Matusow
said, the technical nature of the information provided was
overwhelming before experts were hired.
</P>
<P>
   That aspect limited public input, argued Ted Smith, executive
director of the San Jose-based Silicon Valley Toxics Coalition .
</P>
<P>
   Smith also claimed that Project XL benefited Intel far more than
Valley residents.
</P>
<P>
   ``They got the grand slam of regulatory relief,'' Smith said.
</P>
<P>
   The group helped organize more than 100 labor and environmental
leaders voicing concerns over Project XL when it was introduced.
But it became difficult to rally lawmakers to its cause, he said,
so their concerns were never fully addressed.
</P>
<P>
   ``The environmental community in Arizona is pretty small to
begin with and pretty demoralized,'' Smith said.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, another member of the Project XL citizens group who is also
an environmentalist said Intel and the program have worked to
increase public accountability.
</P>
<P>
   ``If all the industries in the Valley followed their example,
they'd pollute less,'' said Steve Brittle, president of Don't Waste
Arizona. ``These people at Intel are refreshingly different.''
</P>
<P>
   One example Brittle offered and Chandler city officials have
cited is Intel's processing of wastewater to near drinking-quality
purity before returning it to the aquifer.
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Reach the reporter at bruno.navarro(a)arizona republic.com or
(602) 444-7940.
</P>
</TEXT>
