<DOCNO> NYT20000731.0032 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-31 08:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7980 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a BC-HAYWORTH-AZR &LR;      07-31 0990
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HAYWORTH-AZR </SLUG>
  
BC-HAYWORTH-AZR(a) 
 &HT;    HAYWORTH'S PAC LUCKY IN GAMING CASH(a) 
 &HT;    (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)(a) 
 &HT;    By REPORTER NAME(a) 
 &HT;    c.2000 The Arizona Republic(a) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   (PHOENIX) - Three years ago, Rep. J.D. Hayworth orchestrated the
defeat of a $1.9billion tax on Indian gaming.
</P>
<P>
   Now he's cashing in on that effort.
</P>
<P>
   Hayworth has raised more than $60,000 from Indian gaming
interests for his political action committee, including donations
from 15 Indian nations with gambling, according to federal campaign
finance records.
</P>
<P>
   The Scottsdale congressman's committee, called TEAM PAC, raised
about $80,000 through May. And most of that cash is being funneled
to Republican House and Senate candidates who might not know much
of the money comes from gaming interests.
</P>
<P>
   Larry Makinson, executive director of the Center for Responsive
Politics, calls the situation ``fascinating'' and compares it to
attempts by the tobacco industry to camouflage campaign
contributions by donating through subsidiaries.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the potentials of leadership PACs is to act as money
laundries - to take money from radioactive sources that might be
embarrassing and filter it to candidates,'' Makinson said.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I think it's quite extraordinary to have two-thirds of the
money of a leadership PAC coming from one industry. That's very
unusual. And particularly since he's giving to conservative
candidates who might have real problems taking money from gambling
interests.''
</P>
<P>
   OTHER INTERESTS
</P>
<P>
   But the GOP lawmaker downplays the gaming ties, pointing out
that Indian nations have many economic interests besides gambling.
Hayworth, like many conservatives, opposes gambling. But he says he
recognizes it is legal and that tribal sovereignty must be
respected.
</P>
<P>
   ``For better or worse, when Congress passed the Indian Gaming
Act in 1986, that offered another avenue that perhaps I would not
advocate for economic opportunity. Yet it is what is part and
parcel of a free people,'' Hayworth said.
</P>
<P>
   Hayworth points to Gila River Farms and high-tech businesses on
the Navajo Reservation as examples of other businesses that are
thriving on reservations.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think across Indian country as tribes move toward economic
empowerment, what we're finding is a commonality of interests:
lower taxes, more jobs, more opportunity and no taxation in
tribally owned enterprises,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It just so happens that one out of every four of my
constituents is Native American. I take a look at the big picture.
And yes, to a certain degree it does involve economic enterprises
that involve gaming. But that's not the totality of the picture.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, all of the Indian nations that donated to TEAM PAC
operate gaming businesses. The committee is a leadership PAC, a
legal tool used by members of political parties to funnel thousands
of dollars into tightly contested congressional races. The
committees also are a way for ambitious officeholders seeking to
build support for leadership posts and establish national networks
they can tap to help their own election bids down the line.
</P>
<P>
   Makinson said Indian nations and gaming interests are rapidly
increasing donations to political campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've exploded,'' he said. ``The casino and gaming industry
is the fastest growing industry that there is.''
</P>
<P>
   Gary Bohnee, a spokesman for the Gila River Indian Community,
said political involvement is a natural outgrowth of Indian
nations' growing economic success. He pointed out that Hayworth has
supported a number of other issues besides gaming, including water
rights and tribal sovereignty.
</P>
<P>
   The tribe's $4,000 donation to TEAM PAC, Bohnee said, was to
support Hayworth's efforts in Congress.
</P>
<P>
   ``The community is fortunate to be in the position to offer
assistance in that regard,'' Bohnee said, adding that Indian tribes
have discovered what many groups have known for years about the
power of campaign money in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a way to get in the door. It's fair to say that a lot of
the actions happen in Congress come from the relationships that are
developed with members.''
</P>
<P>
   And Kate Spilde, director of research for the National Indian
Gaming Association, says the infusion of money from gaming has
given tribes much more power at the national level. But she says
that comes not from campaign donations, but from the solidarity
that pursuing the issue creates.
</P>
<P>
   Although most Indian nations traditionally lean Democratic,
Spilde said tribes are branching out.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gambling creates strange bedfellows,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   NO PROBLEM WITH SOURCE
</P>
<P>
   Several of the more than 20 campaigns that have accepted
donations from TEAM PAC were contacted for this story. Only two,
Reps. Brian Bilbray, R-Calif., and Merrill Cook, R-Utah, responded.
</P>
<P>
   Both said they had no problem taking the money.
</P>
<P>
   Connie Humphrey, Cook's chief of staff, pointed out there's
little gambling in Utah, where most voters oppose it. She said Cook
didn't know that the $1,000 TEAM PAC donation to his campaign
contained money from gaming interests. But she added he probably
would have accepted the money anyway.
</P>
<P>
   And Bilbray's chief of staff, John Woodard, said the only two
groups Bilbray refuses to accept money from are the tobacco
industry and the National Rifle Association.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not seen as a negative,''' Woodard said. ``A lot of the
tribes are using the money to improve local communities, and that's
good.''
</P>
<P>
   Hayworth says he isn't surprised to see his colleagues accept
the donations. He vows to continue to build connections between
conservatives and Indian nations.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are no permanent adversaries,'' Hayworth said. ``There
are, instead, when it comes to the first Americans, only permanent
interests. And to the extent that our majority can find a common
interest with Native Americans across the broad spectrum of
economic endeavors, I welcome that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-31-00 0802EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000731.0033 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-31 08:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7981 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a BC-GOPMCCAIN-AZR &LR;      07-31 0798
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOPMCCAIN-AZR </SLUG>
  
BC-GOPMCCAIN-AZR(a) 
 &HT;    MCCAIN RELEASES HIS DELEGATES(a) 
 &HT;    (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)(a) 
 &HT;    By JEFF BARKER(a) 
 &HT;    c.2000 The Arizona Republic(a) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   (PHILADELPHIA) - An encounter with hecklers during a speech
Sunday demonstrated for Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz., the difficulty
of trying to straddle two political worlds.
</P>
<P>
   It was a bizarre day - one that only an unorthodox politician
like McCain could have.
</P>
<P>
   On the day before the opening of the Republican National
Convention, McCain found himself being booed and hissed inside a
college auditorium during a ``Shadow Convention'' intended to offer
a hip alternative to the button-down GOP version. Almost all the
other prominent Republicans in town stayed away.
</P>
<P>
   Hours later, McCain was basking in the glow of a tribute to his
aborted presidential campaign by his former delegates and campaign
staff. Confetti rained from a ballroom ceiling, and McCain choked
back tears as he freed the delegates to vote for soon-to-be nominee
George W. Bush.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a good fight, my friends,'' McCain said. ``I release
all of these delegates.''
</P>
<P>
   The day's highs and lows grew out of the dual agenda that McCain
is pursuing here.
</P>
<P>
   As a senior GOP leader, he is dutifully trying to rally
independent voters to back Bush, and will address the convention in
that regard Tuesday night. But he is also playing a second role
here: a government reform crusader who seems to stand outside his
party and at times is even disdainful of it.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, McCain's worlds clashed.
</P>
<P>
   He was shouted down, and nearly walked out, as he addressed a
rowdy audience at the Shadow Convention, which is across town from
the real one.
</P>
<P>
   In introducing McCain, syndicated columnist Arianna Huffington
foreshadowed the heckling when she said he is engaged in ``a
special high-wire act'' and is trying to be a reformer ``within the
system.''
</P>
<P>
   The Shadow Convention will spend the next five days mocking
politicians for catering to wealthy special interests, and
criticizing the gap between rich and poor and ``the failed war on
drugs.''
</P>
<P>
   A noisy segment of the predominantly college-age crowd couldn't
handle McCain's blend of party loyalist and reform crusader. They
whooped and applauded when he spoke of shaking up the political
system, but some booed and hissed when he said he ``would urge all
Americans to support my party's nominee, Gov. George Bush of
Texas.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain hesitated, then resumed his praise of Bush as ``the
candidate who offers change.''
</P>
<P>
   The crowd at the University of Pennsylvania's Annenberg School
auditorium soon interrupted again with shouts of ``Wrong!'' and
``This isn't why we're here!''
</P>
<P>
   McCain paused, then said, ``If you like, I do not need to
continue.''
</P>
<P>
   Huffington implored the crowd to be respectful. More catcalls
followed, though McCain was able to finish his remarks.
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, McCain said the interruptions were simply part of
politics. ``We can't shut them out of the political process, and
I'm glad they're in,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the experience pointed to a critical question facing
McCain: Can he keep faith with the GOP without abandoning those who
see him as an independent voice?
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a balancing act,'' said Rick Davis, McCain's former
campaign manager. ``John McCain looks at the field and you get two
choices, and who is closer to getting through his reform agenda?
It's George W. Bush.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain offered a lukewarm endorsement of Bush after the
primaries, and says he'll set aside time to campaign for him before
November. Senior Bush campaign officials joined McCain on Sunday
when he formally released his delegates.
</P>
<P>
   But some Republicans also believe McCain breached etiquette by
not retiring his campaign bus, the ``Straight Talk Express,'' which
he rode to Philadelphia with scores of reporters.
</P>
<P>
   ``In many ways, John McCain is a crusade, and he is a crusade
that transcends this process that's under way whereby each party
picks its nominee,'' said Terry Madonna, a political expert at
Pennsylvania's Millersville University.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Senate is not filled with giants anymore, and McCain has
become a movement,'' Madonna said.
</P>
<P>
   Madonna also said the Bush campaign may have mixed feelings
about McCain. On the one hand, McCain can help Bush by attracting
swing voters - independents and Democrats. On the other, McCain
could siphon away interest from Bush if he is not deferential to
the party nominee.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think being deferential is a role that anybody ought
to play,'' said former Sen. Warren Rudman, R-N.H., a McCain ally
now backing Bush. ``Respectful, yes. Deferential, no. And he is
very respectful of Gov. Bush.''
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Reach the reporter at jeff.barker(a)arizonarepublic.com.
</P>
