<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-31 08:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7986 &Cx1f; tic-z
r e BC-BIOGRAPHY-AZR &LR;      07-31 1483
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIOGRAPHY-AZR </SLUG>
  
 BC-SLUG-BIOGRAPHY-AZR(a) 
 &HT;    BIOGRAPHIES NEVER LOSE POWER TO FASCINATE(a) 
 &HT;    (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)(a) 
 &HT;    By BARBARA YOST(a) 
 &HT;    c.2000 The Arizona Republic(a) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Journalist Elizabeth Taylor's history professor once told her
that the perfect subject for a biography should be a scoundrel.
</P>
<P>
   A dead one.
</P>
<P>
   She took that advice to heart when she began her biography of
one-time Chicago Mayor Richard Daley. Daley fit Taylor's criteria:
dead since 1976 and known for the strong-arm tactics with which he
ruled the Windy City for two decades.
</P>
<P>
   (beginitalic)American Pharaoh: Mayor Richard J. Daley: His
Battle for Chicago and the Nation(enditalic) is just one of the new
biographies being published this year that probe the lives of
famous people from football great Walter Payton to the late
Japanese emperor Hirohito to American newspaper luminary William
Randolph Hearst to Jesus.
</P>
<P>
   Though novels dominate the book trade, biographies are a steady
source of revenue, one of the staple items in the bookseller's
pantry. Even Edmund Morris' offbeat 1999 biography of Ronald Reagan
couldn't kill the genre, though no other author has been inspired
to imitate Morris' controversial style of inserting himself
fictionally into his story.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a fascination with people's lives and the time in
which they lived,'' says Terry Adams, an editor at Little, Brown &AMP;
Co., which published (beginitalic)American Pharaoh(enditalic).
``It's a genre that's of perennial interest.''
</P>
<P>
   Inspired by the nascent biographical genre created by Plutarch
(A.D. 46-119) in (beginitalic)Parallel Lives(enditalic), the
tradition began in earnest during the second century with the
creation of hagiography, in which monks penned the lives of
Christian saints as role models for their congregations.
</P>
<P>
   Today's biographies glorify both the mighty and the lowly. They
fall into two categories: serious, historical works (Carl
Sandburg's (beginitalic)Abraham Lincoln(enditalic), James Boswell's
(beginitalic)The Life of Samuel Johnson(enditalic)) and Kitty
Kelly-style pop-culture treatments ((beginitalic)Jackie
Oh!(enditalic), (beginitalic)The Unauthorized Biography of Frank
Sinatra(enditalic), countless volumes on Princess Diana).
</P>
<P>
   Though most subjects are well known, ordinary people can also
make for fascinating reading - if their story is compelling and
well written or if they rose to fame from humble beginnings.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are really curious about the famous, how they went from
obscurity to re- &QL;
</P>
<P>
   known,'' says Gayle Shanks, book buyer for Changing Hands
bookstore in Tempe.
</P>
<P>
   And, says Adams, ``It has to be a life that resonates today.''
</P>
<P>
   When America needs heroes, he notes, it embraces stories about
people like Charles Lindberg in such works as A. Scott Berg's 1998
(beginitalic)Lindberg(enditalic).
</P>
<P>
   As author Taylor learned, however, biographical subjects need
not be heroic. The Library of Congress lists 351 biographies of
Adolf Hitler, including 1999's (beginitalic)Explaining Hitler: The
Search for the Origins of His Evil (enditalic)by Ron Rosenbaum.
</P>
<P>
   Taylor, literary and Sunday magazine editor of the
(beginitalic)Chicago Tribune(enditalic), first considered writing a
biography of Mayor Daley when she moved to Chicago in 1984 from New
York, where she had been a correspondent for (beginitalic)Time
(enditalic)magazine. As she pored over public records and archives
to acquaint herself with her new city, she gleaned the importance
of Daley's legacy and saw him not only as a local politician but
also as someone whose influence spread beyond the city he embodied.
</P>
<P>
   ``All roads led to Daley,'' she discovered.
</P>
<P>
   In the book, she sums up his importance with one of Daley's own
quotes: ``This is Chicago. This is America.''
</P>
<P>
   Although legendary Chicago journalist Mike Royko had authored
(beginitalic)Boss: Richard J. Daley of Chicago(enditalic) in 1971,
Taylor and co-author Adam Cohen believed the definitive work had
not been written. Royko's book violated her tenet of publishing a
biography only after the subject's death and reportedly so offended
Daley's wife that she would walk into stores and turn copies of the
book to face the wall.
</P>
<P>
   Taylor and Cohen enjoyed the cooperation of a member of the
Daley family but did not write a whitewashed profile. Nor is it the
standard born-in-a-log-cabin time line of events.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not a `what he had for breakfast' kind of biography.
This is not about his personal life,'' she says. ``What's
interesting is how he intersected with the world and with the
city.''
</P>
<P>
   Good biographies put their subjects into that kind of historical
context, says Sarah Gold, editor of forecasts for(beginitalic)
Publishers Weekly,(enditalic) the book industry news magazine.
Analysis helps acquaint the reader with the subject.
</P>
<P>
   An interest in famous people is more than just a penchant for
gossip, Gold says. Some readers gravitate to biographies as a
history lesson, making historical figures popular subjects -
Abraham Lincoln, George Washington, Benjamin Franklin.
</P>
<P>
   And new information can rekindle interest in an old subject.
When stories about Thomas Jefferson's slave mistress, Sally
Hemings, recently became public, Jefferson was suddenly a hot topic
two centuries after his death. In 1998, Joseph J. Ellis published
(beginitalic)American Sphinx: The Character of Thomas
Jefferson(enditalic).
</P>
<P>
   While biographical subjects need not be paragons of virtue, they
must have led interesting lives. A new biography of Cy Young, the
famed 19th-century baseball player who lent his name to a pitching
award, got a lukewarm review from (beginitalic)Publishers
Weekly(enditalic). Young might have been a great pitcher, Gold
says, but his personal life was never major league.
</P>
<P>
   Still, sports figures are always reader favorites. Last
September, David Maraniss published the acclaimed (beginitalic)When
Pride Still Mattered: A Life of Vince Lombardi(enditalic). Cyclist
Lance Armstrong, who beat cancer and then won the Tour de France,
has just published his autobiography, (beginitalic)It's Not About
the Bike: My Journey Back to Life.
</P>
<P>
   (enditalic) And just out: (beginitalic)Payne Stewart: The
Authorized Biography(enditalic), the saga of the golf champion who
died in a freak plane journey last October.
</P>
<P>
   (beginitalic) (enditalic) Lives of celebrated writers also
provide rich fodder for literature. In April, no fewer than two
books on Marcel Proust were published: (beginitalic)Marcel Proust:
A Life(enditalic) by William C. Carter and(beginitalic) Proust's
Way: A Field Guide to In Search of Lost
Time(enditalic)(beginitalic) (enditalic)by Roger Shattuck.
</P>
<P>
   One of the most talked-about books of last fall was
(beginitalic)Secrets of the Flesh: A Life of Colette(enditalic),
Judith Thurman's engrossing tale of the great French writer.
</P>
<P>
   Literary biographies can be a means of interpreting an author's
work, says Judith Sensibar, professor of English at Arizona State
University. Sensibar, a William Faulkner scholar, is writing a
biography that explores Faulkner's relationship with the three most
important women in his life: his mother, Maud; his nanny and former
slave Caroline Barr; and his wife, Estelle.
</P>
<P>
   ``The story is compelling,'' Sensibar says. ``My objective is to
illuminate the reading of his art.''
</P>
<P>
   Using biographies to illuminate an author's art has gone in and
out of favor, says Sensibar's colleague, ASU English Professor
Randel Helms. During the 1930s and '40s, that approach was dubbed
the ``biographical heresy.'' When Helms was in college in the
1960s, professors taught that biographical information was
irrelevant to the study of an author's work.
</P>
<P>
   But when the so-called New Criticism emerged a decade later,
biography was reborn as a means to understanding literature.
</P>
<P>
   Now Helms embraces literary biography. When teaching the poetry
of William Butler Yeats, for example, he notes that many of Yeats'
poems cannot be understood unless the reader is aware of the poet's
fascination with 19th-century Irish activist Maude Gonne, who
snubbed his repeated marriage proposals.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you don't know that story, those poems don't make sense,''
Helms says. ``You'd be reading them in a vacuum.''
</P>
<P>
   Also edifying, he says, is the life of poet Philip Larkin, whose
sweet, romantic poems belied his sexist and racist views.
</P>
<P>
   Biography will remain one of the standards of literature, Shanks
believes. Nearly two millenniums after monks invented the genre,
readers still enjoy snooping into people's lives, whether the
subjects are saints or sinners.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't imagine that changing,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
<P>
   &UR; To read the first chapter of (beginitalic)American
Pharaoh(enditalic), log on to www.azcentral.com/rep/books.
</P>
<P>
   Reach the reporter at barbara.yost(a)arizonarepublic.com or at
(602) 444-7936.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
