<HEADER>
A8012 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u p BC-CVN-MICHIGAN-HNS &LR;      07-31 0670
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CVN-MICHIGAN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
MICHIGAN DELEGATES PREDICT BUSH VICTORY IN FALL &HT;    By ERIC ROSENBERG
 &HT;    c.2000 Hearst Newspapers
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ Michigan State Sen. Bill Schuette, one of the
state's 58 delegates to the Republican National Convention,
predicted Sunday that Texas Gov. George W. Bush will carry the
state in November, despite an unpredictable and fiercely
independent electorate that voted for Bill Clinton in 1996 and
1992.
</P>
<P>
   Schuette, a former congressman who represents the Midland
region, said Bush has broad enough appeal to attract
independent-minded Republicans, Democrats and union members of both
parties, who helped tip the Feb. 22 GOP primary in favor of Ariz.
Sen. John McCain.
</P>
<P>
   ``With a lot of hard work and effort, yes, Bush will win
Michigan,'' Schuette said in an interview. ``It will be a tough and
bare-knuckled campaign, but Bush will pull it off.''
</P>
<P>
   Schuette added that Bush, with his message of tax cuts and
education reform, ``will be a big draw for a lot of Michigan's
swing Democrats and independent voters.''
</P>
<P>
   An ardent Bush supporter, Schuette, a McCain delegate, had been
bound by party rules to vote for the senator here on the first
ballot this week during the Republican National Convention. But
McCain, who won seven primaries and had 231 delegates before he
ended his presidential bid in March, on Sunday urged those
delegates to support Bush.
</P>
<P>
   In Michigan's open primary, McCain won 51 percent of the vote to
43 percent for Bush, mainly because of independent and Democratic
voters.
</P>
<P>
   In an effort to heal party rifts, McCain gave Bush six delegates
to add to the six the Texas governor had won, leaving the Arizona
senator with 46 of the state's 58 delegates coming in to this
week's convention.
</P>
<P>
   Michigan, which has 18 electoral votes, is a key battleground
state that both major parties are aggressively targeting.
</P>
<P>
   A July 18-22 poll of 500 registered state voters showed Bush and
Vice President Al Gore, the presumptive Democratic presidential
nominee, in a dead heat, each with 37 percent, while Green Party
candidate Ralph Nader got 8 percent and Reform Party candidate
Patrick Buchanan, 2 percent. Twelve percent were undecided. The
poll was conducted by Marketing Resource Group of Lansing, Mich.
</P>
<P>
   But among the registered voters likely to vote, 41 percent
supported Bush, 35 percent backed Gore, 7 percent went for Nader
and 2 percent favored Buchanan. Fifteen percent were undecided. The
poll had a margin of error of plus or minus 4.5 percentage points.
</P>
<P>
   Demonstrating the importance Republicans place on Michigan, Bush
plans to make four campaign stops in the state immediately
following the GOP convention.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview, Michigan Gov. John Engler called the state
``competitive'' in the fall election. Engler said Bush will be
targeting the state's labor vote in particular. Roughly 30 percent
of Michigan households include a union member. ``That's a big swing
vote,'' Engler said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if George Bush will get half of the union vote,
but he is going to compete for a big share of it,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   While Michigan supported Clinton in 1992, 19 percent of voters
backed Texas billionaire Ross Perot. Clinton carried the state
again in 1996 and Perot got 9 percent. The state went Republican in
1984, voting to re-elect Ronald Reagan, and in 1988, voting for
George Bush, the Texas governor's father.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Rep. Dave Camp, R-Mich., said the Republican Party
platform, which once again has an unwavering anti-abortion plank,
will not hurt the GOP's chances of winning the state and taking
back the White House.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't mean that everybody in the party thinks that way,''
said Camp, a five-term representative from Michigan's fourth
district and an adviser to House Speaker Dennis Hastert, R-Ill.
Camp added that ``voters may not agree with every candidate on
every issue. I have people who vote for me who don't agree with
me.''
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
