<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICHELIN-ON-TRAVEL-INTRO-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FROM THE HUMBLE TIRE, THE EXALTED STAR
</HEADLINE>
  ATTENTION EDITORS: The following material, the introductory column
for the MICHELIN ON TRAVEL feature from The New York Times
Syndicate, is for use by MICHELIN clients. Nonsubscribers can use
this article only by special arrangement with the Syndicate. For
purchase information, see end of text. 
 (ART ADV: Photos of Michelin guides and Michelin logo are available
on Newscom or by calling William Gonzalez at 212-499-3355.) 
 By GAIL ZWEIGENTHAL 
 c.2000 Michelin 
 World rights 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)
<TEXT>
<P>
   It all began in Paris 100 years ago. The final preparations for
the Universal Exhibition were under way; the construction of the
``underground'' and the Alexander III Bridge were making news. At
the same time, with much less fanfare, automobile-tire impresarios
Edouard and Andre Michelin decided to promote their products by
offering their motorist-clients a book of practical travel
information. After all, the pneumatic tire had been invented only
five years earlier, and traveling by automobile in France was still
a rather daring adventure.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to approximately 50 pages devoted to tires _
frequently the victims of nails in this era of horse-drawn vehicles
_ and such vital information as lists of spare parts to be carried
in the vehicle and where to have it repaired, the guide contained
the first allusions to touring for pleasure, indicating picturesque
roads and sights worth visiting and offering hotel recommendations.
</P>
<P>
   The Michelin brothers introduced their book at the World's Fair
and distributed it free. The cover was red _ and thus was born the
``Red Guide to France.'' Over the next century, the French guide
would be joined by those of 11 other European countries.
</P>
<P>
   Guides to countries such as Belgium, Germany and Switzerland
quickly followed the initial one, but it wasn't until 1920 that
restaurants were included. At the same time, it was decided that
advertisements would no longer be accepted, thus ensuring
impartiality.
</P>
<P>
   In 1926, the ``star'' rating system was introduced _ one star
denoting a ``very good restaurant in its category.''
</P>
<P>
   Five years later came the first designation of two- and
three-star restaurants _ ``worth a detour'' and ``worth a special
journey,'' respectively. (The bestowers of these stars were the
Michelin inspectors _ professionals who generally had backgrounds
in hotel and restaurant management and who performed their jobs
unannounced in complete, and legendary, anonymity.)
</P>
<P>
   It's unlikely that anyone in those early years could have
imagined the future power of the Michelin stars _ so coveted that
restaurant owners would spend enormous sums of money redecorating
their establishments in the desperate hope of getting that elusive
third star. Nor certainly could they have foreseen that the removal
of a star could be so devastating that in 1966, demotion from two
stars to one would cause a Parisian chef to commit suicide.
</P>
<P>
   The star system was also employed in a new group of guides that
were established in 1926 to give travelers all manner of
information about their chosen destinations. Contents included
suggested itineraries, detailed historical background, ratings for
major attractions _ both natural and manmade _ and suggestions for
nighttime activities. Famous places were pointed out as well as
lesser-known places of interest: quaint markets, trendy bistros and
hip nightspots. The cover of THIS book was green _ as are the more
than 200 titles that are part of this series today.
</P>
<P>
   The importance of these volumes was indicated in a 1978 article
in ``Gourmet'' magazine that stated, somewhat tongue in cheek:
``After an existence of some consequence lasting two thousand
years, London has at last arrived. It has been given a Michelin
'Green Guide' of its own.''
</P>
<P>
   In that first London guide, 15 sites were deemed worthy of three
stars, compared with 10 in New York, 9 in Paris and 29 in Rome.
</P>
<P>
   Writers of the ``Green Guides'' are also anonymous, although the
``Gourmet'' sleuth was able to ascertain that that year's London
expert was a native Londoner of Scottish and French parentage who
had been educated at Oxford and had written several other guide
books.
</P>
<P>
   In his preface to the 1900 ``Guide Rouge,'' Andre Michelin
wrote, ``This volume was created at the turn of the century and
will last at least as long.'' Time has proven him to be correct.
</P>
<P>
   (Gail Zweigenthal was formerly editor-in-chief of ``Gourmet''
magazine.)
</P>
<P>
   For more information, consult Michelin's Web site:
</P>
<P>
   www.michelin-travel.com.
</P>
<P>
   ---------------------------------------------
</P>
<P>
   &UR; EDITOR: Visit The New York Times Syndicate Web site at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for more information on MICHELIN
ON TRAVEL and other features. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NONSUBSCRIBERS: To publish a ``separate-buy'' feature article, it
must be purchased. Please contact one of these sales
representatives: &LR;
</P>
<P>
   --U.S. and Canada: DEBRA WEYDERT in New Jersey at
1-732-390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697.
</P>
<P>
   --Europe and Asia: KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11; fax,
47-42-80-44 or 47-42-18-81; telex, 282-942.
</P>
<P>
   --Latin America: ANA PENA in New York, 212-499-3333; fax,
212-499-3382.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-31-00 0934EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
