<DOCNO> NYT20000731.0048 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-31 09:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8031 &Cx1f; tab-z
u t BC-MICHELIN-ON-TRAVEL-BU     07-31 1620
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICHELIN-ON-TRAVEL-BURGUNDY-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOOD, WINE AND ART FLOURISH IN BURGUNDY'S ROCKY SOIL
</HEADLINE>
  ATTENTION EDITORS: The following material, the first destination
column from the MICHELIN ON TRAVEL feature from The New York Times
Syndicate, is for use by MICHELIN clients as of August 1, 2000.
Nonsubscribers can use this article only by special arrangement
with the Syndicate. For purchase information, see end of text. 
 (ART ADV: A photo and a map of Burgundy are available on Newscom or
by calling William Gonzalez at 212-499-3355.) 
 By GAIL ZWEIGENTHAL 
 c.2000 Michelin 
 World rights 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``A meal without wine is like a day without sunshine'' wrote the
18th-century Frenchman Jean-Anthelme Brillat-Savarin. And how
fitting that the great author and gastronome lived in the heart of
Burgundy, then as now, one of the most celebrated wine regions of
the world.
</P>
<P>
   The visitor to Burgundy today will find delectable local
specialties to accompany the great reds and whites. These include
boeuf bourguignon (a rich braise of beef and vegetables)and
coq-au-vin (a savory stew of chicken in red wine), best made with
the snow-white chickens of Bresse, the most southerly part of
Burgundy.
</P>
<P>
   These birds are so prized that they're sold with a special label
guaranteeing their origin and quality and are known throughout
France. Another gastronomic product of the region is known
worldwide: intensely flavorful mustard, manufactured in Dijon and
often sold there in charming, handpainted pots.
</P>
<P>
   What better place to sample this condiment than the city for
which it's named? But those willing to put off gastronomic
gratification for awhile will find that Dijon has other treasures
as well. It has been an influential cultural and architectural
center since its heyday in the 14th and 15th centuries, and much
remains from that time to intrigue the visitor.
</P>
<P>
   Foremost is the magnificent Palace of the Dukes of Burgundy
which now houses the Museum of Fine Arts. Reach it via a stroll
through the surrounding old district of beautiful, stone mansions
and half-timbered 15th- and l6th-century houses.
</P>
<P>
   Many cafes with outdoor seating will beckon temptingly, but head
straight for the Palace. Here you'll find the original ducal
kitchens built in 1435, with six huge chimneys that were barely
sufficient for the preparation of feasts worthy of the Burgundian
court, then the wealthiest and most influential in France.
</P>
<P>
   Art treasures include the tomb of Philip the Bold, the first of
the four dukes of Burgundy to secure the services of the finest
artisans in Europe. Three artists, including Claus Sluter, one of
the greatest sculptors of the 14th century, worked successively for
25 years on the ducal tomb. Philip's effigy, watched over by two
angels, reclines on a dais supported by a procession of amazingly
realistic mourners.
</P>
<P>
   Hours could be spent among this museum's wonders: medieval gold-
and silverware; carved ivory; Renaissance furniture and paintings;
weapons and armor dating from the 13th to the 18th centuries.
</P>
<P>
   Visitors ready to turn their attention to matters gastronomic
might try Mulot and Petitjean where the turn-of-the-century decor
is richly scented with the aroma of the Burgundian specialty, pain
d'epices, a spicy gingerbread cake.
</P>
<P>
   For something to bring home, keep an eye out for the Auger
shops. Here you'll find local products such as candies, mustards
mixed with all manner of herbs and spices, and creme de cassis.
This black currant liqueur is the flavoring for the popular
white-wine-based aperitif named Kir after a former mayor of Dijon
who would serve it tirelessly to guests at the town hall.
</P>
<P>
   The fame of Dijon mustard and boeuf bourguignon notwithstanding,
what most people surely think of when they hear the word Burgundy
is ...wine.
</P>
<P>
   The cultivation of the vine was introduced by the Romans who
conquered the region in 52 BC. The young, fruity reds of
Beaujolais, the crisp, dry whites of Chablis, the truly great crus
of the Cote-d'Or such as Chambertin and Pomerol (red) and
Corton-Charlemagne and Meursault (white) _ these are Burgundy.
</P>
<P>
   A few days devoted to touring the region's vineyards can be
delightful. The celebrated ones of the Cote-d'Or (Golden Hillside)
stretch from Dijon 37 miles south to Santenay. For the true wine
lover, it's thrilling just to drive along this ``Road of the Great
Wines'' and to read, one after another, the signs bearing the
magical names: Clos Vougeot, Savigny-les-Beaune, Romanee-Conti.
</P>
<P>
   Many vineyards are open to the public for guided tours and most
have tastings _ the wine perhaps accompanied by the region's savory
gougere cheese pastry _ with the opportunity to buy bottles or
cases at prices well below what you'd pay back home.
</P>
<P>
   The road south from Dijon leads to Beaune where a wine auction
each November draws connoisseurs from all over the world. Beaune is
known, too, for its architectural treasures. The most famous is the
Hotel-Dieu, which was founded in 1443 as a hospital for the care of
the poor and used as a general hospital until 1971.
</P>
<P>
   The building, with its distinctive roof line covered in
multicolored tiles, was built as an act of penance by Nicholas
Rolin, chancellor to the last of the great dukes of Burgundy.
Miraculously, considering more than five centuries of constant use,
it has survived intact.
</P>
<P>
   It contains an immense hall spanned by carved and painted
timbers where nuns cared for the sick, who lay, sometimes two or
three to a bed, in 28 beds covered in red and white bedcloths.
</P>
<P>
   With little hope for recovery, the poor could look at a painting
of ``The Last Judgment'' by the Flemish master, Rogier van der
Weyden, that dominated an altar at the end of the room. Today, this
formidable polyptych with its graphic depiction of hell is
displayed in a room designed specifically for this purpose. A
mobile magnifying glass enables visitors to study the smallest
details of the highly expressive faces in this masterpiece.
</P>
<P>
   End your cultural experiences in Beaune (as opposed to your
eating, drinking and shopping ones) with a visit to the Burgundy
Wine Museum, housed in the former mansion of the Dukes of Burgundy.
Here, a comprehensive exhibit explains the entire history of
Burgundian vineyards and the cultivation of the vine.
</P>
<P>
   All this talk of wine, but what about cheese, considered by many
its ultimate pairing? Good cheeses abound in Burgundy (try the
sinfully rich Epoisses). It should be no surprise that
Brillat-Savarin had something to say on this subject as well.
</P>
<P>
   His comment? ``A dessert without cheese is like a beautiful
woman with only one eye.'' There can be no doubt that a glass of
fine red Burgundy would have accompanied this epicure's cheese. &QL; 
