<HEADER>
A8037 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-MONEY-HP12C-ART-BOS &LR;      07-31 1158
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONEY-HP12C-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TO PROJECT WEALTH, MORE ADVISERS BETTING ON COUNT OF MONTE CARLO 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A graphic is being sent to NYTNS clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchases by calling
888-346-9867 or 888-603-1036.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SCOTT BERNARD NELSON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the world of financial advice, the HP-12C is a classic.
Planners swear by it, MBAs flaunt it, Web tools are modeled after
it, and savvy investors struggle to understand it.
</P>
<P>
   One of the things Hewlett-Packard's ubiquitous financial
calculator does is forecast how much a pool of money is likely to
be worth in the future. If you start with X amount and add Y
dollars for Z number of years, the palm-size machine can tell you
how much money _ down to the penny _ you'll end up with.
</P>
<P>
   That, at least, is the pitch generations of investors have
heard. But a growing number of professional advisers are
questioning the wisdom of relying on such one-dimensional ``time
value of money'' calculations.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a major limitation to any straight-line compounding
of money,'' said Ray Ferrara, a national director of the
29,000-member Financial Planning Association. ``The number you get
is one of many possible outcomes, and it's not any more or less
likely than thousands of other outcomes.''
</P>
<P>
   In other words, pinning your financial future on the belief that
your investment dollars will grow to a specific amount by a
specific date is a sucker's bet. Maybe they will, but more likely
they won't. And the difference could be big.
</P>
<P>
   Consider the example of a 60-year-old man planning to retire in
five years. He has $1 million set aside, and wants to know how much
it will grow to on retirement day.
</P>
<P>
   Most advisers would simply plug the numbers into their HP-12C,
or one of the numerous Web sites or computer programs that do
essentially the same calculation. Assuming annual returns of 11
percent on his investments, the man would end up with $1.69 million
five years down the road.
</P>
<P>
   But assume that instead of earning exactly 11 percent each year,
the man's portfolio lost 15 percent the first year and 26 percent
the second (roughly the performance of the S&AMP;P 500 in 1972 and
1973). It might then post gains of 46 percent, 30 percent, and 20
percent the next three years to bring the overall average to 11
percent.
</P>
<P>
   In the second case, the man's pot of money would grow to $1.43
million over five years _ $252,000 less than under the flat-line
assumption.
</P>
<P>
   ``It turns out that the timing of returns is critical,'' Ferrara
said. ``It's not enough to say that a client's money is likely to
earn 11 percent per year without giving them a sense that the way
those returns are generated could make a difference.''
</P>
<P>
   To deal with that uncertainty, some advisers and at least one
financial-services company are turning to Monte Carlo analysis. And
like most trends, Monte Carlo is rapidly moving online.
</P>
<P>
   Regardless of whether it's on the Internet or in software, Monte
Carlo analysis uses hundreds or even thousands of calculations
rather than a single one. It takes a list of potential market
returns, which in the case of our example might be plotted like a
bell curve around 11 percent, and runs the projection over and over
again using returns pulled at random from the list.
</P>
<P>
   Done enough times, the results form a pattern that can tell you
the probability of achieving your goals.
</P>
<P>
   In the case of the 60-year-old man, for example, Monte Carlo
analysis might tell him that he has a 48 percent chance of actually
having at least $1.69 million by retirement. If he needs that much
money but isn't comfortable with a probability less than 50-50, he
can adjust variables in the calculation _ years until retirement,
for example _ until the likelihood increases to, say, 70 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone is convinced that Monte Carlo analysis will take
the financial-planning industry by storm.
</P>
<P>
   Morningstar research director John Rekenthaler wrote this week
on his firm's Web site that ``Monte Carlo simulations aren't
intrinsically better than conventional mathematics,'' and he
ridiculed advisers and journalists for jumping on the bandwagon.
Morningstar's ClearFuture service, which gives 401(k) advice to
paying clients, uses a different mathematical approach to
calculating probabilities.
</P>
<P>
   Like it or not, though, Monte Carlo analysis has the makings of
a fairly important trend. Dozens of services use it to guide
professional investors and pension-fund managers these days, and a
couple of Internet sites provide it directly to the Web-surfing
public. Among them:
</P>
<P>
   --www.financialengines.com is far and away the early leader in
Web-based Monte Carlo analysis, and for good reason. The site was
founded by William Sharpe, inventor of the Sharpe Ratio and
recipient of the 1990 Nobel Prize in economics.
</P>
<P>
   The site takes your income and investment information, then
shows your odds of reaching retirement goals with a weather
forecast _ bright sunshine (you'll make it easily) to thunderstorms
ahead (not so fortunate). It allows you to put specific mutual
funds or stocks into the equation, and it runs probability analysis
not only on their individual returns but on factors such as
inflation and interest rates.
</P>
<P>
   The analysis is free, but you'll have to cough up $14.95 to
$39.95 quarterly if you want personalized advice about how to bring
more sunshine to the forecast.
</P>
<P>
   --www.financeware.com unveiled its WealthSimulator service just
this week. It's a little more geeky and complicated than Financial
Engines, but not enough to scare serious investors from giving it a
try.
</P>
<P>
   In the place of sunny and cloudy skies, WealthSimulator offers
plain, old-fashioned bar charts and line graphs. Another
difference: It uses historical market returns for various asset
classes (from 1926 to 1999) to create its list of possible returns,
from which the Monte Carlo analysis pulls random scenarios.
</P>
<P>
   As with Financial Engines, you'll have to dig deep if you want
professional advice from the site. It costs $149 per year if you
sign on as an individual, but it's free if you sign up jointly with
your financial planner.
</P>
<P>
   --www.troweprice.com/
</P>
<P>
   retirement (then click on ``retirement income'') has embraced
Monte Carlo analysis, but not without an adviser's hand-holding.
Mutual fund company T. Rowe Price offers information about its
Retirement Income Manager service at the Web site, but forces you
to talk to an adviser over the phone to actually participate.
</P>
<P>
   Three years in the making, T. Rowe's service will run 500
financial scenarios on your retirement accounts, then provide a
30-page report outlining the probability of reaching your goals.
From beginning to end, including at least three conversations with
an adviser, the process can take 30 days or more.
</P>
<P>
   The service is comprehensive but not cheap. Total cost: $500.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-31-00 0954EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
