<HEADER>
A8038 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-MONEY-TRAUSCH-BOS &LR;      07-31 0738
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONEY-TRAUSCH-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VACATION LUNACY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SUSAN TRAUSCH  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Ah, the vacation purchase _ the silly hat, the ugly shirt, the
20-pound clay pot shaped like a frog, the etching from the Orient
that will never quite blend with plain vanilla decor, the tie rack
with the hand-carved mermaids, the taffy-in-a-tub, and the $15,000
Turkish rug.
</P>
<P>
   ``An impulse purchase,'' Christine Cimino, communications
supervisor at Collette Tours in Pawtucket, R.I., says of the rug.
She was there when a seemingly sensible human being fell under the
spell of the magic carpet, deep into what might be called ``The
Vacation Zone.''
</P>
<P>
   Anything can happen out there. A person who is the soul of
thrift at home, who has contributed to the 401(k) since its
inception, who has savings account contributions automatically
deducted from the paycheck every week, and who rolls pennies on the
weekends, suddenly breaks out in Istanbul, or London, or Miami or
Cleveland.
</P>
<P>
   It's the old ``Hey, hey, hey, this is vacation and we're having
some fun now'' mentality that wipes clean the logic tape and makes
a Leaning Tower of Pisa lamp look like a work of art.
</P>
<P>
   There was never any talk of Pisa lamps at home. Nobody said:
``Boy, when I get to Italy, the first thing I do is head for the
tacky lamp emporium.'' These things just come upon tourists, sort
of like food poisoning.
</P>
<P>
   ``Something possesses them,'' says Mona Strick, director of
sales and marketing at Garber Travel. ``People who would never buy
a Gucci pocketbook get on a cruise ship and drop $500 on a bag.''
</P>
<P>
   They also go for the $200 bottles of wine at dinner, says Bob
Dickinson, president of Carnival Cruise Lines in Miami. Why?
Because it's there, and so are they, and restaurants on land mark
it up to $600. So in The Vacation Zone it looks like a deal.
</P>
<P>
   Jewelry does too.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any serious vacation destination has jewelry stores,'' says
Dickinson. ``They're on the ships, in Cancun, in Paris, and in
Branson, Mo. You've got a couple traveling with no worries and no
work and things are going great. So after two or three days the
husband wants to show his appreciation. He says `Thank you' with
jewelry. If nothing is happening, he buys jewelry to say, `Please.'
''
</P>
<P>
   What's the wildest thing he ever saw a tourist buy?
</P>
<P>
   ``An 8-foot totem with seven faces,'' says Dickinson, recalling
a tour to Alaska. ``A guy carried it in two four-foot pieces, had
it wrapped in paper and string, and put it in the overhead bin on
the plane.''
</P>
<P>
   Nigel Osborne, president of Insight Vacations in Boston, offers
this maxim for the person who would schlep too much: ``If it's
bigger than you are, ship it.''
</P>
<P>
   He has seen people trying to bring home huge Buddhist carvings
from China, or weighing down their suitcases with horseshoes,
souvenirs from his company's Grand National race tour to Great
Britain.
</P>
<P>
   ``A vacation is intangible,'' he observes. ``You can't touch it.
You can only experience it. But people want to bring back the feel
and smell of the trip.''
</P>
<P>
   Which may explain the tourist who bought a $600 sheepskin coat
in Turkey.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was huge,'' says Cimino at Collette Tours. ``It took up
three feet in her suitcase. It looked like one of those flying
monkeys in `The Wizard of Oz.' ''
</P>
<P>
   But the woman didn't know that until she got home. In The
Vacation Zone she looked like Julie Christie in ``Dr. Zhivago.''
</P>
<P>
   A person comes back from Dallas with boots and a ten-gallon hat
that are worn maybe once in Massachusetts. They don't even pass for
the Saturday-morning trip to the dump _ much too
west-of-Springfield for the flannel-shirt crowd shaking hands with
the pols running for the open selectman seat.
</P>
<P>
   So the cowboy gear goes into the back of the closet, saved for
Halloween _ maybe, depending on who's throwing the party. The stuff
joins the moccasins, straw bags, Hawaiian shirts, and other ``have
to have it'' treasures now turned into ``can't throw it out''
albatrosses.
</P>
<P>
   Ugly, unusable, redundant, or outrageously priced though these
things may be, they are still loved for where they once were, and
where the buyers once were, when an impulse purchase made fools of
their budgets and themselves. Being there is always worth it.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Susan Trausch is a member of the Globe staff. She can be reached
by e-mail at trausch(at)globe.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
