<HEADLINE>
SHIPPING COMPANIES' DISPUTE SETS CANADA WAR GEAR ADRIFT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By COLIN NICKERSON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HALIFAX, Nova Scotia _ A Soviet-built, American-owned cargo ship
steaming under the flag of a tiny Caribbean nation and manned by a
Ukrainian crew is holding hostage hundreds of Canadian battle
tanks, along with huge quantities of munitions and other war gear,
in a bizarre deep sea standoff.
</P>
<P>
   The maritime drama underway in the cold waters of the North
Atlantic was sparked by a financial feud between two private
shipping companies but is threatening to become a national
humiliation for Canada, whose leaders seem reluctant to use
military force to storm to the rescue of the military.
</P>
<P>
   The superfreighter GTS Katie is carrying 10 percent of Canada's
entire force of armored vehicles, including 580 battle tanks,
personnel carriers, and reconnaissance vehicles, plus 390 giant sea
containers of weapons, sophisticated electronics warfare gear, and
three hapless Canadian soldiers escorting the equipment home from
peacekeeping operations in the Serbian province of Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our information is that they are being well-treated,''
Canadian military spokesman Captain Thomas St. Denis said Sunday,
referring to the soldiers. ``But there is no resolution of the
situation.''
</P>
<P>
   The Katie was supposed to have unloaded the military cargo in
Montreal on July 16. Instead, the rogue ship is maneuvering in
circles 600 miles east of Halifax while Canada's Minister for
Defense fusses, fumes, and issues tough statements to the media.
For all the bluster, however, the government has thus far been
unwilling to take stern steps to rescue its arsenal from the
unarmed freighter and its merchant crew.
</P>
<P>
   The Katie has been chugging in a holding pattern beyond Canada's
maritime boundary since July 18. The ship's owner, Third Ocean
Marine Navigation Co. of Annapolis, Md., acknowledges that it has
instructed the captain to remain in international waters until
legions of lawyers and diplomats sort out a complex dispute
involving subcontractors and fine points of maritime law.
</P>
<P>
   ``The ship has plenty of fuel,'' said Peter Margan, president of
Third Ocean. ``If I have to, I can sit out there for 50-plus
days.''
</P>
<P>
   Defense Minister Art Eggleton warned over the weekend that
Canada may take ``robust'' measures to retrieve its tanks and
munitions. Canadian news reports, quoting unidentified officials,
said the government is seriously considering a ``show of naval
strength'' to force the Katie into port.
</P>
<P>
   Late Sunday a Canadian military spokesman, Capt. Bruce Poulin,
said an Aurora surveillance aircraft had conducted ``overflights''
of the vessel, and raised the possibility that the ship would
``resume a course'' for Canadian waters, although he stressed that
``negotiations are continuing.''
</P>
<P>
   But so far, despite a growing public clamor, Ottawa has refused
to dispatch warships to bring the wayward vessel to bay. ``We're
not looking at a Rambo situation,'' said Randy Mylyk, spokesman for
the Defense Ministry. ``All diplomatic and other means are being
used to bring an end to the impasse.''
</P>
<P>
   He added, however: ``No option has been excluded.''
</P>
<P>
   Some Canadian politicians are furious at a situation in which an
American company is, in effect, thumbing its nose at the Canadian
military to resolve a financial dispute with a third party.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our lack of sea-lift capability threatens to create an
international incident of national embarrassment,'' said Art
Hanger, a member of Parliament.
</P>
<P>
   Hanger was referring to military cuts that have left Canada
incapable of moving its forces around the world. Instead, the
military has to hitch rides with American or British forces, or _
as in this case _ hire civilian firms to carry its equipment and
fighters to distant peacekeeping missions.
</P>
<P>
   None of the parties involved would discuss details of the
dispute, but the Canadian government said it originally contracted
with a Montreal firm, Andromeda Navigation, to transport the
equipment. Andromeda, in turn, hired Third Ocean Marine to provide
ship and crew. The disagreement involves those two cargo companies,
not the Canadian government directly. The Maryland company is
refusing to relinquish the military gear or the three soldiers
until Andromeda makes payments on alleged debts.
</P>
<P>
   The stakes are higher than in ordinary shipping disputes because
the cargo is not simply bananas or steel ingots, but a substantial
portion of a NATO nation's military might. But to seize Katie on
the high seas would technically represent a Canadian act of war
against the nation of St. Vincent and the Grenadines, under whose
flag of convenience the ship is registered.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the three Canadian soldiers caught on the Katie
describe their ordeal as not especially harrowing, although they
are getting sick of watching Russian-language videos, the only
entertainment aboard the cargo vessel, which served as a Soviet
military transport before the 1991 collapse of the Communist state.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're being treated fine,'' Master Corporal Dan Daly told CTV
News in a satellite phone interview Saturday. ``We're waiting to
let the situation play out.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
