<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LANE-COLUMN0801-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Napster's end won't stop the e-music
 &HT;    By Mark Lane
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTONA BEACH, Fla. _ It was early in the a.m. and something
woke me. A sound. The faint plastic-on-plastic tap of computer
keys.
</P>
<P>
   I squinted toward the sound and saw it was just my daughter
reacting to a federal court order.
</P>
<P>
   Suspecting she had only a day left to use Napster, she was up
late downloading the last few songs. She was joined by hundreds of
thousands.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. District Judge Marilyn Patel granted an injunction
Wednesday closing Napster. She agreed with the Recording Industry
Association of America that Napster is a copyright-infringement
machine.
</P>
<P>
   A federal appeals court, however, stayed the injunction hours
before the ordered shut-down. The sleep loss was unnecessary.
Napster probably will keep going at least another six weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Napster came to my attention when my teen-aged son loaded it on
my computer. Every time I boot up, there's a surprise waiting.
</P>
<P>
   The program connects your computer with the Napster server. This
allows you to search for music files on the hard drives of everyone
else connected to Napster's server.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody likes two-handed columnists, but I can see points in both
sides of this fight.
</P>
<P>
   Recording companies don't want their world to change. They want
to keep issuing music on overpriced CDs. Whatever its faults, this
system pays the people who play the tunes.
</P>
<P>
   As someone who writes things for a living, I think that paying
people for creative work is A Good Thing. It allows us to live in
houses.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, the music industry has a history of opposing
every technology that comes down the pike _ player-piano rolls,
radio broadcasting and recording tape. Despite their cries of
certain doom, each became a blessing in disguise.
</P>
<P>
   Napster means you can listen to something before buying it. It
means that if you only like one song on an album you don't need to
pay big bucks for the whole CD. It means you that if you want to
hear something new you are not at the mercy of formula radio
stations and obnoxious, trash-mouthed DJs. It means you need to
depend on record stores with no jazz or classical bins and cool
clerks who consider anyone over 25 as a possible nursing-home
escapee.
</P>
<P>
   Napster was a gift from the techno gods to new bands,
underground music and garage bands desperate to be heard.
</P>
<P>
   Believing the jig was up, I used the same evening to download
Cheap Trick's ``I Want You to Want Me.'' Cheap Trick is a guilty
pleasure. If a CD by the group were found around my house, I would
be ridiculed by my children, shunned by my peers and growled at by
dogs.
</P>
<P>
   But when you have something like this hidden away in the
magnetic coating of a hard drive, nobody can guess how bad your
taste really is.
</P>
<P>
   Still, we return to the original question: who's going to pay
the piper? How will keep lead singers in hair spray?
</P>
<P>
   Regardless of anyone's concern for starving musicians, this case
is not the end of the story. Even if the record companies
ultimately win.
</P>
<P>
   Technology does not die off by court decree. There are at least
a half dozen programs that do something similar to Napster, but do
it in hard-to-prosecute ways.
</P>
<P>
   Napster's 20 million users aren't going to slink away in defeat.
They have tasted a more flexible way to find more varied music.
They aren't going back.
</P>
<P>
   E-music is here to stay. The industry needs find a way to peddle
tracks on the Internet that would be cheaper but still allow people
to make a living playing music. A tall order, to be sure.
</P>
<P>
   But if they can't pull it off, the black market for sound may
overwhelm the above-ground star-making machinery of the popular
song. Short of establishing a Music Police Squad, it can't be
stopped.
</P>
<P>
   And if they come to my door, I'll deny everything.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Lane is a columnist for The Daytona Beach (Fla.)
News-Journal. He may be reached at mark.lane(at)news-jrnl.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
