<SLUG> BC-SCHUETT-COLUMN0801-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Superwoman on an off day
 &HT;    By Elizabeth Schuett
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GIBSONBURG, Ohio _ ``I AM NOT SUPERWOMAN!? Gail yells into the
phone plastered against my ear. ``A pox upon Martha Stewart!''
</P>
<P>
   Rather than ask what has tilted her day into a spell of the
nasties, I join in. ``YEAH! And Helen Trent and Our Gal Sunday,
too!'' The Cape Cod end of the connection falls silent for a just a
second while she thinks that one over.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who's that?'' she asks. I knew she would. Gail's 12 years
younger than I am.
</P>
<P>
   ``Radio soaps my mother listened to,'' I explain. ``They'd be on
every day when I came home from school for lunch. Helen Trent was
the '40s idea of superwoman. She was unmarried, made her own
living, kept everybody happy including Gil Whitney, her rich
boyfriend who spent most of his dialogue on proposals of marriage _
and she never raised her voice.''
</P>
<P>
   Silence. Then, ``You're kidding. They really had stuff like that
on the radio back then?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Can a girl from a little mining town in the west find
happiness as the wife of a wealthy and titled Englishman? And now,
Our Gal Sunday.''
</P>
<P>
   More silence, then, ``You're putting me on, right? You can't
even memorize your social security number and I'm supposed to
believe you have total recall of a 60-year-old soap opera?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Yep. His name was Lord Henry Brinthrop and she was his Lady,
Sunday. Naturally, Sunday was sweet, and Lord Henry was a wise and
adoring husband. Just your everyday perfect people.''
</P>
<P>
   Gail is astounded that anyone would have committed so much
useless stuff to memory and asks how it happened. It's like
anything else, I explain. If you hear it enough when you're young,
you never forget it, and I was a captive
</P>
<P>
   audience, listening to Mother's soaps over meat patties and
Campbell's soup, five days a week until I went off to a junior high
school that was too far away to walk home for lunch. ``It's kind of
like, why do I remember 12 times 12 is
</P>
<P>
   146.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Why do you remember that?'' Gail asks. ``It's not right.'' I
tell her it's probably close enough unless it's one thousand and
forty-six. She sighs and gets on with it.
</P>
<P>
   ``For years I did superwoman,'' she groans. ``I had three kids
running around the house, all shorter than the counter where I was
kneading bread dough. All day long I was in the kitchen baking
rolls, cookies, desserts _ everything
</P>
<P>
   from scratch.
</P>
<P>
   ``And don't forget the garden,'' she adds in a flash of memory.
``I grew all of our own vegetables so I could kill myself canning
stuff, making pickles and jellies, just like perfect wives and
mothers should. Where did I find the time?
</P>
<P>
   And who ever told me I had to do all that?''
</P>
<P>
   Out of curiosity I ask if she's feeling guilty because she blew
off the day. She asks how I guessed. I tell her it happens to me
all the time. ``I'm lucky to have one normal day a week.''
</P>
<P>
   Which leads us to another of our ``what's normal?'' discussions.
Forget the psychological baloney about normal being an arbitrary
idea that varies according to the unwell mind that's determining
its parameters. We're beyond
</P>
<P>
   the ``feel good'' stuff. We want some answers here.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe we'd be ``normal'' if we had husbands, we decide. Maybe
we've lived alone too long. ``Just think,'' Gail begins in a
``nyah, nyah, I told you so'' singsong, ``if you had a husband
you'd probably have to stop sleeping outside in a
</P>
<P>
   hammock all summer.''
</P>
<P>
   Not to be outdone, I chime in: ``Oh yeah'' Well, if you had a
husband you'd have to stop digging up your woods and moving all the
trees around every couple of years.''
</P>
<P>
   We fall silent for a moment, apparently rethinking our quest for
normality. Maybe it's not what we really want. Trouble is,
somewhere in the back of our minds is the irresistible urge to put
on an apron and dust the knickknacks
</P>
<P>
   while the pot roast cooks.
</P>
<P>
   It's a generation thing _ but we're fighting it.
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth Schuett writes for Cox News Service. Mail: 320 West
Madison, Gibsonburg, OH 43431 or e-mail: eschuett(at)nwonline.net
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
