<SLUG> BC-HEAD-TO-HEAD0801-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    EDS: Head to Head is an occasional feature in which Michael
Carvell and Troy Oxford will offer different viewpoints about a
popular video game title.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    `Virtua Tennis' a grand slam of authenticity
 &HT;    By Michael Carvell
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Playing ``Virtua Tennis'' is the next best thing to being on the
court with a racket in your hand.
</P>
<P>
   This Dreamcast title _ in my opinion _ is the best yet by Sega
Sports, which is saying a lot considering this is the same crew
that produced highly acclaimed titles such as ``NFL2K'' and
``NBA2K.''
</P>
<P>
   But maybe never has a sport been captured and reproduced as well
as with ``Virtua Tennis.''
</P>
<P>
   This is as realistic as it gets on the TV screen. In fact, this
game looks so good that a passerby asked me if I was watching
Wimbledon when I was playing a grass-court match against the
computer opponent.
</P>
<P>
   You have your choice of 16 players, including eight that are
nationally ranked, with American Jim Courier being the most
well-known. Picking a player is strategic, as you must choose an
athlete who fits your own playing style and excels on the selected
tennis surfaces of grass, clay or hard court.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Thomas Johansson of Sweden is known as a ``fast
runner,'' being able to chase down about every ball on the court.
However, Johansson's regular swing and power are average, at best.
Australian Mark Philippoussis is a ``big server'' but may have
problems at times with moving around the court.
</P>
<P>
   The player movements in ``Virtua Tennis'' are as lifelike as a
developer can make them. They are so good in this game that you can
actually use it as a study tool to work on your own serve and
volley.
</P>
<P>
   On a scale of 1-10, I award ``Virtua Tennis'' a 9.99. My wish
for the sequel is for bigger names, such as Pete Sampras or Andre
Agassi, or top women's players.
</P>
<P>
   You'll enjoy the game even if you aren't a terror on the court
</P>
<P>
   By Troy Oxford
</P>
<P>
   c. 2000 Cox News Service
</P>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ I think I'm going to have to agree with Mr. Carvell on
this one. ``Virtua Tennis'' is on my list of the best games to have
for your Dreamcast.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the realistic animation, character modeling and
television-style camera work, the game play is very simple and
solid. Sure, the eye candy is nice, but what good is it if it
doesn't play well? My knowledge of tennis would barely fill a
thimble, but I had no problem adapting to the game immediately.
</P>
<P>
   After I finally got the basics down, I was able to fine-tune my
shot control thanks to the training stages interlaced throughout
the World Circuit mode. From knocking over bowling pins with a
single serve to dashing back and forth across the court to take out
a series of tennis ball machines, I was able to increase my skill
level with a variety of exercises.
</P>
<P>
   Most of my playing took place in the brilliant World Circuit
mode. By taking a player from competition to competition all over
the globe, I was able to sample a little of everything in the
tennis world. From singles matches to doubles matches, clay courts
to grass courts, I played a good variety of scenarios.
</P>
<P>
   As I completed the various competitions, I won money to buy new
outfits, equipment and partners for doubles competitions. It's a
nice little feature that Sega provides to reward your efforts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Virtua Tennis'' also allows up to four players to play
simultaneously. This is another great aspect of the game. No more
swapping controllers back and forth and taking turns. Everyone can
get in there and play. Although there are other four-player titles
out there, I don't think I've had as much multiplayer fun with
those as I've had with ``Virtua Tennis.''
</P>
<P>
   There is one little smudge on this gem of a game, however, and
that is the absence of female players. I wonder how many more units
Sega would have sold if Anna Kournikova were selectable. As Michael
mentioned earlier, perhaps the sequel will have the selection.
</P>
<P>
   If you Dreamcast owners get a chance to buy this game, get it.
``Virtua Tennis'' is in very high demand and after playing it, it's
easy to understand how the initial 50,000 copies sold out so
quickly.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
