<HEADER>
A8079 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-NETWATCH0801-COX     07-31 0712
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NETWATCH0801-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Oxygen.com a halfway fresh concept
 &HT;    By Frances Katz
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The Oxygen cable channel for women never lets you
forget for a minute that there is also an Oxygen Web site.
</P>
<P>
   A black strip with Web site addresses runs continuously across
the Oxygen channel. While it's not as annoying or depressing as the
CNBC all-day Nasdaq ticker, it does bring a new dimension to
television viewing.
</P>
<P>
   Anyone who has seen the Oxygen channel knows there's not a whole
lot to see. Typically it's nothing more than several very hip, very
trendy ``Sex and the City'' wannabes sitting around in sweater sets
and stilettos talking about nothing much deeper than how they like
their boyfriends to dress or asking makeup experts whether it's all
right to wear blue eye shadow to board meetings. (Just so you know,
it's not.)
</P>
<P>
   PBS this is not, and the average female viewer probably has
deeper and more interesting conversations with the counter help at
Starbucks.
</P>
<P>
   But while the hosts babble on about the topic of the day, keep a
close eye on the Web sites running across the bottom of the screen.
Get a pen and notepad and keep them on the coffee table. You might
find some nifty stuff here. During a segment about buying art
online, several interesting Web sites popped up that offered great
resources for buying prints as well as tips on getting exactly what
you pay for. Last week, a segment on cowgirl chic featured all
kinds of links to Web sites for real cowgirls as well as a neat
board game with a cowgirl theme.
</P>
<P>
   However, if you think you can remember this endless swirl of Web
sites, guess again.
</P>
<P>
   Unless the Web site is flashed on the screen over and over
again, as is the Web site for advertiser Kraft (www
</P>
<P>
   .kraftfoods.com), remembering which Web site had the tips for
planning a hiking trip or those neat art-deco clocks they were
showing is tough.
</P>
<P>
   If you have Web access, as Oxygen is betting you do, you can log
onto the Web site www.oxygen.com and find a list of links featured
on the latest installment of whatever ``show'' you were watching.
Even though it looks as if it's just people sitting around talking,
these shows really do have titles.
</P>
<P>
   When you head to the Oxygen Web site, you'll be in for a
pleasant surprise and great disappointment. It's a rare Web site
that can be both brilliant and awful at the same time, but somehow
Oxygen seems to do just that.
</P>
<P>
   Visitors to the Oxygen site hoping to find the same list of
sites they saw on TV or to find out some other information related
to the cable network get the added bonus of wandering through some
of Oxygen's online content. The content is a lot richer in depth
and intelligence than its TV counterpart. (Its recent salute to
novelist Judy Blume was beautifully designed and had lots of
intelligent input from Oxygen readers.)
</P>
<P>
   However, when you leave the interesting and beautiful original
content area and head for the TV tie-in area, you will be reminded
of leaving democratic West Berlin and crossing over to Communist
East Berlin before the wall came down. There's a distinct
difference, and that's a real shame.
</P>
<P>
   Trying to find the cowgirl game was an impossible mission. The
``She-Commerce'' area listed six Web sites related to ``cowgirl
fashion.'' I am positive many more sites flashed across the bottom
of the screen than the paltry few listed on the site. And the
cowgirl-themed board game that looked like so much fun when the
hosts were playing it on the air was nowhere to be found. It was a
miserable letdown and at least one online sale lost.
</P>
<P>
   The Oxygen Web site works when it does its own thing. It falls
to pieces when it tries to mesh with the cable channel. To really
separate Oxygen from the pack of still obscure cable channels and
so-called women's Web sites, Oxygen.com needs to pay more attention
to its poor relation, the cable channel, and make the tie-in as
interesting to visit and as easy to navigate as the rest of the
site. There's no doubt the staff at Oxygen.com is up to the task,
and making the Web site more interesting than the cable channel
certainly won't take that much work.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
