<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    New senator takes seat
 &HT;    By Staff Reports
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Zell Miller, Georgia's former governor, is now a U.S.
senator. The Georgia Democrat took the oath of office on Thursday.
Gov. Roy Barnes appointed Miller to fill the seat left empty by
Republican Sen. Paul Coverdell's death. In his first Senate speech,
Miller pledged to serve all Georgians, not just one political
party. He then cast a few votes before all senators returned to
their home states for the Senate's August break.
</P>
<P>
   Miller must run in a special election Nov. 7 to keep his seat in
the Senate. It appears none of Georgia's Republican congressmen
will challenge the Democrat in that election. Some other Republican
politicians in the state are considering the race.
</P>
<P>
   BUSH PICKS RUNNING MATE
</P>
<P>
   Republican presidential candidate George W. Bush broke with
tradition last week by announcing his vice presidential choice
early. He chose former Secretary of Defense Dick Cheney to run as
his vice president. Normally, presidential nominees make those
announcements at their party's national convention. The Republican
convention begins today and will run through Thursday. Cheney, who
is 59, was a congressman from Wyoming during the 1980s. He was
later secretary of defense when Bush's father was president.
</P>
<P>
   MIDEAST LEADERS GO HOME
</P>
<P>
   Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak and Palestinian leader Yasser
Arafat abandoned peace talks last week. But they remained hopeful
that the two sides could reach an agreement later. At Camp David in
Maryland, the leaders couldn't agree on who would control certain
parts of the city of Jerusalem. Palestinians want control of the
Arab parts of the city, so they can make it the capital of a new
Palestinian state. Israel claims Jerusalem as its own capital.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
