<HEADER>
A8082 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-NFKK-CONVENTIONS0801-     07-31 0734
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NFKK-CONVENTIONS0801-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    During the next few weeks, Republicans and Democrats will meet
for their national conventions
 &HT;    By Keith Still
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Surf your TV channels this week, and you'll have
trouble ignoring the political shindig going on in Philadelphia.
It's called the Republican National Convention, and you'll see a
bunch of people waving flags, flapping campaign posters and wearing
funny hats.
</P>
<P>
   What really goes on at political conventions?
</P>
<P>
   Republicans _ their party's nickname is the ``Grand Old Party''
_ and Democrats each hold a national convention every four years.
Right now it's the GOP's turn to party. Democrats will wait till
mid-August, when they meet in Los Angeles. Traditionally, the party
that controls the White House _ in this case, the Democrats _ holds
its convention last. But with political conventions, being last is
not a bad thing. Candidates like to go last because attention is
focused on their campaign closer to the election, which this year
is Nov. 7.
</P>
<P>
   DID YOU KNOW?
</P>
<P>
   Conventions didn't come along until the 1830s. Until then,
members of Congress would get together to choose a presidential
nominee for their parties.
</P>
<P>
   CONVENTIONAL WISDOM
</P>
<P>
   Nominating a presidential candidate was once the major goal of
political conventions, says University of Georgia political science
professor Charles Bullock. Delegates to the convention would gather
and cast their votes for the candidate they wanted to appear on the
ballot in November.
</P>
<P>
   The process was often heated and full of suspense, Bullock says.
If a candidate failed to win a majority of votes, delegates would
be asked to vote again ... and again ... until someone won. Some
candidates would drop out between the ballots, or deals would be
cut to change delegates' votes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was quite common to go through several ballots,'' Bullock
said. ``If a convention deadlocked, they might often adjourn. Party
leaders would retreat to smoke-filled rooms to work it out.''
</P>
<P>
   DID YOU KNOW
</P>
<P>
   In 1924, it took 102 ballots before Democrat John W. Davis
finally received the nomination at the convention. He lost to
Republican Calvin Coolidge in the November election.
</P>
<P>
   MODERN-DAY CONVENTIONS
</P>
<P>
   Nominating a presidential candidate is still part of today's
conventions, but the drama is long-gone. Before 1972, most
delegates were hand-picked by their states' governors, mayors or
other big leaders. They weren't bound to support any candidate.
</P>
<P>
   Today, when you vote for a candidate in the primaries or
caucuses, you're actually voting to send delegates to the
convention who will support your choice. Presidential wannabes
often lock in enough delegates to win the nomination months before
the conventions. Both Democrat Al Gore and Republican George W.
Bush secured their nominations in mid-March.
</P>
<P>
   So, why hold conventions at all?
</P>
<P>
   ``If conventions have a function today, it's to mobilize the
troops ... the committed,'' Bullock said. ``They rub shoulders with
their party leaders and see their nominees speak. That energizes
them to go home and campaign.''
</P>
<P>
   There's also what's called the post-convention ``bump,'' which
is a temporary boost in popularity.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most people don't watch the conventions, but they do see the
news,'' Bullock said. ``And that's dominated by mostly positive
news from the conventions.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the short run, voters are attracted to the party holding
the convention because of that media coverage.
</P>
<P>
   WHAT YOU SHOULD LOOK FOR . . .
</P>
<P>
   The four-day conventions are about more than just nominating a
candidate.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the day, committees will meet to draft each party's
official ``platform,'' or statement of beliefs.
</P>
<P>
   Each night, party leaders and big names will give rousing,
televised speeches.
</P>
<P>
   After the nominee is officially selected, he will go on
television, formally introduce the person he has chosen to run as
his vice president and make a big speech. The speech usually
focuses on his campaign themes and is designed to rally the party
faithful. If you choose just one night to watch the conventions,
then Thursday would be the night, Bullock says.
</P>
<P>
   CNN, C-Span, MSNBC and Fox News will offer extended coverage.
Check the daily TV listings for times of events.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
