<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECH-CENTERPIECE0801-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Can't live without 'em
 &HT;    By Frances Katz
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Some people are in love with their pets. Others spend
hours lovingly attending to their cars or boats. And then there are
those special people who are deeply attached to technology.
</P>
<P>
   Whether it's a Palm Pilot or the latest in paging or e-mail
gadgets, these Internet executives, come heaven or high water,
won't leave home without them.
</P>
<P>
   Erika Jolly, EarthLink's vice president of portal product
management, doesn't go anywhere without her PalmV hand-held
personal digital assistant.
</P>
<P>
   ``The reason I got hooked on my Palm is because I am on the road
so much, and I can see my schedule at a quick glance,'' she says.
``I'm always on my phone if I'm not in meetings, and I can get my
contacts whether they are advertisers, content partners or members
of my team.''
</P>
<P>
   Jolly commutes between EarthLink's offices in Atlanta and
Pasadena, Calif., at least every other week. The Palm helps her
keep track of where she's going and what she's doing.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are so many features on the Palm that are so cool, like
the MapQuest feature, which lets you download maps,'' she says.
``It's so much better than having a pile of paper to drag around
with you.''
</P>
<P>
   Jolly uses the PalmV. ``It's the latest one,'' she says, ``and
it's got all the mega-stuff. I did try the PalmVII, and I went back
to the PalmV. The VII was too big, and it didn't fit into the
pocket of my Tumi backpack real well.''
</P>
<P>
   (Jolly bought the Tumi backpack because it had a special
compartment to hold her Palm Pilot. ``It's so cool,'' she says.)
</P>
<P>
   However, Jolly says her love affair with the Palm may soon be at
an end.
</P>
<P>
   She just bought a new silver Motorola Timeport cellular phone
from Sprint PCS. (Sprint PCS has a relationship with EarthLink.)
</P>
<P>
   She's waiting for a clip-on mobile organizer add-on for her cell
phone that her boss got her hooked on. ``The basic idea is it fits
right on the back of your phone. It has a touch-screen user
interface, so you can scroll through your address book, find the
person you want to call, then your phone calls that person. It's
got an address book, a calendar and a to-do list,'' she says. ``How
cool is that? I ask you, how cool is that? I just have to have
it.''
</P>
<P>
   INSTANT COMMUNICATION
</P>
<P>
   Jim Lanzone, co-founder and marketing vice president of eTour
(www.etour.com) doesn't go anywhere without his Blackberry Rim.
</P>
<P>
   a reason to carry that big thing around with me,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   As much fun as the Blackberry can be, it's also a useful tool
for staying in touch with co-workers strewn around town and around
the country.
</P>
<P>
   Lanzone estimates he gets between 200 and 300 e-mails a day.
With his heavy travel schedule, having the Blackberry with him
means he can respond to important messages without having to lug
his laptop computer around and wait until he had someplace to plug
in to check messages.
</P>
<P>
   ``People need to talk to me, or they have to show me a document
right away,'' he says, ``And I can get all of that, and I can get
it real time. When I'm not at my desk, it's the easiest way to
reach me. It's one of the essential tools.'' He uses it regularly
to communicate instantly with his ad agency, public relations firm
and radio media buyer.
</P>
<P>
   ``It also has curbed my cell phone use drastically. I used to
have by far the highest cell phone bills in the company. It was
almost absurd. Now it's about a quarter of what I used to have.''
</P>
<P>
   Lanzone's wife, Shannon, is also learning to live with her
husband's passion for his Blackberry.
</P>
<P>
   ``My wife loves it and she hates it,'' he says, laughing. ``My
dad named this thing the bumble, because it buzzes when it goes
off. Everyone loves to tease me about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Lanzone says another great feature of the Blackberry is that you
can be a computer geek without anyone ever knowing. ``I wear it in
the office. But when I step out into the real world, I put it in my
pocket so I won't be laughed at in the street by small children.''
</P>
<P>
   PAGES, PAGES EVERYWHERE
</P>
<P>
   The halls of BellSouth are unusually quiet, but it's not because
the people are unfriendly. In the halls, the offices and even in
the elevator, nearly everyone is in his or her own private world,
busily typing away on BellSouth Interactive pagers.
</P>
<P>
   Stan Yeatts, vice president of Internet portal services for
BellSouth.net, was one of the first to have his own pager. When he
got it, he was working in another department and used it to stay in
touch with his very busy boss. ``We'd see each other in person
about once a month, and this was a great way to stay in touch.''
</P>
<P>
   The BellSouth pager can do a variety of things. Each user has a
specific pager Internet address, so it's also possible to use a PC
to send e-mail directly to the pager. Pager users can also send
e-mail to other pager owners and other computers, or even send a
message that can be delivered by telephone.
</P>
<P>
   ``The cool thing about this is that it's always on,'' Yeatts
says. ``You get immediate feedback. You know when the message is
sent. You know when it's been read. With our BellSouth crowd, the
only reason somebody didn't get the message is if their battery
died or they are on an airplane.''
</P>
<P>
   The always-on pager also came in handy during a big meeting with
corporate officers.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a new person in the meeting, and someb' '' Yeatts
says his wife also uses the PC to send e-mail that appears almost
instantly on his pager.
</P>
<P>
   However, Yeatts knows even the silent act of sending an e-mail
under a restaurant table can be a little annoying.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is true that a lot of people are irritated by this stuff.
... It's a subtler version of the cell phone problem. You try not
to answer the page when someone is in the middle of a very
interesting conversation.''
</P>
<P>
   Yeatts says he has macros set on his pager that let the sender
know he's busy and he'll get back to them later. If something is
urgent, he tells them to send it again and mark it urgent and he
will read it.
</P>
<P>
   ``The great thing about it is you can always stay connected,''
he says. ``It's about real-time, wireless communication.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
