<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECH-FAMILY0801-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Computer ideas for ending kids' late-summer boredom
 &HT;    By Staff Reports
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ As the heat becomes unbearable, the kids come inside
to play. If boredom sets in and your imagination thins to
suggesting soap operas to the little ones, turn instead to the
computer.
</P>
<P>
   There are a number of new programs and Web sites that offer fun
stuff for kids to do, with a little education thrown in to boot.
</P>
<P>
   If the youngsters are between 3 and 8, take a look at
``Putt-Putt Joins the Circus,'' a delightful romp for both the
Windows and Macintosh platforms.
</P>
<P>
   It's from Humongous Entertainment, which has put out a number of
terrific programs for younger children.
</P>
<P>
   Putt-Putt is an animated purple car who, accompanied by his dog,
Pep, solves memory and logic puzzles.
</P>
<P>
   This is the fifth adventure for Putt-Putt, who first appeared in
1992.
</P>
<P>
   In his latest outing, Putt-Putt arrives at the circus only to
discover that there's trouble with the five main acts.
</P>
<P>
   Phillipe the Flea doesn't like his quarters, and Honko the Clown
speaks only in Honkish. Then there are the Flying Porkowskies,
who'll perform without a safety net only when pigs fly, Ivan the
Semi-Strong Man and Reginald the Lion.
</P>
<P>
   Along the way, Putt-Putt meets other characters and helps them
solve their problems.
</P>
<P>
   The suggested retail price for ``Putt-Putt Joins the Circus'' is
$24.99.
</P>
<P>
   Humongous is within a select circle of children's software
publishers that create enduring animated characters.
</P>
<P>
   The company also has introduced Freddi Fish, Pajama Sam and SPY
Fox into kids' lives.
</P>
<P>
   Humongous products are widely available at retail, on the Web
(www.humongous.com) and by calling 1-800-499-8363.
</P>
<P>
   The Web site also offers activities for children, as well as
tips and tricks. For older kids, log on to Mirriam-Webster's Web
site for kids at www.wordcentral.com to find out what a
``clickaholic'' is. You may be one.
</P>
<P>
   What's a clickaholic?
</P>
<P>
   Why, an enticon, of course.
</P>
<P>
   Created by young wordsmiths, these words are some of the entries
in the ``Build Your Own Dictionary'' section of the site.
</P>
<P>
   Clickaholic means ``someone who is on the computer constantly,
or someone who clicks the mouse constantly,'' while enticon
appropriately means ``a fabricated word.''
</P>
<P>
   The idea behind ``Build Your Own Dictionary'' is for children to
e-mail their creations to their friends and become excited about
words, says Merriam-Webster publicist Arthur J. Bicknell.
</P>
<P>
   Set up like a school, the Web site takes the user through a
hallway of options, from a science lab where kids can conduct word
experiments to a teacher's lounge where users can learn how a word
gets into the dictionary.
</P>
<P>
   There's also a daily buzzword so kids can astound relatives with
unusual words.
</P>
<P>
   ``Word Central gets 5 million hits a month, and it's growing,''
Bicknell said.
</P>
<P>
   The site won a Parents' Choice Award from the Parents'
Foundation and a 2000 Webby award for the best educational Web site
from the International Academ allows buyers of the game to play it
together with family and friends on the living room TV screen
rather than huddled in front of a computer.
</P>
<P>
   You can now play this $39.95 game in the group environment, like
non-video games such as ``Pictionary'' and ``Trivial Pursuit.''
Divide into the teams and put the PlayStation control in the hands
of your smartest teammate.
</P>
<P>
   A virtual Regis Philbin is your host, complete with his charming
wit and sometimes bratty attitude. The two-player game starts off
with the ``fastest finger'' mode, in which you have to put four
items in chronological order quicker than your opponent to earn the
right to play for money.
</P>
<P>
   The questions in the ``fastest finger'' round can sometimes be
ridiculously hard, forcing both teams to guess repeatedly. It can
test Philbin's temper.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess we have a bunch of Mensa candidates in there,''
Philbin says sarcastically. ``I guess you know I'm just kidding.''
</P>
<P>
   Another stinger from Philbin: ``Hey, hey _ what's the IQ in this
room? I'm getting concerned.''
</P>
<P>
   If both teams fail every attempt, then the game starts over. But
not without some final words from our host.
</P>
<P>
   ``Come on, guys, how many times can we do this?'' Philbin says.
``You are pathetic. The game is over. I'm getting out of here.''
</P>
<P>
   Once you're in the money seat, ``Millionaire'' becomes much more
enjoyable. Just like on TV, you have access to three lifelines:
phone a friend, ask the audience and 50/50.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps nothing in the PlayStation game is more impressive than
the phone-a-friend option. It is an available option for each of
the 600 questions. Choose the phone alternative, and you have
access to one of the virtual game show host's wacky friends,
ranging from a snooty doctor to a person with ESP who leaves advice
on the greetings of his answering machine.
</P>
<P>
   With a limited number of questions, you will start seeing
repeats as early as the 10th time you play. But it doesn't
necessarily make it much easier.
</P>
<P>
   With ``Who Wants to Be a Millionaire: 2nd Edition,'' the $100
question can be just as challenging as the one for $8,000. Or they
can be exactly the same, just 15 to 20 games apart.
</P>
<P>
   Even with the assistance of friends, it is tough to make it to
the $64,000 mark. If you are able to win $1 million, then you are
either very intelligent or have a superb photographic memory. Just
remember, it's only a virtual $1 million.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
