r a BC-CONSUMERQ&AMP;A0801-COX     07-31 1217
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONSUMERQ&AMP;A0801-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Consumer Q&AMP;A
 &HT;    By Jane Greig
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _
</P>
<P>
   Q: My astronomy class would like to know why a spring tide is
called that. Could you help?
</P>
<P>
   _ Gina Crouchet
</P>
<P>
   A: These tides rise or ``spring'' up, hence the name. Spring
tides have nothing to do with the spring season. Spring tides,
which are higher than other tides, occur during the new and the
full moons. The moon's and the sun's gravities combine to pull sea
water along the same line, reports Brad Armosky, science educator
at the McDonald Observatory.
</P>
<P>
   Neap tides, on the other hand, are those in which the water
rises and falls the least. These tides occur near the first and
last quarter phases of the moon when the Earth, moon and sun form a
triangle. Q: I am looking for a clothes steamer like the ones
clothing stores have. I do not want a hand-held one. I want the
kind that has the water tank on the floor with the hose and nozzle
attached.
</P>
<P>
   _ Gayle F. Young
</P>
<P>
   A: Jiffy Steamers are sold in several catalogs, or pick up one
from the Jiffy Steam company at (800) J2-JIFFY. Steamers are made
in three sizes: travel (hand-held), residential and commercial. The
residential model ($189) works for everything _ drapes to suits. It
even temporarily turns off if it runs out of water. Not an
attractive item, but it does the job. Worth the investment _ about
the price of several steam irons. Q: I have several POW bracelets
that were popular during the Vietnam War. How can I find out if the
people whose names are on the bracelets made it back home or died
in captivity, and how they are doing now?
</P>
<P>
   _Teresa Brawner
</P>
<P>
   A: The National League of Families of American Prisoners and
Missing in Southeast Asia at (202) 223-6846 can help you with the
names on your bracelets. As of June 29, the number of Americans
still missing and unaccounted for from the Vietnam War is 2,014.
This nonprofit maintains lists of all those unaccounted for in
Southeast Asia as well as the latest statistics provided by the
Department of Defense POW/MIA office Q: I recently heard about a
Web site where you could receive a free credit report,
www.freecreditreport.com. I understand the requirement for personal
information such as full name, address, and Social Security number.
However, when they ask for a credit card number I exited the Web
site. Why would they need a credit card number?
</P>
<P>
   It makes me wonder if this is a legitimate Web site or another
scam?
</P>
<P>
   _ Gary L. Robinson Sr.
</P>
<P>
   A: Legit. The credit card number is information used to
authenticate that the person requesting the report is the same as
the subject of the report, says Laurie Edwards of iPlace, site
sponsor. On this site, the card number is also used to pay for a
credit monitoring service (30 days free, then a charge). Not really
``free'' if it is tied to receiving this service. Using a credit
card also allows you to cancel the service or challenge the charge
if the card is used improperly. A no-strings-attached site such as
iPlace.com, a site delivering everything from credit reports to
neighborhood information in exchange for your profile, asks for a
credit card number as identification also. Want to bypass all this?
Pay $8 to a credit reporting company and skip the ``free'' offers.
Q: Do you know the address for Deborah Yates, who was nominated for
a Tony Award for the musical ``Contact''? I went to high school
with her here in Austin, but had lost touch until I saw her on the
Tony Awards._ Susan Lewis
</P>
<P>
   A: The Southern Methodist University student landed a job as a
Rockette when she moved to New York in 1994. ``Contact'' was her
breakthrough role. Send your lauds to her in care of Peter
Sherwood, Sames &AMP; Rollnick Associates, 250 W. 57th St., Room 703,
New York, NY 10107.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Our son is 17 and is interested in joining the Marines once
he graduates. He has taken Ritalin for Attention Deficit Disorder
on and off for the last 10 years. He only takes it sporadically
recently. His has always been a mild to moderate case. I hear that
the Marines will not accept anyone who has ever taken Ritalin.
Could you please find out?
</P>
<P>
   _ M.G.
</P>
<P>
   A: What you heard is correct. Generally, having taken Ritalin
would keep a candidate from qualifying for the Marines. However,
Marine spokesman Patrick Gibbons notes this road block is waivable.
Your son's use of Ritalin will be reviewed by the Bureau of
Medicine. It's worth a try if he is serious about serving in the
Marines.
</P>
<P>
   Q: We have just returned from a trip to San Miguel, where we
bought Talavara pottery. We were told by several vendors that it
would be safe to use the plates and bowls that are not lead-free as
long as they were not heated in the oven or microwave. Can you
confirm the safety of using the pottery?
</P>
<P>
   _ Kay T.
</P>
<P>
   A: Not exactly. Pick up a lead test kit at area hardware stores
which will tell you if there is lead in the glaze (not the amount
of lead, just its existence). The Poison Control Center notes heat
(and acidic foods) exacerbate the problem, but lead can leach from
pottery glaze whether it is heated or not. Want to be safe? Use the
pieces for decoration only. Remember, children are more at risk.
For more information, call the center at (800) 764-7661.
</P>
<P>
   Q: If each couple is allowed two children only, the population
on Earth will stay the same or decrease. My husband thinks it will
grow. I think I am right, and my husband thinks he is right. Can
you settle this?
</P>
<P>
   _ Kyoung Chung
</P>
<P>
   A: No, but statistician and demographer Thomas Pullum from the
University of Texas can. Replacement fertility rate would have to
be slightly more than two children in the United States (2.1 to be
exact). The excess (.1) is needed to compensate for mortality.
Pullum reports the worldwide fertility rate is 2.9 per couple, so
the world population is increasing about 1.8 percent per year.
``Even if the average number of births dropped to replacement level
immediately, world population would continue to grow for several
decades,'' concludes Pullum. The population boom means many couples
are in prime child bearing ages, so replacement fertility would
result in more births than deaths. Given this population momentum,
even if fertility dropped to 2.1 immediately, by 2025 the world
wcontainers with the 1 or 2 recycle marking, but I'm curious what
the other numbers mean. Some are stamped with a 5, for example.
Also, I noticed on a bottle of Kiss My Face lotion marked with a 2
symbol the statement ``do not recycle this container.'' What's that
all about?
</P>
<P>
   _ Jim Noel A: Approximately 80 percent of recycled plastic
bottles are marked No. 1 or No. 2 (such as milk jugs). Plastic
bottles marked No. 3 (polyvinyl chloride), 4 (low density
polyethylene) and No. 5 (polypropylene) are locally nonrecyclable.
For more details, contact Ecology Action's executive director,
Michael Risden, at 322-0000 or visit ecology-action.org. The Kiss
My Face lotion bottle should state ``do recycle this bottle,''
according to spokeswoman Donna Myer. Perhaps you misread it.
</P>
<P>
   Contact Jane Greig at P.O. Box 670, Austin TX 78767; (512)
445-3697; e-mail jgreig(at)statesman.com; or fax (512) 445-3968.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
