Southeast Asia as well as the latest statistics provided by the
Department of Defense POW/MIA office Q: I recently heard about a
Web site where you could receive a free credit report,
www.freecreditreport.com. I understand the requirement for personal
information such as full name, address, and Social Security number.
However, when they ask for a credit card number I exited the Web
site. Why would they need a credit card number?
</P>
<P>
   It makes me wonder if this is a legitimate Web site or another
scam?
</P>
<P>
   _ Gary L. Robinson Sr.
</P>
<P>
   A: Legit. The credit card number is information used to
authenticate that the person requesting the report is the same as
the subject of the report, says Laurie Edwards of iPlace, site
sponsor. On this site, the card number is also used to pay for a
credit monitorel the service or challenge the charge if the card is
used improperly. A no-strings-attached site such as iPlace.com, a
site delivering everything from credit reports to neighborhood
information in exchange for your profile, asks for a credit card
number as identification also. Want to bypass all this? Pay $8 to a
credit reporting company and skip the ``free'' offers. Q: Do you
know the address for Deborah Yates, who was nominated for a Tony
Award for the musical ``Contact''? I went to high school with her
here in Austin, but had lost touch until I saw her on the Tony
Awards._ Susan Lewis
</P>
<P>
   A: The Southern Methodist University student landed a job as a
Rockette when she moved to New York in 1994. ``Contact'' was her
breakthrough role. Send your lauds to her in care of Peter
Sherwood, Sames &AMP; Rollnick Associates, 250 W. 57th St., Room 703,
New York, NY 10107.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Our son is 17 and is interested in joining the Marines once
he graduates. He has taken Ritalin for Attention Deficit Disorder
on and off for the last 10 years. He only takes it sporadically
recently. His has always been a mild to moderate case. I hear that
the Marines will not accept anyone who has ever taken Ritalin.
Could you please find out?
</P>
