<DOCNO> NYT20000731.0093 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-31 11:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8116 &Cx1f; tab-z
u a BC-SCIENCE-BRIEFS-DISCOV     07-31 0948
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCIENCE-BRIEFS-DISCOVER-$ADV25-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BREAKTHROUGH BRIEFS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use Tue., July 25, 2000, or anytime thereafter.) 
 &HT;    
 ATTENTION EDITORS: The following material from The New York Times
Syndicate is for use by DISCOVER NEWS SERVICE clients.
Nonsubscribers can use this article only by special arrangement.
For purchase information, see end of text. 
 &HT;    
 (Color slides are included.) 
 By THE EDITORS OF DISCOVER MAGAZINE 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) 
 &HT;    
 FEARS FOR EARS  
 &HT;    American farmers have planted 20 million acres of genetically
modified corn, engineered to repel predatory insects without using
noxious chemicals.
 &HT;    If farmers are not careful, a new report warns, the scheme could
backfire and breed even more troublesome strains of pests.
 &HT;    The modified crops pump out Bt toxin, a natural insecticide
created by bacteria. Some insects, in turn, carry genes that
protect them from the toxin. To check the spread of those genes,
the U.S. Environmental Protection Agency requires that farmers
intersperse fields of genetically modified crops with islands of
non-modified plants.
 &HT;    The idea is that insects in the refuges would remain vulnerable
to Bt toxin, and the bugs would interbreed to keep the whole
population susceptible.
 &HT;    For the first time, scientists have proof the tactic works.
Entomologist Anthony Shelton of Cornell University and his
colleagues sowed fields of altered broccoli and then unleashed
broccoli-eating diamondback moths.
 &HT;    In fields containing refuges of non-modified plants, resistance
genes were less likely to be spread through the moth population.
 &HT;    But there is a big caveat. Spraying the refuges with pesticides
_ a common practice among farmers, and one permitted by EPA
regulations _ sped the appearance of toxin-resistant moths.
 &HT;    ``Any time you spray insects on a plant, you are never going to
get 100 percent mortality,'' Shelton says. ``You end up putting a
mosaic of doses on the plants-some high, and some low. Where the
doses are low, you won't kill all the insects, and those that
survive will be more likely to develop resistance.''
 &HT;    
 STAR TREK SYRINGE  
 &HT;    The doctors keep saying it won't hurt a bit, and it keeps
hurting. There's got to be a better way to get drugs into the body
than a brutal needle and syringe.
 &HT;    Chemist Terry Burkoth and his collaborators at PowderJect
Pharmaceuticals in Oxford, England, agree. They have replaced the
needle with a flashlight-size tube that uses a jet of helium to
accelerate powdered drugs to supersonic speeds.
 &HT;    Just press it against the skin, and the PowderJect system shoots
a dose directly into the underlying cells. The drug particles are
so small that the patient hardly feels a thing.
 &HT;    And the supersonic shot could make it easier for doctors to
deliver precise dosages of drugs to hard-to-reach regions just
below the skin's upper layer.
 &HT;    
 PICTURE-PERFECT PLASTIC  
 &HT;    Because of a rogue speck of dust floating around Stephen Chou's
lab at Princeton University, your next computer monitor may display
a much sharper image.
 &HT;    An electrical engineer, Chou was working on a better way to
configure polymer plastics used to make light-emitting diodes, or
LEDs, and other electronics.
 &HT;    One of his graduate students pressed a mask into a layer of
plastic, preparing to transform the material into a pattern of
electrical circuits. By a fluke, bits of dust got behind the mask.
When Chou removed it, he was startled to see that an array of
beautiful, highly regular microscopic pillars had sprung up where
the mask did not lie flush on the surface.
 &HT;    Chou thinks his polymer pillars will simplify the manufacturing
of LED video displays, which have better resolution than
cathode-ray tubes but are expensive to build.
 &HT;    Color LED screens usually contain three different materials to
display the red, blue and green parts of the picture.
 &HT;    ``In the old technology, you had to fabricate each color
separately,'' Chou says. ``With this process, you can fabricate all
the colors at the same time, using the pillar height and size to
control the color.''
 &HT;    
 MODERN SWINGER  
 &HT;    In the robotics laboratory at Japan's Nagoya University, a
strange machine swings from bar to bar like a gibbon.
 &HT;    Toshio Fukuda and Jun Nakanishi, along with Dan Koditschek at
the University of Michigan, recognized that the primate's
arm-to-arm movement is a very complex form of locomotion and set
out to build a robot that could master it.
 &HT;    They demonstrated that a simple double joint _ essentially a
pendulum linked to another pendulum _ could perform the key
swinging motion.
 &HT;    Then the Nagoya group built the Brachiator III, which has legs
to generate initial momentum and a computer vision system to figure
out where to place its handlike grippers.
 &HT;    Nakanishi believes that lessons learned from building the
swinging robots will aid the design of future walking, hopping, or
jumping automatons.
 &HT;    ----
 c.2000 Discover magazine 
<TEXT>
 &UR; EDITOR: Visit The New York Times Syndicate Web site at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for more information on DISCOVER
NEWS SERVICE and other features. &QL;
