<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; Monday, July 31, 2000 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; EDITORS: &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Hearst News Service will file these stories for Tuesday. If
you have questions, please call Judy Holland or Mark Helm at
202-298-6920.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (``HNS'' appears in all sluglines.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   PAINTED-MURAL (San Francisco) _ Garth Benton says that if Ann
and Gordon Getty didn't want his mural in their San Francisco
mansion any more, it would have been easy to detach it from the
wall. Instead, he claims, the local philanthropists and socialites
painted over the $327,000 mural, violating a rarely used California
law barring
</P>
<P>
   the destruction of fine art. By PETER HARTLAUB.
</P>
<P>
   CADDY-DEVILLE _ Cadillac's flagship sedan, the De-Ville, has
been completely redesigned for 2000 in what may be a last-ditch but
highly successful attempt to save this car marque from what looked
to be certain extinction. By CHAMBERS WILLIAMS III.
</P>
<P>
   FANG-EXAMINER (San Francisco) _ When the mid-March deal was
struck for the late John Fang's family to buy The Examiner, the
patriarch's wife, Florence, went to his grave and left a copy of
The Examiner, whose bold headline said ``SOLD.`` ``I know that when
people pass away, they should lie in peace,`` said Florence Fang.
``But this time, I just had to tell him. . . . I think he read
it.`` By ANNIE NAKAO, ELIZABETH FERNANDEZ, MATTHEW YI AND DEMIAN
BULWA.
</P>
<P>
   POLITICS (``P'' category)
</P>
<P>
   GOP-SPEAKERS (Philadelphia) _ Instead of displaying members of
Congress at the Republican National Convention this week, the Bush
campaign has tapped teachers, single moms, farmers, community
leaders and small businesspeople to parade before the delegates. By
ZACHARY COILE.
</P>
<P>
   GOP-INTERNET (Philadelphia) _ Political junkies may need to put
down their remotes and pick up their mice for comprehensive
coverage of the Republican Convention in Philadelphia. This year,
the Republicans expect more than 100 Web-based outlets to cover the
convention, with countless other news organizations also funneling
coverage to their own Web sites. By MATT TAYLOR.
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT(``e'' category)
</P>
<P>
   FILM-EASTWOOD - (Space Center, Houston) For a guy who is 70 _
yes,
</P>
<P>
   Dirty Harry is a senior citizen _ Clint Eastwood looks
remarkably fit. The acting legend talks about acting his age _
``I'd play a grandfather in a second,'' being a major star for 35
years and corralling three other young old-timers to play ``Space
Cowboys'' in the movie opening Friday. By LOUIS B. PARKS.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS/FINANCIAL NEWS (``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   FEARLESS-EXECUTIVE (Undated) _ Being afraid of spiders or snakes
or even your own shadow might not hurt your career, but what if
you're afraid that you're simply not good enough _ or that people
will resent you if you speak up? Those sorts of fears can hamper or
even destroy a career. Fear of inadequacy is the most common such
pitfall, management
</P>
<P>
   psychologist and executive coach Alan Downs says in his recently
released book, ``The Fearless Executive.`` By DAVE MURPHY.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   SALTER-COLUMN (Philadelphia) _ If you don't count the fact that
the platform committee of their very own party has totally screwed
and humiliated them _ AGAIN _ this is a great year to be a
pro-choice Republican. By STEPHANIE SALTER.
</P>
<P>
   MORSE-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ By now, most people probably have
heard The San Francisco Examiner is no longer a Hearst paper. It's
now a Fang paper, and the Chronicle is a Hearst paper. We've
already started to talk about the old Examiner with nostalgia even
though we'll be here another four months putting it out the same as
usual. By ROB MORSE.
</P>
<P>
   NIGHT-CABBIE (San Francisco) _ There's one thing that's obvious
when you're driving a taxi: I hear views. On just about everything.
This lets me question whether my own thoughts have any merit. Some
people are always unhappy. Others are so happy all the time you
think they're a little out of it. Younger people are generally
happier than older people. Women seem to be happier than men. I see
so many down-and-out souls and wonder what keeps them going.
</P>
