<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NATASHA-LYONNE-INTERVIEW-FAIRCHILD-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNCAGED LYONNE  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  ATTENTION EDITORS: The following material from The New York Times
Syndicate is for use by clients of ``HIGH STYLE AND MORE.''
Nonsubscribers can use this article only by special arrangement.
For purchase information, see end of text. 
 &HT;    
 By MERLE GINSBERG 
 (One color slide is available.) 
 From W magazine 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) 
 &HT;    If hair is destiny, then Natasha Lyonne's future is going to be
huge. Not to mention wild and out of control.
 &HT;    Of course, hair isn't really destiny (unless you're Kirsty
Hume). But Lyonne, who grew up in Manhattan and went to an
exclusive private school with a bunch of what she calls ``total,
like, icy snobs,'' has her own idiosyncratic notions about the
world _ and one of them is that her mammoth strawberry-blond mane
has sealed her fate. And not necessarily in a good way.
 &HT;    ``I guess it depends on how you feel about Medusa,'' sighs the
diminutive Lyonne, 21. (As she speaks, her hair _ even after a
marathon blowdry _ is expanding a little in the New York humidity.)
 &HT;    ``I'm so fed up with being the kooky funny girl,'' she says.
``And I know it all starts with the hair. I'm not that funny. I'm
fairly antisocial, and I live in my head _ I'm always analyzing
everything. But having crazy hair always makes people think I'm
wild and funny.''
 &HT;    Then there are Lyonne's numerous other quirks: the
chain-smoking, the exaggerated New York accent (which, in
combination with her gravelly voice, makes her sound like a female
Harvey Fierstein), the hipster vocabulary and the long list of
outre interests, including a passion for slasher films.
 &HT;    Most wacky of all, however, is Lyonne's taste in film roles,
which seems to get even wackier as she gets older. Although she's
starred in a couple of studio films (most recently ``Slums of
Beverly Hills'' and ``American Pie''), she's much more likely to be
found in offbeat, semi-obscure indies such as the campy comedy
``But I'm a Cheerleader.''
 &HT;    In the film, Lyonne plays a girl who's sent away to a
conservative cheerleading camp after her parents and would-be
boyfriend begin to suspect she's gay. Naturally, while doing
splits, she falls for a girl (Clea Duvall). Following
``Cheerleader,'' Lyonne will appear this fall in something called
``Confessions of a Trickbaby.''
 &HT;    ``I'm still turning down mainstream movies all the time,'' the
actress says between constant puffs on a cigarette. ``I just keep
turning down that boring stuff.''
 &HT;    She adds that she's not always in the running for big Hollywood
projects, such as the upcoming ``Charlie's Angels.'' ``No one asked
me to be the third angel,'' she says with mock disappointment.
 &HT;    Actually, playing a tough-but-glamorous detective wouldn't be
much of a stretch for Lyonne, who's been standing up for herself
since she was a young girl. When her snooty Manhattan schoolmates
made fun of her hair, she beat them up. So independent was she as a
teen-ager that her mother let her get her own apartment.
 &HT;    ``Can you imagine an 18-year-old getting by a co-op board?''
Lyonne says with a snicker.
 &HT;    Lately, Lyonne says, she's been behaving more and more like a
true adult, much to her surprise.
 &HT;    ``I'm starting to realize that cashmere is more comfortable than
fishnets,'' she says, proud to have moved beyond the rock-chick
look. ``I'm starting to kind of like the idea of being a female.''
 &HT;    Much of her newfound maturity may stem from her very grown-up
relationship with 22-year-old actor Edward Furlong (``American
History X,'' ``Terminator 2''), whom she met on ``Detroit Rock
City'' more than a year ago.
 &HT;    ``We got the L.A. house, we got the dog, we got the DVDs,'' she
says. ``I even cook! Low carb.''
 &HT;    Lyonne suggests that no one but Furlong could have lured her
from New York to the West Coast.
 &HT;    ``I mean, I just spent a year and a half in L.A. just to be with
this dude!'' she says. ``He's one of the real ones _ true hot
stuff. But I was so based in New York and not willing to change
that. I was the big tough-ass New Yorker. Now he says he saw
through that at the very beginning, and that was what was so silly
and endearing about me _ putting on this tough act when I'm just
this little girl.''
 &HT;    Furlong and Lyonne are so devoted to each other that he became
fiercely jealous of her kissing scenes in ``Cheerleader'' _ even
though they were with a woman.
 &HT;    ``And Clea and I were already friends long before the movie,''
Lyonne says. ``The last thing we were going to do, since neither of
us is into girls, is go for each other.''
 &HT;    Lyonne played another gay character earlier this year _ a '70s
activist in HBO's ``If These Walls Could Talk II'' _ but she's not
too worried that the public will misconstrue her sexuality.
 &HT;    ``Everyone in high school thought I was gay, because they never
saw me with a guy,'' she says. ``Truth was, I couldn't get a date.
So I was happy they thought I was gay. At least that meant I wasn't
a loser.'' c.2000 Fairchild Publications 
<TEXT>
