<HEADER>
A8185 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a BC-PAINTED-MURAL-HNS &LR;      07-31 0537
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PAINTED-MURAL-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     GETTYS SUED OVER EFFACING MURAL 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By PETER HARTLAUB  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Garth Benton says that if Ann and Gordon Getty
didn't want his mural in their San Francisco mansion any more, it
would have been easy to detach it from the wall.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, he claims, the local philanthropists and socialites
painted over the $327,000 mural, violating a rarely used California
law barring the destruction of fine art.
</P>
<P>
   Benton responded by filing a lawsuit in San Francisco Superior
Court. A Getty family spokesman said experts are working to restore
the painting.
</P>
<P>
   The world-renowned artist, who reportedly has painted for the
homes of such luminaries as Bob Hope and former President Gerald
Ford, wants $327,000 in damages, plus his attorneys fees paid.
</P>
<P>
   Benton also wants punitive damages, which by state law would go
to a California charitable or educational activity involving fine
arts.
</P>
<P>
   Getty family spokesman Larry Kamer confirmed that Benton's mural
had been painted over with ``some other kind of paint,'' not by a
commissioned artist.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because Mrs. Getty has dedicated much of her life to the
restoration and preservation of fine art, she is now working with
experts to remove the paint from the mural and restore it to its
original condition,'' Kamer said.
</P>
<P>
   Ann Getty was out of the country and Gordon Getty could not be
reached for comment.
</P>
<P>
   The garden-style mural was created in Pebble Beach, and it was
installed in the Gettys' mansion in 1986.
</P>
<P>
   Benton, who lives in Alabama, says the mural, which measures 15
feet tall and 40 feet wide, was painted on canvas, then attached to
the wall of the mansion.
</P>
<P>
   A picture of the mural accompanying the complaint shows a
painting of a balcony overlooking a field, with a monkey in the
corner being fed by a young girl.
</P>
<P>
   Benton says he knows the painting was on the wall in the early
1990s, but the lawsuit does not say when it was painted over.
</P>
<P>
   Benton claims he called the Gettys in March, hoping to get a
photograph of the work for listing in his upcoming catalogue
raisonn.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit states: ``Within the following week, Benton was
advised by an assistant to the Gettys that the work had been
painted over.''
</P>
<P>
   Benton also could not be reached for comment, and his lawyers
did not return calls seeking comment.
</P>
<P>
   Alabama arts and tourism magazines say Benton's clients have
included not only Hope and Ford, but also Barbra Streisand,
Danielle Steel, Carol Burnett and producer Aaron Spelling.
</P>
<P>
   He also painted a 1983 mural that was featured at the J. Paul
Getty Museum in Malibu, which is closed for renovations until next
year.
</P>
<P>
   The Gettys are fixtures in San Francisco high society. Getty's
father once was believed to be the richest man in the United
States. Born in Los Angeles, Gordon Getty has split his time
between being a composer and a philanthropist.
</P>
<P>
   Gordon and Ann Getty were married in Las Vegas in 1964.
</P>
<P>
   Before Texaco Inc.'s takeover of Getty Oil in 1984, Gordon
Getty's share of the trust income was about $30 million per year,
according to a New York Times article.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
