<HEADLINE>
BOOKS RECENTLY REVIEWED IN THE BOSTON GLOBE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``The Circus Fire'' by Stewart O'Nan (Doubleday, $24.95). A
fiction writer turns his attention to examining the 1944 big-top
fire in Hartford that took more than 160 lives and changed
thousands of others. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``The Obedient Father'' by Akhil Sharma (Farrar, Straus &AMP;
Giroux, $23). A novel about the dark side of politics in India, and
the even darker side of the man at the story's core. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``The Feast of Love'' by Charles Baxter (Pantheon, $24). Think
of ``A Midsummer Night's Dream'' transferred to the flatlands of
Michigan, with a ventriloquist's touch sprinkled in _ and you have
the setting for a delightfully poetic tale. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``The Chief'' by David Nasaw (Houghton Mifflin, $35).
Exhaustively researched and straightforwardly told, the life of
William Randolph Hearst emerges from the shadow of ``Citizen
Kane.'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``How to Read and Why'' by Harold Bloom (Scribner, $25). The
eminent critic shares his thoughts on favorite books _ not in
deep-dish essays, but in epigrammatic reader's notes.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
