<HEADLINE>
GOING AFTER GRANDPARENTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By THOMAS OLIPHANT  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; CONSHOHOCKEN, Pa. _ As it turns out, Al Gore is a tad on the
old side of typical.
</P>
<P>
   George W. Bush is going to be a lot less typical.
</P>
<P>
   As a grandparent, that is _ as dynamic a segment of American
society as you can find these rapidly changing days.
</P>
<P>
   ``The typical way of thinking about grandparents is by age, and
it is upside-down wrong,'' says Steve Barsh, at 35 the CEO of the
most highly regarded of the new Web businesses (iGrandparents.com)
devoted to the their concerns. ``The truth is that this is a new
life stage for maturing baby boomers who are in their prime, who
travel more, are more wealthy, healthier, and are going to live
longer than their own grandparents.''
</P>
<P>
   As the grossly scripted nominating convention phase of the
presidential campaign begins, the more revealing glimpses of this
election are of action away from the podiums: the rules and
platform committees, the hype and partisanship of issue pandering.
</P>
<P>
   To each campaign, the mention of age brings out instinctive
responses about Social Security benefits, long-term care, medicare,
and nursing homes. Call it Viagra politics. But new thinking
focuses elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   For starters, the average age at which Americans become
grandparents turns out to be 47, not exactly Geezerhood. That's
five or so years younger than Gore was when daughter Karenna made
him and his wife, Tipper, grandparents last year. With his twin
girls barely out of high school, George and Laura Bush will be
waiting a lot longer than most Americans do. Today's
demographically typical grandparent is just 62 years old.
</P>
<P>
   With their nearly paid-off homes and rising investment
portfolios, grandparents already hold nearly half the country's
household wealth, a chunk that is going to explode to about 60
percent during this decade. Right now, grandparents are spending
$30 billion a year on their grandchildren; during this decade, that
number should explode above $100 billion, growing at twice the
anticipated rate of overall economic growth.
</P>
<P>
   This is about far more than toys and savings bonds.
Increasingly, grandparents are the most important source of
financial aid for two almost out-of-reach expenses for their own
kids' families: getting in the front door of a first home and
financing higher education. On top of that, more than 6 million
kids are being raised solely by their grandparents. And the roughly
one-third of all grandparents who live in the same metropolitan
area with their grandkids are likely to be an important source of
child care.
</P>
<P>
   The company Barsh is running from this middle-class suburb a
dozen miles removed from the GOP convention in Philadelphia is way
ahead of the politicians.
</P>
<P>
   ``We see ourselves as driving the interactivity between
grandparents and grandkids, monetizing it,'' he says in New
Economy-speak. ``We want to be a one-stop shop for this
relationship, as grandparents not only play but seek a bigger role
in their grandchildren's lives.''
</P>
<P>
   As one of the company's founders, Lawrence Chimerine, puts it,
the two most important things to know about grandparents is that
they are not old and that they are passionate about the welfare of
their grandchildren. If the politicians in both parties are
inclined to think Social Security first, Chimerine knows that a
grandparent is as likely to be concerned with the quality of the
public schools.
</P>
<P>
   Chimerine is well known in the business world as one of the
country's leading economists. But, as he puts it, he's also a
60-year-old delighted to have 1.3 grandchildren. His company was
founded to aggregate grandparents around something better than junk
news and mindless chat.
</P>
<P>
   The first venture capital placement was just completed. There is
already revenue from advertising and partnering _ mutual fund
empires and credit card companies. The e-business starts next
month.
</P>
<P>
   As run by Barsh, iGrandparents is acutely conscious of
post-Nasdaq crash, post-shakeout reality. If the precrash obscenity
was gazillions for meaningless, 30-second spots on the Super Bowl,
postcrash means carefully building a customer base that actually
makes money, though membership is free.
</P>
<P>
   Part of what they see is the liberating effect of prosperity, a
key element of Bush Think. Confidence in the economy give many
people the time and the money to worry about other things: the
culture, role models, their grandkids' school and living
environments. And wealth brings issues into play that may enable
Bush to break off chunks of older voters concerned about estate
taxes and other high-end taxes.
</P>
<P>
   The natural landscape favoring the ``out'' party competing for
an open White House at this early point favors Bush among the
three-quarters of all Americans over 50 who are grandparents.
</P>
<P>
   That reflects a growing group that complains the business here
is ignoring them.
</P>
<P>
   They're called great-grandparents.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Thomas Oliphant is a Globe columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
