<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SANDERS-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOP HOPING TO SPOTLIGHT PARTY DIVERSITY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BOB RAY SANDERS 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ Back in the days when television was broadcast
mostly in black and white, the National Broadcasting Co. created a
stylized peacock to remind viewers that it had more color than any
other network.
</P>
<P>
   This week, the GOP will begin displaying its own peacock image,
hoping to prove that it, too, can present programs ``in living
color.'' After Thursday, Republicans hope to be known as the ``full
color'' party.
</P>
<P>
   At least from the stage of the Republican National Convention _
and, of course, in front of prime-time TV audiences _ there will be
more color than I can ever remember in the GOP. The party will
parade its high-profile minorities across the huge platform for the
next four days to reinforce Gov. George W. Bush's message of
inclusion.
</P>
<P>
   If you were to judge it only from what you will see on the TV
screen this week, you might think the Republican Party has spent
the whole year in a tanning salon, attending diversity workshops
and spending a lot of time in sensitivity sessions.
</P>
<P>
   With NBC, there was truth in advertising; it was the color
leader in television 35 to 40 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   With the GOP, some people are joking that there will be more
black and brown people on the convention stage than there will be
in the entire audience at First Union Center, for still more than
90 percent of the 4,132 delegates and alternates is white.
</P>
<P>
   Among 116 of the 124 Republican delegates from Texas, The
Associated Press reports that 8 percent are Hispanic, 2 percent
black, 1 percent mixed race and 1 percent Asian. So although the
Anglo population constitutes only 55 percent of the Lone Star State
(and is predicted to be less than 50 percent by 2008), whites make
up 88 percent of the Republican delegation from the state.
</P>
<P>
   The ``presentation of the colors'' will take on fresh meaning
during this convention. You will see all those Republican people of
color you know, and many whom you've never heard of.
</P>
<P>
   Retired Gen. Colin Powell, who's being talked about as secretary
of state in a Bush administration, will be on display, as well as
the highest-ranking Hispanic state officeholder in Texas, Railroad
Commissioner Tony Garza. The latter was one of Bush's first
appointments, being named Texas' secretary of state during the
governor's first term in office.
</P>
<P>
   Garza and Dallas native Alphonso Jackson, a black businessman
and longtime Republican who's the former head of the Dallas Housing
Authority, have been named assistant secretaries of the convention.
</P>
<P>
   Also featured in high-profile spots will be Condoleezza Rice, an
African-American who is one of Bush's foreign policy advisers, and
U.S. Rep. J.C. Watts of Oklahoma, perhaps the Republicans'
fastest-rising (if not brightest) African-American stars.
</P>
<P>
   There will be other Hispanics and blacks _ ``regular folks''
such as a teacher, businessman, community worker _ who will get to
tell their stories before the convention crowd and the national TV
audience.
</P>
<P>
   To its credit, and especially the credit of Bush, this
Republican convention will not look like those from the past, and
that's exactly what the governor wants.
</P>
<P>
   As technicians and performers went through rehearsals yesterday,
it was also evident that there will be a different feel to this
one.
</P>
<P>
   Judging from what I heard of the convention orchestra, and a
run-through with the Philadelphia Boys Choir, even the music will
be diverse. I heard a little funk. Someone was rehearsing a Stevie
Wonder song, and the boys choir added a touch of African rhythm
with a rendition of ``Circle of Life'' from the movie ``The Lion
King.''
</P>
<P>
   (Bob Ray Sanders is a columnist for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the
World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
