<DOCNO> NYT20000731.0118 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-31 13:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8222 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-BOOKS-MYSTERY-BOS &LR;      07-31 0827
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-MYSTERY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A DETROIT VOICE TO RIVAL PARKER, AND A PLOT TO MATCH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROBIN W. WINKS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   There are many writers who have tried to capture the patterns of
speech that make so many readers admire Raymond Chandler. By far
the most successful has been Robert B. Parker. In turn, Parker has
had many imitators. There may have been a time when Loren D.
Estleman began by tracing the hands of Chandler and Parker on
sheets of paper and putting them up on his refrigerator, but long
since he has become a powerful, compassionate voice of his own. ``A
Smile on the Face of the Tiger'' (Mysterious Press, $24.95) may
well be his best book _ which is saying something, since it is his
14th Amos Walker novel and he has written 30 other books as well,
including six ``Detroit novels'' that unfold the history of that
weird and often unhappy city, a city Estleman clearly loves from
time to time. ``Smile'' is also part of the Detroit story, for it
turns on a book about the 1943 race riot.
</P>
<P>
   Walker, a private eye with a sharp tongue and a quick wit, is
hired to locate the author of a tawdry paperback novel written many
years before. Finding the writer proves surprisingly difficult, and
Walker meets the usual cast of characters who show up in a search
story, though Estleman makes them far more interesting than most
writers do. The novel becomes an act of homage to all those
paperback-original crime novels, from Fawcett and Pocket Books and
Dell and Signet, that launched so many writers and even more
readers. It ends up a nice illustration of how fact and fiction
become confused, and I recommend it all the way.
</P>
<P>
   Marcia Muller does not write quite as well as Estleman does, but
she plots beautifully, and having grown up near Detroit, she has
some of the Motor City's grit. ``Listen to the Silence''
(Mysterious Press, $23.95), though, is set in various locales well
to the west. Her series figure, Sharon McCone, learns when her
father dies that he has left some legal papers concerning the
adoption of a Baby Girl Smith, who is to be known as Sharon McCone.
Shocked, she sets out to learn about her past, and the road is
hard, especially when it becomes clear that few want her to solve
her own mystery. Several writers have turned to the search for
self-knowledge to gird up mystery novels recently, and Muller
handles this theme with a sure hand, with nice little vignettes of
Missoula, Mont., Boise, Ida., and other fast-growing cities of the
future.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Samuel also tells a good story, but his prose is
remarkably wooden. In ``Rock, Paper, Scissors'' (Simon &AMP; Schuster,
$25), we meet Hank Savage, who ``strode into the office, his dark
eyes scouring the room for any objective cause for his boss's
aberrant behavior. Standing six feet, three inches tall, and
weighing just under 210 pounds, his rock-hard frame carried less
than 8 percent body fat.'' Perhaps I'm just jealous, but I find a
little of this goes a long way. The story, however, is as
intriguing as it is improbable: The US secretary of state organizes
the kidnapping of the pregnant daughter of a tycoon in order to
force the tycoon into giving up a plot to kill Saddam Hussein. The
only person who can stop these haywire machinations is Sarah
Peterson of the Secret Service, who is assigned to guard the
secretary and who was traumatized by the murder of her father
before her eyes when she was 3. This is the kind of thing one likes
if this is the kind of thing one likes, as someone once said.
</P>
<P>
   Normally Gerald Seymour would be a hard-nosed antidote to such
nonsense, but ``A Line in the Sand'' (Simon &AMP; Schuster, $25) is
less than the best work from the author of so good a book as
``Harry's Game.'' Still, Seymour is always a compelling writer, and
this often sad tale of how Frank Perry spied for the British
government and betrayed his Iranian colleagues, only to be turned
adrift by those who had suborned him, moves steadily toward the
kind of shocking conclusion one has learned to expect. A
professional assassin is hunting for Perry, who is moved to a small
Suffolk coastal town where almost everyone turns upon him when they
realize he has brought danger to them. Perry is not very likable,
but Seymour makes us care for him and his family nonetheless.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, Paul Lindsay's ``The Fuehrer's Reserve'' (Simon &AMP;
Schuster, $25) provides a rousing page-turner that makes sense. The
``reserve'' of the title is the artwork amassed by Adolf Hitler and
Hermann Goering. Taz Fallon of the FBI is at work on a kidnapping
when he is drawn into the search for this cache of art treasures,
which are going to be used to finance a band of neo-Nazis. The
prose crackles, as the saying goes, and Lindsay brings us happily
back to the sharp lines of Estleman, reminding us just how
enjoyable such popular fiction can be in the hands of someone who
knows the language well.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
