<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-31 13:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8224 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-CRIME-VICTIMS-BOS &LR;      07-31 1417
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CRIME-VICTIMS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CRY `BLOODY MURDER': FIGHTING BACK TO SAVE YOUR LIFE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SCOT LEHIGH  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's a nagging fear of modern life.
</P>
<P>
   The knife-wielding thug who leaps into your car at a light.
</P>
<P>
   The gun-toting hoodlum who steps from the shadows on a darkened
street.
</P>
<P>
   The wild-eyed psychopath who charges into a fast-food restaurant
brandishing an assault rifle.
</P>
<P>
   Your life may depend on how you react in a few short seconds.
What do you do?
</P>
<P>
   Unlikely as the average person is to face such peril, that's
still a question worth contemplating as the Massachusetts homicide
rate, though low, edges higher.
</P>
<P>
   It's a matter made vivid by recent abductions and murders in the
region, including a carjacking in Providence that ended in the
slaying of Jason Burgeson, 20, of Lakeville and Amy Shute, 21, of
Coventry, R.I.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps it'sis even worth a family discussion in a summer marked
by the conviction of a Falmouth man for the July 1999 murder of
27-year-old Melissa Gosule of Boston, who had been stranded by a
breakdown, growing fear about the fate of 16-year-old lifeguard
Molly Ann Bish of Warren, who disappeared on June 27, and an
attempted hijacking Friday at New York's Kennedy Airport.
</P>
<P>
   At one time, police tended to counsel crime victims to stay
calm, to be compliant, to accede to the demands of the criminal, in
the hope that they would be released unharmed.
</P>
<P>
   These days, law enforcement professionals shy away from giving
concrete advice. ``There is no hard and fast rule,'' says William
Bratton, former New York City police commissioner and now a private
consultant. ``It really is situational.''
</P>
<P>
   Special Agent Chris Whitcomb, of the FBI's Critical Incident
Response Group, acknowledges the bureau's reluctance to give a
specific answer. ``Every situation is different,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   But a former San Diego SWAT team mission leader and ex-Marine is
now rushing in where the FBI fears to tread. And his advice is
drawing attention.
</P>
<P>
   The situations may be different, says Sanford Strong, but the
rules should be clear: ``The bottom line is that when men and women
are faced with a violent crime or terrorists taking hostages, they
must act immediately, when control over them by deranged minds is
at its least. They must be able to break through paralyzing fear
and concentrate on survival decisions they have previously made.''
</P>
<P>
   Strong, whose views have been featured on ``Good Morning
America'' and ``The Today Show,'' has taught his techniques to
business executives and their families in 18 countries. He minces
no words about one key mental hurdle a person must clear.
</P>
<P>
   ``You are going to get injured,'' says Strong. ``Accept it.''
</P>
<P>
   A failure to accept that possibility makes people accede to
demands that put their lives at progressively greater danger as
criminals consolidate their control over them.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, Strong isn't advocating resisting a holdup.
Surrender your belongings as fast as you can, he counsels. But in
circumstances where a criminal tries to make you his captive, you
must react rapidly and forcefully, he says.
</P>
<P>
   Some Strong advice:
</P>
<P>
   In a hostage situation, make a break for freedom even if that
means crashing through a window and potentially drawing gunfire.
(There, passengers who leapt to their feet and rushed off a
National Airlines jet at the sight of a gunman in Friday's abortive
hijacking had the right idea.)
</P>
<P>
   If someone invades your car and orders you to drive, flee the
vehicle if you can; if you can't, crash the car into a parked
vehicle, a telephone poll, a hydrant or a dumpster, even if your
children are inside.
</P>
<P>
   If more than one carjacker is involved and one has the wheel,
try to force a crash by attacking the driver's face, says Strong,
who taught survival tactics to officers during almost 20 years with
the San Diego Police Department.
</P>
<P>
   The more quickly one reacts, the better his or her chances of
survival, Strong says. But how to fight through the shock and
terror that often leaves victims paralyzed with fear when violent
crime occurs?
</P>
<P>
   The best way is to have prepared yourself in advance, says
Strong, who recommends a simple mental exercise: When reading or
watching any crime story, take a moment to ask what the victim
might have done, early on, to escape. Did she get into a car when
she might have fled? Did he let fear freeze him into inaction when
he might have struggled? Obey a command to be silent instead of
screaming?
</P>
<P>
   ``If you have a situation where a woman was abducted at
gunpoint, stuffed in a car, driven out to a remote place, and raped
and murdered, if you take one thing from that, it is probably that
her biggest mistake was in the first few seconds, when she should
have run,'' Strong says.
</P>
<P>
   Which underscores one of his strongest imperatives: You must not
let yourself be moved from the place of confrontation, which he
calls ``crime scene number one,'' to a more remote location, which
he labels ``crime scene number two.''
</P>
<P>
   But what if the abductor has a gun or knife and threatens to
kill you if you don't obey? Strong has a disturbing, but logical,
reply: If your attacker is willing to kill you at that moment, in a
public place, what will he do later, once he has moved you to a
more secluded spot?
</P>
<P>
   Strong's is controversial counsel.
</P>
<P>
   Other crime specialists say a victim should assess a given
situation and decide for himself what course _ resistance or
compliance _ offers the greatest likelihood of survival.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unfortunately, while people would like a rule of thumb about
how to react when confronted, rules of thumb are relatively
worthless,'' says James Alan Fox, Lipman professor of criminal
justice at Northeastern University. ``You basically have to follow
your instinct.''
</P>
<P>
   In hostage situations, time is usually on the side of the
captives, says former Boston Police Commissioner Francis ``Mickey''
Roache, now a Boston city councilor. ``If we can get a phone in and
communicate (with the hostage-takers), we can start a discussion,''
Roache says. ``I have a hard time seeing why we should deviate from
what has been a successful approach.''
</P>
<P>
   As for rape, Steven McCarthy, manager of the Violent Criminal
Apprehension Program for the Massachusetts State Police, says
Strong's advice may well deter one type of rapist, who often back
off in the face of resistance, but might incite two other types,
categorized as ``anger excitation'' and ``sadistic'' rapists, to
even greater physical violence.
</P>
<P>
   ``For many rapes, to resist would be the correct response, but
the problem is there are different types of rapists,'' says
McCarthy. ``That is why people who are knowledgeable are very
hesitant about giving blanket advice, because how are you going to
educate the lay person about how to assess what type of offender
they are dealing with and do an accurate assessment of their own
capabilities?''
</P>
<P>
   To that criticism, Strong replies that, though all crimes are
different in some ways, they are alike enough in key aspects to
assert that your best chance of surviving comes if you act
immediately to escape.
</P>
<P>
   Second, though making a situational judgment sounds goods, it is
unrealistic to expect a victim to assess his prospects and
opportunities effectively while a crime is occurring.
</P>
<P>
   ``Assessment at the time a crime is going down is too late,''
Strong declares flatly. ``The person without decisions made ahead
of time will be paralyzed with fear. He will freeze up.''
</P>
<P>
   Strong also cites a massive 1985 study which, he says, showed
that in 96 percent of the 1.6 million rape cases examined, the
types of injuries were essentially the same whether a woman
resisted the rapist or not. Resisting increased the level of injury
by only 2 percent, Strong says.
</P>
<P>
   If there are those who question Strong's philosophy, others
basically endorse it.
</P>
<P>
   ``That whole '70s mindset we used to hear about `don't ever
fight' and `if he wants to rape you, just acquiesce,' is bull,''
says Reed Hillman, former head of the Massachusetts State Police.
``Fight, fight, fight is my philosophy. Fight as long as you can,
scream as long as you can.''
</P>
<P>
   Strong says the ultimate defense of his survival techniques is
this: He is teaching people to respond the way police officers are
trained to react.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't have to be a cop to make life-or-death decisions
like a cop. You just have to think like one.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
