<HEADER>
A8226 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i BC-FOREIGN-JOURNAL-BOS &LR;      07-31 0837
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOREIGN-JOURNAL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRACKING AN IRISH PILGRIMAGE TO A FRENCH SHIRTMAKER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN CULLEN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ For much of the last century, the Irish have flocked to
France, as much for religious reasons as for the foie gras.
</P>
<P>
   Busloads of Irish descend regularly on Lourdes, a market town
tucked into the southwestern corner of France where, in 1858, a
14-year-old girl named Bernadette Soubirous said she saw an
apparition of the Virgin Mary.
</P>
<P>
   It was the first of 18 visions reported by the French peasant
girl. Her life was popularized by Hollywood in ``Song of
Bernadette,'' and she was made a saint in 1933, 54 years after her
death.
</P>
<P>
   For more than a century, Lourdes has attracted millions of
pilgrims, a disproportionate share of them Irish, who until recent
years were among the most fervent, devout Catholics of Europe. In
1990, Cardinal Tomas O Fiaich, the beloved leader of the Catholic
Church in Ireland, suffered a heart attack and died in Lourdes
while leading a pilgrimage there.
</P>
<P>
   But Ireland has changed, changed utterly, as William Butler
Yeats once put it. The influence of the church has waned over the
past decade, partly because of scandals involving pedophile
priests, and, some say, because of Ireland's booming economy.
Attendance at Mass has fallen dramatically.
</P>
<P>
   As Ireland has become more secular, it seems only natural that
the Irish have a new, secular shrine in France: the Charvet shirt
boutique just off the Place Vendome, one of the richest, most
exclusive, commercial areas of Paris.
</P>
<P>
   Since October, when a Dublin tribunal investigating widespread
political corruption found that Ireland's former prime minister,
Charles J. Haughey, had used $50,000 he had solicited from rich
businessmen to buy shirts at one of the most exclusive shirtmakers
in the world, Irish people have flocked to Charvet the way they
used to flock to Lourdes.
</P>
<P>
   They pose for photographs outside the venerable shop, and
sometimes venture inside to gawk at the crystal chandeliers, the
oak paneling, the Oriental rugs and the cuff links in bowls
scattered around the shop.
</P>
<P>
   And they pose indelicate questions about their former prime
minister. Their questions are met, like this reporter's were, with
stony silence.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will not talk about that,'' an elegantly dressed salesman
said the other day. ``Please, will you leave?''
</P>
<P>
   Well, at least he said please.
</P>
<P>
   The Irish like nothing better than a good laugh, and they've
been yucking it up at Charvet. While many patrons of Charvet retire
to the nearby Ritz Hotel after a visit to the shop, many Irish
usually go to Kitty O'Shea's pub, 100 yards down the street.
</P>
<P>
   Brian Loughney, the pub's owner, has an impish sense of humor.
From a purely selfish point of view, he thanks his lucky stars for
the proximity of his pub to the shirt shop, which was the
beneficiary of blank checks given to Haughey by Ireland's current
prime minister, Bertie Ahern, who was the financial manager of the
Fianna Fail party.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can stand outside on the sidewalk, have a nice quiet pint,
and look down the street and see where our tax money was going,''
said Loughney, who casts a cold eye on politicians like Haughey.
</P>
<P>
   Maria Nelson, the pub's manager, said they recently hosted 20
nurses from Cork who won a free trip to Paris as part of a radio
competition. ``They weren't in here five minutes before they ran
down the street to Charvet,'' she said. ``They were taking photos,
having a great laugh for themselves. It was quite a scene.''
</P>
<P>
   While the store won't come right out and say it, Charvet's
discreet sales staff is none too pleased about the Irish pilgrims.
But, then, Charvet is one of those Parisian specialty shops where
customers will brave even a group of giggling nurses from Cork to
buy some of the world's most prestigious shirts.
</P>
<P>
   And it is one of those shops where, if you have to ask the
price, you can't afford it. When asked about one of the striped
cotton dress shirts made from luxurious Egyptian cotton, a salesman
politely responded, ``That is about 200 of your American dollars.''
</P>
<P>
   Haughey's cost even more, because they were custom made, and he
had his initials, CJH, embroidered on the left breast pocket. But
trying to get the salespeople to cough up what Haughey's shirts
cost is like asking the IRS for an undeserved refund.
</P>
<P>
   Back at Kitty O'Shea's, meanwhile, Wayne Mills was pulling pints
of Guinness behind the bar, chuckling about the irony of moving
here from Arklow, County Wicklow, only to be closer to the heart of
his nation's corruption investigation.
</P>
<P>
   One of his customers, Padraig Wilson, a young Dubliner, grew
thoughtful as he nodded toward Mills for another pint.
</P>
<P>
   ``Madonna's about to have another baby,'' Wilson mused about the
very pregnant pop singer. ``She named the first one Lourdes. Maybe
she'll name this one Charvet.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Kevin Cullen is the Boston Globe London Bureau chief.
</P>
</TEXT>
