<HEADER>
A8229 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l BC-WHITE-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      07-31 0616
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WHITE-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REAL PICNIC ROSTER: KIDS, DOG, BUGS, DIRT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE WHITE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Despite what you may read in certain magazines, a real picnic
doesn't involve a damask tablecloth and a wicker picnic basket from
Restoration Hardware.
</P>
<P>
   There is no unobstrusive little Muscadet nor any refreshing
young Beaujolais, surprisingly chilled, at a real picnic. Nor will
you find any dainty watercress tea sandwiches. And it goes without
saying that a real picnic owes nothing to olive tapenade, sun-dried
tomatoes, or goat cheese.
</P>
<P>
   You won't see beautiful people at a real picnic, not, at least,
the kind of beautiful people who inhabit ads in glossy magazines.
Real people go to real picnics.
</P>
<P>
   A real picnic has certain essential elements, as follows.
</P>
<P>
   Weather. The best weather for a real picnic is what TV weather
forecasters call ``a chance of showers.'' There is no chance
involved at all. It will rain at some point, perhaps several
points, providing a measure of meteorological uncertainty crucial
to the success of a real picnic.
</P>
<P>
   Location. A real picnic is never set on the sweeping lawn of a
mansion overlooking the sea. Neither does it take place in an
officially designated picnic spot with wooden tables, barbecue
grills, and bathroom facilities. The ideal spot for a real picnic
is within sight of a ``No Trespassing'' sign. This lends the picnic
an aura of clandestine excitement. A view is nice for a real
picnic, but not necessary. Grass adds a pleasant touch. And low
shrubbery comes in handy.
</P>
<P>
   Children. A real picnic involves several children, one or two of
whom will wander off somewhere and get lost, briefly, thereby
throwing everybody into a panic and heightening the confusion that
is the hallmark of a successful real picnic.
</P>
<P>
   Dog. Every real picnic should have at least one dog, to help
find wandering children, to chase squirrels, to bark frequently for
no apparent reason, to eat leftovers and get sick on the ride home.
</P>
<P>
   Blanket. A real picnic is never spread upon a linen or even a
cotton tablecloth but on an ancient khaki Army blanket that smells
vaguely of mothballs or mildew, or both. The blanket's rough
texture should be enhanced with years of embedded beach sand, some
of which will work loose during the picnic and find its way into
the food.
</P>
<P>
   Car. The car that provides transportation to a real picnic may
be old or new, as long as it has something seriously wrong with it.
A real picnic is no fun without the constant, nagging fear that the
car will break down on the trip home.
</P>
<P>
   Insects. No real picnic is complete without plenty of insect
repellent and lots of anxious talk about dangerous bugs _ killer
bees, deer ticks, army ants, Formosan termites, West Nile
virus-bearing mosquitoes, etc.
</P>
<P>
   Food. The success of a real picnic is in direct proportion to
the number of calories consumed. Fried chicken. Potato salad.
Deviled eggs. A big cake with gooey frosting that gets stuck in the
children's hair. Real picnic food is always eaten with the hands.
And it's never packed in a special basket or hamper, but piled into
brown paper bags. At the end of the day real picnickers should be
able to throw away everything but the children, the dog, and the
blanket.
</P>
<P>
   Drinks. Homemade lemonade, preferably warm, is the official
drink of the real picnic. If anyone insists on cold lemonade, don't
use an insulated container that needs to be washed later. Buy a bag
or two of ice and let it melt in the back seat of the car so
someone can sit in the wet spot and complain all the way home.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Diane White is a Boston Globe columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
