<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-31 13:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8236 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i BC-MIDEAST-AMERICANS-BOS     07-31 1528
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MIDEAST-AMERICANS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AMERICAN JEWS' PASSIONATE ENGAGEMENT WITH ISRAEL IS WANING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL PAULSON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Ehud Barak and Yasser Arafat left Washington empty-handed last
week, hoping to forestall violence in Israel now that they had
failed to make peace at Camp David. But the Mideast leaders had
succeeded in making thinkable the unthinkable: The status of
Jerusalem, long claimed by Israel as its eternal and indivisible
capital, is now in play.
</P>
<P>
   And the fact that American Jewry didn't balk at the concept of
shared sovereignty over Jerusalem illustrates how far the community
has come in its thinking about Israel since the first round of
Middle East peace talks concluded successfully at Camp David in
1978.
</P>
<P>
   American Jews, weary after decades of Mideast strife, are
increasingly emotionally distant from Israel, and more focused on
problems facing their own community here in the United States. For
most American Jews, the dream of Zion has been realized, but the
dream of peace has not.
</P>
<P>
   But the collective shrug at the notion of negotiations over the
status of Jerusalem also is recognition that Israel today is
getting bigger and stronger economically and militarily, if not
geographically, while the American Jewish community is getting
weaker by virtue of demographics, and, some argue, assimilation.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's classic politics: You claim something is taboo, but then
it turns out to be not quite as taboo as you thought it was,'' says
Rabbi Irving ``Yitz'' Greenberg, president of the Jewish Life
Network, a New York foundation working to bolster American Jewish
institutions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jerusalem has a central significance for Jews everywhere, but
nevertheless the reality is American Jews want peace for Israel,
and if Israelis say shared sovereignty in Jerusalem is the price of
peace, the only groups who will oppose it are the groups that
oppose the whole peace process.''
</P>
<P>
   This latest round of peace talks comes as Israel, long the
symbolic center of Jewish life, emerges also as the demographic
heart of the Jewish world for the first time since the days of the
Bible. The Jewish population of Tel Aviv (about 2.4 million in
1996) has surpassed that of New York City (1.9 million), and within
the next generation, the Jewish population of Israel (4.6 million
in 1996) is expected for the first time to pass that of the United
States (5.7 million).
</P>
<P>
   The American Jewish community's extraordinarily close
relationship with Israel was forged first by the dream of Zionists
seeking a return to the storied land of milk and honey, then by
immigrants and Holocaust survivors who put their backs into the
creation of a Jewish state in 1948, and finally by alarm over the
security of Israel after wars in 1967 and 1973.
</P>
<P>
   But today Israel is economically and militarily strong, while
the Jewish community in America is, at least demographically,
decreasing in influence. The Jewish percentage of the US population
has dropped from about 4 percent to about 2 percent, and is
expected to continue to fall, and although accurate statistics are
difficult to compile, some scholars believe that Muslims have
already eclipsed Jews as America's largest non-Christian minority.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're no longer patrons, we're partners, and that's a
different relationship,'' says Nancy K. Kaufman, executive director
of the Jewish Community Relations Council of Greater Boston.
Kaufman frets that the many American Jews paid little attention to
the events at Camp David.
</P>
<P>
   ``My greatest concern is not what people think about the peace
process, but that they didn't think anything at all,'' she says.
``The apathy has been developing for the last several years, and
it's of great concern. The complexity and the years of waiting and
wondering and the lack of understanding by a lot of people has just
created a disconnect in the relationship between American Jews and
Israel.''
</P>
<P>
   The relationship between American Jews and Israel began to lose
intensity in the early 1980s, as Israel's invasion of Lebanon
muddied the Middle East scenario for some American Jews.
</P>
<P>
   ``American Jews, like everybody else, realize that Israel is no
longer a tiny beleaguered state, and certainly is not a third-world
country,'' says Jonathan D. Sarna, chairman of Near Eastern and
Judaic Studies at Brandeis University. ``And American Jews, like
lots of people, have become more aware of the Arab side of the
dispute, and where it once seemed to be a case of black and white,
with virtue on one side and hatred on the other, there has now come
about an understanding that there were wrongs committed on both
sides.''
</P>
<P>
   Another factor influencing the relationship was the near panic
set off among American Jewish community leaders by a 1990 study
claiming that half of all American Jews are marrying non-Jews.
While the study has since been disputed, it nevertheless forced a
wholesale rethinking of American Jewish community priorities, and
led to the current boom in Jewish day schools, as well as adult
education programs.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the first 20 years following the '67 war, Israel became
the banner, the symbol, and the central story of what bound Jews
together,'' says Barry Shrage, president of Combined Jewish
Philanthropies of Greater Boston. ``The Jewish community is now
attempting to balance that with the development of stronger
community life. It's not that we don't love Israel as much, but
Israel has become so strong, there may be less need.''
</P>
<P>
   Shrage's organization is at the vanguard of a movement by
American Jewish charitable agencies to shift their philanthropy
from Israel to the United States. In some places, as much as 70
percent of American Jewish philanthropy was once directed to
Israel; in Boston just 30 percent of contributions now goes
overseas.
</P>
<P>
   Personal connections to Israel are not as strong as they once
were. Just 18 percent of American Jews now view visiting Israel as
essential. By some estimates, young Jewish Americans are less
likely to visit Israel than those from Australia, Great Britain, or
Mexico, according to Barry Chazan, a professor at Hebrew University
in Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
   American philanthropists recently started a program called
Birthright Israel that provides free trips to Israel to Jewish
youngsters. The program is an effort to strengthen the connection
of American Jews with Judaism, as well as with Israel.
</P>
<P>
   Those American Jews who do focus on Israel no longer speak with
one voice. There are doves and hawks and everything in between;
during this latest round of negotiations, one group of prominent
American Jewish leaders ran a newspaper ad critizing Barak's
posture; another group of leaders countered with one supporting the
prime minister.
</P>
<P>
   On top of the apathy and the division are a traditional
deference by American Jews to the Israeli government.
</P>
<P>
   ``The silent majority of American Jews, even those with clear
cut political views, have the view that Israeli leaders are the
ones who make the decisions, and most American Jews are reluctant
to second guess judgments made by democratically elected Israeli
leaders,'' says Martin J. Raffel, chief operating officer of the
Jewish Council for Public Affairs. ``They see their role as
supporting a U.S. policy which strengthens Israel.''
</P>
<P>
   So if Israeli Jews are ready to talk about some kind of shared
administrative structure over Jerusalem, so are American Jews.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even as little as five or ten years ago, no Israeli prime
minister would have survived had they brought this issue as far as
Barak has,'' says Kenneth Bricker, spokesman for the American
Israel Public Affairs Committee, a lobbying group.
</P>
<P>
   There are other factors at work too. Jerusalem is no longer
divided as it was prior to 1967, but it's not exactly united
either.
</P>
<P>
   ``The ideological argument was that Jerusalem was united, but
the truth of the matter is, if you talk about a lot of parts of
East Jerusalem, the average Israeli does not know where they are
and is not prepared to fight a war over it,'' says Ilan Peleg, a
government professor at Lafayette College. ``Jerusalem is divided.
That's the reality on the ground, and that's what Barak is building
on. And people are so sick and tired of the whole conflict that
they're not going to insist on having an Arab neighborohood under
Israeli control.''
</P>
<P>
   Israel's staunchest defenders say the Jewish community's
willingness to consider some kind of movement on Jerusalem is the
ultimate sign of strength.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jerusalem is different than most other issues, because
Jerusalem makes its way every single day into the consciousness of
every Jew _ because Jerusalem has been the source of hopes and
dreames of every Jew since time immemorial,'' says Steven Grossman,
the former president of the American Israel Public Affairs
Committee is considering a run for governor of Massachusetts. ``But
it is a sign of maturity and a growing up process over the years to
realize that to have everything you ever articulated may stand in
the way of peace.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Michael Paulson writes about religion for The Boston Globe.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-31-00 1338EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000731.0126 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-31 13:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8237 &Cx1f; tab-z
r l BC-POWELL-QUALITIES-SLAT     07-31 1325
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POWELL-QUALITIES-SLATE </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POWELL WOULD HAVE MADE A GREAT VICE PRESIDENT -- BUT THAT'S ALL 
</HEADLINE>
  (Slate commentary)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (The following ``separate buy'' article from SLATE, the premier
online magazine of politics and culture, is available from the New
York Times Syndicate. Please contact syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480)
</P>
<P>
   (David Plotz is Slate's Washington bureau chief.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BY DAVID PLOTZ &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A hallowed rite of American politics ended last Tuesday. Every
few weeks for the last six years, reporters have speculated
hopefully about whether Gen. Colin Powell would deign to run for
president or vice president.
</P>
<P>
   Countless polls have confirmed the general's astounding
popularity_ only 7 percent negative! That's better than motherhood!
</P>
<P>
   His every refusal has been dissected for a loophole. (What
exactly does, ``My answer is irrevocably no'' mean, anyway?) Even
when it became obvious that George W. Bush would pick Dick Cheney,
Dan Rather was claiming that Bush and his father were still trying
to convince the general to grace the ticket.
</P>
<P>
   When he declined a presidential run in 1995, Powell declared
that running for office was ``a calling that I do not yet hear.''
Now it seems clear he never will.
</P>
<P>
   Powell has telegraphed that he would serve as Bush's secretary
of state, and he will almost certainly get the job if Dubya wins.
But electoral politics is not likely. The general will be 67 by the
next presidential election, too old for a first run. He has become
the Mario Cuomo of the GOP, the girl who always got away.
</P>
<P>
   So this is the moment to wonder what we missed. What kind of No.
1 or No. 2 would Powell have been?
</P>
<P>
   Powell's fairytale biography tends to overwhelm actual thinking
about him. His story is too perfect. The son of striving West
Indian immigrants, he grew up in the tough, polyglot South Bronx.
He was an aimless kid, but he found order and meaning in the Army.
He rode military service from Vietnam soldier to national security
adviser to chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff. Eventually, he
prosecuted the most successful war in U.S. history, then retired to
help at-risk kids.
</P>
<P>
   For many, Powell is confirmation of the American dream: A black
man from modest circumstances can do anything if he works hard
enough. He affirmed idealism about the U.S. military: It is the
meritocratic, colorblind institution it claims to be. And he is a
role model and champion of hard work, discipline, honesty, loyalty,
patriotism and good humor.
</P>
<P>
   But the retelling of his spotless life suppresses cool
consideration of the general's fitness for office.
</P>
<P>
   Powell would have been a funny kind of candidate. American
voters demand that their politicians be (or pretend to be)
mavericks. Every presidential candidate promises to shake things
up, claims to be impatient with the ways of Washington, and wants
to seize power back from the bureaucrats and return it to the
people.
</P>
<P>
   Generals have traditionally made compelling candidates because
they appear to be warriors who won't be deterred by Beltway
opposition. This is not Powell. Despite his military service and
apparent outsiderness, he has exactly the qualities Americans say
they don't want in a president. He is an organization man, fiercely
loyal to bureaucracies, happy with the status quo, at least as
comfortable taking orders as giving them.
</P>
<P>
   Powell's military career testifies to his skills as a
bureaucratic infighter. He had one year of real combat_ a nasty
stint as a Vietnam adviser_ but mostly he was a staff officer,
planning and advising superiors on strategy and logistics.
</P>
<P>
   Powell was great at getting along. In a 1968-69 tour of Vietnam,
he served as a staff officer in the division that committed the My
Lai massacre. He arrived in Vietnam after the massacre occurred but
before it was discovered. As Charles Lane chronicled in the New
Republic, Powell made no aggressive effort to investigate war
crimes when he was asked to look into them, and he brushed off a
soldier who had complained.
</P>
<P>
   According to Lane, Powell also kept his head down as a White
House fellow during Watergate. When Powell worked for Ronald
Reagan's National Security Council, he objected quietly to the
Iran-Contra arms-for-hostages deal but then helped Defense
Secretary Caspar Weinberger arrange the dubious transfer of
missiles to Iran.
</P>
<P>
   As chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff, Powell confirmed his
reputation for caution and bureaucratic chess-playing. He won
credit from goo-goos for cutting the Pentagon budget after the Cold
War. But military reformers were dismayed by his methods. He did
not significantly trim any of the four service arms. More
important, he made little effort to reorganize the Pentagon to
fight new, less conventional kinds of war.
</P>
<P>
   Powell also preached the Powell doctrine, his gospelstemming
from Vietnamthat American troops should never be committed to
battle without overwhelming force and overwhelming popular support.
This philosophy, designed to protect the U.S. military from
anything that could tarnish its reputation, arguably elevated
Pentagon interests over national ones.
</P>
<P>
   So when Saddam Hussein invaded Kuwait, Powell opposed driving
him out, favoring sanctions instead. When war came, Powell pushed
to end it quickly before Saddam fell or the Republican Guard was
smashed. Powell, who voiced his objections privately, carried out
President Bush's orders superbly and ended up a hero.
</P>
<P>
   But Powell has never absorbed any blame for the U.S. decision
not to vanquish Saddam, nor for our failure to intervene in Bosnia,
another policy he pushed.
</P>
<P>
   In a Washington Post article, Robert Kagan recently contended
that Powell's reluctance to use force, discomfort with the U.S.
acting as a global cop, and general caution make him an iffy choice
for secretary of state. Under Powell, Kagan hints, the Department
of State might retrench into isolationism and inactivity just when
the United States must be more engaged in the world than ever.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1997, Powell has devoted much of his time to America's
Promise, a group he founded to encourage volunteering that helps
kids. It too has been marked by his establishmentarian,
bureaucratic style. Powell, a superb recruiter, enlisted
corporations, nonprofits, and governments to commit resources to
children. (America's Promise pushes mentoring, safe places for
kids, and child health among its ``five promises.'')
</P>
<P>
   But despite scads of Powell-centered PR, it's not clear the
organization has achieved much. The New York Times, the newspaper
Youth Today, and philanthropy scholar Pablo Eisenberg have smacked
America's Promise for operating secretively, exaggerating
accomplishments and resisting objective assessments of its
programs. Corporations have failed to deliver on some of their
commitments. Those that have delivered have made their
contributions to big, establishment charities, rather than the
grass-roots ones that most help needy kids.
</P>
<P>
   Powell's history, in short, does not suggest that he would have
made a great president. That job requires an impatient leader who
likes to slice through red tape, not create it, and who wants to
shake up the government, not pacify it.
</P>
<P>
   But we have missed a superb vice president, someone who would
complain mildly in private but follow the president's orders in
public, someone who would protect the federal bureaucracy while
making it slightly more efficient, someone who wouldn't take risks,
someone who would stay out of trouble.
</P>
<P>
   Someone a lot like Al Gore.
</P>
<P>
   -------
</P>
