<HEADLINE>
MOVIES RECENTLY REVIEWED IN THE BOSTON GLOBE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; !!! &LR;  ``The Five Senses'' Five alienated people, living in the
same building in Toronto, emerge from their respective states of
isolation through their senses. It sounds suffocatingly schematic,
but filmmaker Jeremy Podeswa handles touch, sight, taste, smell,
and hearing with enough light-handedness to keep the mix compelling
and at times even elegant. (R) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; !! &LR;  ``Nutty Professor II: The Klumps'' Eddie Murphy, back again
with lots and lots of latex and other makeup as he plays all but
one of the chunky Klump family. They dote on and make trouble for
large, lovable Sherman, who discovers a youth serum. There are
laughs, especially when Grandma Klump acts up, but more nuttiness
and less padding would have kept sequelitis at a greater distance.
(PG-13)
</P>
</TEXT>
