<SLUG> BC-RENO-TRAVEL-MATURE-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE MATURE TRAVELER: RENO'S HISTORIC RICHES 
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  ATTENTION EDITORS: The following material from The New York Times
Syndicate is for use by WAY TO GO! clients. Nonsubscribers can use
this article only by special arrangement. For purchase information,
see end of text. 
 &HT;    
 (Color slide included.) 
 By ADELE MALOTT 
 Condensed from The Mature Traveler Newsletter 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) 
 &HT;    Like anyone living in a popular tourist destination, I developed
a standard tour itinerary years ago for my out-of-town friends who
wish to see all that Reno, Nev., has to offer.
 &HT;    Because Reno is known for gaming, most of my visitors want to
stop at a casino to try their luck at gambling or to see a show.
But it doesn't take long for the area's natural beauty to weave its
magic. Even in midsummer, the snow-dappled Sierra Nevada set
against the clear blue sky is like a magnet for sightseers.
 &HT;    My personal tour starts in Truckee, home of the Donner Memorial
Museum, (530) 582-7892, that tells the heartbreaking story of the
Donner Party who were trapped in the Sierra Nevada during one of
our area's worst winters.
 &HT;    Then it's up Route 89 to Tahoe City for a stop at Fanny Bridge
overlooking the Truckee River. Fanny Bridge gets its name from the
poses people strike as they lean over the bridge to watch the giant
trout swim below.
 &HT;    A driving tour of Carson City, the capital of Nevada, is next.
Then, depending on the mood of the group, we head west to Genoa _
reputedly Nevada's first settlement and home of the state's oldest
saloon _ or east to Virginia City _ where the rich ore deposits of
this lavish boomtown helped finance Union efforts in the Civil War
and buy Nevada early statehood.
 &HT;    A visit to Reno wouldn't be complete without a walk along the
Truckee River and downtown _ usually with a stop at the National
Auto Museum _ and a meal at a Basque hotel, where ethnic fare is
served family-style at long tables.
 &HT;    But beware: If a Basque meal strikes your fancy, be prepared to
eat. A lot. The food is served in a series of seemingly endless
courses, giving diners ample time to visit with table mates who may
hail from other parts of the city, country or world.
 &HT;    A drive to Pyramid Lake, just northeast of Reno and famous for
being the location where Charleton Heston was filmed parting the
Red Sea in the ``The Ten Commandments,'' usually tops off my
official tour.
 &HT;    Recently, when I took a group of out-of-towners on a sightseeing
trip of the city, I realized how outdated my tour route had become.
All the sites I've mentioned are indeed worth visiting, but now
there's so much more to explore.
 &HT;    For example, a trip to Pyramid Lake and Paiute Indian
Reservation's Fish Hatchery, (775) 476-0500, where one can see how
prehistoric cui-ui fish are being saved, now can include a stop at
the new Tribal Museum and a visit to the Bureau of Land
Management's Wild Horse Adoption Center, (775) 475-2222 or
www.blm.gov/whb. Horses from Nevada's vast open spaces are brought
and kept here until people adopt them.
 &HT;    The Truckee River, with its 100-mile ribbon of rapids that lead
from Lake Tahoe down to Pyramid Lake, always has been a vital part
of my tour. Now, it's even more important.
 &HT;    Downtown Reno is where the Truckee River intersects with
Virginia Street, the town's main drag. It's home to many new
developments, including:
 &HT;    _ A walk with promenades for special events, such as ballet and
symphony performances.
 &HT;    _ Riverside paths, a favorite with bikers and hikers.
Eventually, these will run the length of the city once development
is completed.
 &HT;    _ Many unique Riverfront buildings, including the Riverside
Hotel and Casino, which is being converted into lofts and studios;
Christ Scientist Church, which is becoming the Lear Theater; and
McKinley School, which has been restored as an arts-and-cultural
center.
 &HT;    Some developments have new twists, such as the bluff overlooking
the south side of the Truckee River, where Reno's elite built homes
in what is now called the Newlands area. These days, local
residents involved in historic preservation lead tours of the area,
mostly for Elderhostel students, (877) 426-8056 or
www.elderhostel.org. Special group tours can be arranged by calling
the Historic Reno Preservation Society, (775) 322-1638.
 &HT;    At the other end of Virginia Street is the town's signature
landmark, an overhead street sign that proclaims Reno as ``The
Biggest Little City in the World.'' This is the fourth version of
the sign, which during World War II served as a landmark for
veterans heading home from the Pacific.
 &HT;    Two models of the sign adorn downtown. The newest is known to
turn green on St. Patrick's Day or go dark during Christmas carol
sing-alongs, while the other model is mounted outside the National
Auto Museum on Lake Street.
 &HT;    West of Reno, my tour now includes a stop at Chrissie Caughlin
Park beside the Truckee River. It's a place I have walked my
miniature schnauzers for years, but I now know that pioneers
traveling in covered wagons used a large pine tree, roughly four
feet in diameter, as their ``post office'' and stuck notes for
other immigrants on its trunk.
 &HT;    Further west, it's possible to take a look-see at the
still-visible tracks of the Donner Party wagon train on either side
of Dog Valley Road near a small town called Verdi.
 &HT;    Reno is rich in history, from miners searching for quick riches
and pioneers hurrying to reach California, to railroaders laying
the train tracks that would stitch together the North American
continent. For decades, it stood as an oasis for people traveling
to other places.
 &HT;    Now, Reno is no longer just a pass-through town. In fact, the
place that's so dear to my heart has finally become a fascinating
vacation destination in its own right.
 &HT;    For more information Reno, call (800) 367-7366 or visit
www.renolaketahoe.com on the Web.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Readers are invited to submit questions and comments to Adele
Malott, c/o The New York Times Syndicate, 122 East 42nd St., 14th
Floor, New York, N.Y. 10168. Send Adele a postcard from your trip
with ideas, questions and information on the bargains you find for
seniors.
 &HT;    Questions may also be sent to Adele by electronic mail. The
address is MatureTrav(at)aol.com. (For (AT) use the symbol on your
keyboard.)
 &HT;    Adele Malott is the publisher of THE MATURE TRAVELER: Travel
Bonanzas for 49ers-Plus, a newsletter for mature travelers.
 &HT;    
 c.2000 The Mature Traveler Newsletter 
