<HEADER>
A8247 &Cx1f; ttf-z
u t BC-ALL-AROUND-ORLANDO-TR     07-31 2173
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ALL-AROUND-ORLANDO-TRAVEL-DOING-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHAT'S DOING IN ORLANDO  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  ATTENTION EDITORS: The following material from The New York Times
Syndicate is for use by WAY TO GO! clients. Nonsubscribers can use
this article only by special arrangement. For purchase information,
see end of text. 
 &HT;    
 (Color slides and B&AMP;W map available.) 
 FROM THE NEW YORK TIMES 
 By SARA KENNEDY  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) 
 &HT;    If competition breeds creativity, then the theme parks in and
around Orlando are a case in point. They have some of the most
imaginative ways for guests to spend their leisure time. Everything
from a roller coaster that shoots its human cargo from the starting
gate with all the subtlety of a missile launcher to a beautiful
carousel based on the art of Dr. Seuss greet visitors to Orlando
theme parks this summer.
 &HT;    Vacationers will also find an entirely new park, SeaWorld's
Discovery Cove, which opened July 1. It features a tropical, beachy
setting populated with 10,000 fish and 300 birds. Guests can play
with dolphins under the supervision of trainers, and enjoy
leisurely swimming, snorkeling and sunning with smaller crowds and
no lines, thanks to a daily limit of 1,000 patrons.
 &HT;    Orlando's theme parks, which last year attracted more than 60
million visitors (up from 48.5 million in 1996), are trying to
handle the crush of crowds better. Discovery Cove's competitors are
trying various ways to cut down waiting lines, a chief complaint of
theme park customers.
 &HT;    Walt Disney World has inaugurated Fastpass, in which guests can
pick up free tickets near its 18 most popular attractions for later
in the day when the lines are shorter. Universal is testing a
similar arrangement called Fast Track. Disney also opens a
different theme park early each day, offering first admittance to
guests at Disney hotels. Until Sept. 4, Universal is rewarding
multiday ticket holders and its hotel guests with early entry to
its two parks, from 7 to 10 a.m. daily.
 &HT;    A spring drought that fueled wildfires and meant watering
restrictions for millions of Floridians seems to have left the
theme parks unscathed. During visits in June, pathways were lined
with bright blooms of bougainvillea and hibiscus, big shade trees
were heavy with foliage, and the acres of perfectly trimmed grass
were as lush as always.
 EVENTS  
 &HT;    Theme parks aren't the only show in Orlando, believe it or not.
Although the calendar of special events seems to thin out a bit in
summer, diversions exist elsewhere in the city.
 &HT;    This summer, audience members help solve a mystery set in deep
space at the Orlando Science Center's planetarium. Performances,
which run through Aug. 31, feature a planetarium show and a live
actor. It's based on the PBS geographical quiz show ``Where in the
World Is Carmen San Diego,'' and is included with admission to the
center: $14.25, seniors $13.25, ages 3 to 11 $11.
 &HT;    Through Sept. 10, ``Hunters of the Sky'' looks at birds of prey,
with over 70 mounted specimens of falcons, eagles, owls and other
raptors. The center, at 777 East Princeton St., is open daily;
(407) 896-7151.
 &HT;    Through Sept. 3, ``Art of the 20th Century,'' at the Cornell
Fine Arts Museum, on Holt Avenue at Rollins College in Winter Park,
looks at the last 100 years through European and American painting,
sculpture, prints and drawings from the permanent collection. Free
admission; closed Monday. Call (407) 646-2526.
 &HT;    The Orlando Museum of Art, 2416 North Mills Ave. in Loch Haven
Park, will display beadwork, baskets and decorated animal hides
from Kenya, Tanzania and other East African countries. The
exhibition runs through May 27. Admission is $6, seniors and
students $4, ages 4 to 11 $2; closed Monday: (407) 896-4231.
 &HT;    The Orlando-University of Central Florida Shakespeare Festival
begins Sept. 20, with previews of ``The Woman in Black,'' a
Victorian mystery by Stephen Mallatratt, from a book by Susan Hill,
which runs through Oct. 28. Performances are at the Orange County
Historical Museum Theatre in Loch Haven Park, at Princeton and
Mills Avenues in Orlando. Tickets: $7 to $20; (407) 893-4600.
 &HT;    At Disney's Wide World of Sports, adjacent to the theme parks,
the 2000 Junior Olympic Games, the Amateur Athletic Union's top
event, features track and field competition from July 31 through
Aug. 5. The 250-acre complex is off Exit 25B of I-4. Daily general
admission is $9, ages 3 to 9, $7; (407) 939-1505.
 SIGHTSEEING  
 &HT;    At Discovery Cove, off Exits 27A and 28 of I-4, guests come face
to face with bottlenose dolphins. They can touch the animals, and
trainers allow some patrons to play water games with the dolphins.
The park requires reservations. It employs one staff member for
every five guests to provide supervision for the dolphins, better
service and no waiting lines. Admission is $179 for ages 6 and
older who want to swim with dolphins; ages 3 to 5 and those
skipping a dolphin swim pay $89.
 &HT;    Admission includes a meal outside at the Laguna Grill, use of
snorkeling and beach gear (towels, chairs, hammocks), and a
seven-day pass to the original SeaWorld park nearby, where visitors
can see Shamu and ride the Kraken, a roller coaster that made its
debut last month; (877) 434-7268.
 &HT;    Otherwise, ticket prices are one area where Orlando's theme
parks don't show variety. Prices for a one-day, one-park ticket for
ages 10 and up at Disney World's theme parks are $46; ages 3 to 9,
$37. The Magic Kingdom and Disney-MGM Studios are off Exit 25B;
Epcot and Animal Kingdom, Exit 26B. For all Disney parks
information: (407) 824-4321.
 &HT;    Ticket prices are the same at SeaWorld, at Exits 27A and 28,
(407) 351-3600; and Universal, at Exits 30A and 29B, (407)
363-8000. Various multipark and multiday tickets are also
available.
 &HT;    The theme-park attractions with the highest profile _ in the
physical sense _ are roller coasters, and Orlando boasts a crop of
wild new ones. SeaWorld's Kraken rises 15 stories, then plunges its
screaming passengers toward earth at 65 m.p.h. Riders on the
Incredible Hulk are practically blown out of the starting gate from
what looks like a giant missile launcher at Universal's Islands of
Adventure park, which opened in May 1999.
 &HT;    The Rock 'n' Roller Coaster at Disney-MGM Studios, which opened
a year ago, treats its riders to an equally explosive start,
accelerating from zero to 60 m.p.h. in 2.8 seconds, with the music
of the band Aerosmith pumped through the seats.
 &HT;    A simulator game that pits guests of DisneyQuest, an indoor
interactive playground, against the same motley gang from the
Pirates of the Caribbean ride opened June 21 outside the park in
Downtown Disney. Four players, all wearing three-dimensional
goggles, board a sailing ship under attack (its deck sickeningly
weaves and rolls on springs controlled by computer) and defend
themselves with cannons. Tickets cost $27, ages 3 to 9, $21.
 &HT;    Universal's ``Terminator 2,'' a film that opened in 1996 at
Universal Studios Theme Park, involves three-dimensional thrills
and bizarre special effects, including fog and rain. It's the usual
end-of-the-world scenario, starring Arnold Schwarzenegger, complete
with realistic guns booming and screeching pileups.
 &HT;    One of the most elegant new rides is the beautiful interactive
carousel of Dr. Seuss animals _ pull the reins and hair might fly
up or a tongue stick out _ at Islands of Adventure. The bright pink
and blue carousel is based on the art of Dr. Seuss.
 &HT;    One park that has no problem with crowds is Splendid China, a
76-acre park opened in 1993 by a Chinese company to acquaint
Americans with the country's culture. It features nearly deserted
gardens with more than 60 miniature models of historical Chinese
sites.
 &HT;    Sparse crowds usually greet its chief daily theatrical
production, the ``Mysterious Kingdom of the Orient'' _ a pity since
it is a knockout performance of colorful costumes, traditional
Chinese song and dance, acrobatics and martial arts. Follow Route
192 west from I-4 to Exit 25B in Kissimmee (directions and ticket
information from park employees may be incorrect). Admission costs,
which include the show and a terrible meal, are $19.95, and $9.95
ages 5 to 12. Call (407) 396-7111 or (800) 244-6226.
 WHERE TO STAY  
 &HT;    It's always easier to park your car and stay on the grounds of a
theme park, but hotels and food usually cost more. A moderately
priced choice is Disney's All-Star Resorts, at Exit 26B of I-4,
with a mammoth complex of 5,760 basic rooms with outdoor pools,
bakery, food court and free bus service to Disney attractions.
Rooms are $74 to $104 a night; (407) 934-7639.
 &HT;    Minutes east of the theme parks is the Hampton Inn-Orlando
Convention Center hotel, 8900 Universal Blvd., which opened in
April 1999. The staff is helpful and friendly; there is a heated
outdoor pool; the free Continental breakfast includes cereals,
bagels, yogurt, fruit and waffles; and the 170 spotless rooms, with
maple furniture and decorated in bright, tropical colors, are $69
to $109, depending on the season; (407) 354-4447, fax (407)
354-3031.
 &HT;    Budget: A simple hotel tucked away off Interstate 4, the Comfort
Inn Maingate South is an easy 15-minute ride from most of the theme
parks. It is off I-4 Exit 23, eight miles west of Walt Disney World
at 5510 U.S. Highway 27 North. Its 150 rooms cost $40 to $100, more
on holidays; outdoor pool; (800) 255-4386, fax (863) 424-1723.
 &HT;    Luxury: Elegant, sand-colored Italian marble and huge bouquets
of native orchids give the lobby of the Peabody Orlando, 9801
International Drive, a distinctive Florida feel, and it's fun to
watch the hotel's mascot ducks cavort in the fountain. Its 891
modern rooms are decorated in yellow and moss green; doubles are
$330 a night; outdoor pool and children's pool with waterfall;
(407) 352-4000, fax (407) 351-0073.
 &HT;    The Grand Floridian Resort and Spa, Disney's sprawling
Victorian-style hotel, boasts 900 quaint rooms, decorated with
printed wall coverings, marble-top sinks, ceiling fans and
Victorian woodwork. Big gingerbread porches with climbing roses
overlook a lagoon on theme park grounds with a man-made beach and
two outdoor pools, one for children. Off Exit 25B. Doubles are $304
to $400; (407) 824-3000, fax (407) 824-3186.
 WHERE TO EAT  
 &HT;    At Universal's CityWalk, a 30-acre dining and entertainment
complex, Jimmy Buffett's Margaritaville is (what else?) completely
casual. Try conch fritters dipped in honey-mustard sauce, followed
by Caribbean grilled chicken salad, topped with almonds and
habanero-mango ranch dressing, and key lime pie for dessert. Dinner
for two with margaritas, about $50; (407) 224-2155.
 &HT;    Nearby, also at CityWalk, you'll find Emeril's, the Orlando
branch of a series of restaurants owned by the popular TV chef
Emeril Lagasse. Reservations are recommended. Specialties include
an appetizer of Maine lobster cheesecake; roasted rack of lamb with
a Creole mustard sauce, and fresh Florida orange cake with
strawberry compote. Dinner for two with wine, $125; (407) 224-2424.
 &HT;    Of all the theme parks, SeaWorld serves some of the best food,
and its casual Bimini Bay restaurant, with waiters and waitresses
wearing Hawaiian shirts, is typical. The menu features salads,
pasta and seafood; try the fresh Florida grouper sandwich or
marinated steak on a roll with sauteed onions and peppers. Lunch
for two with beer costs about $40 (you must have a park pass);
(407) 351-3600.
 &HT;    Two sessions of a gospel brunch occur every Sunday morning at
the House of Blues Music Hall, at Downtown Disney (where no park
pass is needed), featuring nationally known and local gospel
performers, and an all-you-can-eat Southern buffet. The meal and
show cost $28; ages 3 to 9, $15. It's a good idea to buy tickets at
least a week in advance at (407) 934-2583, fax (407) 934-2216, or
at the House of Blues box office.
 &HT;    A good family-style restaurant near Walt Disney World is
Pebbles, 12551 State Road 535; (407) 827-1111. It serves a nice mix
of dishes adults enjoy, like the excellent black bean soup ($3.25)
or Mediterranean salad ($7.50), and child-friendly items like the
cheeseburger ($6.95)and white chocolate mousse ($3.95). 
 &HT;    -----
 &HT;    (Sara Kennedy lives in Tampa.)
 &HT;    -----
 c.2000 Sara Kennedy 
