<HEADLINE>
THE RISE _ AND FALLING PRICE _ OF THE DVD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL BLOWEN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In March 1997, the DVD format debuted with about 900 titles and
players costing as much as $1,000. Now, with 9,000 titles and
inexpensive players, DVD is on the cusp of replacing audio CD, VHS,
CD-ROM, and video game discs and cartridges.
</P>
<P>
   The digital versatile disc or digital video disc _ no one agrees
on what DVD stands for _ has revived the home video market,
breathed new life into old movies, given actors and directors the
option to discuss their work on alternate tracks, and, with
declining prices for both discs and players on the horizon, has
become affordable for the consumer. Players can now be purchased
for $150 and the average price of a disc is expected to fall to
$20-$25 retail before the end of the year. As of last month, more
than 2 million players have been sold, according to Jim Taylor,
author of ``Demystifying DVD,'' the definitive book on the format.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before its third birthday in March, 2000,'' writes Taylor,
``DVD had become the most successful consumer electronics product
ever.''
</P>
<P>
   Paul Kagan, an industry analyst, expects 172 million discs to be
purchased
</P>
<P>
   this year and estimates that, by 2006, the total number will
reach 623 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``The sky's the limit,'' says Martin Greenwald, president of
Image Entertainment, one of the largest distributors and licensees
of DVD titles. ``I thought the laserdisc would catch on, but people
weren't ready. Now they are. The only problem with the boom is
getting the discs out to the public and keeping the quality high.''
</P>
<P>
   According to Paul Sweeting, who writes for both Video Business
and Variety, rental spending is up 3.3 percent at a time when most
experts believed the rental market would continue shrinking. And
it's due to the increased availability of DVD titles. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Stealing a look &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But there's a problem. As long as there are products people are
willing to buy, there'll be others who are willing to steal them.
Piracy is a huge issue for the producers. For several years, Steven
Spielberg refused to release his films in DVD because of piracy
problems. Walt Disney Co. chairman and CEO Michael Eisner, who has
released many of the Disney animated films on DVD, is threatening
to delay ``Snow White and the Seven Dwarfs'' until he receives more
assurances that safeguards will be improved.
</P>
<P>
   The movie is ``one of the backbones of the company, and it could
be lost forever,'' Eisner told a joint committee of Congress
earlier this summer. ``We're considering not doing it.''
</P>
<P>
   Eisner, as quoted in Video Business magazine, called the threat
of digital piracy ``the most devastating thing to happen to the
entertainment business, I think, in 75 years.''
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after Eisner's testimony, Congress passed the Digital
Millennium Copyright Act, a law designed to protect the studios
against piracy. The Motion Picture Association of America and
various other groups dedicated to preserving creative property have
filed suits against a variety of Web sites accusing them of
illegally copying DVD movies.
</P>
<P>
   US District Court Judge Lewis Kaplan is currently hearing
testimony in New York in the case of Eric Corley, a computer hacker
who explained how to decode DVDs on his Internet site. The studios
are suing Corley to prevent the ``unauthorized distribution of
their copyrighted material.''
</P>
<P>
   Marsha King, vice president of worldwide business affairs for
Warner Home Video, testified, ``If the legislation is not upheld,
then we've lost our protection for products in the digital
domain.''
</P>
<P>
   While Kaplan issued an injunction preventing Corley from
unlocking the encryption codes, most industry analysts expect that
no matter which side wins in New York, the other side will appeal
and the legal ramifications won't be decided until the case, as
expected, gets to the US Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
   ``The big issue now is not whether DVD will succeed, but how we
should go about our business,'' said consultant Andrew Harrington. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Clarity begins at home &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Part of the appeal of the DVD, aside from a clearer picture
and crisper sound, is the additional information and entertainment
value of the ancillary tracks,'' says R O'Donnell, a spokesman for
Criterion and Home Vision, two major DVD manufacturers and
distributors. ``Our staff has also played an important role in film
preservation.'' Since videotape tends to disintegrate through use
over time, films last much longer when imprinted on DVD.
</P>
<P>
   The additional appeal of DVD is that movie producers, directors,
and actors are beginning to see the new format not as a competitor
to the theatrical run, but as another step in a movie's
evolutionary path.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope that more people get to see the film,'' says Sigourney
Weaver, who took time out from a film she's shooting to discuss the
fate of ``A Map of the World,'' an independent film that didn't
find a large audience during its theatrical run last fall and is
slotted for release on DVD in mid-September.
</P>
<P>
   ``The big films tend to crush the smaller ones in the
theaters,'' says the star of ``The Year of Living Dangerously,''
``Ghostbusters,'' ``Alien,'' and dozens of other movies with
budgets large and small. ``This film came out of the festivals,
including the Boston Film Festival, with great promise, but it's a
complex film and needs good word-of-mouth. Unfortunately, it didn't
last long enough in the theaters to get that going. Everyone in the
movie business seems to be so impatient. I'm hoping that it'll find
its audience on DVD.''
</P>
<P>
   Frankie Muniz, 14, star of ``My Dog Skip,'' believes that the
additional commentary tracks on DVD add to the film's entertainment
value. On the alternate track, the young actor talks about bonding
with Enzo, the Jack Russell terrier who plays the majority of
Skip's scenes. Enzo, by the way, is the son of Moose, who plays
Eddie, the pooch on ``Frasier.'' Moose plays the older Skip at the
end of the film.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't know what to expect when I sat down to do the DVD,''
says Muniz, before reporting to work for his successful situation
comedy, ``Malcolm in the Middle,'' earlier this week. ``I was just
honest. I think the movie's just awesome and I'm not saying that
because I'm in it. I would think it was the best movie even if I
wasn't in it. I just sat down and talked about the movie. It was
cool.''
</P>
<P>
   At last week's Video Software Dealers Association conference in
Las Vegas, industry professionals no longer debated the acceptance
of the format but how to proceed in the future.
</P>
<P>
   While the piracy issue remains unresolved, the DVD titles are
pouring out of the studios as fast as the manufacturers can press
the discs. Upcoming releases include ``Men in Black'' with
commentary by director Barry Sonnenfeld and star Tommy Lee Jones,
on Sept. 5, ``The Perfect Storm'' on Nov. 14, and ``Gladiator'' on
Nov. 21.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
