A8279 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-BOOK-CLIFT-BOS &LR;      07-31 0684
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-CLIFT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GAUGING THE PROSPECT OF A WOMAN BECOMING PRESIDENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RENEE LOTH  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
MADAM PRESIDENT 
Shattering the Last Glass Ceiling 
By Eleanor Clift and Tom Brazaitis. Scribner. 349 pp. $26. 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Do women deserve consideration for high political office as a
matter of sheer equity, or because they will fundamentally change
the way business is conducted in the halls of power? This question
is never quite addressed in ``Madam President,'' a timely look at
the nation's sputtering efforts to envision a woman in America's
top job.
</P>
<P>
   There are 65 women in the 106th Congress, 92 in statewide
office, and 1,670 in state legislatures, and sometimes it seems
that authors Eleanor Clift and Tom Brazaitis have interviewed every
one. Like many of the pragmatic activists pushing female
candidates, the book itself seems more intent on achieving critical
mass than on examining the unique perspective and negotiating style
women might bring to the national stage. From Elizabeth Dole and
Geraldine Ferraro to Arizona's superintendent of education, Lisa
Graham Keegan, the tales of scores of ``ladies in waiting'' are
told in detail. Massachusetts Lieutenant Governor Jane Swift even
gets her own chapter.
</P>
<P>
   But Clift, a contributing editor at Newsweek magazine, and
Brazaitis, her husband and a Washington columnist for the Plain
Dealer of Cleveland, make few distinctions among the women they
consider, Republican or Democrat, hawk or dove, big spender or
skinflint. They do, however, make the point that women who play
against stereotypes (tough on crime, conservative on social
spending) may have a better chance at pioneering election to the
highest office _ sort of a feminist take on
only-Nixon-could-go-to-China.
</P>
<P>
   In this way, the book reflects the ambivalence that has plagued
the women's movement for at least 20 years: Is it better to excel
at playing the game by the old boy rules, or to change the rules?
The authors cannot suppress a certain pride in the fact that
Secretary of State Madeleine K. Albright displays a Thatcheresque
willingness to prosecute a war, or that California congresswoman
Ellen Tauscher was named to head a Democratic Party fund-raising
committee that offers $10,000 contributors ``special entree to
members (of Congress) and issue briefings in exchange for financial
support.'' It is this kind of business as usual that many voters
hope women will reject.
</P>
<P>
   Clift and Brazaitis are thorough reporters and display a
journalistic reserve that would be admirable in a magazine or
newspaper article but seems rather dry for a book, considering the
clarion call in the title. The narrative is not well-organized; if
it had been written chronologically or thematically it might have
had more drive. As it is, a little Jeanne Kirkpatrick is shoehorned
into the chapter on Dole, a little Sandra Day O'Connor is in the
section on women governors.
</P>
<P>
   Still, ``Madam President,'' with its careful recitation of the
hurdles women candidates face, is an invaluable primer for any
woman who is considering a run for office at any level. And with
the Democratic veepstakes still in full swing, it could prompt at
least one presidential candidate to give more than the obligatory
once-over to a woman for that job _ not because the
vice-presidential choice ever counts much in winning elections
(just ask Ferraro), but because the very act of interviewing women
can give a presidential hopeful a fuller perspective.
</P>
<P>
   Women have much to offer national campaigns, but the white-hot
glare of the spotlight makes all but the strongest wither. Dole,
who abandoned her bid for president earlier this year, is typical
of the ambitious woman whose ``childhood and young adulthood was a
steady march of achievement'' but couldn't stand the risk of
failure. On the way to attaining critical mass, women in politics,
business, science, and other nontraditional pursuits look forward
to the day when they are allowed not to excel, to achieve, to break
barriers, but simply to participate.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-31-00 1346EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
