A8280 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-BOOK-BLOOM-BOS &LR;      07-31 0987
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-BLOOM-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AMY BLOOM SHEDS LIGHT ON EVERYDAY CHARACTERS IN DARK HOURS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GAIL CALDWELL  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
A BLIND MAN CAN SEE HOW MUCH I LOVE YOU 
By Amy Bloom. Random House. 163 pp. $22.95. 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Empathy is one of the implicit prerequisites for a good writer
of fiction; next to sensibility (an instinctual regard for nouns
and verbs) and imagination, it may be the trait that matters most.
As a practicing psychotherapist, Amy Bloom presumably relies daily
upon this quality, which abounded through her 1993 debut, the story
collection ``Come to Me,'' and her 1997 novel, ``Love Invents Us.''
She grapples with the darkest of subjects _ psychosis, betrayal,
the death of children _ and yet infuses these caverns with light:
The perspective is so unruffled and intimate that she might as well
be rendering a morning spent baking cookies in a sun-filled
kitchen. Her distinguishing premise is the warmth of the ordinary,
in other words, for Bloom must have long realized that suffering,
whether madness or illness or a shattered heart, is as common as
night, and can be just as hard to stare down and describe.
</P>
<P>
   The stories of ``A Blind Man Can See How Much I Love You'' all
draw on this generosity of affect, which allows them to be more
bearable than their subjects sound in summary: a best friend
struggling through the last ravages of cancer; a son, ravaged by
grief, who takes illicit refuge in his stepmother's arms. See?
Death and incest, but portrayed here with grace, authenticity, and
even considerable wit. In the paired stories of ``Lionel and
Julia,'' delivered in the first and then third persons, a son
announces in the opening paragraphs that he slept with his
stepmother the day after his father's funeral. The next 40 pages
are spent understanding how this could have happened _ the cliff's
edge of grief and misplaced yearning they both walked, the price
extracted for that moment of desperation. It's one thing to
consider this experience _ the Oedipal kiss of death _ without the
individual human quality; quite another to meet the mother in
question, who turns out to be a gray-haired jazz critic with a
heart the size of Utah, as well as her own crater of regret.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps because Bloom isn't frightened of such human misfires,
she can see beyond their tragic consequence to the fear and
confusion that spawned them. And love walks the hallways of all
these rooms, whether they hold the mother grieving her infant son
in ``Stars at Elbow and Foot'' or the young woman in ``The Gates
Are Closing,'' a child of Holocaust survivors, whose lover is
succumbing to Parkinson's. Partly everyone just soldiers on: When
the Holocaust daughter tries to explain to her mother that
Buchenwald may have had something to do with her brother's mental
illness, the mother brushes her aside: ``Please,'' she tells her.
``We're very lucky. We're fine. Louis has your Uncle Morti's
nervous stomach, that's all.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Louis recovered from his nervous stomach,'' the narrator tells
us, ``with enough Haldol to fell an ox, and when he got obese and
shaved only on Sundays and paced my mother's halls day and night in
backless bedroom slippers, this was Uncle Morti's legacy as well.''
</P>
<P>
   Bloom's ability to see past the shock of alienation to its human
core hovers over the design of her title story, which begins with
the adoration of a mother for her little girl, ``a mutual
admiration society of two smart, strong, blue-eyed women, one five
and one thirty-five.'' Jane loves Jessie with the unequivocal
boosterism every parent knows; loves her, too, in every infinite
unfolding moment that she realizes her child feels more at home as
a boy. This is a story, in capsule, about gender reassignment, or
transsexual crisis, but Bloom's compassionate reach has made it
something else _ an exploration of identity where the answers lie
in tenderness, desire, and unflagging loyalty.
</P>
<P>
   But this collection is slighter than Bloom's widely admired
``Come to Me''; its shadows of individual sorrows start to seem
redundant after a while, which is hardly the point. And the stories
falter at times under an externally imposed quality of literary
artifice, where Bloom sacrifices her unerring psychic candor for a
more academic notion of what a story ought to be. This reveals
itself most often in weak or too-neat endings: a mother's grief
salved by sacrifice; fear and sorrow soothed, however transiently,
by love. Life is messier than this, as Bloom well knows, and her
stories end most resonantly when they're left to the stony path of
ambiguity. More unnerving though less frequent is an occasional
creakiness of craft, when people hear through walls or see through
binoculars in order to further the plot.
</P>
<P>
   Mostly, though, the abundance of humanity in ``A Blind Man Can
See How Much I Love You'' is enough to carry it, for the simple
reason that Bloom blasts a hole through the narrow spaces of
provincial thought: She delivers terrible news in palatable ways.
The finest story in the collection is markedly different from the
rest. Told in the first person by an unapologetically angry woman
who's been mauled by her own life, ``The Story'' is about the
unscripted, unkempt disappointments that await you on the road. It
is also, to its credit and daring, about the art of deceit that we
call fiction _ the ways we manipulate, revise, or bend the
narrative to shoehorn it into order. Some people will not take to
this story; it is self-conscious and artful, and almost vehemently
anti-Bloom. But it has about it an architectural truthfulness and
pain that I appreciated: No tidy endings or sweet transcendence,
just the demon of daily living. That's a universal beast that won't
be tamed by either literary finery or the 50-minute hour, and it
seems to me fitting, and oddly courageous, that Bloom has given it
the final say.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
