<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-31 13:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8282 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-BOOK-BERNICE-BOS &LR;      07-31 0777
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-BERNICE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AN ILLUMINATING ACCOUNT OF THE LIVES OF ABUSED WOMEN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALYSSA HAYWOODE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
SAVING BERNICE 
Battered Women, Welfare, and Poverty 
By Jody Raphael 
Northeastern University Press, 184 pp., $45 (cloth), $16.95
(paperback) 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   At first, Bernice Hampton's story sounds so grim it invites
cynicism. Her father was an alcoholic who beat his wife and put his
son in a bucket, poured gasoline on the boy, and tossed in a match,
burning the child to death. He told his wife that if she testified
against him, he would kill her and everyone else in the family. An
aunt went to court and told the truth.
</P>
<P>
   Putting this story in chapter one of a book called ``Saving
Bernice: Battered Women, Welfare, and Poverty,'' could seem like a
pathetic ploy for sympathy. But Jody Raphael, head of the Center
for Impact Research, a nonprofit organization in Chicago, has
written a more profound book.
</P>
<P>
   Virginia Woolf quotes head each chapter _ haunting reminders
that women have been poor ``not for two hundred years merely, but
from the beginning of time.'' Even with a room of one's own, Woolf
says, women must struggle to pay the rent and furnish the room. In
a foreboding tone, she warns that the obstacles women face include
men.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to Woolf, Raphael deftly mixes news stories,
research, interviews, anecdotes, and statistics. It is, however,
Bernice's raw narrative that drives the book. Although she tells of
being a teenage victim of rape, dating violence, and domestic abuse
who ends up on welfare for eight years, readers are not asked for
pity. Instead, Raphael offers insight.
</P>
<P>
   Take the anecdote _ you can often find it in newspaper stories,
or politicians' remarks _ about the welfare mother who drops out of
a training program. She may seem lazy, fearful, addled, or
unconcerned about her children. But Raphael argues that the woman
may not be the problem at all. In Bernice's case, her partner,
Billy, would take her books, refuse to baby-sit for their children,
beat her, or rape her when she attended classes or training
programs. Bernice explains: ``Billy knew that our life was nothing.
If I went to work, he would have lost me. He knew it, and that was
what he was afraid of. He was right. If I had been able to get a
job, I would have been gone.''
</P>
<P>
   A memoir might provide a flimsy haven, the sensation that by
definition the tale of a tragedy is only one person's story. But
the point of this book is that Bernice _ even in her most tortured
moments _ is not alone. And Billy is no aberration. Raphael quotes
training program staff who confirm that domestic violence is a
common problem. Employers describe women who come to work with
bruises. And studies show that women who are stalked by abusers
lose time at work.
</P>
<P>
   Raphael whacks traditional gender roles, arguing that the desire
for a ``normal'' life causes some women to put up with abuse that
may trap them in poverty in order to keep families intact.
Similarly, Billy and other men in the book argue that women should
stay home. This faded chestnut becomes a justification for
sabotaging or even beating women.
</P>
<P>
   Although the book often reads like a novel, Raphael makes a
compelling public policy plea. Before the first chapter ends,
readers get a thorough education. An easily digestible 156 pages of
text, the book is nonetheless packed with information. Even readers
who disagree with Raphael are likely to concur with her call for
more research.
</P>
<P>
   Raphael tackles controversial issues: men's jealousy of women's
earnings, and the idea that while women of all incomes suffer from
domestic violence, poor women are more vulnerable to this abuse.
Raphael argues that teenagers' pregnancies may be due not to
carelessness but to coerced sex. Women who keep having babies, she
notes, may do so because their partners refuse _ even violently _
to use contraception. And she discusses the impact of
post-traumatic stress disorder on victims of domestic violence. A
vital point: Look at the men. Study their conflicts and stresses
and help them meet their economic needs.
</P>
<P>
   As for Bernice, she is working by the book's end. Sadly, her son
lives with Billy, who is in another abusive relationship. But like
Hester Prynne at the end of ``The Scarlet Letter,'' Bernice says
she believes that men and women can get along. She talks of reading
about a ``nice little block'' where in one house a man abused his
partner, but eventually left because women neighbors kept calling
the police. Bernice's and the book's powerful last words: ``I want
to live on that block.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-31-00 1347EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
