<DOCNO> NYT20000731.0158 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-31 13:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8283 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-BOOK-PUTNAM-BOS &LR;      07-31 1132
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-PUTNAM-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AN UNPLANNED MODERN TREND: A SLIPPING SENSE OF COMMUNITY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL KENNEY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
BOWLING ALONE 
The Collapse and Revival of American Community 
By Robert D. Putnam. Simon &AMP; Schuster. 541 pp. $26. 
 
ALMOST HOME 
America's Love-Hate Relationship with Community 
By David L. Kirp. Princeton University Press. 350 pp. $24.95. 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In ``Bowling Alone,'' Robert D. Putnam amasses an overpowering
body of statistical evidence to buttress his argument that the
sense of community has been lost in American society.
</P>
<P>
   The paradigm that produces the title is the decline in the
number of people who belong to bowling leagues _ and thus bowl
together _ even as bowling remains a popular pastime. Further
evidence, both anecdotal and statistical, comes from the records of
bridge clubs, service organizations, church groups, and the like.
</P>
<P>
   As Putnam, a professor of public policy and former dean of
Harvard University's Kennedy School of Government, puts it, well
into the 1960s, Americans were ``joiners,'' entering ``into ever
deeper engagement in the life of their communities.'' But in the
years since then, ``we have been pulled apart'' _ or perhaps more
accurately, have pulled ourselves apart _ ``from one another and
from our communities.''
</P>
<P>
   This argument, originally made in a 1995 article in Journal of
Democracy, attracted considerable academic criticism, mainly about
its methodology. The current book is an attempt both to prove the
original point with new data and to suggest how that lost sense of
community can be restored.
</P>
<P>
   A curious thing about this decline of community _ or of ``social
capital,'' to use the favored public-policy term _ is that America
appears to be awash in ``community.'' It is pretty much impossible
to go through a day's worth of news without finding references to
aggressively powerful or power-hopeful communities _ the ``South
Boston community'' on the one hand, or various minority
``communities'' that would like a taste of such power on the other.
</P>
<P>
   If, as Putnam has put it, social capital represents those
``features of social life'' such as personal networks and shared
activities that help people ``to act together more effectively to
pursue shared objectives,'' then surely the ability of the South
Boston ``community'' to require ``community benefits'' from
would-be developers fits the definition.
</P>
<P>
   This observation provokes a further one: It is an open question
whether more social capital is necessarily a good thing. On this
point, Putnam has arrayed a series of indices. They suggest that
states that rank high in social capital _ in New England,
especially Vermont, and the upper Midwest, especially the Dakotas
(despite, apparently, the endemic poverty and alcoholism on the
Indian reservations) _ have lower rates of violent crime, are
``less pugnacious,'' with children ``who are better off'' and watch
less TV.
</P>
<P>
   Useful _ and engagingly written _ anecdotal evidence on this
subject is presented by David L. Kirp, Putnam's academic opposite
number at the University of California at Berkeley. One such
account describes a community coming together in the aftermath of
the brush fires that swept through the Berkeley-Oakland hills in
1991, destroying some 3,300 homes. ``People who had been burned out
of their homes painted ceramic tiles to memorialize what they had
lost'' _ grandma's china, ``the squirrels who used our telephone
lines as a highway'' _ that ``had an emotional punch akin to the
AIDS quilt.''
</P>
<P>
   When they weren't designing tiles, homeowners were banding
together ``to negotiate bigger insurance claims.'' And when the
insurance money rolled in, those neighborly homeowners proceeded to
build monster villas to replace the arts-and-crafts bungalows that
had been destroyed. As Kirp puts it, ``An inviting hillside of
winding roads, thick foliage, and informal houses had been
transformed, at the cost of more than a billion dollars, into the
kind of place that nobody supposedly wanted.''
</P>
<P>
   It is instructive to place this anecdote against a hypothetical
case that Putnam presents to illustrate the public and personal
benefits of social capital. Putnam's hypothetical couple, Bob and
Rosemary Smith, are parents of 6-year-old Jonathan. They ``support
public education in principle,'' but the local elementary school is
``a shambles.'' Instead of pulling out for a private school, Bob
and Rosemary decide to stick around and organize a PTA.
</P>
<P>
   In public-policy speak, the PTA not only improves the school,
but ``allows for the deepening of interpersonal bonds and `we-ness'
between families and educators.'' And there are personal benefits
for Bob and Rosemary _ ``another couple or two with whom they can
catch a movie on Friday nights'' and more contacts for Bob to call
on if he loses his job.
</P>
<P>
   Taken together, the two cases illustrate an important caveat
that Putnam raises about the value of social capital. ``Sometimes,
`social capital,' like its conceptual cousin `community,' sounds
warm and cuddly,'' he writes. But while ``networks and the
associated norms of reciprocity are generally good for those
inside, the external effects of social capital are by no means
always positive.'' Community-relations officers for police
departments, for example, will privately acknowledge that one
unintended consequence of an alert and vigorous neighborhood crime
watch is to move that neighborhood's criminals along to another,
less-watchful, neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   Which brings up the issue of what to do about all this.
</P>
<P>
   Putnam is very much into think tanks and the like, several times
referring to ``a concerted nationwide conversation'' involving
``thinkers and doers'' that he has ``spearheaded'' in recent years.
(Regrettably, he does not name any specific social-capital product
that has resulted from these conversations.) But at least he seems
to be on the right track with suggestions about the value of
participating in local governmental affairs and community cultural
groups. And, he notes, ``what we need is not civic broccoli _ good
for you but unappealing _ but an updated version of scouting's
ingenious combinations of values and fun.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps, if Americans are no longer ``joiners'' in the old Boy
Scout, Kiwanis, bowling league tradition, the answer lies in taking
advantage of informal opportunities. One bit of sociological
information that should bother readers who consider themselves
friendly and sociable is that the number of times Americans
entertain friends at home has dropped from about 14 times a year in
the late 1970s to about eight now.
</P>
<P>
   A neighborhood cookout appears long overdue _ but please, no
``concerted neighborhood conversations.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
