<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-31 13:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8284 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-BOOK-ESZTERHAS-BOS &LR;      07-31 1293
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-ESZTERHAS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WICKED PLEASURES, EMPTY CALORIES   IN A GONZO TOME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOSEPH P. KAHN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
AMERICAN RHAPSODY 
By Joe Eszterhas. Knopf. 432 pp. $25.95. 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   If presidents get the histories they deserve, and it says here
they do, then it's fitting that we go from ``Dutch,'' an authorized
Ronald Reagan biography that trafficked in fictional characters and
presidential cluelessness, to ``American Rhapsody,'' an
unauthorized Bill Clinton biography that mixes Hollywood depravity
with musings on (and by) the president's private parts.
</P>
<P>
   Which begs the immediate question: Is it too late for the
Democrats to draft Warren Beatty? Because _ forget presidential
timber _ Beatty would make sensational copy. A dream candidate for
the Drudge Age, a walking, talking DNA sample on the Gap dress of
history. ``The flesh he liked to press was horizontal, not
vertical,'' writes Joe Eszterhas of Beatty, comparing him to
Clinton, in a sentence that neatly captures both the wicked
pleasures and empty calories stuffed inside the bloated roast pig
of a book that is ``American Rhapsody.''
</P>
<P>
   Eszterhas is the latest to take measure of the Clinton conundrum
(masterful pol/mendacious skirt-chaser), much to the consternation
of others who have already made a buck or two exploring the subject
and have yet to share a shag rug and a bong with Sharon Stone, darn
their luck. Best known as a highly paid Tinseltown hack (``Basic
Instinct'' and ``Showgirls'' are two of his screenplays), Eszterhas
was at one time a youthful champion of the New Journalism, back in
the days when Rolling Stone was gathering no Kate Moss profiles and
gonzo was a trip, not a cliche. It's nice to see he hasn't lost his
journalistic fastball, even if he's pitching in a more rarefied
league these days _ so rarefied that a publisher will apparently
pay you millions of dollars not to do any reporting, then peddle
your work as nonfiction. Yo, Joe, is this a great country or what?
</P>
<P>
   Three years ago, Eszterhas dropped everything he was working on
(and hasn't the film industry suffered since?) to hunker down with
all the Clinton material he could get his paws on, from the Starr
report to Monica Lewinsky's memoirs. Eszterhas had begun to
recognize in Clinton the same uncontrollable appetites _ for sex,
drugs, rock 'n' roll, and denial _ that shaped the behavior of an
entire generation, appetites that killed Elvis (one of Clinton's
early role models), made a media star out of pornographer Larry
Flynt, and caused Hollywood to release movies like ``Jagged Edge,''
also written by Eszterhas. In other words, the author saw a lot of
himself in the president, and vice versa.
</P>
<P>
   Having decided to explain Bad Boy Bill to the rest of us,
Eszterhas goes all the way, baby, like the governor portrayed in
``American Rhapsody'' with the White House in his sights and his
pants down around his ankles in the back seat of a Cadillac with
Someone Other Than Hillary. And why not the Full Monty? Hollywood
is a perfect lens through which to view contemporary Washington,
Eszterhas suggests. In Hollywood, oral sex is not regarded as sex
at all but rather as a ``little break in a busy afternoon'' for
hard-working male executives.
</P>
<P>
   How perfectly Clintonian! (Or Packwood-esque! Or Gingrich-like!
Your favorite adjective here). And what better final take on the
Clinton years, no? Does anyone this side of Hope, Ark., even
pretend to care how someone like David McCullough would handle the
cigar incident, or what Robert Caro would do with Juanita
Broddrick? Nah.
</P>
<P>
   Give us Kathleen Willey's Oval Office grope, intercut with
scenes from producer Robert Evans's mink-accented bedroom. Give us
James Carville _ rumored to be Hunter S. Thompson's illegitimate
brother! _ kneecapping Clinton's political opponents. Give us a
president who has functioned, in Eszterhas's words, as ``the wet
spot on America's bed.'' Give us footnote 209 to the Starr report,
the one that Nobody Talks About. Give us, Eszterhas says, a
commander in chief who is a compulsive onanist, does drugs with his
cokehead brother, and survives impeachment thanks to two defenders
_ Flynt and Vernon Jordan _ who turn out to have been shot by the
same assailant, a coincidence even Oliver Stone could not make up.
</P>
<P>
   Weaving together two narrative forms (one plainly fictional) in
a way that purportedly separates fact from fantasy, Eszterhas goes
so far over the top as to render any such distinction meaningless.
As a journalist, he's about as reliable as Clinton was a grand jury
witness; as an entertainer, he's Ted Koppel crossed with Ted
Nugent. Eszterhas has plenty to say about his own exploits of the
flesh, too, much of it mildly amusing if not exactly on a par with
the Camp David peace talks for historical significance. ``The truth
was that in the battle of the sexes, many of us were war
criminals,'' he observes, before claiming to have been
rehabilitated by his second marriage. (We'll wait for her memoirs
before rendering judgment.)
</P>
<P>
   The dark heart of this book, though, is occupied not by
sex-crazed Hollywood moguls or even by a phone-sex-crazed Clinton,
but by Richard M. Nixon _ no big surprise, really, in a rambling,
'60s-style manifesto stoned to the gills on generational juices.
JFK may have been priapic, LBJ bombastic, and Reagan a drooling
hypocrite, but Nixon was a true force of evil, the author writes.
Nixon The Night Creature, along with J. Edgar Hoover, the
wire-tapping drag queen. And because Clinton represents everything
Nixon hated _ ``the symbol and personification of the generation
that drove him from office,'' Eszterhas writes _ he is that much
more a sympathetic figure to boomers who came of age loathing Nixon
and who now recoil from born-again pols like George W. Bush, even
though he's a member of their generational tribe.
</P>
<P>
   So where does all this place Eszterhas politically? Does he
betray a conservative or liberal bias? As in the more capable hands
of Thompson, gonzo is a reportorial form that resists easy
categorizing. Thus it is with Eszterhas, who comes from a culture,
after all, that worships money and power far more than political
ideology.
</P>
<P>
   In a Hollywood where Disney executives send along copies of the
XXX-rated Tommy Lee-Pamela Anderson honeymoon tape in the same
package as ``The Lion King'' and ``Beauty and the Beast,'' family
values are better defined by the Sopranos than by the Christian
Coalition, anyway. Hey, have you heard the one about the studio
head who had sex on the balcony of an agent's home in sight of
dozens of party guests? In Hollywood, a story like that is all over
town the next morning. Everybody cares, and then nobody does 15
minutes later. Which is why Hollywood shrugged its shoulders at the
intern-in-the-Oval-Office story, according to Eszterhas. Yawn. Been
there, done that.
</P>
<P>
   So give Eszterhas his due, if not his seven-figure advance.
Quibbling over the factual accuracy of ``American Rhapsody'' is a
bit like chastising the Who for singing ``My Generation'' in the
year 2000, or Minnesota voters for electing Jesse Ventura anything
other than wrestling commissioner. It's utterly beside the point.
Either this book nails the essence of Washington and Hollywood
today _ the two-faced, casting-couch, power-grabbing,
electorate-pandering grotesqueness of it all _ or it does not.
Either it rocks, or it flops. The verdict here is that, like
Clinton and his tenure in office, it's a big, sprawling,
self-contradictory mess: hilarious, profane, improbable, and too
long by half.
</P>
<P>
   And if Warren Beatty ever does get elected president, we already
have a leading candidate for the job of White House spokesman.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
