<HEADER>
A8292 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-ISRAEL-POLITICS-ART-4     07-31 0733
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-POLITICS-ART-470&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RIGHT-WING LEGISLATOR WINS PRESIDENCY OVER PERES; BARAK WINS
NO-CONFIDENCE VOTE 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: This early version will be updated with a Jerusalem-datelined
story by John Kifner.) (ART ADV: Photo NYT2 is being sent to NYT
photo clients. Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by
calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
 
 By CHRISTOPHER S. WREN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In a political upset, a relatively unknown right-wing legislator
was elected Monday as the eighth president of Israel, edging out
his more celebrated opponent, former Prime Minister Shimon Peres,
by a vote of 63-57 in parliament.
</P>
<P>
   The president-elect, Moshe Katzav, 55, has served in the Israeli
parliament for 23 years and held several ministerial posts for the
right-wing Likud Party. His election Monday was hailed by Likud,
which has been the most prominent opponent of conceding any land to
the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
   The humiliating defeat for Peres, 76, reflected a contentious
mood in parliament that portended even more serious political
problems for Prime Minister Ehud Barak, who rode out a
no-confidence vote Monday following his return from a summit
meeting last week with the Palestinian leader, Yasser Arafat, in
the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Barak's ruling coalition was fractured when three parties
defected to protest his decision to join the summit talks. The
defeat Monday of Peres for the presidency threatened to further
undercut Barak's precarious minority government, which survived the
no-confidence motion by a vote of 50-50 with eight abstentions and
12 legislators not present. That was 11 votes short of the 61-vote
majority needed to bring it down.
</P>
<P>
   Almost everyone, from Israeli political commentators to daily
newspapers, had predicted a shoo-in for Peres. Peres won the Nobel
peace prize for his work in helping to bring about the peace
accords reached in Oslo between the Israelis and the Palestinians
in 1983. In addition to serving as prime minister three times,
Peres was also defense minister, foreign minister and finance
minister. He just resigned Sunday as regional cooperation minister.
</P>
<P>
   Katzav, who was born in Iran and raised among immigrants in the
Israeli town of Kiryat Malachi, where he became mayor at 24, is
descended from Sephardic Jews who immigrated from Arabic and
Islamic countries. The elite Ashkenazi Jews of European origin have
traditionally dominated Israeli politics.
</P>
<P>
   The presidency of Israel is considered a ceremonial position and
therefore nominally non-political. But Katzav's predecessor, Ezer
Weizman, had thrown his prestige behind the peace process espoused
by Peres and now Barak. Weizman resigned last month after becoming
embroiled in a scandal over accepting donations of cash from a
French businessman.
</P>
<P>
   Katzav on Monday stressed that his priority would be national
unity and declared his intention to become the president of ``all
Israelis.'' He attributed his election to a desire in parliament
``to bring about a calmer, more unified society.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I intend to contribute to the reduction of tensions within our
society, and I will be the representative of all classes,'' Katzav
said, according to The Associated Press.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Katzav called upon ``Arabs of Israel, the religious and the
secular, Sephardim and Ashkenazi, to see me as their
representative, their president.''
</P>
<P>
   To win the presidency, Katzav needed a simple majority of 61
votes in the 120-seat parliament. But in the first round of
balloting, he received 60 votes while Peres got 57. The three
remaining legislators abstained by casting unmarked ballots.
</P>
<P>
   In the second round, Katzav picked up all three abstentions to
win the presidency with 63 votes to Peres' 57, touching off a
celebration among Likud legislators, some of whom cried and hugged
one another.
</P>
<P>
   Katzav has been described as an earnest but relatively colorless
politician. But his election highlights an ongoing ethnic-political
struggle between the country's Sephardic underclass and its
Ashkenazi establishment.
</P>
<P>
   Barak, having survived Monday's no-confidence vote in parliament
_ his second in a month _ will confront another vote Wednesday on
whether to convene early elections, which otherwise would not fall
due for another three years.
</P>
<P>
   (With reporting by John Kifner in Jerusalem)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
