<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CVN-PHILLY-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CITY OF BROTHERLY LOVE COULD WOO OR BOO BUSH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BUD KENNEDY 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ This city will never escape its history. Nor its
reputation.
</P>
<P>
   As the natives would say, you got yer Ben Franklin. You got yer
George Washington. But the name everybody remembers first is yer
Santa Claus.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the city that booed Santa Claus,'' said Steve Harmon,
a former Dallas radio personality now at a budding Philadelphia
country music station. ``People here know all about that.''
</P>
<P>
   That was at halftime of a Philadelphia Eagles pro football game
in 1968, not as long ago in memory as the city's last national
political conventions in 1948.
</P>
<P>
   This week, the nation will see whether the same Philadelphia
that bitterly despises the Dallas Cowboys will boo or cheer two
guys from Texas: George W. Bush and Dick Cheney.
</P>
<P>
   That is, if the locals even stay in town in the face of warnings
of traffic, protests and chaos, not to mention the Republican
National Convention.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be madness,'' said Jason Williams, 29, guiding
the Philadelphia Ghost Tour on its nightly sundown search for the
spirits of Franklin and other Founding Fathers in the old homes and
cemeteries around Independence Hall.
</P>
<P>
   ``They say 12,000 delegates, 50,000 protesters _ and another
50,000 from the media? Philly people are getting out of town.''
</P>
<P>
   The chaos began over the weekend when the Benjamin Franklin
Parkway, the broad boulevard from downtown to the Eakins Oval and
the Philadelphia Museum of Art, was blocked for protest marches.
That also cut off the main route to the museum's ``Rocky steps'' of
movie fame and to the bright red Alexander Calder statue ``Eagle,''
fetched from its previous home in downtown Fort Worth last year and
perched here on its way to a new home in Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   Texas Republicans will find other familiar sights: the Thomas
Eakins painting ``Swimming,'' at the Philadelphia Museum on loan
from a Fort Worth museum and even a bronze statue of a longhorn
across from the ``Eagle'' at a fountain in the Eakins Oval. Several
hot dog stands sell franks with bacon and barbecue sauce called
``Texas wieners.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Bush's entourage will find that Philadelphians are of a
single mind about Texans, Harmon said: ``They hate 'em.''
</P>
<P>
   He carefully described his Philadelphia listeners as ``crusty.''
``They don't have a soft exterior, but they're good people down
inside.''
</P>
<P>
   They love Dallas music by the Dixie Chicks and LeAnn Rimes, he
said. ``But they hate losing to the Cowboys. Now, they sure hate
this convention tying up the town.''
</P>
<P>
   Harmon and his radio partner, Scott Evans, will risk stirring
that attitude Tuesday when they have Bush's father, noted country
music fan and former President Bush, as a radio guest.
</P>
<P>
   They are not the only hosts who invited the senior Bush and hope
he brings his son along.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know his father is coming here for a party, but _ say, do
you know anything about the governor's schedule?'' museum director
Dr. Marc Micozzi asked hopefully. His Muetter Museum, a medical
school history center, features an exhibit on presidential
surgeries but also showcases ``Siamese Twins in Fact and Fiction.''
</P>
<P>
   The governor will arrive Wednesday, missing a Tuesday party at
City Hall featuring the building of a mile long hoagie sandwich,
followed by a midsummer Mummers parade.
</P>
<P>
   Other planned events for delegates include a tour of the QVC
cable shopping network studio in nearby West Chester, Pa., on
Wednesday morning and, for Young Republican delegates and guests,
late-night happy hours every night and an end-of-convention disco
party until 6 a.m. Friday hosted by MTV.
</P>
<P>
   If other delegates stray into Philadelphia's dozens of downtown
pubs and bars, they will find Katmandu serving a drink called
``Nixon's the One'' and the Irish Pub pouring its version of ``The
American Dream.''
</P>
<P>
   A different fantasy experience can be achieved at PoliticalFest,
a giant local festival staged to attract tourists and visitors to
the downtown convention center, miles from the convention at the
First United Center sports arena.
</P>
<P>
   At PoliticalFest, similar to the interactive ``NFL Experience''
festival at Super Bowls, children or political junkies of any age
can:
</P>
<P>
   _ Pick up a fake press pass.
</P>
<P>
   _ Sit before a camera and anchor a mock TV news report.
</P>
<P>
   _ Make a whistle-stop campaign speech from the back of a rail
car.
</P>
<P>
   _ Sign the Declaration of Independence.
</P>
<P>
   _ Wave signs from a fake convention floor.
</P>
<P>
   _ Sit at a mock Oval Office desk.
</P>
<P>
   _ Or even emerge waving from the door of a mock Air Force One.
</P>
<P>
   Journalism students from Fort Worth's Texas Christian University
took turns coming out of Air Force One waving ``victory'' hand
gestures like Richard Nixon.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody here asks whether I'm for Bush, and I'm not,'' said
Emily Ward, 20, of Springtown, Texas. She has begrudgingly
fulfilled several requests to say ``y'all.''
</P>
<P>
   Not far away, vendor Beverly Hills, 53, of Cordova, Tenn., was
trying to sell red, white and blue cloth cowboy hats for $25.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've put my life savings into this,'' she said, explaining how
she plans to recover her $42,000 investment.
</P>
<P>
   ``It'll be packed this weekend,'' she said. ``The Texans will be
coming in. Texans never have enough cowboy hats. I hope George W.
doesn't let me down.''
</P>
<P>
   Surely, then, the alternative newspaper Philadelphia Weekly was
not referring to Texans on Friday when it greeted visitors with a
single 3-inch high headline:
</P>
<P>
   ``GO HOME!''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
