   TAIWAN-CHINA (Hong Kong) _ Taiwan's president, Chen Shui-bian,
issued another appeal Monday to the Chinese government to reopen
negotiations between the two countries. But his overture was all
but lost in the face of his deepening political troubles at home
and evidence of mounting impatience in Beijing. By Mark Landler.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-CORRUPTION (Shanghai, China) _ China on Monday sentenced a
former central government official to death for taking almost $5
million in bribes, the highest-profile case yet in the country's
marathon anti-corruption drive. By Craig S. Smith.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FINANCIAL &LR;  (``f'' code)
</P>
<P>
   BUYING-ELECTRICITY (Undated) _ There was a time, not so long
ago, when buying electricity was a no-brainer. The local utility
was the only game in town, the state set the rates, there was
little to do but sign on the dotted line. These days, not only are
there myriad utilities and upstart energy companies to choose from,
but countless permutations and combinations of ways to contract for
electricity, including buying it on the Web. As a result, all kinds
of businesses _ from metal smelters to property managers, from
manufacturers to telecommunications companies _ are rethinking not
only how they buy that critical electricity, but who is doing that
buying, how much they are paid, even whom they report to. By
Claudia H. Deutsch.
</P>
<P>
   CANADA-MEDIA (Montreal) _ Conrad Black, the Canadian media
magnate whose holdings include The Daily Telegraph, The Jerusalem
Post and The Chicago Sun-Times, has sold most of his Canadian
assets _ including 50 percent of The National Post _ for $2.4
billion in cash stock to CanWest Global Communications, Canada's
third-largest television network. By James Brooke.
</P>
<P>
   TIME-WARNER-JUNO (Undated) _ Time Warner and Juno Online
Services have reached a deal to allow Juno to offer high-speed Web
access over Time Warner's cable system network. By Saul Hansell.
</P>
<P>
   PEARSON-NCS (Undated) _ Pearson plc, the British media company
that owns The Financial Times, has agreed to acquire National
Computer Systems Inc. as part of a push into the U.S. education
market. By Geraldine Fabrikant.
</P>
