<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-31 14:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8312 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a BC-CADDY-DEVILLE-HNS &LR;      07-31 1316
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CADDY-DEVILLE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;       CADDY DEVILLE GETS RESTYLE TO TEMPT AFFECTIONS OF YOUNG 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By G. CHAMBERS WILLIAMS III  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Cadillac's flagship sedan, the De-Ville, has been completely
redesigned
</P>
<P>
   for 2000 in what may be a last-ditch but highly successful
attempt to save it from what looked to be certain extinction in the
late
</P>
<P>
   '90s. The problem was that the DeVille hadn't been keeping up
with the
</P>
<P>
   times. That is, it wasn't being designed to appeal to the people
who can
</P>
<P>
   most afford to buy it: upscale baby boomers in the prime of
their careers,
</P>
<P>
   with lots of spending power.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the DeVille remained a big, boatlike, glitzy luxury
sedan that
</P>
<P>
   was a clear throwback to the '60s and '70s, when there still was
a market
</P>
<P>
   for such vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   In today's auto market, savvy buyers who have the big bucks to
spend on
</P>
<P>
   their cars don't want the kind of vehicle that an old-style
Cadillac
</P>
<P>
   represents: lots of gratuitous flash, but no real performance or
staying
</P>
<P>
   power.
</P>
<P>
   That's why they have been embracing the luxury brands from
Europe and
</P>
<P>
   Japan, such as Mercedes, BMW, Lexus, Infiniti, Audi and Acura.
</P>
<P>
   Forget the past, though, because Cadillac has made almost all of
the
</P>
<P>
   right moves with this new DeVille, and it should finally be
drawing some
</P>
<P>
   serious attention from affluent, educated boomers.
</P>
<P>
   I say almost, because the styling still might not be quite what
baby
</P>
<P>
   boomers are looking for.
</P>
<P>
   In what I believe had to be a concession to loyal DeVille buyers
of the
</P>
<P>
   past, the car still looks like a Cadillac, although it's not
quite as
</P>
<P>
   large and boat-like as its predecessor.
</P>
<P>
   That's not all bad, though, because even though it still is
readily
</P>
<P>
   identifiable as a Caddy, there's really not much of the old
DeVille left.
</P>
<P>
   This car is new from the ground up, built on the chassis of the
popular
</P>
<P>
   Seville, which Cadillac drastically changed in the early '90s to
try to
</P>
<P>
   appeal to a younger market.
</P>
<P>
   The new DeVille has front-wheel drive, just like the Seville,
and it has
</P>
<P>
   the same basic drivetrain __ the outstanding Northstar System,
with a
</P>
<P>
   powerful but efficient 4.6-liter V-8 engine and smooth-as-glass
four-speed
</P>
<P>
   automatic transmission. The engine turns out 275 horsepower (300
in the
</P>
<P>
   uplevel DTS model).
</P>
<P>
   Beyond the styling and the drivetrain, the new DeVille has
something
</P>
<P>
   else that has never been a strong attribute of a giant Caddy:
great road
</P>
<P>
   handling. It doesn't wallow all over the road like DeVilles of
the past;
</P>
<P>
   in fact, like the Seville, it has become something of a driver's
car.
</P>
<P>
   But that improvement really hasn't come at the expense of ride
and
</P>
<P>
   comfort, as is often the case when performance is enhanced in a
luxury
</P>
<P>
   car. Sure, the new DeVille isn't quite as big as it used to be,
but it's
</P>
<P>
   still a comfortable ride for up to five adults __ six in a pinch
__ and it
</P>
<P>
   still smoothes out bumps almost as well as before (but without
the bounce).
</P>
<P>
   GM says the new DeVille is a trimmer, nimbler execution of a
spacious
</P>
<P>
   luxury sedan, and is three inches shorter and two inches
narrower than the
</P>
<P>
   car it replaces, giving it a trimmer, more athletic appearance.
</P>
<P>
   But its wheelbase is actually 1.5 inches longer, and its
interior space
</P>
<P>
   is virtually as roomy as the 1999 model.
</P>
<P>
   Despite its trimmer appearance, it still is classified a large
car by
</P>
<P>
   the EPA.
</P>
<P>
   High-tech gadgetry abounds in the new DeVille, which should help
in its
</P>
<P>
   bid to appeal to those savvy baby boomers, most of whom have
three or four
</P>
<P>
   personal computers at their disposal, as well as the latest TVs,
audio
</P>
<P>
   systems and home appliances.
</P>
<P>
   Among the gadgetry in our test car for the week, the 2000
DeVille DHS
</P>
<P>
   (base price $45,595 plus $720 transportation), were the
DeVille's unique
</P>
<P>
   night-vision system ($1,995) and the GPS satellite navigation
system with
</P>
<P>
   moving map display ($1,995).
</P>
<P>
   The Raytheon night-vision system, patterned after an infrared
system
</P>
<P>
   used by U.S. troops in the Gulf War, projects a display onto the
lower
</P>
<P>
   part of the windshield in front of the driver showing what lies
in front
</P>
<P>
   of the car's headlights, about a half-mile down the road. It
uses an
</P>
<P>
   infrared beam that picks up the heat of animate objects in the
car's path,
</P>
<P>
   such as a bounding deer or a child running into the street.
</P>
<P>
   It's the first application of this military technology to a
civilian
</P>
<P>
   motor vehicle, and it will be exclusive to the DeVille at least
for the
</P>
<P>
   first two years; after that, General Motors might expand it to
other
</P>
<P>
   vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   San Antonio Cadillac dealers say the system has been popular
with
</P>
<P>
   DeVille buyers who either live in the Hill Country, or who drive
in those
</P>
<P>
   hills regularly, where deer crossing highways at night is a real
safety
</P>
<P>
   problem.
</P>
<P>
   We didn't see any deer during our test drive, but the system did
show us
</P>
<P>
   some people crossing the road ahead of our headlight beams,
giving us
</P>
<P>
   plenty of time to slow down.
</P>
<P>
   The navigation system is in addition to the DeVille's built-in
GM OnStar
</P>
<P>
   system, which connects the driver to a live operator anytime, by
pushing a
</P>
<P>
   button, to get real-time directions or help.
</P>
<P>
   Using the car's built-in GPS system, OnStar tells the telephone
operator
</P>
<P>
   exactly where the car is, and the operator can give the driver
directions
</P>
<P>
   to any destination, help out with hotel or dining reservations,
or even
</P>
<P>
   summon emergency help.
</P>
<P>
   But if the driver wants to navigate on his or her own, the
navigation
</P>
<P>
   system will lead the car to the destination that the driver
programs into
</P>
<P>
   it, and a colorful moving map on the dash shows the driver
exactly where
</P>
<P>
   the car is at all times.
</P>
<P>
   Another high-tech component is the DeVille's ``Ultrasonic Rear
Parking
</P>
<P>
   Assist,'' part of an $895 safety/security package that also
includes the
</P>
<P>
   Stabilitrak automatic stability system and a built-in
garage-door opener.
</P>
<P>
   The parking-assist system uses ultrasonic beams to ``look''
behind the
</P>
<P>
   vehicle while it is backing, and to alert the driver with a
series of
</P>
<P>
   rapidly increasing beeps as the vehicle nears an obstacle.
</P>
<P>
   Front and side air bags are standard for front-seat passengers,
while
</P>
<P>
   our test car came with the optional side air bags for the rear
outboard
</P>
<P>
   passengers ($295).
</P>
<P>
   Other standard equipment on our DHS (the midlevel model)
included
</P>
<P>
   Magnasteer power rack-and-pinion steering, electronic level
control,
</P>
<P>
   four-wheel antilock disc brakes, all-speed traction control,
16-inch
</P>
<P>
   chrome wheels, audible theft-deterrent system, rain-sensing
windshield
</P>
<P>
   wipers, keyless entry, power and heated outside mirrors, power
</P>
<P>
   windows/seats/door locks, wood trim and steering wheel, leather
seats,
</P>
<P>
   power tilt and telescopic steering column, electronic compass in
the
</P>
<P>
   rearview mirror, Bose AM/FM/cassette/compact-disc sound system
with eight
</P>
<P>
   speakers, memory function for all personal settings, heated
seats, power
</P>
<P>
   rear sunshade and manual side-window rear sunshades, and daytime
running
</P>
<P>
   lights.
</P>
<P>
   Options on our car, besides the night vision, navigation system,
</P>
<P>
   safety/security package and rear-seat side air bags, included a
six-disc,
</P>
<P>
   glove-box-mounted CD changer ($595); and white-diamond exterior
paint
</P>
<P>
   ($650).
</P>
<P>
   Total sticker was $52,740, including transportation.
</P>
<P>
   EPA fuel economy ratings are 17 miles per gallon in the city and
an
</P>
<P>
   impressive 28 mpg on the highway. The tank holds 18.5 gallons of
gasoline,
</P>
<P>
   and unleaded regular is recommended. That's a departure from
most luxury
</P>
<P>
   cars, whose owner's manuals usually ask for premium fuel.
</P>
<P>
   G. Chambers Williams III, (210) 250-3236;
chambers &LR; express-news.net.
</P>
</TEXT>
