<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000731.0166 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-31 14:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8325 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k BC-LEVENDOSKY-COLUMN-NYT     07-31 1078
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEVENDOSKY-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BABBITT'S VISION WOULD PRESERVE LARGE LANDSCAPES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 (EDITOR'S NOTE: Charles Levendosky, editorial page editor of the
Casper (Wyo.) Star-Tribune, has written about public lands issues
for over a decade and is respected for his insight into these
issues. His e-mail address is levendos(at)trib.com.)  
 By CHARLES LEVENDOSKY   
 c.2000 Casper (Wyo.) Star-Tribune   
<TEXT>
<P>
   There's a move afoot to name a new national monument. Secretary
of the Interior Bruce Babbitt returned to northern Arizona last
week to discuss the future of the Paria (``Pa-ree-ah'') Plateau,
nearly 300,000 acres of federal wilderness bordering the Colorado
River as it flows south out of Glen Canyon Dam.
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks ago, Babbitt led a hike 1,500 feet up Spencer Trail so
participants could view the Vermilion Cliffs which make up the
Paria Plateau.
</P>
<P>
   It seems clear that Babbitt wants to preserve this area of his
home state, and national monument status may be the only way for it
to happen.
</P>
<P>
   We can expect Babbitt to make a series of new national monument
recommendations to President Clinton soon _ probably after the
Republican National Convention. Paria Plateau will certainly be
among the areas recommended.
</P>
<P>
   Something special is happening with the more than 3.8 million
acres of public lands that have already been granted national
monument status by Clinton _ a vision _ Babbitt's vision for
preserving large tracts of landscape for the future and the
enjoyment of the American people.
</P>
<P>
   Beginning with the Grand Staircase Escalante National Monument,
the more than 3.3 million acres of public land administered by the
Bureau of Land Management that have been set aside as national
monuments by this administration will continue to be under BLM
control. In the past, most of the national monuments were put under
the management of the National Park Service.
</P>
<P>
   The BLM administers millions more acres of public land than any
other federal lands agency. Babbitt wants to erase the BLM's image
as the ``bureau of livestock and mining'' and give the agency a
sense of pride in managing prime landscapes and ecosystems as
national monuments.
</P>
<P>
   This represents a change in direction for the BLM, but deeper
still, it represents a radical change in perception of what should
be set aside as national monuments.
</P>
<P>
   In a speech Babbitt gave at the University of Denver Law School
on Feb. 17, he outlined a plan for the creation of ``landscape
monuments.'' He said the original ``postage stamp'' monuments to
preserve archeological ruins were a product of a vision from the
past.
</P>
<P>
   ``Doesn't it make sense in light of a subsequent 100 years of
understanding to say that we have room in the West to protect the
landscape, an _ if you will _ an anthropological ecosystem,''
Babbitt asked rhetorically. ''The real science on these landscapes
doesn't come out of digging out a room and extracting a few pots.
That was the 19th century _ and it was important. The real
discoveries of today come from asking the deeper question of `How
did communities manage to live in spiritual and physical
equilibrium with the landscape?' ... We can do better than to
protect five or six Indian ruins out on that land and say that
there is room in this culture for a quarter-million acres from
which we honor the past and, more importantly, learn, and take
inspiration from the past.''
</P>
<P>
   The newly established Aqua Fria National Monument, less than an
hour's drive from Phoenix, is a 71,100-acre landscape monument. It
preserves ancient ruins, at least 450 prehistoric sites,
petroglyphs and prehistoric agricultural features like terracing.
</P>
<P>
   Aqua Fria National Monument is, for the mobile public of
Phoenix, a landscape preserve not far from home that can be
appreciated after a comparatively short drive. It's the city park
concept made grander with grandeur -- large vistas found outside of
cities but serving them and states and the people of the entire
nation.
</P>
<P>
   The Paria Plateau, if it becomes a national monument, will be a
landscape monument greater than itself. It borders the Kaibab
National Forest and the Paria Canyon Vermilion Cliffs Wilderness
Area in Arizona and the Grand Staircase Escalante National Monument
in Utah. A Paria Plateau National Monument could interlock those
vast vistas and scenic landscapes in perpetuity _ for all of us and
the generations we leave behind.
</P>
<P>
   In March, Babbitt asked the BLM to create a system to make
policy and provide guidance for the management of the national
monuments, national conservation areas, and other areas designated
for important scientific and ecological characteristics. BLM
Director Tom Fry announced the creation of the National Landscape
Conservation System in mid-June. Larry Finfer, the BLM's assistant
director for communications was named interim director.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview July 28, Finfer said about landscape monuments,
``These places are going to be different from (national) parks.
They're not going to be necessarily classic tourist destination
sites. They're not going to have a lot of facilities in them. The
touch is going to be light in them. The facilities will be located
primarily in the surrounding communities. That's the basics of what
was done at the Grand Staircase, for example. They're going to be
different from parks in that way.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're going to be different also in the sense of some of
what are considered traditional uses like hunting, fishing,
grazing, and even in a case or two, oil and gas might be continued
out there. There's a sort of niche the BLM can fill in preserving
open spaces that's not quite the same as parks. Keeping them
remote, but allowing for some continuation of traditional uses ...
where those uses are compatible with the purpose for which the area
was established. In just about all cases, there will be no new
mineral location, no new leasing and regulation of off-highway
vehicles -- but no outright ban.''
</P>
<P>
   Finfer emphasized that his office would only provide guidance
and policy, that the management of any site would be left to those
on site.
</P>
<P>
   Babbitt said in his February speech, ``right now on this
landscape it's pretty much either/or.'' He is right. Either we set
aside some of these vast unique vistas and landscapes to preserve
them in their uniqueness, or the new urban sprawl across the West
will eat them away. Now is the time _ before it is too late.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
