Columnist Karen Lincoln Michel argues that the recent decision by
the National Academy of Recording Arts and Sciences to add a Native
American category to the Grammy Awards lineup next year may be well
intended but falls short. The Academy created only one category:
best Native American Music Album. She writes: ``That's similar to
having a single award for Latin music ... It's going to be
extremely difficult to find the best Native American recording when
you consider the category also includes contemporary native music,
a growing genre in recent years.'' (slugged:
BC-NATIVE-MUSIC-GRABS-GRAMMY-NEW-AMERICA-NYTSF)
</P>
<P>
   BEYOND TICKLING THE IVORIES _ This excerpt from Emerge magazine
by contributing columnist Calvin Wilson looks at two of today's
American jazz greats, pianists Matthew Shipp and Andrew Hill. These
two experimental jazz artists have roots in the musical past.
Indeed, Shipp cites Hill, 62, as one of his idols. Wilson examines
the predecessors who inspired these two contemporary artists and
how they continue to set standards of their own. (slugged:
BC-REIGNING-JAZZ-PIANO-MEN-NEW-AMERICA-NYTSF)
</P>
<P>
   SOFTENING THE GOP _ The GOP is making headway with Latino voters
these days, writes columnist James Garcia. But more than a few
Latino politicos will tell you this is inherently bad. If you are a
``Latino Republican,'' they say, you are a ``vendido,'' a sellout.
Maybe, maybe not. Garcia believes that if there is such a thing as
a kinder, gentler ``21st Century Republican Party,'' then it's
epitomized by its newest recruits _ Latinos. If Latinos can
moderate the Republican Party _ humanize it, make it truly more
compassionate than it has been _ then the Latino community, and the
nation as a whole, will be better off. (slugged:
BC-IMPACT-OF-LATINO-VOTE-NEW-AMERICA-NYTSF)
</P>
<P>
   COME TOGETHER _ In this commentary from a recent issue of KoreAm
Journal, the writer, a Korean-American who wishes to remain
anonymous, offers his opinion on the historical meeting between
President Dae Jung Kim of South Korea and Chairman Jong II Kim of
North Korea. ``Both sides have their own ideas of how North and
South should become one,'' he writes. ``The agreement essentially
states that both sides agree to disagree on that issue. It will be
interesting to see how that works out.'' He closes his article by
stating that although his Korean side yearns for the two Koreas to
become one, the American in him is skeptical of the show of
friendship and doubtful of the ``Stalinist state's intentions.''
(slugged: BC-REFLECTIONS-ON-KOREAN-SUMMIT-NEW-AMERICA-NYTSF)
</P>
<P>
   -0-
</P>
