<HEADER>
A8338 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r p BC-CVN-TEXASDELEGATES-TE     07-31 0810
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CVN-TEXASDELEGATES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEXAS DELEGATION MEMBERS TO BACK TICKET DESPITE DISAGREEMENTS ON
ISSUES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KAREN BROOKS 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ Bill Eastland stepped through his first political
loophole at 16 while growing up in the affluent Highland Park
neighborhood of Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   It was summer 1964, and Eastland and some buddies decided to
stage a carwash to raise money for Barry Goldwater's Republican
presidential bid. But red tape threatened when the ``local
constabulary'' wouldn't let them carry political signs on a busy
corner.
</P>
<P>
   That's where politics came in.
</P>
<P>
   The mother of one of the boys was an attorney who persuaded City
Hall that it was legal for them to carry signs if they were
walking. The event went on, they raised $400, and the teen-age
Eastland stumped for a GOP icon.
</P>
<P>
   This week marks another milestone for Eastland. After a decade
of trying, the Arlington, Texas, accountant is at the Republican
National Convention in Philadelphia as one of 248 delegates and
alternates representing Texas and officially nominating Gov. George
W. Bush for president.
</P>
<P>
   ``Being elected a delegate or alternate to the national
convention is basically an honor that is bestowed on people for
party service,'' said Eastland, 52, who has worked as a volunteer
at two national conventions.
</P>
<P>
   Delegates vote on the party platform and party rules and hear
speeches from elected officials and internationally known
activists. Alternates step in when their assigned delegate can't be
there for an important vote.
</P>
<P>
   The Tarrant County delegation includes the two top officials of
the Texas Christian Coalition, the leader of the Eagle Forum, two
preachers and several ardent anti-abortion activists. Several have
run unsuccessful campaigns for elected office, and many have worked
behind the scenes for Bush since he was running for governor.
</P>
<P>
   Some in the delegation don't consider themselves part of the
conservative Christian segment of the party, although they say that
they will put aside their differences for the benefit of party
unity.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not my way or the highway,'' said Don Diamond, 55, of
Cleburne, a Johnson County alternate from a district in which the
three delegates are a preacher, an anti-abortion activist and a
lifetime member of Daughters of the American Revolution.
</P>
<P>
   Diamond considers himself socially conservative and opposes
abortion. But in contrast to his party platform's call for an
absolute ban on abortion, Diamond believes that, if a mother's life
is in danger, she and her doctor should be allowed to decide if an
abortion is needed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want George W. Bush to succeed, and whatever disagreements I
have should not stand in the way,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   All Republican statewide officeholders and several legislators
are delegates. Many of the other delegates and alternates are
Christian conservative activists, including state GOP
second-in-command David Barton of Annetta, who wrote a book called
``The Myth of Separation'' and owns a faith-based construction
company called Wallbuilders.
</P>
<P>
   Others include Kelly Shackleford, head of the conservative Free
Market Institute in Dallas, and Jeff Fisher, a former Christian
Coalition official.
</P>
<P>
   Party leaders characterize the state delegation as ``mainstream
conservative,'' led by Sens. Phil Gramm and Kay Bailey Hutchison,
Lt. Gov. Rick Perry, Attorney General John Cornyn and State
Comptroller Carol Keeton Rylander.
</P>
<P>
   Although the abortion debate gets most of the media attention,
some delegates stressed that they're more interested in such issues
as education, health care, taxes and government regulation.
</P>
<P>
   Delegate Eleanor Hutcheson, 74, of Fort Worth is opposed to
abortion. But her true passion lies in education issues, and, as a
member of the Daughters of the American Revolution, she has spent
most of the past decade reviewing textbooks for the state. She ran
for the state Board of Education but lost.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Fisher and other local Christian conservatives agree that
disagreements on how to prioritize issues shouldn't split the
party.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd love to see a constitutional amendment (banning abortion),
but it's not all or nothing,'' said Fisher, a Bedford pastor and
former Christian Coalition officer. ``You've got to look at what
you can accomplish.''
</P>
<P>
   The Christian conservatives believed that they accomplished
their main goal going into the convention when Bush announced the
conservative, anti-abortion Dick Cheney as his running mate.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he listened,'' said Michele Quinones, a member of the
State Republican Executive Committee. Christian conservatives had
threatened an uprising unless Bush selected a staunch social
conservative.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
