<HEADER>
A8341 &Cx1f; tab-z
r l BC-RABBI-SPORTS-SPIRITUA     07-31 0898
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RABBI-SPORTS-SPIRITUALITY-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHY WE SHOULD PRAY BEFORE -- AND AFTER -- GAMES 
</HEADLINE>
   (Commentary)  
 &HT;    
 &HT;    (To purchase this ``separate buy'' article from the New York
Times Syndicate please contact syndicate sales representative DEBRA
WEYDERT at 732-390-4480)
 &HT;    
 By RABBI ELI HECHT  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    
 &HT;    
 &HT;    As a young student in a cheder _ private Jewish school _ I was
discouraged from playing sports. Our teachers, called rebbes, were
from the old country. They displayed an aversion to any kind of
organized sport.
 &HT;    For many of them, sports meant body-worship and that was a big
no-no. For others, sports meant pitting the weak against the
stronger, teaching that the deciding factor in life is that might
counts and what was right makes no difference.
 &HT;    The rebbes said, ``Sports is not kosher and not productive.
Sports bring out the worst in people. You can get hurt, or worse,
pick up violent tendencies.''
 &HT;    My friends from European families told me that only the
irreligious free-thinkers sent their children to sports. I felt
this was not a valid explanation _ a lot of American kids who went
to the gym or to soccer games were not irreligious. Thinking that
sports could be the precursor of becoming faithless was crazy.
 &HT;    Being one of the only American-born students among a class of
European children, I knew that here in America sports were the in
thing: ``A healthy body in a healthy mind.'' I knew of some great
Jews in sports like baseball's Hank Greenberg and Sandy Koufax.
 &HT;    Regardless of our teachers' feelings, we would organize games of
soccer and stickball. During our class recess we would enjoy fierce
competitive games. I would return to class all sweaty and excited.
I wondered what in the world could be wrong with sports?
 &HT;    In high school I had a more enlightened rebbe who saw sports as
a way to unify people of all colors and creeds. He taught us that
in a game everybody learns to play together, that no one can go off
and do whatever they want. Each player has a responsibility to each
other. The team spirit in playing together is what makes the
winning.
 &HT;    So sports become kosher and our school had a basketball team.
 &HT;    Later on I attended rabbinical seminary. I asked my teacher, an
old rabbi in his 80s, about sports. He said sports are good for
America. In the old country, he said, people had nothing to do on
weekends for entertainment. They would drink and plan pogroms. Here
in America the people go to games and vent all their energy with
something safe and sound.
 &HT;    Thinking about sports I become aware of an interesting anomaly.
It's the no-contact games that are often followed by violence while
the more punishing sports have little or no violence.
 &HT;    The welterweight title fight in Los Angeles between Oscar De La
Hoya and Shane Mosely resulted in a very close split decision. De
La Hoya and his fans were not happy with the decision, but the
spectators went home peacefully.
 &HT;    On the other hand, the Los Angeles Lakers' championship game
produced violent celebrations, causing havoc and riotous
conditions. Police cars were destroyed and lives were threatened.
 &HT;    Why would a seemingly innocent no-contact game cause so much
havoc while boxing, the killing-machine game, has no such
aftermath?
 &HT;    I think we may have lost the spiritual message of the games. We
have lost contact with our souls.
 &HT;    The late Lubavitcher Rebbe, Rabbi Menachem Mendel Schneerson,
world leader of Hassidic Jewry, once commented on the game of
soccer:
 &HT;    ``When a child has studied Torah and he wants to go out and play
ball, he should not be criticized. Rather, we must show him how he
can play ball ``for the sake of Heaven.'' Recreation contributes to
his health, which will, in turn, give him a greater capacity to
learn Bible.
 &HT;    The purpose of a Jewish child's life is to learn Torah and
fulfill mitzvahs. Playing ball can contribute toward this goal. If
he wins he thanks God for his victory.
 &HT;    Phil Jackson, coach of the Lakers, is the son of a
fundamentalist Christian preacher. Jackson is reported to believe
in the path of spirituality. It has been said he uses Zen
meditation and incorporates spirituality into his coaching.
Buddhism, basketball and spirituality all go hand-in-hand in
helping his team win.
 &HT;    The recent ruling by the Supreme Court forbidding students to
offer a prayer before a game is wrong. The ruling reinforces the
message that sports encourage players and spectators to worship the
body and not the spirit.
 &HT;    I believe it would do America well not only to have a prayer
before the game but a prayer after the game, thanking God for
giving the human race the capability to compete in a harmonious
fashion.
 &HT;    The spirit of our competition should move the spectators toward
acknowledging that sports can bring us all together for a good
time. If we had prayed after the Laker game there would have been
no losers, only winners.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    -----
 &HT;    c.2000 Rabbi Eli Hecht
<TEXT>
<P>
   (Rabbi Eli Hecht is vice president of the Rabbinical Alliance of
America and past president of the Rabbinical Council of California.
He is the director of Chabad of South Bay in Lomita, Calif. and
writes a monthly Op-Ed column for the Long Beach Press-Telegeam.)
</P>
</TEXT>
