<DOCNO> NYT20000731.0174 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-31 14:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8342 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r p BC-GOP-SPEAKERS-HNS &LR;      07-31 0822
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOP-SPEAKERS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     CONVENTION TRIES TO PUT NEW FACE ON GOP 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By ZACHARY COILE  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA - Republicans control the U.S. Senate and the House
of Representatives, but TV viewers wouldn't know it from watching
the party's national convention this week.
</P>
<P>
   Only a handful of Republican members of Congress have been asked
to speak at the weeklong event. And although Republicans control 37
of the nation's governorships, only two GOP governors _ besides
presumptive nominee Texas Gov. George W. Bush _ will address the
convention.
</P>
<P>
   Instead the Bush campaign has tapped teachers, single moms,
farmers, community leaders and small businesspeople to parade
before the delegates and the TV cameras.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bush is trying to reinforce the image that this is not your
father's Republican Party,'' said Jack Pitney, a political
scientist at Claremont McKenna College. ``He is hoping when people
channel-surf on their TVs and happen to come across the Republican
convention, they will see someone who looks a lot like
themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush campaign officials, who have been honing the speakers list
for months, also plan to put an unprecedented number of minority
speakers on the podium. Retired Gen. Colin Powell and former
Stanford provost Condoleezza Rice, both of whom are black, are
scheduled to give prime-time speeches this week. A little-known
Latino assemblyman from Los Angeles, Abel Maldonado, will deliver a
speech in Spanish.
</P>
<P>
   The choice of speakers shows Bush understands two key political
facts: First, the public has grown increasingly cynical and weary
of politicians, particularly Washington politicians. And second, in
order to win in November, he's going to have to do better than past
Republican nominees among women, independents and minority voters.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a new kind of Republican,'' explained Gerald Parsky,
chairman of the California Bush campaign, using a line that has
become a steady refrain from Bush allies and spokespeople.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a new kind of Republican politics,'' Parsky said. ``They
want to hear from citizens and people who represent interests that
traditionally have been left out of the Republican party.''
</P>
<P>
   But the speakers, particularly the choice of minorities,
contrast with the audience listening to them. An Associated Press
survey found 83 percent of the GOP convention delegates are white.
And the diversity of speakers, analysts say, isn't likely to help
the Republicans cut into the Democrats' overwhelming advantage with
voters who are minorities come November.
</P>
<P>
   This year's strategy is a departure from the 1996 GOP convention
in San Diego, where the podium was dominated by cabinet members,
diplomats and other inside-the-Beltway officials.
</P>
<P>
   A review of the speakers list for the 1996 convention showed
that of the 44 people who spoke, 26 were senators, U.S.
representatives or governors.
</P>
<P>
   On this year's convention agenda, of the 52 scheduled speakers,
only 10 are top elected officials _ if you include Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Elected officials have been replaced by people like Kim Jennings
of Rodgers, Ark., a single mother, and Gayle White, a
fifth-generation farmer from Oklahoma, who will discuss tax policy
with a twist.
</P>
<P>
   Jennings will talk on Wednesday about the challenges of working
while going to school and the tax bite she suffered. And White will
spotlight how the estate tax hurts family farmers.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for House Speaker Dennis Hastert said the speaker
understood Bush's desire to show a different face to the party this
election year.
</P>
<P>
   ``We feel very comfortable with the Bush campaign's desire to
highlight real Americans, and to keep the message focused on what
Gov. Bush and Republicans want to do for this country,`` the
speaker's spokesman, John McGovern, said.
</P>
<P>
   Barbara O'Connor, a communications professor at Cal State
Sacramento, called Bush's effort part of a ``heartland strategy``
to portray himself as a leader from outside Washington who
understands voters' daily problems. It's similar to the strategy
Bill Clinton used when he, as the governor of Arkansas, ran for
president in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   O'Connor suspects the ultimate aim may be to paint Democratic
Vice President Al Gore as a creature of Washington _ son of a
senator, 16-year member of Congress and vice president for eight
years _ who is out of touch with the average American.
</P>
<P>
   The strategy, however, could backfire on Bush. He is the son of
a president and his ties to Washington are shown by his kitchen
cabinet of former aides to President George Bush and his choice of
Dick Cheney, his father's Defense secretary, as the vice
presidential nominee.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cheney is an inside-the-Beltway person, and most of (Bush's)
advisors have had extensive Washington experience,'' O'Connor said.
``The message of the convention is different from the reality.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
