<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000731.0175 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-31 14:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8343 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r k BC-MORSE-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      07-31 0870
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MORSE-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     FANGS FOR THE MEMORIES 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By ROB MORSE  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Everyone has heard stories about William
Randolph Hearst. They've heard about this ``miserable little
sheet'' his father gave him. WRH said it lovingly.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone has heard about the little war in Cuba and the colorful
brand of journalism he helped invent _ I won't mention the specific
color.
</P>
<P>
   By now, most people probably have heard The San Francisco
Examiner is no longer a Hearst paper. It's now a Fang paper, and
the Chronicle is a Hearst paper.
</P>
<P>
   We've already started to talk about the old Examiner with
nostalgia even though we'll be here another four months putting it
out the same as usual. Media stories about the Chronicle purchase
can't call this paper ``failing'' anymore. ``Malodorous'' and
``horse-trading'' may stick around for awhile.
</P>
<P>
   It was with a sense of relief that I finally read a positive
description of The Examiner. An Associated Press article on Friday
described this newspaper as ``the storied afternoon daily.''
</P>
<P>
   There's a proud tradition of stories here, ones about Hunter
Thompson when he was an Examiner columnist, ones about the
political consultant who somehow managed to get his ankle broken
during a meeting in the editorial board room, and ones about our
executive editor who married the movie star.
</P>
<P>
   Stories are what newspapers are all about, not just the stories
in the paper, but ones about the paper. But they aren't the whole
story. People are. This place is filled with amazing people.
</P>
<P>
   Here's how amazing the folks at The Examiner are: Some are still
here. And eager young staffers are still signing up.
</P>
<P>
   These people have been doing their jobs as well as ever, maybe
better, while they've been sitting in limbo. Check out our coverage
of the Hearst-Chronicle deal for the last year.
</P>
<P>
   Willie Brown is still under an Examiner microscope. We still
cover the state Capitol like one of our own neighborhoods, a
particularly freaky one. The Examiner sports section is still the
best in the Bay Area. The Examiner is still watch-dogging the
Police Department, the Planning Department, developers and minority
contracting.
</P>
<P>
   It's only one columnist who may have been slacking off a bit,
getting a lot of those ``taking the day off'' squibs where his
column should appear.
</P>
<P>
   The days have been going by very slowly. It's almost a year
since the Hearst Corp. announced it was buying the Chronicle. It's
been a year in slow-cooking hell.
</P>
<P>
   In Friday's paper, the timeline of the Examiner-Chronicle deal
was just as long as the timelines of the histories of both papers.
That tells you all you need to know.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, many of our colleagues went to other publications,
dot-coms or rural hideouts far from a news rack.
</P>
<P>
   We've had so many goodbye cakes we're getting hyperactive from
all the sugar. Maybe that's what keeps us going, along with the
idea that the Bay Area could have a great newspaper at the end of
all this.
</P>
<P>
   We decided to ride this sled named Rosebud as far as it goes.
We're here out of loyalty to this small band of quirky individuals
and this storied afternoon daily. We just had no idea how long the
sled ride would be.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody wants to hear about the suffering of journalists, any
more than they want to hear about lawyers' struggles with their
consciences or Bill Gates' troubles with contractors working on his
mansion.
</P>
<P>
   We're not so bad off. The Examiner is a wonderful dysfunctional
family, and when the going gets dysfunctional, we're functional.
</P>
<P>
   If this has been water torture, then it's Evian, or maybe scotch
and water for a lot of us. We can still make jokes about this
situation.
</P>
<P>
   One friend said the last year at The Examiner has felt like a
Band-Aid being pulled off very slowly, one hair at a time.
</P>
<P>
   Another friend said it's like stepping into dog poop and
thinking you got it off, but it's always there.
</P>
<P>
   To me, a recent frequent flier, it's like one of those flights
where you get stuck on the runway, unable to take off or go back to
the terminal.
</P>
<P>
   Now, at least, we're moving.
</P>
<P>
   Clint Reilly lost his lawsuit, and it looks like he won't sue
again, at least not for a while.
</P>
<P>
   Thank you very much, Clint, and may you be elected
mayor-for-life of a small island in the South China Sea.
</P>
<P>
   Here's how loyal Examiner staffers are to their paper.
</P>
<P>
   One of my best friends has been ill in the hospital and wasn't
in the office when the judge ruled that the Hearst Corp. could buy
the Chronicle. When I called him on Friday, he didn't want to talk
about his health. He wanted to talk about the health of The
Examiner.
</P>
<P>
   He's furious about the Fangs getting the archives of The
Examiner. He thought Clint Reilly had done everyone a favor by
throwing a spoke in the wheels of Hearst. He didn't want The
Examiner's name given away for (or with) a pot of gold.
</P>
<P>
   He didn't want The Examiner style to disappear. He was
passionate about it.
</P>
<P>
   That's the Examiner style. It won't die.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Rob Morse is a columnist for the San Francisco Examiner, P.O.
Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120.)
</P>
</TEXT>
