<HEADER>
A8346 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r k BC-SALTER-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      07-31 0986
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SALTER-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     CHOICE, NOT AN ECHO 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By STEPHANIE SALTER   
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA - If you don't count the fact that the platform
committee of their very own party has totally screwed and
humiliated them _ AGAIN _ this is a great year to be a pro-choice
Republican.
</P>
<P>
   That's what everybody kept saying during the jam-packed Planned
Parenthood reception Sunday night in the Grand Ballroom of the Park
Hyatt Hotel.
</P>
<P>
   Isn't this something? Can you believe it?
</P>
<P>
   Hundreds and hundreds of abortion-rights Republicans, all under
one roof! And most wearing big buttons that read ``Don't Squash
Freedom of Choice'' and showed an elephant with his foot about to
crash down on the Liberty Bell.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a great thrill to be around so many like-minded people,''
said the master of ceremonies, actress Dina Merrill. ``Especially
after the week we've had.''
</P>
<P>
   You can say that again.
</P>
<P>
   The GOP platform committee not only refused to alter one word of
its misogynistic abortion plank _ which vows to nullify Roe vs.
Wade with a constitutional amendment _ the majority added a special
little bonus for the procreation-obsessed Christian right:
</P>
<P>
   A pledge to withdraw all federal funding that provides public
school teenagers with information about contraception, and use the
money instead for abstinence-only education programs.
</P>
<P>
   Try as she might, the best thing that Planned Parenthood's
national president, Gloria Feldt, could say about the situation
was, ``By golly, you're gaining on them, and you have forced a
different kind of conversation this year.''
</P>
<P>
   As a pro-choice Catholic, I know what it's like to be affiliated
with a large group whose mostly male leadership refuses to trust
women with agency over their wombs. But at least I don't have to go
into a voting booth every four years and re-elect the pope to be
considered a loyal Catholic.
</P>
<P>
   How bad does it have to get before pro-choice Republicans do
something serious about this mess?
</P>
<P>
   Something like gather, hundreds strong, in a ballroom and give
their sexist party leaders a public ultimatum: Lose the abortion
plank or lose us to the Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   It's not as if they don't know what they're up against. Or can't
articulate their rage.
</P>
<P>
   Had it not been for all the chunky gold jewelry, Chanel pumps
and semi-successful face-lifts, one could have mistaken the Hyatt
crowd for a gathering of radical '60s feminists.
</P>
<P>
   Roselyn O'Connell, the first Republican woman to head the
National Women's Political Caucus, was truly eloquent in her
savagery.
</P>
<P>
   ``You are the people who represent the heart and the soul of the
Republican Party, not the anti-choice zealots who are holding this
party hostage!'' she told the audience.
</P>
<P>
   And yet, despite the hostage crisis, she said:
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe reason will prevail, and we will get that
anti-choice, anti-woman, antediluvian plank out of our platform!''
</P>
<P>
   And so they may.
</P>
<P>
   Just not for another four years.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, if their anti-choice boy Dubbya gets elected
along with his even anti-er-choice running mate Dick Cheney, the
United States of America can kiss safe and legal abortion goodbye.
</P>
<P>
   Is it really worth setting up that irreparable disaster to beat
Al Gore?
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Arlen Specter of Pennsylvania, the highest-ranking
Republican to address the Hyatt audience, may not have meant to,
but he solved the Zen koan that is pro-choice Republicanism in the
era of anti-choice zealot hostage takers. Speaking of what ``good
Republicans'' all the gathered folks were, he said:
</P>
<P>
   ``It may be that we're TOO good of Republicans _ to be as
passive and docile as we are.''
</P>
<P>
   Bingo, senator. Or, as we used to say in the radical '60s: If
you're not part of the solution, you're part of the problem.
</P>
<P>
   Despite all the fiery rhetoric and threats of retaliation in
2004, it appears that most pro-choice Republicans have not yet
tired of having their noses rubbed deeply enough in you-know-what.
</P>
<P>
   In this convention, like the one before it and the one before
that, the platform says the GOP is committed to making all abortion
illegal, even for pregnant women and teenagers who were raped or
the victims of incest. Even for women who are likely to die because
of their pregnancy.
</P>
<P>
   True, this time, during the platform crafting process, there
actually was a sufficient number of pro-choice delegates _ 27 out
of 107 _ who raised their hands in protest, thus qualifying the
group to lodge an official minority report against the abortion
plank.
</P>
<P>
   But, as Susan Cullman of the Republican Pro-Choice Coalition
told the Hyatt crowd:
</P>
<P>
   ``When it came time for the people who raised their hands to
sign their names, somehow the pen got lost.''
</P>
<P>
   Talk about profiles in courage. The minority report wouldn't
have changed much of anything except posterity. But, when it came
time to OWN their pro-choice position, too many platform delegates
wimped out.
</P>
<P>
   Of more than a dozen speakers at the Planned Parenthood
reception, Dr. Leroy Carhart probably received the loudest ovation.
A courageous Nebraska gynecologist, he recently helped persuade the
U.S. Supreme Court to reject a deceptively worded law that would
have banned all abortions in his state.
</P>
<P>
   A Republican, Carhart told the audience that legislators have
proposed an amendment to Nebraska's constitution that would force
him to LEAVE the state and would remove him from his position on
the medical staff at the University of Nebraska.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ladies and gentlemen,'' Carhart said of this year's GOP
abortion and family planning platform planks, ``this is scary.''
</P>
<P>
   Ladies and gentlemen, it is going to get worse.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Stephanie Salter is a columnist for the San Francisco Examiner,
P.O. Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120. Her electronic mail address
is salter(at)examiner.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
