r k BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-TEX     07-31 0737
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LET THE CHENEY-BASHERS HAVE THEIR FUN WHILE THEY CAN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BILL THOMPSON 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Democrats are having fun ripping Dick Cheney's congressional
voting record and painting the Republican
vice-presidential-nominee-to-be as some sort of snarling right-wing
ideologue. Good for them _ it's always nice to have a little fun
right before you get your clock cleaned.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, the current flurry of Cheney-bashing falls into
the category of instant gratification; it will have no long-term
impact on the outcome of the presidential election.
</P>
<P>
   For one thing, nobody chooses a presidential candidate to
support on the basis of that candidate's choice for a running mate.
For another, Cheney left Congress to become secretary of defense
back in 1989 _ which means that his legislative voting record as a
House member from Wyoming pretty much qualifies as ancient history
in today's blink-and-it's-forgotten world.
</P>
<P>
   Even many Democrats believe that votes cast by a politician in a
previous life on Capitol Hill are basically irrelevant. They are
obligated to believe that in order to rationalize the many votes
against gun control and abortion rights racked up in Congress by
their current presidential candidate, Al Gore.
</P>
<P>
   Gore says he's changed his views over the years. But he can't
change those votes. And Democrats say that's OK.
</P>
<P>
   Cheney can't change his votes, either, and in most cases he
probably wouldn't want to. He said the other day that there might
be a few positions that he would ``tweak'' if given another crack
at them today, but he was then and is now a proud conservative who
believes in conservative values and in conservative solutions to
society's problems.
</P>
<P>
   That's not OK, say liberal Democrats who insist on
characterizing any opposition to liberal political and social
doctrine as right-wing extremism. But in attempting to slap the
extremist label on Cheney, the Democrats and their liberal henchmen
in the media might be crashing into a brick wall.
</P>
<P>
   They can deride Cheney's votes in Congress till the cows come
home. They can misrepresent and even flat-out lie about positions
that Cheney took on certain issues till their lungs give out. But
they will never convince the public that Dick Cheney is an
extremist.
</P>
<P>
   And why not, you ask?
</P>
<P>
   Because Dick Cheney is not an extremist. Any reasonable person
can figure that out the moment he opens his mouth.
</P>
<P>
   Left-leaning media stars have been raking Cheney over the coals
for days on end, and yet Cheney has come across as a sensible and
moderate advocate of mainstream conservative ideals that achieved
widespread public acceptance during the 1990s, if not sooner.
</P>
<P>
   No amount of political propaganda can persuade a thinking voter
that a candidate is something that he is not. Dan Quayle's
detractors were able to discredit the former vice president as a
vapid nitwit for one reason and only one reason: Quayle was a vapid
nitwit.
</P>
<P>
   Calling Cheney a ``Jesse Helms Republican'' may seem like
brilliant strategy to the Democrats who disseminate anti-Cheney
propaganda on the Internet. But as the campaign progresses and the
American people become more familiar with Cheney, voters not only
will realize that such a description is inaccurate but will
seriously question the credibility of those who devised it.
</P>
<P>
   In the cutthroat game of negative politics, overreaching can be
dangerously counterproductive.
</P>
<P>
   So let the Democrats have their fun. Let them rant and rave
about votes cast by Cheney when he served in Congress during an
earlier millennium. Let them cluck over George W. Bush's choice of
a running mate as they try to convince the electorate that the
Republicans' soon-to-be presidential nominee made a mistake when he
selected Cheney.
</P>
<P>
   Come to think of it, the fun might be over as we speak. A
presidential preference poll conducted shortly after the
Bush-Cheney ticket made its public debut last week gave Bush a
double-digit lead over Gore among likely voters.
</P>
<P>
   The election is more than three months away. But could it be
that the post-fun clock-cleaning has begun?
</P>
<P>
   (Bill Thompson is a columnist for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
You can reach him at (817) 390-7787 or
billthompson(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
