r p BC-GOP-INTERNET-HNS &LR;      07-31 0798
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOP-INTERNET-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     'TALK SHOW ROW' BEING SQUEEZED OUT BY `INTERNET ALLEY' 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By MATT TAYLOR  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Political junkies may need to put down their
remotes and pick up their mice for comprehensive coverage of the
Republican Convention in Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   The Internet has exploded since the last presidential election
in 1996, when only about a dozen dot-com news organizations covered
the GOP convention in San Diego. This year, the Republicans expect
more than 100 Web-based outlets to cover the convention, with
countless other news organizations also funneling coverage to their
own Web sites.
</P>
<P>
   ``This will be the most accessible convention in history,''
convention press secretary Tim Fitzpatrick said. ```Internet Alley'
was an afterthought four years ago, but now it has overtaken `Talk
Show Row,' which provided broadcasters easy access to
information.''
</P>
<P>
   Sagging ratings prompted TV networks to drop gavel-to-gavel
coverage of the major conventions this year. Web sites like
PseudoPolitics.com, Speakout.com, Policast.com and even
ComedyCentral.com are seizing on the chance to redefine the way
conventions are covered.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will provide a unique interactive experience,'' said
PseudoPolitics.com's executive producer and managing editor Sam
Hollander. His site will offer several 360-degree live Web cams
that can be operated by viewers, audio feeds from convention
speakers and commentators, plus chat rooms for viewers to discuss
the goings-on in real time.
</P>
<P>
   ``The public usually has a director telling them what to watch
and there has been no ability to participate,'' Hollander said.
``We are allowing you to choose what you listen to and how you
interact _ the control is in your hands.''
</P>
<P>
   The issues cable channel Comedy Central usually cover might be
mainstream, but its take on them isn't.
</P>
<P>
   ```Indecision 2000' will be our first foray into the convention
with a Web site,'' Comedy Central spokesman Steve Albani said. ``We
will be producing original content specifically for the Web _
serious coverage of the campaign with a comedy twist.``
</P>
<P>
   Among those adding to the twist supplied by The Daily Show will
be political correspondent Robert Reich and Bob Dole, who will both
provide analysis throughout the convention.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now Bob Dole is a serious guy,'' Albani said, ``but he has a
sense of humor.''
</P>
<P>
   Another site, Speakout.com, targets the activist community with
polls, petitions and direct e-mail to politicians.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will take two sides and background information, frame it,
and then you can take action,'' said Speakout.com Vice President
Chris Vestal. ``We are small and we are trying to do something
different.''
</P>
<P>
   MSNBC is anything but small, but is instead an example of how
much online convention coverage has changed since 1996.
</P>
<P>
   ``The last convention came only a matter of weeks after we
launched,'' MSNBC Executive Editor Michael Silberman said. ``We
were still just trying to figure out how to run the site.''
</P>
<P>
   Silberman said this year's MSNBC coverage will feature Web-only
coverage from a team of reporters, other stories from the
Washington Post and Newsweek, and video from NBC News.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't do any streaming (audio) at the 1996 convention, but
now the Web has become another TV channel,'' Silberman said. ``This
is still a major news event and it's important for any news
organizations to show their smarts for television reporting,
producing and ability to break news.''
</P>
<P>
   Not only is convention coverage shifting toward the Web, the
tools available to media for covering the convention are advancing
as well.
</P>
<P>
   The GOP has built an on-site Intranet to provide facts,
statistics and transcripts to all journalists, and has created a
communications infrastructure that includes 8,000 phone lines,
2,000 ISDN lines, 500 DSL lines and 6,600 miles of fiber optic
cable.
</P>
<P>
   While online coverage is surging, some observers wonder if
increased coverage on the Internet can offset waning public
interest in political conventions.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Patterson, of Harvard's VanishingVoter.org, said gaining a
political audience as a consequence of the Internet was missing the
point.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have monitored Web use, and it tends to complement other
media,'' said Patterson. ``It tends not to stand alone, so the
audience will be tiny.''
</P>
<P>
   Patterson also questioned whether the Web is ready to change the
way the public views conventions.
</P>
<P>
   ``This will not be the wired convention. Not this time,'' said
Patterson. ``The Internet will be a substantial medium once all the
pieces are in place, but television is still the easier way to view
the convention - that audience will be bigger.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
