<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-31 14:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8379 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-GOP-RDP-ART-630&AMP;ADD-N     07-31 0837
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOP-RDP-ART-630&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REPUBLICAN CONVENTION OPENS IN PHILADELPHIA 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: This early version will be subbed with a story by Richard L.
Berke.) 
(ART ADV: Photos are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
 By JULIAN E. BARNES   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ Republicans opened their convention Monday,
beginning what party leaders hope will be a highly scripted
four-day celebration for their presidential nominee, Gov. George W.
Bush.
</P>
<P>
   The first real business of the convention came Monday afternoon
when the delegates approved by voice vote a platform that reaffirms
the party's staunch position opposing abortion while adopting
Bush's ``compassionate conservative'' positions on issues like
education and immigration.
</P>
<P>
   Bush is in Ohio Monday on a cross-country bus tour that is
wending its way toward Philadelphia and is expected to arrive here
on Wednesday morning. In advance of his arrival, his running mate,
former Defense Secretary Dick Cheney, and other political
surrogates have been in Philadelphia since the weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Cheney arrived here Sunday and on Monday morning met with
delegates outside the convention hall. He continued to defend his
conservative voting record as a member of the House of
Representatives from 1979 to 1989 and to reconcile that record with
Bush's contention that the ticket represents a new kind of
Republican.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the things I feel best about is my record voting for
smaller government, lower taxes, the policies of Ronald Reagan,''
Cheney said.
</P>
<P>
   Cheney met briefly with the delegation from Wyoming, his home
state. But he spent much of the day in his hotel room working on
the acceptance speech he is scheduled to deliver on Wednesday
night.
</P>
<P>
   Since Bush asked Cheney last week to run with him on the
Republican ticket, Democrats have criticized the Republican vice
presidential candidate's congressional voting record.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats have focused on Cheney's votes against a resolution
calling for the release from prison of Nelson Mandela, the former
president of South Africa, and for his vote against banning plastic
guns and so-called cop killer bullets.
</P>
<P>
   In interviews on Sunday, Cheney defended his vote against
Mandela's release but said he would now support the ban on the
bullets.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats began broadcasting advertisements in 17 states on
Sunday criticizing Cheney's votes against the school lunch program,
Head Start and the Clean Air Act.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Cheney's record sits well with the more than 2,000
delegates who have come to Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   According to a New York Times/CBS News poll of delegates, the
Republicans who have gathered here are far more conservative than
average Republican voters. The delegates by and large support large
tax cuts and school vouchers, and oppose gun control, curbs on
trade, environmental safeguards, abortion rights, prescription drug
subsidies for the elderly and campaign finance regulations.
</P>
<P>
   Karl Rove, the chief strategist for the Bush campaign, played
down the dichotomy between the delegates and the message from the
podium in an interview Monday on ``Political Points,'' a joint
production of ABCNEWS.com and The New York Times on the Web. Rove
said that the delegates would not have nominated Bush if they did
not agree with his message and agenda.
</P>
<P>
   ``The people in this convention hall represent the grass
roots,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush has sought to prevent any issues from flaring into
controversy at this convention by keeping tight-fisted control of
the proceedings, including requiring speakers to follow
pre-approved, scripted themes.
</P>
<P>
   Rove defended the scripted nature of the convention and said
voters are hungry for a positive message.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone wants a convention focused on a forward-looking
message,'' Rove said. ``Parties always strive to have a
noncontroversial, positive convention.''
</P>
<P>
   The speakers scheduled for Monday evening include retired Gen.
Colin L. Powell, who is slated to speak on community and volunteer
service.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   A top Republican official said that Powell had told Bush that he
intends to use the national platform to challenge the Republican
nominee to live up to the ideals Bush outlined in a July 10 speech
to the National Association for the Advancement of Colored People
in Baltimore.
</P>
<P>
   In that speech Bush said ``the party of Lincoln has not always
carried the mantle of Lincoln,'' and he pledged that ``strong civil
rights enforcement will be a cornerstone of my administration.''
</P>
<P>
   The scene outside the convention center was quiet as dozens of
secret service agents guided delegates and journalists through
metal detectors and x-ray machines. But in downtown Philadelphia
the police made the first convention-related arrests. Eight people
protesting a U.S. Army training school were arrested after they
blocked traffic during the morning rush hour.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
