<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-31 15:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8384 &Cx1f; tab-z
r l BC-MALE-PLANT-ALLERGY-NY     07-31 0840
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MALE-PLANT-ALLERGY-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FAVORING `MALE' PLANTS LEADS TO MORE WIND-BORNE ALLERGIES  
 &HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;    (The following ``separate buy'' article from HealthScout, a
leading online source of health and lifestyle news, is available
from the New York Times Syndicate. Please contact syndicate sales
representative DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480)
 &HT;    
 &HT;    
 BY ROBERT PREIDT  
 c.2000 HealthScout.com  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by The New York Times Syndicate) &LR;  &QL;
<P>
   If you suffer from allergies, you might want to follow your nose
outside to your yard to sniff out the cause of your suffering.
</P>
<P>
   By planting the wrong types of trees and other landscape plants,
we're drowning our cities and ourselves in pollen, says California
author Thomas Ogren in his new book, Allergy-Free Gardening: A
Revolutionary Approach to Landscape Planning.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's so obvious that you would have thought somebody would
have discovered this years ago,'' says Ogren, a former landscape
gardening instructor.
</P>
<P>
   The problem, in a nutshell, is that most cities and private
landscapers and nurseries favor a few dozen types of male,
wind-pollinated plants, instead of a blend of male and female
insect-pollinated trees and shrubs.
</P>
<P>
   That's because male trees don't produce so-called ``litter,''
which is old seeds, seed pods or fruit that mess up your yard. But
while male trees don't create that debris, they do pump out huge
volumes of pollen.
</P>
<P>
   Ogren says many people mistakenly believe pollen is dispersed
far and wide so there's nothing you can do to get away from it. But
after examining previous research and doing his own pollen
dispersal counts, Ogren says an allergenic, pollen-pumping tree in
your own backyard exposes you to 10 times the pollen than from a
tree down the street.
</P>
<P>
   ``Under the drip line of the tree, that's where most of the
pollen falls,'' he says. ``Even if you have a big, tall tree,
within 50 feet of the tree almost all of the pollen has fallen out
right in the immediate vicinity.''
</P>
<P>
   He compares it to second-hand smoke.
</P>
<P>
   ``If a guy is standing a block away and the wind is blowing
toward you, you're going to smell the cigarette smoke. But when
you've got that big male (tree) pumping out all this pollen and
that big tree is in your yard, it's just like being in an elevator
with a guy smoking a cigar,'' he explains.
</P>
<P>
   There's another problem with the predominance of male trees and
lack of females.
</P>
<P>
   ``The female trees are all electrically charged positive. The
airborne pollen is negative. The two are mutually attracted. So
when you have a large female tree in your urban landscape, that
acts as a magnet and draws the pollen to it. It doesn't just catch
it by accident,'' Ogren says.
</P>
<P>
   ``But when you take the landscape of today, there are few female
trees. So now you've got way more males and almost no females and
you_ve got all this pollen drifting around and there are no pollen
traps there for it.''
</P>
<P>
   Ogren developed a system called the Ogren Plant Allergy Scale
(OPALS), to grade more than 5,000 plants from 1 (best) to 10
(worst). The ratings are based on a number of factors including
whether the plant is insect or wind pollinated, whether it has
large, bright flowers or tiny, off-white or greenish flowers, and
the length of its pollen period.
</P>
<P>
   Current allergy scales are too simplistic because they give only
a high or low allergy ranking and tend to be too general when
comparing species, Ogren says. But, he adds, within the same
species of some trees, you can find different cultivars that rank
at the top and the bottom of the OPALS scale.
</P>
<P>
   Ogren says anyone involved in landscaping, from city arborists
to individual homeowners, needs to pay more attention to this
problem and use the OPALS system to clear the air. He's been
contacted by officials in a number of cities, including London,
about his scale.
</P>
<P>
   And the OPALS system is being used by the U.S. Department of
Agriculture Forest Service in a study to develop allergy rankings
of a number of American and Canadian cities.
</P>
<P>
   Many cities are now interested in rating plants based on pollen,
particularly in the Southwestern United States, says David Nowak,
project leader of the USDA Forest Service's Northeastern Research
Station in Syracuse, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   And even the desert doesn_t offer the escape it once did. Many
people move to the Southwest to escape allergies, but find they're
still having problems, he says. That's because many re-create
landscapes using allergy-causing plants from their previous homes.
</P>
<P>
   An allergy expert says Ogren's book could help turn the tide of
pollen.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a book that will probably find a place in schools that
teach landscaping and those people will begin to think about these
things,'' says David Stadtner, a retired allergist in Stockton,
Calif., who wrote the foreword to Ogren's book.
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   (The HealthScout.com Web site is at http://www.HealthScout.com.)
</P>
</TEXT>
