<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-31 15:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8390 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i BC-EGYPTAIR-FAMILIES-BOS     07-31 1202
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EGYPTAIR-FAMILIES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EGYPTAIR CRASH VICTIM'S FAMILIES CLING TO EACH OTHER 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (a and i coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TATSHA ROBERTSON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Tom Billings received his mother's orthotic shoe inserts in the
mail last month.
</P>
<P>
   He was thankful.
</P>
<P>
   In another time, he would have tossed them in the closet. But
nine months after his mother died in the crash of EgyptAir flight
990, which plunged into the sea off Nantucket, the items have made
the tragedy all too real.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a crash like this, your people disappear in thin air,''
said the Boston lawyer. ``I think all of us have been yearning for
a connection to the crash. This is the closest thing.''
</P>
<P>
   In homes across the United States, families of the 129 Americans
who perished among the 217 people on the flight have received
shredded pieces of luggage, coins, wallets, baby's shoes _
fragments of lives, smelling of the sea and jet fuel.
</P>
<P>
   Their loved ones' belongings come as the result of an
association formed by the families. The group, based in
Massachusetts, has successfully fought for the return of the
passengers' personal effects, the collection of DNA samples to help
identify bodies, and the unsealing of data from the federal
investigation of the crash.
</P>
<P>
   But as the group plans a memorial service in Newport, R.I. Oct.
31 and braces for the upcoming release of a government report on
the crash, they say one thing is missing: A sense of alliance with
the relatives of 62 victims in Egypt suffering the same losses.
</P>
<P>
   This was, after all, a tragedy that once united people of
different cultures in their suffering, as American Muslims rushed
to comfort family members of Egyptian victims and an Egyptian
airline sought to offer assistance to grieving Americans.
</P>
<P>
   But ongoing speculation over the cause of the crash seems to
have thwarted efforts to unite the victims' families. Some
Egyptians say the US investigators have rushed to blame an
allegedly suicidal Egyptian copilot. Some Americans say that
EgyptAir has treated victims from the two countries differently.
</P>
<P>
   ``To the extent that the families are divided they are not
effective, and could be played off against one another,'' said Jim
Brokaw, the association's president. ``They don't speak as one
voice, so they are not listened to.''
</P>
<P>
   Brokaw, of Chicago, and his siblings in Vermont lost their
stepmother and father in the crash.
</P>
<P>
   Samir El Shanawany, general manager of EgyptAir's North American
operations, denied that the airline is trying to keep the two
groups apart. El Shanawany said the company has created a toll-free
telephone number for the families and recently established a
confidential Web site so that all survivors, American or Egyptian,
could voice their concerns.
</P>
<P>
   But since the crash, Egyptian officials have vehemently rejected
findings from US investigators indicating that the Boeing 767 was
deliberately brought down by copilot Gameel el-Batouty. This month,
a book by an Egyptian journalist suggests the flight was either
sabotaged by a bomb or simply experienced mechanical failure.
</P>
<P>
   James Hall, chairman of the US National Transporation Safety
Board, told Congress that the movement of the plane prior to the
crash was ``consistent with a deliberate action on the part of one
of the crew members.''
</P>
<P>
   But Brokaw and other family members say the dispute over what
happened in the plane's final flight has left them unable to grieve
with the Egyptians. Family members said EgyptAir has consistently
refused to give them names or telephone numbers of Egyptian
families.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know those people have to be going through the same thing
we are,'' said Shari Gemmil of Washington, D.C., who lost her
mother and stepfather in the crash.
</P>
<P>
   Gemmil said the two Web sites that have been set up for the
families have allowed Americans and Canadians to share the healing
process, as well as their concerns.
</P>
<P>
   Slowly, said Brokaw, some of the Egyptian families are
discovering the site through word of mouth and beginning to contact
the Americans on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   They were apparently unaware that American families had already
banded together to express their concerns about the identification
of bodies, the pace of the investigation, and other matters.
Brokaw, as president, met with the ambassador of Egypt, as well as
EgyptAir officials, before noticing some progress.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, Egyptian officials have agreed to send four people
from each family to attend the memorial service in Newport. And, by
last winter, American families that had initially complained about
the pace of identifying remains were sending back DNA samples to
the Rhode Island's medical examiner's office. Egyptian families, by
contrast, have only recently begun to submit samples, said Brokaw.
</P>
<P>
   An EgyptAir official blamed the delay on the United States:
``Regretfully, the US government attempts to provide sampling kits
from the Egyptians failed because the laboratory contracted by the
US government went out of business.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, American family members say they are also concerned that
EgyptAir hasn't made advance payments in equal amounts to settle
claims by families, as did Swissair, American Airlines, and Alaska
Airlines after recent crashes. Instead, Brokaw said, the airline
has made advances only to those who can show proof of need.
</P>
<P>
   ``This unnecessarily complicates and prolongs the process of
getting financial help to those in need,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Brokaw and Billings said they believe Egyptian-born families now
in the United States are experiencing the most hardships. In one
case, said Brokaw, an Egyptian woman living in Arizona discovered
that she couldn't afford to stay in the United States after her
husband died in the crash. She had to return to Egypt. In another
case, an Egyptian-born man in California had to take in his
grandchildren after his daughter died.
</P>
<P>
   Chris Carlsen, an attorney handling EgyptAir's insurance
underwriters, said nearly all of the families in Egypt have settled
with the airline. EgyptAir officials said they have provided
advance payments of as much as $40,000 to some family members.
</P>
<P>
   Carlsen also said they are beginning to talk to American and
Canadian families, whose relatives made up most of the passengers
on the plane, about their claims.
</P>
<P>
   Gemmil said that as of now, she is going to put all her energy
in planning the memorial service. Others say they are hoping to
receive more information about their relatives' remains.
</P>
<P>
   So far, only a few remains have been found intact. Those remains
that cannot be identified will be placed in a cemetery in Newport.
</P>
<P>
   Brokaw's sister _ Fran Brokaw of Stafford, Vt., received her
father's battered suitcase in the mail.
</P>
<P>
   ``It looked just like a truck ran over it,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Brokaw said it was hard to look at the little brown carry-on
suitcase that her father took everywhere with him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Seeing it and holding it made it all real,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Some survivors have decided not to accept any personal effects
at all, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``But,'' she said, ``in some ways it's helpful to be able to
hold it and know it was with him.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-31-00 1511EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000731.0185 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-31 15:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8394 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e BC-RAP-MUSIC01-COX     07-31 2323
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAP-MUSIC01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    An open-minded critic finally listens to rap
 &HT;    By Charles Passey
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ There I am, doing my morning workout at
the gym, when I finally decide to pop the tape I've been avoiding
into my cassette player. It's Eminem's chart-topping The Marshall
Mathers LP, and if you've read any of the headlines concerning this
Michigan-born rapper, you'd understand my hesitation.
</P>
<P>
   Eminem specializes in a style of rap that's harder than
hard-core. Defiantly rude and crude, it's a celebration of man at
his most misogynistic and homophobic. The fact that the artist's
life closely resembles his music _ his wife recently attempted
suicide after attending one of his concerts _ only adds to the
legend.
</P>
<P>
   I'm fully prepared to hate the album _- and the first couple of
cuts confirm my expectations. Public Service Announcement, the
opening selection, offers a hint of what's to come, warning
Eminem's listeners that ``if you don't like (the album),'' you're
welcome to perform a certain sexual act on the artist. That's
followed by Kill You, in which Eminem (aka Slim Shady) articulates
his formula for mayhem: There are brutal descriptions of the artist
raping his own mother and committing other violent crimes against
women.
</P>
<P>
   But as the album plays on, something strange starts to happen: I
find myself drawn into Eminem's menacing universe. A song about a
psychotic fan (Stan) and an autobiographical rant (The Real Slim
Shady) resonate with a blend of crassness and verve. Leaving the
gym, I keep wanting to listen, so I switch to my car stereo. By the
time Eminem comes to the album's most harrowing cut, Kim, the
musical equivalent of watching a man go postal, I am sitting in my
driveway, unwilling to hit the stop button, and am left with two
unshakable conclusions.
</P>
<P>
   The man is brilliant. And I'm going to do everything in my power
to make sure my oldest child, an 8-year-old boy who's just
beginning to explore the vast terrain of pop music, never gets his
hands on this album.
</P>
<P>
   Which, of course, is precisely the way Eminem wants it. I'm 36
years old, white and comfortably middle class, a demographic far
removed from rap's target audience of urban black and suburban
white teenagers. This isn't my music _ and the very reason it
offends me is the very reason kids are drawn to it. It's the
age-old principle of rebellion. My parents, who grew up during
Sinatra's heyday, still struggle with rock _ and that is no doubt
what partially attracted me to it. I remember watching Blondie
perform on Saturday Night Live, enraptured by Deborah Harry's icy,
punk-princess persona; my mother asked me to turn off the
television.
</P>
<P>
   Now, my music is relegated to nostalgic anthologies and I'm the
one who's out of touch. As a rule, I don't listen to rap
recordings. And I don't line up to buy tickets to rap concerts,
such as the ``Up In Smoke'' tour, featuring Eminem, Dr. Dre, Snoop
Dogg and Ice Cube, which comes to the National Car Rental Center on
Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   But my story is a little more complex. I'm not just a
36-year-old white guy, I'm also a critic. For more than a decade, I
have made my living writing primarily about music and musicians,
first in the classical field _ I once considered becoming an opera
singer _ and more recently in pop and rock. But during this time, I
have generally avoided rap. I like to consider myself open-minded:
My record collection ranges from Sondheim to the Rolling Stones,
Mozart to the Dave Matthews Band. But there are no albums by
Run-D.M.C., the Beastie Boys or Dr. Dre.
</P>
<P>
   Now, there are.
</P>
<P>
   A few weeks ago, I gave myself the challenge of coming to terms
with rap. I wanted to know what all these kids were listening to. I
wanted to understand how a genre that many critics wrote off in its
early years _ who ever heard of ``songs'' in which nobody sang? _
had managed to survive more than two decades. And not just survive,
but prosper.
</P>
<P>
   Since the first rap record in 1979, Rapper's Delight by the
Sugar Hill Gang, rap has shifted from its streetwise New York
origins to become an international phenomenon. According to the
Recording Industry Association of America, rap accounted for 10.8
percent of all record sales in 1999, putting it in a virtual tie
for the first time with country music. (Rock remains the industry
leader, with 25.2 percent, but its market share has slipped
dramatically in the last decade.) Look at the latest Billboard pop
charts and you'll find four rap or rap-dominated albums occupying
the top five spots. (The one exception? Britney Spears, of course.)
</P>
<P>
   Soundtrack of Middle America
</P>
<P>
   The phenomenon extends well beyond music. Rap is the leading
edge of the entire aesthetic wave known as hip-hop, a term that
encompasses nearly everything rooted in the black urban cultural
experience, from dancing to fashion. But if hip-hop's creators are
largely black _ and even that has started to change with the
current rage for white rappers like Eminem and Kid Rock _ its
audience has become increasingly white. Look at MTV and it's
obvious that rap is now the soundtrack of Middle America. Even my
8-year-old son, who's exposed to a spectrum of fairly clean-cut rap
artists on the kid-oriented Nickelodeon cable network, claims it as
his music.
</P>
<P>
   So what's my problem?
</P>
<P>
   Actually, I'm not that different from most parents I know _ or
even most pop critics of a certain age. On a certain level, we all
don't get it. A current story in the American Journalism Review
talks about how newspapers are being forced to reexamine who they
have covering music _ and the critics themselves admit there's a
problem. The piece quotes 58-year-old Village Voice pop critic
Robert Christgau, one of the few senior music scribes who's made an
earnest attempt to stay current. ``Hip-hop is the great
generational divide,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   To try to cross that divide, I did what any critic would do: I
listened. In my weeklong foray, I sampled bits and pieces of about
a dozen albums, ranging from the ``old school'' rap of the Sugar
Hill Gang to such contemporary voices as Dr. Dre and Will Smith. I
also read Nelson George's seminal volume on rap, Hip Hop America.
And I talked to everyone from a rap-loving spokesman with a
Washington media think tank to a local artist who specializes in
Christian rap.
</P>
<P>
   The mere mention of a Christian rapper brings me to the first of
many lessons I learned _ that there as many kinds of rap as there
are rappers. While it's the hard-core artists who often grab the
headlines, particularly such ``gangsta'' rappers as Tupac Shakur
and Notorious B.I.G., whose violent lifestyles ended in their
murders, these represent just one branch of an ever-growing tree.
There are the party rappers who started it all (Sugar Hill Gang,
Run-D.M.C.), the alternative rappers who bring an avant-garde
mindset to the urban scene (De La Soul, A Tribe Called Quest), the
female rappers who blend soul and spice (Queen Latifah,
Salt-N-Pepa). And there are icons aplenty: rap balladeer L.L. Cool
J, Public Enemy, pop rapper Will Smith, South Florida's own
booty-rapping, free-speech advocate Luther Campbell, and rap's
Grammy girl, Lauryn Hill, whose R&AMP;B-shaded solo debut became the
first hip-hop recording to win the industry's highest honor, Album
of the Year.
</P>
<P>
   The sheer diversity was something I didn't expect to encounter.
On a lazy afternoon, I listened to A Tribe Called Quest's The Low
End Theory, an album that overflows with the cool, funky vibes of
jazz _ and not just because bassist Ron Carter appears as a guest.
Hearing the muted horns, the lyrics that refer to everything from
Shakespeare to pagers (more on that aspect later), the recording
struck me as a quintessential Beat-generation-inspired expression
(remember, the Beat poets also did their thing to jazz). This is
rap that any adult could appreciate _ or at least any adult with
taste.
</P>
<P>
   But the point is not to focus on a particular album. Saying you
don't like rap because of some sex-and-violence-filled rant is a
little like saying you don't like rock because of Marilyn Manson's
music. Any genre that has passed the test of time has room for
everybody. A colleague told me about an Orthodox Jew who raps about
the Holocaust. I wouldn't be surprised if there's a country-western
rapper out there.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, when I looked closer at the ``gangsta''
subgenre, I couldn't automatically write it off. True, much of it
revolves around limited themes (sex, drugs and street violence),
told in the same brutal, foul-mouthed style. As much as I tried, I
had a hard time distinguishing Dr. Dre's The Chronic from Tupac
Shakur's 2Pacalypse Now, both considered important historical
recordings. And on first listening, I could barely make it through
N.W.A.'s Straight Outta Compton. But another colleague urged me to
listen again. This time, I got it: The title track tells it all _
this is music that exposes the underside of America. It's the anger
of a riotous Los Angeles after the Rodney King trial, set to a
furious beat. You may not like the message, but attention must be
paid.
</P>
<P>
   Not that rock hasn't offered its share of political commentary,
from Bob Dylan to U2. By contrast, most black music during the '60s
and '70s, from the Motown sound of The Supremes to the disco beat
of Donna Summer, rarely asked you to do anything more than listen
with a smile or dance. There were such noteworthy social-minded
exceptions as Marvin Gaye and Stevie Wonder, but it took rap to
truly unleash the urban message.
</P>
<P>
   Ambitious in its scope
</P>
<P>
   And it's not just ``gangsta'' artists who have something to say.
You'll find your share of conscience on everything from Grandmaster
Flash's groundbreaking 1982 single The Message, which chronicles
one man's quest to hold on to his sanity amidst all the urban
decay, to Will Smith's recent Just the Two of Us, which talks about
the challenges of fatherhood.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rap nowadays is no different from the folk music of the '60s;
they're coming up with the same grass-roots vibes,'' says local
Christian rapper Proverb, whose group, 1Way, has released two
nationally acclaimed recordings.
</P>
<P>
   But even when rap is not asking you to think, it's usually
ambitious in its scope. From album to album, I was consistently
impressed by the sheer length of rap songs. Whereas rock and pop
rarely venture beyond five minutes _ you can't risk the possibility
of turning off radio programmers _ rap has trouble thinking in such
short terms. Take the song that started it all, Rapper's Delight.
It's a 14-minute party of a record that holds up remarkably well, a
playful vision of the inner city that's as big and proud as the MCs
behind the mike. You hear the same ambition when rap artists ``free
style'' _ improvise lyrics on the spot. The best go on like a great
rock guitarist on a mighty tear.
</P>
<P>
   Clever wordplay
</P>
<P>
   And yet, where is that ambition in rock today? Consider
alternative rock, says Anthony DeCurtis, a Rolling Stone
contributing editor and rap aficionado. He points to the grunge
bands' ``refusal of scale, refusal of fame.'' By contrast, he adds,
``I like that the rappers go for it ... That, to me, is exciting.''
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, however, rap is about lyrics. The many prosaic
rappers notwithstanding, the genre's hallmark may be its clever
wordplay. You can find examples left and right. Here's the Sugar
Hill Gang in Rapper's Delight: ``I say can of beer that's sweeter
than honey/Like a millionaire that has no money/Like a rainy day
that is not wet/Like a gambling fiend that does not bet/Like a
Dracula without his fangs/Like the boogie to the boogie without the
boogie bang/Like collard greens that don't taste good/Like a tree
that's not made out of wood.'' And here's A Tribe Called Quest in
What?: ``What's a childbirth without the umbilica?/What's United
Parcel without the deling such personal favorites as The Police's
Every Breath You Take and The Clash's Rock the Casbah, in the end,
it's the beat that propels rap. And while that beat can be expanded
and explored in countless ingenious ways, from the funk rhythms of
Dr. Dre to those jazz musings of A Tribe Called Quest, it's still
just a beat. To my ears, raised on Bach and rock, it's melody that
seduces the ears, that attaches itself to a lyric and lets you feel
its emotional content. That's why rap's lyrics are so short and
clipped _ they're defined by rhythm. I can't help but think of it
as a limitation.
</P>
<P>
   Complaint of ownership
</P>
<P>
   And let's go back to sampling: This, too, is a problem for me _
and one that has bothered many musicians, blaclight' (1979) and
Grandmaster Flash's `The Message' (1982):
</P>
<P>
   You can find these two seminal singles on various rap
anthologies (I chose one called Old School Rap, Volume 1, on the
Thump Records label). Both hold up remarkably well after all these
years, the former offering a generous taste of rap in its best
party-days mode, the latter giving an early glimpse of rap's social
conscience.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  N.W.A.'s `Straight Outta Compton' (1989):
</P>
<P>
   This is ``gangsta'' rap before it got a bad rap _ an
uncompromising vision of America's urban nightmare. Just check out
the title cut.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  A Tribe Called Quest's `The Low End Theory' (1991): Think rap
meets the avant-garde. This jazz- and funk-flavored album is an
alternative rap definition of cool.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Lauryn Hill's `The Miseducation of Lauryn Hill' (1998): After
her success with the Fugees, Hill released this R&AMP;B-shaded solo
debut. It took rap to another place, blending heart and soul with
the rhythm of the street.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Eminem's `The Marshall Mathers LP' (2000): You'll hate the
message, but you can't ignore the man's creativity. And Stan is one
of the most chilling songs you'll ever hear _ a powerful narrative
that builds to a shocking conclusion.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
