<DOCNO> NYT20000731.0195 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-31 15:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8417 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a BC-FANG-EXAMINER-HNS &LR;      07-31 1212
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FANG-EXAMINER-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     FANGS SET TO MAKE HISTORY 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By ANNIE NAKAO, ELIZABETH FERNANDEZ, MATHEW YI and DEMIAN
BULWA  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ When the mid-March deal was struck for the late
John Fang's family to buy The Examiner, the patriarch's wife,
Florence, went to his grave and left a copy of The Examiner, whose
bold headline said ``SOLD.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I know that when people pass away, they should lie in peace,''
said Florence Fang. ``But this time, I just had to tell him. . . .
I think he read it.''
</P>
<P>
   With the ink dry on Friday's transfer of the 135-year-old
Examiner to the Asian American publishing family, Florence Fang,
65, and her three sons - James, Ted and Douglas - have even more to
celebrate.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel very happy and grateful,'' she said in a phone
interview from her Hillsborough, Calif., home. ``I feel we have a
long way to go. We have a heavier burden, because all the Asian and
Chinese communities are looking upon us. I will do my best.''
</P>
<P>
   In San Francisco's Chinese American community - where penniless
immigrant John Ta Chuan Fang arrived from Taiwan in the early 1950s
- the rags-to-riches rise of his family to a media dynasty with
potent political connections has awed some and dismayed others.
</P>
<P>
   What's undisputed is the fact that The Examiner's sale - part of
the Hearst Corp.'s purchase of the San Francisco Chronicle - makes
the Fangs the first Asian Americans to own a major daily newspaper
in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   That is significant in a city that is now 37 percent Asian,
according to the latest census estimates.
</P>
<P>
   ``If anything, this encapsulates part of the changing
demographics and political atmosphere in San Francisco's civic
life,'' said David Lee of the Chinese American Voters Education
Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Friday's completion of the sale of The Examiner to the Fangs
drew widely divergent views.
</P>
<P>
   Praising the Fangs as driven immigrants who have achieved the
American Dream, Housing Commissioner Julie Lee, founder of the San
Francisco Neighbors' Association, said, ``For a minority family to
own a paper is very tough to begin with. But they are fighters.
They don't give up easily. They are very determined, even though
they've had a lot of bad publicity.''
</P>
<P>
   Critic L. Ling-Chi Wang, UC-Berkeley's chair of ethnic studies,
offered another perspective.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Fangs know what they want: money and power,'' Wang said.
``And they pursue it vigorously and relentlessly. They play
hardball. There will probably be even more fear of them now. The
constituency they have is driven by fear and self-interest . . . by
convenience and necessity.''
</P>
<P>
   Still others say the Fangs' success merely mirrors most American
journalism enterprises.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're first and foremost business people who've made inroads
into the political landscape,'' said Henry Der, former executive
director of Chinese for Affirmative Action who is now state deputy
superintendent for education. ``The line is very blurred between
business and politics. But that's no different from any other
newspaper business.''
</P>
<P>
   The crowning achievement of those efforts was their purchase of
The Examiner - for $100 million while receiving a $66 million
subsidy from the Hearst Corp. to run it.
</P>
<P>
   It's a coup that even their critics had to admire.
</P>
<P>
   ``Where else do you get that kind of deal?'' said Wang. ``The
Fangs are laughing all the way to the bank.''
</P>
<P>
   But Benny Yee, redevelopment commissioner for San Francisco and
a longtime family friend, said that if John Fang were here, he
wouldn't be laughing.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he were alive today, I'm telling you, he would be crying
(with joy),'' said Yee. ``I can see the tears running down his face
now.''
</P>
<P>
   Yee said journalism was John Fang's passion and life work.
</P>
<P>
   The Shanghai-born Fang's involvement in journalism began at age
11, when he journeyed alone to inland China and sold newspapers for
a living. He later studied journalism at Taipei's Chen Chi
University and worked at the New Life newspaper, a
government-controlled paper in Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
   He came to San Francisco in 1952 to study ``everything'' at
UC-Berkeley.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of getting a master's degree in journalism, however, he
began working at the Chinese Daily Post and Young China Daily News
newspapers - both organs of the Kuomintang, Taiwan's then-ruling
Nationalist Party. While on a trip back to Taiwan, he married
Florence Fang in 1960.
</P>
<P>
   Capitalizing on the fact that Chinatowns were becoming tourist
attractions, John Fang began publishing ``Chinatown Handy Guide''
booklets in major cities.
</P>
<P>
   In 1979, he started the family's newspaper dynasty by founding
AsianWeek, a English-language tabloid aimed at Asian American
communities.
</P>
<P>
   It was a commitment that benefited others, said Sandy Close,
executive editor of Pacific News Service.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ted (Fang) helped me start `Yo!''' said Close of the
syndicated column written for and by youth. ``And his father helped
start a Spanish-language newspaper. It speaks to me of inclusion
that every ethnic community would do well to emulate.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1987, the Fangs boldly expanded, acquiring the Independent, a
West of Twin Peaks weekly. They turned it into a cheeky
thrice-weekly free broadsheet, upping the press run from 80,000 to
200,000.
</P>
<P>
   With their acquisitions grew political power. The Fangs, who are
Republicans, became key backers of politicians from both parties.
</P>
<P>
   As the Fang sons grew up, they took places in the family
business. Ted, 37, is publisher of the Independent. Elder brother
James - married to the daughter of the former mayor of Shanghai -
is the 39-year-old publisher of AsianWeek while Douglas, 35,
handles the papers' online operations.
</P>
<P>
   The family's fortunes soared after the Fangs used the paper to
campaign to elect Frank Jordan mayor in 1991. James Fang was
appointed as director of international trade.
</P>
<P>
   With each new venture, the Fangs were developing clout, not just
in Chinatown but in high political circles.
</P>
<P>
   And they have not been shy about using the pages of the
Independent to advocate for politicians they support and issues
they feel strongly about.
</P>
<P>
   However they're viewed, the Fangs are posed to set a precedent
when they take over The Examiner in roughly four months. That
burden is made heavier by the way the Fangs obtained the paper.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many Asians will feel a sense of pride and vindication that an
Asian American has cracked the ownership of a serious and
well-known American newspaper,'' said William Woo, journalism
professor at Stanford University and former editor of the St. Louis
Post-Dispatch. ``It's not the same as founding a newspaper. They
essentially bought it at a fire sale. They went out and found the
remnants of a Justice Department requirement. So in the long run,
the pride that Asians get depends on what the Fangs are able to
accomplish with this paper. I think the Fangs have a very steep
road ahead of them.''
</P>
<P>
   But all those cautions were not in the mind of Florence Fang on
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``My husband would have been the happiest person - it was his
dream,'' she said. ``Do we celebrate? Not yet. Today, I want to be
very quiet and start thinking of the whole thing.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
