<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-31 15:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8420 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a BC-SCI-BRODY-HEALTH-NYT &LR;      07-31 1174
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-BRODY-HEALTH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PERSONAL HEALTH: FIBROMYALGIA: REAL ILLNESS, REAL ANSWERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Science Times)  
 By JANE E. BRODY    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Is it a real disease?'' is the most frequently asked question
about fibromyalgia, an ailment characterized by chronic widespread
musculoskeletal pain. The cynical tone that usually accompanies the
question suggests that many think this syndrome is all in a
person's head, the result, perhaps, of an emotional disorder or an
attempt to avoid the demands of work and life.
</P>
<P>
   Not so, say experts who have spent years studying this
controversial disorder. Yes, some people with fibromyalgia may be
depressed or anxious, but wouldn't you be if you couldn't carry a
bag of groceries, walk through a park or tie your shoelaces without
considerable pain?
</P>
<P>
   And yes, there is as yet no convincing physiological explanation
for the array of symptoms suffered by people with fibromyalgia. It
is neither an inflammatory disorder nor a degenerative disease. Its
victims look perfectly normal. But when even mild pressure is
applied to certain points on the body that do not normally hurt,
most of those areas are painfully tender in a person with
fibromyalgia.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Don Goldenberg, rheumatologist at Newton-Wellesley Hospital
and Tufts University School of Medicine in Boston, cites studies
indicating that 10 percent to 12 percent of the population suffers
from persistent widespread pain, women more than men and older more
than younger. Many of these people have no well-defined
musculoskeletal disease but rather satisfy the diagnostic criteria
for fibromyalgia, making it the second most common diagnosis in
rheumatology clinics, behind osteoarthritis.
</P>
<P>
   The National Institutes of Health estimates that 3.7 million
Americans over 18 have fibromyalgia: about 3.4 percent of women and
0.5 percent of men and more than 7 percent of women from 60 to 79.
</P>
<P>
   A decade ago, after careful study, the American College of
Rheumatology concluded that chronic pain patients without some
other well-defined disease who had mild or greater tenderness at 11
or more of 18 specific points on the body could be said to have
fibromyalgia. But pain is only part of the problem. Patients with
fibromyalgia typically also suffer from fatigue, sleep disturbances
and headaches, as well as depression and anxiety.
</P>
<P>
   The disorder is often mistaken for osteoarthritis, which may
coexist with it in the elderly. It may also be confused with
degenerative spinal disk disease, a nerve entrapment syndrome or
chronic Lyme disease. As with these other disorders, symptoms of
fibromyalgia are often made worse by weather, stress or
inappropriate exercise.
</P>
<P>
   Half or more of fibromyalgia patients have or once had other
disorders that lack a defined organic basis, like chronic fatigue
syndrome, chronic headaches or irritable bowel syndrome. This has
led some to believe that fibromyalgia is a psychosomatic disorder,
an emotional problem that manifests itself as a physical one. But
while half or more of people with fibromyalgia have a history of
depression, most have no current psychiatric illness.
</P>
<P>
   Certain organic aberrations have been found in people with
fibromyalgia, although it is not yet known if these came before or
after the syndrome developed. Among them are changes in nervous
system chemicals that may explain the common problem of disturbed
sleep. Fibromyalgia patients typically lack restorative, or
slow-wave, sleep, which can result in chronic fatigue and
heightened sensitivity. Levels of substance P, a chemical related
to pain, and some abnormal pain-related peptides are at high levels
in the cerebrospinal fluid of fibromyalgia patients, who may also
have insufficient blood flow to parts of the brain involved in pain
perception.
</P>
<P>
   Patients often report that their chronic pain is preceded by a
physical or emotional trauma, like a neck injury from a car
accident or loss of a job. Or the disorder may follow an infection.
For example, 10 percent to 25 percent of Lyme disease patients
develop fibromyalgia that persists for months or years after they
have received adequate treatment for Lyme disease. These patients
do not respond to prolonged treatment with antibiotics that treat
Lyme disease. Despite considerable investigation, no infectious
organism _ not Epstein-Barr virus or any other suspect
micro-organism _ has been identified as a cause of fibromyalgia.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Dennis Turk, a pain specialist at the University of
Washington School of Medicine in Seattle, summed up the perplexing
disorder: ``Because fibromyalgia is so confusing, other people
wonder if it's real. This contributes to the sufferer's emotional
distress.''
</P>
<P>
   Fibromyalgia is considered a chronic problem that could last
indefinitely. But proper treatment, which may involve medication to
improve sleep along with a specially designed exercise program and
psychological counseling, can greatly alleviate a patient's
discomfort and disability.
</P>
<P>
   Even when patients are not depressed, studies have shown that
taking low doses of an antidepressant can often treat the
underlying sleep disorder and alleviate the accompanying fatigue.
But experts warn against using sleeping pills, sedatives or
alcohol, because these may only make the sleep problem worse.
</P>
<P>
   The pain and disability associated with fibromyalgia can become
a self-fulfilling prophecy. As patients with pain refrain more and
more from physical activity, their muscles become increasingly
deconditioned and susceptible to pain from the slightest exertion.
</P>
<P>
   ``The most important key to managing muscles affected by
fibromyalgia is to keep them moving,'' says Stacie Bigelow, a
health educator and counselor who has had fibromyalgia for nearly a
decade. In her sensible and informative new book, ``Fibromyalgia:
Simple Relief Through Movement,'' she likens the problem to a
cement truck that must keep the cement moving to keep it from
solidifying. Unused muscles become stiff and painful.
</P>
<P>
   The key in fibromyalgia is to increase daily activities
gradually so that muscles do not remain in one position for long
and to adopt a program of gentle exercise to recondition muscles,
along with a stretching routine that also helps to reduce pain.
Bigelow's book details ways of adopting a program of activity and
exercise (alternating with rest) that, though it may not seem so at
first, is essential to reducing the pain of fibromyalgia and
relieving the associated disability.
</P>
<P>
   Another excellent book, ``Fibromyalgia and the Mind-Body-Spirit
Connection,'' by Dr. William B. Salt II and Dr. Edwin Season,
describes the enormous benefits that can be gleaned from a
relatively brief form of counseling called cognitive behavioral
therapy, which helps people address self-defeating thoughts that
can aggravate pain and make adopting changes to alleviate pain
difficult. If you find yourself thinking that you can never get
better or that you can't stand it anymore, cognitive behavioral
therapy can be very helpful.
</P>
</TEXT>
