<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOP-PLATFORM-575&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REPUBLICAN DELEGATES ADOPT NEW PARTY PLATFORM 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: This story will be updated by 9 p.m. EDT with a 1,000-word
version by Robin Toner; the text is available on the Web:
www.nytimes.com) By DANIEL J. WAKIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ Maintaining the promise of a friction-free
convention, delegates to the Republican National Convention swiftly
adopted a platform Monday that adheres to most of the party's core
conservative principles but softens some of the edges on other
issues in keeping with Gov. George W. Bush's effort to project a
more compassionate image.
</P>
<P>
   The platform was approved by the delegates in a voice vote, in
the first major action at the convention. It maintains a tough line
on abortion and rejects special rights for gays and homosexuals. It
calls for a reduction in the size of the federal government and for
tax cuts. The platform enshrines other basic Republican touchstones
like the pre-eminence of the family and a need for ``rebuilding the
American military.''
</P>
<P>
   The theme of the platform closely matches the message of the
convention, as scripted by the Bush campaign. The first chapter's
title, for example, is ``The American Dream: Prosperity with a
Purpose,'' echoing the message in Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   The language on abortion, despite the appeals of pro-choice
Republicans, remains particularly strict. The platform condemns a
recent Supreme Court decision prohibiting states from banning what
critics call partial birth abortions. It calls for a ``human life''
amendment to the Constitution and legislation ``to make clear''
that the 14th Amendment applies to fetuses.
</P>
<P>
   Also included was support for the appointment of judges ``who
respect traditional family values and the sanctity of innocent
human life,'' which abortion rights supporters denounce as a litmus
test for judges.
</P>
<P>
   But in recognition of Bush's strategy of pulling in moderate
voters, the platform differed from previous ones on some major
issues.
</P>
<P>
   There was no call for abolishing the Department of Education, a
favored goal of conservatives. In fact, the 73-page document
devoted four pages to education, which polls show is one of the
major concerns of Americans.
</P>
<P>
   It listed the principles for ``what works'' in education:
``strong parental involvement, excellent teachers, safe and orderly
classrooms, high academic standards and a commitment to teaching
the basics _ from an early start in phonics to mastery of computer
technology.'' It emphasized greater control over education,
increasing the number of charter schools and allowing students in
dangerous schools to transfer.
</P>
<P>
   Notable was language reaching out to foreign-born citizens. ``As
a nation of immigrants, we welcome all new Americans who have
entered lawfully and are prepared to follow our laws and provide
for themselves and their families,'' the platform said.
</P>
<P>
   The balancing act embodied by this platform reflected the perils
of Bush's strategy of tempering the party's harder-edged views.
While reaching out to more moderate voters and Democrats willing to
abandon Vice President Al Gore, his eventual opponent, Bush risks
alienating his Republican core.
</P>
<P>
   The debate before Monday's vote reflected that. More
conservative members fought fiercely to keep in the call for the
abolishment of the Education Department.
</P>
<P>
   On the other side of the divide, less conservative members of
the platform committee failed to keep out a statement that
homosexuals had no place in the military. Even Bush had more in
common with the losers in that battle. He supports the ``don't ask,
don't tell'' policy, a spokesman said, which the Clinton
administration has adopted.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   On other gay issues, the platform said that no ``special legal
protections or standing in law'' should be granted gays, nor should
civil unions.
</P>
<P>
   ``The family is society's central core of energy. That is why
efforts to strengthen family life are the surest way to improve
life for everyone,'' the platform said. And later: ``We support the
traditional definition of `marriage' as the legal union of one man
and one woman, and we believe that federal judges and bureaucrats
should not force states to recognize other living arrangements as
marriage.''
</P>
<P>
   On foreign trade, the platform calls for a ``new and ambitious
round'' of multilateral negotiations aimed at opening markets,
efforts to have countries bring down tariffs so more U.S. goods can
be sold and a tightening of export controls over military
technology.
</P>
<P>
   It also calls for giving the next president so-called fast-track
negotiating authority. And it supports the development of
bioengineered crops, an idea that is at odds with many European
economic allies and trading partners.
</P>
</TEXT>
