<HEADER>
A8426 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r p BC-KENNEDY-COLUMN-TEX     07-31 0640
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KENNEDY-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EVANGELIST FOLLOWING BUSH'S CUES
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 By BUD KENNEDY 
 c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ This should be David Barton's week in the
spotlight, a week when the Texas historian and best-selling
evangelical Christian author could show Republicans around the
birthplace of what he calls a ``godly'' nation founded under
``Christian principles.''
</P>
<P>
   So where is this outspoken Texan whose religious books are
quoted across America? Where is this Texan who wants Supreme Court
judges impeached and calls separation of church and state a
``myth''?
</P>
<P>
   Ssshhh. He's the state party vice chairman now. So he's
following the same script as the Guv.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm trying to build bridges, trying to seek common ground in
the party,'' said Barton, 46, of rural Annetta in Parker County,
west of Fort Worth.
</P>
<P>
   Once a Bible-preaching evangelical guest speaker, he comes to
this week's Republican National Convention in a state leadership
role.
</P>
<P>
   ``You make gains a little at a time,'' he said. ``A lot of the
voters in the Christian movement don't understand that. They want
everything changed right now.''
</P>
<P>
   For now, common ground is named George W. Bush. The Texas
governor is a Methodist who calls for ``compassionate
conservatism,'' but also speaks the evangelical language of
``knowing'' Jesus Christ as a ``personal savior.''
</P>
<P>
   With the once-powerful Christian Coalition lobbying group
divided, Barton sees himself as a connection between mainstream
evangelicals who want, say, prayers at high school football games,
and extreme groups who want America reinvented as a ``Christian
nation'' under a religious government.
</P>
<P>
   Four years ago in San Diego, Barton pitched evangelical books
and videos to the latter group, selling his meticulous research
suggesting that the Founding Fathers may have intended to govern by
the Bible. (Since then, his most popular book, ``The Myth of
Separation,'' has been withdrawn and re-edited to remove some
unverified content. It is now titled ``Original Intent.'')
</P>
<P>
   This week, joining 17,000 Republicans in the home of
Independence Hall and the Liberty Bell, he not only won't give any
``heritage'' speeches _ he might not even revisit the historic
sites which were the backdrop for his books.
</P>
<P>
   ``Philadelphia is great for a historian,'' he said. ``There is
no better place to see American history than the place where the
principles of our government were established. That's something to
be celebrated.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet he plans to quietly shop for antique documents and add to
his collection of Revolutionary War-era publications.
</P>
<P>
   ``No tours,'' he said with a shrug and a grin. ``I think our
delegates can find it all.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead of giving his old rapid-fire speeches filled with quotes
and statistics about how America has gone bad since school prayers
ended in 1962, now Barton delivers a broad plea for all Americans
to vote and participate in government.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to get people more involved,'' he said. ``I'm disturbed
that the voter turnout is so low. On either side of the aisle, I
want more people taking part. That adversarial process turns out a
better final product.''
</P>
<P>
   He insisted that his leadership role has not changed his
message.
</P>
<P>
   ``I used to promise that anybody could get involved,'' he said.
``Then, I was only speaking to religious groups.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, I'm giving the same speech. But instead of telling
Christian groups to get involved, I'm telling civic clubs and
Republican clubs and all sides to get involved.''
</P>
<P>
   Sounds like the gospel according to Bush.
</P>
<P>
   (Bud Kennedy is a columnist for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
You can call him at (817) 390-7538, or e-mail:
budk(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
