<HEADLINE>
LASER EYE SURGERY'S TURF WAR 
</HEADLINE>
  (Science Times) 
(Editors: Also See SCI-EYE-DECIDE and SCI-EYE-WITNESS) 
(ART ADV: A graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By KENNETH CHANG   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Harriet Bass lay on a table at the New York Eye and
Ear Infirmary, her right eye propped open by a metal ring, staring
up at a red dot of light.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're going to feel a little pressure,'' Dr. John A. Seedor
told Bass, a 49-year-old casting director, as he was about to slice
into her cornea. Using a motorized blade known as a keratome,
Seedor cut a circular flap around the cornea, about one-third of an
inch wide and one-150th of an inch thick, and peeled it back.
</P>
<P>
   Switching to a computer-controlled laser, Seedor trained an
invisible beam of cool ultraviolet light on the exposed soft
underlayers. The lenses within Bass' nearsighted eyes bent light
too sharply, making her vision fuzzy. The laser vaporized bits of
cornea in a way that flattened the curvature at the front of Bass'
eye to bring images at the back of the eye, on the retina, into
focus.
</P>
<P>
   ``All right, Harriet. It looks beautiful,'' Seedor said. He
placed the flap back down, caressing it with a brush back into
place. ``Ready for the other eye?''
</P>
<P>
   Seedor repeated the procedure. The operation took about 15
minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Although the Food and Drug Administration approved the procedure
only last year, Lasik, short for laser in-situ keratomileusis, has
quickly grown into a $3 billion-a-year industry, with 750,000
Americans expected to choose the surgery this year. Intended to
correct nearsightedness, the procedure can now treat farsightedness
as well.
</P>
<P>
   With 1.2 million American customers expected next year, Lasik is
becoming the issue in a financial turf war between ophthalmologists
and optometrists, between top-dollar surgeons and low-cost,
high-volume centers.
</P>
<P>
   Ophthalmologists are the eye surgeons with medical degrees who
perform the surgery. Optometrists are specialists in measuring
vision who prescribe eyeglasses and contact lenses, and,
increasingly, handle the care before and after Lasik surgery.
</P>
<P>
   Lasik's popularity is easily explained: For the vast majority of
patients, it is safe, effective and, increasingly, affordable.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a simple procedure,'' said Dr. Richard S. Koplin, medical
director of LaserOne in Manhattan. ``It's not brain surgery.''
</P>
<P>
   With so many people willing to pay out of pocket _ most
insurance companies do not pay for the procedure, because they
regard it as ``cosmetic'' _ to be rid of contacts or glasses, Lasik
surgeons have turned to the familiar marketing tools: celebrity
testimonials, billboards, radio and television advertisements,
telemarketing.
</P>
<P>
   For would-be patients, the choices _ LaserOne, Lasik Vision, the
Laser Center, Insight Laser Center, Infinity Laser Center, among
others _ can bewilder.
</P>
<P>
   Three general business models have evolved. Seedor is in the
mode of a traditional practice: A patient pays for the attention
and experience of the surgeon, $2,650 an eye in Bass' case.
</P>
<P>
   Centers like Lasik Vision and LaserOne are decidedly corporate
and mass market; Carmine Asparro of Bellmore, taking advantage of
the grand opening special at Lasik Vision in Garden City, N.Y.,
paid just $500 for Lasik on his right eye. (His left already had
20/20 vision.)
</P>
<P>
   The third is an increasingly popular arrangement known as
``co-management'' in which a patient's optometrist handles the
initial evaluation and postoperative care in exchange for part of
the fee. The Laser Center in Manhattan, for example, works with
about 75 optometrists who send a stream of patients. The
optometrists make money from a procedure that eliminates the need
for their services.
</P>
<P>
   At the Laser Center, Evan Mason of Irvington paid more than
Bass: $5,500 for two eyes. Yet she never met her surgeon, Dr. Mark
G. Speaker, before the surgery and has not seen him since. No
studies have showed which approach yields better results, and all
three have their critics and defenders.
</P>
<P>
   Marketing materials from the traditional Lasik surgeons often
darkly hint that their cheaper competitors might be skimping to
make a profit.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Joseph Dello Russo of the New Jersey Eye Institute in
Bergenfield charges $2,800 per eye. ``I know what I'm worth,'' he
said. ``You're not going to get an experienced surgeon for $1,000
an eye.''
</P>
<P>
   Michael R. Henderson, president and chief executive of Lasik
Vision Corp., which runs centers in North America, is similarly
emphatic. ``If you pay $5,000,'' he said, ``you're simply being
gouged.''
(MORE) nn
</P>
<P>
   But Dr. Susan Fromer, an ophthalmologist at Garden City Lasik
Vision, says higher-cost surgeons can coexist with the high-volume
centers. In addition to her work at Lasik Vision, Fromer also
performs the surgery in her private practice in Manhattan, charging
$3,600 for two eyes.
</P>
<P>
   In her practice, Fromer handles the evaluation and postoperation
visits herself. At Lasik Vision _ which now charges $999 an eye
after 1,000 people quickly signed up for the introductory special _
an optometrist on the staff handles those duties, although Fromer
says she reviews the optometrists' data.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe in both models,'' Fromer said. ``It's an issue of
handholding. The level of care is the same.''
</P>
<P>
   In the co-management debates, some ophthalmologists are
concerned about the appearance of optometrists' steering patients
their way.
</P>
<P>
   Others fear that optometrists may be slow to recognize
complications after operations. The Laser Center is ``an economic
model,'' said Dr. Joseph Evitar, a surgeon at Chelsea Eye
Associates in Manhattan. ``You can't know what is really going on.
You're relying on someone else's judgment.''
</P>
<P>
   Speaker, on the other hand, says he carefully chooses his
co-managing optometrists. ``It wouldn't reflect well on me if I
were associated with someone who wasn't knowledgeable,'' he said.
The payment, 20 percent, is simply for the visits before and after.
``They are entitled to be paid for their services,'' he said,
``just like any other profession.''
</P>
<P>
   Mason said she was not aware that $1,000 of the $5,000 she paid
Speaker was going to her optometrist, Arkady Selenow, but that did
not bother her. ``I trust Dr. Selenow,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Optometrists say they know their patients better and that
results in better care.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not just a prescription,'' said Selenow, who practices in
Manhattan and Queens and co-manages about 1,000 Lasik cases a year.
``It's knowing their complete lifestyle. You know if they're going
to be happy. It's not just a science. There's an art to it, too.''
</P>
<P>
   For example, he said, a person who spends lots of time reading
or staring at a computer screen might be dissatisfied with 20/20
vision, because up-close viewing might be uncomfortable. Leaving
the vision slightly nearsighted might be a better option.
</P>
<P>
   With Mason, 44, Selenow steered her toward monovision, where her
right eye was corrected to 20/20 vision, while her left eye was
intentionally left a slightly nearsighted 20/40. That creates a
sort of bifocal vision, with the right eye to focus on distant
objects and the left eye for close-up reading.
</P>
<P>
   The sparring over co-management has escalated to the
professional societies of ophthalmologists and optometrists.
</P>
<P>
   This year, the American Academy of Ophthalmology and the
American Society of Cataract and Refractive Surgery released a
paper declaring that co-management should be ``an exceptional,
rather than a routine, occurrence,'' applicable, say, to someone
who lives far from the surgeon.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the co-management of patients is done on a routine basis
for predominantly financial reasons,'' the two organizations said,
``it represents unethical behavior and may be illegal.''
</P>
<P>
   The American Optometric Association countered, ``This conclusion
is not grounded in law, regulation, or the American Academy of
Ophthalmology's own Code of Ethics.''
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks ago, the International Society of Refractive Surgeons,
which includes ophthalmologists and optometrists, also said that
co-management was acceptable and that it was developing guidelines
for it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Properly structured, legal co-management arrangements should
not be cast under a pall just because they're co-management,'' said
Dr. Jeffrey B. Robin, the society's executive vice president.
</P>
<P>
   While no study offers a comprehensive picture, anecdotes point
to potential pitfalls.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Marc Odrich, director of refractive surgery at Columbia and
medical director of VISX, a laser manufacturer, tells of one
co-managed Lasik patient referred to him.
</P>
<P>
   The woman's eyesight was worsening, and an exam quickly showed
why: cataracts were clouding her lenses. Her optometrist had not
spotted the problem. The ophthalmologist did not check and, relying
on the optometrist, performed the operation. It went smoothly, but
the cataracts render it useless.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't fault the optometrist,'' Odrich said. ``I fault the
doctor who is operating on someone else's exam. You've got to do
the exam. This doesn't absolve you from being a doctor.''
</P>
<P>
   Most Lasik patients encounter no problems at all, although 1
percent to 10 percent require a second Lasik operation to fine-tune
their prescriptions.
</P>
<P>
   Still, complications do occasionally occur, some serious.
</P>
<P>
   During surgery, the flap-cutting keratome might jam or create a
wrinkle in the cornea, in perhaps one in 500 eyes, said Dr.
Jonathan Carr, director of medical services for the Lasik Vision
chain.
</P>
<P>
   After surgery, a range of problems can arise, although most can
be easily treated if caught promptly. About one in 500 will
experience an inflammation under the eye, Carr said. The odds of an
infection are about one in 10,000. There is one reported case of a
35-year-old man who had one eye removed after a Lasik-induced
infection.
</P>
<P>
   The operation also cuts down on production of tears, leading to
eyes that need drops. Almost always, the condition improves after a
few months.
</P>
<P>
   For some, particularly those with large pupils, Lasik can result
in nighttime glare and blurry halos around street lamps. Only
rarely does bothersome glare persist longer than a few months, Carr
said.
</P>
<P>
   Other surgical alternatives exist, including corrective lenses
implanted in the cornea. That procedure costs about the same and is
reversible.
</P>
<P>
   In June the FDA approved a new procedure called laser thermal
keratoplasty for treatment of mild to moderate farsightedness in
people over 40. The condition affects an estimated 60 million
Americans. The procedure takes less than three seconds: The thermal
laser fires 16 bursts in two concentric rings, causing cornea
tissue to shrink and steepening the edges.
</P>
<P>
   Improvements with Lasik are expected to help extremely
nearsighted people and those with oddly shaped corneas. For most,
Lasik already produces the results as promised.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm seeing perfect,'' Evan Mason said a couple of weeks after
her surgery. ``It was perfect that night.'' Monovision, which she
tested with contact lenses before her surgery, was also no problem.
``I adapted immediately.''
</P>
<P>
   Asparro, who took advantage of the special offered by Lasik
Vision, is also a satisfied patient. ``I'm so happy I did it,'' he
said. ``Love it. Would recommend it to anyone.''
</P>
<P>
   A couple of months after her surgery, Bass' vision is 20/50, not
the intended 20/25. She has bought reading glasses.
</P>
<P>
   She has a second operation scheduled _ an ``enhancement'' in
industry parlance and included in the original cost.
</P>
<P>
   ``They think they have to do me again at the beginning of
August,'' she said. ``It's not as easy as I thought it would be. I
am not a disgruntled patient by any means. I'm still satisfied with
the work because it's greatly improved over what I used to see.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
