<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-EYE-WITNESS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EYE WITNESS ACCOUNT OF LASIK SURGERY 
</HEADLINE>
  (Science Times) 
(Eds: Also See SCI-EYE-SURGERY and SCI-EYE-DECIDE) 
 By SARAH LYALL    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Surgery that would let me give up my glasses forever
had always sounded too good to be true, like one of those ads
promising that you can earn $10,000 a month by sitting around the
house doing nothing. I had been discussing it with my eye doctor
for years, and for years, the doctor had told me the technology was
not yet advanced enough.
</P>
<P>
   But he changed his mind because of improvements in the
technology. ``We can do it, if you're ready,'' he said last summer.
</P>
<P>
   I directed my unfiltered gaze to the eye chart on the wall. It
was silly to bother. As usual, I couldn't make out any of the
letters. In truth, I couldn't even tell that there was an eye
chart.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, I told him, I'm ready.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, I had my concerns. I worried that it would smell like
burning eyeball, or feel as if someone were taking an X-acto knife
to Jell-O. I worried that I would go blind, develop a disfiguring
infection or have to spend the rest of my life wearing tinted,
oversized double-thick aviator glasses.
</P>
<P>
   There is no question that I was severely nearsighted and a good
candidate for Lasik treatment. I'd worn glasses since I was 7 and,
according to family legend, failed to see the beautiful wild goat
silhouetted against the sunset while we were on vacation in Greece.
</P>
<P>
   Those first glasses _ bulbous tortoise-shell ones that clashed
with my Dorothy Hamill haircut _ were followed by other, equally
dismaying ones, and then some years later by contact lenses, which
tended to become dry, scratchy and unbearable, forcing me back into
the glasses.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, my eyesight kept spiraling downward, finally settling
at a miserable -8.5. This is roughly equivalent to having 20-1,600
vision, meaning that what a perfectly sighted person could see from
1,600 feet away, I could see at 20 feet. But I wore my disability,
which included considerable astigmatism, with perverse pride,
happily using it to explain a number of my most glaring personal
failures, including a pathological fear of heights, an inability to
remember what people looked like, and a tendency to drive in a way
that made my passengers want to take the bus.
</P>
<P>
   What would happen, I wondered, when I lost the ability to not
see?
</P>
<P>
   It happened last fall, at a laser lab in the gold-encrusted
Trump Tower on Fifth Avenue and 57th Street. Fortified with the
drugs I'd been prescribed, Valium and Percocet, I took my seat
along with a half-dozen other laser patients, all of them men in
their mid-'30s. They had brought their wives. I brought my mother.
We were all nervous.
</P>
<P>
   We swapped stories about lifetimes hobbled by corrective lenses,
and then it was my turn. I sat down, surrounded by nurses whose
job, it seemed, was to prevent me from running from the room. Then
the doctor began, one eye after the other.
</P>
<P>
   He gave me some numbing drops. Then he clamped my eyelid open to
prevent me from blinking, and put a suction ring around my eye.
Then he took the microkeratone _ which looks like a mini-version of
a butcher's meat-slicing machine _ and moved it across the eye,
cutting a tiny flap in the cornea.
</P>
<P>
   After that, which made everything go dark for about a minute,
the actual laser was not that bad. The suction ring was removed,
and I could see again. My job was not to flail erratically, not to
sob pitiably, and, most frighteningly, not to divert my eye from a
light blinking overhead.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whatever you do, DON'T LOOK AWAY,'' my doctor said ominously.
I did not smell burning, of fresh eyeball or singed flesh or
anything else. And I didn't feel any pain, only a lot of discomfort
and a strong desire to shout, ``Get your finger out of my eye!''
</P>
<P>
   The the doctor flooded my eye with liquid, taking what felt like
a mini-paintbrush and stroked my eyeball over and over, to get the
flap to re-attach itself over the cornea. Then he did the same
thing to the other eye.
</P>
<P>
   It didn't hurt, but by the end, my eyes felt so dry and scratchy
that all I wanted to do was close them and crawl away somewhere
dark. Which is what I did next, in a dimly lighted communal
recovery room along with several patients who had already had the
surgery.
</P>
<P>
   The other patients' wives (and my mother) asked anxiously how we
felt. We felt as though someone were blowing sand into our eyes
with a straw. But when I left the laser lab, wearing a pair of
goggles and an enormous pair of surgical sunglasses, I had enough
vanity left to make it clear to those who joined us on the Trump
Tower elevator that, No, I had not had a face lift, but an
important, medically necessary ocular procedure. (My insurance
company didn't think it was medically necessary: It cost $5,000,
out of pocket).
</P>
<P>
   The next few weeks were strange ones, as my eyes healed and I
began to realize that I could see again in a way that I had never
imagined.
</P>
<P>
   It's a hard feeling to describe, because it's not as if I'd been
actually blind before. But I'd always taken my fragile sight to be
a precarious commodity, a favor that, having been granted, could
easily be snatched away. And then there was the ever-present fear
of being caught in a thunderstorm in the middle of the woods,
losing my contact lenses, breaking my glasses and starving to death
when I could not find my way home.
</P>
<P>
   Now, I've almost forgotten all those years of gray, all those
lenses and inchoate worries. My eyes are better than 20-20: I can
see the tiny little line of letters at the bottom of the eye chart,
the optional ones. When I wake up, it's just me facing the world
without any distorting layers, with eyes that seem sharper and
brighter and more alive than they ever have before.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
