</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-EYE-DECIDE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DECISIONS, DECISIONS: QUESTIONS TO ASK A LASIK SURGEON 
</HEADLINE>
  (Science Times) 
(Eds: Also See SCI-EYE-SURGERY and SCI-EYE-WITNESS) 
 By KENNETH CHANG    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   For would-be Lasik patients, there is unfortunately no way to
compare the results of different surgeons. The gushing testimonial
of a friend may be misleading: Lasik's results are so good that the
majority of patients of any surgeon will be happy with the outcome.
</P>
<P>
   Many experts recommend asking surgeons, ``How many Lasik
procedures have you done?'' Some studies have indicated that, on
average, a surgeon's rate of complications drops over the course of
the first 300 or so Lasik procedures.
</P>
<P>
   But Dr. Marc Odrich, director of refractive surgery at Columbia
University and medical director of the laser manufacturer VISX,
says he believes newer flap-cutting keratomes have smoothed out the
learning curve.
</P>
<P>
   He suggests these questions for Lasik surgeons:
</P>
<P>
   _ What is the ``enhancement'' rate, that is, what percentage of
patients require a second surgery to fine-tune the prescription?
``I think that tells you how careful they are with the initial
work-up and the refraction they are getting,'' Odrich said.
</P>
<P>
   _ What percentage of people do you turn away? ``If the answer is
almost nobody, that would give me concern,'' Odrich said. ``I think
that's the hardest part of the procedure: the judgment. There are
lots of patients who are better off not having the surgery.''
Conditions that could rule out patients include thin corneas, past
herpes infections in the eyes, diabetes and unrealistic
expectations.
</P>
<P>
   _ For people over 40, do you recommend monovision? With
monovision, one eye is left somewhat nearsighted, postponing or
eliminating the need for reading glasses. If so, ask the doctor if
a trial with contact lenses is offered.
</P>
<P>
   _ What complications have you had and how have they turned out?
There are two ways that a doctor can avoid complications. ``No. 1
is you're lying,'' Odrich said, ``and way No. 2 is you've stopped
operating.'' What is more telling is how the surgeon handled the
complications.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
