<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NATIONOFLONERS-1100(2Takes)-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WE DON'T JOIN CLUBS OR MIX WITH NEIGHBORS AND SOCIETY IS SUFFERING
FOR IT
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 By LIZ STEVENS 
 c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Lo, the ironies of our postmodern culture.
</P>
<P>
   If the Internet is ostensibly igniting new communities,
cellphones are making us easier to reach and home officing is
keeping us closer to our loved ones, then why are we so lonely?
</P>
<P>
   OK, maybe you're not exactly lonely. But if you're an average
American, you're not nearly as connected to the people around you
as your parents or grandparents were, according to a new book.
</P>
<P>
   You don't vote as regularly.
</P>
<P>
   You don't join clubs as much.
</P>
<P>
   You don't entertain at home as often.
</P>
<P>
   Chances are, you spend more time each week watching ``Friends''
than making them.
</P>
<P>
   Sounding a little more familiar?
</P>
<P>
   According to Harvard public policy Professor Robert Putnam, not
only are all of the above statements true, but they also threaten
the very well-being of American society.
</P>
<P>
   Putnam's book, ``Bowling Alone: The Collapse and Revival of
American Community,'' assembles a century's worth of research to
reveal just how disconnected we've become from our communities, our
neighbors and even our friends. The professor argues that ``social
capital'' _ the bonds between people _ is as important to a
productive society as an educated work force and efficient
factories. That is, the more we volunteer together, socialize
together and stand up for causes together, the more we learn to
trust one another and build strong civic foundations.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, television, mobility, computers and economics, as
well as changes in family structure and age, have all contributed
to the growing gulf between individuals in the United States,
Putnam contends. As a result, Americans, especially younger
generations, now suffer from what he terms ``civic malaise.''
</P>
<P>
   Since ``Bowling Alone's'' debut in June, Putnam has crisscrossed
the country, speaking to TV and radio audiences and drawing
impressive crowds at public appearances _ 800 in Greensboro, N.C.;
1,000 in Manchester, N.H.; 500 in Hartford, Conn. His research has
undeniably hit a nerve.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some guy in Montana and a woman from Pennsylvania said the
same thing,'' notes Putnam during a phone interview. `` `Professor,
you've described exactly my life. My mom was active and I would
love to be active, but I don't seem to be able to find the time or
ways to do that.' Or `My dad was active in the Moose Club, but I
don't want to belong to a funny hat organization.'''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Putnam's theory of disengagement first struck a chord in 1995,
when he published an article in the little-known Journal of
Democracy. (The title of the paper, and now the book, refers to the
fact that participation in league bowling decreased by more than 40
percent between 1980 and 1993, while individuals bowling increased
by 10 percent). The mainstream media somehow caught wind, and, as
Putnam writes, ``a deluge struck.'' The professor was invited to
Camp David by President Clinton and profiled in People magazine.
</P>
<P>
   Why? Putnam believes that he had ``unwittingly articulated an
unease that had already begun to form in the minds of many ordinary
Americans,'' he writes.
</P>
<P>
   But the critics were at his heels, too. ``People said, `You
forgot about soccer leagues or reading groups or self-help
groups,''' Putnam recalls. So he went back to the data, looking for
evidence. ``To my shock,'' he says, he found that the original
article actually ``underestimated'' the extent to which Americans
have become disconnected.
</P>
<P>
   The disengagement that Putnam reveals ``is typical of what
sociologists are alarmed about in a post-modern society,'' notes
Howard Kurtz, a professor of sociology and criminal justice at
Oklahoma City University. ``We don't have the local soda shop
anymore where the kids hang out,'' he says. ``Today, people go to
the mall and consume.''
</P>
<P>
   Kurtz's own experience echoes Putnam's findings. When his
children were in school, he socialized with their friends' parents,
but his interactions outside of that were limited.
</P>
<P>
   ``I talk to a lot of people who just don't know anybody,'' he
says. ``I've lived in this house for the past five years, and the
gentleman across the street from me passed away, and I didn't even
know his name.''
</P>
<P>
   Kurtz attributes some of the disconnectedness to an increased
rationality among Americans. When making decisions about where we
live, how many children to have or whether to invite a stranger to
dinner, we use our heads more than our hearts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's say you see a neighborhood kid who is doing something he
shouldn't be doing,'' Kurtz says. ``In the past you would have
said, `Hey, quit doing that.' Now, you think, `I better not say
anything to the boy because his parents might sue me,' or `The
police are supposed to take care of that.'''
</P>
<P>
   The popularity of a show like ``Friends,'' he suggests, may be
due to our yearning for the kinds of deep, emotional bonds that the
characters seem to have _ the kind Americans take less and less
time to develop these days, according to Putnam.
</P>
<P>
   Cindy Crain is a glaring exception. Sort of. Since moving to
Fort Worth in 1988, Crain has flexed her civic muscle almost
ceaselessly in local and national organizations. Ten years ago, at
age 27, she was the youngest member of the local League of Women
Voters and eventually became its president. She recently quit her
job as the city of Fort Worth Web master to start her own business
and work part time for Councilman Clyde Picht.
</P>
<P>
   But despite her exhaustive public involvement, Crain can't
remember the last time she chatted with her neighbors. If she
wanted to go shopping on the weekend, she admits, she wouldn't know
who to call.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have no strong relationships,'' Crain says. ``Probably
because as a working mother there are so many social hours in a day
and you choose.''
</P>
<P>
   MORE
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
