<HEADER>
A8446 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-FALLTV-NOBUZZ-TEX     07-31 1279
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FALLTV-NOBUZZ-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FALL TV: WHERE DID OUR BUZZ GO?
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 By KEN PARISH PERKINS 
 c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA, Calif. _ If anything can be gleaned from the recently
concluded broadcast network/press mating dance, where networks,
studios, producers and stars pumped every new project as the next
groundbreaking phenomenon, it's that the promotion departments of
the big four networks have their work cut out for them.
</P>
<P>
   Buzz concerning the upcoming fall season will have to be
manufactured because for the first time in a long time the buzz is
about the lack of it. Of the 30 or so pilots screened during the
12-day network portion of the Critics Press Tour, only NBC's
``Ed,'' a whimsical, lighthearted male take on ``Providence,'' and
``Gilmore Girls,'' a disarmingly effective drama about a
mother-daughter relationship slated for the WB, showed enough
promise that they may, at some point anyway, turn into solid
dramas.
</P>
<P>
   Bette Midler's ``Bette,'' on CBS, Andre Braugher's ``Gideon's
Crossing'' and Geena Davis' ``The Geena Davis Show,'' both on ABC,
and a remake of ``The Fugitive'' (CBS), starring former ``Wings''
star Tim Daly, arrived as the most-discussed series only to lose
steam quickly after the pilots were deemed less than spectacular.
</P>
<P>
   Braugher's ``Gideon's Crossing,'' featuring the Emmy-winning
actor as a devoted doctor at a teaching hospital, ``looked''
gorgeous and so wanted to prove its unconventionality that it
opened with a nearly three-minute conversation between a doctor and
patient, the camera remaining tightly on their faces.
</P>
<P>
   So high-minded is ``Gideon's Crossing'' that viewers will be
asked to sit and ``listen'' to what this series has to say, which
often hinges on medicine as a kind of spiritually edifying
profession. That's ambitious and refreshing.
</P>
<P>
   But ``Gideon's Crossing,'' featuring a nice variety of new
faces, is so thoughtful and quiet, and moves at such a snail's pace
that viewers conditioned to the shoot-from-the-hip style of ``ER''
may very well abandon it by the 30-minute mark. Not by reaching for
the remote, but by dozing off.
</P>
<P>
   Just as lethargic was Davis' sitcom about a career woman who
falls for a widower and his two kids. Peter Horton
(''thirtysomething'') is the dad, and plays him as though he's got
a gun at his back.
</P>
<P>
   At least Davis had a pilot. Michael Richards, the first
``Seinfeld'' star to return to weekly TV, and John Goodman
(''Roseanne''), met with critics but came empty-handed.
</P>
<P>
   Richards' sitcom, ``The Michael Richards Show'' on NBC, about a
bumbling detective named Vic, is being retooled, which is never a
good sign. He became defensive when a reporter brought up the
infamous big-star disaster _ Nathan Lane's ``Encore! Encore!'' _
and spent most of the night at a post-press-conference party
pleading his case to reporters.
</P>
<P>
   Goodman, who is so uncomfortable with interviews that all he did
was grunt, let his producers talk for him. They didn't say much,
except that they are still trying to find a title for the series,
let alone figure out how they will approach the star's character,
who is a gay man trying to patch things up with his son. (He was
married at some point.)
</P>
<P>
   Another sign of trouble is the continued decline of David E.
Kelley (''Ally McBeal,'' ``The Practice''), who, after giving us
the dreadful, unfocused ``Snoops'' last season, could have his
second consecutive bomb. ``Boston Public,'' a Fox series that
explores the work lives of teachers, is far more over-the-top than
the usual thoughtful or intelligently quirky dramas Kelley
develops.
</P>
<P>
   There are some nice touches _ it is, after all, Kelley _ but
critics lashed out at the writer/producer in uncharacteristic
fashion, wondering why he decided to take the easy way out by
portraying a school as a war zone.
</P>
<P>
   In the episode we screened, a teacher sick of being bullied by
students fires a gun in class; the principal, played by Chi
McBride, slams a student into a locker; and another teacher spends
most of the episode running up and down the halls, screaming that
she can no longer take the profession.
</P>
<P>
   Kelley dismissed every notion that he was relying on stereotypes
to make his case, and grew downright angry when it was pointed out
that he spent his Boston years in private schools before going to
Princeton.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's ridiculous to think that I have no knowledge
whatsoever of public schools,'' Kelley said afterward. ``Should I
only be allowed to write about the law?'' (The next day, students
from a Chicago area high school filmed for the documentary series
``American High'' called the pilot ``kinda stupid.'')
</P>
<P>
   ``Boston Public'' wasn't the only series to stir controversy.
The pilot of ``The District,'' a CBS series starring Craig T.
Nelson as a newly hired police commissioner of Washington, D.C.,
focused on the commissioner wiping the city clean of incompetent or
corrupt black officials.
</P>
<P>
   The pilot prompted a heated exchange between producers and a
black reporter that didn't stop until black actress Lynne Thigpen
nearly leaped out of her seat to scream, ``You cannot ask every
black actor or every writer to write icons _ to write only
representations of the black community!''
</P>
<P>
   The reporter agreed, but said that neither should television
constantly ask writers to make African-Americans the villains.
</P>
<P>
   Nelson, who had remained silent through it all, said: ``Geez, we
never got this kind of discussion about `Coach,' &UR; '' referring to
the sitcom about a football coach. ``I think it's going to be an
interesting year.''
</P>
<P>
   It should be. NBC's mid-September broadcast of the Summer
Olympics will push back the official start of the 2000-2001 season
to October, but expect some networks like UPN to debut some series
in August and September. Another oddity compared with years past is
that there's simply less new programming.
</P>
<P>
   With two movie nights, ``Monday Night Football'' and four hours
of ``Who Wants To Be a Millionaire,'' ABC had room for just 2 1/2
hours of new fare. Its Saturday night ``Thrillogy'' having failed,
NBC is resorting to movies. That means there are just 31 new shows
this fall on the six networks, down significantly from a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   Comedies are in short supply, which proves again that the sitcom
format is going through a serious drought, although David Alan
Grier could have a breakthrough with NBC's ``DAG,'' if the writing
improves. Grier, who plays a secret service agent guarding the
first lady (Delta Burke), was hilarious during his panel discussion
_ humor that, thus far, has not translated on screen.
</P>
<P>
   Additional episodes will reveal whether The WB's ``Gilmore
Girls,'' which has the makings of a terrific family series, has the
heart, prickly edges and good, frank writing that's evident in the
pilot. Having lost WGN's stable of stations, The WB is down in
audience numbers from last season and is now behind UPN in total
viewers.
</P>
<P>
   UPN's best bet is ``Girlfriends,'' a sassy, quickly paced comedy
about four black women.
</P>
<P>
   Which brought to mind ``Spike Girls,'' the drama about female
cops going undercover as beach volleyball players.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't bring myself to (B.S.) you,'' UPN president and CEO
Dean Valentine said, after trying to come up with a more diplomatic
answer. Finally, he said what many reporters were feeling about
much of what we'd seen.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was just bad.''
</P>
<P>
   (Ken Parish Perkins is TV critic for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. You can call him at (817) 390-7862, or e-mail:
kpperkins(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
