<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000731.0215 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-31 16:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8448 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l BC-NATIONOFLONERS-2ndTak     07-31 1047
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NATIONOFLONERS-2ndTake-TEX </SLUG>
 
 UNDATED: and you choose. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   And more and more Americans are choosing to remain uninvolved,
Putnam argues. Venerable national clubs and organizations such as
the Lions, Masons, PTA, NAACP, American Legion and the American
Association of University Women have been bleeding membership since
their peaks (most often before 1960).
</P>
<P>
   The Rotary Club of Fort Worth _ the third-largest Rotary Club in
the world _ has managed to buck the trend: The club is down only 38
members since its peak membership of 735 in 1989-1990. But that's
changing. A 10 percent drop in membership annually is average for
most Rotary clubs, says the Fort Worth club's executive director,
Neva Williams.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rotary the world over is declining in membership,'' Williams
acknowledges. ``It's a real issue, and everybody is trying to find
the right key to work.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   No one factor has caused Americans to disengage, but Putnam sees
the main culprit as this: The postwar generations are simply less
community-oriented than their parents and grandparents. They're
more materialistic, less patriotic, more cynical and less
politically interested, according to the mountains of data that
Putnam researched.
</P>
<P>
   ``Part of it is the experience of living through the great
national challenge of (World War II). That formed the grandparents
in a way that none of us has ever been exposed to,'' says Putnam.
War is obviously not a solution, he stresses, ``but we do need to
find some, I think, moral equivalent of that _ some challenge that
younger generations will feel unites us.''
</P>
<P>
   The generations are divided by more than wartime experience.
Kids today have to deal with questions of sexuality, drugs and
careers much sooner than their parents did, notes Joyce Williams,
chairman of the department of sociology and social work at Texas
Woman's University in Denton. ``Because of exposure to the media,
the Internet and movies, young people are more sophisticated.''
</P>
<P>
   And probably more cynical. They're certainly less trusting, the
research shows.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to teach kids how to not trust strangers for their own
protection,'' Williams adds, ``but on a certain level, we teach
them not to trust anybody because we want them to survive.''
</P>
<P>
   Of her grown children, both in their 20s, Neva Williams says,
``They have a different feel than my generation did. School spirit
was nothing to them and to me it was everything. ... Outside of
work, they're not as involved (in the community).''
</P>
<P>
   Neva Williams, who thrived on the interactions dorm life
provided during her college years, was surprised to find that ``the
big thing'' for her daughter's generation was to room alone _ and,
if possible, not in the dorm.
</P>
<P>
   And what of our physical surroundings? Is it possible that strip
malls and freeways have contributed to civic disengagement and
social isolation? Putnam allows that metropolitan sprawl is a
factor, but other cultural observers are far more adamant.
</P>
<P>
   ``As I see it, the central issue is that we have turned
virtually every town in America into a place that is no longer
worth caring about,'' says James Howard Kunstler, the author of
1996's ``Home From Nowhere.'' Kunstler has for nearly a decade been
one of the most outspoken critics of suburban development. In his
opinion, the insidious effects of ugliness can't be underestimated.
</P>
<P>
   In Kunstler's utopia, stately architecture would replace the big
box aesthetics of Wal-Mart and Target. Wide sidewalks, public
transportation and mixed-use developments would encourage people to
leave their cars behind. And the rebirth of the public space would
inspire citizens to reclaim their civic voice.
</P>
<P>
   ``This thing we call the public realm is also the physical
container of our civic life,'' Kunstler stresses. ``It is the
dwelling places of our community life ... and when you degrade it
and turn it into a universal car slum, you injure and degrade the
quality of our collective civic life.''
</P>
<P>
   TWU's Williams believes Putnam may be overstating the extent of
disengagement. Like some of Putnam's strongest critics, she
suggests that the professor's findings may be too focused on the
lifestyles of white, middle-class and upper-middle-class
individuals.
</P>
<P>
   ``Demographic changes in the population are probably more
important than he made them out to be,'' she says. ``With the
influx of Southeast Asians and continual growth and migrations of
the Latino population, we're just more culturally diverse, and it's
hard sometimes to build common bridges across those kinds of
differences.''
</P>
<P>
   Crain is less optimistic. She recently traveled as part of a
U.S. State Department delegation to Skopje, Macedonia, to aid the
process of democratization and was asked by members of the local
women's union about voter turnout in Fort Worth. So she told them.
In the May school-board and crime-district election, less than 5
percent of eligible voters went to the polls.
</P>
<P>
   The women were horrified, says Crain, who thinks she knows why
so few citizens showed interest.
</P>
<P>
   ``People think, `I'm not hungry, I'm not angry, my quality of
life is not threatened, so my participation is irrelevant,''' she
says. ``We're a consumer society, and until something impinges on
our ability to freely consume, we'll stay apathetic.''
</P>
<P>
   Putnam did discover one positive trend that goes against the
grain. The research seems to show that, in the 1990s, teens and
people in their early 20s volunteered substantially more than in
generations past. He's planning a national summit for later this
year, Old Guard Meets Vanguard, as an opportunity for civic-minded
young leaders to connect with and learn from older generations. His
Web site, www.BowlingAlone.com, provides a forum for what Putnam
hopes will evolve into a national debate about re-engaging the
American public.
</P>
<P>
   ``At this point, my role is to be sounding an alarm and say to
people, `This isn't your problem, it's our problem (as a society),'
'' he says. ``There are enormous strengths in this country. It's
not that we don't have problems, but there is a lot of really
creative thought going on about how to fix this, and I'm learning
myself.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
