<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-31 16:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8449 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r k BC-WRIGHT-COLUMN-TEX     07-31 0849
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WRIGHT-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOW IMPORTANT IS THAT NO. 2 SPOT?
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 By JIM WRIGHT 
 c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's a funny thing about vice presidential nominations. Hardly
any politician professes to want the office; yet few have ever
turned it down when it's actually offered.
</P>
<P>
   George W. Bush's nod to Richard Cheney is a case in point. So,
quite possibly, will be Vice President Al Gore's selection of a
running mate. Don't be surprised if it, too, produces someone who's
indicated previously that he had no interest in the job.
</P>
<P>
   Often the vice presidential selection is part of an effort to
balance the ticket for broader voter appeal. Bush's teaming up with
Cheney offers no geographic diversity, but it does provide an
otherwise missing dimension of Washington experience.
</P>
<P>
   In that, it's reminiscent of Bill Clinton's choosing Al Gore, or
Jimmy Carter's picking then-Sen. Walter Mondale. Mondale of
Minnesota did bring a Northern balance to the ticket headed by a
Southern governor.
</P>
<P>
   The Bush-Cheney combination offers American voters two Texas
oilmen. What it adds to Bush's self-description as a
``compassionate conservative'' is a heavy emphasis on the latter
word.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody could doubt Cheney's credentials as a thoroughgoing
conservative. His opposition to clean-air and clean-water
legislation offers a clue, his closing of military hospitals
another.
</P>
<P>
   Cheney has opposed even the mildest forms of gun control, such
as bans on armor-piercing bullets or imported plastic handguns that
foil metal detectors.
</P>
<P>
   He has voted against Head Start, the Equal Rights Amendment,
college assistance grants _ even against childhood inoculations. He
wants to abolish the Education Department. In recession years, he
opposed extending unemployment compensation.
</P>
<P>
   Dick Cheney is no moderate.
</P>
<P>
   If Bush were trying to attract moderates, an obvious choice
would have been Sen. John McCain. Bush seems more comfortable with
Cheney, who reassures the right wing.
</P>
<P>
   Still, we shouldn't give the selection and its ideological bent
too much credence in predicting the election's outcome. Franklin D.
Roosevelt was overwhelmingly elected four times, picking three vice
presidents with practically nothing in common. Where might we find
three more disparate personalities than John Nance Garner, Henry
Wallace and Harry Truman?
</P>
<P>
   Historically, vice presidential nominees have had very little
impact on presidential elections. Only once in modern times has a
vice presidential choice probably made a crucial difference in the
results.
</P>
<P>
   That was in 1960, when John Kennedy's selection of Lyndon B.
Johnson arguably brought Texas and enough other Southern states
into the Democratic column to capture the prize in that close
contest.
</P>
<P>
   There are several instances when the losing vice presidential
nominee seemed better known and more popular than the winner
(Sargent Shriver vs. Spiro Agnew in 1972, for example, or Lloyd
Bentsen vs. Dan Quayle in 1988.) Voters were focused on the top of
the ticket. They wanted Richard Nixon instead of George McGovern,
George Bush instead of Michael Dukakis.
</P>
<P>
   So just how important is the vice presidency, or the person who
occupies it? Only as important as the president wants it to be?
Garner, after serving as vice president, said the job wasn't worth
``a bucket of warm spit.'' Johnson, while in that office, once told
me that he considered being in the House or Senate a much more
effective and desirable position.
</P>
<P>
   When business interests implored William McKinley to embrace
Theodore Roosevelt as his vice presidential nominee, it wasn't to
magnify Roosevelt's influence; it was to get the popular young
trustbuster out of their hair as governor of New York. The vice
presidency seemed a harmless post to chain him to.
</P>
<P>
   In 1960, news people asked President Eisenhower to name one
prominent national accomplishment of his vice president, Richard
Nixon, during their eight years in office. The old general replied,
with what seemed like uncharacteristic tactlessness, that if they'd
give him a week he might think of something.
</P>
<P>
   Then why all the flap about who gets the nod? Just how important
is the vice presidential choice? Important enough to stop and
reflect that we might be electing a president without realizing
that we are.
</P>
<P>
   Five men in the 20th century (Theodore Roosevelt, Calvin
Coolidge, Harry Truman, Lyndon Johnson and Gerald Ford) became
president simply by being vice president when a presidential
vacancy occurred.
</P>
<P>
   Try to imagine how differently history might have played out if
Roosevelt had died with Garner or Wallace, instead of Truman, in
the No. 2 spot. It staggers the mind.
</P>
<P>
   Vice presidents are important, not because they affect elections
but because they could affect history.
</P>
<P>
   (Jim Wright of Fort Worth is a former speaker of the U.S. House
of Representatives. You can write him at P.O. Box 1413, Fort Worth,
TX 76101, or at j.wright(at)tcu.edu. Visit the Star-Telegram's
online services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
