<HEADER>
A8453 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-WRESTLING-LEAGUES03-C     07-31 1842
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WRESTLING-LEAGUES03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Future wrestling stars pay dues in 'indie' rings
 &HT;    By Andrew Chow
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ The leagues carry ominous-sounding names: Outlaw.
Hardcore. Violent.
</P>
<P>
   The performers' names sound even worse: Filthy the Clown.
Reckless Youth. Suicide Solution.
</P>
<P>
   And almost weekly somewhere in southwest Ohio, you can find them
in local gymnasiums, VFW halls and National Guard armories taking
punches, jumping off ring posts, sometimes even rubbing their
opponent's head on ropes laced with barbed wire.
</P>
<P>
   All the while dreaming of one day becoming the next pro
wrestling superstar.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll never give up,'' said Phil ``Mr. Saturday Night'' Mamula
of Dayton, who wrestles with Unified Championship Wrestling, a
loose association of local wrestlers who put on shows. ``But it's
the same odds that an inner-city kid has of making it to the NBA.''
</P>
<P>
   Welcome to the world of independent wrestling, a world of big
dreams and little money. For fans, ``indie'' wrestling is an
inexpensive, immediate alternative to professional wrestling
organizations such as the World Wrestling Federation and World
Championship Wrestling.
</P>
<P>
   ``The independents are where all the big stars are coming
from,'' said J.L. Thrush, a former performer with Unified
Championship Wrestling. ``Like in the old days, you'd claw and
crawl your way up to the feds (major wrestling federations). It
takes a lot to get there.''
</P>
<P>
   During the past five years, indie wrestling has taken off here
and elsewhere, growing with the popularity of professional
wrestling. And almost every weekend, hundreds of local spectators
pay about $10 to watch choreographed matches between their favorite
stars. Some performers are a pale reflection of their pro wrestling
counterparts; others, backed by years of training and practice,
come very close to measuring up.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like the fighting,'' said a smiling 8-year-old Jacqueline
Wilkinson, who accompanied her uncle to a recent match at Piqua's
National Guard armory. ``But my mom and dad told me it's not
real.''
</P>
<P>
   The action may be orchestrated, but the dreams are real.
</P>
<P>
   ``In five years, I hope to be with one of the major wrestling
organizations ... on a national level with people who don't just do
this as a hobby,'' said Conley Stanley, a 23-year-old man who
performs as ``The Future'' Logan Caine.
</P>
<P>
   Pro wrestling is big business. Industry leader WWF recently
reported fourth-quarter income of almost $13 million, thanks to
merchandising, live events and cable TV shows that draw millions of
viewers several times each week.
</P>
<P>
   The independent scene is much different, organized mainly by
die-hard fans who take it upon themselves to find local talent,
venues and promotional opportunities.
</P>
<P>
   ``Locally, we have a good, strong fan base,'' Mamula said. ``We
draw a crowd of 250 to 300 regularly, guaranteed, for every show.
I've seen as many as 3,000 at one show. It's all about how much
time you have to prepare and promote the show.''
</P>
<P>
   In Thrush's view, only a handful of wrestlers have what it takes
to make it to the top. Two Ohio candidates are Stanley and Chris
Spradlin.
</P>
<P>
   ``Both of them have hearts for the sport,'' Thrush said. ``It's
their talent _ their charisma, how they wrestle, the whole package.
If you don't have that, you won't amount to anything.''
</P>
<P>
   By day, Stanley is a mild-mannered clerk in a downtown Dayton
law office.
</P>
<P>
   By night, perhaps 11 times a month, Stanley dons a black
metallic spandex singlet and becomes the alter-ego local fans know
as ``The Future'' Logan Caine.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes I feel like Superman,'' said Stanley, as he prepped
for a show. ``I go from my day job, where I'm the low guy on the
totem pole, to the wrestling ring, where I'm the center of
attention.''
</P>
<P>
   Stanley knows first-hand what it takes to make it big. His big
brother, Al Sarven, is WWF star Al Snow, whose gimmick had him
taking orders from a severed mannequin head.
</P>
<P>
   Stanley ``is following in his big brother's footsteps,'' said
his mother, Alvada Stanley. ``Early on, Con could tell you the
stats of any wrestler you wanted to know.''
</P>
<P>
   The brothers collected wrestling magazines and were avid fans of
wrestling on TV. As he grew older, Stanley played football and was
active in organized wrestling and Muse Machine, an arts awareness
organization. He talked with his father about becoming a pro
wrestler before breaking the news to his mother.
</P>
<P>
   ``Trust me, I tried to discourage him,'' she said. ``But no
matter what I said, he was going to follow his heart to be a
wrestler. He has this natural ability to entertain.''
</P>
<P>
   Success in a wrestling career will be a struggle, she added,
``but I feel he's got the talent to go into one of the
federations.'' For now, Stanley is one of about 15 performers who
wrestle for Heartland Wrestling Association, a Cincinnati group
formed five years ago by former pro wrestler Les Thatcher. In
addition to organizing matches, Heartland runs a a six-month
training camp for aspiring wrestlers.
</P>
<P>
   Dubbed ``Les Thatcher's Main Event Pro Wrestling Camp,'' the
camp is held in Heartland's gym in Cincinnati and offers supervised
training four days a week. The cost is $2,500. Students from around
the country and even Europe have completed their initial training
at the camp. This year, Heartland entered into a development
contract with the WCW, meaning the professional league will send
prospective talent to Thatcher's school for training.
</P>
<P>
   Over five years, the school has averaged about 50 students a
year, half of whom are from the greater Cincinnati and Dayton
areas, said Marty Adams, who in addition to working with Heartland
co-hosts a radio show Wednesday evenings.
</P>
<P>
   This year, enrollment has doubled, thanks to the WCW contract
and national exposure on MTV's ``True Life'' documentary series and
ABC's newsmagazine ``20/20 Downtown.''
</P>
<P>
   ``In six months they get just the basics,'' Adams said. ``It
takes years and years and years of finding the right gimmick and
developing the right mike skills to get them to the level of
someone like (WWF star) Stone Cold Steve Austin.''
</P>
<P>
   Sarven, for example, worked the indie circuit for about 12 years
before being discovered by Extreme Championship Wrestling and the
WWF, Adams said.
</P>
<P>
   Such success is the exception.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anything is possible, but the odds of that happening _ you
might as well go play the lotto,'' Adams said, noting a rising
number of wannabe pros. ``It's a very tough business to break into
nowadays.''
</P>
<P>
   Wrestling's popularity has brought critics, as well, who see a
tendency toward more and more violent extremes and worry about the
influence it might have on children. The May 1999 death of pro
wrestler Owen Hart, 34, who fell to his death during a wrestling
show, also focused media attention on the sport.
</P>
<P>
   Spradlin now primarily wrestles under the name Chris Hero,
having caught criticism and ridicule, as well as national
attention, with his first name, Wifebeater.
</P>
<P>
   Spradlin, 20, changed his name when a women's group in Wisconsin
raised the issue after seeing ``Wifebeater'' on a promotional ad.
Spradlin said the name was not intended to advocate domestic
violence, that it was derived from the white tank top undershirts,
sometimes called ``wifebeaters,'' he wears as his trademark.
</P>
<P>
   After the Wisconsin match, however, the name was the talk of
such TV shows as ABC's ``Politically Incorrect'' with Bill Maher
and MTV's ``The Tom Green Show.''
</P>
<P>
   Spradlin's mother, Mary Lou, concedes she never cared much for
the Wifebeater name.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said to Chris, you're going to get a lot of static with
that,'' she said. ``But I loved (the attention). Just that little
bit of adversity led to untold coverage nationwide.''
</P>
<P>
   The attention has taken Spradlin around the country, garnering
him a spot with controversial rap group Insane Clown Posse on its
coast-to-coast ``Juggalo'' wrestling tour. Earlier this year,
Spradlin took his act overseas, where he taped several shows for a
German TV wrestling program.
</P>
<P>
   Today, Spradlin performs primarily in and around the Midwest,
most recently in Pittsburgh, Cincinnati and Louisville.
</P>
<P>
   His mom remembers accompanying her son on trips with his Boy
Scout group, including one outing to a pro wrestling show when
Spradlin was about 8.
</P>
<P>
   ``He just loved it,'' she said. ``We met several of the
wrestlers, and he spoke to them personally. I think that's where
the impetus was.''
</P>
<P>
   After graduating from high school in 1998, Spradlin spent $2,500
for training at a renowned wrestling camp in Florida.
</P>
<P>
   He loves his sport.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's nothing you can compare it to _ telling a story
through your actions,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of it gets bad press and deserves it,'' he added, ``like
the groups in New Jersey that use weed wackers on people's
stomachs. That's just really bizarre. I didn't pay $2,500 to do
that.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, stunts that intentionally aim to cause bleeding injuries
_ known as ``extreme'' or ``hardcore'' wrestling _ have sometimes
gotten top billing on the local indie circuit as well.
</P>
<P>
   The need for shock value has driven some performers to land on
tacks, broken glass and tables _ stunts both Spradlin and Stanley
say they just don't understand.
</P>
<P>
   ``That stuff hurts. I don't do any of that,'' Stanley said. ``To
make someone buy your match, you don't have to cut yourself.''
</P>
<P>
   The extreme wrestling audience ``wants to see entertainment.
Wrestling is secondary,'' Adams said. ``There has to be a line
drawn, especially with kids not having proper training and trying
to do these kinds of things. That's the worry.''
</P>
<P>
   Many wrestlers say they are keenly aware of the influence they
have on children.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is what makes it possible _ fans and kids,'' said
wrestler T.J. Powers, 40, as he signed autographs for eager young
fans at a recent show. Powers, his wife and their five children
live in Las Vegas.
</P>
<P>
   Powers, part of the ``High Rollers'' indie wrestling tag-team,
said the business ``has gotten crazier'' since he began performing
18 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``When it comes down to the independents, it's a whole different
world,'' Powers said. ``You might have to travel five, six hours to
make little or nothing.''
</P>
<P>
   Promoters, too, stand to gain little from local indie shows,
which can cost between $1,500 and $2,000 to put on, Adams said.
Ticket prices are typically between $5 and $10, with attendance
ranging from 50 to as many as 700, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Indie wrestlers, meanwhile, are usually paid between $25 and
$75.
</P>
<P>
   ``On the independent scene, if you're running the operation
right, you have to pay insurance and a state (athletic) commission
fee, and have your own professional ring and truck,'' Adams said.
``A lot of shows, by the time all your expenses are paid, you're
left with only a couple hundred dollars.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't be in it for the money,'' he continued. ``It's a
labor of love for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
