<SLUG> BC-WRESTLING-GRAPEVINE03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Veteran wrestling announcer dies
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sad news hit the professional wrestling community on past Friday
when long-time announcer Gordon Solie was found dead in his New
Port Richey, Fla., home. Solie, 71, died of brain cancer.
</P>
<P>
   For thousands of wrestling fans in Florida and Georgia, Solie
was the voice of professional wrestling. He was the lead announcer
for Championship Wrestling from Florida from 1960-87, and Georgia
Championship Wrestling from 1980 until it became World Championship
Wrestling in 1993. It was at Georgia Championship Wrestling that
Solie's career took off as the show was telecast throughout the
United States on Ted Turner's superstation TBS.
</P>
<P>
   Solie was know for his scratchy voice and vivid descriptions of
the mayhem in the ring. But it was that scratchy voice, the result
of many years of smoking. Smoking put an end to Solie's career in
1993 after he underwent surgery for throat cancer.
</P>
<P>
   The World Wrestling Federation continues to beat down World
Championship Wrestling. In WCW's backyard _ Atlanta _ the WWF will
have a larger crowd for Monday's ``Raw is War'' than WCW had for a
recent ``Nitro.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
