<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-31 16:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8462 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u k BC-CVN-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      07-31 1003
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CVN-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
BACK TO THE FUTURE &HT;    By MARIANNE MEANS
 &HT;    c.2000 Hearst Newspapers
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ The coronation of Gov. George W. Bush marks the
triumphant return to power here of the traditional mainstream
Republican establishment that was banished by Ronald Reagan's
ideologically driven troops 20 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   This is a younger, southwestern branch of the old eastern elite
that was dominated by Wall Street barons, Ivy League
internationalists and the well-bred GOP country club set where
Bush's father, the former president, and grandfather, a Connecticut
senator, had their political roots. And it is still full of former
Reagan backers, but they are now more practical than they
originally were. And not as noisy.
</P>
<P>
   The convention redirects the party away from the divisive social
issues and anti-government fervor of Reagan's tenure toward
familiar conservative economic policy that protects the interests
of the rich without terrifying the rest of the country.
Conversations with Reaganite delegates indicate they are supporting
Bush not out of devotion but out of a practical feeling that he
might actually win. The GOP has backed off the demand that
diversity die and that everyone fit into a single mold dictated by
the far right. We are back to pragmatism and compromise, thank
goodness. It is the only way to govern.
</P>
<P>
   The Reagan era, in which governing seemed an afterthought, is
over.
</P>
<P>
   The old Repugblican establishment barely exists on the Eastern
seaboard any more. The likes of New York Gov. Nelson Rockefeller
are ghosts of the past. GOP strength has shifted to the South and
West, where Bush is a perfect fit for the new GOP, a son of the
elite reborn in the new region, speaking a fresh tongue but filled
with the old values and a respect for big money and limited
government.
</P>
<P>
   Nancy Reagan will be the guest of honor at a social event here
Tuesday but she will not deliver an emotional speech to cheering
delegates as she did at Bob Dole's 1996 convention, which was still
controlled by Reagan lieutenants. Mike Deaver, a Reagan White House
adviser, was quoted as saying she decided to leave her ailing
89-year-old husband to come to Philadelphia because she felt it
would be ``one of the last chances to keep the Reagan prairie fire
alive.''
</P>
<P>
   For the former first lady, it is too little too late. The fire
has gone out. There will be no Patrick Buchanan or Pat Robertson at
Bush's convention to stir up right-wing passions over so-called
``cultural wars'' against working women, ethnic minorities, gays,
immigrants and people who think they lead decent lives without
waving a Bible. Religious right followers still have enough
influence to force Bush to stick to the intolerant anti-abortion
position Reagan imposed on the party in 1980 as well as the newer
anti-gay stand. But that's about all they are getting here.
</P>
<P>
   Bush learned from his father's mistakes in losing his 1992
re-election bid and is imitating on the right President Clinton's
successful restructuring over the past eight years of a Democratic
Party that had moved too far to the left. Revenge is sweet,
particularly when you can bug the opposition with its own tactics.
It means putting a pretty face on a very conservative agenda. It
also means no controversy and a world of generalities.
</P>
<P>
   Bush claims to be a ``different kind of Republican.'' The
difference, however, is between himself and Reagan, not himself and
the Republican establishment that nurtured the elder Bushes. It is
a difference in style and emphasis more than one of conservative
outlook. The selection of former Secretary of Defense Dick Cheney
exposed the right-wing core of a campaign that Bush is trying to
sell as one of reasonable moderation. Cheney, remember, incredibly
declared in 1994 in the face of the financial chaos in the health
care industry that ``there is no health crisis'' in America.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, Bush adopted the ``different kind'' line from Clinton,
who hid behind it during his own 1992 campaign. And Clinton
recognized the steal. ``That's the message isn't it?`` he scoffed
recently. ``Blur, blur, blur.'' It takes one to know one.
</P>
<P>
   The convention's pollyanna atmosphere is so bland, however, that
there is a great deal of talk about the declining importance of
this quadrennial event. It is meant to introduce Bush to all those
voters who haven't been paying attention to the campaign thus far.
And first impressions are indeed important.
</P>
<P>
   But he is bathed in such a rosy glow that we cannot really know
who he is, beyond the fact that he's not Reagan.
</P>
<P>
   For Republicans eager to take back the White House, that is
enough. But the rest of us will still be left to wonder whether he
is just pulling a fast one.
</P>
<P>
   For the moment, Bush's ploy is smart politics. A dull convention
is a good convention from the nominee's point of view.
</P>
<P>
   But it drives the media nuts. The absence of news is not
wonderful for television ratings and newspaper sales. Heck, the
paid commericals being put out by both Democrats and Republicans
are more interesting than the convention speeches.
</P>
<P>
   So is this the last convention hurrah? Not since 1968 has a
convention had a good floor battle worth watching. In recent
decades the presidential nominees have been obvious long before the
delegates gathered.
</P>
<P>
   But there's still a purpose for the gathering. It's an
opportunity for like-minded political souls to commune with one
another, to rub elbows with their leaders and to feel a sense of
involvement in the coming crusade.
</P>
<P>
   A week is clearly becoming too long a stretch for this sort of
political socializing, however. Perhaps two days would suffice. One
day to review the platform and another to review the two
candidates. Maybe broadcast television, which has limited its
coverage to one hour each night, would rediscover the charms of
political discourse if there weren't so much of it. In this case,
less might be more.
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
