<SLUG> BC-SCI-TONSILS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A NEW ALTERNATIVE TO TONSILLECTOMIES: SHRINK, DON'T CUT
</HEADLINE>
   (Science Times) 
 By ANDREW POLLACK   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   It is no longer routine, as it was in the 1950s, for children to
have their tonsils removed to prevent persistent infections. But
for the estimated 500,000 Americans who still do undergo
tonsillectomies each year, one thing has not changed: The procedure
is a painful one that leaves people with difficulty swallowing for
up to two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Somnus Medical Technologies, a small medical device company
in Sunnyvale, Calif., has won Food and Drug Administration approval
for an alternative to tonsillectomy it claims will be less painful
and allow for a quicker recovery. The idea is to shrink the tonsils
rather than cut them out.
</P>
<P>
   Experts caution that the technique is still highly experimental
and not likely to be widely adopted until more testing is done.
</P>
<P>
   Tonsillectomies hurt because they leave a raw surface exposed
after the tonsils are cut out. A small percentage of patients
suffer from dehydration, because they cannot swallow for days, or
from postoperative bleeding. While newer techniques, like use of a
laser instead of a knife, have been developed for removing tonsils,
they have not done much to reduce pain or recovery time because
they still leave a surface exposed.
</P>
<P>
   Somnus' technique involves inserting tiny needle electrodes into
the tonsils to deliver radio frequency energy. The energy burns the
tissue in a controlled way, killing cells and causing the tonsils
to gradually shrink from within.
</P>
<P>
   This minimizes pain and bleeding, the company said. The
operation, which takes less than an hour, can be done under local
anesthesia, whereas tonsillectomies are often performed under
general anesthesia.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've done this procedure and people have gone back to work the
next morning, which is unheard of for a tonsillectomy,'' said Dr.
Lionel M. Nelson, an ear, nose and throat doctor in San Jose,
Calif., who is the medical director of Somnus. ``I had one guy eat
a sandwich a couple of hours after I did it.''
</P>
<P>
   The procedure is not totally painless. Susan Holden, an
administrative assistant in San Jose who had the procedure
performed in late 1998, said it felt afterward as if she had strep
throat, with dry mouth and pain in talking or eating certain foods.
But she said the swollen tonsils she frequently endured before the
operation had not come back.
</P>
<P>
   Some doctors express caution.
</P>
<P>
   The procedure has been tested only on adults, not children, who
account for about four-fifths of tonsillectomies. The company is
planning trials on children, but for them, the procedure would be
performed under general anesthesia, eliminating one of the
advantages.
</P>
<P>
   Even for adults, only Nelson has tried the technique, and he has
performed it on 12 people. He has published one paper covering nine
patients who were followed after the operation for 12 weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to follow up patients for several years to see if the
tonsils are going to regrow or not,'' said Dr. Nira Goldstein,
assistant professor of otolaryngology at the State University of
New York Downstate Medical Center in Brooklyn. She is a member of a
committee dealing with tonsils for the American Academy of
Otolaryngology-Head and Neck Surgery.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, since Somnoplasty, as it is called, does not
completely remove the tonsils, it might not be applicable as a
treatment for recurrent tonsil infections. It would be used mainly
for people whose breathing is obstructed by enlarged tonsils,
Nelson said.
</P>
<P>
   Such patients now roughly equal the number of patients who
undergo tonsillectomies to treat infections. While antibiotics have
reduced the problem of infections, there is growing awareness of
sleep apnea, a condition in which breathing is interrupted numerous
times at night, putting a strain on the heart and making it
difficult to get a restful night's sleep.
</P>
<P>
   Somnoplasty is already used to treat sleep apnea and snoring by
shrinking the tongue, nasal tissue or the soft palate. But
Goldstein and others said since there was an extra risk in using
the procedure on tonsils because they are very close to the carotid
artery, which carries blood to the brain. Doctors must be certain
the vibrations caused by the radio frequencies will not harm that
artery.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Lawrence W.C. Tom, an otolaryngologist at Children's
Hospital of Philadelphia, who is also a member of the academy
tonsil panel, said Nelson's scientific study was ``very limited.''
But he added, ``If it works as they say it does, it has a lot of
potential.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
