<SLUG> BC-CVN-POVERTY-1100(2Takes)-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRESIDENTIAL CAMPAIGN MEANS LITTLE TO RESIDENTS OF BORDER COLONIAS
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 By JAY ROOT 
 c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAREDO, Texas _ For the nation's political establishment, these
are exciting times. The nominating conventions are under way. Vice
presidential candidates are being picked and vetted. Ads are
hitting the airwaves.
</P>
<P>
   But here in dusty Ranchitos 359, an impoverished ``colonia'' on
Texas 359 outside Laredo, convention fever has not taken hold.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, as far as Dolores Estrada is concerned, Philadelphia and
the Republican National Convention might as well be on the moon.
She is equally unimpressed with the Democrats, despite their recent
claims that Gov. George W. Bush is to blame for the decades-old,
grinding poverty here.
</P>
<P>
   Estrada, 40, is more worried about her dwindling supply of
water, which she stores in four 55-gallon drums in front of her
house and refills every few days _ or whenever she can afford to
pay someone a few dollars to deliver it.
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether she thought that a Bush presidency would bring
progress, Estrada said that she was unaware that he was even
running.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't know that until you told me just now,'' said Estrada,
whose children endure 105-degree temperatures without so much as a
fan. They have no electricity, no car. Their toilet is a foul and
sweltering closet that sits over a hole in the ground outside.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is (Bush) going to come here?'' she asked, expressing interest
only long enough to get in a word about her pressing needs.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Bush wants to be president, and he wants us to vote for
him,'' she said, ``he needs to bring us water.''
</P>
<P>
   It is not an uncommon refrain. Running water and sewer service
are a luxury in the state's 1,500 or so ``colonias,'' which,
translated from Spanish, means ``colony,'' or subdivision, and has
come to denote squalor.
</P>
<P>
   The 400,000 people who live in them are among the poorest
residents in the United States, virtually untouched by the
prosperity that is touted on the campaign trail and heralded on
Wall Street.
</P>
<P>
   Though major improvements have been made in the ``colonias''
over the last decade, progress has been slow in coming, and those
who live here suffer high rates of preventable disease,
particularly hepatitis, tuberculosis and a plethora of intestinal
maladies.
</P>
<P>
   While much of the nation enjoys historically low unemployment
rates, poverty and joblessness continue to run extremely high along
the border. Of the 10 most poverty-stricken counties in the United
States, four are located on the Texas-Mexico border.
</P>
<P>
   Sister Rosemary Welsh, a Laredo-based nun who is one of Webb
County's best-known advocates for ``colonia'' residents, said
elected leaders display a stunning lack of urgency to clean up the
pockets of poverty.
</P>
<P>
   ``You wonder why it just doesn't get done,'' said Welsh, who
oversees a clinic that provides care for ``colonia'' residents.
``You'd really think that we'd have water everywhere in the United
States.''
</P>
<P>
   Democrats have used the wretched conditions along the border to
tar Bush, saying he should have done more to help ``colonia''
residents. The Democratic National Committee recently put out a
video on the ``colonias,'' complete with run-down shacks and
shabbily clad children. It is entitled, ``This Is George W. Bush's
Texas.''
</P>
<P>
   But state Rep. Henry Cuellar, D-Laredo, who has authored some of
the legislation addressing ``colonia'' issues, said the attacks are
unfair.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not something you can just turn on a faucet and say it's
taken care of,'' Cuellar said. ``I've been dealing with the
``colonias'' for a long, long, long time, and I know the depth of
the problem is just the tremendous amount of dollars that we need
to address the issue.''
</P>
<P>
   SLOW PROGRESS: ``Colonias'' began to form during the 1950s, when
agriculture began to boom at the same time farmers and ranchers
largely quit providing housing to their laborers.
</P>
<P>
   For those seeking the dream of home ownership and escape from
high rents, a small lot could be purchased for about $50 down and
low monthly payments _ albeit with extremely high interest rates.
</P>
<P>
   Many were told by developers that water and sewer service would
be coming soon. It never happened.
</P>
<P>
   Now tens of thousands of residents must haul their own water,
sometimes from wells 10 or 20 miles away. Homes usually have
outdoor privies for bathrooms and cesspools to treat sewage, though
some residents can afford septic tanks, usually crudely made.
</P>
<P>
   State and local governments have stepped in with laws to halt
the growth of ``colonias''_ mostly by making it illegal to sell
small plots of land without water and sewer service _ and by
providing money to bring in water and septic lines.
</P>
<P>
   But the projects aren't cheap, and they don't get done
overnight. Among the challenges are obtaining easements on
``colonia'' roads, which the residents own. Turf battles between
city and county officials have also caused delays.
</P>
<P>
   It has been nearly 10 years since a group of ``colonias'' in
Laredo's Webb County was designated as eligible for state water and
wastewater funding, said Webb County Commissioner Judith Gutierrez,
whose district includes many of the ``colonias.''
</P>
<P>
   She expects state water board officials to finally approve next
month a $23 million project to bring service to 15 ``colonias'' _ a
cost of about $18,000 per household.
</P>
<P>
   Still, even when the work is completed, half of the 48
``colonias'' in Webb County _ collectively containing about 17,000
people _ will still not have water or sewer service, officials
said.
</P>
<P>
   For those not included in the project, Gutierrez said, funding
is ``not even on the radar screen right now.''
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, the number of ``colonia'' residents continues
to grow, as many of them are driven from booming Laredo by
ever-rising housing costs.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've noticed that when we take house-to-house surveys from
one year to the next, the population is always different,'' said
Juan Vargas, Webb County's economic development director. ``And it
is always an increase.''
</P>
<P>
   MORE nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
