<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-31 16:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8487 &Cx1f; tab-z
u a BC-VOTER-INITIATIVES-ADV     07-31 1537
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VOTER-INITIATIVES-ADV31-NEWHOUSE </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
$ADV31  
 SIGNATURE DRIVES TRIP OVER LEGAL HURDLES 
</HEADLINE>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: This article from NEWHOUSE NEWS SERVICE for
MONDAY, July 31, is available as a ``separate-buy.'' For
information about purchasing the article, contact DEBRA WEYDERT of
The New York Times Syndicate at 1-732-390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697;
e-mail: weyded nytimes.com.) 
 By TOM BRAZAITIS  
 c.2000 Newhouse News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Convinced that their elected representatives are in the pockets
of special interests, Americans in the 24 states that allow ballot
initiatives are trying to take the law into their own hands on
issues from bilingual education to universal health care.
</P>
<P>
   But the very legislators the citizen-lawmakers are trying to
circumvent are making it difficult for them to get their issues on
the ballot.
</P>
<P>
   Petition drives in various states have come up short of
legislative requirements.
</P>
<P>
   In Ohio, the state's League of Women Voters recently abandoned a
two-year effort for a constitutional amendment that would prevent
politicians from gerrymandering congressional and Ohio General
Assembly districts.
</P>
<P>
   The League had marshaled a coalition of 14 organizations,
including the Ohio AFL-CIO, to gather the 335,000 signatures needed
for the amendment that would have given citizens instead of
politicians the power to draw new district lines after the 2000
Census.
</P>
<P>
   Failing to collect enough signatures last year, the League
redoubled its efforts to put the issue on the ballot this November.
</P>
<P>
   But the League quietly halted its initiative in June, saying
``it became apparent that the amount of funding needed to collect a
sufficient number of signatures and then to conduct a media
campaign for its passage was not forthcoming.''
</P>
<P>
   Ohio's relatively stringent requirements for ballot initiatives
almost necessitate the hiring of paid signature gatherers at a rate
of up to $1.25 per valid signature.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a citizen's right to get something on the ballot, yet
it's so difficult to do it. How much of a right is it?'' asked Anne
Smead, past president of the League.
</P>
<P>
   The AFL-CIO reached the same conclusion on two other ballot
questions it had pledged to work for: whether women should be paid
the same as men for equal work and whether patients should be
allowed to sue HMOs. It was a decision that AFL-CIO spokesman Kent
Darr described as sad.
</P>
<P>
   ``We looked at the money we thought we would have to spend and
the money we thought would be spent against us, and we bailed
out,'' Darr said.
</P>
<P>
   In the state of Washington, health-care providers hoping to put
a proposal for universal health care on the ballot collected as
many as 12,000 signatures a week in the final stages of their drive
but fell short of the necessary 220,000 signatures. They are
starting again from scratch.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the legislature is in the pocket of the insurance
companies, doctors are in a bad place, and patients are in a bad
place,'' said Dr. Stuart Bramhall, a psychiatrist spearheading the
universal-care initiative.
</P>
<P>
   In Massachusetts, proponents of a patients' bill of rights
managed to get the needed signatures, only to have the Legislature
respond by passing a watered-down version of the reforms. Dr.
Timothy McCall, head of the committee promoting the initiative,
which remains on the November ballot, said the Legislature's
last-minute bill weakened support for the initiative and may
confuse voters.
</P>
<P>
   Initiative proponents occasionally find a sugar daddy.
California and Michigan have school voucher issues on the Nov. 7
ballot, thanks to well-heeled backers: venture capitalist Timothy
Draper in California and Amway President Dick Devos in Michigan.
</P>
<P>
   Draper supports the proposal to offer $4,000 of tax money per
child attending private or parochial school in California,
regardless of parental income. Devos is backing a Michigan
initiative that would provide vouchers for students in high schools
with graduation rates of less than 67 percent.
</P>
<P>
   With the National Education Association and American Federation
of Teachers campaigning against the initiatives in both states, the
California contest may cost more than $50 million, about evenly
divided between those for and those against the measure. Greg
McNeilly, a spokesman for the Michigan initiative, said his side
will spend at least $5 million but still expects to be outspent by
opponents.
</P>
<P>
   Money isn't the only obstacle for sponsors of ballot
initiatives.
</P>
<P>
   Dane Waters, president of the Washington-based, nonpartisan
Initiative and Referendum Institute, cites a number of ``assaults''
on the initiative process:
</P>
<P>
   -- Several states have passed legislation requiring all petition
circulators to be residents of the state and, in some cases, to be
registered voters themselves. This prevents trained teams of paid
circulators from coming into a state to gather signatures.
</P>
<P>
   -- Missouri shortened the period for gathering signatures
without reducing the number that are required to get an issue on
the ballot.
</P>
<P>
   -- Wyoming added a requirement that a percentage of signatures
must be gathered from voters in at least two-thirds of Wyoming
counties. Because many Wyoming counties are sparsely populated,
this adds to the burden of getting the required number of
signatures.
</P>
<P>
   -- Nebraska passed legislation stipulating that a constitutional
amendment must be approved in two separate elections.
</P>
<P>
   -- Oregon increased by 50 percent the percentage of signatures
required to get a constitutional amendment on the ballot.
</P>
<P>
   Petitioners sometimes hurt their own cause by drafting poorly
written initiatives. Courts have halted a number of initiative
efforts because of faulty wording and, in one case, extraneous
markings on petition sheets.
</P>
<P>
   In July the Colorado Supreme Court knocked off the ballot a
measure to limit bilingual education because the measure's title
and summary gave the impression that parents would have a choice
between bilingual classes and English immersion classes when, in
fact, most children would have been required to join mainstream
classes after a year of bilingual education, the Denver Rocky
Mountain News reported.
</P>
<P>
   Also in July, the Arkansas Supreme Court invalidated a proposal
to abolish property taxes, ruling that the amendment was misleading
and confusing. The decision came two days after proponents turned
in 103,000 signatures, 30,000 more than necessary to put the issue
on the ballot, the Associated Press reported.
</P>
<P>
   Waters' Initiative and Referendum Institute cited a
Massachusetts Supreme Court ruling that ``any extraneous marking on
a petition sheet whatsoever -- even a couple of dots or accidental
pen scratches -- invalidates every signature on that sheet.''
</P>
<P>
   Courts also have limited the places where petitions can be
circulated. The Washington Supreme Court, for instance, upheld the
practice of making grocery stores off limits to petition
circulators.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest obstacle for petitioners is the U.S. Postal
Service's June 1998 ban on circulating petitions outside post
offices, Waters said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The ban makes collecting signatures in less-populated counties
difficult, if not impossible,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The institute is trying to persuade the U.S. Postal Service to
repeal the ban but anticipates having to challenge the restriction
in court.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're seeing a diminishing number of initiatives reaching the
ballot because of the increasing difficulty,'' Waters said. ``We're
not seeing as many mom and pop initiatives. With the trend toward
more signatures being required in less time and other restrictions,
only well-financed special interests can use the initiative
process.''
</P>
<P>
   (OPTIONAL TRIM FOLLOWS)
</P>
<P>
   Ohio Secretary of State J. Kenneth Blackwell is sympathetic to
petitioners' complaints but says ``there is bound to be tension
between direct democracy and the republican form of government.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Politicians, Democrats and Republicans, are quick to remind
you that ours is a representative form of government,'' he said.
``As a defensive move, most legislative bodies tend to ratchet up
the criteria and the requirements in order to protect their turf.''
</P>
<P>
   Blackwell said elected officials have a right to set the bar
relatively high for ballot initiatives, but they sometimes
overreach. Limiting signature gatherers to residents or even
registered voters in a state is one restriction that goes over the
line in Blackwell's view, because only registered voters in the
state can legally sign the petitions and vote on the issue.
</P>
<P>
   Blackwell said elected officials would be wise to deal with the
reasons the public has lost faith in them, particularly by being
willing to confront controversial issues. ``Elected leaders are
timid in their leadership,'' he said. ``They don't want to make
hard choices or tough decisions. It is relatively easy for the
legislative bodies to put a referendum on the ballot and duck the
tough issues.''
</P>
<P>
   (Tom Brazaitis is a staff writer for The Plain Dealer of
Cleveland)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
