<DOCNO> NYT20000731.0232 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-31 16:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8493 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r p BC-CVN-POVERTY-2ndTake-T     07-31 1029
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CVN-POVERTY-2ndTake-TEX </SLUG>
 
 LAREDO, Texas: always an increase.'' 
<TEXT>
<P>
   `LIES. PURE LIES': If all goes as planned, the 15 thirsty
``colonias'' targeted in the Webb County project will have water in
three years, maybe four, county planning officials say.
</P>
<P>
   One of them is Ranchitos 359, where Estrada lives.
</P>
<P>
   Another is ``colonia'' San Carlos, where 81-year-old Marcelina
Alvarez has been living in a plywood and particle-board home,
without plumbing, for the last 13 years.
</P>
<P>
   A first-generation American born near Robstown, Alvarez retired
from her job canning asparagus years ago, and now lives with a
granddaughter and five great-grandchildren. She is lucky to have an
indoor toilet _ fed by water buckets _ which empties into a
cesspool outside. The family pays $100 to have it cleaned twice a
year.
</P>
<P>
   Some have that unpleasant task performed every month, but
Alvarez calls for the vacuum truck only once every six months,
which could explain the overpowering stench wafting up from the
haphazardly covered, underground container.
</P>
<P>
   Alvarez has heard that water service is coming, but she has
heard that before. She said she'll believe it when she sees it.
</P>
<P>
   ``They come saying they're going to do this, they're going to do
that,'' she said, her voice trailing off as she brushed flies from
her face and ants off the table. A granddaughter, Irasema Sanchez,
chimed in: ``They're lies. Pure lies.''
</P>
<P>
   HEALTH WORRIES BRING CHANGE: Dirty water and poor sanitation are
blamed for the high incidence of infectious disease along the
border.
</P>
<P>
   According to a Texas Health Department study, between 10 percent
and 48 percent of ``colonia'' children ages 1-12 have been infected
with hepatitis A, a disease affecting the liver. It is often
transmitted through water contaminated by human feces.
</P>
<P>
   Adult rates are much higher, officials say. An estimated 70
percent or more of the adults in the ``colonias'' of Webb County
have been infected, according to Rogelio Garcia, acting director of
the Laredo health department.
</P>
<P>
   Likewise, according to the State Health Department's Division of
Tuberculosis Control, a person living in a border county has twice
the chance of contracting TB compared with someone living elsewhere
in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``Until you see it, taste it, feel the grit in your teeth, I
don't think you can truly understand the kind of conditions of the
people who live here and try to survive and raise their children,''
said Dr. Maurice Click, a physician who has worked extensively in
Webb County's ``colonias'' and has advocated a more active state
response.
</P>
<P>
   A chief problem is that people build unsophisticated pit
latrines that tend to flood when it rains. So bacteria are washed
all across the ``colonias,'' causing disease that is often
transported to other cities and states by migrant workers, he said.
</P>
<P>
   LEGISLATIVE ACTION: The threat of disease migrating beyond the
border was one of the primary reasons for a series of legislative
actions that began in the late 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, $600 million in state, local and federal money has
been directed toward the ``colonias,'' mostly for providing water
and sewer service to residents there, state figures show. Estimates
for providing those services to all ``colonia'' residents range
from $1 billion to $2 billion, which doesn't include other
infrastructure needs such as roads, streetlights and trash service.
</P>
<P>
   In 10 years, 15,000 residents have been provided with both water
and sewer service, according to figures from the Texas Water
Development Board, which oversees the infrastructure projects.
About 80,000 residents have received either water or sewer service.
</P>
<P>
   Less clear is how many of the 400,000 ``colonia'' residents
currently have running water and sewer connections. The office of
the Texas secretary of state estimates that about 86 percent have
water and about 12 percent have sewer service, up from 77 percent
and 1 percent, respectively, in 1992. Various academic sources
report slightly lower rates of water service and slightly higher
rates of sewer service.
</P>
<P>
   Either way, most agree progress has been made, though not all
agree who should take the credit. Gutierrez, the Webb County
commissioner, said former Gov. Ann Richards was more directly
involved in helping ``colonias'' and faulted Bush for never
visiting one during his trips to South Texas and El Paso.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not the Texas George Bush talks about,'' she said.
``I've never seen him in the `colonias.'''
</P>
<P>
   She also complained that the ``colonia'' ombudsman for Webb
County _ one of six people assigned by the state to oversee
``colonia'' relief efforts _ was ineffective and unfamiliar with
the area. The ombudsman was recently fired, but the secretary of
state's office declined to say why.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, meanwhile, said he is proud of his record on ``colonias,''
and aides point to figures showing that most of the household water
hookups in the last decade have occurred since he took office in
1995.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a fantastic record. We'll have (hooked up) thousands
of people who heretofore had no water or sewer at their homes by
the time my administration is over,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   `LITTLE PEOPLE': The political sniping means little back in
Ranchitos las Lomas, off Highway 59 on the outskirts of Laredo.
Here no plans exist to bring water, let alone sewer service. It is
just too far from the water source, officials say.
</P>
<P>
   Most residents here pay 50 cents for 250 gallons of water that
is clean but not always odor-free. But Norma Martinez, a
36-year-old social worker, pays $5 to have it trucked to her house.
</P>
<P>
   The ``colonia'' has no stop signs or streetlights, and when it
rains, the school bus doesn't come, so her children must walk three
miles back home on a sheet of mud that sticks to their shoes and
clothes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think because we're far away, we're like an abandoned
`colonia' out here,'' she said. ``We're little people.''
</P>
<P>
   (Jay Root is Austin bureau chief for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. You can call him at (512) 476-4294, or e-mail:
jroot(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
