<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JUST-ONE-HAND-LIFEBEAT-NYTSF </SLUG>
 
 ONE HAND, ONE HEART
 ATTENTION EDITORS: This article is for use by clients of The New
York Times Syndicate's LIFEBEAT service. For more information about
purchasing this article as a ``separate-buy'' _ or becoming a
client of LIFEBEAT _ contact one of the New York Times Syndicate
sales representatives listed at the end of the text. 
 By MARY TAYLOR PREVITE 
 c.2000 New York Times 
 World rights 
<TEXT>
<P>
   I felt the screaming jolt, the split-second whine. Out in the
field behind the farmhouse, I was a curious child, too close to an
unsupervised, snarling buzz saw. One minute my left hand was tanned
brown from the Canadian summer, with slender fingers stained from
wild strawberries. One bump and one scream of the buzz saw later,
it was a bloody, mangled mess.
</P>
<P>
   That night Dr. Trefry cut it off. It was 1947. I was 14 years
old.
</P>
<P>
   I loathed my handless arm. For weeks I wouldn't even look at it
_ the monster arm that made me different. I tested out cans and
can'ts: Will boys like a 14-year-old girl with just one hand?
Braiding pigtails, playing the piano, tying shoes _ can I do it
with just one hand?
</P>
<P>
   I hated _ still hate _ the everyday game of ``let's pretend'':
people looking, looking twice, then pretending they didn't notice.
I wanted them to say, ``What happened to your hand?'' I wanted them
to make it ordinary.
</P>
<P>
   In a can-do family, my daddy saw me looking out at a world
defined by what I could not do. Daddy agonized. I was his youngest
daughter.
</P>
<P>
   He was braiding my pigtails, wrapping the ends in rubber bands
one day. ``Shall I tell you a secret, Mary, sweetheart?'' he asked.
``When Bertie first heard that you lost your hand, do you know what
he said to me?''
</P>
<P>
   I waited.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bertie told me, `Now Mary can't ride her bicycle.'''
</P>
<P>
   Bertie was my little brother, not yet 7. I suspected he was
eyeing my new British Raleigh with its hand-grip brakes.
</P>
<P>
   ``And do you know what I said to him?'' Daddy paused. ``I told
him, `Well, I don't know why not.'''
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know why not'': I tacked the words in my heart like a
banner. And not just the words, but his believing in me.
</P>
<P>
   Mother, who wouldn't let any Taylor hide behind the nonsense of
``I can't,'' enrolled me at the college up the street for Hammond
organ lessons. I would play the keyboards with one hand and two
feet. And excuses about not doing dishes? ``A Taylor never says `I
can't,''' she would remind me as she lined me up with the rest. And
then she sat me down and taught me to crochet.
</P>
<P>
   When I lost my hand, the preacher's wife hoped out loud that God
would grow it back. He didn't.
</P>
<P>
   But he gave me daily triumphs.
</P>
<P>
   Well, yes, I have I-wish-I-had-my-hand days. I hate
eat-while-standing refreshments of every kind. If my one hand holds
the saucer, what hand will bring the cup of coffee to my lips?
</P>
<P>
   I hate every bottle cap that I can't open with just one hand.
And necklaces that I can't latch with just one hand. And bracelets
that won't slip on.
</P>
<P>
   I've had nightmares. After I wrenched my good shoulder a while
ago, my ultimate nightmare awoke me with cold sweats: my one and
only hand immobilized. I have no spare. I shudder at what-if's:
What if I couldn't dress myself? Drive to work? Wipe my bottom?
Write? Or feed myself? The aching terror of being dependent haunts
me.
</P>
<P>
   But you know what? It was hard to beat the high of seeing my
daughter skipping to church in her Easter Sunday dress that I
sewed. Or setting a record at the auction with a quilted wall
hanging that I pieced.
</P>
<P>
   Somewhere deep inside, my cheering section shouts and stomps and
waves each time I do something someone thought I couldn't. When I
pinned my daughter's diapers. When I made the college volleyball
all-stars. When I tie my shoelaces. When I set my hair in curlers.
Small victories.
</P>
<P>
   Something cheers inside.
</P>
<P>
   (Mary Taylor Previte, 67, is a New Jersey assemblywoman and the
administrator of the Camden County Youth Center.)
</P>
<P>
   ---------------------------------------
</P>
