<HEADER>
A8496 &Cx1f; tab-z
u l BC-PETS-PSYCHOLOGY-LIFEB     07-31 1211
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PETS-PSYCHOLOGY-LIFEBEAT-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PETS THINK AND FEEL MORE THAN WE KNOW
</HEADLINE>
  ATTENTION EDITORS: This article is for use by clients of The New
York Times Syndicate's LIFEBEAT service. For more information about
purchasing this article as a ``separate-buy'' _ or becoming a
client of LIFEBEAT _ contact one of the New York Times Syndicate
sales representatives listed at the end of the text. 
 By TONI GARDNER  
 c.2000 Hearst Communications Inc.  
 World rights 
<TEXT>
<P>
   One of the joys of living with pets is catching a glimpse of
what makes them tick. What we learn about our pets from experts,
friends, and, especially, our own observations _ sometimes
surprises us but ultimately helps us take better care of them. With
long-running contact, however, we sometimes come to take our pets
for granted. That's when we may miss a clue to understanding pet
behavior. Here are some situations that deserve a closer look.
</P>
<P>
   To communicate with our pets we need to listen as well as talk
to them. Does a dog howl, for instance, from loneliness? A dog that
is isolated from its family, either canine or human, may indeed cry
out for company, just as wolves locate one another in the wild.
</P>
<P>
   With their heightened pack identity, beagles especially are
prone to plaintive howling when left alone. But some breeds, like
my schipperke, Momo, who is rarely left all alone, just can't
resist replying to other dogs' howling. It is another throwback to
their wolf heritage: The pack sings as one recreationally early in
the morning and in the evening to initiate the hunt. In Momo's
case, the daily one o'clock firehouse siren inspires him to warble
along and other neighborhood dogs often join in the vocalizing.
</P>
<P>
   One of the first signs of illness for any animal is loss of
appetite. But is your cat sick or just a finicky eater? If it turns
food away, make sure first that there isn't a health problem by
asking your vet. After that, look on food preference as a
potentially serious problem in itself.
</P>
<P>
   According to ``CatWatch,'' the newsletter of the Cornell
University Feline Health Center in Ithaca, N.Y., some cats would
rather starve than eat food they don't like, and preferences can be
set as early as six months. Kittens raised on a varied diet develop
democratic palates.
</P>
<P>
   Housebreaking dogs calls for the use of a crate, but is it
really true that dogs never soil their crate? Most animals try to
keep their sleeping area clean, but that doesn't mean you can count
on it. Puppies have to learn control, and they can't be expected to
wait for unreasonably long periods. A puppy should be taken outside
immediately after eating and drinking, and no adult dog should have
to wait longer than 20 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   No dog _ adult or puppy _ should be held in a crate for more
than four hours at a stretch. The crate should be large enough for
the dog to stand, turn around and lie down comfortably, but not so
large that there will be room set aside for eliminating.
</P>
<P>
   And when the dog is in the yard, how best to fence it in?
``Invisible,'' that is, electric- or sonar-producing fences, keep
the landscape clear and may cost less than traditional fencing.
Pain, however, is the tool. Even if, as some argue, the pain may be
mild, you must decide if you desire these conditions for your pet's
overall well-being.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the fences are rendered ineffectual when dogs dash
through them in hot pursuit of a squirrel or another dog, then
won't come back for fear of the shock that awaits them. If you
don't want to erect a wooden fence, try planting evergreens around
your property, then linking them with barely visible garden wire.
</P>
<P>
   Taking your dog with you on outings is fun, but the dog should
ride inside the cab if you drive a pickup truck. Sudden braking,
swerves or bumps in the road can send a dog flying out of the back
of the truck and airborne debris can also cause injury.
</P>
<P>
   ``If absolutely necessary,'' recommends Michael Kaufmann, the
American Humane Association's director of educational programs, in
Englewood, Colo., ``a dog can be put in a crate that is securely
fastened to the truck bed.'' Some states have laws against dogs
riding in the backs of trucks.
</P>
<P>
   For cats, outdoor adventures often include vigorous tree
climbing. Cats love to sink their claws into rough bark and shoot
straight up the trunk. Sometimes, though, they glue themselves to a
branch and refuse to come down. The reason is not that they're
afraid of the height, but that their anatomy is better suited to
ascent than descent.
</P>
<P>
   John Hermanson, associate professor of biomedical sciences at
Cornell University's College of Veterinary Medicine, in Ithaca,
N.Y., explains, ``Squirrels and some other arboreal mammals have
specialized capabilities that allow them to rotate their ankles
nearly 180 degrees while climbing head-first down the trunk of a
tree.'' Since cats don't have this ability, you may have to haul
out the ladder to help them down. You can try benign neglect first:
Cats often creep down by themselves without the stress of people
surrounding them.
</P>
<P>
   One situation fraught with tension is a dogfight. Even though
your dog may be on a leash, someone else's may not be. Or two dogs
might be playing seemingly peacefully in the park when_ without
warning _ a fight breaks out.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our first instinct _ to try to break up the fight by yelling
or grabbing our dogs _ is not the correct solution,'' warns Michael
Kaufmann of the AHA. In the intensity of the moment, your own dog
could inadvertently bite you; yelling only heightens the emotional
turmoil. Instead, drop your leash and pause.
</P>
<P>
   Most dogfights, however terrifying, last only seconds. But if a
small dog is being victimized or if the fight doesn't end promptly,
try spraying the dogs with a hose, swinging a big stick or throwing
clothing into the fray to intervene.
</P>
<P>
   Of all the inner workings of our pets, the one we may least
understand is the powerful, seemingly interpsychic connection
between them and us. Rupert Sheldrake examines the ways animals
tune in to our behavior in his book ``Dogs That Know When Their
Owners Are Coming Home'' (Crown; 1999; $25).
</P>
<P>
   According to Sheldrake, the bonds between our companion animals
and ourselves may be so strong that they create a ``morphic
field,'' a physical connection that enables them to locate us
across distances and to anticipate our actions even before we
consciously know them ourselves. The deeper our bonds, it seems,
the more we learn about the nature of life itself.
</P>
<P>
   (Toni Gardner is a contributing editor of ``Country Living''
magazine.)
</P>
<P>
   ---------------------------------------
</P>
