<HEADER>
A8499 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-BREASTCANCER-0801-COX     07-31 0365
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BREASTCANCER-0801-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    BREAST CANCER TREATMENTS LACKING FOR ELDERLY
 &HT;    By LARRY LIPMAN
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON - Women over 80 often do not get full treatment for
early stage breast cancer, according to a study released Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Women over 80 were 16 percent less likely than younger women to
be referred to a radiation oncologist upon the discovery of breast
cancer, the study said.
</P>
<P>
   In cases where a lumpectomy was performed _ conserving much of
the breast _ women over 80 were 3.4 times less likely to receive
follow-up radiation therapy, the study indicated.
</P>
<P>
   Women who do not receive radiation therapy after a lumpectomy
have a 40 percent chance of a cancer recurrence within 10 years,
the study said. Women at 80 have an average life expectancy of
slightly more than nine years.
</P>
<P>
   That means ``a good portion of them stand a chance of the cancer
coming back and it's much more difficult to treat'' a second time,
said Dr. Jeanne S. Mandelblatt, who led the study.
</P>
<P>
   The study of 718 female patients was conducted by the Lombardi
Cancer Center at Georgetown University Medical Center and included
researchers from 29 hospitals. It was financed by the federal
Agency for Healthcare Research and Quality and published in today's
(ITAL) Cancer (END ITALICS) journal.
</P>
<P>
   The study did not determine why older women receive less
aggressive treatment, but Mandelblatt said it may be because
``there are potentially some age biases in treatment. The
physicians may feel that older women don't expect to live long.''
</P>
<P>
   Another reason may be that physicians are uncertain what is the
best clinical treatment for older women because, until recently,
women over 80 have been excluded from clinical trials, she said.
</P>
<P>
   As in previous studies which have found a racial disparity in
treatment, this one found indications that black women seemed to be
less likely than white women to receive radiation after a
lumpectomy.
</P>
<P>
   On the web: Agency for Healthcare Research and Quality:
www.ahrq.gov
</P>
<P>
   Larry Lipman's e-mail address is larryl(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
