<HEADER>
A8502 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-TV-BETTEMIDLER-840(2T     07-31 0667
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-BETTEMIDLER-840(2Takes)-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BIG STAR, BIG FLOP? NOT IF BETTE HAS ANYTHING TO SAY ABOUT IT
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 By KEN PARISH PERKINS 
 c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA, Calif. _ Bette Midler was addressing journalists via
satellite from a vacation spot in Florence, Italy, when a
questioner referred to a guest star in Midler's new comedy series
as Nathan Lane. He meant Danny DeVito and apologized profusely for
the gaffe. Too late. Damage was done. Executive producer Jeffrey
Lane, sitting in a hotel ballroom here facing reporters, buried his
face in his hands while director Andrew D. Weyman simply rolled his
eyes.
</P>
<P>
   Midler looked befuddled and panicked, as though she'd somehow
been officially passed the mantle of The Big Star Jinx.
</P>
<P>
   Nathan Lane stands as the latest and greatest casualty in the
networks' pitiful record of unsuccessful television ventures
involving big-name stars, and it's apparent that Midler, a
self-proclaimed ``TV virgin,'' wants to stay as far away from that
vibe as humanly possible.
</P>
<P>
   No such luck. ``Bette'' is slated for an October premiere on
CBS, and like Nathan Lane's ``Encore! Encore!,'' which seemed
doomed from the start, this sitcom is already going through cast
changes. Lindsay Lohan, the young actress playing Midler's
daughter, is gone after her parents decided not to move their
family from New York City to Los Angeles, where the series will be
shot.
</P>
<P>
   During the critics press tour, CBS was able to screen a
rough-cut 22-minute pilot episode, which shows Midler in her
current career paradox _ an aging actress fighting a
youth-obsessed, male-dominated business that's heartless at its
core. Known for her extraordinary _ and seemingly boundless _
energy and effervescence, Midler is at her animated best, using her
gifts for physical comedy and quite the wicked tongue to rip at the
surface phoniness of Hollywood. She even disses cinematic peers
like Sally Field. (There's a scene where Midler promises to beat
her to a pulp.)
</P>
<P>
   Yet ``Bette,'' at least in its early form, is surprisingly thin
as a laugh-out-loud comedy.
</P>
<P>
   Jeffrey Lane says they will re-shoot some scenes, and Midler
appears sincere and passionate about making a sitcom that
challenges viewer expectations. But the series, which also stars
Kevin Dunn as Midler's understanding husband, Roy, and Joanna
Gleason as her agent and best bud, Connie, already looks
formula-driven, and like another misstep by a network that thinks
signing a big name to a sitcom deal means the work is done.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're well aware of the notion that big-name stars merely
parachute into a series and everything supposedly falls into place
from there,'' Lane says. ``I can assure you, that hasn't been the
case here.''
</P>
<P>
   Adds Midler: ``A lot of people came in and pitched very typical
sitcom situations. (The scripts) were a divorced mother with a
child struggling, a woman whose husband runs out on her and leaves
her holding the bag. The only person who really captured my voice
is Jeffrey Lane ... and when you can't do that, it makes it hard.
I've seen some who have tried.''
</P>
<P>
   Was she speaking of ``The Geena Davis Show,'' perhaps? Airing on
ABC, the series written around the Oscar winner offers the
well-worn premise of a fast-track career woman (Davis) who moves in
with a widower (Peter Horton) and his two children.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to dialogue that's about as irreverent as ``Full
House,'' Horton, in his first comedy, is as stiff as a metal door.
He told critics during the show's panel that he was uncomfortable
within the setup/punch line sitcom formula, which explains it, but
I can't image the viewing audience cutting an actor slack for
learning on the job. Davis is far more fluid, which helps, since
she is in nearly every frame of the pilot.
</P>
<P>
   But the romantic chemistry between the two is nonexistent, and
there's nothing particularly interesting about the series that will
keep viewers from turning elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   MORE nn
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got some things to do still,'' Davis says after her
panel, which got a polite reception from critics. Cast changes are
already under way.
</P>
<P>
   It's apparent that shows built around big-name stars are, from
the start, developed differently, and that's the problem. Instead
of beginning with an idea or premise and then working toward the
casting and the development of good scripts, networks often start
with an established star and work backward toward the idea.
</P>
<P>
   Networks continue to roll the dice on such productions because
the payoff could be huge, if successful. NBC did such a thing with
Bill Cosby in the '80s. Cosby had three straight series bombs
before ``The Cosby Show'' hit with audiences and saved a network's
fortunes.
</P>
<P>
   Aside from Davis, ABC is banking on Gabriel Byrne in the sitcom
``Madigan Men'' and Andre Braugher in the drama ``Gideon's
Crossing,'' about a dedicated doctor in a teaching hospital.
</P>
<P>
   ``All too often,'' says Garth Ancier, president of NBC
Entertainment, ``you have someone else who has been a star on
television returning to television, and the audience is just not
that excited about seeing them. And they would rather discover
their own stars in a new way or see people used in a different way.
And it's certainly an expensive way of getting attention. Because
generally in the case of Davis, you're putting up 22 episodes at
$200,000 an episode as guarantee to do business with that star. And
then you develop the show after that.''
</P>
<P>
   When it works, the network programmer and producer look like
geniuses; when it doesn't ...
</P>
<P>
   In ``Encore! Encore!,'' which featured Nathan Lane as a
world-famous Italian opera star who returned to the family vineyard
in Napa, Calif., to sulk after his career abruptly ended, Ancier
says, ``As talented as Nathan Lane and the cast were, there was a
fundamental flaw structurally in doing a show set in a vineyard in
Napa Valley. Boy, is it hard to tell stories in Napa County, for an
ex-opera star.''
</P>
<P>
   NBC might be having the same problems with Michael Richards, the
first ``Seinfeld'' star to return to television in series form. The
pilot for ``The Michael Richards Show,'' with Richards cast as a
modern-day bumbling detective, has already been sent back to the
lab for re-shooting. Talking with Richards, who is a producer on
the series, didn't clear up much.
</P>
<P>
   When someone compared his start with that of Nathan Lane,
Richards responded, and rather tersely, ``Can't see how that
compares to us. We know exactly what we're doing, where we're
headed.''
</P>
<P>
   That must have been a recent phenomenon, since NBC had nothing
to show critics except for a short trailer of Richards driving down
a Los Angeles street and bursting into loud song to drown out a car
horn that won't go off. That was it.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast, Midler is far ahead of the game. And she's
returning to the early tradition of some TV sitcoms in which stars
play themselves.
</P>
<P>
   ``I come from that tradition, actually,'' says Midler, who, as
in the show, has one teen-age daughter. ``I'm probably the last
person in show business who does. I mean, my age is right and I
remember all those people as being, you know, real lights in my
life when I was a kid. So, yeah, we're close to getting this thing
in pretty good shape.''
</P>
<P>
   Then there is ``Roseanne's'' John Goodman and his team of
producers. They have yet to come up with a title for his Fox
series, let alone how the basic concept will develop. It's about a
gay man and his son, but that's all we know since no pilot was
screened.
</P>
<P>
   Goodman, slumped between his two producers during a news
conference, gave little indication that he was awake, let alone
bursting with creative ideas over his first lead vehicle.
</P>
<P>
   Joking (at least one would hope), a producer finally asked the
crowd, ``Got any ideas?''
</P>
<P>
   (Ken Parish Perkins is TV critic for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. You can call him at (817) 390-7862, or e-mail him at
kpperkins(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
