<HEADER>
A8508 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a BC-SCI-AMERICAN-YOGA-2TA     07-31 0759
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-AMERICAN-YOGA-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AMERICAN INFLUENCES HELP REDEFINE PRACTICE OF YOGA 
</HEADLINE>
  (Science Times) 
 By ANN POWERS    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LENOX, Mass. _ Many of America's masters recently descended upon
the Kripalu Center for Yoga and Health here for a conference on
``The New American Yoga.''
</P>
<P>
   Virtually anyone who has bought a book or video, attended a
workshop, or unfurled a mat in a major studio would have recognized
someone here. This was as close to a summit meeting as yoga has
come.
</P>
<P>
   Erich Schiffmann of Los Angeles, the star of a best-selling yoga
video featuring Ali McGraw, declared the conference a ``power
spot.'' Sharon Gannon and David Life, the founders of the favored
rock star hangout, Jivamukti Yoga in Manhattan, came to teach and
stump for animal rights.
</P>
<P>
   Veterans like the Bay Area's Rama Jyoti Vernon mingled with
younger masters like Baron Baptiste, who teaches power yoga on
ESPN. Other yoga teaching stars included Rod Stryker, Don
Stapleton, Judith Lasater, Todd Norian and John Friend.
</P>
<P>
   The group represented the scope of approaches, from sweaty
``strong'' yoga to tension-melting restorative poses, that are
taking yoga beyond the confines of the counterculture to the
mainstream of American fitness. They came to stretch and breathe
with eager students in the weekend's daily classes, but more
important, they came to discover what their approaches had in
common, and how they might add up to a definition of American yoga.
</P>
<P>
   These leading lights had one thing in common: none were of
Indian descent. Most had studied with Indian masters, including the
now-elderly triumvirate of BKS Iyengar, K. Pattabhi Jois, and Sri
TKV Desikachar, whose principles of precision, heat and healing
still dominate the discipline. But as they devised their own
styles, the Americans mixed their knowledge with native experience
to create the wide-ranging approach that has caught on today.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the '60s and '70s, a number of swamis came to the U.S., and
there was an emphasis on the spiritual side of yoga,'' said Kathryn
Arnold, editor of Yoga Journal, the unofficial organ of American
yoga, in an interview during the conference. ``The philosophy was
more integrated into the asana practice,'' she said, referring to
posture. ``They've all gone away, basically, or they've really
aged. And there's been this inheritance of the yoga by the
Americans themselves. And so we are redefining it. ''
</P>
<P>
   Indian teachers still influence American yoga. Integral, the
school led by Swami Satchidananda from his ashram in Yogaville,
Va., has dozens of schools nationwide. Bikram Choudhury's hot yoga
technique is popular in Hollywood. Yet like American Buddhism, the
yoga shaped by Western-born teachers has its own attributes. Its
practical, world-friendly character is having an impact on
Americans who would never visit an ashram.
</P>
<P>
   Yoga Journal says that 12 million people practice hatha yoga,
the physical limb of a system that also includes ethics, breath
work and meditation. Instructors here have combined different
strains of Indian yoga to suit modern American tastes. Many have
been drawn by the athletic ashtanga-based styles that have become
popular here.
</P>
<P>
   Others prefer gentler therapeutic styles like Kripalu. Americans
are sticking to their yoga mats long after tae-bo videos have been
buried in the closet. Indeed, yoga is so popular that a group of
longtime leading practitioners, the Yoga Alliance, has formed to
explore criteria for certification.
</P>
<P>
   To say American yoga is just aerobics with chanting misses a
large reason for its popularity. For many, the practice is
spiritual, or at least psychological. Books like Schiffmann's
``Yoga: The Spirit and Practice of Moving Into Stillness'' are as
popular as old-fashioned self-help tomes. People who once turned to
therapy now seek inner peace from teachers who simultaneously help
them tone their abs.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a bifurcation in the psychotherapy world, as a result
of managed care in this country,'' said Stephen Cope, a Kripalu
teacher, psychotherapist and the author of ``Yoga and the Quest for
the True Self.'' ``You've got managed care, very focused on
medication, with short-term time limits on psychotherapy. Then you
have this whole stream of people, the so-called worried well, with
their spiritual quests, their desire to be fully alive, their
attempts to be in better relationships. Where are they taking that?
They're not taking it to psychotherapy any more, because they can't
afford it.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Americans use the yoga mat as a therapist's couch, and often, as
a church pew.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our culture really likes the physical stuff,'' said John
Abbott, the publisher of Yoga Journal. ``We're all ingrained from
the earliest age that it's good to do exercise. And then you find
this, wow, this is more than exercise. This is something about
living.''
</P>
<P>
   The ecumenical approach that so well serves American attitudes
is new in yoga. In the 1960s and 1970s, yoga practitioners came in
two varieties. Either they were health nuts at the YMCA,
uninterested in yogic philosophy, or they were serious disciples
who took Indian names, wore bright or white robes, and followed
gurus.
</P>
<P>
   But the guru paradigm has largely crashed and burned.
Communities like Kripalu, whose guru, Amrit Desai, left in scandal
in 1995 after 20 years, are having to reinvent themselves. Kripalu
has thrived as a self-defined post-guru community, training
hundreds of nonsectarian teachers per year. The model based around
a charismatic leader often led to egotism and corruption and
students fled disillusioned. In addition, many Americans grew wary
of adopting a culture that was not their own. ``Most of the major
ashrams did fall,'' said Sudhir Jonathan Foust, Kripalu's director
of curriculum. ``Maybe because of the sensitivity of these
particular cultures, they were the first to fall. But they weren't
the only ones. In the Catholic Church, in synagogues, in schools,
no question in government _ it's almost like our society won't
tolerate that structure any more. Which has set us up for this new
paradigm of experimentation.''
</P>
<P>
   As secular America has opened up to new notions of the inner
life, through therapeutic practices and New Age conjectures, the
seekers of the counterculture have been coming down to earth. These
two paths met in the middle in the physical practice of yoga,
especially as it was transmitted to today's leading teachers by
Indians like B.K.S. Iyengar.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were just coming out of the '60s change-your-consciousness
thing, and many of us were in our heads, and wanting to meditate,
and reach samadhi,'' said Patricia Walden, a renowned teacher and
longtime student of Iyengar, referring to enlightenment. ``Iyengar
was like, `Stand on your feet. Feel your feet.' He was so
practical. His famous quote was, `How can you know God if you don't
know your big toe?'''
</P>
<P>
   The major question for American yoga is how to reconnect God and
that big toe.
</P>
<P>
   The Kripalu conference often felt like a strictly religious
gathering, with chanting, meditation, and talks like Schiffmann's,
which extrapolated on basic Eastern ideas of nonduality, and
Gannon's, a discourse on the relationship between ahimsa, the Hindu
ethic of nonharming, and animal rights. The last question Foust
asked the gathered teachers, at a closing panel, was, ``Do you
believe enlightenment is possible?'' Everyone answered yes.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the teachers stood united in anti-sectarianism. ``There's
more of a cross-pollination of the practices,'' Abbott said. ``In
the Indian tradition, gurus have their yoga and only their yoga.
Here, there's good communication among teachers, and the students
feel comfortable going from one place to the other. That's very
American, I think.''
</P>
<P>
   Traditionalists may consider the turn away from ashrams and
gurus a caveat to the capitalist truism that whatever sells is
good. Friend addressed this accusation in his keynote speech,
standing up for eclecticism on the grounds that any spiritual
influence is better than none at all. Yet he pointed out that
teachers and students both needed to challenge themselves to go
deeper.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you wear a deity on your T-shirt or have one in your home,
maybe find out what it means,'' Friend joked, hinting at the
proliferation of blue-skinned Krishna prints on today's fashion
runways.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
