<HEADER>
A8524 &Cx1f; taf-z
s t BC-PRACTICAL-TRAVELER-$A     07-31 1214
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PRACTICAL-TRAVELER-$ADV06-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CRUISE SHIPS AND THE DISABLED 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Fla., Canada, Bahamas)   (For release Sunday, August 6)  
 By BETSY WADE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the spring of 1998, Tammy Stevens of Jacksonville, Fla., who
uses a wheelchair, booked a three-night cruise to the Bahamas
aboard Premier Cruises' Oceanic, a 35-year-old ship sailing out of
Port Canaveral. Although she said she was assured by her travel
agent and the line that her cabin aboard the Oceanic, also
identified as the Big Red Boat I, was wheelchair-accessible, she
found it was not.
</P>
<P>
   Stevens said she wrote Premier to complain and was given a
certificate for a 50 percent discount on a future cruise. After
that, she began to look for a lawyer. Her subsequent legal action
passed a watershed on June 11, when the U.S. Court of Appeals in
Atlanta ruled that the Americans With Disabilities Act applies to
``places of public accommodation'' aboard cruise ships, even
foreign-flagged cruise ships if they are in U.S. ports or waters.
</P>
<P>
   This marked the first court decision in which the provisions of
the disabilities civil rights act, which is just 10 years old, were
declared to apply to foreign-flag vessels owned by foreign
corporations. The only American-flagged ocean cruise ship, the
Independence, owned by American Hawaii Cruises, was declared a
``place of public accommodation'' under the act last year by a
court in Hawaii. The Justice Department says it has not received
complaints about ferries, lake and river vessels in the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   The Florida decision comes years, probably at least five, before
the Department of Transportation and the Department of Justice are
likely to complete any guidelines for accessibility on oceangoing
ships. On this basis, among others, Premier's lawyers are asking
for a rehearing by the 11th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals.
</P>
<P>
   ``The opinion as written,'' the Premier petition said, ``will
have a significant effect on virtually the entire cruise and
shipping industry, a major revenue source for the State of Florida
and the United States.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe the court has misinterpreted the ADA to apply to
vessels,'' said Gary E. Davidson, a lawyer for Premier in Miami.
</P>
<P>
   The lawyers on both sides acknowledge that the 3-0 ruling by a
panel of the appeals court is unlikely to be reheard, and it is
possible that Tammy Stevens vs. Premier Cruises may go to the
Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
   Wheelchair accessibility on cruise ships is a complex issue.
About the time Stevens took her cruise, a federal agency known as
the Access Board was forming an advisory committee to discuss what
sort of rule might be proposed. The committee includes
representatives of the cruise industry, and such consultations are
drawn out. The committee is scheduled to report to the Access Board
on Nov. 17. The board will then ponder a recommendation to the
Department of Transportation. After more public comment, a rule
would become final. If the pattern in other areas _ hotels, for
example _ is followed, ships entering service after a certain date
would have to meet the criteria right away and older ships would
get longer to make ``readily achievable'' adaptations.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Beatty, who calls himself project manager for the Access
Board, points out conflicts likely to impede proposed rules. Safety
laws for ships require ledges and sealable barriers to keep water
from flowing everywhere if the hull is pierced. No one wants to
reduce safety at sea, yet the difficulties for wheelchair users are
apparent when one notes that the formal name of the Access Board is
the Architectural Barriers and Transportation Compliance Committee.
Further, Beatty said, you could create a series of protective
devices that would be pointless if the boat heeled, as a sailboat
inevitably does and even a big cruise vessel sometimes may.
</P>
<P>
   Beatty and others note that market forces have brought improved
accessibility, mainly on new vessels, built with an awareness that
future customers are to be found among graying baby boomers.
Elevators, selected cabins with extra-wide entrance and toilet
doors, roll-in showers and closets with pull-down rods are found on
new ships. Older ships are hard to fix, and as the ADA unfolded in
the '90s, retrofitting proved the most difficult.
</P>
<P>
   The Oceanic, built in 1965, is an older ship. In her complaint,
Stevens said she saw an ad for a three-night cruise aboard the
Oceanic and decided to buy a cruise for her mother, herself and two
other family members for Mother's Day. She said in an interview she
was told there were four ``handicapped cabins,'' one of them
wheelchair accessible, and it was booked for Mother's Day. Stevens
shifted her date to get the cabin, and said she had to pay more
than the advertised starting price of $349 for it. The
accessibility was limited to a ramp over the ledge on the bathroom
door, she said, but the toilet was so close to the door that she
could not get to it in her wheelchair. She was forced to use a
bucket or have her guests lift her onto the commode, she said, and
bathe from a bucket or be lifted into and out of the shower.
</P>
<P>
   Stevens' lawyers, Jennifer L. Augspurger and Arlene Karin Kline
of Boca Raton, initially sued for deceptive practices under Florida
law and for an injunction under the federal disability law. The
Department of Justice supported a revised complaint. Officials
there and advocates for the disabled consider the facts in the case
appropriate for a court test of the applicability of the law.
</P>
<P>
   The 1998 complaint identified Premier as a Canadian corporation,
but Davidson said that the line was a Cayman Islands corporation
then, and is now a Bermuda corporation. The Big Red Boat I
continues to list itself as Bahamian, one of the more popular
``flags of convenience'' used by virtually all oceangoing cruise
vessels visiting the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Premier has been discussing the case with other companies and
the International Council of Cruise Lines, an association
representing 17 lines in the North American market. A spokeswoman
for this organization said no conclusion had been reached.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the National Transportation Safety Board recently
renewed efforts to get cruise ships to enhance their smoke
detectors so they emit a sound in the area where smoke is found. At
present, fire alarms register on the navigation bridge, and a
general alarm is sounded by an officer there. The safety board said
that in 1996 and 1997 fires the time elapsed led to six deaths and
77 injuries from smoke inhalation.
</P>
<P>
   In 1992, the International Convention for Safety of Life at Sea
required that smoke detectors be installed by 1997, but not that an
alarm sound in the area. In 1997, the safety board recommended the
change, to no effect, and an effort before an international body
earlier this year failed. Jim Hall, the safety board chairman, said
that the cruise companies had failed to deal in good faith with the
problem of cruise ship fires, which ``continue to occur with
troubling regularity.''
</P>
<P>
   The cruise line council said the sensitivity of the detectors
would lead to false alarms, and passengers might ignore a real
alarm. It said there were ``technical and operational drawbacks''
to the recommendations.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
