<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-31 17:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8526 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r k BC-NIGHT-CABBIE-HNS &LR;      07-31 1057
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NIGHT-CABBIE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     NIGHT CABBIE HEARS VIEWS ON EVERYTHING 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By THE NIGHT CABBIE  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ I've just turned up Powell when a young woman
flags me from the front of Max's. She's in her 30s and wears a long
white coat. Some man is standing to the side of her, talking, with
his hands in his pockets. I pull up and she turns from him and gets
right in. Where to, miss? I ask her. She looks at me and seems very
flustered.
</P>
<P>
   ``What in the hell did he think I looked like?'' she says. We
are still stopped. I look at her in the rearview. ```I'm just
standing there, minding my own business,'' she says, ``when this
guy comes right up to me and tells me he'll pay me $60'' for a sex
act.
</P>
<P>
   I don't say a word, but I shake my head side to side. Then she
tells me the hotel she wants to go to.
</P>
<P>
   I tell her I think it's an unfortunate incident. ``Do I look
like a hooker?'' she says. No, I tell her, but you were standing in
a spot where they are sometimes, particularly at this hour. ``This
is the first time that has ever happened to me in my life,'' she
says. We arrive at the place and she pays me. As she starts to
exit, I tell her, ``Miss, I'm not telling you this to ruin your
evening, but this hotel was once a house of prostitution _ around
1900. Or so the story goes.'' She doesn't say a word, gets out and
goes right in the door.
</P>
<P>
   There's one thing that's obvious when you're driving a taxi: I
hear views. On just about everything. This lets me question whether
my own thoughts have any merit. Some people are always unhappy.
Others are so happy all the time you think they're a little out of
it. Younger people are generally happier than older people. Women
seem to be happier than men. I see so many down-and-out souls and
wonder what keeps them going. I see severely handicapped people
living in the street and wonder what kind of society tolerates
that. I see people actually living on quarters and wonder how
that's possible. I put 240 hours a month on this job to pay my
bills, but I have a lot of energy. I see that a lot of society
doesn't. What if I run out of energy?
</P>
<P>
   It's been an exhausting morning. I head to my favorite gas
station before going in. If you think prices are high at your pump,
you should see what the cab companies charge us.
</P>
<P>
   I pull in and look for an open spot. I'm never the only cab
there. I yell out my pump number for the guy to turn it on and I
start thinking about how much I'm looking forward to going home to
rest. Suddenly this young man yells from the next pump over, ``Taxi
driver! Hey, taxi driver! I want to talk to you.'' He comes toward
me. He's wearing a red Pendleton shirt and scans the place as he
approaches.
</P>
<P>
   ``Taxi man,'' he says once he's by my cab, ``you know you're out
there on the streets at night with many strange people. You need
protection.'' I ask what kind of protection he's talking about. He
looks around, then opens his shirt. He points to this huge knife
still in his waistband. What's that? I ask him. He pulls it out and
gives it to me. I take it out of the sheath. It's about a
foot-and-a-half long with a saw blade and jagged teeth on one side
and a razor edge on the other. The handgrip has stainless steel
knuckles built in.
</P>
<P>
   He takes it back. ``They give you trouble,'' he says, then he
circles my gut with it. ``Or two slices, one on each side of the
neck, takes a man down. I want twenty for it.'' I take it back.
Sold, I tell him, and throw it on my front seat. I tell him it's
the type of knife Maximus needed in the arena in ``Gladiator.'' The
movie, you know? ``I haven't seen that one,'' he says. In an
instant, he's gone. I pay for the gas and exit. Later, I look
closely at the blade. It says, ``Frost Cutlery. Surgical Steel.''
Who knows where he got it? But it fits in my briefcase.
</P>
<P>
   I'm in the bus zone dropping three young men off at the Mitchell
Brothers when a young dancer there comes out and gets in my cab.
Just as she does, one of the security men at the place flags an
out-of-town cab, calls her over and tells her, ``Get in this cab.''
I jump out and tell him he can't do that. It's illegal for
out-of-town cabs to pick up fares in this city and you know it, I
tell him.
</P>
<P>
   A tall young man in a green coat says, ``Mind your own business.
We're security here so take off.'' Of course he uses stronger
language. The second guy starts laughing and says, ``We do it all
the time because you
</P>
<P>
   guys are such scum.'' The younger one starts approaching me in a
menacing manner when his buddy calls him off. We're scum? That's
what you call us after bringing thousands of fares to this place?
The guy in the green coat kicks my cab. I'm pissed as I drive off.
I suppose I could stop by a police station, but instead I just jot
a note down on my SFO stubs and forget about it.
</P>
<P>
   I'm driving in an area I used to live in a few years back. As I
approach Laurel shopping center, a young boy in front of Noah's
Bagels puts his hand up. He can't be more than 12. ``Jackson near
Fillmore,'' he says, jumping in. We take off and I ask how it's
going. ``It was going pretty good until I did some bad Web trades
on my dad's account.'' I ask him what happened. ``I bought a bunch
of stocks this morning, like Qualcomm, Etoys, and they all went
down badly.'' I ask if he's trading on the Internet. Yes, he tells
me. I ask him if his dad knows he's doing this. ``No, not yet. He
won't be home till Monday. Can you make a left up here, then a
right on Washington? I want to drive by my mom's first.''
</P>
<P>
   On Washington he asks me to slow down. ``She's not home,'' he
says as we pass this house at a crawl. We turn back. I ask him how
bad the hit was. ``About $16,000,'' he says. I ask if he has
liquidated the trades yet. ``No, I'm going to wait to see what
happens tomorrow.'' I tell him that's his second mistake. We stop,
he pays me and says, ``They've never gone down on me before.'' I
tell him he should tell his dad, then I wish him luck. He'll need
it.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (The Night Cabbie appears every other Monday in The Examiner.
He's on our Web site at www.examiner.com/cabbie. You can call him
and leave a message at 777-8738, write him c/o The Examiner, P.O.
Box 7260, SF 94120. Or send email to cabbie &LR; examiner.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
