<HEADLINE>
HOW CLEAN IS THE SURF? IT'S OFTEN HARD TO KNOW 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Fla., N.J., Calif.)   (For release Sunday, August 6)  
 By JOHN H. CUSHMAN Jr.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Three years after the Environmental Protection
Agency launched a broad program to better protect the public from
the hazards of sewage and other pollution at beaches, there has
been only scattered progress on a number of fronts.
</P>
<P>
   With the summer recreation season now at its peak, it is still
difficult for people in many places to find out at a particular
time whether the local water is clean enough for safe swimming.
Some states have improved notification procedures and some have
tightened standards for testing water for pathogens, but others
have not.
</P>
<P>
   Many people never consider that the surf may not always be clean
enough to swim in, and data collected by the EPA shows that
problems are widespread. In its latest annual survey of both coasts
and the Great Lakes region, the agency found that state and local
authorities closed or posted warnings at 459 beaches at least once
last year _ almost one out of four of the 1,891 beaches surveyed.
</P>
<P>
   The Environmental Protection Agency's data showed that
California had 182 beaches reporting at least one closure or
warning during 1999. That's far more than the runners-up, Florida
with 48 and Illinois with 46. New Jersey had 19, and New York 11.
But state-to-state comparisons are difficult, because different
states have different rules for testing the waters and responding
to the test results.
</P>
<P>
   The agency said that the percent of beaches with polluted water
was ``essentially the same as last year.'' Amy Gambrill, an
official in the agency's water office, said the main problem was
bacteria in the water coming from sewage overflows and runoffs
after storms.
</P>
<P>
   Many beaches are frequently contaminated when untreated sewage
flows into the ocean, carrying a variety of bacteria, viruses,
protozoa and parasites that can cause illnesses ranging from
diarrhea to hepatitis. The contamination can last for several days
after each overflow.
</P>
<P>
   Much of what the agency has been trying to accomplish for the
last three years to protect the public remains undone. About a
third of the local jurisdictions surveyed have not yet adopted the
EPAs criteria for monitoring water quality, which call for testing
five times a month for E. coli (at freshwater beaches, such as the
Great Lakes) and enterococcus bacteria (in ocean waters). At 5
percent of beaches, the water is sampled only after heavy rains or
known spills.
</P>
<P>
   This summer, the agency will propose tighter standards against
sewage overflows. It recently completed its final storm-water
regulations to better control runoff after heavy rains. Both steps
should lead to fewer spills.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton has also ordered the agency to come up with
new offshore ocean water-quality standards, similar to those that
govern freshwater rivers and lakes. By next spring the EPA expects
to complete new guidelines for states on beach water quality. But
all these regulations will take time to go into full force.
Meanwhile, Congress has not acted on legislation, under
consideration for several years, that would require state and local
governments to follow uniform standards and make public
announcements whenever beach waters are polluted.
</P>
<P>
   In most parts of the country there is no simple and reliable way
for vacationers to find out about water quality at individual
beaches. The EPA generally recommends that people call the local
department of public health or state department of natural
resources. Agency officials said that people should avoid swimming
shortly after heavy rains.
</P>
<P>
   The Clean Beaches Council, a nonprofit organization, has what it
calls a Blue Wave program under which it has certified 30 beaches
in seven states as meeting its criteria for water quality and other
standards. The organization works with state and local
environmental authorities to verify compliance and lists certified
beaches at www.cleanbeaches.org.
</P>
<P>
   Some states _ notably California, under a new state law _ are
expanding their monitoring of beach waters and creating systems for
letting the public know when the water is not safe, both by making
announcements in the news media and by posting current data on the
Web.
</P>
<P>
   But without uniform requirements under federal law, these
systems are spotty at best.
</P>
<P>
   In Florida, for example, several counties post the results of
bacteria sampling at their most popular beaches at
www.doh.state.fl.us/environment/beach/default.html. But there is no
law or source of money to allow for a statewide program, according
to Robert Nobles of the state's health office.
</P>
<P>
   The EPA also has a Web site, and for years has been promising to
post current water conditions nationwide there, giving everybody a
single place to check for water conditions. But agency officials
said it was likely to be at least another year before that happens.
Meanwhile, the Web site contains only data from the annual survey
of beaches _ something that is of little use to somebody planning a
weekend getaway.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
