<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-31 17:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8529 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r f BC-FEARLESS-EXECUTIVE-HN     07-31 0861
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FEARLESS-EXECUTIVE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     FEAR CAN RUIN A CAREER 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By DALE MURPHY  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Being afraid of spiders or snakes or even your
own shadow might not hurt your career, but what if you're afraid
that you're simply not good enough - or that people will resent you
if you speak up? Those sorts of fears can hamper or even destroy a
career.
</P>
<P>
   Fear of inadequacy is the most common such pitfall, management
psychologist and executive coach Alan Downs says in his recently
released book, ``The Fearless Executive.'' Downs, a former San
Francisco resident who used to be in charge of executive
development at Hewlett-Packard in Palo Alto, outlines seven common
fears in his book:
</P>
<P>
   Inadequacy: You simply don't have the talent to do the job, so
you are constantly trying to prove to others that you're
infallible.
</P>
<P>
   ``The executive driven by a fear of inadequacy is blinded to the
humanity of others, choosing to view them as objects, or modules,
to be moved about the game board of the organization - a game he is
determined to win at all costs,'' Downs writes. ``No one, including
infallible executives, can get ahead without enlisting the help of
others, so these executives may turn on considerable charm,
sympathy or understanding if necessary to win over someone as a
useful ally.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the pawn has served his purposes and is of no further
use, he may be coolly discarded.''
</P>
<P>
   Rejection: Your bosses won't accept you, so you'll be stifled in
your attempts to move up. Even presidents can be hampered by this
fear, Downs says, because they're afraid of being rejected by
voters.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem arises when you go beyond desiring approval and
are consumed by the fear of rejection,'' Downs writes. ``You clamp
down on your relationships and refuse to allow anything to
transpire that might cause you to be rejected. Your need for
approval becomes overwhelmingly strong, even stronger than your
desire to do good business.
</P>
<P>
   ``You trade off your own person to become the executive you
think others want you to be. You discard your own talents and
passion in order to play a role that you mistakenly believe will
win the approval of others.''
</P>
<P>
   Scarcity: Scrambling madly to protect what you already have, and
thinking that possibilities are finite. These are executives whose
main strategy is simply to slash costs rather than taking risks to
grow the business, and those who think they are diminished somehow
if a colleague succeeds.
</P>
<P>
   Reality: Thinking there is a quick fix to complex problems.
Downs says executives will sometimes bring in consultants
unnecessarily, figuring they can come up with a painless solution
even though no such thing really exists.
</P>
<P>
   The unknown: Executives will stick with the status quo rather
than facing the uncertainty of change.
</P>
<P>
   Authority: Those who accept authority without question, bending
over backward to appease authority figures and giving up
responsibility for their own success.
</P>
<P>
   Aging: Assuming that your abilities will diminish with age, and
you will become obsolete.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview, Downs said that the fears of inadequacy and
rejection are not only the most common, but the most destructive to
executives. He said those who feel inadequate often won't directly
address that fear, but will dig themselves in deeper by trying to
move around it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rather than admit that you've made a mistake, you'll just keep
pouring money into that same hole,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Downs added that many executives will hire consultants to
protect themselves from what they perceive as their own inadequacy.
``It behooves the consultant to feed that feeling of inadequacy.''
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, consultants sometimes can help those with a
fear of rejection. The consultants, rather than the executive, can
challenge the conventional wisdom, so the executive doesn't have to
worry about being the bearer of bad news.
</P>
<P>
   He said the fear of authority is probably the hardest to
overcome because it is often deep-seated from childhood. And
everyone has someone to answer to, whether it's a rank-and-file
worker responding to a supervisor or a CEO answering the board of
directors.
</P>
<P>
   With all the fears, he urges readers to acknowledge whatever
irrational beliefs underlie the fear, try to push past the fear and
take positive action in the direction of the fear. For people with
the fear of authority, for example, he suggests making a list of
the strengths and weaknesses of their authority figures, showing
those people as human beings with the same sorts of flaws as
everyone else.
</P>
<P>
   Downs said everyone has fears, but he hopes the awareness of the
fear can help people concentrate on building their strengths.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think a little bit of each of the fears is healthy. It
pushes you to examine what you're doing. It's also been said that
someone without any fear is a sociopath. There's some truth to
that.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Dave Murphy is the careers editor of the San Francisco
Examiner, P.O. Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120. His electronic
mail address is murphy(at)examiner.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
