<HEADLINE>
HEALTH AND FITNESS NOTES AND NEWS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (REPEATING to add photo-graphics note)  (ART ADV:  Photo  is being sent to NYT photo clients.  Graphic  is
being sent to NYT graphics clients. Nonsubscribers can purchase
one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
 (The Science Times)  
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   PATTERNS: Antibiotics, When Patients Want Action
</P>
<P>
   The desire of patients for a tangible outcome from a trip to the
doctor and the desire of harried doctors to move on to the next
patient are two of the most powerful factors behind the misuse of
antibiotics, according to a study by researchers at Brigham and
Women's Hospital in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   ``We found that culture and economics play a large role in the
overconsumption of antibiotics in this country,'' said Dr. Jerry
Avorn, the lead author of the survey article, which appeared last
month in The Annals of Internal Medicine.
</P>
<P>
   By prescribing antibiotics, a doctor signals to a patient that
the condition is treatable and that the patient is being cared for,
Avorn wrote. ``This perspective helps to explain the `drug hunger'
that many symptomatic patients bring to the physician visit, which
they feel satisfied only by receiving a prescription.''
</P>
<P>
   For doctors feeling the time constraints of managed care,
writing such prescriptions, even for conditions they suspect are
viruses (and not affected by bacteria-killing drugs), is an
effective way to bring an office visit to a close without
disappointing or angering patients, the study said.
</P>
<P>
   Add the pressure from drug companies advertising and consumers
stressing the need for the latest in drugs, and ``it is not
surprising that the small voice of therapeutic restraint and
concern about microbial resistance is so difficult to hear above
the din.''
</P>
<P>
   PROGNOSIS: A Higher Risk for Babies Born at Night
</P>
<P>
   Very few babies die during the first week of life. But for some
reason, the risk is higher for babies born during the night than
those born during the day, according to a German study published on
Friday in The British Medical Journal.
</P>
<P>
   The study, by researchers at the Phillips University of Marburg,
reviewed records from nearly 400,000 normal, low-risk deliveries in
an effort to substantiate similar findings from earlier studies in
Wales.
</P>
<P>
   Daytime births, defined as those between 7 a.m. and 9 p.m.,
outnumbered night births by 231,939 to 148,991.
</P>
<P>
   Fifty-seven of those infants died in the first week of life. But
the death rate for night-born babies was close to twice that of
daytime deliveries. When the field was narrowed to infants who died
of asphyxia, the difference in mortality rates was close to four
times.
</P>
<P>
   ``This may be a result of staff's increased physical and mental
fatigue during the night,'' the researchers wrote. ``Overreliance
on less experienced staff may be another important reason.''
</P>
<P>
   CONSEQUENCES: Clues to Ecstasy's Effects on Addicts
</P>
<P>
   An autopsy of the brain of a chronic abuser of the drug ecstasy
suggests that it may work by causing violent fluctuations in the
brain chemical serotonin, according to a report last week in
Neurology.
</P>
<P>
   Animal studies of ecstasy, an amphetamine derivative, have found
it can trigger a sudden release of serotonin, which has a powerful
effect on mood. Dr. S.J. Kish of the Center for Addiction and
Mental Health in Toronto said users of the drug reported increased
awareness of emotion and heightened feelings of intimacy.
</P>
<P>
   The researchers led by Kish compared serotonin levels of the
brains of 11 people who had not used drugs with those in the brain
of a man who had died at age 26 after using ecstasy heavily since
the age of 17. ``The levels of serotonin and another chemical
associated with serotonin were 50 to 80 percent lower in the brain
of the ecstasy user,'' Kish said. ``This is the first study to show
that this drug can deplete the level of serotonin in humans.''
</P>
<P>
   Ecstasy users commonly appear lethargic and depressed after the
drug wears off, including the addict in the study, whose friends
said he appeared depressed and had slow speech and reaction time
after binges.
</P>
<P>
   Further research, Kish said, may show whether supplementing
serotonin levels might help those seeking to go through withdrawal.
</P>
<P>
   PERCEPTIONS: Man, Superman, Clark Kent and Woman
</P>
<P>
   A new study of male body images found that the average young man
wants to look like Superman and thinks that women want men to look
like Superman, while women really want men to look like Clark Kent.
</P>
<P>
   The study, in the August issue of The American Journal of
Psychiatry, focuses on what researchers call ``muscle dysmorphia,''
a syndrome in which men become obsessed with fears that they are
small and frail _ in many ways the flip side of anorexia nervosa.
</P>
<P>
   The study, led by Dr. Harrison Pope of the McLean Hospital in
Boston, sought to compare the responses of 200 young men in Boston,
Paris and Innsbruck, Austria, who were not bodybuilders, to get a
sense of how they compared their perceptions of their own bodies to
an ideal.
</P>
<P>
   The men were shown an image of a male body on a computer screen
and asked to alter it in terms of fat and muscle until it reflected
first, their own bodies, second, how they would like their bodies
to look, and finally, the body type they thought women found most
attractive.
</P>
<P>
   Generally, their images of their own bodies were roughly
accurate, Pope wrote. But that does not mean they like them. In all
three countries, the ideal body type chosen carried an average of
28 pounds of muscle more than the men possessed. And on average,
the men supposed that women would like an additional two pounds of
muscle on top of that.
</P>
<P>
   But when the researchers asked women to use the same device to
select the ideal male body type, what they came up with ``a very
ordinary looking male body.''
</P>
<P>
   HYPERTENSION: When the White Coats Befuddle Doctors
</P>
<P>
   Doctors call it ``white coat hypertension'' when a patient's
nervousness during an office visit results in a misleadingly high
blood pressure reading. But sometimes the opposite is true, and a
study published in The Archives of Family Medicine suggests that
more people than thought may be escaping diagnosis because of what
its authors called ``white coat normotension.''
</P>
<P>
   To test their theory, researchers from the University of British
Columbia and the University of Akron chose 319 people believed to
be healthy, and compared five office blood pressure measurements
with ambulatory measures, that is, readings taken away from the
office over a period of 10 to 12 hours.
</P>
<P>
   They found that almost one in four of the patients had
white-coat normotension: Their ambulatory measures showed high
blood pressure that had not appeared in the office readings.
</P>
<P>
   These patients were more often men who were older, drank more
alcohol and included more ex-smokers than the group's average. But
the psychologists on the team were unable to identify any
definitive mental trait that would give a clue about who was at
risk for underdiagnosis or why.
</P>
<P>
   The researchers suggested that physicians should feel confident
only about office readings that were clearly at one end of the
scale or another. ``Given the apparently high prevalence rates of
both types of misdiagnoses, practitioners need to consider
seriously that between one-third and one-half'' of office blood
pressure readings are wrong, they wrote.
</P>
</TEXT>
