<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CVN-GOP-BUSH01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    BUSH SPEECH WILL 'RESPECT' DEMOCRATSBy JENA HEATH
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ Gov. George W. Bush will take subtle aim at the
Democrats Thursday when he delivers his prime-time speech before
the Republican National Convention in Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   ``He will needle his opponents a little but he will treat them
with respect,'' Bush spokeswoman Karen Hughes told reporters
Monday. ``He will not engage in the kind of trash-and-burn attack
style politics that we've become so sick of out of Washington,
D.C.''
</P>
<P>
   Hughes said the speech will include Bush's theme of restoring
dignity and honor to the White House _ a gentle jab at the scandals
that have plagued the Clinton administration. He will also contrast
his proposals on a variety of issues, including providing
prescription drug coverage for the elderly _ a theme the campaign
has been emphasizing more lately and one poll show plays well with
voters _ with the Clinton administration's record, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Campaigning in six swing states on the way to Philadelphia, Bush
has subtly intensified his criticisms of the current
administration. He frequently tells the large and enthusiastic
crowds that the nation is being led by a man who doesn't know
``what the meaning of the word is is,'' a reference to the Monica
Lewinsky scandal.
</P>
<P>
   Hughes said Bush would not use that line in the convention
address, which she described as, ``a very positive and uplifting
speech. It's a leadership speech.'' The speech reads about 30
minutes without interruption and will be similar to the one Bush
has been delivering at campaign rallies, she said.
</P>
<P>
   At a Bush rally in Dayton Monday, the tone was upbeat with
criticism of Clinton limited to issues. That was in stark contrast
to the day before, when a string of Bush introducers in Hamilton
County, the Republican heart of Ohio, lambasted Clinton using some
of the most vitriolic language on the campaign trail yet.
</P>
<P>
   Bush and his wife, Laura _ who kicked off the convention Monday
with her own speech _ gathered at the Cincinnati home of Bill and
Kathie DeWitt late Sunday afternoon for a practice session.
DeWitt's family once owned the Cincinnati Reds baseball team and he
helped Bush buy the Texas Rangers. Longtime friends Mercer and Gaby
Reynolds were also there along with other DeWitt family members.
</P>
<P>
   All told, 12 people gathered in the DeWitt living room where
they cleared out some furniture and set up a podium so that Bush
and Laura could run through their speeches using a teleprompter. It
was the fourth time Bush has read his speech through and about the
second time he has practiced with the teleprompter.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if Bush is becoming more comfortable with the
teleprompter, Hughes said: ``I hope. I think so.''
</P>
<P>
   Laura woke at about 5 a.m. Monday to do a round of morning talk
show interviews and later could be seen on the convention floor
preparing for her prime time speech.
</P>
<P>
   ``She said she's a little nervous about her speech but she's
looking forward to it,'' Hughes said.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking with reporters at Dayton International Airport, Bush
said the practice session went `` pretty good.'' He said that he
did not help Laura with her speech and that they didn't watch each
other practice.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to see her speech on first delivery,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush headed to the airport to say goodbye to Laura, who was
headed to Philadelphia, and to greet their twin daughters, Jenna
and Barbara, 18, who are traveling with their mother. The couple is
leaving it to the girls to decide if they will appear on stage
during his speech. The couple has been careful to guard the twins'
privacy. They appeared on stage the night of the New Hampshire
primary and on Super Tuesday night but have mostly stayed out of
the limelight.
</P>
<P>
   ``I
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
