<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-31 17:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8535 &Cx1f; taf-z
s t BC-TRAVEL-OLY-SYDNEY-QUE     07-31 1195
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-OLY-SYDNEY-QUEENSTREET-$ADV06-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A STROLL DOWN WOOLLAHRA'S QUEEN STREET 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, August 6)  
 By JANE PERLEZ   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Visitors to the Olympics who need an antidote to the events and
the crowds can spend a few hours wandering along Queen Street in
Woollahra. The quiet, tree-lined area is filled with antiques
stores and a few smart restaurants. Much of Sydney has become
overwhelmed with new building and brash architecture, but
Woollahra, one of the early settlements of the colonial city, has
retained its original terrace houses, shady trees and village
atmosphere.
</P>
<P>
   In the last decade, Queen Street, the main thoroughfare of
Woollahra, about 10 minutes by car or bus from the city center, has
become the fashionable antiques haunt for Sydney's new wealthy,
their decorators and connoisseurs. A showcase, the street is not a
place for bargains, although by American standards the prices are
fair and quite bearable. The emphasis is on English and European
furniture, silver, jewelry and porcelain, although interest in
Australiana surfaces from time to time. Sydney people tend to be
enthusiastic about Australian painters, particularly their
renditions of the outback landscape, but less so about early
colonial furniture.
</P>
<P>
   The storekeepers on Queen Street are friendly and knowledgeable.
Many live on the surrounding streets of Woollahra or in neighboring
Paddington, another area dominated by 19th-century terrace houses
with its own array of galleries. Habitues of Queen Street are eager
to retain the ambience of small shops, which include an
old-fashioned butcher and a fruit and vegetable store nestled among
the windows that glisten with burnished cherry-wood desks,
sparkling silver, handsome porcelain and Art Nouveau jewelry. So
far Queen Street, unlike Kings Road in London, has not been invaded
by brand name clothing stores and music outlets.
</P>
<P>
   One way to tackle a buying or browsing excursion would be to
start at the top where bustling four-lane Oxford Street gives way
to peaceful Queen Street. Almost immediately on your left, you will
find the Charles Hewitt Gallery, a source of antique prints and a
haven for contemporary Australian artists and photographers.
Hewitt, who is also a specialist in period and modern picture
framing and furniture, prides himself on showing up-and-coming
Australian artists as well as established painters. During the
Olympic period, he has chosen two Australian artists: Jacqui Comer,
whose semi-abstract canvases focus on aerial views of the
Australian landscape, and David Naseby, who interprets the
Australian outback in bold, stark colors and forms. His stockroom
is filled with the work of other Australian artists, including Tim
Snowdon's evocative still-life paintings.
</P>
<P>
   A few doors farther along the street is Anne Schofield Antiques,
a boutique with a fine collection of antique jewelry from the
Georgian period to the 1920s and '30s. Schofield, who has been in
business since the late 1960s, is known as the doyenne of her field
in Australia. Glamorously adorned with some of her jewelry, she
presides behind the glass counters, happily explaining the finer
points of a string of Tahitian pearls or the clarity of the
diamonds in a '30s Cartier bracelet. The store itself is a bijou: a
small room in the colors of the jewels and crowned by a pair of
enormous crystal chandeliers from Czechoslovakia. A serious dealer,
Schofield's inventory ranges from the spectacular (an 1850 English
diamond necklace for $70,000) to the decorative (Indian gold disc
earrings for $700) and a few less expensive bracelets and lockets,
at $1.72 Australian to the U.S. dollar.
</P>
<P>
   On the opposite side of Queen Street, you will find G.L.
Auchinachie &AMP; Son, where Ian and Gina Auchinachie are the second
generation to run the family antiques business. Here, the range is
enormous, in both price and style. The Auchinachies specialize in
early English furniture, and will sell you a set of eight mahogany
Sheraton dining room chairs that costs $27,000. Or they will gladly
sell a piece of Victorian needlework for $60. They have a stock of
English country chairs with rush seats and oak dressers. They ship
to the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Toward the center of Queen Street is the charming Michael A.
Greene Antiques, where a trove of more reasonably priced and
carefully selected jewelry, silver and porcelain is displayed in
easy-to-see cases. The owners, Michael and Victoria Greene, know
and love their wares, most of which are small and easy to pack.
Sometimes, one will spot a coveted item such as a crocodile-leather
traveling toiletry trunk fitted with the original glass bottles and
containers. Always on hand: sterling silver napkin rings,
candlesticks and boxes. The jewelry case abounds in affordable
pins, lockets and bracelets. The shop also specializes in the 1920s
and '30s ceramics of the English designer Clarice Cliff.
</P>
<P>
   For antique books, McCormick's is known in Sydney as a
top-of-the-line dealer in colonial manuscripts and books on the
early voyages to Australia. This upstairs shop also deals in
prints, maps and period black-and-white photographs. If the prices
are a bit out of bounds, this is still a marvelous place to browse
carefully among rare volumes.
</P>
<P>
   A favorite of decorators is Hamish Clark Antiques, where there
is an eclectic mix of 18th- and 19th-century English furniture,
porcelain, desk-top bowls and boxes, and quilts.
</P>
<P>
   Queen Street is not just antiques. Cose, a small store in the
courtyard of Queens Court, is loaded with designer glassware and
china from Italy and France as well as unusual, finely made French
leather handbags and latest-look faux jewelry. Almost next door in
the courtyard is Leslie McKay Books, one of the best book stores in
Sydney, with a good stock of Australia's current generation of
fiction writers.
</P>
<P>
   A stroll through Queen Street would not be complete without
stopping for fuel. Caffe Agostinis in the Queen Street courtyard _
you cannot miss it because the tables with wide canvas umbrellas
spill outdoors _ is an informal spot with fresh ingredients and
reasonable prices. The owner, Margie Agostini (blond hair, white
chef's jacket) is usually in attendance in the open kitchen. She
serves a great salad of arugula, asparagus and avocado at lunch for
$6.15, and heartier fare in the evening: seafood, veal and chicken
dishes at about $11.50 (plus 10 percent tax). No alcohol is served
but you can buy a bottle of wine at the Woollahra Hotel across the
street.
</P>
<P>
   Another pleasant restaurant is Bistro Moncur, where the noise
level is fashionably intense, with a clientele from the
neighborhood. As everywhere in Sydney, the fish is fresh, and there
is steak as well. Prices for a main course are $13 to $17.
</P>
<P>
   To finish off the shopping expedition, you can sink into a
comfortable chair or perch on a stool at the Woollahra Hotel, on
the corner of Queen and Moncur Streets. This traditional Australian
pub has been done over with sleek wood floors and handsome
furniture. To celebrate your good buys, a bottle of Australian
Petaluma Crozer champagne will be about $18.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
