<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CVN-TECHNOLOGY01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    REPUBLICANS GO HI-TECH IN PHILLY
 &HT;    By ANDREW J. GLASS
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ Since the image makers at the Republican National
Convention decreed that the speakers' podium would be a
politician-free zone on Monday night, the presiding politician was
safely kept three miles away.
</P>
<P>
   House Speaker Dennis Hastert, the convention's permanent
chairman, opened the session while standing in historic Carpenters'
Hall beside an actor dressed as Thomas Jefferson.
</P>
<P>
   It was first of several closed-circuit high-definition video
feeds to be pumped into the jumbo screens the First Union Center.
And it underscored the fact that whatever this convention may lack
in the way of controversy, there's no shortage of technological
wizardry.
</P>
<P>
   In 34 days, the GOP planners have converted the Philadelphia
Flyers locker room into a high-tech super-secure nerve center to
handle the convention's formidable communication needs. The complex
houses enough computer power to handle the telephone system of a
mid-sized city.
</P>
<P>
   An internal network, known as an intranet, allows speeches,
platform texts and other documents to go online as soon as they are
ready, rather than having to wait to be duplicated and handed out
in paper form. Most news organizations covering the convention have
chosen to plug into the internal system.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond the convention complex, all members of the
Internet-enabled public have been invited to become ``virtual
delegates.'' On Monday, registered users with fast online links
could watch, among other clips, the entire 45-minute speech that
Richard Nixon gave in Miami in accepting the party's 1968
presidential nomination.
</P>
<P>
   The convention Internet site also offers such amenities as an
online shop. (Three golf balls stamped with the convention logo go
for $11.95.)
</P>
<P>
   Large screens located throughout the complex let viewers watch
the proceedings remotely in high-definition video. But the
organizers decided not to compete with a number of news
organizations, including C-SPAN and America Online, that are
putting the convention on the Internet in streaming video.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, we approached both the Republicans and the Democrats
to offer to set up all their convention communications needs,''
said Stephen Rohleder, the Washington-based managing partner of
Andersen Consulting. ``We thought,'' Rohleder added, ``it would be
a fine way to advance the cause of e-government.''
</P>
<P>
   Only the Republicans, however, took up Andersen's offer.
</P>
<P>
   The hands-on job of coordinating a slew of telecom vendors and
Internet nodes at the GOP site fell to Andersen's Dean Griffin, who
serves as the convention's chief technology officer. As part of the
bargain, Andersen also contributed about $850,000 in services to
the Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   Griffin, 51, supervises the First Union site with a scrambled
radio-telephone system that appears permanently attached to his
right ear. After the convention ends, the whole advanced system
will service the Philadelphia police department.
</P>
<P>
   ``Four years ago, the technical expertise and the (Internet)
bandwidth simply wasn't there to do what we are doing here now,''
Griffin said. He noted with pride that the 2000 setup for the first
time gives reporters who utilize the convention's general press
room free high-speed Internet access for their laptops.
</P>
<P>
   On the Web: www.gopconvention.com
</P>
<P>
   Andrew J. Glass' e-mail address is andyg(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
