<SLUG> BC-CLINT-EASTWOOD-IN-SPACE-COWBOYS-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`SPACE' CASE: CLINT EASTWOOD HEADS INTO ORBIT 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 (Includes a color slide of Clint Eastwood with Tommy Lee Jones,
Donald Sutherland and Courtney B. Vance in a scene from ``Space
Cowboys.'') 
 By CINDY PEARLMAN  
 World rights except Chicago. 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features.)  
 &HT;    As a rule, Clint Eastwood likes to keep his feet on the ground,
or at least no higher aloft than a horse's back.
 &HT;    It all goes back to 1951, when as a young soldier hitching a
ride on a Navy plane back from Seattle to his base in California,
Eastwood took an unscheduled detour into the Pacific Ocean.
 &HT;    ``At those moments in your life, you're not really scared,''
Eastwood says. ``You just think about the next step. What can I do
to save this day?''
 &HT;    The plane went down, and the 21-year-old soldier spent the next
five hours fighting to stay alive in freezing, shark-infested
waters.
 &HT;    ``I felt like a pretty lucky punk on that day,'' the 70-year-old
actor says with a chuckle. ``But maybe something subconscious made
me want to stay on the nice, firm ground for the rest of my life.''
 &HT;    Well, until now, anyway. His new movie, ``Space Cowboys,'' takes
him about as far off the ground as anyone gets: Eastwood, who also
directed, plays a 70-year-old astronaut called back to NASA for one
last mission with three similarly aged former comrades, played by
James Garner, Tommy Lee Jones and Donald Sutherland.
 &HT;    Actually, Sutherland says, the flying scenes weren't nearly as
tough as a physical-exam scene which required all four to bare
their not-so-hardbodies.
 &HT;    ``I thought about asking for a butt double,'' Sutherland says,
grimacing. ``But at my age it sounded redundant _ my butt has just
naturally doubled!''
 &HT;    Appropriately, Eastwood has returned to Houston, where the film
was shot, to promote it with an appearance at the NASA Space Center
prior to the movie's nationwide opening on Aug. 4. Looking sinewy
and handsome in a grey suit jacket, matching shirt and tailored
beige pants, Eastwood has hair as silver as the space shuttle
parked outside.
 &HT;    Unlike many of the film's target audience, he says, he didn't
grow up dreaming of being an astronaut.
 &HT;    ``When I was a kid, they didn't have astronauts,'' he says. ``We
only had Buck Rogers and Flash Gordon. My God, my age is showing!''
 &HT;    Sutherland and Eastwood were actually together the night that
men first walked on the moon.
 &HT;    ``Clint and I were in Yugoslavia making `Kelly's Heroes' (1970)
in 1969, sitting in a hotel watching a black-and-white television
when Neil Armstrong walked on the moon,'' Sutherland recalls.
 &HT;    Eastwood nods.
 &HT;    ``Unfortunately,'' he says, ``someone was speaking in
Yugoslavian over him when he said `One small step for man ... ' I
was sitting there going, `What did he say? What did he say?' We had
to read about it in another paper later.''
 &HT;    These days Eastwood rarely co-stars with his generational peers,
but he says he enjoyed the chance to work with seasoned veterans
such as Garner, Jones and Sutherland.
 &HT;    ``Most of us had met each other or known each other for a long
time,'' he says. ``These guys are old pros. So the first day you
just sit around and have a cigar and tell a few jokes. Pretty soon,
you are all there. And then you just go ahead and jump into a
scene.''
 &HT;    In other words, ``Space Cowboys'' was, like most Eastwood films,
shot without the extensive rehearsal that's the industry norm.
 &HT;    ``This is not an intellectual art form,'' the actor/director
says. ``It's an emotional art form, a gut-reaction art form. And
the more you allow your inner guts and emotion to drive you, the
more fun you can have with it all. If you try to think a scene to
death, it kind of beats you up.''
 &HT;    There was plenty else to beat them up, Eastwood adds, beginning
with the basic equipment of space flight.
 &HT;    ``The space suits make you weigh about 400 pounds,'' Eastwood
says. ``In outer space there's no weight, so they're not bad. In
gravity, however, they are almost impossible. You always feel like
you're about to tip and fall through the wall.''
 &HT;    It's only the latest hurdle in a legendary Hollywood career that
stretches back to his big break on television's ``Rawhide'' in
1959. Along the way he's played ``Dirty Harry'' Callahan, ridden
the spaghetti-Western range, co-starred with a chimpanzee _ twice _
and, oh yes, directed and starred in the Oscar-winning
``Unforgiven'' (1992).
 &HT;    After close to 50 years in the business, however, Eastwood says
that he thinks he's at his peak, at least as an actor.
 &HT;    ``I simply know more about life,'' he says matter-of-factly.
 &HT;    Eastwood admits to amazement at how long his career has lasted.
 &HT;    ``Every actor has that dilemma where they think their present
job is their last job,'' he says. ``I just never thought too much
about it _ I just kind of kept going.''
 &HT;    He shrugs.
 &HT;    ``You get a little bit of the brass ring,'' he adds, ``and you
get obsessed by work, which I am not now. And I thank God for
that.''
 &HT;    Helping the father of four avoid getting obsessed is his new
family life with his wife, newscaster Dina Ruiz, and their
3-year-old daughter.
 &HT;    ``If anyone wants to know what's the best part of aging,''
Eastwood says, ``it's losing that obsession for work and spending a
little more time with family and personal life. I'm spending more
time with family and friends, and I think that it's great fun.''
 &HT;    He was 67 when Morgan Eastwood was born on Dec. 13, 1996, and
Eastwood says he has no regrets.
 &HT;    ``It's great having a 3-and-a-half-year-old,'' he says. ``I keep
joking, `I didn't have any grandchildren, so I had my own
grandchildren.'
 &HT;    ``I guess it's unfair that the male gender can always have kids
at an older age,'' he adds, ``but I really appreciate it. I love
it. And I'm much more attentive to my kids now than I ever was
before.''
 &HT;    And, yes, the former Man With No Name does his share of the
babysitting.
 &HT;    ``I can tell you everything about Barney, every part of it,'' he
says cheerfully. ``But with Pokemon I had to draw the line a little
bit. I do know all the Scooby Doo tapes, backwards and forwards.
 &HT;    ``Don't tell anyone.''
 &HT;    He laughs.
 &HT;    ``Here's one good thing about aging,'' Eastwood says. ``You
suddenly don't take yourself so seriously.''
 &HT;    At 70, the actor says, life looks pretty good.
 &HT;    ``I'm still working,'' he says. ``I can still work in an
industry that still wants me. I'm just playing different roles than
we played 50 years ago _ and that's not bad.''
 &HT;    As for the future, he candidly admits that he isn't sure.
 &HT;    ``I get asked about the future of the film business and my part
in it,'' he says. ``And it's tough for me to anticipate where it's
all going, because this is the information age. Things are changing
so rapidly.
 &HT;    ``I think the future of films belongs to the next generation,''
he says. ``I've carried it as far as I can carry it. Now everyone
else is on their own.''
 c.2000 Cindy Pearlman  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Cindy Pearlman is a Chicago-based free-lance writer.) &LR; 
 &UR; EDITOR: For further information on ``Space Cowboys,'' consult the
official Web site at www.spacecowboys.net. And don't forget to
visit The New York Times Syndicate Web site at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for information on StarBeat and
other features. &QL; 
