<SLUG> BC-DONAL-LOGUE-IN-THE-TAO-OF-STEVE-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALMOST FAMOUS: DONAL LOGUE DANCES ON THE BRINK OF STARDOM 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 (Includes a color slide of Donal Logue in a scene from ``The Tao of
Steve.'') 
 By IAN SPELLING  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features.)  
 &HT;    Donal Logue gathers no moss.
 &HT;    Over the past two years, Logue has acted in nine feature films,
a short digital video and two television pilots. And, somewhere in
between, he and his girlfriend welcomed into the world a son named
Flinn, now 17 months old.
 &HT;    The actor obviously has ignored the advice of his pal, fellow
thespian Bill Paxton.
 &HT;    ``Bill is a great guy with a great attitude,'' Logue says by
telephone from his Los Angeles home. ``But one thing he told me is,
`You're special, man, so don't be available for weddings and bar
mitzvahs.'
 &HT;    ``I understand that,'' the actor says. ``It's one take on
things. But if I had to hang up the phone now, go grease my hair,
put on strange glasses and become somebody else for a while, I'd be
psyched.''
 &HT;    OK, so Logue loves his craft. But you're probably still asking,
who is this guy?
 &HT;    He's a familiar face to a lot of people, actually. Jimmy the cab
driver in MTV's old ad spots? Logue. Quinn, the bad guy in
``Blade'' (1998)? Logue. The priest in ``Runaway Bride'' (1999)?
Shane Pencil in the Madonna spoof ``Medusa: Dare to Be Truthful''
(1992)? Tom Colton in the ``X-Files'' episode ``Squeeze'' (1993)?
Logue, Logue and Logue.
 &HT;    As for those aforementioned nine films, there was ``Runaway
Bride,'' ``The Big Tease'' and ``Takedown,'' all released in 1999,
as well as the 2000 titles ``Reindeer Games,'' ``The Patriot,''
``The Million Dollar Hotel,'' ``Steal This Movie!'' ``The
Opportunists'' and ``The Tao of Steve.''
 &HT;    Two of those movies, ``The Opportunists'' and ``The Tao of
Steve,'' are currently in limited release. Logue takes a supporting
role in ``The Opportunists,'' playing a working-class guy from
Queens, N.Y., who tries to improve his lot in life by pressuring a
reluctant ex-con (Christopher Walken) into making one more big
score.
 &HT;    ``It's a good little film,'' says Logue, a 34-year-old native of
Ottawa, Canada. ``When I was in New York and couldn't find work, I
just always wanted to be one of those actors who worked on the
street in cool, gritty independent movies. So this was my chance.
 &HT;    ``I also got to work with Christopher Walken,'' he adds. ``It's
his character's story, and it was nice to see Chris play a normal
guy.''
 &HT;    Not to give short shrift to ``The Opportunists,'' but
opportunity really knocks with ``The Tao of Steve.'' The offbeat
romantic comedy places Logue in the spotlight _ it's his
character's story this time. Logue plays Dex, once a college stud
and now, on the eve of his 10-year reunion, a portly kindergarten
teacher whose dating habits are based on the Tao of Steve, a
philosophy incorporating the musings of Lao-tzu, Groucho Marx and
Heidegger.
 &HT;    Dex's belief in the Tao of Steve is put to the test when he
meets Syd (Greer Goodman), a woman who designs scenery for the
Santa Fe Opera and rides motorcycles. And the more he gets to know
Syd, the less useful the Tao of Steve becomes.
 &HT;    The film, co-written by Goodman and Jenniphr Goodman and
directed by Goodman, elicited cheers at the Sundance Film Festival,
and was subsequently snapped up for distribution by Sony Pictures
Classics.
 &HT;    ``I related to the story on every level, as a guy who had to use
his humor and wit and anything else to do well in the Darwinian
process of hooking up with hot chicks when I was in high school and
college,'' Logue says. ``I'd also studied all these thinkers when I
was at Harvard. So many film scripts have pathetic references to,
say, Nietzsche. The people making `Tao of Steve' actually
understood the references they were making.
 &HT;    ``On the set, a lot of ideas were bouncing around between
Jenniphr and Greer, but it was very democratic,'' he adds. ``They
gave me a lot of rope, and I'd also fight for my own ideas
sometimes, and that was OK. Everybody's opinions were respected.''
 &HT;    Heading into release, the buzz is that ``The Tao of Steve''
could emerge as this year's indie sleeper, 2000's ``The Full
Monty.'' Logue likes the sound of that, but he's been there before
and seen his hopes dashed.
 &HT;    ``I'm very psyched that it got to the first stages of that
process, because so many of the `little films that could' that I've
done just never got over the hump,'' he says. ``I did one called
`The Size of Watermelons' (1996) with Paul Rudd. The audience
response to it was similar to `The Tao of Steve,' but it just never
got legs.
 &HT;    ```The Tao of Steve' got to Sundance and it's getting
distribution, but it scares the sh-t out of me what happens after
that,'' he says. ``By virtue of being on 3,000 screens, every major
film in America _ even `Rocky and Bullwinkle' _ gets seen by
someone. Little films start in a couple of cities and go to five
and, hopefully, build to more.
 &HT;    ``So I'm nervous and excited and interested in seeing what
happens,'' he concludes. ``I hope for the best, but expect that it
might not be `The Full Monty.' Could you imagine if it was?''
 &HT;    Later this summer, Logue will appear as part of the ensemble
cast in the Abbie Hoffman biographical feature ``Steal This
Movie!'' And in the fall he'll begin shooting ``Grounded for
Life,'' a television sitcom that Fox will keep on tap as a
midseason replacement.
 &HT;    If either ``The Tao of Steve'' or ``Grounded for Life'' catches
a bit of instant karma and breaks out, Logue could be whisked along
for the ride. Though the prospect of better roles in better
productions appeals to the actor, he once again waves a caution
flag.
 &HT;    ``Having a bit of a name might be nice, but I have no desire to
be a star,'' Logue says, pronouncing the final word as a diva-esque
``stahr.'' ``I get into arguments over this.
 &HT;    ``Some people think, `Well, stars want to be stars,''' the actor
says. ``Yeah, some do, but Kurt Cobain was a talented musician who
I don't think was built in such a way, inside, that he wanted to be
mobbed at the grocery store.
 &HT;    ``You can be an introverted, introspective person and enjoy
being an actor and have a gift for it,'' Logue says. ``I can be
introverted and extroverted. I like people. Right now, anyone I've
met who's recognized me has been very cool and pleasant.
 &HT;    ``I hope that won't change.''
 c.2000 Ian Spelling  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Ian Spelling is a New York-based free-lance writer.) &LR; 
 &UR; EDITOR: For further information on ``The Tao of Steve,'' consult
the official Web site at www.taoofsteve.com. And don't forget to
visit The New York Times Syndicate Web site at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for information on StarBeat and
other features. &QL; 
 &UR; (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) &QL; 
 &UR; (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.)
 &UR; ------------------------------------------------- &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
