<HEADER>
A8549 &Cx1f; tab-z
w e BC-COMIC-BOOK-WRITER-STA     07-31 1457
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COMIC-BOOK-WRITER-STAN-LEE-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STAND-UP COMICS: STAN LEE KEEPS THE CLOBBERIN' COMING 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 (Includes a color slide of comic-book creator Stan Lee, amid
drawings of many of his creations.) 
 By PHILLIP ZONKEL  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features.)  
 &HT;    Stan Lee is ready for his close-up.
 &HT;    In June, the comic-book icon went to Malibu for the shooting of
his walk-on role in the new ``X-Men'' film, which opened July 14.
During a beach scene, as a hideously deformed mutant arises from
the ocean, Lee _ who, along with artist Jack Kirby, created the
X-Men back in 1963 _ has a two-second screen appearance as a
hot-dog vendor.
 &HT;    ``I used the Stanislavsky method,'' Lee says, furrowing his
brow. ``I tried to think like a hot-dog vendor, look like a hot-dog
vendor. I don't think you'd suspect for a minute that I'm not
really a hot-dog vendor.''
 &HT;    Do you want ketchup and mustard with that?
 &HT;    Condiments aside, the 77-year-old Manhattan native is arguably
the most influential comic-book creator of all time.
 &HT;    In 1940 the 16-year-old Lee joined Timely Comics, the precursor
to Marvel Comics, writing everything from horror stories and
Westerns to romances and war dramas. Two decades later he reignited
the faltering super-hero genre, sweeping Marvel Comics to the
industry forefront with his larger-than-life characters, who did
much more than leap tall buildings in a single bound.
 &HT;    By 1968 Lee had revolutionized the comic-book business, creating
such memorable series as ``The Amazing Spider-Man,'' ``The
Avengers,'' ``Daredevil,'' ``Dr. Strange,'' ``The Fantastic Four,''
``The Incredible Hulk,'' ``Iron Man,'' ``Thor'' and ``The X-Men.''
 &HT;    ``He was a prolific creator and really laid the foundation for
Marvel Comics,'' says Michael Dean, news editor of The Comics
Journal, an industry trade publication. ``They were so imitated by
other companies that you could say he laid the foundation for the
comics industry as it exists today.''
 &HT;    Not that Lee can be held responsible for the dark,
ultra-violent, hypersexual comic books that occupy much of today's
market.
 &HT;    ``I used to pride myself on the fact that every story I did
could be read by a very young child without the parent worrying
about it,'' says Lee, relaxing with his feet on his desk in his
office in Encino, Calif. ``I always try to put a little bit of
humor in. I don't like depressing stories. I don't like violence _
I like a lot of action, I like fight scenes, but to me there's a
difference between action and violence.
 &HT;    ``I tried to keep it clean enough and understandable enough for
young kids,'' he concludes, ``and yet intelligent enough and
engrossing enough for older readers. You walk a fine line.''
 &HT;    To judge by the popular success of his 1960s comics _ not to
mention their skyrocketing value as collector's items now _ Lee
seems to have found that balance.
 &HT;    ``I grew up reading these comics, and there's a definite voice
that was unique for the time,'' the 45-year-old Dean says. ``His
main idea was that they would be super-heroes with feet of clay.
They would have the same problems as real people _ Spider-Man had
problems with girls and at work.
 &HT;    ``What you see in the comics is a lot of effort to inject
serious literary elements,'' Dean says. ``You have internal
psychological conflicts within the characters, which you didn't
normally see before Stan Lee. He wanted to elevate the form a
little bit, but also knew how absurd that looked when you put it
alongside guys in costumes swinging from webs. So he established a
very camp tone _ sometimes it's very serious, but often he'll
puncture the story with little asides.''
 &HT;    That mix of serious drama and tongue-in-cheek humor is apparent
in director Brian Singer's hit movie ``X-Men,'' currently topping
the box-office charts. Lee had no creative input on the film _
though he has an executive-producer credit, Lee says, ``It's more
of an honorary title. I didn't have that much to do with producing
it'' _ but screenwriter David Hayter's story is adapted from
original ideas developed by Lee and by Chris Claremont, who wrote
the comic book from 1975 to 1991.
 &HT;    The basic premise of the movie, like that of the comic book, is
the notion that the United States isn't necessarily a land of the
free for people who are different from the norm. It's no
coincidence that Lee launched the comic in 1963, at the height of
the civil-rights movement.
 &HT;    ``There's a connection, but it was subliminal,'' Lee says. ``All
I was thinking about was how to come up with a good team of heroes
and a good team of villains that could have interesting adventures.
 &HT;    ``But when I started writing it, it seemed fun to do heroes with
special powers who not only aren't appreciated by the public, but
also are hated and harassed and hounded by the public,'' he
recalls. ``It occurred to me that that was quite a good metaphor
for bigotry and persecution, because they were being persecuted
just because they were different.''
 &HT;    Thirty-seven years later, Lee believes, those themes are still
relevant.
 &HT;    ``I'm sorry it's needed today. I wish it wasn't necessary, but
we all know it is,'' he says. ``I'm glad Brian Singer and David
Hayter made it a big part of the movie. It will give a depth that
the average action picture doesn't have.''
 &HT;    Lee stopped writing for Marvel on a regular basis in 1972,
moving up to the publisher's office. Five years later he began
writing the daily ``Spider-Man'' newspaper strip, which still is
syndicated in more than 500 newspapers.
 &HT;    In 1998, after 26 years as publisher, Lee left Marvel to join
media guru Peter Paul in launching Stan Lee Media. He left behind a
unique legacy: To date, more than 2 billion of his comic books have
been published in more than 75 countries and 25 different
languages.
 &HT;    A publicly held business, Stan Lee Media creates animation
franchises. The company's initial offering was a comic book
starring the Backstreet Boys as super-heroes. Lee also has joined
forces with his former arch-rivals, DC Comics, for ``Just Imagine
Stan Lee Creating,'' for which he's writing original stories
starring DC titans such as Superman, Batman and Wonder Woman. The
first issues are expected by early 2001.
 &HT;    And now Lee, who won his first comic-book stripes back in the
days of World War II, has entered cyberspace. In February he kicked
off ``The 7th Portal,'' an Internet comic accessible at
www.stanlee.net. It features 14 new crimefighters and evil enemies,
his first new-character creations in more than 25 years.
 &HT;    In other words, at 77 Lee is busier than ever. The only thing
that would make him happier would be if he could stop writing.
 &HT;    ``I don't really like to write,'' he admits. ``Once I'm writing
it's OK, but it's so hard for me to sit down and begin. There are a
million things I'd rather do _ watch television, take a walk, talk
to my wife, ride a bike, do anything.
 &HT;    ``Writing is a lonely process,'' he says. ``I can't have any
distractions. I sit alone in my room and write.
 &HT;    ``I love it when it's finished,'' Lee says, brightening. ``Even
doing it isn't bad _ it's knowing you have to do it that's bad. But
once you're into it, it rolls out.''
 &HT;    But don't expect Stan Lee to put down his pen any time soon.
 &HT;    ``I love creating things,'' he says. ``To me, providing
entertainment of any sort is the most fun you can have. When the
public likes what you're doing, that's so rewarding.''
 c.2000 Phillip Zonkel  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Phillip Zonkel is a Long Beach, Calif.-based free-lance
writer.) &LR; 
 &UR; EDITOR: For further information on Stan Lee Media, consult the
official Web site at www.stanlee.net. And don't forget to visit The
New York Times Syndicate Web site at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for information on StarBeat and
other features. &QL; 
