<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-31 17:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8557 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-COUNTRY-BOOK-REVIEW-N     07-31 1031
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COUNTRY-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`A PLACE IN THE COUNTRY': EGOS IN A DREAM HOUSE `WITHOUT EGO'
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds.: Publication notes are at end of review.) 
 By MICHIKO KAKUTANI     
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In her charming 1989 memoir, ``Sleeping Arrangements,'' Laura
Cunningham created an indelible portrait of her 1950s childhood in
the Bronx. She conjured up a working-class world built on an
absurdly grandiose scale: a world where apartment buildings
sprouted Babylonian turrets and Egyptian friezes, and streets
aspired to be wide Parisian thoroughfares, a now vanished world
that once nurtured a young girl's romantic dreams.
</P>
<P>
   Cunningham's latest book is a kind of bookend to ``Sleeping
Arrangements'': It chronicles the author's journey from the
cacophonous streets of the city to the bucolic, bug-infested hills
of upstate New York and her ongoing love affair with a farmhouse
that she and her ex-husband bought 18 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Though often as engaging as ``Sleeping Arrangements,'' ``A Place
in the Country'' lacks that earlier book's easy, organic shape: It
reads less like a memoir than like a series of overlapping (and
occasionally repetitive) magazine pieces. Some of the chapters are
small, comic essays chronicling a city dweller's bumbling efforts
to master the rudiments of country living: ``Green Acres'' meets
``A Year in Provence.'' Other chapters are more elliptical,
melancholy accounts of Cunningham's attempts to grapple with health
concerns and a failing marriage.
</P>
<P>
   The opening portions of the book recapitulate much of the
material from ``Sleeping Arrangements,'' recounting the author's
girlhood in the Bronx. Her early peripatetic life with her mother,
it seems, instilled in her a craving for a real home: For the first
four years of her life, Cunningham recalls, she and her mother
sought shelter in relatives' overcrowded apartments, camping out in
foyers, entryways, even under dining room tables. It was while
sharing a three-room apartment with five other people that her
dream of living in a stand-alone house took root, a dream shaped by
her immigrant grandmother's memories of a country place, a dacha,
back home in Russia.
</P>
<P>
   After an interlude in the suburban wilds of Tuxedo Park, N.Y. (a
community she satirized in her 1980 novel, ``Third Parties''),
Cunningham and her husband embarked on a 10-year search for the
perfect country house: ``I did not want,'' she writes, ``a house
with a mistaken identity _ a Mediterranean villa or an adobe house.
I wanted a house that sprang naturally from its roots; a native
place, a home farm,'' a house, in other words, ``without ego.''
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, they found their dream house several hours north of
the city: a pale yellow colonial named The Inn, set on 13 acres, at
the very center of what had once been a great estate. To one side
lived Lord and Lady Hodgson, who had been selling off bits of the
family estate over the years; to another side was a dairy farm
owned and operated by a father and son team, Abner Bower Sr. and
Abner Bower Jr.
</P>
<P>
   Like many former city dwellers, Cunningham and her husband soon
succumbed to the ``have to'' mindset of ``the obsessive country
place revisionist.'' Cunningham's passion became turning a cistern
that had been boarded over for more than a century into a swimming
pool, a project that would entail removing all the old water (which
contained, she estimates, some five dozen rat skulls per 5,000
gallons), coating the pit with sealer and then refilling it with
new water.
</P>
<P>
   As for her husband, Cunningham writes, he became obsessed with
stocking their ``farm'' with animals: a menagerie that soon came to
include two demented goats named Lulu and Lulubelle who devoured
50-pound sacks of Goat Chow like bags of potato chips, a half-dozen
foul-smelling geese, 38 irritable chickens and a puffed-up rooster
named Mr. Chicken who ``ate about a hundred dollars' worth of
chicken feed a day'' and soon grew so large that he looked like
``an ad for a chicken or a person in a chicken suit.''
</P>
<P>
   Adept at poking fun at her and her husband's city-slicker
dreams, Cunningham also gives us some delightful portraits of the
people who became their neighbors and friends. She tells us about
the Smithsons, another couple from the city, who stocked their pond
with $10,000 worth of koi fish and installed a zen waterfall. She
recalls Lord Hodgson phoning to apologize for ``the poor color of
the foliage this year'' and hoping ``to do better for you next
fall.'' And she memorializes the estate's late caretaker, Cecil
Green, who for almost 60 years presided over the grounds, tending
to the boilers in winter, the gardens in summer and the year-round
mending of the fences.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because of Cecil,'' she writes, ``I know windmills once stood
behind my house, that potatoes grew in the yard, and that the
foundation that walls my tennis court was once part of a great
dairy barn. `Mice chewed matches,' was how Cecil explained the fire
that burned down the barn long before my time.''
</P>
<P>
   In the course of her own 18 years in the country, Cunningham
says she has witnessed the gradual demise of a way of life. Nearby,
she notes, malls ``were replacing mountains, spawning satellite
strips like lunar landing stations, almost overnight.'' Modular
houses were popping up like mushrooms in the fields, and light
pollution was blanching the nighttime skies. By the turn of the
millennium, Lord Hodgson had sold his manor house to the followers
of an Indian swami, who had once visited the estate in the 19th
century. And the Bowers, too, put their dairy farm on the block.
Their farm equipment was sold at auction, the cows trucked away to
a new home.
</P>
<P>
   A New York City psychiatrist bought the Bowers' farm for just
over a million dollars and within days had workmen tearing down
silos and installing lacquered doors. Cunningham, a city girl who
by now had logged more years in the country than in New York, began
thinking of borrowing some cows from a farmer down the road: She
says she could no longer envision life without them.
</P>
<P>
   PUBLICATION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `A PLACE IN THE COUNTRY'
</P>
<P>
   By Laura Shaine Cunningham
</P>
<P>
   287 pages. Riverhead Books. $24.95.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-31-00 1747EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
