<HEADER>
A8561 &Cx1f; tab-z
r a BC-ECOM-BRIDES-ONLINE-NY     07-31 1182
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ECOM-BRIDES-ONLINE-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ORDERING BRIDES ON THE WEB: OLD BUSINESS, NEW SOURCE  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;    (ATTENTION EDITORS: This article is for use by clients of The
New York Times Syndicate's E-COMMERCE NEWS SERVICE. The weekly
package of articles offers an in-depth look at how the business of
electronic commerce is changing our lives. For more information
about purchasing this article as a ``separate-buy'' _ or becoming a
client of E-COMMERCE NEWS SERVICE _ contact one of the New York
Times Syndicate sales representatives listed at the end of the
text.)
 &HT;    (ART ADV: Color image is available in JPEG format by calling
William Gonzalez at 212-499-3355.) 
 &HT;    
 By JULIE CHECKOWAY  
 c.2000 The New York Times  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   Men with fantasies and women with hopes have always managed to
connect. Now sites that draw on those dreams have exploded across
the Web.
</P>
<P>
   The fastest growth appears to be in sites that promote
international marriages, Internet versions of the 19th-century
mail-order-bride business. More than 200 such sites exist in the
United States alone, with earnings for some estimated at as much as
$2 million a year, although other operators cite much lower
figures.
</P>
<P>
   According to a report by the Immigration and Naturalization
Service, the number of marriages between American men and foreign
women who met through online matchmakers has doubled in the last
decade, totaling 4,000 to 6,000 a year.
</P>
<P>
   The international online-matchmaking services are thriving
largely because of increased Internet access worldwide, low
overhead, low start-up costs and an abundance of eligible foreign
women, 100,000 to 150,000 of whom advertise themselves on
e-matchmaking sites each year.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1970s most mail-order brides came from the Philippines,
where the economy was in shambles. Today more than half of the
online mail-order-bride businesses cater to men seeking mates from
Russia and Ukraine, countries in steep economic decline where, not
coincidentally, women make up more than 80 percent of the
unemployed.
</P>
<P>
   Which is why most such sites are heavy on postings like this
one, from Nataliya, a 29-year-old, divorced nonsmoker from Russia:
``I am tender, caressing dantist with unusual sense of humor. I
have daughter with appearance and character of angel ... I am
looking for man ... not greedy, tender, not tedious.''
</P>
<P>
   Nataliya has been ``viewed'' 655 times since November on
www.cherry-blossoms.com, the site operated by the Hawaii-based
Cherry Blossoms Inc., which has been in the mail-order-bride
business for 26 years. Cherry Blossoms used to rely solely on its
expensively printed catalogs, says Mike Krosky, president of the
company. Today, however, 50 percent of its business comes from the
Internet, compared with only 15 percent to 20 percent in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Choosing a mate from another culture is not unusual _ the United
States is home to millions of cross-cultural marriages. What is new
is the increasing sophistication of international e-matchmakers in
their delivery of services.
</P>
<P>
   Many companies use the same features found on other e-commerce
sites, such as electronic shopping carts. Critics contend that this
approach underscores the suggestion, always present in the bride
business, that the woman is being bought _ a fantasy that, they
contend, contributes to high rates of divorce or abuse after
reality sets in.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever lies at the heart of the transaction, the competitive
advantages _ and the profits _ for site owners arise from their
ability to provide clients with more than merely a woman's address.
</P>
<P>
   The Cherry Blossoms site, for example, boasts a database of more
than 16,000 women, which can be sorted by country of origin,
education, age, eye color, race, height, weight, religion, number
of children and whether she is a smoker or a drinker. A visitor
types in his criteria, and head shots of women who fit that profile
appear on the screen. Double-clicking on a head shot produces a
full-body shot, a biography and vital statistics.
</P>
<P>
   But at Cherry Blossoms and other leading sites, the address
database is merely a portal to a menu of services that are intended
to extract money at nearly every step a client takes toward the
altar.
</P>
<P>
   Cherry Blossoms, like other established sites, begins by
charging a client when he requests an address. Starting at $75,
Krosky's company offers a membership fee that provides a client
with 15 addresses. At the high end is the ``Premier Guaranteed
Membership,'' which, at $595, includes 100 addresses, plus two
``individualized searches'' of the database, which Krosky conducts
on the client's behalf, one-to-one coaching with Krosky _ himself
married three times, most recently to a woman from the Philippines
whom he met through his own business _ and an online photograph and
biography which, Krosky says, guarantees a client ``60-plus
letters'' from women.
</P>
<P>
   Other innovations include e-mail forwarding. A client can
request that his photograph or a love letter be hand-delivered in
three to five days, rather than in two to three weeks by
international mail.
</P>
<P>
   One of Krosky's competitors, Scanna International
(www.scanna &QC; .com), adds a link to Flower and Gift International
(www.smartlink.net &QC; /ais/flower). There the delivery of roses, a box
of chocolates and a card costs a customer at least $155, and can
also include _ at additional cost, of course _ a snapshot of the
woman receiving her gift. Another rival, Euroladies
(www.euroladies.com), offers three-way conference calling with an
interpreter.
</P>
<P>
   Both Euroladies and Scanna offer the fiancee a visa-preparation
kit. At the top of the price scale are organized tours to Russia
and Ukraine, offered by Euroladies and Scanna. Euroladies
guarantees that men will meet more than 800 women in 10 days for
$3,000 to $5,000, including hotel and airfare. Scanna offers a
referral to Anastasia Tours, which offers tours for the same price
as Euroladies. Anastasia's tours include introductions to 600 to
1,000 women and a 10-percent discount ``when you bring a friend.''
</P>
<P>
   Even if true love does not last, the e-matchmaking sites are
ready to help: Some men are repeat customers, returning to the same
Internet site on which they had found a previous, now-ex wife.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Julie Checkoway is director of the creative-writing program at
the University of Georgia in Athens.) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; -------------------------------------------------
</P>
<P>
   EDITOR: Visit The New York Times Syndicate Web site at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for more information on E-COMMERCE
NEWS SERVICE and other features.
</P>
<P>
   NONSUBSCRIBERS: To publish a ``separate-buy'' feature article,
it must be purchased. Please contact one of these sales
representatives:
</P>
<P>
   --U.S. and Canada: DEBRA WEYDERT in New Jersey at
1-732-390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697.
</P>
<P>
   --Europe and Asia: KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11; fax,
47-42-80-44 or 47-42-18-81; telex, 282-942.
</P>
<P>
   --Latin America: ANA PENA in New York, 212-499-3333; fax,
212-499-3382.
</P>
