<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-31 17:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8565 &Cx1f; ttf-z
r a BC-ECOM-SMALL-BUSINESSES     07-31 1218
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ECOM-SMALL-BUSINESSES-ON-WEB-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHRINKING WORLD MEANS BIG GAINS FOR THE LITTLE GUYS, TOO  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;    (ATTENTION EDITORS: This article is for use by clients of The
New York Times Syndicate's E-COMMERCE NEWS SERVICE. The weekly
package of articles offers an in-depth look at how the business of
electronic commerce is changing our lives. For more information
about purchasing this article as a ``separate-buy'' _ or becoming a
client of E-COMMERCE NEWS SERVICE _ contact one of the New York
Times Syndicate sales representatives listed at the end of the
text.)
 &HT;    
 By BARBARA WHITAKER  
 c.2000 The New York Times  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   For a private investigator near Cincinnati, it means a chance to
find better prices on office supplies and T-shirts. To the owner of
five convenience stores in Mississippi, it opens doors to
expansion.
</P>
<P>
   Individually, small businesses may seem like small potatoes, but
as a whole, they are increasingly seen as a big deal when it comes
to business-to-business transactions on the Internet. A myriad of
dot-com companies are developing marketplaces and services to give
small businesses the same opportunities available to large
corporations.
</P>
<P>
   ``Suddenly, the whole world can be your territory,'' said Bruce
Richardson, a senior vice president at AMR Research Inc., an
industry and market analysis firm in Boston specializing in
e-business strategy and infrastructure. ``You know the saying, `On
the Internet, no one knows you're a dog.' It's sort of been the
great equalizer.''
</P>
<P>
   Over the past year, Internet-based business exchanges,
e-marketplaces and free and fee-based business services have
proliferated for small and midsize businesses.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, the field is ``not out of diapers,'' said Thomas M.
Koulopoulos, the president and founder of Delphi Group, an advisory
company specializing in business and technology. He and other
analysts think it will be three to five years before these
exchanges become serious e-commerce operations.
</P>
<P>
   But as with most things related to the Internet, time is of the
essence as marketplaces vie to organize the buyers and sellers that
will determine the success of these ventures. While big businesses
with well-established supply chains have an advantage, the sheer
magnitude of small business _ there are 5.5 million businesses with
fewer than 500 employees in the United States _ makes them an
attractive group to organize.
</P>
<P>
   The likely result, Koulopoulos said, ``is a pecking order, a
hierarchy of exchanges.''
</P>
<P>
   At the top are exchanges controlled by big corporations, such as
automakers, which broaden into smaller business sectors that are
just beginning to form. The creation of such markets is viewed as
an opportunity to fundamentally change the way small businesses
operate.
</P>
<P>
   But while the potential is there, many small businesses lack the
equipment and ability to participate fully. For companies trying to
establish marketplaces, that can mean providing a little help.
</P>
<P>
   For example, GlobalSupplyNet.com, a company that organizes the
janitorial supply industry, is providing some of its clients with
computers and initially allowing them to use the service for free.
</P>
<P>
   They see the highly fragmented business as the perfect target.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a $32 billion industry, and they're all little players,''
said Steven Odzer, the company's founder. ``These people want to
use the Internet, but they have no one to help them.''
</P>
<P>
   While organizing marketplaces is the main goal of many
companies, many small businesses are entering the marketplaces
piecemeal, often as buyers looking for better prices on supplies.
</P>
<P>
   Joe Ryan, a private investigator near Cincinnati with a
family-run business called Investigative Concepts, turned to
Mondus.com, an e-marketplace geared to small and midsize
businesses, to see whether he could save money in purchasing.
</P>
<P>
   Mondus allows businesses to obtain competitive quotes on goods
and services. Ryan estimated that he saved about half of what he
normally spent on items such as envelopes and stationery.
</P>
<P>
   For Malcolm Carmichael, the vice president of a family-owned
business that operates five convenience stores near Laurel, Miss.,
the Internet has offered a means to eliminate the voluminous
paperwork for inventory and bookkeeping. The task was eating up
hours of manpower and keeping the company from expanding.
</P>
<P>
   Carmichael said he had looked at stand-alone systems to link his
stores, but they would have cost $50,000 to $80,000 to build, not
including upkeep. But through a recent Internet offering,
Storereport.com, he has accomplished the same connection for $99 a
month for each store with an investment of less than $4,000 in
computers.
</P>
<P>
   Storereport is a good example of the ambitions being built on
the small-business market. Bill Scott, who created the site, wants
to do more than link stores to process their paperwork. His goal is
to create a Web market to serve oil marketers and gas-station and
convenience-store operators.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we had 35,000 convenience stores online, we'd be in a
position to do that,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   So far, Scott has five customers with 20 convenience stores,
most of which also sell gasoline. He hopes that his expertise in
technology will help him organize the market, but competition will
most likely be fierce. Five other groups, including the National
Association of Convenience Stores, would like to do the same thing,
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Finding an established group to build on is becoming
increasingly important for companies setting up
business-to-business operations. While analysts estimate that more
than 600 business exchanges are operating on the Internet, they
predict that number will shrink to fewer than 100 by 2001 because
independent exchanges have found it hard to attract and control
business.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the doors being opened, the jumble of offerings and
shifting playing fields can make it difficult for small businesses
to find what works for them.
</P>
<P>
   ``The hardest part is finding these sites,'' said Maria
Barreros, the business development manager at KNC Marketing, the
company Investigative Concepts used for its T-shirt purchase on the
Mondus site.
</P>
<P>
   Barreros has sold excess inventory on eBay and scoured
government purchasing sites. But it can still be difficult to find
what you need, she said, and it's easy for a small business to get
overlooked when selling.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know my boss believes that if we're not in this within the
next couple of years, we'd be out of business,'' Barreros said.
``But at this time it hasn't made a big impact.''
</P>
<P>
   -------------------------------------------------
</P>
<P>
   EDITOR: Visit The New York Times Syndicate Web site at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for more information on E-COMMERCE
NEWS SERVICE and other features.
</P>
