<P>
   SHRINKING WORLD MEANS BIG GAINS FOR THE LITTLE GUYS, TOO
</P>
<P>
   ECOM-SMALL-BUSINESSES-ON-WEB _ Small businesses are increasingly
becoming a big deal when it comes to business-to-business
transactions on the Internet. A myriad of dot-com companies are
developing marketplaces and services to give small businesses the
same opportunities available to large corporations. For example,
the Internet enabled Malcolm Carmichael to eliminate inventory and
bookkeeping paperwork for the five convenience stores he operates
near Laurel, Miss. Joe Ryan, a private investigator in the
Cincinnati area, has cut his office-supply expenses in half by
using Mondus.com. By Barbara Whitaker.
</P>
<P>
   ORDERING BRIDES ON THE WEB: OLD BUSINESS, NEW SOURCE
</P>
<P>
   ECOM-BRIDES-ONLINE _ Men with fantasies and women with hopes
have always managed to connect. Now sites that draw on those dreams
have exploded across the Web. The fastest growth appears to be in
sites that promote international marriages, Internet versions of
the 19th-century mail-order-bride business. More than 200 such
sites exist in the United States alone, with earnings for some
estimated at as much as $2 million a year. A report. By Julie
Checkoway. WITH PHOTO.
</P>
