A8554 &Cx1f; tab-z
w a BC-JOHN-WATERS-DIRECTS-C     07-31 1465
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JOHN-WATERS-DIRECTS-CECIL-B-DEMENTED-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SWIRLING WATERS: JOHN WATERS ZOOMS IN ON `CECIL B. DEMENTED' 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 (Includes a color slide of John Waters directing Melanie Griffith
in a scene from ``Cecil B. Demented.'') 
 By SHEP MORGAN  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features.)  
 &HT;    Call him ``the pope of trash,'' a moniker bestowed by none other
than American scatological icon William Burroughs. Call him ``the
duke of dirt.'' Call him ``trashmeister.''
 &HT;    Whatever you call him, John Waters was shocking audiences long
before the Farrelly brothers first struck box-office gold with
their wildly outrageous comedies.
 &HT;    Now the 54-year-old anti-establishment filmmaker, whose perverse
sense of humor and talent for cultural satire are as sharp as his
pencil-thin mustache, is taking on Hollywood itself in ``Cecil B.
Demented,'' opening nationwide on Aug. 11.
 &HT;    The action-filled, off-the-wall send-up stars Melanie Griffith
as a movie queen kidnaped by the crazed Cecil B. Demented (Stephen
Dorff) to star in a radical underground movie. The supporting cast
includes such Waters regulars as Ricki Lake, Patricia Hearst and
Mink Stole.
 &HT;    Waters got the idea for his latest effort from the gay newspaper
The Advocate.
 &HT;    ``They did an interview with me and called me `Cecil B.
Demented,''' he recalls. ``It made me laugh, and I took it as a
compliment. Then I began to think about creating a fictitious
super-hero who was willing to risk everything, even his life, to
make an anti-Hollywood propaganda movie.
 &HT;    ``It's got a lot of action scenes,'' he adds, ``which I've never
done before. I call it my `Die Hard for the Hollywood-Impaired.'''
 &HT;    While shootouts, fights and car chases abound in ``Cecil B.
Demented,'' the black comedy's biggest surprise is Griffith's
no-holds-barred spoof of the stereotypically spoiled, difficult
Hollywood diva.
 &HT;    ``I knew I had to get a real A-list actress to play the part,''
Waters says. ``I think Melanie was very brave to take on that whole
persona of the star bitch. She has a really good sense of humor
about herself, which is why she's survived the ups and downs of
making films.
 &HT;    ``After she saw the script, I went to her house for a meeting,''
he continues. ``It was right up the street from where O.J. used to
live, which gave me a nightmare vision as I drove by. Then I
knocked on her door, and Melanie answered wearing skintight
black-leather jeans, a T-shirt with a skull on it, and no make-up.
 &HT;    ``I thought, `There's my girl.'''
 &HT;    Griffith dove wholeheartedly into the tasteless, foul-mouthed
spirit of the film.
 &HT;    ``I told her she was a Waters girl and she had to go for it,''
the director says. ``We did have a little negotiation over her
fringed hair, false eyelashes and mascara. Let's just say we talked
about that more than her swearing.''
 &HT;    Ironically, Waters admits that he had more qualms about one
outrageous moment than Griffith did.
 &HT;    ``There's a scene where she's giving Ricki Lake, who plays her
assistant, a hard time,'' he recalls, ``and Melanie says something
like, `I'm in the presidential suite where Nixon and his wife
stayed _ find out if Pat Nixon got f--ked here.'
 &HT;    ``My uncle was undersecretary of the interior for Nixon,'' the
director says, ``and I suddenly thought, `If he sees this, he's
really going to get mad.' But I left it in.''
 &HT;    Griffith has praised Waters as a filmmaker who ``doesn't give a
sh-t,'' but he doesn't quite see that as a compliment.
 &HT;    ``I do give a sh-t what people think,'' he says. ``Otherwise, I
don't think I'd have been making movies for 36 years. I do care,
and bad reviews are more painful than good reviews. I guess you
could say my list of people whose opinions are important to me is
selective.''
 &HT;    The film's radical moviemakers are wont to spout anti-industry
slogans such as ``Hey, hey, MPAA, how many movies do we have to
censor today?'' _ but, ironically, Waters had less trouble than
usual with the Motion Picture Association of America and its
ratings board.
 &HT;    ``We got an R for `Cecil B. Demented,''' he says, ``for `crude
sexual content, violence, drug usage and language.'
 &HT;    ``I hate it when they say `language,''' he adds. ``That's just
poor English. Why don't they just come out and say `bad language?'
Anyway, an R for a John Waters film is certainly nothing to get
excited about. I was happier when they gave the re-release of `Pink
Flamingos' an NC-17.''
 &HT;    As with all his films, from the enduring cult favorite ``Pink
Flamingos'' (1972) to ``Hairspray'' (1988), ``Serial Mom'' (1994)
and ``Pecker'' (1998), ``Cecil B. Demented'' was shot in the
director's native Baltimore, where some of the town's oldest and
most famous movie palaces were the setting for attacks on
everything from high concession prices to emotionally simplistic
family films.
 &HT;    Going to movies isn't as much fun as it used to be, Waters
believes.
 &HT;    ``More than anything, I'm bothered by people who talk during a
screening,'' he says. ``I got in a big fight the other day because
someone was yakking nonstop in `Scary Movie.' I loved it when
someone in the film got killed for talking in a theater _ it was
like art imitating life.
 &HT;    ``I also hate people who bring babies,'' he adds. ``I actually
said to one couple with a kid who started crying, `Couldn't you get
a baby sitter?' They said, `Sorry, no.' Like it was my problem.''
 &HT;    Waters drew on his own experience to depict the bargain-basement
world of Cecil B. Demented and his no-budget productions.
 &HT;    ``I couldn't have made `Pink Flamingos' without some financial
help from my father _ and thankfully he never saw it, because I
know he would hate it,'' Waters says. ``I actually went over budget
_ I had planned to spend $10,000, and it cost $12,000.
 &HT;    ``I was doing films on a shoestring and on the run,'' he
recalls. ``I guess my worst experience was getting arrested while
we were doing `Mondo Trasho' (1969) with Divine. It was a scene
where she's driving in a big red Cadillac, and she passes this
hitchhiker and imagines he's nude. So we had this naked guy
standing by the side of the road, and somebody called the cops.
 &HT;    ``We ran and Divine got away,'' Waters says, ``which doesn't say
much for the Baltimore cops, since she weighed about 300 pounds.
They caught me, and I was charged with conspiracy to commit
indecent exposure. I got off, but I remember having to show all my
films to the district attorney, which was a memorable moment.''
 &HT;    Ironically, Waters tells the story of Cecil B. Demented at a
time when his own career has been edging into the mainstream, with
his recent films enjoying larger budgets and wider audiences.
 &HT;    ``Even though I'm spoofing Hollywood movies, I'd have to say
Hollywood has not been horrible to me,'' he admits. ``I've had some
executives say, `I love your movies, but I couldn't risk my job by
giving you the money to do one.' I understand that. I'm not going
to give them a huge hit.''
 &HT;    As for his enduring reputation as, to quote one critic, ``the
arbiter of blatant, graphic tastelessness,'' Waters doesn't shy
away from it.
 &HT;    ``I plead guilty,'' he says, ``but I'd like to put one adjective
before those words: `joyous.' I can think of movies that are
tasteless and vile, but they aren't witty and they aren't very
funny. I've done comic obscenity and joyous obscenity.
 &HT;    ``I'm not Cecil B. Demented,'' he concludes with a shrug. ``But
if he were real and made a movie, I'd be the first to buy a
ticket.''
 c.2000 Pentacom Productions  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Shep Morgan is a Hollywood-based free-lance writer.) &LR; 
 &UR; EDITOR: For further information on ``Cecil B. Demented,'' consult
the official Web site at www.dementedforever.com. And don't forget
to visit The New York Times Syndicate Web site at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for information on StarBeat and
other features. &QL; 
