<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Tuesday, Aug. 1, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York
Times News Service. For information call: 888-603-1036.) 
 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   All-time high temperatures will be in jeopardy in a few places
across the Great Basin Tuesday as heat intensifies under the
auspice of very warm high pressure aloft. Daily records will
probably fall in parts of Utah, Idaho, Nevada and interior
California, while thunderstorms sprout over mountains in response
to the uneven heating of valleys and peaks.
</P>
<P>
   Isolated but potent thunderstorms will menace eastern Montana
and western North Dakota near a warm front. Meanwhile, locally
heavy rains will douse the central Gulf Coast as sluggish
thunderstorms erupt.
</P>
<P>
   Hit-or-miss clusters of thunderstorms will produce locally heavy
rains over the sultry Middle Atlantic states. Locally heavy rains
are also possible over upstate New York and southern New England.
</P>
<P>
   FOCUS: ELUSIVE TARGET
</P>
<P>
   Warnings were in effect Monday for the island of Oahu as
Tropical Storm Daniel, which sprung to life off the coast of Mexico
on July 23, passed north of Hawaii. Since 1950, only three
hurricanes have directly affected Hawaii. In all three cases, Kauai
was the only big island to be hit. Hurricane Iniki and Hurricane
Iwa, both of which formed over the central Pacific in 1992 and 1982
respectively, lashed Kauai, although, technically, Iwa's eye did
not quite come ashore. In 1950, Hurricane Dot hit Kauai, making it
the only eastern Pacific hurricane to hit the Hawaiian Islands in
half of a century.
</P>
</TEXT>
