<P>
   CVN-POVERTY &QL;
</P>
<P>
   LAREDO, Texas _ For the nation's political establishment, these
are exciting times. The nominating conventions are under way. Vice
presidential candidates are being picked and vetted. Ads are
hitting the airwaves. But here in dusty Ranchitos 359, an
impoverished ``colonia'' on Texas 359 outside Laredo, convention
fever has not taken hold. Indeed, as far as Dolores Estrada is
concerned, Philadelphia and the Republican National Convention
might as well be on the moon. She is equally unimpressed with the
Democrats, despite their recent claims that Gov. George W. Bush is
to blame for the decades-old, grinding poverty here. By JAY ROOT.
Story has moved in ``p'' political category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   CVN-PHILLY &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ This city will never escape its history. Nor its
reputation. As the natives would say, you got yer Ben Franklin. You
got yer George Washington. But the name everybody remembers first
is yer Santa Claus. ``This is the city that booed Santa Claus,''
said Steve Harmon, a former Dallas radio personality now at a
budding Philadelphia country music station. ``People here know all
about that.'' That was at halftime of a Philadelphia Eagles pro
football game in 1968, not as long ago in memory as the city's last
national political conventions in 1948. This week, the nation will
see whether the same Philadelphia that bitterly despises the Dallas
Cowboys will boo or cheer two guys from Texas: George W. Bush and
Dick Cheney. By BUD KENNEDY. Story has moved in ``p'' political
category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   CVN-SANDERS-COLUMN &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ Back in the days when television was broadcast
mostly in black and white, the National Broadcasting Company
created a stylized peacock to remind viewers that it had more color
than any other network. This week, the GOP will begin displaying
its own peacock image, hoping to prove that it, too, can present
programs ``in living color.'' After Thursday, Republicans hope to
be known as the ``full color'' party. By BOB RAY SANDERS. Story has
moved in ``p'' political category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   CVN-TEXAS DELEGATES &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ Bill Eastland stepped through his first political
loophole at 16 while growing up in the affluent Highland Park
neighborhood of Dallas. It was summer 1964, and Eastland and some
buddies decided to stage a carwash to raise money for Barry
Goldwater's Republican presidential bid. But red tape threatened
when the ``local constabulary'' wouldn't let them carry political
signs on a busy corner. That's where politics came in. By KAREN
BROOKS. Story has moved in ``p'' political category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   N A T I O N A L &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   MURDERABILIA &QL;
</P>
<P>
   UNDATED _ Foot scrapings from ``railroad killer'' Angel Maturino
Resendiz: $9.99. Crime-scene photos of Charles Manson murder victim
Sharon Tate: $62. A letter written by Darlie Routier, the convicted
child killer from Rowlett, Texas: $20. On eBay and other online
auction sites, so-called ``murderabilia'' can create the same kind
of bidding frenzy as Beanie Babies or Pokemon cards. But the
practice has drawn the wrath of some victims' rights advocates, who
contend that it is wrong for the sellers to make money off the
notoriety of brutal crimes. By MARY DOCLAR. Story has moved in
``a'' general news category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   L I F E S T Y L E &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
