<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-31 18:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8595 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a BC-PLAYBOY-GORE-HNS &LR;      07-31 0502
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PLAYBOY-GORE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     CATHOLIC LEAGUE URGES GORE TO CANCEL PLAYBOY MANSION
FUND-RAISER 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)   
 &HT;     By JUDY HOLLAND   
 &HT;     c.1999 Hearst Newspapers   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Catholic League on Monday urged Vice President
Al Gore to cancel a Democratic fund-raiser scheduled for next month
at the Playboy mansion in Los Angeles, saying it is ``offensive''
and ``disconcerting.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Loretta Sanchez, D-Calif., who Gore has tapped to be vice
chairman of the Democratic National Committee, has planned an
invitation-only Aug. 15 reception during the Democratic convention
for her political action committee, Hispanic Unity, at the mansion
of Playboy magazine founder Hugh Hefner.
</P>
<P>
   That date coincides with the Feast of the Assumption, a Catholic
Holy Day that commemorates the taking into heaven of Mary.
</P>
<P>
   ``To hold an event on this date at a place that celebrates the
denigration of women is particularly offensive to Catholics,'' said
William A. Donohue, president of the Catholic League, the nation's
largest Catholic Civil Rights Organization. ``To top it off, since
most Hispanics are Catholic, it is sending a message that is doubly
objectionable.''
</P>
<P>
   Donohue said Playboy writers have made ``disparaging'' remarks
about Catholics and noted that the magazine has contributed to
Catholics for Free Choice, a pro-abortion group denounced by the
bishops in 1993 and 2000. He urged Gore in an open letter released
Monday to cancel the fund-raiser.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not to do so would be to send a message to Catholics that is
disconcerting,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But Sanchez, 40, has refused to back down, insisting the
reception will continue as planned.
</P>
<P>
   Sarah Anderson, a spokeswoman for Sanchez, said it would be held
outside the grounds of the Hefner mansion in a tent. ``There will
not be playmates attending this event,'' Anderson said. ``We are
only using the mansion.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore has objected to the venue of the event, but has stopped
short of publicly calling for Sanchez to change it.
</P>
<P>
   Hefner and his daughter, Christie Hefner, CEO of Playboy
Enterprises, have given $1,500 to Gore's presidential campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Patrick Scully, a spokesman for the Catholic League said it
isn't enough for Gore to voice disapproval.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not good enough that Gore said he isn't going, he ought
to cancel it,'' Scully said.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Rep. Patrick J. Kennedy, D-R.I., chairman of the
Democratic Congressional Campaign Committee, said the Playboy party
``sets a bad public image`` for his party.
</P>
<P>
   He told National Public Radio he will discourage his colleagues
from attending, saying the event ``totally contradicts what our
party stands for in terms of equal rights, civil rights for all
people and respecting the human dignity of every individual.''
</P>
<P>
   The Playboy Foundation, six corporations and a 40-member host
committee are underwriting the event. About 600 people are expected
to pay $5,000 each to attend and Hefner is expected to drop by.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-31-00 1821EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000731.0290 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-31 18:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8597 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-CVN-BUSH-FALL01-COX     07-31 0976
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CVN-BUSH-FALL01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    FBy KEN HERMAN
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ Gov. George W. Bush, who got his current
government job by picking four issues and hammering on them ad
infinitum, will use an expanded version of the same strategy to try
to win the White House.
</P>
<P>
   ``We hope he has matured and grown, so it's five (issues), not
four,'' Karl Rove, Bush's long-time strategist, said Monday as the
Republican National Convention got under way.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1994 Texas gubernatorial race, the Big Four issues were
juvenile justice, welfare, education and tort reform. For the next
100 days, Bush will work to put the focus on education, Social
Security and Medicare, tax cuts, military overhaul and what Rove
calls ``the next step in welfare reform.''
</P>
<P>
   Stand by for overkill.
</P>
<P>
   ``At about the time that you begin to get really sick of (the
five issues), the American people will say, `You know what? Bush is
talking about five things and we ought to give him a chance to do
those things,''' said Rove.
</P>
<P>
   The path that Bush is confident will be his road to the White
House also includes help from the other side. Every Al Gore attack
is a boost, say Bush aides who believe the electorate is in the
mood for positive campaigns and will punish those who go negative.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will respond if attacked,'' said Rove, ``but I think the
American people after the last eight years, and for a lot of other
reasons, are at a point where they would prefer to learn more about
the candidates and their respective agendas. ... What matters this
year is less the punch that the counterpunch.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush stayed positive in both his gubernatorial races. But he
showed a negative side this year when Sen. John McCain of Arizona
made some strong showings in the presidential primaries, including
running a radio ad accusing McCain of voting against money for
cancer research.
</P>
<P>
   Rove declined to identify the cancer ad as counterpunching.
</P>
<P>
   ``Counterpunching is when a charge is leveled and the rejoinder
both answers the charge and elevates the debate,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Bush strategy looks good on paper, according to University
of Virginia political scientist Larry Sabato. But it's never been
road-tested.
</P>
<P>
   ``My question is to what degree will they respond to Gore's
negativity,'' he said. ``That's critical. It's hard for me to
imagine Bush would willingly play Dukakis,'' who wasn't aggressive
enough against former President Bush and lost the 1988 election.
</P>
<P>
   ``Will they merely counterpunch? Will they launch their own
attacks?'' he asked. ``If the answer is no, Gore has a good
chance.''
</P>
<P>
   Rove doesn't think so.
</P>
<P>
   ``I made it clear. And if not I'll make it clear even more
emphatically, we will counterpunch. We will not sit supinely by and
absorb the blows, let them distort the record and go on. We will
come back and we will come back hard. People will respond to that
better than they will the initial assault,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Bush strategy also will be heavy on the candidate's image as
a guy you'd like to have lunch with, a factor long cited by even
his political foes in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's this myth that the Democrats want to run the campaign
on issues and we want to run it on personality,'' said Rove.
``That's half-right. ... We want to run it on personality AND
issues.''
</P>
<P>
   The dual approach is calculated to score well for Bush among
three groups his team has targeted as pivotal: suburbanites,
Catholics and Hispanics.
</P>
<P>
   Bush aides are defining suburbanites as men and women in
slightly older suburbs. They generally align as what Rove calls
``weak Republicans or unaffiliated independents.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush believes his five-issue campaign plays right into what's on
these voters' minds.
</P>
<P>
   Bush has been working on Catholics ever since McCain and others
tried to nail him for speaking at Bob Jones University in South
Carolina, a school with anti-Catholic teachings.
</P>
<P>
   The Catholic factor this year is multiplied by their
disproportionate numbers in some key states, including the
industrial Midwest.
</P>
<P>
   While Bush probably has to carry the suburban and Catholic votes
to win the White House, he merely has to make a strong showing
among Hispanics.
</P>
<P>
   There are relatively few Hispanics in many of the swing states,
but Hispanics will be important in California and Florida. A
California win probably would guarantee victory.
</P>
<P>
   The overall strategy is geared to a bottom line that Bush now is
just 44 electoral votes short of the 270 needed for victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a lot of opportunities from which to get the
additional 44,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to preparing for the day-to-day campaign, Bush aides
are working toward key moments, such as the debates scheduled for
October.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our debate strategy can be summed up in one word: Survive,''
he said. ``We hope to survive Governor Bush's necessary appearance
in debates against the world's most pre-eminent debater, a man who
is more proficient at hand-to-hand debate combat than anybody the
world has ever seen.''
</P>
<P>
   As the real battle draws near, Team Bush _ backed by polls
showing their man surging _ is convinced the candidate has the
right five issues, the right style and the right message.
</P>
<P>
   ``The election is far from over,'' said Rove. ``This race is
going to be, by Labor Day, single digits one way or the other.
There are going to be points after the Democratic convention where,
in all likelihood, we are going to be behind.''
</P>
<P>
   But Rove knows there is no masking a strategist who believes he
has hit on just the right strategy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I apologize if I sound overconfident,'' he said. ``I'm the
most anxiety-ridden guy you've ever met in your life.''
</P>
<P>
   Ken Herman's e-mail address is kherman(at)statesman.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
