<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-31 18:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8598 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r k BC-SANDERS-COLUMN-TEX     07-31 0725
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SANDERS-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TWO MEETING HOUSES, BUT WHAT A WORLD OF DIFFERENCE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients)
 By BOB RAY SANDERS 
 c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ It's a long way from the 1,000-seat Arch Street
Meeting House, a half block from where Betsy Ross sewed the first
Stars and Stripes in 1777, to the 22,000-seat First Union Center
across town.
</P>
<P>
   Not in distance. But in time. And purpose.
</P>
<P>
   The meeting house was built in 1804 by the Religious Society of
Friends (or Quakers). It sits on property that Pennsylvania founder
William Penn had set aside about a hundred years earlier as a
burial ground for members.
</P>
<P>
   More than 20,000 people are interred there, many of them having
died from a series of yellow fever epidemics in the late 18th
century.
</P>
<P>
   It's hallowed ground.
</P>
<P>
   The First Union Center is home to the Philadelphia 76ers
basketball team, the Philadelphia Flyers hockey team, other
big-time sports and entertainment events and, for this week only,
the Republican National Convention. The $210 million arena has 126
private suites and 14 club boxes.
</P>
<P>
   It's something to see, but there's nothing holy about it.
</P>
<P>
   How I wish the people gathered at First Union Center could learn
something from the folks who still assemble at the nearly
200-year-old Arch Street Meeting House. After all, Republicans came
back to Philadelphia _ their very first convention was held here in
1856 _ to remember, reflect and reportedly to reaffirm some of the
ideas and principles of the Founding Fathers and mothers.
</P>
<P>
   Sandy Sudofsky, a receptionist and tour guide at the meeting
house, proudly and reverently told a curious North Texas visitor
about her meeting there last week.
</P>
<P>
   She explained that although the weekly, monthly and annual
meetings at the house are scheduled, they are not planned,
conducted or otherwise orchestrated. In fact, most of the worship
``service'' (for lack of a better word) is held in absolute
silence.
</P>
<P>
   ``At my meeting a week ago, we started in silence,'' she said in
a tone just above a whisper. ``We were silent for almost 15 minutes
when this melifluous voice sang the first verse of ``Amazing
Grace.'' There was another 10 minutes of silence, and then six- or
seven-minute messages, all building on this idea of God's glory.''
</P>
<P>
   She paused, then continued: ``Some more silence, and then this
equally beautiful voice sang the last verse of ``Amazing Grace''
and tied it all together.''
</P>
<P>
   No one in the crowd of 100 had appointed the speakers or
singers, she told me.
</P>
<P>
   ``We did it completely spontaneously,'' she said. ``We felt a
closeness to God, and a closeness to each other.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole meeting was unprogrammed.''
</P>
<P>
   Unprogrammed?
</P>
<P>
   There is no way the thousands of folks meeting at First Union
Center this week could go ``unprogrammed.'' Even the ``surprises''
have been carefully planned.
</P>
<P>
   Everything has been timed, rehearsed and evaluated for its
effectiveness before a national audience. There is no room for
spontaneity. Even the thousands of red, white and blue balloons are
netted in place high above the convention floor waiting for their
precise cue to float down to the screaming crowd after Gov. George
W. Bush makes his acceptance speech as the Republican nominee for
president.
</P>
<P>
   Before I left the house, Sudofsky proudly told me about how the
Quakers had treated the Indians, and their slaves (before slavery
was banned by the group in 1776), and the part the Friends played
in the Underground Railroad to help liberate blacks. She spoke of
how they had welcomed other religious groups, even those that had
been abusive to Quakers in the past.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were inclusive,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   And that's what the Republican are trying to be here: inclusive.
The Republican National Committee even dedicated a giant mural last
weekend to the people of Philadelphia, honoring Harriet Tubman and
those brave men and women who operated the Underground Railroad. It
towers above Chestnut Street, and it is magnificent.
</P>
<P>
   It was a very nice gesture by the GOP. But, of course, it had
been programmed.
</P>
<P>
   (Bob Ray Sanders is a columnist for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. You can call him at (817) 390-7775, or e-mail:
bobray(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
