u p BC-CVN-BUSH-STRATEGY-HNS     07-31 1018
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CVN-BUSH-STRATEGY-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
BUSH STRATEGIST OUTLINES ELECTORAL MAP &HT;    (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)
 &HT;    By STEWART M. POWELL and CHARLES J. LEWIS
 &HT;    c.2000 Hearst Newspapers
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLUMBUS, Ohio Republican George W. Bush, vowing to be a
populist president who ``stands by your side,'' headed toward the
GOP convention Monday buoyed by his campaign's calculation that he
leads in enough states to be within 44 electoral votes of winning
the White House.
</P>
<P>
   Bush cautioned enthusiastic campaign audiences across Ohio
against overconfidence, warning that his edge in state-by-state
polls across the nation could slip once Vice President Al Gore
storms out of the Democratic convention in mid-August.``I want to
remind you, the polls may look good today that's the good news,''
Bush told several thousand invited partisans gathered beneath
rain-threatening skies on the campus of the University of Dayton, a
150-year-old Roman Catholic college.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bad news is the election isn't tomorrow. We've got a lot
of work to do and I'm looking forward to doing the work.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Mike Dewine, R-Ohio, echoed the cautionary tone. ``Make no
mistake about it this is going to be a tough race,'' Dewine warned,
urging GOP loyalists in the bellwether state of Ohio to turn out to
vote in November.
</P>
<P>
   As Bush and Dewine were urging caution, Bush's chief political
strategist, Karl Rove, told reporters at the GOP convention in
Philadelphia that state-by-state polls show Bush ahead in enough
states to put him just 44 votes shy of the 270 electoral votes
needed to capture the presidency.
</P>
<P>
   Rove said Bush has rolled up an electoral edge in state-by-state
polls that include Alaska, the swath of states from California's
Sierra Nevada mountains across the Plains to the Missouri River,
most of the South and Indiana. Rove said his calculation showed
Bush leading in polls in states with a total of 226 electoral votes
just 44 votes shy of the 270 electoral votes needed to win the
presidency.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is an embarrassment of opportunities for the Bush
campaign'' because so many states look like they could go for Bush
in November, Rove boasted to reporters in Philadelphia, site of the
GOP convention that opened Monday. He said Bush's electoral
strength in other states, including Washington state and some
Midwestern states, provides ``a lot of opportunities from which to
get the additional 44 (electoral votes) to make up for any that we
may lose'' in the West or the South.
</P>
<P>
   Tucker Eskew, a Bush campaign spokesman based at the GOP
convention, emphasized the campaign's snapshot of the
state-by-state electoral calculus could change at any time. ``We
feel those electoral votes are ours today but that's today,'' Eskew
said. ```The count could change at any time and probably will.'''
``We're 44 votes shy in this accounting but if you take Washington,
Oregon, California, Iowa and Missouri or some combination of those
states you're getting to where you need to be,'' Eskew said.
``Ideally, you want a comfortable margin of victory but 270 is the
magic number.''
</P>
<P>
   Presidential candidates seek to win the national popular vote
but under the Constitution, American presidential elections are
decided state-by-state, with each candidate's showing in a state
determining whether that candidate wins that state's electoral
votes on a winner-take-all basis. The number of electoral votes is
the total number of congressmen and senators in each state. Bush
continues to lead Gore in nationwide public opinion surveys,
including a Los Angeles Times survey released Monday that showed
likely voters favoring Bush over Gore, 51 percent to 42 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Green Party candidate Ralph Nader drew 4 percent. Reform Party
candidate Pat Buchanan drew 1 percent. The survey had a margin of
error of 3 percent.
</P>
<P>
   An electoral vote count maintained by the political newsletter
Hotline based in Washington, D.C., paints an even brighter picture
for Bush, with statewide polls in 41 states since March giving Bush
the lead in 32 states with 357 electoral votes and Gore the lead in
9 states with 131 electoral votes.
</P>
<P>
   Bush on the campaign trail and Rove in Philadelphia both noted
Bush's early strength in the five states in which the prospective
GOP nominee is carrying out a pre-convention barnstorming tour
toward the convention, including Ohio, West Virginia, Kentucky,
Missouri and Arkansas. `
</P>
<P>
   ``We've seen huge crowds,''' Bush told a rally in Dayton before
traveling to the state capitol in Columbus for an evening rush-hour
rally. ```These are states that Republicans have not done well
lately in but that's going to change come November.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, a Republican has not carried any of the five states
visited by Bush in his pre-convention warm up at least since 1988.
</P>
<P>
   Rove, saying Bush was in ``reasonably good shape'' in states
such as Ohio and Missouri, said that the GOP candidate is even
leading in traditionally Democratic West Virginia. President Ronald
Reagan was the last Republican to carry the state in his
re-election landslide in 1984. Rove asserted that Bush is
positioned to become the first Republican to win the state in an
open presidential election without an incumbent on the ballot since
1928.
</P>
<P>
   ```This is not going to be an election that you could today
characterize as coming down to New Jersey, Pennsylvania, Ohio,
Michigan and Illinois
</P>
<P>
   the traditional battleground states,'' Rove emphasized.
</P>
<P>
   Rove said Bush hoped to cement his electoral edge by targeting
three groups of swing voters:
</P>
<P>
   Suburban men and women who are traditionally some-time
Republicans or unaffiliated independents, who live in slightly
older suburbs.
</P>
<P>
   Roman Catholics, who make up large blocs of voters in each of
the swing states.
</P>
<P>
   Hispanics, who are present in significant numbers in a small
number of battleground states and have weak ties to the Democratic
party and are influential, depending upon turnout.
</P>
<P>
   (Stewart M. Powell and Charles J. Lewis can be reached at
202-298-6920.)
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
