<SLUG> BC-TV-AMERICANHIGH-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
`AMERICAN HIGH' IS TRUE REALITY TV &HT;    w/optional trims
 &HT;    By MIKE McDANIEL 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle &HT;    ``Survivor'' and ``Big Brother,'' it has been argued before, are
<TEXT>
not reality shows. They are game shows produced under controlled
and contrived situations.
<P>
   There's something a bit false about ``The Real World,'' too.
That show features young people (aspiring actors, most of them)
``forced'' to live the good life in luxurious digs for three
months.
</P>
<P>
   If you want reality, check out ``American High,'' debuting
Wednesday on Fox. It's the closest thing to reality TV we're going
to get, short of hooking us all up with cameras and mikes and
telecasting ourselves 24-7 _ and how deadly dull would that be?
</P>
<P>
   ``American High'' is not dull, but it can be deadly. It is also,
in turns, delightfully and horrifically real.
</P>
<P>
   ``I figured if I was going to do this, I might as well put my
full self into it and totally reveal everything I was thinking,''
Morgan Moss said in a recent interview.
</P>
<P>
   Morgan is one of 12 suburban Chicago high school students who
agreed to be videotaped for the 10-month project. Camera crews
followed them from class to class and also at home, and the
students also shot video themselves.
</P>
<P>
   So what viewers get is a tightly edited collection of moments
from the lives of 12 very real young people. And one of those
moments, courtesy of Morgan in Episode 2, shows Morgan's home life
from his perspective. It's not a pretty picture.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clean your room right now,'' his mother shouts.
</P>
<P>
   His father calls him ``an obnoxious kid'' and ``a lousy
student.''
</P>
<P>
   His little brother shoots him the finger.
</P>
<P>
   And Morgan turns the camera on himself and lashes back. His word
for his parents is an expletive.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't sure what to do and how to get into it,'' Morgan
said. ``I started talking, and I just got into it. Once I was able
to say what was on my mind, I didn't really feel embarrassed at
all.''
</P>
<P>
   Morgan's father, Alan Moss, was sheepish in his reaction to his
son's video outburst.
</P>
<P>
   ``We figured that this was going to be something that was going
to be very special for Morgan,'' the elder Moss said. ``We were
just going to be ourselves, and what falls out is going to fall
out.''
</P>
<P>
   But having seen what his son has shot, ``We sit there and shake
our heads. It's sort of in for a penny, in for a pound.''
</P>
<P>
   The brainchild for this nonfiction drama is Oscar-nominated
filmmaker R.J. Cutler (``The War Room'' and ``A Perfect
Candidate''). It was his idea to show what life for a group of high
school students was really like, to collect stories and somehow
make a drama series out of them. He chose Highland Park High School
outside of Chicago because ``we wanted a suburban school'' and ``I
knew people there.''
</P>
<P>
   ``At the beginning of (the last) school year, we invited all the
seniors interested in participating, and their families, to come to
an assembly,'' Cutler said. ``We explained what we were doing and
why.''
</P>
<P>
   One of Cutler's producers taught a course in documentary
filmmaking, which the participating students took. Ground rules
included a pledge that no one would be filmed without his or her
permission and that rough cuts would be available to participants
and their families before they were aired.
</P>
<P>
   (As a kind of payment to the school, producers ``left behind a
bunch of video equipment,'' Cutler said.)
</P>
<P>
   More than 1,000 students applied to be part of the project, a
number whittled down to 25, then 12. The project resulted in 2,800
hours of film, which is being edited into 13 half-hours for showing
on Fox. The first two episodes run at 8 and 8:30 p.m. Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The emphasis is on real, and the students appear to have no
qualms in revealing what's inside their heads. That makes the
project illuminating and troubling at the same time.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you watch the show, it's kind of like, whoa, my life,''
said Sarah Mages, the only junior of the bunch. (The others are
seniors who are entering college this fall.) ``All the things we
say are obviously true because we said it, but it's like a shock to
watch your life on TV.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not embarrassed of my feelings. I think one of the
greatest parts about the show is we're all honest with our
feelings.''
</P>
<P>
   Sarah's life vividly contrasts with Morgan's. She lives a quiet,
introverted life.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that's one of the coolest parts of the show,'' she
said. ``I hope there are other kids going through the same kind of
issues I'm going through, who'll look at me and say, `Wow, you
know, she's OK.' Like, even though she's lonely, she lives her
life.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Sarah's is not completely lonely. There's a romance between her
and another teen participating in the video project, Robby Nathan.
</P>
<P>
   Robby, like Morgan, has no problem opening up in front of a
camera.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it was because I was so (mad) at school and adults and
... people that just don't understand kids, yet are bossing us
around and telling us what to do,'' he said. ``That's why I opened
up, because I want things to change. I want them to realize that we
might be 17 or 18, but we've got a lot going on in our head _ more
so than anyone thinks, you know?''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (END OPTIONAL TRIM) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Other participants include Brad, Robby's best friend, who is
openly gay; Mike, a football star; Anna, who's got a crush on Mike;
Allie, whose home life includes a father with a pregnant mistress;
Tiffany, an African-American at the mostly white school; Suzie, a
self-described opera diva; Salima, Brad's confidante; Pablo, a poet
with a wild party streak; and Kaytee, writer of funny love songs.
</P>
<P>
   Drug issues come up in Episode 5. The topic of sex is also
discussed. Robby, for example, talks about how Brad broke the news
to him that he is gay.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you look in someone's eyes, when they've told you a
secret that's been hidden for 17 years _ it was just this total
solitude and loneliness,'' Robby said. ``When I looked in Brad's
eyes, it was the kind of look _ like feelings that were in his eyes
_ that no one should ever have to feel.''
</P>
<P>
   The students found the video experiment a rewarding experience.
What about the parents?
</P>
<P>
   In the first episodes, ``Morgan sets his credo,'' said Alan
Moss. ``I don't think we (he and wife Mary) were at all surprised
by it. I mean, you got to remember, it's 18 years of living on this
roller coaster with him.''
</P>
<P>
   The videos validated the parents' feelings about their son.
</P>
<P>
   ``We could look at each other, kind of nod and say, `Yeah, I
suspected that was in there,' or `I knew that was going to come out
at some point.'
</P>
<P>
   ``Basically, this thing was a wonderful thing for Morgan because
my contention has always been, `If we can just get this kid to
survive high school, he's going to become who he needs to be.' And
high school is something that needs to be survived.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody doesn't work the way Ozzie and Harriet used to work.
I've seen five episodes now, and I'm incredibly pleased to see how
honest he was. Some of it's disturbing, but I don't think there's
much he could do that would surprise us, in terms of doing
something totally off the edge. Because he's been pushing the
envelope since he was in day care.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (END OPTIONAL TRIM) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   XXX END OF STORY
</P>
