<HEADER>
A8604 &Cx1f; taf-z
s t BC-TRAVEL-OLY-SYDNEY-ART     07-31 1323
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-OLY-SYDNEY-ARTS-$ADV06-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AUSTRALIA'S OLYMPIAN PURSUIT OF THE ARTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, August 6)  
 By SUSAN GOUGH HENLY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Australia has well-deserved credentials as one of the great
sporting nations of the world, but its reputation in the arts is a
more recent phenomenon. For visitors to the Olympic Games, the
Sydney Olympic Arts Festival, with its roster of dance, music, art,
theater and film, offers an enticing bonus, a way to appreciate the
rich and diverse culture of this antipodean nation and place
Australia's artistic achievements in an international context. The
six-week-long festival actually starts a full month before the
Games commence, to set the stage and to showcase the full scope of
arts offerings.
</P>
<P>
   At daybreak on Aug. 18 on Congwong Bay in La Perouse, southeast
of the city, the dawn call of the Eora people _ the Aboriginal
tribe of the Sydney area _ begins a day of welcoming the world to
the festival. The Aboriginal opera singer and actor Deborah
Cheetham will join other female singers in arias accompanied by
local musicians playing traditional instruments. These ceremonies,
entitled ``Tubowgule'' (pronounced TIE-bah-gool), meaning ``The
Meeting of the Waters,'' continue at noon in the Royal Botanic
Gardens with traditional male dancing, body painting and story
telling, all of which pay respect to ancestral traditions.
</P>
<P>
   As dusk falls, the forecourt of the Sydney Opera House is the
setting for the climax of the welcoming ceremony, choreographed by
Stephen Page, artistic director of Australia's leading indigenous
performing arts group, the Bangarra Dance Theatre. Dancers and
children will be accompanied by Marc Newson's dramatic lighting of
the opera house in aqueous patterns.
</P>
<P>
   This is one episode of his four-part ``subliminal lighting''
installation, ``Energy of Australia,'' which will transform the
Opera House every night during the Festival. In this first
installation, the desired effect is that the 21st century will seem
to disappear into the earliest times of Australia's first
inhabitants. All three of the ``Tubowgule'' events are free.
</P>
<P>
   This sense of drama and spectacle permeates the festival,
according to Leo Schofield, the festival's director. ``I felt that
it was important to mount events of scale since the Olympic Games
are the most important international festival of all,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, the first musical event, on Aug. 19, is Mahler's Symphony
No. 8, the Symphony of a Thousand, at the SuperDome in the heart of
the Olympic Park. ``I see this symphony as the invocation of the
creative spirit and, as such, I hope it will be a cultural
highlight,'' Schofield said.
</P>
<P>
   Edo de Waart conducts the Sydney Symphony Orchestra, which will
be joined by an international roster of soloists, including
Alessandra Marc, Elizabeth Connell, Jane Henschel, Vinson Cole and
massed choirs from Sydney, Melbourne, Canberra and Britain. ``It is
a little quirky, too, staging a classical symphony in a sports
stadium, but it is important to make the link between sport and art
and to emphasize that the arts festival is part of the action, not
elitist and separate,'' Schofield added.
</P>
<P>
   Olympic arts festivals were enshrined in the modern Olympic
Games ethos by Baron Pierre de Coubertin, who revived the Games in
the late 19th century. ``Olympism,'' Coubertin said, ``is the
concept of strong physical culture, based in one part upon the
spirit of chivalry and, for the other, upon aesthetic
sensitivity.'' Thus in both the ancient and early modern Olympic
Games a country might win gold not only for discus throwing but
also for poetry.
</P>
<P>
   While this sentiment appears a little naive in our high-stakes
sports world and while it would be politically imprudent to find
judges for artistic events today, Sydney's full-scale Olympic Arts
Festival is a salute to the baron's aims. On the eve of the opening
ceremony of the competition, Sept. 14, the festival and the games
will be united in the Olympic Torch Galas at the Sydney Opera
House. The ballet superstar Sylvie Guillem will appear with stars
of Opera Australia and the Australian Ballet at the Opera Theater,
while the tenor Andrea Bocelli will perform at the Concert Theater.
</P>
<P>
   The Olympic torch will arrive at the opera house en route to the
Olympic Stadium, and as the torchbearer runs up the steps, the
opera house itself will appear to burst into flames in another of
Newson's installations.
</P>
<P>
   So what are the festival's themes? ``I wanted to emphasize the
celebratory nature of this international event,'' Schofield said.
``And considering the fact that many visitors are not English
speaking, I placed a strong focus on dance and music. There is also
a highlight on youth at the dawning of a new century.''
</P>
<P>
   About 70 percent of the performing and visual arts events are
Australian, with some remarkable indigenous Australian work. These
are benchmarked against a diverse array of international talent.
Here are some highlights:
</P>
<P>
   DANCE
</P>
<P>
   There is an embarrassment of riches in the dance offerings, from
Pina Bausch and her Tanztheater Wuppertal's ``Masurca Fogo,'' from
Aug. 30 to Sept. 3 at the Capitol Theater, to Graeme Murphy's epic
``Mythologia,'' performed by the Sydney Dance Company and the
60-member Sydney Gay and Lesbian Choir from Aug. 19 to 26, also at
the Capitol. Lin Hwai-Min's Cloud Gate Dance Theater performs
``Nine Songs'' (which begins with the image of a magical
water-filled lotus pond and ends with 800 candles leading into a
star-filled night sky) Aug. 19 to 22, and the tai-chi-based ``Moon
Water,'' Aug. 25 to 27 at Her Majesty's Theater, danced to Bach's
Six Suites for Solo Cello.
</P>
<P>
   The Bangarra Dance Theatre performs ``Skin,'' a new work in two
parts by Stephen Page. ``Shelter'' is inspired by the cultural
world of the women of Utopia, in Australia's Central Desert region,
highlighted by the art of Emily Kngwarreye.
</P>
<P>
   ``Spear'' is a collaboration with the Aboriginal
singer-songwriter Archie Roach and forges a new urban identity for
Aboriginal men, from Sept. 19 to 30 at the Sydney Opera House Drama
Theater. The New York choreographer Bill T. Jones uses an
astonishing range of music in his latest work, ``You, Walk,'' to
explore the blending of different cultures Aug. 31 to Sept. 4 at
Her Majesty's Theater.
</P>
<P>
   MUSIC AND OPERA
</P>
<P>
   The violinist Maxim Vengerov performs Tchaikovsky's Violin
Concerto with the Sydney Symphony Orchestra Sept. 29 and 30 at the
Sydney Opera House Concert Hall. The orchestra will also be
performing Wagner's ``Goeterdammerung'' in concert Sept. 5 and 8 at
the Concert Hall.
</P>
<P>
   Simone Young, the only woman to have conducted the Paris Opera,
will conduct Opera Australia in a new production of Verdi's ``Simon
Bocca-negra'' on Aug. 30 and eight days in September at the opera
house. Riccardo Muti conducts the Orchestra Filarmonica Della Scala
performing works from an all-Italian repertory Sept. 27 and 28 at
the Opera House Concert Hall.
</P>
<P>
   The Asian Youth Orchestra, representing outstanding young
musicians across the continent, teams up with the Beaux Arts Trio
on Aug. 26, as well as the Chinese-Australian violinist Cho-Liang
Lin on Aug. 25, both at the Opera House Concert Hall. The violinist
Pinchas Zukerman plays Beethoven's Violin Concerto and Bartok's
Concerto for Orchestra with Australia's premier youth orchestra,
the Global Freeway Australian Youth Orchestra on Sept. 1, also at
the Opera House Concert Hall.
</P>
<P>
   The amplified strings of the Australian Chamber Orchestra joins
with New York's Bang on a Can's rock-classical lineup of cello,
bass, keyboards, percussion, electric guitar, saxophone and
clarinet to present new works by the Australian composer Brett Dean
and the British composer Steve Martland. And the German cabaret
singer Ute Lemper also stars in two concerts at the Concert Hall,
on Sept. 17 and 24.
</P>
<P>
   (MORE) nn
</P>
<P>
   THEATER
</P>
<P>
   The British company DV8 Physical Theater straddles the
boundaries of dance and theater and challenges conventional notions
of both. Its Australian-born producer, Lloyd Newton, is creating a
new work for the festival, which will later open in London. The
play, at the Everts Theater, Seymour Theater Center, Aug. 16 to
Sept. 3, explores perfection and pretense, how society measures
individuals and how they, in turn, value themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Neil Armfield directs an Australian cast in Co. B. Belvoir's
adaptation of ``The Marriage of Figaro'' at the Sydney Opera House
Drama Theater, Aug. 19 to Sept. 14. Students of the Australian
National Institute of Dramatic Art present the premier of ``There
Is No Need to Wake Up,'' a hallucinogenic fantasy inspired by
Sigmund Freud, Aug. 31 to Sept. 14 at the Opera House Playhouse.
</P>
<P>
   Gale Edwards directs the Sydney Theater Company in the Jacobean
thriller ``The White Devil'' Aug. 18 to Sept. 13 at the Theater
Royal. Michael Bogdanov directs the Bell Shakespeare Company
(Australia's national Shakespeare company) in a radical
interpretation of Shakespeare's antiwar play ``Troilus and
Cressida,'' Sept. 18 to 30 at the Sydney Opera House Playhouse.
</P>
<P>
   For all of September, the young performers of Australia's
renowned Flying Fruit Fly Circus team up with performers from the
Shanghai Acrobatic Troupe of China under the Big Top in Prince
Albert Park.
</P>
<P>
   VISUAL ARTS
</P>
<P>
   From Aug. 18 to Nov. 12, the Art Gallery of New South Wales is
presenting ``Papunya Tula: Genesis and Genius.'' This landmark
exhibition highlights the key role of the Western Desert art
movement of the 1970's, when Western media like canvas and acrylic
began to be used by indigenous Australian artists.
</P>
<P>
   The gallery is also saluting 20 Australian icons of visual art _
including Tom Roberts, Russell Drysdale and Sidney Nolan _ from
Aug. 4 to Oct. 29, as well as mounting an exhibition of fragments
of the Dead Sea Scrolls through Oct. 15.
</P>
<P>
   The Museum of Contemporary Art will show a retrospective of the
Aboriginal urban artist Lin Onus, this Friday through Oct. 29, and
highlight the work of six international and Australian installation
artists as they explore the intersection of art and sport Aug. 16
to Nov. 13.
</P>
<P>
   At the Powerhouse Museum, Leonardo's masterwork of art and
science ``The Codex Leicester'' is on loan from Bill Gates from
Sept. 6 to Nov. 5. Also on view through Nov. 15 is ``1,000 Years of
the Olympic Games,'' sculptural and ceramic treasures from ancient
Greece.
</P>
<P>
   Through Dec. 3, the Museum of Sydney will offer a major
photographic survey, ``Sydneysiders,'' by Lorrie Graham.
</P>
<P>
   POTPOURRI
</P>
<P>
   In addition to all these events, performances and exhibitions,
there are two more festivals within the Olympic Arts Festival.
</P>
<P>
   Hemispheres, a festival of music from around the globe, Sept. 9
and 10 at Centennial Park, will star more than 40 contemporary,
Latin, world, funk, dance and blues acts performing on two stages
with D.J.s and dancers. Juan de Marcos' Afro-Cuban All Star band is
a highlight.
</P>
<P>
   Sunscreen Sydney, a celebration of cinema from Sept. 1 to 10,
will offer a free program of Australian classic films, which will
be shown in five unusual locations. They include Bruce Beresford's
``Breaker Morant'' at St. Andrew's Square; Fred Schepisi's ``The
Devil's Playground'' at Cathedral Square; George Miller's ``The Man
From Snowy River'' at Hyde Park, and Peter Weir's ``The Cars That
Ate Paris'' on the top floor of the Enacom Car Park, King Street.
</P>
<P>
   Other highlights will include dinner conversations with
Australia's best-known filmmakers, a mainstream international
cinema champions program at Hoyts Paris Cinemas and a free national
short-film competition, at the Fox Studios backlot, Sept. 4 to 10.
For more information, see www.sunscreen.com.au, which is expected
to be running this week.
</P>
</TEXT>
