</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-BROADWAY-DANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ON BROADWAY, WHERE ACTORS GET PHYSICAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (Science Times)   By ALISON HENDRIE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Swinging onstage at Broadway's New Amsterdam Theater,
Christopher Jackson belts out his opening number in the musical
``The Lion King'' while suspended by a rope 25 feet above the
audience.
</P>
<P>
   As Simba, a role for which he is the understudy and will take
over permanently this month, he must convincingly move with the
strength and grace of the lion he portrays.
</P>
<P>
   Down the block at the Martin Beck Theater, Michael Berresse woos
his leading lady in the revival of ``Kiss Me, Kate'' by lithely
scaling a three-story balcony like a kid on a jungle gym.
</P>
<P>
   These days the Broadway musical's modern choreography is far
more rigorous and physical than the song and dance era of Ethel
Merman or Carol Channing.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's much more athletic and aerobic,'' said Kathleen Marshall,
the choreographer. ``You have the phenomenon of people going to the
gym, developing stronger, leaner silhouettes and more muscular
bodies.''
</P>
<P>
   More strength means more opportunities for choreographers to
create challenging routines that highlight a performer's skills.
</P>
<P>
   Knowing Berresse's background as a gymnast and diver, Marshall
crafted the climbing sequence in ``Kiss Me, Kate'' with him in
mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always been very physical and I've developed athletes'
habits,'' Berresse said. ``In truth, Broadway dancers are
professional athletes and they are finally being recognized as
such.''
</P>
<P>
   Choreography may be faster and more hard-hitting because the
world itself is moving faster than ever.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just as records keep getting broken in sports and athletes run
faster and jump higher than they did 30 years ago,'' Marshall said,
``dancers are able to do more, bringing a new level of athleticism
to their work.'' A 1996 Olympic gymnast, Aliane Baquerot, made her
Broadway debut this year as Linda Manero in ``Saturday Night
Fever'' and says a disciplined sports background is a help in this
almost nonstop dance show. ``You find a lot more acrobatics today
instead of just traditional musical theater-type dance,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Manny Kladitis, a producer who has been involved with the
theater since 1965 and is producing ``Saturday Night Fever,''
traces the trend toward more physical theater to the resurgence of
dance itself.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dance and exercise bring on this rush that gets the audience
going, the kind of physical and sexual energy you might get when
you're exercising yourself,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Such brawny Broadway performances are not limited to dance,
however, as evidenced by the strenuous climbing and mock fighting
in the rock opera revival of ``Jesus Christ Superstar.'' Trained as
a dancer with the Alvin Ailey Repertory Ensemble, Lana Gordon,
portraying dual roles as a Disciple and Herod's Girl, tackles her
first nondance role with as much vigor as anything she has done en
pointe. ``People want to see action,'' she said, describing a scene
in which she hoists herself up a steep scaffold in one of the big
numbers. ``They don't want to see you just standing around.''
</P>
<P>
   Preparing for the new demands requires more than the traditional
voice and dance lessons and while most troupers get an ample
aerobic workout eight times each week, strength training,
stretching, yoga and even meditation play crucial roles. As a
former fitness trainer, Jackson knows his way around a gym and
trains a minimum of five times a week. ``It's a matter of survival
to stay in tip-top shape,'' he said, recalling a knee injury that
set him back three months. ``I train like an athlete because I
perform like one.''
</P>
<P>
   As Tommy Djilas in ``The Music Man,'' Clyde Alves, recipient of
this year's Fred Astaire Award for Outstanding Dance on Broadway,
reaches into his own sports history as a wrestler and gymnast and
soccer and hockey player to leap through his performance, capped by
a particularly memorable spread-eagle jump over a young cast
member. ``It takes more discipline to warm up and keep in shape
than before,'' said Alves, whose warm-up includes push-ups, sit-ups
and meditation.
</P>
<P>
   Gordon finds yoga offers a good balance between mind and body,
not to mention a tremendous vocal warm-up. She takes a class every
day. Pilates, the discipline of controlled stretching and toning
exercises beloved by dancers, keeps a large proportion of
performers limber and strong for the rigors of the theater.
</P>
<P>
   The line between performance and pumping iron continues to blur
with the proliferation of Broadway-based aerobic classes cropping
up in gyms across the country. Cast members from ``Chicago,''
``Swing,'' ``Contact'' and ``Saturday Night Fever'' have all taught
health club patrons choreography from the shows in Broadway dance
series at fitness clubs.
</P>
<P>
   As he prepares to take over the lead in ``The Lion King,''
Jackson figures he'll need to put on 5 to 10 pounds over the next
two months because of the show's intensity. ``It's not unusual for
me to drop a couple of pounds in just one show,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
