<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-POLITIS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ISRAELI POLITICAL SCENE HEATS UP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHARLES M. SENNOTT  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ The worst heat wave in the history of the country
was nothing compared to the rising political temperature in
Israel's parliament Monday.
</P>
<P>
   First, there was the stunning upset in the vote for president,
in which Iranian-born Moshe Katsav, a little known Likud lawmaker,
triumphed over Nobel Prize laureate and former Labor prime minister
Shimon Peres.
</P>
<P>
   Then, as the mercury climbed to around 107 degrees outside,
conservative and religious parties in the air-conditioned halls of
the Knesset tried to ride the momentum from Katsav's victory and
drive Prime Minister Ehud Barak from office.
</P>
<P>
   But once again, Barak survived the ``no confidence'' vote, which
would have forced early elections.
</P>
<P>
   In so doing, he bought time to build support for his efforts to
reach a comprehensive peace agreement that would end 52 years of
conflict with the Palestinians. But the vote for Katsav sent a
clear message that the going would be tough.
</P>
<P>
   By the end of the day, with weather forecasters promising some
relief in sight, Israel watched the sun go down on the political
career of Peres.
</P>
<P>
   The last of the Labor party's icons, Peres, 76, was handpicked
to lead by Israel's founding father David Ben Gurion and was an
architect of the historic 1994 Israeli-Palestinian peace agreement
in Oslo, Norway.
</P>
<P>
   Barak had put his support behind Peres for president, hoping he
would help him shore up national courage to clinch a peace deal.
</P>
<P>
   The vote for president became a referendum on Barak's peace
moves with the Palestinians at Camp David, and Katsav's victory
made it glaringly apparent that Barak must now now face an all-out
campaign by the conservative and religious parties who feel he
compromised too much by offering to share sovereignty in Jerusalem,
and by ceding too much land in the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
   As Likud leader and legendary hawk Ariel Sharon told Israel
Radio just moments after Katsav's election to the largely
ceremonial post, ``This is a very important victory, a sign that
the people of Israel do not want the policy of Barak.''
</P>
<P>
   Labor and peace camp leaders, however, saw the vote _ Katsav won
by a margin of 63-57 in the 120-member Knesset _ as a betrayal of
what they say is a majority of Israeli citizens who want peace.
</P>
<P>
   At the Yakovi Brothers Appliances store on Emek Refaim Street,
one of Jerusalem's more upscale shopping boulevards, fans and air
conditioners were selling as fast as the owner, Samson Yakovi, 50,
could get deliveries from a warehouse. People were lined up 10 deep
at his store, buying anything that could proximate a breeze.
</P>
<P>
   Yakovi was a bit distracted watching the voting in the Knesset
on a television set up outside his store. He was the only one
watching since just about everyone else in Israel believed Peres
was a sure bet to win. But then Yakovi let out a cheer that broke
the languid atmosphere of the heat.
</P>
<P>
   ``My friend! Yes! Goodbye Peres!'' Yakovi yelled at the
television.
</P>
<P>
   His reaction to Katsav's victory says a lot about Israel today.
</P>
<P>
   Katsav, like Yakovi, is part of the ``second Israel,'' the wave
of Jewish immigrants from Arab and Islamic countries who arrived in
the early years of the state and formed a struggling underclass
that felt abandoned by the likes of Peres and his Labor party. This
voting bloc has become the backbone of the Likud. Katsav, 55, was
born in Iran and hails from humble roots. His family was assigned
to live in the ramshackle ``transit camps'' set up for new
immigrants after the 1948 war. He came of age in Kiryat Malachi,
one of Israel's development towns, where immigrants have struggled
with unemployment and government neglect.
</P>
<P>
   Yakovi, who was born just two weeks after his parents came to
Israel from Iran in 1950, also lived in a transit camp, which he
says has a lot to do with why he has loved Katsav since the young
mayor of Kiryat Malachi was elected to parliament in 1977.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know, maybe there is a new job for Peres,'' said Yakovi,
unable to contain his laughter watching the voting results on
television and working the cash register at the same time. ``Maybe
he could become the president for the Palestinians.''
</P>
<P>
   Batia Labovich, 26, waiting to drop off a fan that needed
repair, couldn't contain herself and shot back at Yakovi, ``This
vote doesn't have anything to do with what people want in this
country. People want peace. Peres is educated, he is respected. And
now we have Katsav. No one knows who Katsav is, and no one cares.''
</P>
<P>
   Labovich, who is a math teacher and a member of the group Peace
Now, is far more reflective of the population that lives within the
wealthy enclave that straddle the shops and cafes of Emek Refaim.
The verbal clash between the store owner and the peace activist
with a broken fan says everything about the heated battle that is
just beginning in Israel, a country facing a fateful crossroads in
a long journey toward peace.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
