<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOP-PROFILES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MONDAY'S SPEAKERS AT THE GOP CONVENTION 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Among the speakers on Monday evening's program:
</P>
<P>
   Condoleezza Rice
</P>
<P>
   Bush foreign policy adviser
</P>
<P>
   Condoleezza Rice is quarterback of Gov. George W. Bush's foreign
policy team, whose members have named themselves the ``Vulcans.'' A
statue of Vulcan, the god of metalworking in Roman mythology,
overlooks Rice's hometown of Birmingham, Ala. Of the foreign policy
team, Rice is the closest to Bush. He has said that he feels
comfortable asking her the most basic questions. An only child
raised in segregated Birmingham, Rice, 45, joined the faculty of
Stanford University in 1981, before becoming its youngest, first
female and first nonwhite provost.
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth Dole
</P>
<P>
   Former president of the American Red Cross
</P>
<P>
   A thirst for politics and a knack for leadership have made
Elizabeth Dole probably the most recognizable woman in the
Republican Party. Her appearance at the 1996 convention when she
introduced her husband, Bob Dole, was widely praised. She placed
second to Gov. George W. Bush in many national polls before
dropping out of the presidential race last year, and there had been
speculation that Bush had considered her as a vice presidential
contender. A native of Salisbury, N.C., she graduated from Duke
University with a degree in political science in 1958 and received
a law degree from Harvard in 1965. After marrying Sen. Bob Dole, a
Republican from Kansas in 1975, she worked for two Republican
presidents. In 1995, she left her job as president of the American
Red Cross to be at her husband's side during his presidential
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   John McCain
</P>
<P>
   Republican senator from Arizona
</P>
<P>
   John McCain is one of the Senate's most respected members.
Starting as a marginal candidate for president in 1999, McCain
emerged as a threat to Gov. George W. Bush in the primaries,
attracting independents and Democrats. Before dropping out in
March, he won primaries in New Hampshire and Michigan. McCain, 63,
was born in the Panama Canal Zone, the son of a naval officer. He
graduated from the U.S. Naval Academy in 1958 and was a pilot
during the Vietnam War. In 1967, his plane was shot down over North
Vietnam and he spent five and a half years as a prisoner of war.
After retiring from the Navy, McCain moved to Arizona, and was
elected to Congress in 1982. He won the first of his three terms in
the Senate in 1986.
</P>
<P>
   Patricia Funderburk Ware
</P>
<P>
   Family Advocate
</P>
<P>
   Having raised a daughter on her own, Patricia Funderburk Ware
knows the difficulties and hardships of being a single parent.
Living in Raleigh, N.C., she saw lifestyles that led to teen-age
pregnancy and the spread of sexually transmitted diseases _ issues,
she has said, that are particularly epidemic in black communities.
These concerns are the focus of her work as president of the
Preserving Family Well-Being Foundation, an organization that
addresses the problems facing black families.
</P>
<P>
   Theodore Roosevelt 4th
</P>
<P>
   Environmental Activist
</P>
<P>
   The great-grandson of the 26th president, is an investment
banker and an environmental activist. Roosevelt, a managing
director at Lehman Bros. and resident of Brooklyn, was appointed by
Gov. George Pataki of New York to be a board member of the Hudson
River Trust in March 1999. The trust is responsible for designing,
building and operating the Hudson River Park to stretch along the
waterfront of the West Side of Manhattan from Battery Park City to
59th Street.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
