<SLUG> BC-NEWSSTAND01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Female athletes get Esquire triple-coverage
 &HT;    By Don O'Briant
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The August issue of Esquire ($3) celebrates strength and beauty
with three different covers and a 12-page portfolio of women
athletes who hope to win medals in the Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   Featured on the covers are pentathlete Mary Beth Larsen, high
jumper Amy Acuff and triathlete Lokelani McMichael, who became the
youngest woman to compete in the Ironman at 18.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond the photos are ``Dreams,'' the last unpublished short
story by Raymond Carver, and an interesting piece on Harvard Law
School grads who are leaving the profession in droves. One of the
four profiled is Chris Crain, who left a prestigious Atlanta law
firm to become co-owner of Southern Voice, the city's gay
newspaper. He has since bought gay newspapers in New Orleans and
Houston.
</P>
<P>
   Crain says his parents do not accept his homosexuality and
cannot understand why he would waste a Harvard law degree. He still
wears his ring, however, at times when he feels challenged. ``Not
so anyone can see me,'' he says, ``but in my office with the door
closed. I look at it, and it makes me feel better.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Simple solutions: After changing editors and taking a bashing
in the media, Real Simple ($2.95) continues on its mission to make
our lives less stressful. The August issue profiles three women who
have ``achieved balance'' in a busy world, including Leslie
Marshall, a writer who re-connected with nature on Georgia's
Cumberland Island after her 5-year-old daughter's brush with death
and the loss of her friend, John F. Kennedy Jr. Other articles
include guides to preserving your vacation snapshots, watching the
political conventions, and organizing your lingerie drawer. All
equally exciting.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Queen's court: Anna Kournikova is everywhere, it seems, except
in the winner's circle after a tennis tournament. The teenage star
has never won an official tour event, but here she is posing
seductively on the cover of GQ ($3). The accompanying article by
Adam Sachs is about as skimpy as Kournikova's outfits, revealing
nothing about her private life and very little about her
professional life. So what if she has a weak backhand? She
collected $15 million in endorsements last year. More substantial
reading can be found in Bob Drury's story of Jack ``The Turk''
Hasson, a Palm Beach jeweler who swindled Jack Nicklaus, Greg
Norman and other celebrities out of $80 million with fake
gemstones.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Making the list: If you want to know who's hot and who's not
(at least for this month), check out the September issue of Vibe
($3) for the 100 most influential people, places and things in
urban culture. Others in addition to cover subjects Dr. Dre and
Eminem include Tiger Woods, Oprah Winfrey, Russell Simmons,
Donatella Versace, VH1 Behind the Music and Antonio ``L.A.'' Reid.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Makeover: New editor-in-chief Mandi Norwood makes her debut
with a revamped August issue of Mademoiselle ($2.99). Norwood says
the 65-year-old magazine has a new look and a new target audience _
``women in their twenties, on the hunt for fun and success, with
the time and money to spend on themselves.'' Planet Mademoiselle,
for example, is a section designed to spot trends such as make-out
parties for twentysomethings in Dallas, where young women pucker up
with complete strangers.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Weeklies' watch: First, the trio from the $3.50 club: With the
Republican National Convention under way, both Time and Newsweek
devote covers to most things Bush. Time's ``convention special''
takes a look ``Inside the Bush Dynasty'' including George W.,
brother Jeb and patriarch George. Newsweek tags W. and running mate
Dick Cheney as ``The Avengers'' in its special. The Concorde crash
gets second billing in both. U.S. News &AMP; World Report takes a
different spin: How the 1948 convention _ or TV coverage of that
other Philly gathering _ ``changed politics forever.'' ... For
$2.99 each, you can learn why Harrison Ford is ``At Home on the
Range'' in a soft, summer issue of People while in Entertainment
Weekly, the cult phenom Phish gets a 10-page spread. EW also
borrows from TV Guide's marketing department by offering four
different covers showcasing band members. ... And finally in Sports
Illustrated ($3.99), a special double issue showcases a ``Where Are
They Now?'' update. On the cover: former Chicago Bear William
``Refrigerator'' Perry, who's now a ``brick-layin,' bass-hookin'
picture of contentment'' in Aiken, S.C.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Pound for pound: Shape ($2.99) expands to a special double
issue in a bid to help readers fight the battle of the bulge.
Included: ``The Anti-Cellulite Workout,'' which concludes a mix of
cardio, resistance and flexibility training will help. Also this
month: Christy Turlington's tips on yoga beauty. ... YM (Young &AMP;
Modern, $2.99) also takes on pounds with a story on, ``Is Stress
Making You Fat?'' Also in this issue: ``Eating Right'' looks at
healthy eating, including poor picks and better bets at the school
cafeteria.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  E-mail: dobriant(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Don O'Briant writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
