<SLUG> BC-MARKET-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARKET RIDES TECHNOLOGY WAVE UP 
</HEADLINE>
   By KENNETH N. GILPIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Stock prices moved higher Monday, led by bellwether
technology issues, which took a beating for most of last week.
</P>
<P>
   ``The technology and telecommunications market was oversold,''
said Jonathan Olesky, head of block trading at Morgan Stanley Dean
Witter.
</P>
<P>
   The Nasdaq composite index rose 103.99 points, or 2.8 percent,
to 3,766.99, with Intel, Cisco Systems and Oracle increasing. The
gain, the first in four sessions, reversed a bit of last week's 11
percent slide in the Nasdaq index. For the month, the Nasdaq fell 5
percent. So far this year, it is down 7.4 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, strong performances from financial stocks like
Citigroup pulled the Dow Jones industrial average up by 10.81
points, or 0.1 percent, to 10,521.98. Consumer stocks like Wal-Mart
and Procter &AMP; Gamble fell, limiting the rise in the Dow.
</P>
<P>
   The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index gained 10.94 points, or
0.8 percent, to 1,430.83.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the gains, analysts and traders said major market
averages were likely to remain with a small range for most of this
week, and possibly the balance of the summer.
</P>
<P>
   Specifically, they said that economic reports due out Friday,
especially employment data for July, would be key determinants of
how stocks performed between now and Labor Day.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything up to Friday is pretty much noise,'' said Bob
Gasser, head of U.S. equity trading at J.P. Morgan &AMP; Co.
</P>
<P>
   ``But Friday is critical. That data released then has the
ability to swing consensus about what the Federal Reserve Board
will do at the end of the month in one direction, or the other.''
</P>
<P>
   Fed policymakers are scheduled to meet on Aug. 22 to determine
if short-term interest rates need to be pushed higher. Last month
Alan Greenspan, the Fed chairman, told lawmakers economic data to
be released over the course of the next few weeks would determine
the course selected by the central bank.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to have conviction in a market like this,'' said
Philip S. Dow, a managing director in equity research at Dain
Rauscher Wessels in Minneapolis. ``Today feels good, but what will
tomorrow bring? My guess is it will be a difficult environment at
least through Labor Day.''
</P>
<P>
   Among individual stocks, Cisco Systems, which fell nearly 8
percent last week, gained 2 5/8 Monday, to 65 7/16. Intel, which
saw its market value decline by 6.6 percent last week, rose 2 3/16,
to 66 3/4. The price reflects a 2-for-1 stock split that was
effective Monday.
</P>
</TEXT>
