<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-GENERALS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIRING OF GENERALS MAY INDICATE MILITARY SHAKEUP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BRIAN WHITMORE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ President Vladimir V. Putin fired six generals Monday
in a move some said tightened his grip on Russia's military and
indicated that a wider shakeup could be coming.
</P>
<P>
   The generals were fired amid a bitter public feud between
Russia's top two military commanders, Defense Minister Igor
Sergeyev and Armed Forces Chief of Staff Anatoly Kvashnin.
</P>
<P>
   Media reports suggested that the dismissals signaled Putin was
considering removing Sergeyev from office as well. But military
analysts, noting that the generals were far removed from the top
command, called the sackings routine. Putin, they said, simply
wanted to appoint his own people to their posts.
</P>
<P>
   Over the past several weeks, Sergeyev and Kvashnin have argued
publicly over the role of Russia's nuclear forces in the nation's
defense strategy. Kvashnin has suggested that nuclear weapons be
downgraded in favor of developing the country's conventional arms.
Sergeyev, a veteran of Russia's nuclear rocket forces, called
Kvashnin's idea ``insane.''
</P>
<P>
   Military analysts have said the dispute is likely to end in the
ouster of one or the other of Russia's top two commanders. Putin
ordered the two men to jointly submit a reorganization plan for the
military, and the dispute appeared to settle down.
</P>
<P>
   But some media took the firings as a sign that Sergeyev may be
on the way out. Tuesday's edition of the newspaper Izvestia
speculated that Kvashnin was the winner.
</P>
<P>
   ``The commander-in-chief has chosen Anatoly Kvashnin,'' Reuters
quoted an early edition of the newspaper as saying.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now the defense minister must either demand from the Kremlin
an explanation of the mass dismissals of his subordinates, or
accept the challenge hurled at him and prepare for a quick
resignation,'' the paper wrote. ``The next few days will show
whether Vladimir Putin will hand over the Defense Ministry to his
favorite.''
</P>
<P>
   But Pavel Felgenhauer, a Moscow-based defense analyst, said that
while tensions in the military certainly were high over the
Sergeyev-Kvashnin battle, the firings were less important than
suggested.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are second- and third-tier generals. They are not
strategic decision makers,'' Felgenhauer said. ``These firings are
not very consequential in the battle between Kvashnin and
Sergeyev.''
</P>
<P>
   News agencies here reported that all six generals served under
Sergeyev in the Defense Ministry bureaucracy, rather than under
Kvashnin in the General Staff.
</P>
<P>
   But Felgenhauer and others noted that one of the officers
dismissed, General Anatoly Sitnov, recently criticized the
government for allowing Russia's conventional weapons to
deteriorate, a position closer to Kvashnin's than Sergeyev's. The
RTR state television network quoted Sitnov as saying that Russia's
conventional forces will fall hopelessly behind other armies within
10 years.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to Sitnov, who was Russia's defense procurement
chief, the other sacked generals were: Stanislav Petrov, the head
of radioactive, biological and chemical defense; Boris Dukhov, head
of antiaircraft forces; Nikolai Karaulov, the artillery and rockets
chief; Alexander Zobnin, head of funding and trade; and press
service head Anatoly Shatalov.
</P>
<P>
   Two of the generals had passed retirement age while four others,
including Sitnov, were promised new jobs in the military, RTR
television reported.
</P>
<P>
   The six all held their positions on an acting basis and had
routinely offered their resignations when Putin was inaugurated as
president in May, NTV television reported.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
