<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-31 18:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8620 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a BC-POL-TICKER0801-COX     07-31 2026
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POL-TICKER0801-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    GOP convention off to a start
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Republicans opened their convention Monday, beginning what party
leaders hope will be a highly scripted four-day celebration for
their presidential nominee, Gov. George W. Bush. The first real
business of the convention came when the delegates approved by
voice vote a platform that reaffirms the party's staunch position
opposing abortion while adopting Bush's ``compassionate
conservative'' positions on issues like education and immigration.
Bush has sought to prevent any issues from flaring into controversy
at this convention by keeping tight-fisted control of the
proceedings, including requiring speakers to follow pre-approved,
scripted themes.
</P>
<P>
   Party tries a makeover....
</P>
<P>
   It's easy to forget the Republicans have controlled Congress for
the past six years from watching the convention on television this
week. Remarkably, very few GOP members of Congress have been asked
to speak. Instead, the featured speakers include a wide variety of
unelected Americans: teachers, war heroes, small business owners, a
former welfare recipient, a senior citizen, a former Democrat,
entertainers and a professional wrestler. These speakers were
chosen, according to GOP officials, to present the country with
``the new face of the Republican Party.'' When asked why so few
congressional Republicans are speaking, Rep. Tom Davis (R-Va.),
chairman of the Republican Congressional Campaign Committee, said:
``This convention is about nominating George W. Bush to be
president; this convention is not about electing Republican members
of Congress.''
</P>
<P>
   ....but numbers never lie
</P>
<P>
   The Republican National Convention delegates are mostly white,
middle-aged, college-educated, married males, according to an
Associated Press survey in which 89% of the delegates participated.
They range in age from 19 to 97. Many are politicians or lawyers.
About 83 percent are white and 71 percent have a college degree.
''They are the cream of the crop of the people who run the party,''
said Larry Sabato, a University of Virginia politics professor.
''The delegation is not a mirror of America; it's a mirror of the
elite in America,'' he said. The Democratic Party requires each
state delegation to have equal numbers of men and women and to set
aside slots for minorities.
</P>
<P>
   Powell to stress diversity, education in speech
</P>
<P>
   The former Chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff Gen. Colin
Powell heard catcalls at the 1996 Republican National Convention
when he pledged his support for abortion rights and affirmative
action. Delegates said he will be embraced this time, as George W.
Bush tries to reshape the party's image. Powell, who speaks
tonight, plans to tell delegates that education is the nation's
highest priority and will reaffirm his support of affirmative
action. Supporters say Powell's appearance before Republican
delegates who are 83 percent white will help Bush appeal to
moderate voters in battleground states.
</P>
<P>
   Laura Bush's time to shine
</P>
<P>
   Admitting a little nervousness, the wife of Gov. George W. Bush
said she hopes to give some insights into her husband in a speech
welcoming delegates to the Republican convention. ``I think I have
an opportunity to say things about George that other people don't
know about him or can't tell about him,'' Laura Bush said on NBC's
Today show. A former librarian and schoolteacher, Mrs. Bush said
she also will focus her remarks on education and literacy. Later
this week, Mrs. Bush will be feted at a luncheon by the Federation
of American Women where, in a twist, the Texas governor will be one
of the featured speakers on behalf of his wife.
</P>
<P>
   Conventions sees its first arrests
</P>
<P>
   Police dragged eight non-violent demonstrators onto a bus today
after the protesters blocked traffic during the morning rush hour,
marking the first arrests related to the Republican National
Convention. The disruptions occurred as several groups of
protesters hit the streets at midday as delegates prepared to
attend their first session of the convention at the First Union
Center in South Philadelphia. The arrested demonstrators were
denouncing the Army's School of the Americas at Fort Benning, Ga.
Critics have blamed the school for human rights abuses in Central
American countries.
</P>
<P>
   Gore ponders vice presidential pick
</P>
<P>
   While the Republicans have their big show in Philadelphia, Vice
President Al Gore is moving toward announcing his own running mate.
Eight days before Gore says he'll announce his choice, aides are
still saying only that he's considering a ``diverse list'' of fewer
than 10 people and hoping his choice takes a bit of the shine from
Bush's convention in the week before the Democrats gather in Los
Angeles. Massachusetts Sen. John Kerry, Florida Sen. Bob Graham and
former Senate leader George Mitchell are often mentioned as still
in the running. But ``only Al Gore and Warren Christopher know who
is on that short list,'' said spokesman Chris Lehane, referring to
the former secretary of state who is helping Gore with the
selection process.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans playing nice....
</P>
<P>
   Democrats probing for weaknesses to exploit at the Republican
National Convention are frustrated by the lack of dissension,
missteps and red-meat rhetoric they had hoped would undermine the
GOP. With Republicans stubbornly refusing to squabble among
themselves _ over abortion, their platform or George W. Bush's
selection of Dick Cheney as his running mate _ Democrats have been
reduced to implying that Arizona Sen. John McCain still harbors
some lingering animosity toward Bush, and trying to liken Cheney's
choice to George Bush Sr.'s pick of Dan Quayle as vice president in
1988. Still, Democrats acknowledge it is tough to demonize
Republicans who are bending over backward to appear nice. ``The
(Republicans) have put all their hard-liners up in the attic like
an uncle that you only let downstairs for Thanksgiving dinner
because he causes a scene every year,'' said Deomcratic strategist
Bill Carrick. ``I don't know that we're going to see a big bump out
of this, particularly if the Republican message is going to be:
'We're going to be nicer than the Democrats.' ``
</P>
<P>
   .. .Democrats crashing party
</P>
<P>
   Democrats are determined not to let the Republicans' big show go
off without stealing a bit of the spotlight. This week, the
Democrats will drive around town in a black bus emblazoned with the
words, ``Pictured here are all the working people George W. Bush
will fight for'' - and a photo of bare Texas scrubland. A daily
spin conferences will feature guests including Sen. Tom Harkin of
Iowa, and Sen. Patrick Leahy of Vermont. And a ``I Know What You
Did in Texas'' Web site will use eerie graphics to criticize Bush's
``scary record.''
</P>
<P>
   Dick, Lynne and now Mary
</P>
<P>
   The gay rights battle appears poised to enter the
</P>
<P>
   presidential campaign in an unlikely way. Republican vice
presidential nominee Dick Cheney has a lesbian daughter, and
friends report she has already put off grad school to play an
active role on the campaign trail. Until May, Mary Cheney, 31, was
the lesbian/gay corporate relations manager for the
once-notoriously anti-gay Coors Brewing Co., where she negotiated
with gay groups to drop their support for a Coors boycott. Many
believe that Cheney, who is fiercely close to her father, will do
the same to a ticket long antagonistic to gay rights. Vice
presidential nominee George W. Bush opposes workplace anti-
discrimination laws, supports a ban on gay adoptions and says he
wouldn't allow gays to serve openly in the military. Dick Cheney
has also had a dubious record on gay rights issues, voting in
Congress against the Hate Crimes Statistics Act of 1988, and being
a vocal opponent of open gay military service.
</P>
<P>
   All on the same page
</P>
<P>
   The GOP is taking steps to guarantee everyone at the Republican
National Convention is on message, including the delegates.
Convention officials are giving all the delegates their very own
copy of George W. Bush's speeches, policy speeches and campaign
fact sheets in the form of a 453-page book entitled, ``Renewing
America's Purpose.'' ``It's our road map of the governor's key
principles and policies,'' said Convention Chairman Andrew Card.
And for the more computer-savvy delegates there is also a CD-ROM
that includes all of Bush's TV campaign ads.
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan a no-show....
</P>
<P>
   For the first time in 32 years, Pat Buchanan is not attending
the Republican National Convention. He plans to head to the beach
in Delaware for ``some writing and thinking'' - maybe even wegation
section is directly in front of the podium where Bush will accept
the party's presidential nomination Thursday. ``Obviously, there is
a very bright spotlight on Texas this year with our governor
running for president, with his vice presidential pick (having)
Texas ties,'' said Robert Black, spokesman for the Texas GOP.
</P>
<P>
   You're not in Kansas anymore
</P>
<P>
   The seats aren't bad ones, two dozen or so paces from the steps
that lead up to the podium at the First Union Center. Still, they
feel distant for the Kansas delegation. Just four years ago in San
Diego, when Bob Dole was the Republican presidential nominee,
delegates for Kansas, his home state, sat up front and stayed at a
luxury hotel in downtown San Diego. This year, the delegation is at
the Airport Marriott. The delegates believe that if Dole had
remained in the Senate, they might be closer to historic sites such
as the Liberty Bell and Independence Hall. ``We're on our own now,
so we have to scratch and claw for everything we get,'' said state
GOP Chairman Mark Parkinson.
</P>
<P>
   Are you ready to rumble??
</P>
<P>
   The increasingly hostile struggle for power in the Reform Party
between the Pat Buchanan forces and the Ross Perot loyalists who
are supporting John Hagelin for the nomination moved past the point
of negotiable resolution at a rump meeting over the weekend with
the executive committee voting to disqualify Buchanan as a
candidate and the Buchanan faction dubbing the process ``illegal.''
The clash has intensified to such a degree that interim party Chair
Gerald Moan said he is beefing up security for the Aug. 10-13
national convention in Long Beach, Calif. He said he has received a
number of ``death threats,'' including a message on his voice mail
last night saying, ``You miserable piece of . . . . I'm going to
get you, don't worry, I'm going to get you in Long Beach.''
</P>
<P>
   Girl power Alabama style
</P>
<P>
   The all-female staff at Alabama's Republican headquarters got
quite a chuckle recently when an agitated caller demanded to speak
to the office's highest-ranking male. That would be an unpaid
intern, a female staffer delighted in telling him. ``The person
you'll need to talk with is a woman named Twinkle,'' she said. The
caller hung up. Of all the organizing teams at this week's
Republican National Convention in Philadelphia, Alabama's alone
lacks a single male. ``Alabama is last in a lot of things,'' said
Lisa Myers, the party's finance director. ``In this, I guess we're
probably first. Besides, we're probably the only state party that
has nail polish remover in our first aid kit.''
</P>
<P>
   Star wars can wait, GOP enjoys the Car Wars
</P>
<P>
   DaimlerChrysler had crabcakes, the Dodge Copperhead and the
Temptations. General Motors favored barbecue, the Batmobile and
Hank Williams Jr. GOP delegates were the beneficiaries of huge
receptions thrown by the major automakers to curry favor with the
GOP's thirsty followers. DaimlerChrysler decorated Philadelphia's
Convention Center to look like a car dealership for its bash
honoring Oklahoma Rep. J.C. Watts. The GM party was heavier on
Southern accents -- barbecue, baked beans, ham sandwiches and
potato chips . ``I'm from Detroit,'' Michigan political operative
Jim Alexander said at the GM party. ``The food is better here but
the music was much better at Chrysler.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Compiled by Saeed Ahmed from staff and news reports.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
