<SLUG> BC-ISABEL-FEATURE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PLAYWRIGHT'S NEW COMEDY MEETS ALL HER EXPECTATIONS
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Eds: Fact box below) 
By EVAN HENERSON 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   cc,78p3 &QL; 
Around the time playwright Lisa Loomer was thinking about starting
a family, she was also developing an idea for a one-woman show. Her
proposed title: ``Why Bring a Child Into This Lousy World?''
</P>
<P>
   Talk about your loaded questions, especially considering the
lengths to which Loomer knew people would go to have a child.
Hormone therapy and frozen eggs, anyone?
</P>
<P>
   ``The issue of reproductive technology was all around me,'' says
Loomer, who lives in Los Angeles. ``It's all so new and it's
opening up so many options for people and it's something society
has never dealt with before. I just thought it was a fascinating
issue of our times.''
</P>
<P>
   For the record, Loomer and her husband, composer Joe Romano, did
become parents of Marcello, now 2 1/2. And before his birth, Loomer
delivered a new play about the trials and tribulations of impending
parenthood. ``Expecting Isabel,'' which opens Wednesday at the Mark
Taper Forum, might have carried the title ``For God's Sake, Please
Let Me Bring a Child Into This Lousy World.''
</P>
<P>
   A comedy with definite satirical overtones, ``Isabel's'' heroes,
a 30-something husband and wife, go through an odyssey of nearly
Homeric proportions in their efforts to have a child. From a
barrage of assisted reproduction techniques through all manner of
support groups and the maze of adoption, Nick and Miranda nearly
destroy themselves and each other. All for a goal that, most of us
think, should be a snap. What could be more simple and more basic
than having a child?
</P>
<P>
   Oh, just about anything, the playwright says.
</P>
<P>
   ``It used to be so simple. It is not simple now. Infertility is
a huge issue right now,'' says Loomer, who also co-wrote the
screenplay for last year's film, ``Girl, Interrupted,'' for which
Angelina Jolie won an Oscar as best supporting actress. ``The play
asks the question, `How do we decide who we can love because we
have all these seeming choices?' I don't really believe that. I
believe there's a lot of illusion of control in our lives.
</P>
<P>
   ``Really, the arc of the female character in the play is she
goes from having the illusion of control in her life to having
faith. It's from control and fear to faith, and in my own journey
of becoming a parent, I found it came down to faith and love.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Expecting Isabel'' is not, Loomer says, a mirror of her own
experiences or necessarily of any one person in her life. An
exhaustive researcher who plowed into issues of women's health in
creating her 1994 play ``The Waiting Room,'' Loomer collected
plenty of stories from people throughout the infertility and
adoption fields _ from doctors, lawyers, support group therapists
and would-be parents. ``People who saw it in Washington, D.C.,
would say 'Aargh! That's my story!' '' Loomer says.
</P>
<P>
   A Taper commission, ``Expecting Isabel'' premiered during the
theater's New Work Festival in 1997 before getting a staging at the
Arena Stage in Washington, D.C., in the fall of 1998, ultimately
capturing the American Theatre Critics Association's Award for best
play. The Taper also produced the world premiere of Loomer's ``The
Waiting Room'' in 1994. In that earlier work, Loomer tackled the
ways in which women historically have tried to enhance their
appearances _ through such practices as foot binding and breast
enhancement.
</P>
<P>
   Like that earlier work, ``Expecting Isabel'' occasionally uses
broad comic strokes to tell its story. Which is appropriate when
you're addressing such matters as rushing a cup of sperm to a test
site and fertilizing the egg from a hamster.
</P>
<P>
   ``The play just treats the topic without a lot of reverence or
melodrama,'' says Julie White, who plays ``Isabel's''
``I-will-have-a-baby-at-any-cost'' heroine, Miranda. ``It tells it
in almost a circuslike way, but at the heart of it is this simple
and kind of sweet story that many people can relate to.''
</P>
<P>
   White says she can understand Miranda's mania, although the
actress personally never went through the perils of infertility
that her character encounters.
</P>
<P>
   ``All this crazy stuff? Yes, I have friends who have done the
crazy stuff, who have used donor eggs and surrogate moms,'' says
White, the mother of a 13-year-old daughter. ``And I know people
who have adopted. In one case, with some friends of mine, it was
like, 'WE GOT YOU A BABY! YOU HAVE TO DRIVE TO SCOTTSDALE RIGHT
NOW!' '' They drove to Scottsdale and, the next thing you know, it
was like, 'Yow!' They had to stay overnight, and they put the baby
in a drawer.''
</P>
<P>
   Her friends, she says, were totally prepared and yet unprepared.
``No matter how you get children _ if you get them the traditional
way, if you adopt or if you go through all the fertility stuff,
it's still freakishly weird to have a child.'' Miranda and Nick
(who will be played by Tony Award winner Anthony Crivello) trade
off as narrators, and both occasionally come close to losing the
audience's sympathy. Their flaws are visible, says White, but
that's what makes them human.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had to figure out Miranda's engine, her real engine of fear
so that she didn't just become a neurotic chick who has a lot of
food issues,'' said White. ``Yuk! Who wants to spend two hours with
that?
</P>
<P>
   ``But it's fun to see people working together and being in love.
I think you root for them even though you see their individual
flaws.''
</P>
<P>
   In conducting her research, Loomer said she heard stories of
couples whose relationships ended over efforts to have a child, and
others who slogged on for 10 years of infertility treatment.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a huge advocate for adoption, and my feeling is that when
people want to become parents for adoption, they will, '' says
Loomer. ``I've heard of some people who have had tragedies along
the way, and some who haven't.''
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, the playwright has her own version of White's
``drive to Scottsdale now!'' story.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a dear friend, and because I knew they wanted to adopt,
I mentioned it to an adoption facilitator,'' says Loomer. ``A baby
was born, and like three weeks later, these people became parents.
It has every variation of a human story.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   What: ``Expecting Isabel.'' &QL; 
Where: Mark Taper Forum, 135 N. Grand Ave., downtown Los Angeles. &QL; 
When: 8 p.m. Tuesday through Saturday, 2:30 p.m. Saturday and
Sunday; 7:30 p.m. Sunday; through Aug. 27. &QL; 
Tickets: $29 to $42. Call (213) 628-2772. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
