<HEADLINE>
CANADA SENDS WARSHIP TO SHADOW ROGUE FREIGHTER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By COLIN NICKERSON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HALIFAX, Nova Scotia _ A Canadian warship surged out of heavy
fog in the North Atlantic Monday in an attempt to force into port a
rogue US-owned freighter that for two weeks has refused to
relinquish a cargo of battle tanks and other combat gear
representing 10 percent of Canada's armored might.
</P>
<P>
   Monday night the HMCS Athabaskan, a Canadian naval frigate, was
shadowing the freighter GTS Katie at a distance of 1,000 yards,
close quarters in the treacherous sea and a clear attempt to
intimidate the merchant ship's captain.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want that vessel to have absolutely no doubt there is a
warship on its stern, with all that entails,'' said Alastair
Mullin, a spokesman for Canada's Defense Ministry. ``We want to
bring a quick resolution to this.''
</P>
<P>
   The belated show of force appeared to be working. The Katie was
steering a course toward Canadian waters, according to the
military. But Canadian officials acknowledged that the ship's
owner, a Maryland-based shipping company, was still refusing to
call an end formally to a strange deep-water standoff making
headlines on both sides of the Atlantic.
</P>
<P>
   Since July 18, the cargo ship Katie has confounded and
embarrassed the Canadian government by refusing to surrender 580
battle tanks, armored personnel carriers, reconaissance vehicles
and large quantities of munitions, as well as a trio of Canadian
soldiers, being shipped home from a peacekeeping operation in the
Serbian province of Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   The ship's owner, Third Ocean Marine Navigation Co. of
Annapolis, Md., effectively took captive a substantial portion of
Canada's military arsenal in an attempt to settle a financial
dispute with a third party, a Canadian shipping firm. None of the
parties involved will discuss details of the dispute, but Canada
was first humiliated and then angered by attempts to make its
military hostage to a fight between businesses.
</P>
<P>
   The Katie has been tracing huge circles in international waters
600 miles east of Halifax as diplomats and lawyers haggled over
fine points of maritime law in Ottawa, Washington, and other
centers. The Katie flies under a flag of convenience, registered in
the tiny Caribbean nation of St. Vincent and the Grenadines, and to
complicate matters even more, the Soviet-built supercargo carrier's
crew is Ukranian.
</P>
<P>
   Until Monday, Canada's military brass had stood helplessly by as
the Katie ignored entreaties to surrender the military gear. But
late Sunday Canadian Aurora reconnaissance planes spied out the
freighter, and Monday the Athabaskan reached the scene.
</P>
<P>
   Monday night, the Katie was steaming toward the Gulf of St.
Lawrence at a ponderously slow speed of 2 or 3 knots. The Canadian
Navy ordered the gargantuan freighter to increase speed to 12
knots, a rate that would bring the ship into port near Montreal by
the end of this week. The war gear was supposed to have been
unloaded on July 16.
</P>
<P>
   ``The dispute is not fully settled,'' Mullin acknowledged in an
interview from Ottawa. ``But Canada is making clear it will protect
its equipment and its personnel.''
</P>
<P>
   Because of recent military spending cuts, Canada has to rely on
civilian shipping or air companies to transport its soldiers and
gear to peacekeeping assignments around the world.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-31-00 1836EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
