<HEADER>
A8623 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-CVN-NOTEBOOK01-COX     07-31 0594
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CVN-NOTEBOOK01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ Political tidbits from the Republican National
Convention:
</P>
<P>
   Different sides of the Republican party were on display Monday
in neighboring reception rooms at a Philadelphia hotel.
</P>
<P>
   In one, Reps. Bob Barr, R-Ga., and Dan Burton, R-Ind., received
awards for their pursuit of wrongdoing in the Clinton
administration. The award-givers were groups headed by committed
anti-Clintonites Floyd Brown and David Bossie, who worked for the
House investigative committee on which Burton and Barr serve.
</P>
<P>
   Barr received the ``Service Above Self'' award, Brown said, ``in
recognition of your willingness to sacrifice all in pursuit of
honesty and integrity in government.''
</P>
<P>
   Among those in attendance were Phyllis Schlafly, head of the
Eagle Forum, and Gary Aldrich, the former Secret Service agent who
wrote an expose of the Clinton White House.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dan, you point the way and I'll follow you,'' Barr said to
Burton.
</P>
<P>
   The other reception honored Teamsters leader James Hoffa, part
of the GOP's effort to break the Democratic stranglehold on the
labor vote.
</P>
<P>
   Republican luminaries, including former Speaker Newt Gingrich,
were all over that event.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, one Republican who planted himself in front of
microphones and cameras at Hoffa's reception was Barr, who was late
to his own reception as a result.
</P>
<P>
   A plane towing a Confederate flag and an anti-Bush slogan flew
over the the Republican Convention and downtown Philadelphia on
Monday to protest the removal of a several plaques dedicated to
Texas Confederate veterans from the Texas Supreme Court building.
</P>
<P>
   The plane flew over the First Union Center, site of the GOP
convention, toting a 10-by-15-foot Confederate battle flag and a
banner reading ``Bush: Put the TX vets plaques back!''
</P>
<P>
   The protest, sponsored by the Southern Heritage Community, will
continue tomorrow with the plane again pulling a Confederate flag
with a different banner reading ``GOP: No votes for turncoats!''
</P>
<P>
   The Southern Heritage Community is angry with Bush because he
removed the plaques from the Supreme Court building in Austin
without any public hearing or input because of a deal made with
Texas NAACP President Gary Bledsoe.
</P>
<P>
   Political humor here isn't limited to Comedy Central's
``Indecision 2000.'' Ordinary-looking men handed out
official-looking delegate guides on street corners Monday. They
were snapped up by delegates.
</P>
<P>
   But inside, the pamphlets contained the satire of
modernhumorist.com.
</P>
<P>
   It began with a letter purportedly from Philadelphia Mayor John
Street: ``Dear Delegate, Welcome to Philadelphia! I'm glad you're
here to spend your money in the Place that Loves You Back.''
</P>
<P>
   The guide also contains horoscopes (``Aquarius: Uncertainty may
gnaw at your insides, but this is no time to question your support
of school vouchers'') and ads for dates (``Cindi: blonde, smokin'
figure, believes abortion is murder'') that offer ``30 percent off
with NRA membership''; and a ``1 for the price of 2'' coupon.
</P>
<P>
   Check it out at www.modernhumorist.com.
</P>
<P>
   The City of Brotherly Love is showing much more affection to
visiting journalists than some past GOP conventions. At a lavish
press party Saturday night at the Convention Center, journalists
entered through an applauding and cheering gantlet of dozens of
volunteers. Not a single chant of ``No more lies'' was heard.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
