<TEXT>
<P>
   EDITORS: The New York Times News Service will move the following
stories this week from a special New York Times section on
Education Life. All will move in advance for Sunday, Aug. 6.
Questions or reruns: 888-346-9867 or 212-556-1927.
</P>
<P>
   EDLIFE-CATHOLIC-SCHOOLS (Undated) _ Nearly 10 years after many
educators had written them off for dead, Roman Catholic schools in
America are in the midst of an extraordinary revival. Enrollment is
up across the nation. Hundreds of new schools have opened. And more
than 40 percent of all Catholic elementary and secondary schools
have waiting lists for admission. By Timothy Egan.
</P>
<P>
   With Photos.
</P>
<P>
   EDLIFE-RURAL-SCHOOLS (Bloomfield, Mont.) _ Even as the number of
tiny rural schools has plunged in recent years, the fundamental
aspects of teaching and learning inside them _ from multi-age
classrooms and peer tutoring, to interdisciplinary projects and
keeping students with the same teacher for more than one year _ are
being copied in large school systems across the country. Small
classes and, especially, small schools, are increasingly seen as
crucial to students' success in the early grades, leading many
urban educators to create islands within large school buildings
that attempt to foster the intimacy and individual attention of
places like Bloomfield. And, with the Internet, long-held concerns
about the narrow curriculum available in an isolated one-teacher
school are fading. By Jodi Wilgoren.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   EDLIFE-MOZART-THEORY (Undated) _ Never mind that Mozart's
concertos strike peaceful chords in music lovers. In academia, the
battle lines are drawn, and the next salvo in the Mozart wars is
about to be fired. Researchers are mustering data to counter those
who are intent on debunking the ``Mozart effect'' _ the theory that
classical music makes the brain work better _ and they have some
high-profile allies. By Roberta Hershenson.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   EDLIFE-NEWZEALAND (Wellington) _ For the last 10 years New
Zealand has provided a laboratory for many of the educational
theories that have become increasingly popular among would-be
reformers in the United States in recent years, most notably
charter schools and vouchers. Yet when Trevor Mallard became New
Zealand's minister of education several months ago, one of his
first steps was to bolster direct government assistance to troubled
urban schools. Although the programs he announced were hardly
unusual _ more money for early-childhood education, clustering of
schools with common problems, a bigger national investment in
teacher training _ they were notable far beyond this island nation.
The reason: They signaled the end of a decade-long flirtation with
the notion that parental choice and competition among schools
would, in and of themselves, improve the educational offerings of
troubled urban schools. By Edward B. Fiske and Helen F. Ladd.
</P>
<P>
   EDLIFE-CYBERSPACE-COLLEGES (Undated) _ Universe Online is one of
the many so-called distance-learning programs hovering in
cyberspace. According to reports from the U.S. Department of
Education, at least one-third of the 3,500 colleges and
universities in the United States offer distance-learning courses;
within the next two years, four out of every five are expected to
do so. By Abby Ellin.
</P>
<P>
   EDLIFE-ADAPTIVE-TESTING (Undated) _ With virtually everything
becoming electronic and digital, it may be no surprise to discover
that the hum of hard drives has replaced the scent of freshly
sharpened pencils for students taking many of today's standardized
admissions tests. But here is the catch: Most computerized tests
are not merely onscreen versions of what appears in paper
workbooks. Rather than simply scanning in copies of multiple choice
examinations, some test makers have prepared adaptive tests,
meaning that they are designed to adapt, on the fly, to the ability
of the person taking the test. By Lisa Guernsey.
</P>
<P>
   EDLIFE-FRESHMEN-STRESS (Undated) _ While some first-year college
students experience little or no anxiety, most have a stress story,
be it academic or personal, about family or financial
responsibilities, inadequate high school preparation or pressure to
do well in today's increasingly competitive environment. In a 1999
survey of 683 colleges and universities conducted in the first days
of school by UCLA, 30.2 percent of freshmen acknowledged that they
frequently felt overwhelmed, almost double the rate in 1985. By
Glenn C. Altschuler.
</P>
</TEXT>
