<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-31 18:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8640 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-BUYING-ELECTRICITY-AR     07-31 1093
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUYING-ELECTRICITY-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR INDUSTRY, BUYING ENERGY HAS BECOME A COMPLEX COST-CUTTING
ENDEAVOR 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By CLAUDIA H. DEUTSCH   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Last summer, an accident at a local utility curtailed power to
Owens Corning's Kansas City, Kan., plant, sending it scrambling to
find alternative energy. It was a costly, nerve-racking experience.
</P>
<P>
   Since then the company has signed a 10-year contract with Enron
Energy Services to buy electricity for its 20 largest U.S. plants,
and has hired a sales manager from a Belgian utility to handle its
electricity purchases in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   The Enron unit will negotiate the contracts and pay all the
bills. But Owens Corning, a fiberglass maker whose annual
electricity tab tops $200 million, has also hired three energy
specialists to help manage risk, reduce consumption and keep
abreast of technologies.
</P>
<P>
   ``Enron may be driving the car, but we're still in the front
seat,'' said Charles E. Dana, vice president for global sourcing
operations.
</P>
<P>
   There was a time, not so long ago, when buying electricity was a
simple matter. The local utility was the only game in town, the
state set the rates, there was little to do but sign on the dotted
line.
</P>
<P>
   These days, not only are there myriad utilities and upstart
energy companies to choose from, but countless permutations of ways
to contract for electricity, including buying it on the Web.
</P>
<P>
   Different suppliers produce the electricity, transmit it and
deliver it. Futures contracts, derivatives and negotiated rate caps
all offer ways to hedge against wild swings in usage, fuel costs _
a particularly germane consideration nowadays _ or other reasons
for rates that soar and dip and soar again.
</P>
<P>
   Today's energy buyers must know how to predict weather and
economic fluctuations as well as how to drive hard bargains. They
must know how to find suppliers who will give them a cheaper rate
if they switch some of their usage from peak to night or other
off-peak times _ and then, how to skew energy usage so that it can
make more use of that cheaper energy.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's no longer the buying of the commodity that's important,''
said Carol H. Guthrie, group manager for Chevron U.S.A.'s
electricity supply group. ``It's gathering all the information that
allows you to buy it.''
</P>
<P>
   Thus, from metal smelters to property managers, from
manufacturers to telecommunications companies, all kinds of
companies are rethinking not only how they buy that critical
electricity, but who is doing that buying, how much they are paid,
even whom they report to.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not saying energy knowledge is a requirement for all jobs
these days,'' said Robert H. Welsh, a senior partner at the
executive recruiting firm Heidrick &AMP; Struggles International, ``but
if a candidate for chief technology officer also has energy
experience, the client nods happily.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, many companies are pulling chief financial officers and
chief technology officers into energy buying. Others are retraining
and promoting engineers, accountants or particularly talented
buyers. Still others are scouring the regulatory community, the
utilities, even Wall Street for energy-savvy people. And many are
letting consultants seek out suppliers, negotiate contracts, even
survey the company for ways to cut usage.
</P>
<P>
   ``Buying and selling energy has become a real financial play,
and it needs someone with sophisticated knowledge of finance and
energy both,'' said Bruce W. Peterson, a managing director at the
executive recruiting firm Korn/Ferry International, who is
searching for just such a person for a client.
</P>
<P>
   Such people do not come cheap. Doron Cohen, an energy specialist
at the research firm Gartner, knows a vice president at a metals
company who quit in a rage when he discovered that younger, newly
hired energy buyers made more than he did.
</P>
<P>
   ``The person who'll work for $60,000 doesn't have the knowledge
you need, and you can't attract commodities traders unless bonuses
and such give them a shot at making $1 million a year,'' Cohen
said.
</P>
<P>
   The competition, and the inflated pay rates, promises to worsen.
Utilities, now that they increasingly are allowed to sell
electricity in areas with wildly fluctuating climates and usages,
are hiring traders to help lock in margins between the price of
natural gas they buy and the possible prices of power they might
sell.
</P>
<P>
   Companies like Enron Energy Services, which handle purchases for
many clients and thus can more easily justify paying top dollar,
have bid the price for the most experienced traders and energy
specialists through the roof, offering packages of salary, bonus
and equity that can hit $1.5 million a year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Buying energy these days is all about managing risk and income
statements,'' said Harold G. Buchanan, a managing director at
Enron. ``We're more like an investment bank than a utility.''
</P>
<P>
   The result, for corporations, is sticker shock. ``The biggest
challenge was to create that cultural shift in the client's mind,
away from a $60,000 procurement guy to a $200,000 Wall Street
professional who can hedge and contain costs and minimize risk,''
said Richard J. Preng, managing director of the recruiting firm
Spencer Stuart's global energy practice, who recently placed an
energy supply chief at a metals company, for a pay package ``north
of $300,000.''
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, the answer for many companies is to pay
consultants, not staff members. Corning, the optical cable
supplier, used to have four energy buyers; it now has one, whose
main job is to be a liaison with a subsidiary of Amerada Hess,
which has taken over the company's energy programs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Outsourcing lets us focus on the high-level management of
energy,'' said Ernest J. Williams, Corning's director of
procurement operations.
</P>
<P>
   Rockefeller Group International, which owns several office
buildings and industrial parks, saved $500,000 on electricity bills
for two New York City skyscrapers when it hired John Flood, an
energy consultant, to evaluate energy bids. Similarly, Rockefeller
Group's Cushman &AMP; Wakefield subsidiary now lets M.C. Energy
negotiate its electricity contracts at the dozens of buildings it
manages. Frank A. Freda, a Cushman senior managing director,
estimates that M.C. Energy has shaved $2.6 million off Cushman's
energy tab in New York City; he is now using the firm in other
states.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   The ubiquitous Web has given rise to yet another form of
third-party energy buyer: the auctioneer. The Public Service
Enterprise Group's Energy Technologies unit, an energy consultant
in Edison, N.J., just teamed up with Enermetrix.com, a Web
start-up, to run Internet auctions in which Public Service clients
post total energy requirements, and energy suppliers bid to fill
them.
</P>
<P>
   Still, corporate clients keep a close watch on the results.
``The energy buyers are looking at the bids, and I imagine that
higher-level people are giving the final OK on the offers,'' said
Frederick W. Lark, a vice president of Public Service.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, energy is increasingly becoming an executive suite
topic. KeySpan Energy's KeySpan Business Solutions unit, which
designs and builds energy systems, counts among its clients a large
shopping mall developer.
</P>
<P>
   ``They used to let local construction managers write contracts
with local utilities,'' said Anthony Sartor, Keyspan's president.
``Now they have an energy engineer who works with their CFO to
evaluate bids and finance the energy systems.''
</P>
<P>
   For commercial companies, reducing energy costs is a nicety. For
manufacturers, whose energy tabs go into the multimillions, it is a
necessity. Increasingly, such companies are recognizing that
scrimping on energy expertise is penny-wise and pound-foolish.
</P>
<P>
   Hoffman-LaRoche, a unit of Roche Holding, the drug giant based
in Nutley, N.J., recently piggybacked onto an energy contract the
New Jersey Chemical Industry Council had negotiated with Allegheny
Energy, an independent supplier, for its members. But Hoffman,
unlike many companies on the contract, generates some of its own
power. So John Parodi, a former utility executive who became
Hoffman's senior energy manager three years ago, negotiated extra
clauses.
</P>
<P>
   ``I needed the provider to supply energy beyond what we
generated ourselves, but also to cover us if our generators go
down,'' Parodi said. He is now scouting out energy suppliers for
Hoffman-LaRoche plants in other states.
</P>
<P>
   Even companies that have had energy experts for years are taking
a fresh look at them.
</P>
<P>
   Since joining Chevron U.S.A. in 1994, Guthrie has reported first
to the vice president in charge of refining operations, then to the
vice president of a natural gas unit _ ``there was a perceived
synergy in deregulatory processes,'' she explained _ and then again
to a refining executive.
</P>
<P>
   In January, her group's name was changed from energy services to
electricity supply, and Guthrie and her four subordinates report to
the head of procurement. One goal is to whittle the number of
suppliers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Chevron has more than 130 electricity suppliers, and we want
to look at procurement strategies that can span regions and
products,'' Guthrie explained. Last week, Chevron announced that it
had started Chevron Energy Services, a unit aimed at helping
clients control their total energy costs as well.
</P>
<P>
   At Honeywell International, which spends upwards of $300 million
a year on electricity, buyers are broadening their definition of
energy. Honeywell's five specialists _ four of them added to staff
in the last four years _ have worked out contracts with suppliers
of industrial gases in which the suppliers set up shop at a
Honeywell plant and use some of its waste heat, steam and other
sources of energy that might have been vented to the atmosphere.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hydrogen and oxygen are really water and a lot of
electricity,'' said William L. Ramsey, Honeywell's vice president
for the supply chain. ``So it makes sense to work with industrial
gas suppliers as though they were power generators.''
</P>
<P>
   As deregulation continues its slow creep from state to state,
corporate energy czars are rising to prominence at companies that
do not have energy-intensive manufacturing.
</P>
<P>
   Five years ago Bell Atlantic _ which merged with GTE in June,
and is now Verizon Communications _ hired Jeremy Metz, a lawyer
specializing in energy and environment, to head its energy
procurement.
</P>
<P>
   Metz, using his regulatory know-how, has already saved the
company millions by getting it included in every pilot program for
deregulating energy in New Jersey, New York, New Hampshire and
Pennsylvania. And last year he hired another full-time buyer,
someone with 20 years experience buying generation equipment.
``I've got the legal and regulatory experience,'' Metz said. ``He
understands the nuts and bolts of the energy world.''
</P>
<P>
   The company has pulled in operating people, too. Last year it
formed Team Energy _ 12 people pulled from various operating groups
and charged with looking for ways to economize on energy use. It
has hired outside auditors to look for even more efficiencies. And
it has put a link on its Web site that facilities managers can use
to monitor their electric bills.
</P>
<P>
   ``A big part of my job was convincing the people who run our
data centers or network operations that some newfangled power
supplier is going to be reliable,'' Metz said. ``Now they're
convinced, and they're ready to look for other opportunities to
improve the way we use energy.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-31-00 1854EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
