<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-31 18:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8642 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a BC-SCI-PHYSICS-PARTICLES     07-31 0904
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-PHYSICS-PARTICLES-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW CLUES TO NATURE'S LOPSIDEDNESS
</HEADLINE>
  (The Science Times) 
(ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036.) 
 By JAMES GLANZ   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Particle discoveries, like home runs in baseball, get all the
attention from casual fans of physics. The arrival of a new
particle is exciting, important and easy to understand. But while
physicists appreciate the Ruthian impact of discovering a new
elementary particle like the top quark or the recent finding of the
tau neutrino, they know that there is a less heralded realm of
discovery that can do every bit as much to change the course of
science. That realm involves laws of symmetry _ how nature obeys
them, and especially how it breaks them.
</P>
<P>
   Physicists' most hallowed theories of the structure of matter
are based on the interplay of symmetries as revealed by the ways
particles move, interact and decay. For example, the orbits of an
electron in a hydrogen atom depend profoundly on the symmetry, or
invariance, of the force on the electron no matter how the atomic
nucleus is rotated. As in planetary systems, the force depends only
on the distance between the electron and the nucleus.
</P>
<P>
   Measurements of those subtleties can severely test the accuracy
of the theories and reveal their shortcomings. In baseball
language, symmetries are the pitching and defense of particle
physics.
</P>
<P>
   The mysteries of symmetry and asymmetry extend to the cosmos,
too. Scientists have not quite figured out why nearly all the
universe they have observed is made of ordinary matter. If the laws
of particle physics were exactly the same for every particle and
its antimatter partner _ one kind of symmetry _ then the Big Bang
explosion in which the universe is believed to have been born would
have created equal amounts of matter and antimatter, which would
then have annihilated each other, and the universe would be empty.
</P>
<P>
   Announcements Monday by two large, multinational experimental
teams at the 30th International Conference on High Energy Physics
in Osaka, Japan, herald a new round of research to determine the
exact degree of nature's lopsidedness, and what consequences it may
have for the observable universe.
</P>
<P>
   One of the teams is based at the High Energy Accelerator
Research Organization in Tsukuba, Japan, known as the KEK
laboratory for its Japanese acronym. ``It's not just the discovery
of a new particle which is important for particle physics and
cosmology,'' said Hirotaka Sugawara, director general of KEK.
``Symmetry is something we have to understand.''
</P>
<P>
   At the core of this concern are extremely difficult experiments
that observe particles and their antimatter counterparts directly,
in search of slight differences in things like their decay rates
and the particles they decay into. Physicists have known since 1964
that small differences exist, but they have not found a way to
measure just how large the differences are.
</P>
<P>
   Without that quantitative knowledge, physicists have been unable
to determine whether asymmetry is correctly predicted by their
Standard Model of particle physics, the theory that describes all
existing data on the structure and behavior of matter. Any gap
between the predictions and observations would mean that the theory
is wrong.
</P>
<P>
   And if the measured asymmetry turns out to be too small, said
Zoltan Ligeti, a physicist at the Fermi National Accelerator
Laboratory near Chicago, the impact on scientists' understanding of
the cosmos could be serious. ``We would be at a complete loss, and
we would have to say we don't know a conceivable way to produce
more matter than antimatter,'' Ligeti said.
</P>
<P>
   But help in answering those questions is on the way, according
to the simultaneous announcements Monday in Osaka.
</P>
<P>
   The teams, one based at KEK and one at the Stanford Linear
Accelerator Center in California, announced that they had each
succeeded in producing millions of well-known, if somewhat obscure,
particles called B mesons along with their antimatter counterparts.
Scientists at these ``B factories'' plan to compare the decay rates
of B's and anti-B's with a precision that has never before been
possible. The comparison should provide a new measuring stick of
one of nature's most basic symmetries _ or asymmetries.
</P>
<P>
   The results are still so sketchy, and the experiments so
demanding, that neither team is ready to claim definitively that it
has seen the asymmetry, which goes by the name of charge-parity
violation, or CP violation. But as more data streams in, the early
results do show hints of the expected signature of CP violation.
</P>
<P>
   ``These results are very preliminary, and they don't turn the
world of science on their ear,'' said David Hitlin, a physicist at
the California Institute of Technology and a spokesman for
Stanford's BaBar experiment, a play on ``B-bar,'' as anti-B mesons
are often called, and the children's book elephant.
</P>
<P>
   While the results do show hints of CP violation, its observed
strength falls slightly below the predictions of the Standard
Model. Cosmologists already find it difficult to reconcile the
observed asymmetry of matter and antimatter with the amount of CP
violation predicted by the Standard Model, so the conflict would
throw a big curve at theorists _ just what experimentalists love to
do.
(MORE) nn
</P>
<P>
   If the finding holds up as more data comes in, Hitlin said,
``that would be something that would be very exciting.''
</P>
<P>
   But first, the experimentalists will have to agree with each
other. Sugawara said the KEK experiment, nicknamed Belle, had found
a larger value that was in agreement with the Standard Model. With
somewhat less data so far than BaBar, Belle's error bars were also
large, so that the two results could not be said to be in conflict.
An earlier experiment at Fermilab found a still larger value, near
the upper end of the predictions, though once again the
uncertainties were substantial.
</P>
<P>
   Eric Prebys, a physicist at Princeton University who is a
collaborator on Belle, said, ``Everything at the moment is
consistent with each other.''
</P>
<P>
   The measurements are demanding enough that physicists are not
likely to accept any startling conclusions until the numbers are
much more refined and the experiments agree, Prebys said.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, the scientific industry of sorts that has grown
around CP violation did begin with a completely unexpected
discovery in 1964. Before that experiment, which won a Nobel Prize
for James Cronin and Val Fitch in 1980, scientists were sure that
the laws of physics exactly obeyed what is called CP invariance.
</P>
<P>
   Checking for CP invariance involves the following imaginary
process: First, take all particles and reverse their charge (the
``C'' part) from positive to negative or vice versa. Then change
particles with left-handed ``spins'' to being right-handed (the
``P'' part) and vice versa. If the particles behave the same in
this new world as they did in the old, then the laws of physics are
CP invariant.
</P>
<P>
   Since the CP operation changes any particle into its
antiparticle, CP invariance would mean that physical laws are
exactly the same for matter and antimatter.
</P>
<P>
   Cronin, of the University of Chicago, and Fitch, of Princeton,
threw a monkey wrench into that symmetric worldview when they found
that particles called kaons sometimes decayed in a way that
violated this rule. Two Japanese theorists, Makoto Kobayashi and
Toshihide Maskawa, later showed how the Standard Model could be
modified to accommodate this result. But even though the change
should cause CP violation in other particles, experimentalists have
still not unambiguously detected it in anything but kaons.
</P>
<P>
   To make things worse, said Ligeti of Fermilab, theorists find it
problematical, for technical reasons, to compare the kaon results
in a very precise or direct way to the asymmetry that the theorists
put at the heart of the Standard Model. The violation is thought to
be related to something called the weak nuclear force, but effects
of another interaction called the strong force confuse matters in
kaons.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we are after is trying to test whether the Standard Model
is right or wrong,'' Ligeti said. But in order to make a precise
test with kaons, he said, ``we have to compute quantities which we
don't quite know how to compute.''
</P>
<P>
   The predicted effect is both simpler to interpret and larger in
magnitude in B mesons, said Fumihiko Takasaki, a KEK physicist who
is a spokesman for the Belle collaboration.
</P>
<P>
   So both collaborations aimed to create pairs of B mesons and
anti-B mesons by smashing together electrons and their own
antimatter counterparts, positrons, in particle accelerators. The
electrons and positrons are accelerated to high energy in a linear
accelerator and then injected into a ring, where they circulate in
opposite directions and smash together, said Riccardo Faccini, a
BaBar collaborator at the Stanford accelerator center.
</P>
<P>
   In an experimental twist, the electrons and positrons are
injected at slightly different energies so that the B mesons, when
they are created, drift steadily in one direction at about half the
speed of light rather than remaining stationary. The drift amounts
to a clever way to measure time as a meson, and then its
antiparticle, decay in a spray of particles. By allowing
researchers to trace this spray of particle tracks back to their
source, the high-resolution detectors _ called, unsurprisingly,
Belle and BaBar _ pinpoint the spot at which the decays take place.
</P>
<P>
   Since the B mesons are drifting, the distance they have traveled
gives a measure of the time at which the decays took place. By
comparing the detailed time dependence of B meson decays and anti-B
meson decays, physicists can search for evidence of an asymmetry
that indicates CP violation has taken place.
</P>
<P>
   So far, of 10 million B mesons produced in BaBar, 120 have been
of the specific type that allows the team to look for CP violation,
leading to their preliminary results. Belle still has fewer events,
but both teams are collecting large amounts of data in preparation
for an all-out assault on the problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``The science of CP violation in the B physics system is born,''
said Christopher Hill, a physicist at Fermilab.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
