<HEADER>
A8645 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-ISRAEL-POLITICS-ART-N     07-31 1045
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-POLITICS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BARAK BARELY SURVIVES NO-CONFIDENCE VOTE; HIS CHOICE FOR PRESIDENT
IS REJECTED 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photos NYT2, NYT3 are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) By JOHN KIFNER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak survived a
parliamentary no-confidence vote Monday mounted by opponents of his
peace efforts, but his heavily-favored candidate for Israel's
president, Shimon Peres, suffered a stunning defeat in the twilight
of a long career.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Parliament chose Moshe Katsav, a little-known
Iranian-born lawmaker of the opposition Likud Party who began his
political career as mayor of a small working-class desert town.
</P>
<P>
   Ariel Sharon, the hawkish, hard-line Likud leader was, as
expected, unable to muster the 61-seat absolute majority in the 120
seat Knesset, or Parliament, that was needed to topple the
government. With Parliament scheduled to adjourn on Wednesday for
its three-month vacation, the hard-pressed Barak now has a period
to try to rebuild his tattered coalition and push for some form of
resumption of the peace talks that stalled at Camp David.
</P>
<P>
   The vote seemed almost anticlimactic. It came after three hours
of heated debate _ relatively short by Knesset standards _ with
speakers interrupted by rowdy, hand-waving shouts and insults from
the floor. The votes cast were exactly 50 to 50, with 8 abstentions
and 12 members withdrawing, casting no votes.
</P>
<P>
   But it was far from a victory for Barak, who now must piece
together a coalition in the fragmented Parliament from small
parties _ religious, secular, nationalist, liberal and others _
whose interests are often at sharp odds. Indeed, the vote suggested
that many members simply wanted to avoid calling new elections for
fear they would lose their seats.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only thing that is sustaining the prime minister is that
the Knesset members do not want, at this time, to go to elections
within 90 days,'' said Israel radio's chief political analyst,
Yaron Dekel. He added that Peres' defeat was ``a severe blow that
can start a snowball effect that can lead to the downfall of his
government _ this is a prime minister without a government.''
</P>
<P>
   In an analysis a few hours later on Israeli television, after
the no-confidence vote, Dekel said, ``This is the worst day for
Barak since he was elected.''
</P>
<P>
   Much of the political drama Monday centered on the vote for the
largely honorary office of president. Peres, dressed in an elegant
dark suit and blue polka-dot tie, wandered around the Parliament
chamber, ashen-faced, when it became clear that he would lose.
</P>
<P>
   Peres, twice prime minister and winner of the Nobel Peace Prize,
lost to an earnest, but colorless politician who had once been
known as the ``tolerant and polite'' member of Parliament.
</P>
<P>
   The blow was all the more shocking because every pundit in this
intensely political country had called Peres a shoo-in. ``Peres
Poised to Win Presidency,'' was the main headline in the Jerusalem
Post, while in Haaretz it was ``Peres confident of capturing
Presidency.
</P>
<P>
   But when the envelopes in the secret ballot were opened in the
first round of voting at midday, Katsov had 60 votes _ one short of
victory _ while Peres had 53. Three ballots were blank.
</P>
<P>
   Barak and his One Israel floor leaders huddled, worried and
baffled. Sharon's Likud supporters and the ultra-Orthodox Sephardic
members of Shas grinned hugely and, as the final vote showed Katsov
with 63 votes, hugged and cried.
</P>
<P>
   It was a big win for Sharon, the first time the candidate
sponsored by Likud was elected president. The election of Katsav
was also seen as a product of the increasing challenge by Sephardic
Jews _ largely of Middle eastern origin _ to the traditional
Ashkenazi European elite.
</P>
<P>
   And, in a long political career, the silver-haired Peres had
also made enemies. It appeared that about five members of his own
party voted against him in the secret ballot.
</P>
<P>
   Barak had to attend Monday's session and listen to the scorn
heaped on him _ prime ministers do not normally respond in person
to a no-confidence motion _ because Likud's Limor Livnat had taken
the unusual step of getting 40 members' signatures requiring
Barak's presence.
</P>
<P>
   In the debate, Livnat, one of Likud's most forceful orators,
shouted accusations at the prime minister, accusing him of making
major concessions, then, ``you write a letter to Clinton stating
that suddenly it has become clear to you that the Palestinians are
not partners to the talks and they are not negotiating in good
faith.
</P>
<P>
   ``For this we should say `good morning, Elijah.' Finally you
have discovered what we have known for a long time.
</P>
<P>
   Barak sat through the lecture, making a few notes, with his
usual half-smile.
</P>
<P>
   Sharon led off the Likud attack, accusing Barak of broken
promises.
</P>
<P>
   Barak responded by mounting the podium and saying: ``I appeal to
each and every one of you and ask you to rise above petty
politics.''
</P>
<P>
   He cited President Clinton's appearance on Israeli television
Friday, with its hints of moving the American Embassy to Jerusalem
_ a sought-after dream here and a reversal of 50 years of American
policy. ``We strengthened Israel's international standing,'' he
said. ``We removed it from international isolation.''
</P>
<P>
   At the heart of Barak's political problem is a 1996 change in
electoral procedures providing for separate voting for prime
minister and members of Parliament. Although Barak won a strong
mandate in May 1999, defeating Benjamin Netanyahu of Likud with 56
percent of the vote, Barak has had to deal with a fragmented,
unwieldy Parliament with many small parties.
</P>
<P>
   Deputy Defense Minister Ephraim Sneh, an old comrade of Barak's
from the country's most elite secret commando unit and also a
former general, called in frustration Monday for new elections.
</P>
<P>
   ``If, in the current political makeup of the Knesset, we could
not bring about the election of Peres, it is a sign that we will be
unable to pass other things,'' Sneh said on Israel radio.
``Therefore we must go directly to the nation, to present our path,
so that the nation can decide what it wants.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
