<HEADER>
A8646 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k BC-EDITORIAL-BARAK-BOS &LR;      07-31 0378
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-BARAK-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BARAK BESIEGED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It was a spectacle that fused the historic with the mundane.
There was Ehud Barak, the military commander renowned for his
fastidious planning of operations, absorbing the stunning defeat of
his candidate for president of Israel, Nobel Peace Prize laureate
Shimon Peres, and then barely surviving two parliamentary
no-confidence votes just days after he had failed to strike a
historic accord with the Palestinians at Camp David. Barak the
meticulous strategist was compelled to practice the imprecise art
of muddling through.
</P>
<P>
   Since the onset of the democratic era, such spectacles have been
common. Israel's political maelstrom is merely more colorful than
other democracies, more akin to what literary critics call magic
realism. On the eve of the vote for Israel's president, the
spiritual leader of the Shas party, a rabbi in his 90s, said he had
a dream that Peres's opponent was favored by the heavens.
Consequently, all 17 members of the Knesset from Shas voted for the
candidate from the Likud party, Moshe Katsav.
</P>
<P>
   So common to democracies is the problem confronted by Barak that
the Germans have a formulaic phrase for it. They call it the
primacy of domestic politics.
</P>
<P>
   In this case, the undemocratic Yasser Arafat would be wise to do
what he can to assist Barak in muddling through his domestic
difficulties. The same holds true for those monarchs and
presidents- for-life who rule surrounding Arab states and share an
interest in seizing the present opportunity to foster a durable
peace in the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
   It is now up to Barak to form a governing coalition that can
pursue peace during the coming three months, when the Knesset is
not in session. He has said he is confident a majority of Israelis
will support any deal he negotiates with Arafat, reasoning that
Israelis know he does not require instruction on the nation's
security needs.
</P>
<P>
   If Barak does create a coalition conducive to the compromises
needed for peace, Arafat will have to do his part _ while Israel
still has a government willing to seek a realistic solution to the
problem of peaceful coexistence for Israelis and Palestinians.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
