u k BC-EDITORIAL-LOANS-BOS &LR;      07-31 0376
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-LOANS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHORTCHANGING YOUNG MDS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   One of the biggest health problems in the United States is the
lack of access to care faced by residents of rural areas and inner
cities. To get more doctors to work in such underserved parts of
the country, the federal government for over a decade has been
offering bonuses to help cover the tuition loans of graduating
medical students willing to put up with the relatively low pay of
work at a rural or urban community health center.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, the law authorizing the grants expires Sept. 30,
with no reauthorization in sight. Even worse, The New York Times
reported Sunday, the $30 million program has been so underfunded
recently that many doctors have not been getting what was promised
them. This is a dismaying situation that both Congress and the
Clinton administration should address immediately.
</P>
<P>
   Statistics on the availability of doctors in varying parts of
the country or even a city make clear the need for such recruiting
inducements for graduating medical students who, on average, are
leaving school with more than $90,000 in tuition debt. While
managed care programs recommend a ratio of 218 doctors for 100,000
patients, many of the country's health centers are in isolated
areas where there are fewer than 35 doctors for that population.
</P>
<P>
   Funds are especially short this year for the medical education
grants because the Department of Health and Human Services cut back
sharply on them to meet other spending requirements. The health
centers themselves are in no position to make up the difference
because they are being squeezed by inadequate reimbursements for
their Medicaid and Medicare patients.
</P>
<P>
   Two steps are needed. Congress should act quickly to reauthorize
the 1989 law setting up the grants program, and the Clinton
administration and Congress should make sure that a modest $4
million increase in program funding in the House version of the
budget makes it into the spending document's final version. After
years of calling on college graduates to make good on their college
loans, it is unconscionable now for Washington to walk away from
its own commitments.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
