<SLUG> BC-KENNEDY-COLUMN-1stLdWritethru-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MCCAIN UBIQUITOUS AS BUNTING AT GOP CONVENTION
</HEADLINE>
 
 (EDS: Changes hometown of Kalin Olson from Little Rock to Hot
Springs)  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 By BUD KENNEDY 
 c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ Tuesday will be Day Two of the Sen. John McCain
National Convention.
</P>
<P>
   With nobody here yet to shush him _ though Laura Bush might try
_ McCain has been talking on every street corner and shaking hands
at every Philly cheese steak stand, leaving no microphone silent as
he campaigns for Most Popular Ex-Candidate at the Republicans'
convention.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday night, he's giving the keynote speech in prime time
after ``Judging Amy.'' Last night, he opined on ``Larry King
Live.'' All last weekend and all week, he has been tailed by
gaggles of reporters hanging on his every word, except when the
words are ``George W. Bush.''
</P>
<P>
   If Bush doesn't get here soon, McCain may start moving in with
Laura. He's already making big-time moves on the Republican
nomination in 2004.
</P>
<P>
   Granted, everybody here is desperate to see a presidential
candidate. On Sunday night, 600 wavering Republican delegates and
even 10 members of Congress turned out to toast the arrival of a
widely promoted third-party candidate, Captain Morgan of The
Seagram Co.'s Rum Loyalists' Party.
</P>
<P>
   So far, he's the only politician who outdrew McCain. However,
the Republicans may have been attracted by the unfulfilled promise
of an appearance by ``Playboy'' ``playmate'' and vice presidential
candidate Kalin Olson (Miss August 1997) of Hot Springs, Ark.
</P>
<P>
   Without benefit of playmates, McCain still attracted 70
reporters to ride along as he made his grand entrance to
Philadelphia aboard his ``Straight Talk Express'' campaign bus from
Arlington, Va., with three more buses in the caravan.
</P>
<P>
   He was starring on ``Face the Nation'' Sunday. He was
autographing his book, ``Faith of My Fathers,'' at the Bourse
building. He was welcoming his former delegates in a teary-eyed
televised farewell at the Hotel Sofitel.
</P>
<P>
   He even spoke to a warm welcome Sunday at a ``shadow''
counter-convention for college students at the University of
Pennsylvania. The audience of several hundred students, described
as laden with nose rings and tattoos, clapped and chanted his name
_ turning hostile only when McCain said Bush ``is the candidate who
offers change.''
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, he starred in an MTV special from the Hard Rock Cafe.
</P>
<P>
   I'm amazed that he wasn't at City Hall for the assembly of the
World's Largest Hoagie.
</P>
<P>
   They could have used the bologna.
</P>
<P>
   Once, McCain called Bush a ``Pat Robertson Republican'' and said
the governor's knowledge of foreign affairs consisted of trips to
the International House of Pancakes. Now, he compliments Bush's
``inclusive'' campaign, and he had better brag on Bush for at least
several sentences tonight.
</P>
<P>
   McCain has professed no pretensions. ``The last time I looked, I
was a United States senator,'' he said aboard his
once-and-possibly-future campaign bus.
</P>
<P>
   But he also joked to the ``New York Post'' that he was watching
out for a ``grenade from Texas.'' He added: ``Seriously, I believe
Governor Bush sees this in a positive light.''
</P>
<P>
   If Bush saw McCain in a positive light, the senator would be
here on the ticket instead of Dick Cheney. That brings to mind last
week's McCain attempt to upstage the future nominee, when his
friends floated the rumor that he ``might'' accept the second spot
on the ticket when no such deal was in the works.
</P>
<P>
   Monday afternoon, the omnipresent McCain popped up hosting a
blue-ribbon panel discussion on foreign affairs. For a discussion
featuring six former secretaries of state, reporters walked into
the Philadelphia Convention Center press room asking anxiously,
``Where's the McCain speech?'' ``Did I miss McCain?'' ``What time
is McCain?''
</P>
<P>
   Not a single nose ring was in sight as he joked, ``Since I've
withdrawn from the campaign, my reception is getting warmer.
</P>
<P>
   ``If this keeps up, I'm going to demand a recount.''
</P>
<P>
   I'm not sure whether to take McCain seriously. Or Captain
Morgan.
</P>
<P>
   (Bud Kennedy is a columnist for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
You can call him at (817) 390-7538, or e-mail:
budk(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
