<HEADLINE>
US TRIALS WILL BE HOTLY CONTESTED, KAROLYI SAYS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN PAUL DUPONT  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Sixty floors above the Hub, in the Summit Room of John
Hancock's looking-glass tower, only the keenest eye in the land
Monday could have fixed a direction on Sydney.
</P>
<P>
   Peter Kormann and Bela Karolyi were in town to talk about
Olympus _ specifically the US Olympic gymnastic trials to be held
at the FleetCenter Aug. 17-20 _ and in the misty gray of the day,
both men talked of bright, promising horizons in Australia.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are as good as the other teams in the world right now,''
said Kormann, the former Olympic bronze medalist who again is head
coach of the men's team. ``Point for point, we are matched with
them. There are no more mountains to climb. And in the distance, we
see a little bit of glimmering, and it's Olympic medals.''
</P>
<P>
   Fresh from the national championships that concluded Saturday in
St. Louis, Kormann and Karolyi were here with their newly crowned
champions, Blaine Wilson and Elise Ray, touting the return of the
tumblers to Causeway Street. The Olympic trials were also held at
the Fleet in '96.
</P>
<P>
   Wilson, who will turn 26 Wednesday, has already been guaranteed
one of the six spots for the Games in September. Ray, 18, is the
freshest face among a bold, impressive pack of young women who will
try to fend off some formidable older challengers, including the
Magnificent Seven likes of Olympic gold medalists Amy Chow,
Dominique Dawes, Dominique Moceanu, and Shannon Miller.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are looking forward,'' said Karolyi, the '96 women's head
coach and now the team's coordinator, ``to having one of the most
incredible, most fiery, most disputed Olympic trials we ever had _
particularly on the women's side.''
</P>
<P>
   By Kormann's count, the indefatigable Wilson, a returnee from
the '96 team, has rattled off 110 consecutive victories in national
competition. He refers to his sculpted charge as the Tiger Woods of
gymnastics. The triumph in St. Louis brought Wilson an
unprecedented fifth consecutive national championship.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even if you're the best guy,'' said Kormann, Wilson's former
coach at Ohio State, ``to go out 110 times and win five consecutive
USA championships, and prove it on the floor . . . that's extremely
rare.''
</P>
<P>
   Ray and four other relative newcomers took the top five spots in
St. Louis, making life difficult for Chow (sixth), Moceanu
(eighth), and Dawes (ninth). Miller, who has more medals in
international competition than any other gymnast in US history,
came to the nationals only to show that she was serious about being
in shape for the trials. Her petition to compete here is only a
formality, but it remains to be seen whether she can regain her
championship form in time to make the bus to Sydney.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, sure, Miller can come like she's alays done,'' said
Karolyi, ``in very critical moments, and come up with a surprising
high-caliber performance, which immediately changes the whole
ranking.''
</P>
<P>
   Chow didn't place as well in St. Louis as Karolyi expected. He
also thought Dawes would be stronger. But given his read of some of
the younger challengers, that their inconsistency and lack of
experience makes them vulnerable, the colorful coach bellowed, ``It
is not over yet!''
</P>
<P>
   Miller could be especially valuable, perhaps more as a mature,
respected leader than what she might bring to the point total.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a benefit,'' said Karolyi. ``And it's a benefit for
many, many different reasons. First of all, prestige. We put
Shannon on the team, and the prestige of the team immediately _ and
I mean the visibility of the team _ comes up higher. Not inside,
because we all know her. But on the outside, the ones that don't
know _ but they know a Shannon Miller. So Shannon is in there,
boom, and suddenly it's, `Oh my, oh my,'' and Shannon is maybe not
even the best coming into the (tournament), but people are
thinking, `Oh, that's how good they can be.' ''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Jim Delaney, director of public relations for the FleetCenter,
reports that more than 10,000 tickets, about 60 percent of the
house, have been sold for the four-day event. Tickets, sold in
strips of four, remain available in all price categories, ranging
from $65 to $200 per strip. To purchase tickets call 617-931-2000,
or log on to www.fleetcenter.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
