<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-BOOKS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOOKSTORE BULLY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Barnes &AMP; Noble, which calls itself the nation's largest
bookseller, appears to be acting more like the book world's biggest
bully. In April, a New York City law firm claiming to represent
Barnes &AMP; Noble _ Robinson, Silverman, Pearce, Aronsohn &AMP; Berman _
sent a letter to the New England Booksellers Association,
concocting a dispute over the names of two promotional programs.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1990, Barnes &AMP; Noble has run the ``Discover Great New
Writers'' program. The chain holds a trademark on the name. The
program promotes groups of books by new and emerging writers on
specially marked shelves and each year gives a $10,000 award to a
first-time American novelist.
</P>
<P>
   In 1994, the New England Booksellers Association set up a much
smaller program called ``Discovery of the Month,'' selecting one
fiction or nonfiction book to promote every other month.
</P>
<P>
   The B&AMP;N letter insists the names are too similar. To avoid
``unnecessary and costly litigation,'' it asks the association to
``cease and desist'' from using the phrase ``Discovery of the
Month'' and to destroy labels, product packaging, catalogs, Web
pages, Web sites, advertising, and promotional materials ``used on
or in connection with the name Discovery of the Month.'' Lawyer
Todd Braverman, who signed the letter, declined to comment, and
Barnes &AMP; Noble officials didn't return calls.
</P>
<P>
   The request is over-the-top. It's hard to confuse B&AMP;N's highly
visible shelves of ``Discover'' books with the association's
bimonthly effort. Barnes &AMP; Noble's timing is also odd. The two
programs have co-existed for six years. Several B&AMP;N stores have
been members of the booksellers association and have been sent the
smaller program's materials.
</P>
<P>
   Plus, stores in a given industry typically use common sales
language. Protecting trademarks is essential, but not to the point
of leaving other retailers mute. What's next, a patent on
``bestseller list''?
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes heartfelt word-of-mouth can bring a great but
little-known book to the public's attention. This is a gift to
readers and a money-maker for the book industry. But it can only
happen if all bookstores are allowed to speak freely in plain
English.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
