<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-31 19:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8659 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BKN-KENYON-MARTIN-ART     07-31 1519
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-KENYON-MARTIN-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KENYON MARTIN SPEAKING ELOQUENTLY AND SCORING BIG 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo NYT14 has been sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By LIZ ROBBINS    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The bullies on the bus in Dallas did not know who they were
picking on, they only laughed at the small boy's stutter, his pale
skin and his clothes, playing the cruel game of childhood.
</P>
<P>
   His older sister, Tamara, would rush to fight his tormenters, or
restrain him from doing so. Kenyon Martin's anger, meanwhile, rose
up within him like a sermon. Do not doubt me.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, he has learned to control his stutter along with his
temper. He made himself into the best college basketball player in
the country, defying predictions. Today he speaks most eloquently
through his actions, powerful, yet gentle.
</P>
<P>
   Where are those bullies now? ``My mom said she saw a few of them
the other day, just doing nothing,'' Martin said with a distant
smile and a shrug.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps they saw him on television on June 28, the night of the
National Basketball Association draft, when the 6-foot-9-inch,
235-pound forward out of the University of Cincinnati dissolved in
sobs of relief and vindication after the Nets made him the first
overall pick.
</P>
<P>
   He never thought of leaving college early for the draft,
returning to Cincinnati for his senior year specifically to win a
national championship. That dream was shattered along with his
right fibula on March 9, when he landed awkwardly after colliding
with a player on a routine pick in the Conference USA tournament.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, people questioned Martin's leg and ability to heal,
prodded and X-rayed him until his insides glowed, but the Nets
hushed all doubters within minutes at the draft. Now Martin feels
he must validate their choice when the season begins.
</P>
<P>
   ``They had confidence in me,'' he said. ``I never had a doubt
that I would come back and play. A lot of people wondered, but I
never had a doubt. I'm going to go out there and work as hard as I
can. I don't back down from anybody. No matter who it is.''
</P>
<P>
   On the basketball court, Martin cuts a menacing figure with his
four tattoos, fierce glares, slam dunks, rejected shots and swift
sprints. ``People look at him as a mean, tough guy,'' said his best
friend, Don Willis, who met him playing Bitty Basketball when they
were 7. ``But he's a real tender, sweet person.''
</P>
<P>
   Martin is also an animal lover, and after his fiancee's boxer
flunked out of obedience school, only he could tame and mesmerize
the hyperactive dog. He will sit for hours watching ``Big Cat
Diaries'' on the Animal Planet cable channel.
</P>
<P>
   An astute listener with a generous spirit, Martin, 22, is the
product of growing up around strong, caring women. ``He is a better
person than a basketball player,'' Cincinnati Coach Bob Huggins
said of his consensus national player of the year. ``Kenyon's
special.''
</P>
<P>
   Though he is private, his body can be used as a map to his soul,
the pictures and letters in different languages all clues to his
contrasting personality. On his left arm are thick, black Japanese
characters shouting his credo: Never Satisfied. On his right
shoulder is his mother's name in thin letters: Lydia.
</P>
<P>
   Lydia Moore, Tamara Ridley and Martin formed an unbreakable
family triangle early on. Ridley, 26, three and a half years older
than Martin, mothered him almost immediately, from changing his
diaper to fighting his bullies, driving him to basketball games and
cooking for him while their mother often worked two jobs. They were
inseparable as latchkey children in Dallas and still speak daily.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have a bond that's unbreakable,'' Moore said. ``She's
married with two children, but she and her brother, they are joined
at the hip.''
</P>
<P>
   Martin's father, Paul Roby, played basketball at the University
of New Mexico, but Martin remembers meeting him only once, when he
was in grade school, long after his mother moved the family from
Michigan to Texas. When Martin was filling out information forms in
college, he told his sister, ``I put you as my dad on my
paperwork.''
</P>
<P>
   Ridley understood. ``I was more like his dad,'' she said. ``I
was always fussing after him. I wanted him to succeed.'' Go to
Class, Directly  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   If Martin skipped an early morning class at Cincinnati, Huggins
used to threaten to call Ridley. Martin went to class.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tamara taught me how to be a strong person, how to overcome
things,'' Martin said. ``Both she and my mom did. Just growing up,
not letting the bad stuff get between us, making nothing out of
something. My mother worked so she could find a way.''
</P>
<P>
   So did Ridley. She, too, was a single mother, working and going
to school to earn her accounting degree. Ridley is now married with
a daughter, Tatum, 8, and a son, Darius, 4. Her children are almost
exactly the same age difference as she and Martin; they, too, never
fight.
</P>
<P>
   Darius idolizes his uncle, begging for Martin's same tattoos,
wearing his jersey, dressing in basketball gear whenever Martin
returns to Dallas. The adoration is mutual.
</P>
<P>
   The day after the draft, Martin arranged to have a three-bedroom
house built for his mother and to move his sister and her family
into a house on the same block. Ridley currently lives and works
out of her mother's home as a wedding consultant.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now,'' said Martin, who will most likely make the rookie
maximum of $11.4 million over three years, ``it's their time to
relax.''
</P>
<P>
   Even before he was the provider for the family, Martin offered
his sister and mother a sense of calm. ``My sister worries enough
for both of us,'' he said. ``I tell her, `Why worry about things
you can't control?' I never do.''
</P>
<P>
   It is a perspective that took time to develop, an inner battle
he finally mastered on the court. ``I've come 360 degrees with my
temper and my attitude,'' Martin said. ``When I was young, I would
just snap. But I had a coach who told me my attitude wouldn't get
me anywhere.''
</P>
<P>
   That was when Martin was 12 and the shortest player on the team.
As he grew, he excelled defensively but was still reluctant to
emerge on offense. He went to three high schools in Dallas,
including a private school and two public schools. After leaving
the private school, the bus ride to the first public school was so
far from home that he moved in with his sister and niece to go to
Bryan Adams High School.
</P>
<P>
   Martin was not a top high school prospect when he signed with
Cincinnati. ``He was very talented when he came in,'' Huggins said,
``he just didn't have any skills.''
</P>
<P>
   Martin had not qualified academically to play the first semester
at Cincinnati, but kept taking the SAT until he became eligible to
join the team in January. By the 14th game of his freshman year, he
was starting. Still, he played with upper-class stars, like Danny
Fortson and Damon Flint, and averaged only 2.8 points a game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was not productive at all,'' he said. Nor was he
particularly aggressive. ``I didn't want to get fouled because I
struggled at the free-throw line.'' As a freshman, he went to the
foul line only 32 times in 22 games, and made 10.
</P>
<P>
   ``His mechanics were really bad,'' Huggins said. ``As his
mechanics got better and better, he gained more confidence.''
Martin's sophomore year, he shot 47.6 percent from the line, 50 of
105. His junior year, he made 50 of 89, for 56.2 percent. Last
season, he went to the line 206 times and made 141 for 68.4
percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's really got a great aptitude for basketball, and he's a
great listener,'' Huggins said. ``His last two years he coached the
other guys. So much of why Kenyon is so good is that he gets great
pleasure in helping other people.''
</P>
<P>
   Against DePaul his sophomore year, Martin pulled off a
triple-double, with 24 points, 23 rebounds and 10 blocks.
Afterward, he approached Huggins. ``Did I shoot too much?'' Martin
said.
</P>
<P>
   Huggins was amazed. ``The guy really wants to win and he's never
been caught up in statistics,'' he said. ``When he started getting
all the accolades, you wondered if his work ethic would change.''
</P>
<P>
   It only intensified. The summer before his senior year, Martin
decided he would change his game, that this Cincinnati team would
bear his offensive imprint. ``If I could do it in practice,''
Martin said, ``I don't know why I couldn't do it in the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Martin got in the gym and shot ``until his arm fell off,'' the
assistant coach Rod Baker said. He practiced his free throws, his
post-up moves, working out with Corey Blount, the former Cincinnati
player and six-year N.B.A. forward.
</P>
<P>
   Martin's single-minded determination to achieve a national
championship was why Huggins, too, was devastated when his star
went down 3 minutes 4 seconds into Cincinnati's opening-round game
against St. Louis in Memphis in the conference tournament.
</P>
<P>
   ``Get my sister,'' Martin said, on his way into the ambulance.
Tamara was right behind him. Moore, who would cry any time her son
got poked in the eye, was there, too.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   The fracture, like a fault line, led to other disappointing
events. The Bearcats did not get a No. 1 seeding in the NCAA
tournament, and they lost in the second round. Martin's wedding was
to be in Cincinnati in April. Instead, his fiancee of two years,
Fatimah Conley, withdrew from her classes at Xavier to tend to him.
</P>
<P>
   They met during his freshman year at a night club, each
convinced by their separate friends to attend. ``He's a man of few
words and he just sort of introduced himself,'' Conley recalled.
``He didn't have a shady line, he was real calm, though not quite
as confident as he is now. He was a gentle giant.''
</P>
<P>
   Because of their classes and his basketball schedule, they
rarely spent many days in a row together, but then the injury
brought them closer. ``I've known him for three years and he never
complains,'' Conley said. ``If he didn't have any money, he didn't
complain. He never once complained about his leg. Me, coming from
suburbia, we complain a lot. I'm a worry-holic, always wondering
how it's going to be tomorrow, a year from now. He tells me,
`Things are going to be how they're going to be.''' Wedding Plans  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The two plan to get married before the season.
</P>
<P>
   Once she and Martin find a house in New Jersey, Conley plans to
finish work toward her undergraduate chemistry degree, perhaps at
Columbia or New York University.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know the season is going to be very hectic and he'll be away
a lot,'' she said. ``So it's important for me to have my own
life.''
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, they have been living in Santa Monica, Calif.,
since late April. Martin's agent, Dan Fegan, arranged for him to
rehabilitate at the Kerlan-Jobe Institute and Martin has been
working out every morning for three hours, shooting, improving his
strength and quickness, and following Nets team doctors' advice not
to scrimmage until next month.
</P>
<P>
   ``My confidence is at an all-time high, even though I'm not
playing,'' Martin said. ``When I get in games, I know I can play
with anybody.''
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Martin attended Shaw's Summer League in Boston with
the Nets, learning some plays and sitting on the bench watching
free agents and rookies who will most likely never be his
teammates. It was torture.
</P>
<P>
   The leg, he said, will be healed by Oct. 2, when the Nets begin
training camp. He does not see pressure in being anointed a savior
for a Nets team historically tagged by injuries and underachieving.
Rather he is looking forward to running the floor in the up-tempo
offense of the Nets' new coach, Byron Scott.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love playing, I don't look at anything as pressure,'' Martin
said. ``When I'm on the court, I'm so relaxed, I'm more nervous
when I talk to somebody than when I am on the court, in front of
thousands of people.''
</P>
<P>
   But at least with one group, his words flow easily.
</P>
<P>
   After he left Boston, last week, Martin stopped in Cincinnati
because he had promised an elementary school class he would return.
To read to them.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
