<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-31 19:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8662 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-MA-DEAD-BIRDS-BOS &LR;      07-31 0744
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MA-DEAD-BIRDS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANXIOUS PUBLIC DELIVERS BIRDS BY THE BAGFUL TO VIRUS HUNTERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BETH DALEY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ One dead sparrow arrived at the state lab in a Nike
shoebox. Another was unceremoniously dumped in a Shaw's shopping
bag. A crow corpse was even delivered ice cold _ packed in a bag
with fruity popsicles.
</P>
<P>
   Since the West Nile virus was discovered in two crows in the
Boston area last week, state public health authorities have been
overwhelmed with reports _ and bodies _ of suspicious dead birds,
turned in by the concerned public. Just since Friday, they have
logged 200 calls. And Monday, with more calls coming in, state
epidemiologists had to hire a courier service to zigzag across the
state, helping collect everything from dead seagulls to cat-mauled
finches.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the Department of Public Health is asking the public to
only report dead crows. Crows, they said, are particularly
susceptible to the disease, and provide hints of how far the virus
_ which killed seven people in the New York area last summer _ has
spread.
</P>
<P>
   The deluge of bird reports, said public health workers, is a
sign of the tough position they now find themselves in: While they
want the public's help in stopping the disease, they don't want
people to panic when the chances their chances of contracting the
virus are vanishingly small.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are taking a lot of measures to protect a very small number
of people from a bad disease,'' said Dr. Alfred DeMaria, Jr.,
director of the state Bureau of Communicable Disease Control.
``Most people who get it won't even know they have it.''
</P>
<P>
   Quelling the panic is all the more difficult because the West
Nile story has all the elements of a Michael Crichton summer
thriller: A mysterious virus working its way up the Northeast
coast, transmitted to people by the mosquito, one of our most
common nuisances.
</P>
<P>
   ``The mosquito is ubiquitous and that is what is so
frightening,'' said Dr. Robert Youngberg, a psychologist at McLean
Hospital in Belmont. ``There is some element of reality to it all.
And there is a type of progression of how it is getting here.''
</P>
<P>
   And, of course, there are the birds. Crows -- mythological
harbingers of death -- are providing the most visible sign the
disease is among us.
</P>
<P>
   Although the state has been agressively testing birds and
mosquitoes, no other sign of the disease has surfaced, state
officials said Monday. No one has gotten sick. After two infected
crows were found, one in Boston's Jamaica Plain section and one in
suburban Hopkinton, health workers expanded their mosquito
eradication efforts.
</P>
<P>
   The West Nile virus -- which has infected people in Africa, Asia
and Europe -- mysteriously appeared for the first time in the
Western Hemisphere in New York City last year. The city then
embarked on a highly controversial aerial spraying program that had
tens of thousands running for cover. And while initial estimates
predicted that thousands could have been infected, seven elderly
people died.
</P>
<P>
   ``The estimates are that somewhere around 1 in 200 or 300 of
people infected with the virus actually become sick and most of it
is a flu-like virus,'' said Dr. Martin Hirsch, professor of
medicine at Harvard and part of the infectious disease unit at
Massachusetts General Hospital.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just the fact that we have the virus in our area shouldn't
illicit a great deal of fear, but that's not to say we shouldn't be
cautious,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But for many, any outbreak they cannot personally control, is a
reason to panic. In New York, concerts and picnics were canceled
because of West Nile fears.
</P>
<P>
   ``People's anxiety tends to increase when there is less
control,'' said Dr. Donna Pincus, assistant professor at Boston
University and director of the Child and Adolescent Fear and
Anxiety Treatment program. ``You see all this stuff in the media
and it causes intensified fears.''
</P>
<P>
   Pincus predicts that tobacco kills more people every day than
the West Nile virus ever will, but people feel more comfortable
with tobacco because they are controlling its use. They can't
control the West Nile virus.
</P>
<P>
   The search for dead crows, Pincus and others said, is just a way
for people to assure themselves they have a reason to be fearful.
``People seek out information that confirms their thoughts. And
it's natural to want to protect ourselves from danger,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
