<SLUG> BC-GOP-ASSESS-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AT CONVENTION HALL: FAREWELL, SPONTANEITY; HELLO, CHOREOGRAPHY 
</HEADLINE>
   By R.W. APPLE Jr.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ Ronald Reagan used to preach what he called the
11th Commandment: Speak no evil of other Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   But now his party, and the other one, too, have gone him one
better, appropriating the physician's Hippocratic Oath as the
unspoken guiding principle for their quadrennial gatherings: First,
do no harm.
</P>
<P>
   It is that thought, more than anything, that has drained all of
the drama and much of the meaning from modern political
conventions. No surprises are wanted these days. No sore losers. No
floor fights. So long, eccentricity. Farewell, spontaneity; hello,
choreography. No more smoke-filled rooms _ unless you count the
convention hall, which is to be filled with artificial, politically
correct smoke as part of the entertainment here.
</P>
<P>
   The Republicans, who began their 37th national nominating
convention this morning, and the Democrats, who meet in Los Angeles
in two weeks, have been reading the polls and reflecting on the
recent past. Partisans all, they are confronted with the
uncomfortable finding that Americans, a few of whom may actually be
watching on television, hate partisanship and discord.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps it is the times. Perhaps it is because most people are
happy with their lot, with the economy and with the course of the
ship of state. If that is the reason for voters' aversion to
conflict, feel-good conventions could be a passing phase. Hard
times pose hard questions, and those questions get thrashed out not
only in campaigns but also in the conventions preceding them.
</P>
<P>
   This year, though, it's pablum for breakfast, lunch and dinner.
</P>
<P>
   The original raison d'etre of conventions _ nominating
candidates _ vanished a quarter-century ago. Not since the
Republican gathering in Kansas City in 1976, when Gerald Ford
barely held off Ronald Reagan, has there been a genuine contest for
the presidential nomination at a major-party convention. It was
well past midnight when West Virginia finally gave Ford the votes
he needed to go over the top.
</P>
<P>
   And not since 1940 has a rank outsider captured the nomination.
At the Republican convention that year, Wendell L. Willkie finished
third on the first ballot; it took his handlers many hours to put
together the deals that gave him the nomination on the sixth.
</P>
<P>
   There will probably never again be a spectacle even remotely
resembling the epic struggle between rural and urban interests at
the 1924 Democratic convention in the first Madison Square Garden.
John W. Davis of West Virginia was chosen by the exhausted
delegates on the 103rd ballot, but the party had next to nothing
left for the fall campaign, and Davis was trounced.
</P>
<P>
   The new reality is the consequence of the 1968 Democratic
convention in Chicago, which was so rowdy, with spiteful verbal
combat inside the hall and a police riot outside, that the parties
tore up their old rule books.
</P>
<P>
   Today almost all the delegates are chosen by the voters in
primaries and caucuses, not, as of old, by the political bosses.
The delegates know months before they come to town whom they will
vote for. They are bit players now, with badges around their necks
and beers in their fists but no power.
</P>
<P>
   George W. Bush, the man they have come to nominate, told the
National Journal the other day that conventions have become an
anachronism. But that, he insisted, does not _ should not _ mean
they are on the way out.
</P>
<P>
   ``The convention provides a system of rewards for hard-working,
grass-roots people who end up being delegates,'' Bush said. ``I
view it as an opportunity for these people to go back home,
energized to help me get elected.''
</P>
<P>
   Fair enough. It also provides an excuse for a lot of parties,
mostly paid for by big corporations, and yet another setting place
to raise money.
</P>
<P>
   Bush also said that the convention had become ``a place to
showcase ideas more than in the past.'' Not exactly. To be precise,
it has become a place to talk in muted terms about ideas that the
nominee wishes to be heard. If there are abortion-rights supporters
at the podium this week, for example, they will talk about
something else, thanks to what Mr. Bush calls his ``iron-fist''
control of the proceedings. But there will be no oratorical fire on
the other side of the issue, either, and few attacks on the
Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   That was the lesson that politicians drew from the contrasting
conventions of 1992. The Republicans, nominating George Bush the
elder, permitted the clergyman who delivered the opening-night
invocation to compare abortion to the Holocaust and allowed Patrick
J. Buchanan to issue a shrill call to arms for the ``religious war
going on in our country for the soul of America.''
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Tom Ridge of Pennsylvania said this week, ``I felt
absolutely terrible that night.'' Just like a lot of other people
in the hall and out across the country.
</P>
<P>
   The Democrats, on the other hand, staged a pageant of unity
behind Bill Clinton in New York, denying Robert J. Casey, then the
governor of Pennsylvania, a chance to state his anti-abortion
position from the podium. Clinton won, of course, and a new bit of
conventional political wisdom was born: Trouble in August means
trouble in November.
</P>
<P>
   So there will be no echoes here of Barry Goldwater's
belligerence in accepting the 1964 Republican presidential
nomination in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   Quoting Cicero, the Arizonan told the delegates that ``extremism
in defense of liberty is no vice, moderation in pursuit of justice
no virtue.'' He lost, as did William Jennings Bryan of Nebraska in
1896 after perhaps the most spellbinding of all convention
speeches.
</P>
<P>
   Siding with the Western populists against Eastern bankers, Bryan
cried out, ``You shall not crucify mankind on a cross of gold!''
</P>
<P>
   Nor will there be a surprise vice presidential nominee. In 1956,
Adlai E. Stevenson left the choice to the delegates at the
Democratic convention, and a youngster named John F. Kennedy,
though narrowly defeated by Estes Kefauver, set himself up for
1960. Kennedy, in turn, stunned the country by choosing Lyndon B.
Johnson as a running mate. And George Bush chose Dan Quayle.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Now a new tradition is emerging: choose the running mate before
the convention, so as to eliminate that, too, as a potential
disruption.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes the drama of past conventions has lain in credentials
disputes. At Chicago in 1952, Dwight D. Eisenhower's managers
mounted a campaign of dubious legitimacy under the slogan ``Fair
Play'' and succeeded in stripping Robert A. Taft of enough
delegates to assure the general's nomination.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes the drama has lain in the rules. At Miami Beach in
1972, the brain trust of Sen. George McGovern of South Dakota,
headed by Anne Wexler, now one of Washington's most successful
lobbyists, deftly manipulated the rules to guarantee his victory.
</P>
<P>
   And sometimes _ often, in fact _ the drama has lain in the
platform debate, where conflicting ideas on major issues were
thrashed out.
</P>
<P>
   Here in Philadelphia 52 years ago this summer, Hubert H.
Humphrey, the ``Boy Mayor of Minneapolis,'' led a passionate
campaign for civil rights. He told the delegates, assembled to
nominate Harry S. Truman: ``There are those who say we are rushing
this issue of civil rights. I say we are 172 years too late.'' The
Dixiecrats walked out, nominated Strom Thurmond for President and
carried five states. But Truman won _ a reminder that it has by no
means always been politically suicidal to stage a contentious and
divisive convention.
</P>
<P>
   This year, neither convention is likely to tackle such important
issues as drugs, campaign finance and the gulf between the rich and
the poor. The Republicans, deeply divided on the issue of abortion,
will display no prime-time dissent; the minority, abortion-rights
forces, who had enough votes in the platform committee to take a
minority plank to the floor, decided to pass up that chance in the
name of unity.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's all propaganda,'' said Haley Barbour, the chairman of the
Republican National Committee during the 1996 conventions. ``It's
all a TV show. It's not news, but it's hugely important information
for the American people.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet the question remains whether these carefully packaged
four-day Republican and Democratic infomercials will influence the
unaligned, uncommitted voters whom both parties say they want to
reach. With dissent muffled, with debate defunct, will they be
stirred? The low turnouts in recent presidential elections suggest
that all the staging in the world won't do the trick.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
