<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOP-CLINTON-IMPEACH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REPUBLICAN'S AT GOP CONVENTION LEAVING CLINTON'S IMPEACHMENT IN THE
PAST 
</HEADLINE>
   By JAMES BENNET   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ Bill Clinton was impeached, right? No one here at
the Republican National Convention seems to recall.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's forgotten,'' said Robert Livingston, the former
congressman from Louisiana, who abandoned his dream of being
speaker and resigned his seat in the tumult surrounding the
impeachment of Bill Clinton. ``Whether the president was impeached
or wasn't impeached really is a non-issue.''
</P>
<P>
   It sure seemed like a big deal at the time, what with all that
talk about history and the Constitution and the rule of law. But a
convention is no time to boast about a landmark legislative feat.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that what the key to this convention is and what the
key to this election is, is that voters want to focus on issues,''
said Rep. Bill McCollum of Florida. That sounded remarkably similar
to what the president used to say back when he was being impeached
so many years ago. Well, two years ago, anyway. OK, a little less
than that, even.
</P>
<P>
   Back in those days, McCollum used to say things like, ``His
conduct constitutes a great insult to our constitutional system and
subverts our system of government.''
</P>
<P>
   Nowadays, McCollum, who was one of the House members who
prosecuted Clinton in the well of the senate, is running to return
to that chamber as a senator himself. But no one brings up
impeachment on the campaign trail, he said. ``I don't see it coming
up unless a media person asks me,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Clinton, the man who suffered the incredible lightness of
being impeached, was off in Florida Monday raising hundreds of
thousands of dollars for McCollum's Democratic opponent, Bill
Nelson. But McCollum demurred when offered the chance to say that
the president was out for revenge.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if he has or not,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Impeachment is forgotten but not gone.
</P>
<P>
   When George W. Bush refers to restoring ``honor and dignity'' to
the White House, everyone knows that he is talking about the
internship program. Republican congressmen have used the issue in
fund-raising appeals to gingerly targeted conservative donors. And
when pressed about it, Republicans involved declare their pride in
having done what they believed was right, at great political cost.
</P>
<P>
   So there is something poignant in all this silence: Impeachment
has become the Republican pride that dare not speak its name _ like
the Contract with America at the last Republican convention, when
Speaker Newt Gingrich (remember him?) chose in his speech to
emphasize beach volleyball instead.
</P>
<P>
   The closest the platform comes to using the I-word is this:
``And, at a time when the nation felt betrayed by misconduct in
high office, the Republican Congress responded with gravity and
high purpose. We applaud those members who did their duty to
conscience and the Constitution.''
</P>
<P>
   For his part, the genial Livingston said he has moved on. He is
attending the convention as a delegate from Louisiana, and he
helped draw up the platform. He is working as a lobbyist in
Washington and spending time with his family. He cannot vote, he
said, but otherwise representing his clients is ``not so far apart
from what I did as a congressman, in representing constituents.''
</P>
<P>
   He said he had no regrets about losing his job in a fight he
believes the public no longer cares about.
</P>
<P>
   ``The system worked,'' he said. ``I think he had to be
impeached. I think the Senate wasn't ever going to convict him. And
that's life. We all played our roles, and I played mine and moved
on.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-31-00 1910EDT &QL; 
