u a BC-MA-BLOOD-SUPPLY-BOS &LR;      07-31 0665
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MA-BLOOD-SUPPLY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BLOOD SUPPLIES RUNNING LOW IN BAY STATE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RAJA MISHRA  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Massachusetts blood supplies are running dangerously
low and hospitals may soon be forced to postpone some elective
surgeries, health care groups warned Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The cause, they said, is a jump in the number of blood-consuming
surgeries done at area hospitals and a bulge in the eldery
population that is producing an ever-increasing stream of patients.
Donations have not dropped off but are being outpaced by the
increasing demand for blood, the groups said.
</P>
<P>
   The Red Cross and organizations representing doctors and
hospitals issued a call for even more blood donations _ a rare
instance of unity among groups that typically compete for blood
supplies.
</P>
<P>
   ``As of (Monday) morning we are at critical levels in
O-positive, O-negative, A-negative and B-negative,'' said Melissa
Croteau, a spokesperson for the state chapter of the International
Committee of the Red Cross, refering to the different types of
blood.
</P>
<P>
   The Red Cross supplies 65 percent of the state's transfused
blood. They reported Monday that only a one-day supply is on hand,
meaning that if new donations to the blood supply were to abruptly
dry up, transfusions could continue for a single day. The Red
Cross' comfort level is a three- to four-day supply.
</P>
<P>
   Blood transfusions are necessary componants of most surgeries
since when people are cut open, they bleed. Among the procedures
that use the most blood are coronary bypass surgery and various
orthopedic surgeries.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Allan Kliman, a hemotologist at the Spaulding Rehabilitation
Hospital, said emergency surgeries are not threatened by the
shortage, but elective ones may soon be effected.
</P>
<P>
   ``Procedures may have to be delayed. Doctors might have to let
people go without transfusions for a longer period of time,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   The Massachusetts shortage is not an isolated malady. The Red
Cross reported that 32 states have similar problems. This summer,
blood supply drops in the Baltimore and Philadelphia areas prompted
elective surgery postponements at hospitals there. In the New York
City area, some hospitals are allowing patients to drop to
lower-than-normal blood levels before giving them transfusions,
according to the Red Cross.
</P>
<P>
   Shortages in other states impact Massachusetts because the
much-respected hospitals here draw thousands of out-of-state
patients. Unfortunately, out-of-state blood supplies do not follow,
said local health care officials.
</P>
<P>
   The current blood drought is not the product of some new
hematological thriftiness in the public. Donation levels are pretty
consistent with past years, though summer is traditionally slow.
Rather, hospitals are using 5 percent more blood on average this
year, according to a Red Cross study. In July, one Boston-area
hospital called the Red Cross urgently seeking blood for two
pending organ transfusions. The organization had to go to another
state to find the necessary blood.
</P>
<P>
   ``This summer's shortage is almost unprecedented,'' said Croteau
of the Red Cross.
</P>
<P>
   Some area doctors have made the unusual request that excess
blood from hemochromatosis patients _ those who produce too much
blood _ be used for transfusions, said health care groups. Other
doctors have suggested revisiting the discarded practice of asking
the families of patients to provide blood for their loved-ones'
surgeries. These options, however, are not being actively
considered by any area hospitals, said health care groups.
</P>
<P>
   The only permanent solution, the groups said, is to somehow
stimulate public blood donations. To that end, the Massachusetts
Medical Society this week sent thousands of doctors letters urging
them to ask their patients to donate blood.
</P>
<P>
   Those interested in donating blood can call the Red Cross at
1-800-448-3543 or the Massachusetts Medical Society at
781-434-7311.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-31-00 1911EDT &QL; 
