<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEASE-COLUMN-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HEY, KIDS! LEARN HOW TO EXPLOIT PEOPLE FOR FUN AND PROFIT!
</HEADLINE>
  By DARYL LEASE   
 Herald-Tribune, Sarasota, Fla.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   (ITAL) And now we rejoin ``The
Jerry Springer Show,'' already in progress...(UNITAL)
<TEXT>
<P>
   SPRINGER: (pacing pensively) So, let me make sure I have this
straight: Your hobby, your job really, is ambushing people who are
at the lowest emotional points in their lives _ some of them with
serious psychological problems _ and humiliating them in front of
large crowds. Is that what you do?
</P>
<P>
   GUEST: Yeah, that's it, more or less. I don't always ambush
them, though. Sometimes I just get a bunch of people together to
talk about the mess they're in.
</P>
<P>
   SPRINGER: (jaw dropping pensively) And _ help me out here _ you
ask other people over to your place to watch this?
</P>
<P>
   AUDIENCE: (laughter) Jer-ree! Jer-ree!
</P>
<P>
   GUEST: That's right. Lots of people. Some I charge. Others watch
for free, from a distance, but they have to listen to ads from
sponsors.
</P>
<P>
   SPRINGER: (expressing surprise, pensively) Sponsors? You mean,
businesses? Major corporations selling detergent, peanut butter,
stuff like that?
</P>
<P>
   GUEST: Sure. This is America, pal. You can slap an ad on
anything. Even somebody's personal problems.
</P>
<P>
   SPRINGER: (holding microphone with both hands, pensively) What
sort of messes are these people in?
</P>
<P>
   GUEST: Freak show stuff, mostly. You know, some guy sleeping
with his wife's sister and his wife's best friend, whose husbands _
lo and behold _ are sleeping with each other in the same cheap
sleazy motel where the wife is sleeping with the husband's brother
and husband's best friend, on alternating Thursdays. Stuff like
that.
</P>
<P>
   AUDIENCE: (laughter, boos, applause) Jer-ree! Jer-ree!
</P>
<P>
   SPRINGER: (shaking head pensively) And what do these poor people
get out of talking to you?
</P>
<P>
   GUEST: I dunno. Their jollies, I guess. I pay them a little. Put
'em up in a hotel if they're from out of town. I guess they're
starved for attention.
</P>
<P>
   SPRINGER: (voice rising pensively) Do you assist them with these
problems? Do you bring in any professionals like, say, a shrink or
a clergyman to help them work through their troubles?
</P>
<P>
   GUEST: Uh, no. That wouldn't be very entertaining. I'm not into
charity work, bub.
</P>
<P>
   SPRINGER: (lowering voice pensively) You said you pay these
people a little money. Your sponsors, do they pay you well?
</P>
<P>
   GUEST: Yeah, quite a lot of money, in fact. I'm a wealthy man.
If I ever ambushed ``People Who Got Stinking Rich Doing Little or
Nothing,'' I'd be interviewing myself.
</P>
<P>
   SPRINGER: (expressing disgust, pensively) And you're proud of
this?
</P>
<P>
   AUDIENCE: (laughter) Jer-ree! Jer-ree! Jer-ree!
</P>
<P>
   GUEST: Hey, this doesn't define me. It's just something I do. I
bring people together. If I didn't do it, somebody else would.
</P>
<P>
   SPRINGER: (pensively silent) Do people ever get hurt as part of
your fun and games? I mean, really, really hurt, beyond the pain
they brought with them when they met you?
</P>
<P>
   GUEST: Uh, well, sort of. Had one lady get killed recently. But
what do I know about it? I don't meet these people before I ambush
them. It's better that way. It's more extemporaneous.
</P>
<P>
   SPRINGER: (growling pensively) It's not my business, you
understand, but do you feel at all responsible for this violence?
Do you ever consider that you're preying on these pathetic
creatures? That you're exploiting them for profit?
</P>
<P>
   AUDIENCE: (laughter) Jer-ree! Jer-ree!
</P>
<P>
   GUEST: Well, uh, no, not really. They probably would have ended
up where they did without me. They've got problems, like I said.
</P>
<P>
   SPRINGER: (charging stage, pensively) Wait a second! Let's start
to peel away these levels of reality. They're messed up, but don't
your little sideshows just make them worse? Aren't you trafficking
in human misery?
</P>
<P>
   GUEST: Uh, I'm sorry. Are you trying to make some sort of point?
</P>
<P>
   SPRINGER: (shaking head, pensively) What a waste. What a waste
of energy.
</P>
<P>
   AUDIENCE: (laughter, applause) Jer-ree! Jer-ree! Jer-ree!
</P>
<P>
   (ITAL) We interrupt this broadcast to bring you a special
bulletin ... (UNITAL)
</P>
<P>
   (Daryl Lease is a columnist for the Herald-Tribune in Sarasota,
Fla. Contact him at daryl.lease(AT)herald-trib.com.The
Herald-Tribune is a member of the New York Times Regional
Newspapers.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
