<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-31 19:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8679 &Cx1f; tad-z
r f BC-DELTA-VOTE0801-COX     07-31 0434
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DELTA-VOTE0801-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    New vote on union ordered at Delta
 &HT;    By Scott Thurston
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA - The Transport Workers Union is getting a second chance
in its bid to represent ramp workers at Delta Air Lines.
</P>
<P>
   The National Mediation Board has ordered a rerun of an election
last winter in which 17 percent of the Delta's 10,777 eligible ramp
workers voted for the TWU, far short of the majority required.
</P>
<P>
   The federal agency, ruling on a TWU appeal claiming misconduct
by Delta, cited three reasons for ordering a new election:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  The board said it inadvertently disclosed to Delta the number
of election authorization cards that had been submitted in support
of an election, information that is supposed to remain
confidential.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Because of a mailing glitch the board mistakenly sent United
Airlines ballots to 241 Delta workers, which it said ``undermined
the integrity'' of the process.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  The board found ``substantial evidence'' that Delta
supervisors wrongly used ``daily mandatory briefings to discuss
Delta's point of view on the election.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Based upon the totality of the circumstances,'' the board
concluded, ``conditions required for a fair election were
tainted.''
</P>
<P>
   The board rejected, however, a TWU accusation that Delta
unfairly influenced ramp workers by announcing a pay increase and
discount computer purchase plan in the weeks before the election
began, noting that those moves were long-planned and applied to
most employees.
</P>
<P>
   The mediation board will conduct a new mail-in election,
although dates aren't set.
</P>
<P>
   The TWU has scaled back its Atlanta office since last winter's
defeat. John Kerrigan, secretary-treasurer at the union's national
headquarters, said Monday the board's ruling was ``greatly
gratifying and confirms our contention that the actions of Delta
management directly interfered'' with a fair election.
</P>
<P>
   Delta said it is ``profoundly disappointed.'' The company denies
any wrongdoing in conducting meetings or disseminating anti-union
materials.
</P>
<P>
   ``Delta people spoke loud and clear in the first election when
more than 83 percent of eligible voters chose to remain union-free.
We trust our people will again make their opinion known in the
rerun election,'' a company statement said.
</P>
<P>
   Delta, the least-unionized major airline, has seen a jump in
organizing activity in recent years. So far, the only union victory
came last year when 107 pilot instructors narrowly voted to join
the TWU.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
