<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-31 19:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8685 &Cx1f; tab-z
u a BC-WAR-GENERATION-POPMEC     07-31 1236
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WAR-GENERATION-POPMECH-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
'THE WAR GENERATION' HAS SPECIAL PLACE IN HENRY FORD MUSEUM 
</HEADLINE>
   (ATTENTION EDITORS: This article is for use by clients of The New
York Times Syndicate's POPULAR MECHANICS NEWS SERVICE. For more
information about purchasing this article as a ``separate-buy'' _
or becoming a client of POPULAR MECHANICS NEWS SERVICE _ contact
one of the New York Times Syndicate sales representatives listed at
the end of the text.) 
 (ART ADV: Photos of exhibits at the Henry Ford Museum in Dearborn,
Mich., are available on Newscom or by calling William Gonzalez at
212-499-3355.) 
 By MARY SEELHORST 
 c.2000 Hearst Communications Inc.   
<TEXT>
<P>
   D-Day, Pearl Harbor, FDR, penicillin and Orson Welles' ``War Of
The Worlds'' radio broadcast. All of these were part of growing up
for the War generation, often referred to as the ``Greatest
Generation.''
</P>
<P>
   They were raised during the desperation of the Depression and
grew up in the shadow of World War I, one of the most horrific wars
the world had ever seen. They went on to win World War II, and many
would fight again, and die, in the Korean War. To support the war
effort, they became the first recycling generation, turning tires
into gas masks, radiators into rifles and shovels into hand
grenades.
</P>
<P>
   In the early 1940s, with imminent threat of invasion by Hitler's
forces, this was a generation on edge, and not yet aware of the
power and deceptive verisimilitude of the media. So imagine the
terror one Sunday night when they switched on the radio and heard
these words:
</P>
<P>
   ``Ladies and gentlemen, this is the most terrifying thing I have
ever witnessed ... There, I can see the thing's body ... The mouth
is V-shaped with saliva dripping from its rimless lips...''
</P>
<P>
   Orson Welles had struck! It was the 20th century's first virtual
alien experience: Orson Welles' 1938 Mercury Theater radio
broadcast of H.G. Wells' ``The War Of The Worlds.'' Members of the
War generation remember it well, either firsthand or from the
newspaper accounts of the panic it instigated in New Jersey and New
York City.
</P>
<P>
   That they believed Welles' news show drama was a reflection of
the national fear of invasion. It also signaled the power of radio,
a relatively new, live medium which, like its audience, was coming
into its own. And this generation had to learn fast and learn well,
often by making _ and then learning from _ mistakes. Their survival
depended on it.
</P>
<P>
   All of these issues, and more, are on display in the new exhibit
at Henry Ford Museum in Dearborn, Mich., called ``Your Place In
Time: 20th Century America.'' The exhibit covers the six
generations of Americans who came of age in the 20th century and
the people and events that shaped them. The second generation _ the
War generation _ and its accomplishments have received a lot of
long overdue attention recently. The exhibit brings that time in
history to life with photos, displays and interactive vignettes.
</P>
<P>
   A STAR IS BORN
</P>
<P>
   You may be a member of this generation if you recall that bad
times weren't so bad when you were at the movies _ one of the few
fantasy escapes available. Movies had been around for a while, but
were now improved with sound and, starting in 1935, color.
Hollywood stars were bigger than life _ even the child stars like
Shirley Temple and Judy Garland.
</P>
<P>
   Fan magazines became the cornerstone of the neighborhood
newsstand. In their pages, readers could gaze longingly at their
new pals Douglas Fairbanks Jr. and Humphrey Bogart, or covet the
long lashes of leading ladies like Carole Lombard and Joan
Crawford.
</P>
<P>
   In the exhibition, visitors can flip through Silver Screen
magazine. Some ads will look familiar _ Maybelline cosmetics,
LifeBuoy soap and Camel cigarettes, for example. Others may look
strange in light of today's trends _ for instance, one ad touts
``Dr. Walter's reducing brassiere that gives you that trim youthful
figure that the new styles demand.''
</P>
<P>
   Radio, like motion pictures, was a recently improved technology.
Youngsters of the War generation took to radio like today's kids
take to computers. Young people (they weren't called ``teens'' yet)
bought and built sets, broadcast their own messages and listened in
every night to regular shows like ``The Lone Ranger,''
``Amos'n'Andy'' and the ``Grand Ole Opry.'' Soap operas first
appeared as short radio vignettes, sponsored by, well, soap
companies, of course.
</P>
<P>
   Some members of this generation who came of age in the late '30s
and '40s fought in World War II, while the younger ones assisted
their elders in holding down the home front. At home, Uncle Sam
asked for donations of old scrap of all types to make new items for
the war effort.
</P>
<P>
   For example, the exhibit shows that silk and nylon stockings
went into gunpowder bags. One old radiator made 17 .30-caliber
rifles, one old lawnmower reel equaled six 3-inch shells, and the
rubber for 12 gas masks came out of one old tire. One shovel could
make four hand grenades. And lard, the most common shortening of
the day, was collected to make explosives.
</P>
<P>
   They saw new materials, such as plastics and plywood, aluminum
and magnesium, make possible entirely new items like squeeze
bottles, aluminum foil, lightweight auto parts and architectural
elements, and new forms of furniture. After the war, aluminum was
applied to a couple of developments that would become essential to
modern life: beer kegs and aluminum siding.
</P>
<P>
   This generation saw the introduction of streamlined industrial
design, which began as a way to increase the aerodynamic efficiency
of cars and trains, but soon beautified telephones, radios and even
toasters, which in most homes don't travel very fast at all.
</P>
<P>
   Besides the exhibit's interactive vignettes, a decade-by-decade
showcase running the length of the exhibit features photos and
artifacts that speak to each generation (especially the ``tweens''
who, like some of us, fall between generations).
</P>
<P>
   Here we are reminded that the War generation saw the
not-so-long-ago miracle of penicillin, first made available as an
antibiotic during World War II. Along with artifacts, the
exhibition also showcases famous photos of troops embarking on
their fateful D-Day mission, and the mushroom cloud from the big
bomb that helped end the war.
</P>
<P>
   It was quite a ride for these young people. They saw a lot, did
a lot, and no doubt later annoyed their boomer offspring with tales
of youthful hardships. Now mostly retired, they're finally getting
to enjoy some of the things they fought for. Youngsters, you should
listen to their stories. They were there. They saw some of the
greatest changes this world has ever known. In fact, we could all
learn a thing or two.
</P>
<P>
   -------------------------------------------------
</P>
