<SLUG> BC-CAR-CARE-Q&AMP;A-POPMECH-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AUTO CLINIC Q&AMP;A 
</HEADLINE>
   (ATTENTION EDITORS: This article is for use by clients of The New
York Times Syndicate's POPULAR MECHANICS NEWS SERVICE. For more
information about purchasing this article as a ``separate-buy'' _
or becoming a client of POPULAR MECHANICS NEWS SERVICE _ contact
one of the New York Times Syndicate sales representatives listed at
the end of the text.) 
 (ART ADV: An illustration of a car hood mechanism is available on
Newscom or by calling William Gonzalez at 212-499-3355.) 
 By MIKE ALLEN 
 c.2000 Hearst Communications Inc.   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BACK IN THE HOOD
</P>
<P>
   Q: I'm OK for now, but I'm eventually going to need to get into
the engine compartment of my Buick Skylark. The problem is that the
hood release has broken, and there doesn't seem to be any way to
open the hood. My mechanic tried for almost an hour, and he can't
get at the mechanism through the radiator or from underneath. He
suggested cutting a hole in the hood with a blowtorch, but that
seems drastic.
</P>
<P>
   _ Terry Palms, Truth or Consequences, N.M.
</P>
<P>
   A: The cutting torch idea sounds more than drastic, it sounds
downright dangerous. Here's how to proceed: Find a car with the
identical hood release system. There are a couple of GM cars built
on the same platform as yours, so it doesn't necessarily have to be
a Skylark. Open the hood and get the lay of the land, so to speak.
I've done this to open hoods and locked gas cap doors.
</P>
<P>
   Find or make a tool that you can snake into the gap between the
hood and grille. You may need to be inventive. Practice on the open
hood of your example car until you can open it easily. Now you
should be able to pop the latch mechanism on your own car just as
easily. I opened a stuck hood some years ago with a piece of
16-gauge sheetmetal cut into a large hook shape. Other lock
mechanisms may respond better to a coat hanger bent into a small
hook or piece of thick welding rod, depending on whether it's
easier to push or pull.
</P>
<P>
   Last resort is to use a large hole saw on a drill directly above
the latch. It probably will cost only a hundred bucks or so to have
it welded back and painted.
</P>
<P>
   Keep your hood latch lubricated and properly adjusted to prevent
the new cable from breaking.
</P>
<P>
   INCREASE IN OIL USAGE
</P>
<P>
   Q: I have a '94 Buick Century with a 2.2 engine. It's serviced
every 3,000 miles. About a year and a half ago it started to use
oil at the rate of about 1 quart every 3,000 miles. No mechanic is
concerned about this. But this isn't normal, and I believe
something is wrong. Could someone have done something wrong while
servicing it? I hate to think of an engine job.
</P>
<P>
   _ Marlin Feaser, Lebanon, Pa.
</P>
<P>
   A: Well, Marlin, it is normal for an internal combustion engine
to use some oil. One quart per 3,000 miles is well within the range
of normal. GM says consumption rates in the neighborhood of 1 quart
per 1,000 miles are normal. Oil needs to make its way down the
valve guides or past the rings to lubricate things. If you think an
engine uses no oil at all, you're mistaken. Oil analysis shows that
engine oil becomes diluted as it's in use _ sometimes to the tune
of 10 percent to 15 percent with water and unburned fuel residue.
This extra volume can compensate for oil usage and fool you on the
dipstick.
</P>
<P>
   Also, if you're not using the latest grade of oil, it may simply
be vaporized in your crankcase and carried out through the PCV
system. One of the things oil manufacturers try to do when they
blend oil is reduce its volatility so this doesn't happen. Engines
run a lot hotter than in the past, and the hotter the oil, the
faster it boils away. If you're going to a quick lube or mechanic
who's using a brand of oil that's more volatile than what you've
been using in the past, this could easily explain your oil
consumption.
</P>
<P>
   LIMITED
</P>
<P>
   Q: I recently had a limited-slip differential installed by the
local Ford dealer in my 1996 F-350. It doesn't seem to make much
difference. The guys at the garage put it up on the lift, and spun
one rear wheel. The other wheel spins in the same direction, so
they say it's fine. But snowy roads still leave me stuck.
</P>
<P>
   _ Andrew G. Perry, Hendersonville, N.C.
</P>
<P>
   A: And how often does it snow in Hendersonville, N.C.?
Seriously, however, most limited-slip differentials will work
better if there's a little load. When one rear wheel starts to
slip, pull the handbrake up a notch or two to give the differential
clutches something to bite against. If you have an automatic (not
likely on your F-350, I realize), just ride the brake pedal
lightly. Sounds weird, but it works.
</P>
<P>
   RUST NEVER SLEEPS
</P>
<P>
   Q: Recently, while changing the oil on my 1992 Mercury Grand
Marquis, I noticed that the front part of the oil pan (near the
drain plug) had large rust spots. I went to wire-brush the spots
off and discovered that large areas of rust had formed between the
metallic coating and the metal of the pan. The entire coating
flaked off, exposing the metal. I primed the exposed metal, but I'm
concerned that the paint I applied doesn't provide enough
protection.
</P>
<P>
   _ Paul Herman, via Internet
</P>
<P>
   A: That plating was zinc galvanizing, and I'm surprised that it
all peeled off, but not surprised that the front of the pan was a
little rusty. It's exposed to a constant stream of gravel and
pebbles, and is usually sandblasted pretty thoroughly.
</P>
<P>
   Clear away any loose rust and paint, clean with solvent, and
paint with a rust-resistant paint. In my many years of working on
cars I've never seen a car that's driven regularly rust through its
oil pan. Cars in storage or a salvage lot, yes. But not one in
service. Relax.
</P>
<P>
   -------------------------------------------------
</P>
<P>
   EDITOR: Visit The New York Times Syndicate Web site at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for more information on the
POPULAR MECHANICS news service and other features.
</P>
