A8694 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u p BC-CVN-BEDTIME-HNS &LR;      07-31 0502
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CVN-BEDTIME-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRIME-TIME SPEECH SCHEDULED AFTER BUSH'S BEDTIME 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By R.G. RATCLIFFE 
c.2000 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLUMBUS, Ohio _ Texas Gov. George W. Bush's nationally
televised, prime-time speech Thursday night accepting the
Republican presidential nomination will be the most important of
his career _ and it will be delivered after his bedtime.
</P>
<P>
   If there ever was a time during his presidential campaign that
Bush was most likely to mangle his speech, slaughter his syntax,
slur his words or drop nouns from his sentences, it almost always
was at night after a long, busy day.
</P>
<P>
   Bush typically hits the hay at about 9:30 p.m. and rises
sometime between 5:30 and 6:30 a.m. Bush's acceptance speech is set
to be delivered to the Republican National Convention at 10 p.m. in
Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   ``We hope he'll have time for a nap Thursday afternoon,'' Bush
spokesman Karen Hughes said Monday. ``It's a late night, but he's
been looking forward to this moment and he'll make the most of
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Hughes said the campaign is counting on Bush not switching his
internal clock from Texas' Central Time to Philadelphia's Eastern
Time.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it's Central Time, it's close (to his bedtime). We're
assuming his body is still on Central Time,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   During the long days of campaigning in Iowa and New Hampshire
last January, Bush often complained about missing his own bed. He
admitted even carrying his own pillow on the road to help ease his
slumber.
</P>
<P>
   In one of his more notable evening speech stumbles, Bush told a
crowd in Cedar Rapids, Iowa, how in the post-Cold War world (which
he often describes as the ``post-Cold World``) the United States
can no longer focus on the Soviet Union as its enemy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm also running because I want to keep the peace, keep the
peace,'' Bush said. ``When I was coming up, it was a dangerous
world and you knew exactly who the `they' were. It was us vs. them,
and it was clear who `them' was. Today we're not so sure who the
`they' are, but we know they're there.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush's days leading into the convention already appear to be on
the longish side _ running from 7 a.m. to 9 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Texas first lady Laura Bush told Hughes about hearing a clock
chime at 3 a.m., then again at 4 and 5, as she lay awake nervously
thinking of the speech she was to deliver to the convention.
</P>
<P>
   ``He (Bush) was teasing her for waking him up at 5 in the
morning,'' Hughes said, adding that Laura Bush responded that he
should thank her for delivering a convention speech.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's speech _ which takes 38 minutes to deliver without
interruptions _ is expected to run about 50 minutes at the
convention due to applause. Hughes said the speech has undergone a
small amount of rewriting.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is one section where he has consistently had trouble
saying it, and I thought as long as he's having trouble saying it
we ought to change the words and make it more comfortable for
him,'' Hughes said.
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
