<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-31 19:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8699 &Cx1f; tad-z
r f BC-ATL-MACYS0801-COX     07-31 0517
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ATL-MACYS0801-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    By Tony Wilbert
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA - Let the redevelopment of the Macy's building downtown
begin.
</P>
<P>
   Taconic Investment Partners of New York closed on its
acquisition of the historic property at Peachtree and Ellis streets
late last week. It bought the building with partner Benenson
Capital Co. The seller was Federated Department Stores of
Cincinnati, which leased back part of the building for a condensed
Macy's store.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, Taconic principal Paul Pariser said a majority of the
building _ floors two through six _ will be renovated and leased to
Internet, e-commerce and telecommunications companies. ``We will
commence our redevelopment activity shortly,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Mathews, a Colliers Cauble &AMP; Co. executive vice president
who represented Federated, declined to comment on the sale price.
However, based on similar recent sales, the building likely fetched
about $40 million.
</P>
<P>
   The transaction culminates five years of planning for Federated,
which had been seeking an agreement that would allow it to sell the
Macy's building and keep the store open. Downtown boosters hoped
the upper levels would be converted to residential use, and Post
Properties made a run at the building.
</P>
<P>
   The new office and telecom space will bring 500 to 800 workers
to the building, Pariser said. In January, he said the new space
would house 700 to 1,000 workers, but he lowered the estimate after
Taconic decided against adding space to the building's top three
floors. For now, 360,000 square feet will be marketed as high-tech
and telecom switching space.
</P>
<P>
   Interest in the telecom space has been ``tremendous,''
especially from telecommunications and collocation companies, said
Casey Neel, an Insignia/ESG broker who is marketing the space.
``Anybody who comes through for telecommunications space looks at
the Macy's building,'' he said. ``It's hard not to.''
</P>
<P>
   Collocation companies lease space that houses telecom and
computer equipment of several companies. The buildings also are
known as telecom hotels.
</P>
<P>
   Neel said the building's location in the heart of downtown and
its proximity to fiber-optic trunk lines make it a natural for
telecom companies.
</P>
<P>
   The redeveloped Macy's building will be similar to, although
much smaller than, buildings such as 111 Eighth Ave. in New York
that Taconic converted to telecom use.
</P>
<P>
   It houses companies such as WorldCom, Fibernet Telecom Group and
Broadwing Communications.
</P>
<P>
   Pariser said Taconic will seek similar tenants for the renovated
space at the Macy's building, which it has renamed AtlantaXchange.
</P>
<P>
   Federated will condense the downtown Macy's store from 4 1/2 to
three floors, including the Cellar and mezzanine areas. The store
will contain about 200,000 square feet.
</P>
<P>
   Federated has committed to a 20-year lease with options to
extend the lease for an additional 30 years.
</P>
<P>
   A separate entrance for the office space will be constructed at
the corner of Peachtree and Ellis.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
