<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-31 19:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8700 &Cx1f; tab-z
u a BC-GOP-CHRISTIAN-RIGHT-N     07-31 1048
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOP-CHRISTIAN-RIGHT-NEWHOUSE </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHRISTIAN RIGHT TONES IT DOWN FOR GOP CONVENTION 
</HEADLINE>
   (ATTN: The Newhouse News Service has added this story as a TOP
OFFERING to the July 31 report.) 
 ATTENTION EDITORS: This article from NEWHOUSE NEWS SERVICE for
MONDAY, July 31, is available as a ``separate-buy.'' For
information about purchasing the article, contact DEBRA WEYDERT of
The New York Times Syndicate at 1-732-390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697;
e-mail: weyded nytimes.com.) 
 By DAVID GIBSON  
 c.2000 Newhouse News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ While the religious right is still a key presence
at the Republican National Convention, its tone and role are more
low key and less, shall we say, evangelical than in the last
several years.
</P>
<P>
   The main reason for the change, Republicans say, is that the
large bloc of religious conservatives who remain in the GOP fold
has, by mutual consent, agreed that any public feuds or harsh
rhetoric would only serve to undermine the party's overriding
mission.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ultimately, it isn't so much their tremendous enthusiasm for
Bush as a desire to beat Gore,'' said Jeff Bell, a GOP consultant
who worked for the primary campaign of moral conservative Gary
Bauer until the former Family Research Council chief packed it in
after the March primaries.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bush is not militant on the issues important to social
conservatives, but getting him is a lot better than 12 years of
Clinton-Gore,'' Bell said. ``That's more the glue that unites.''
</P>
<P>
   The upshot is that widely known figures like televangelist and
Christian Coalition founder Pat Robertson will not have speaking
roles at the convention, and moral traditionalists like Bauer, Alan
Keyes and Steve Forbes, whose campaign crusades all sputtered this
year, also will be out of sight.
</P>
<P>
   But besides the desire to defeat Al Gore in November, there are
other reasons for the change in strategy, a result of both design
and necessity.
</P>
<P>
   The necessity comes from the series of reversals that Christian
conservatives have faced in recent years. Chief among them is the
simple fact that none of their champions has lasted very long in
the primaries.
</P>
<P>
   This means that come convention time, religious right
organizations don't have much leverage. Candidates have not had to
pay court to Christian conservatives (even though many believe that
indifference to evangelicals came back to haunt Bob Dole at the
voting booths in 1996).
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, the granddaddy of the religious right lobbies, the
Christian Coalition, has gone through a series of well-publicized
travails. In 1997, after the Dole debacle and the advent of
Clinton-Gore II, Robertson's savvy young lieutenant, Ralph Reed,
left the Christian Coalition to go into private consulting, and the
organization's leadership has been a revolving door ever since.
</P>
<P>
   Then last year, the IRS won a long-running case that strips the
Christian Coalition of its tax-exempt status as a nonpartisan
group, a decision that contributed to the financial woes dogging
the group in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   This year, Robertson has righted the ship a bit, using some of
his own money to bail the group out and returning to take an active
role in guiding the organization he started after his own GOP
presidential run in 1988.
</P>
<P>
   But the Christian Coalition is not as feared as it once was, and
Robertson seems to have adjusted to that reality by taking a new
tack of going mainstream. He embraced a Bush candidacy early and
enthusiastically, pledging to work from within for Bush rather than
agitating from without. Party leaders made it clear that would also
mean accepting a diminished role in Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   ``Robertson's a lightning rod at this point,'' said Steve Benen
with Americans United for the Separation of Church and State, a
religious right watchdog group. ``He's well known but not
necessarily well liked, especially at the national level.''
</P>
<P>
   But in many ways the metamorphosis of the so-called ``religious
right'' is also a consequence of its own successes.
</P>
<P>
   Beginning with Jerry Falwell's Moral Majority in the late 1970s,
the religious right has always been essentially a grassroots
movement, and that is now paying off. For example, Christian
Coalition allies and operatives are estimated to have taken control
of Republican organizations in at least 17 states.
</P>
<P>
   More importantly, however, Christian conservatives without
formal affiliation to outside lobbies have steadily integrated
themselves into the fabric of the party to the point that more than
a third of the GOP delegates in Philadelphia identify themselves as
evangelicals, and more than two-thirds say they are sympathetic to
the religious right's agenda.
</P>
<P>
   ``There has been a transformation of the Republican Party as
more of them (evangelical Christians) have become party
activists,'' said James Guth, a political scientist of the
religious right at Furman University in South Carolina. ``Most of
the evangelical Christian leaders are themselves delegates and
elected political officials. They don't need an external
organization to speak for them.''
</P>
<P>
   (OPTIONAL TRIM FOLLOWS)
</P>
<P>
   The transformation also means that Christian conservatives tend
to be more temperate than they were in the days of Patrick
Buchanan, who defected to the Reform Party.
</P>
<P>
   ``Politics is about the need to compromise, and it has induced a
little more pragmatism among Christian conservatives,'' Guth said.
As political insiders, he said, ``they have more of a stake in the
outcome (of the election), and so they make judgments about when to
push and when not to push.''
</P>
<P>
   Roberta Combs, the Christian Coalition spokeswoman and a
longtime activist in the organization, agreed, saying the low
profile of the religious right at the Philadelphia convention is in
fact a sign of their acceptance.
</P>
<P>
   ``We now have a place at the table. We are part of what is going
on. Our role now is to go into the convention united and to come
out of the convention united. We are there to get support for our
issues, and Gov. Bush has shown he is willing to do that. We may
not be out there tooting our horn on television,'' Combs said,
``but we are definitely a presence.''
</P>
<P>
   (David Gibson is a reporter for The Star-Ledger of Newark, N.J.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
