<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-31 19:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8704 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-CVN-BAXTER01-COX     07-31 0585
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CVN-BAXTER01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    TIGHT REIN ON RHETORIC SOFTENS REPUBLICAN IMAGE
 &HT;    By TOM BAXTER
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ Unsympathetic Democrats dismiss it as a
camouflage that the Republicans will soon discard if they get Gov.
George W. Bush elected. Republicans defend it as a pragmatic
restatement of what they've always believed.
</P>
<P>
   But does either explanation fully explain the softened edges of
this year's Republican National Convention?
</P>
<P>
   In part, the generally less strident, more ``inclusive'' (this
week's buzzword) tone of this gathering amounts to a tighter job of
stage managing.
</P>
<P>
   What is remembered as the disastrous Houston convention of 1992
would have seemed much less hard-edged if it had not included Pat
Buchanan's ``culture war'' speech, and those involved in that
convention insist they didn't know what the conservative firebrand
was going to say.
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan is not even in the party this time, and this Bush
campaign is riding much closer herd on those who will speak.
</P>
<P>
   It really is nothing new for Republicans to present a less
conservative image and for Democrats to act less liberal at their
conventions in an effort to win over the broad middle of the
American electorate.
</P>
<P>
   And yet the party's platform and the list of those who will
speak clearly does indicate that at least in the face it presents
to America, the GOP has turned the page from the era when the party
openly pursued so-called ``wedge issues'' to divide traditionally
Democratic conservative voters from their party.
</P>
<P>
   Phyllis Schlafly, a conservative stalwart whose edge has never
been in question and who was attending a fund-raiser for House
Republicans Bob Barr of Georgia and Dan Burton of Indiana, did not
appear entirely thrilled by the new tone of the party Monday. But
she, too, was on board with a campaign Republicans of all stripes
hope will deliver them back to the Promised Land of Pennsylvania
Avenue.
</P>
<P>
   The platform, she observed, was ``muted,'' and she wished more
``interesting'' speakers, such as Barr or Burton, could have been
included in the convention program. But she demurred from open
dissent.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they're happy enough to support the ticket,'' Schlafly
said of conservative Republicans like herself. ``Bush has pretty
well corralled all sections of the party.''
</P>
<P>
   The most striking instance of this softened tone is the almost
total absence of any mention of Bill Clinton's impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're going to hear very little mention of Bill Clinton at
this convention, but that's because the message has penetrated,''
said Floyd Brown, a longtime Clinton critic from Arkansas.
</P>
<P>
   But it's not just an absence of broadsides at the Democratic
president that is noticeable. When Rep. Bill McCollum, who is
running for the U.S. Senate in Florida this year, spoke during the
day Monday, his role as one of Clinton's House prosecutors got
barely a mention.
</P>
<P>
   It confuses things to say this amounts to the Republicans
becoming more liberal, which they are not. ``Civic'' _ as opposed
to ``political'' _ is another word that has been tossed around, and
while that may not be a perfect description, it's closer to the
mark.
</P>
<P>
   One might be ``civic'' and still be conservative, but like the
candidate himself, the word implies a softer rhetoric than has been
applied in the past.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Baxter's e-mail address is tbaxter(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
