u p BC-CVN-LAURA-BUSH-HNS &LR;      07-31 1216
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CVN-LAURA-BUSH-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
LAURA BUSH STEPS INTO THE LIMELIGHT &HT;    (EDS: Story will update after speech is delivered at 10 p.m.)
 &HT;    By DAN FREEDMAN
 &HT;    c. 2000 Hearst Newspapers
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ Defying her reputation as a prim,
noncontroversial former librarian, Texas first lady Laura Bush took
a swipe at the Clinton-Gore administration Monday night, telling
delegates to the Republican National Convention that if her husband
becomes president he ``will not change with the winds of polls.''
</P>
<P>
   Taking a giant step into the limelight in a prime-time speech on
the convention's opening night, Bush addressed presidential
character _ an issue that regularly registers as a high priority
among voters in polls.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've known (George W. Bush) through big legislative successes
and a few defeats,'' Laura Bush said, according to a transcript of
her speech released before her address. In a reference to her
husband's former ownership of the Texas Rangers baseball team, she
said: ''I sat by his side during some winning and many losing
baseball seasons. But George never loses sight of home plate.``
</P>
<P>
   Laura Bush's remarks were a veiled slap at Texas Gov. George W.
Bush's Democratic opponent, Vice President Al Gore, who has been
characterized by Republicans as waffling on issues and saying
anything to get elected. It also is a jab at President Clinton,
whose presidency has been marked by similar accusations.
</P>
<P>
   The governor's ``core principles will not change with the winds
of polls or politics or fame or fortune or misfortune,'' she said
in an address that focused largely on education.
</P>
<P>
   On education, she and her husband had tried to impart to their
twin daughters the lessons their parents had taught them, that
``reading is entertaining and interesting and important. ''
</P>
<P>
   Her husband is running for president ``to make sure every child
in America has that same opportunity to grow up reading,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   The convention represented a big stage for Laura Bush. She
agreed to marry Bush in 1977 on condition that she would never have
to deliver a political speech on his behalf.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the only political promise I ever broke,'' the governor
has told innumerable campaign crowds over the past year.
</P>
<P>
   For Laura Welch Bush, it has been something of a long, strange
trip between the tumbleweed plains of Midland, Texas, where she
cruised Agnes' drive-in for hamburgers, to potential first lady
whose family life is publicly picked over in sometimes excruciating
detail.
</P>
<P>
   In between, there were stops in Houston and Austin as a teacher
and librarian. And there was the mutual friends' barbecue in 1977
where she met Bush. It was an encounter she had actually resisted
because she did not think she would have anything in common with
someone from a political family. (Bush's father was a U.S. House
member from Texas before becoming president and his grandfather was
a U.S. senator from Connecticut.)
</P>
<P>
   The Bushes were married in November 1977. Laura Bush was 31, the
last of her longtime friends to walk to the altar.
</P>
<P>
   Ambition, power and fame _ with all the trimmings _ are not life
qualities to which Laura Bush aspired. ``Traditional,''
``reluctant,'' and ``sheltered'' are words she has used to describe
herself.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, on the campaign trail, she has grown into the role of
high-profile political spouse. She has stumped on her own, talking
about the topic of her convention speech: education. On the
campaign plane when she is traveling with the candidate himself,
Laura Bush is relaxed and informal up to a point, reminding some
reporters of helpful librarians they might have known in grade
school.
</P>
<P>
   Don Evans, a longtime family friend who serves as Bush's
campaign manager, described Laura Bush as ``a lady who's full of
grace'' and ``somebody America will love.''
</P>
<P>
   Has there been a campaign-trail learning curve for her? ``Well,
there is for everybody,'' Evans responded. ``But I guarantee you,
she's there.''
</P>
<P>
   Laura Bush, 53, was the only child of a Harold Welch, a home
builder, and Jenna Welch, who did bookkeeping for him and read
books to Laura aloud.
</P>
<P>
   She knew her future husband just barely in junior high school
before the Bushes moved from Midland to Houston and Bush was sent
to boarding school in Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   About the only blip on the screen of her life is when at the age
of 17, she ran a stop sign in Midland. Her car collided with a
vehicle driven by another teen-ager, a boy she knew. He was killed.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was painful, of course,'' she told one interviewer. It
was ``a very tragic time in my life.''
</P>
<P>
   Laura Bush graduated from Southern Methodist University in
Dallas in 1968. Like her future husband at Yale, the social turmoil
and experimentation of the 1960s passed her by.
</P>
<P>
   She spent the first part of the 1970s as an elementary school
teacher and librarian in Houston and Austin, earning a master's
degree in library science at the Austin campus of the University of
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Teaching in a predominantly minority school in Houston and not
marrying until after age 30 shows she was ``in many ways very
contemporary,'' as she told one interviewer.
</P>
<P>
   Four years after their marriage, Laura Bush gave birth to twin
girls, Barbara and Jenna _ named after the couple's mothers.
Barbara will attend Yale University this fall and Jenna will go to
the University of Texas in Austin.
</P>
<P>
   In many ways the Bushes are a classic odd couple. He is at times
a garrulous jokester who bounces off the walls; she is mostly quiet
and demure. But by all accounts, Laura Bush has been the yin to her
husband's yang.
</P>
<P>
   She has a calming effect on him and years ago helped him quit
drinking before it became a problem. But she acknowledges that he,
in turn, adds a few thrills to her life that she might not
otherwise have expected.
</P>
<P>
   Laura Bush was not wild about the idea of her husband running
for governor of Texas in 1994. And earlier this year she told the
Associated Press, ``I was the last person on board'' when Gov. Bush
was weighing a White House bid.
</P>
<P>
   But if her service as first lady of Texas is any indication,
Laura Bush may well warm to the role of national first lady should
her husband vanquish Gore. From the governor's mansion, Laura Bush
has raised money and lobbied fiercely for Texas libraries and
programs to teach reading to pre-school children.
</P>
<P>
   The education theme of Monday night's speech drew polite sniffs
from Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   ``The campaigns are asking the spouses to do different things,''
said Joseph Andrew, chairman of the Democratic National Committee,
who as at the Republican National Convention at the behest of
various media organizations. Gore's wife ``Tipper speaks out on
substantive issues'' such as mental health, Andrew said. ``With
Laura Bush, the (Republican) campaign has asked her to talk
non-specific generalities because they can't talk about the issues
or the record ... Texas is one of the worst places to raise
children.''
</P>
<P>
   Andew was referring to studies showing Texas ranking at the
bottom of various social indicators. In one such study earlier this
year by the nonpartisan, Baltimore-based Annie E. Casey Foundation,
Texas ranked 44th among 50 states in rates of child poverty.
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
