<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-31 19:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8710 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-MOTHER-REUNION01-COX     07-31 1373
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOTHER-REUNION01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Period of separation will soon end for mother, son
 &HT;    By Jane O. Hansen
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ When Kimberly Howard last saw her son in January 1989,
he was a curly-haired 6-year-old full of wonder and excitement.
</P>
<P>
   The child was about to board a plane with his father to visit
grandparents in Saudi Arabia. She didn't know at the time that her
ex-husband had no intention of bringing their son back.
</P>
<P>
   Weeks later she received the call at her Atlanta home. Laith _
the boy whose wide brown eyes and smile she treasured _ would not
be coming home. Not ever.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was the day my descent into hell began,'' said Howard,
now 42.
</P>
<P>
   For the next 11 years, the mother hoped, despaired, fumed and
fought _ pursuing every person and State Department official she
could who might help get her son back. She even contacted a
vigilante group to see if it could rekidnap her son. ``Then you
realize nobody cares,'' she said. ``It was a civil issue. It had
nothing to do with our relations with Saudi Arabia.''
</P>
<P>
   The day came when she packed away the little boy's pictures in a
box.
</P>
<P>
   ``It got too painful,'' she said. ``I realized Laith wasn't
coming home.''
</P>
<P>
   But six weeks ago, another call came. On June 23, Howard checked
the messages on her answering machine in San Diego, where she had
moved to be closer to her family.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hello, Mum?'' an adult-sounding male voice said. ``This is
Laith.'' He told her he loved her and wanted to see her. It was the
first time she'd heard his voice in 11 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just started crying,'' Howard said last week, crying again
as she spoke. ``I was in shock.''
</P>
<P>
   Howard's family calls it a miracle. Laith Khayyat _ who will be
18 in October _ is due to arrive late tonight in California.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm numb,'' Howard said. ``I thought I'd never see him again.
``
</P>
<P>
   Howard met Abdulaziz Khayyat in the early 1980s while the two
were students at San Diego University. She was tall,
strawberry-blonde, studying business. He was slender, dark-haired,
a student of engineering. They fell in love, married and had a son.
</P>
<P>
   When Laith was a baby, Khayyat convinced his young wife to
return with him to Saudi Arabia, where he was the prized son of the
king's tailor. Howard soon realized that even an American woman
could not travel, speak, dress or act as she pleased there. She
eventually escaped with her son in a dramatic ruse orchestrated
with the help of her parents and an American couple in Saudi
Arabia.
</P>
<P>
   When her husband was transferred back to the United States about
a year later, Howard served him with divorce papers, and a
California court awarded her custody of their son.
</P>
<P>
   But the bitterness wore off in time. Howard decided the boy
needed his father, and the two worked out amicable visitations. It
seemed to be working until Howard moved to Atlanta to take over a
day care center. While she was getting settled in their new home,
she let Laith visit his paternal grandparents. It was a
life-changing decision, one she calls shamefully stupid.
</P>
<P>
   After he was gone, she kept pictures of Laith on the bulletin
board at her day care center. She tried to live normally, and says
she grew to love a nearby lake, where she rented pontoon boats and
swam with friends. But she calls her time in Atlanta a dark period
in her life.
</P>
<P>
   In those first years after her son was taken, Howard frequently
called the State Department, which opened a case but offered little
hope. ``Can we go in there with a vigilante squad and guns and
remove the child from the home?'' a spokeswoman said in 1992. ``No,
we cannot.''
</P>
<P>
   Currently there are 950 similar cases of children abducted by a
parent and taken to a foreign country.
</P>
<P>
   As years passed, Howard became increasingly depressed.
Thanksgiving and Christmas were lonely holidays. ``I had nothing to
celebrate,'' she said. She realizes now why she lost so many
friends. She could not get over the loss of her son.
</P>
<P>
   ``People's lives go on,'' she said. ``Mine stopped. It's very
difficult for people to understand. Even your family. Nobody wants
to hear about stuff like this.''
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, she says, the State Department closed Howard's case.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then, a miracle,'' said Jane Howard, Kim's sister in
Charlotte, N.C. On June 19, Laith walked into a U.S. consulate and
said he wanted to find his mother. The State Department quickly
retrieved Howard's file and tracked her down.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always knew that Laith would try to find us,'' Jane Howard
said.
</P>
<P>
   After receiving that first message from Laith, Howard bought a
tape recorder to record his next call, and she and her family began
to prepare for his homecoming.
</P>
<P>
   They've rented an ultra-stretch limousine, big enough to carry
her parents, two sisters and their children.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought it would be better to have a group meet him,''
Howard said. ``I'm kind of scared. And I'm sure he is too. I want
him to know that he has a family here who loves him and has missed
him very much.''
</P>
<P>
   On July 4, Laith called again.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he was in shock, having finally gotten hold of me,''
Howard said. ``He wanted to hear my voice.''
</P>
<P>
   He told her they needed to sit down and talk. ``I let him carry
the conversation,'' Howard recalled. ``I was scared. He said he
loved me and his father, and it's very hard for him.''
</P>
<P>
   He told her he'd applied for a scholarship through an oil
company that would pay for his education in the United States. He
said he wanted to be an engineer or a doctor, but he didn't know
whether he would remain in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was killing me, but I didn't say anything,'' Howard said.
</P>
<P>
   They talked for more than an hour. ``He's matured,'' she said.
``He does have a Saudi accent, but he speaks excellent English.''
</P>
<P>
   When he asked why she had never visited him in Saudi Arabia, she
hesitated. ``I said, 'Well, the country doesn't allow women to
travel.' He doesn't understand how harsh it is.''
</P>
<P>
   She says at some point she will explain what happened _ how his
father wouldn't even let her talk to him on the phone. But for now,
she doesn't want to scare him away with criticisms of his father.
</P>
<P>
   It's hard for Howard to imagine what her son looks like. He told
her he was 196 centimeters, slightly over 6 feet 5 inches tall. His
hair is still curly, ``and he made a point of telling me that he
does not look like his dad,'' she said, laughing. ``I don't think
his dad has allowed him to have any pictures of me, trying to wipe
me out of Laith's memory. I always wondered, did he remember me?''
</P>
<P>
   She says they were both nervous.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the scary part,'' she said. ``In my mind, he's still 6
years old. ``
</P>
<P>
   Now he's a mature young man. ``He's a smart kid. He's really
thought about this.''
</P>
<P>
   Since that call, she's been in a fog _ excited but tortured by
the wait. Although she taped the July 4 conversation, she
accidentally erased it. Last weekend, she left the house with her
shirt on backward. ``It's just overwhelming,'' she said. ``I'm a
bundle of nerves.''
</P>
<P>
   Howard wants her story to be an inspiration to others. ``There
are a lot of men and women out there whose children were
abducted,'' she said. ``I know not all of them turn out like this.
I mean, I still don't know what's going to happen. But there is
hope.''
</P>
<P>
   She admits she's still angry. ``The thing is, he's a young man.
I lost his growing up,'' she said. ``But I'm not going to focus on
the past. You have to go forward.''
</P>
<P>
   Last Wednesday, Laith called again. This time she got it on tape
for good.
</P>
<P>
   He told her he would be coming home Tuesday, that his father had
bought him the ticket.
</P>
<P>
   ``Are you coming to visit or go to school?'' she asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, I'm staying with you, Mum,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tuesday, I can't wait. Oh, I'm so happy,'' the mother said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Me too, Mum.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I just can't wait to see you,'' she said. ``It's been so long.
I love you so much, I can't wait.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I love you too, Mum.''
</P>
<P>
   Monday, the State Department said Laith was still scheduled to
arrive today.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been over 11 years,'' Howard said. ``Another day won't
matter.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
