<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-31 19:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8712 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a BC-BRAINSTUDY0801-COX     07-31 0331
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRAINSTUDY0801-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Disciplines converge at Center for Brain Research
 &HT;    By Kevin Lamb
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   FAIRBORN, Ohio _ The new Center for Brain Research at Wright
State University's School of Medicine will encourage collaboration
among scientists who study different aspects of the brain's
functions in health and disease.
</P>
<P>
   The center was established in July with a donation from the
Kettering Fund.
</P>
<P>
   Departments ranging from anatomy, physiology, biophysics,
neurology and psychiatry will share the laboratories, imaging
technology and research staff of the new center in the school's
Biological Sciences Building.
</P>
<P>
   ``No single laboratory or experimental approach can solve the
technical problems presented by the diversity of structures and
functions in the brain and central nervous system,'' said Robert
Fyffe, the researcher who is the center's first director.
``Interdisciplinary collaboration is essential for the future of
brain research.''
</P>
<P>
   As an example, Fyffe cited the collaborative process in
determining the function of a protein called TASK-1, which helps
move potassium in and out of brain cells. Researchers from Wright
State and Imperial College in London recently reported their
results in the Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences
journal.
</P>
<P>
   They determined that TASK-1 helps regulate the communication of
nerve impulses from brain cell to brain cell. Learning that raised
the possibility of someday regulating that potassium flow to help
treat epilepsy, ataxia and other neurological disorders that result
from hyperactive or uncoordinated communication among brain cells.
</P>
<P>
   ``What starts off as a fundamental research question in basic
science can suddenly appear to have direct clinical relevance,''
Fyffe said. ``None of us know where the questions will take us.''
</P>
<P>
   Contact Kevin Lamb at kevinlamb(at)coxohio.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
