<SLUG> BC-VENEZUELA-POLITICS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHAVEZ FAILS TO WIN MANDATE FOR ABSOLUTE POWER
</HEADLINE>
 By LARRY ROHTER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CARACAS, Venezuela _ With final results in Sunday's
``mega-election'' here tabulated Monday, President Hugo Chavez has
won an overwhelming personal victory, but his coattails were
apparently not quite long enough to pull into Congress the
followers needed to guarantee him absolute powers.
</P>
<P>
   Chavez won 59 percent of the vote. But in the races for the
National Assembly, pro-Chavez parties won 99 of 165 seats, which
fell just short of the two-thirds majority that would have turned
the new single-chamber legislature into a rubber stamp.
</P>
<P>
   The two-thirds watershed was crucial to Chavez's plans to carry
out the ``peaceful social revolution'' he has promised supporters.
With it he would have avoided any opposition resistance to
decisions to discharge Supreme Court judges and members of
Congress, decree certain laws, and appoint prosecutors, members of
the Central Bank board and other officials.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we need from here on in is to find the path to national
unity,'' said Henrique Salas Feo, the opposition governor of the
state of Carabobo, in what was seen as a veiled message to Chavez
to be more conciliatory. ``The divisions must end, and we must all
have the conviction that we are members of the same community.''
</P>
<P>
   But Chavez's majority in the National Assembly is still large
enough to assure passage of an ``enabling law'' that would allow
him to decree at least some of the sweeping measures unpopular with
the opposition. It was the granting of those special powers last
year that allowed Chavez to dissolve the opposition-dominated
Congress and take over the judicial system.
</P>
<P>
   Also working in his favor is the fact that his adversaries
remain fragmented and demoralized. His main rival, Francisco Arias
Cardenas, showed few gifts as a campaigner or orator, and the
right-of-center political party that divided power for 40 years,
called Copei, has all but vanished as an electoral force, winning
only five seats in the new legislature.
</P>
<P>
   The traditional left-of-center party here, known as Democratic
Action, did much better, and will be the second-largest political
grouping in this nation of 23 million people, which in recent years
has been the main source of oil imported by the United States. The
party holds 32 seats in the National Assembly and won four or five
governorships, depending on the outcome of one especially tight
race.
</P>
<P>
   At the state level, Chavez did better than expected. His
Patriotic Pole coalition won at least 12 of 23 governorships,
including the re-election of his father in his home state of
Barinas, and also appears to have won a majority of the country's
336 mayoral races. Many analysts had predicted exactly the opposite
outcome.
</P>
<P>
   The election Sunday to ``re-legitimize'' Chavez's rule was
required by a new constitution whose formulation and approval by
voters has been the main focus of his first 18 months in office.
The constitution significantly expands the powers of the federal
government, especially the executive branch, while eliminating a
ban on presidents immediately seeking re-election, and extending
their term of office to six years from five.
</P>
<P>
   Chavez quickly made it clear that he intends to take full
advantage of all the new features and powers of the charter. In his
victory speech early Monday, for instance, he indicated that he
already plans to run for a second term, in hopes of being the
nation's chief executive when Venezuela marks the bicentennial of
its independence in 2011.
</P>
<P>
   In the speech, delivered from the balcony of the presidential
palace, Chavez mocked Arias Cardenas and other political rivals,
but took an unusually conciliatory tone toward business leaders who
have frequently been objects of his wrath.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are all sailing in the same boat,'' he said, adding that he
needed them to ``help save the Venezuelan economy,'' which
contracted by 7.2 percent last year despite record high oil prices.
</P>
<P>
   Business leaders responded optimistically to that olive branch.
``If he is holding out a hand, now is the time to shake it,'' said
Antonio Herrera, vice president of the Venezuelan-American Chamber
of Commerce.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, differences persist over how to make the economy
grow. In the victory speech, Chavez made a point of saluting his
minister of planning and development, Jorge Giordani, and of
finance, Jose Rojas, who have taken most of the criticism for his
economic policies.
</P>
<P>
   To Robert Bottome, publisher of Veneconomia, the country's
leading business newsletter, this declaration of support did not
bode well. ``Nothing makes me think this president is willing to
change his policies,'' he said. ``If you don't change Giordani and
Rojas, you don't change anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Whatever course he takes, Chavez will be under pressure to
deliver results soon. When Edelmira de Gil, a Chavez supporter, was
asked Sunday at a polling place here how long she would be willing
to wait before seeing an improvement, she quickly replied, ``three
or four months.'' If Chavez ``doesn't keep his word,'' she warned,
``he won't get re-elected.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
