<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VENEZUELA-BUSINESS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VENEZUELANS LEAVING FOR BETTER BUSINESS CLIMATE IN US 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (f and i coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD CHACON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CARACAS _ The economy is shrinking and unemployment is
disturbingly high. But perhaps the most telling sign ofVenezuela's
economic troubles may be in a word that residents have created:
``Mianeros,'' a name for those who've packed their bags and left to
seek better fortunes in Miami.
</P>
<P>
   Some economists estimate that as many as 150,000 Venezuelans
have left the country over the last two years for other, more
promising places like Florida to escape the country's protracted
crisis, which has seen a severe loss of jobs and an increase in
crime.
</P>
<P>
   It is precisely this problem that many experts say the country's
leftist president, Hugo Chavez, must now address after his
resounding reelection on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``He should talk more about opening markets and making Venezuela
more attractive for businesses if things are going to get better,''
said Roberto Bottome, director of VenEconomia, a think tank which
publishes an economic newsletter. ``If not, we'll continue to lose
businesses and we'll keep losing our most educated and talented
people.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite an economy which contracted by 7 percent last year and a
15 percent unemployment rate, Chavez, the 46-year-old,
beret-wearing former paratrooper, was given a strong endorsement
from voters on Sunday to proceed with his so-called ``peaceful
revolution.''
</P>
<P>
   He won 59 percent of the vote in an election that pitted his
fiery, populist platform against the more moderate and pro-business
agenda of Francisco Arias, a former military comrade. With more
than 80 percent of ballots counted, Arias had won 38 percent of the
vote. A third candidate, former Caracas Mayor Claudio Fermin, had
the remaining three percent.
</P>
<P>
   The election was part of a new constitution and political
overhaul that has been Chavez's main concern since he was first
elected in December 1998. But now that the president has solidified
his political power for at least the next six years, business and
industry leaders are urging him to put more emphasis on re-igniting
the country's stagnant economy.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been in crisis for more than a year and more than three
with a depressed industrial sector,'' Juan Calvo, president of the
Industrial Federation of Venezuela, told the Caracas daily El
Universal. ``This has to be solved with energy and decisiveness.''
</P>
<P>
   Speaking to thousands of supporters early Monday morning from a
balcony at the Miraflores presidential palace, Chavez vowed to make
economic growth a priority. But exactly how he would do that
remains unclear.
</P>
<P>
   Chavez, who speaks frequently about ``a humane economy,'' seems
more drawn to a government-controlled economy like Cuba than a more
liberal free-market like Mexico's. Among other Latin American
leaders, Chavez stays closest to Cuban President Fidel Castro, who
used a Saturday press conference in Cuba to publicly send warm
wishes to his friend.
</P>
<P>
   ``He should be looking more at countries like the United States
as a model for fixing this economy,'' said Andres Alvarez, a
41-year-old restaurant owner in downtown Caracas who voted for
Chavez. ``Yes, I believe in helping the poor, but even the poor
will turn on him if things don't improve.''
</P>
<P>
   Experts said Chavez will need a comprehensive strategy to
attract businesses and investors and to get the economy moving
again:
</P>
<P>
   --The country's legal code and labor laws must be revised to be
more business friendly.
</P>
<P>
   --Venezuela's growing crime problem must be tackled quickly.
</P>
<P>
   --The country's current image must be changed to one that
welcomes trade, not rejects it.
</P>
<P>
   Over the last two years, the country has lost more than 500,000
jobs and $3 billion in capital. Multinational companies such as
Unilever, Honda, Fiat and Warner-Lambert have either left Venezuela
or cut back their presence, taking white- and blue-collar jobs with
them.
</P>
<P>
   ``When an investor or business decides to come here, there is a
long list of pros and cons that are considered,'' Bottome added.
``Right now, Venezuela has more cons.''
</P>
<P>
   Chavez will have less than a veto-proof majority in the new
legislature to push whatever economic program his administration
puts together. His Patriotic Pole coalition won 60 percent of the
body's 165 seats, making it likely that he'll have to do some
negotiating with opposition parties to get his proposals approved.
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Arias, 49, who stood by Chavez during a failed
1992 coup attempt only to break away and challenge him for the
presidency, pledged to continue leading a broad, business-oriented
opposition against the president's coalition.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is our responsibility to this country to keep fighting for
a stronger, better Venezuela,'' Arias, who has not yet conceded
defeat, said in a speech Monday. ``We will make sure that an
opposition exists to protect all citizens of this country, rich and
poor.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
