<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-31 19:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8724 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u l BC-FLAVOREDMEDS-HNS &LR;      07-31 1103
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLAVOREDMEDS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
A TASTY RX: GREAT FLAVORS HELP KIDS' MEDICINE GO DOWN &HT;    w/Photos
 &HT;    By DANIEL J. VARGAS
 &HT;    c. 2000 Houston Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   (Undated) _ Medicine.
</P>
<P>
   That one word can send your taste buds shuddering and your inner
child searching for a bed to hide under.
</P>
<P>
   You can taste it now: a bitter, thick syrup that's supposed to
taste like cherry, except it's more like a menthol-reeking shot of
cheap booze that invokes a vengeful gag reflex.
</P>
<P>
   Ah, memories.
</P>
<P>
   However, things are getting sweeter for children who take
medicine by the spoonful.
</P>
<P>
   Four Houston-area pharmacies are using the FLAVORx program _ the
Baskin-Robbins of children's medicine. It uses more than 50
concentrated flavors from apple to mocha cappuccino to mask the
bitterness of children's medicine, making it more palatable for
young tykes.
</P>
<P>
   No more trickery or use of mild force-feeding measures to get
the medicine down the hatch.
</P>
<P>
   ``Children have a better sense for bitterness,'' says Kenny
Kramm, president of FLAVORx, based in Washington, D.C. ``As we get
older, our tastes change. Things we didn't like when we were
children don't bother us now. That's why when parents taste the
medicine, they don't see what the big deal is.''
</P>
<P>
   He still has fond recollections of when Mom used a towel to tie
him to her so he couldn't get away come medicine time.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone can understand this problem. It's a universal one,''
Kramm says.
</P>
<P>
   He knew something needed to be done to spice up the taste of
children's medicine when he came home one day to find that his wife
had cooked their daughter's anti-seizure medicine with eggs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Parents resort to doing whatever they can think of _ putting
it in chocolate syrup or in foods,'' Kramm says. ``But with some
drugs, those things can interact with the medication. For instance,
citrus can reduce the efficacy of some medicines.''
</P>
<P>
   So he paired up with his father in the early 1990s to experiment
with flavorings in the family's Washington, D.C., pharmacy. After
three years of trial and error taste-tests, they came up with a
300-page formulary, or recipe book, that tells the pharmacist how
to re-flavor medications _ both prescription and over-the-counter.
</P>
<P>
   In the past four years, FLAVORx has spread to 2,500 pharmacies
in the United States, Canada, Australia and New Zealand, and at 50
hospitals, including the Baptist Health System in San Antonio.
</P>
<P>
   Shannon W. Martin asks the Medicine Shoppe Pharmacy in Spring,
Texas, to use it in all of her 15-month-old daughter's medications,
which are usually antibiotics. About 10 percent of the pharmacy's
customers ask for flavoring.
</P>
<P>
   When Martin smelled her daughter's first antibiotics, she
likened it to the stench of ``dirty socks.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I won't even consider giving it to her without the
flavoring,'' she says. ``You don't do that to a child. You don't do
that to a dog.''
</P>
<P>
   Without the flavoring, Martin says, it would be difficult for
her daughter to swallow it without any fuss.
</P>
<P>
   ``As good a baby as she is, I imagine we might have had to hold
her down and give it to her,'' she says. ``This is just one more
comfort that makes our job as parents easier.''
</P>
<P>
   Although there are more than 50 sweet-tasting flavors, not all
blend well with each medication.
</P>
<P>
   Kramm says 15 flavors work with penicillin _ the least
compatible of all drugs. Amoxicillin is an easygoing kind of
medicine, mixing well with every flavor, he says.
</P>
<P>
   It may take more than one to suppress a nasty taste. For
example, Biaxin, a children's antibiotic with a gritty texture,
needs a triple punch of grape, watermelon and vanilla to mask its
bitter taste, Kramm says.
</P>
<P>
   Pharmacists and Kramm say the added flavor concentration neither
changes the medicinal properties of the drug nor dilutes it.
Because most children's medicine is stored in powder form and water
is added to make the syrup or liquid form, pharmacists simply
subtract a specified amount of water and replace it with droplets
of flavor.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bottom line is patient compliance,'' says Joe Staller,
owner and pharmacist at north Houston's Red Oak Pharmacy, which
also offers the flavorings. ``That's the name of the game. It's not
doing any good if it's not going down.''
</P>
<P>
   That's important when children are taking antibiotics for ear,
sinus and bronchial infections. Doctors usually prescribe a 10-day
supply that must be finished completely. If not, the infection can
resurface.
</P>
<P>
   Kramm says kids can sample flavors at the pharmacy to find out
which one they like best. And if they change their mind about the
flavor they've chosen, it can be re-flavored without throwing out
the original medication.
</P>
<P>
   He says parents shouldn't worry about kids trying to drink or
take more of the medicine than they should because of its improved
taste. Nevertheless, it should be kept out of reach and sealed with
a child-resistant top.
</P>
<P>
   ``The flavors make them more palatable, but a child won't drink
an entire bottle, believe me,'' Kramm says.
</P>
<P>
   At Horizon Pharmacy in Houston, several parents a day come in
requesting flavoring.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Roosth, a pharmacist for 38 years, says the pharmacy, which
has used the FLAVORx program for several years, charges $2.50 for a
flavoring. The most popular are cherry, bubble gum, lime and grape.
</P>
<P>
   He says pharmacists have flavored medicines for hundreds of
years, especially when they frequently compounded medications.
Sometimes pharmacists would add vanilla or mint. Now the idea is
just more sophisticated.
</P>
<P>
   ``A teaspoon of sugar makes the medicine go down,'' Roosth says.
</P>
<P>
   Sonja Jezierski, a pharmacy manager at Kroger in The Woodlands,
Texas, says her store does about 10 flavorings a day since it
adopted the FLAVORx program about three weeks ago. The Kroger
pharmacy, which also charges $2.50 for flavorings, is a test market
for the grocery chain in the Houston area, she says.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be a popular thing,'' Jezierski says.
</P>
<P>
   For those who don't want to pay the extra fee or aren't near a
pharmacy that offers the service, Staller suggests that the child
suck on an ice cube or lollipop before being given the medication.
This should mask any aftertaste, he says.
</P>
<P>
   Roosth admits that though the vast majority of
flavoring-medication combinations are right on target, ``sometimes
medicine just tastes like medicine.''
</P>
<P>
   And for the record, not one sickly child has asked him for mocha
cappuccino. These kids are too young to hang out and sip a grande
coffee drink at Starbucks.
</P>
<P>
   X X X END OF STORY
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
