<SLUG> BC-GOP-DVIERSITY01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Some blacks are finding their political roots with the GOP
 &HT;    Eds. All names are correct
 &HT;    By Miriam A. Garcia
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ Colorado delegate Syl Morgan-Smith is the only
Republican in her family. In fact, she is the first one in four
generations.
</P>
<P>
   ``This shows the great return of African-Americans to our
party,'' said Morgan-Smith, one of a handful of black Colorado
delegates.
</P>
<P>
   Her family left Lincoln's party for the Democratic party after
the Great Depression, as did many others. People needed assistance
from the government to survive, but today's economic boom should
drive people back to the Grand Old Party, Morgan-Smith said.
Morgan-Smith is attending the Republican National Convention.
</P>
<P>
   Lawmakers and delegates at the convention said that the party is
gradually becoming more diverse.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think more and more minority groups are getting involved
with the party,'' said Sen. Wayne Allard, R-Colo. ``They are
playing a greater role.''
</P>
<P>
   Allard cited the state's diversity among elected officials
including the only Native American in Congress, Sen. Ben Nighthorse
Campbell, Colorado State Rep. Joe Nunez, who is Hispanic, and Lt.
Gov. Joe Rogers, who is an African-American.
</P>
<P>
   Rogers had a prime spot on the convention floor Monday
afternoon, speaking from the main stage. Speaking to a full
convention hall, Rogers talked about the vision of Texas Gov.
George W. Bush.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are committed to stirring the waters of opportunity in our
land,'' said Rogers, chairman of the Republican Lieutenant
Governors Association and the group's youngest member.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bush is a rising star renewing America,'' Rogers said.
</P>
<P>
   Rogers was one of several African-Americans slated to speak on
the convention floor this week.
</P>
<P>
   Much has been said about the inclusion of minorities to the
line-up, which did not include other prominent Republicans
including Colo. Gov. Bill Owens.
</P>
<P>
   In response to the snub, Owens' spokesman Dick Wadhams said in
press reports last week that Owens ``never anticipated he would be
asked'' and that ``it's not a surprise that Joe Rogers would be
asked. He's one of the highest ranking African-American Republican
elected officials in the nation.''
</P>
<P>
   The relationship between Owens and Rogers has become contentious
during their year and a half of working together.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, Owens refused Rogers' request to let him veto
a bill that will allow future governors to pick their own running
mates. The bill, which Owens let become law without his signature,
will replace the current system of having running mates picked by
the state party assembly or at a primary election.
</P>
<P>
   The presence of Rogers on the podium Monday is part of a GOP
effort to change it's image, officials say.
</P>
<P>
   But the audience in the First Union was mostly white. According
to the Associated Press, about 83 percent of the delegates are
white, 4 percent black, 3 percent Hispanic, 1 percent Asian and 0.4
percent Native American. And about a dozen of the state delegations
are entirely white.
</P>
<P>
   ``We must diversify. The picture of this country is changing,''
said Morgan-Smith, who marched in several civil rights
demonstrations with the Rev. Martin Luther King Jr. in Birmingham,
Ala.
</P>
<P>
   The party's image has changed dramatically since Glen Neidert,
an alternate delegate to Colorado, joined the party about 50 years
ago, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The party has been trying to (become more diverse) for years
but people have not recognized it for what it is,'' Neidert said.
</P>
<P>
   Now that Morgan-Smith is back to her family's political roots,
she is trying to encourage her family to vore GOP, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I see opportunities for my grandchildren that I could not
envisioned 30 years ago,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``My mom would go to a store and if she saw a dress she liked,
they wouldn't let her try it on because it wouldn't be
merchantable. Yet here I am, a delegate in the year 2000 in the
city where our democracy was framed.''
</P>
<P>
   Miriam A. Garcia's e-mail is miriamg(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
