   ISRAEL-PERES (Jerusalem) _ At the moment Monday when the
announcement of the first of the two Knesset votes for Israel's
next president made it all but certain that he had lost the last
major battle of his 60-year political career, Shimon Peres, Noble
laureate, three-time prime minister and one of the most enduring
standard-bearers for Middle East peace, remained proudly, though
unobtrusively, in character. The result, with 60 votes for Moshe
Katsav, 57 votes for Peres, and three blank ballots, brought
groans, slumped shoulders and moist eyes among parliamentarians
backing Peres' bid to become Israel's eighth president. To those
who know him well, the 76-year-old statesman appeared ashen, but in
the simplicity of his manner and words he did nothing, despite the
moment's pain, to bely his reputation for courtliness and courage.
By John F. Burns.
