<SLUG> BC-RUN-CROUSE-COLUMN-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT WASN'T THE WAY ARNOLD DREW IT UP
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KAREN CROUSE  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Dreaming really big dreams is a lot like drawing
very delicate lines, Dominique Arnold discovered last week. If you
make a gl mistake, one that can't be covered up or erased, you
don't scrap the whole sketchbook; you simply flip to a fresh page
and start anew.
</P>
<P>
   At the recent U.S. Olympic Track and Field Trials, Arnold was so
close to putting his signature on arguably his finest work of art,
he had his i's dotted. Nearing the midway point of the 110-meter
hurdles final, the trained artist from Washington State was right
where he needed to be to finish in the top three and earn a berth
in Sydney.
</P>
<P>
   His signature, alas, would end in a line that abruptly skittered
off the page, four years of painstaking work ruined by an
accidental brush with the fourth hurdle. Arnold tripped, failed to
finish the race and was left off the U.S. Olympic team after
leading all qualifiers in the heats and the semifinals.
</P>
<P>
   While Allen Johnson, Mark Crear and Terrence Trammell celebrated
their 1-2-3 finish, Arnold was left to turn the page on his track
career and start fresh. It was no simple task.
</P>
<P>
   Arnold's drawings had turned dark in the days leading up to the
Trials. He took it as a sure sign that he was ready to run the race
of his life in Sacramento.
</P>
<P>
   His sketches included a abstract rendering ``of a guy getting
impaled,'' Arnold told us at the time, and you didn't have to be
renowned art critic Robert Hughes to appreciate the imagery;
Arnold's aim was to lance one of the deepest sprint hurdles fields
in history.
</P>
<P>
   For two rounds he did just that, winning his qualifying heat and
a stacked semifinal that included Johnson, the 1996 Olympic gold
medalist.
</P>
<P>
   Alas, it took three sterling races, lined up one after the other
like hurdles on a track, to join the five-ring circus in Sydney.
The process, which puts the trials in the Olympic qualifying meet,
invariably ends up breaking more hearts than Anna Kournikova.
</P>
<P>
   Arnold, 26, was crushed when he woke up each of the two mornings
after the hurdles final and realized it was no nightmare, that his
Olympic dream had been deferred at least four more years. Over and
over he replayed that last race in his head.
</P>
<P>
   He saw himself overtake Valencia's Crear (the Olympic silver
medalist in Atlanta) and draw even with Johnson and fly over the
fourth hurdle with so much speed he felt the same rush he had in
his previous two races, a sensation, he said, that was ``like
breaking free from a mist of confusion.''
</P>
<P>
   What happened next unwinds in Arnold's mind in super slow
motion. The toe of his trail leg hit the fourth hurdle and as fast
as you can exhale, Arnold lost his footing and fell.
</P>
<P>
   One of the indelible images we took from the Trials was of
Arnold slumped on the track, rubbing his smooth head in his hands,
a dazed victim who had been robbed of his dream in broad daylight.
</P>
<P>
   In a heartbeat, years of hard work and sacrifice were snatched
from Arnold, never to be recovered. We wondered how hard it was to
pick oneself up and move on. So we caught up to Arnold on Sunday,
shortly before he left for a four-meet tour of the lucrative
European track circuit.
</P>
<P>
   The Olympics is a big deal because it's the one meet every four
years that the world watches. But between now and Sydney the race
is on for another kind of gold, one no less valuable to someone
like Arnold, with rent to pay and a car and a body to fuel and no
wealth of sponsors.
</P>
<P>
   To dwell on the disappointment of the Trials would be to risk
docking his own pay with lackluster races in places such as
Stockholm, where Arnold will compete today. Athletes at Arnold's
level can't afford to be just dreamers, they have to be pragmatic,
too.
</P>
<P>
   So on the third day after his Olympic dream took a tumble,
Arnold returned to the Cal State Northridge track where he trains.
His first workout since returning from Sacramento was, in his
words, ``a little more intense'' than usual. It was almost as if by
sweating Arnold hoped to cleanse himself of the memories of his
fall.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was thinking about the screwup,'' Arnold said. ``I was
thinking, 'I don't want this to happen again.' ''
</P>
<P>
   He ran fast enough to ``break free from a mist of confusion,''
only this time Arnold didn't falter. He cleared all the hurdles his
coach, Jeff McAuley, put in his path. It was the first day of the
rest of Arnold's athletic career.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't eagerness or anxiety that got me in the finals,''
Arnold said. ``That's just the hurdles. You risk falling every time
you race. The one thing I can take from (the final) is that I was
right there (with Johnson and Crear) until I fell. Maybe if the
opportunity presents itself down the road, I'll be able to feel
like I did in that race, only I'll just be able to finish it.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead of an Olympic medal, Arnold has his sights set on
breaking the 13-second barrier (he clocked a personal best of 13.14
in the semis at the Trials). Then there's the American record of
12.92, held jointly by Johnson and Roger Kingdom. Arnold agreed
that it would be a nice consolation prize.
</P>
<P>
   Arnold sounded upbeat. The previous day he had resumed
sketching, as sure a sign as any that he has put that sad Sunday in
Sacramento behind him. Over the weekend, he worked on a drawing he
had started at the Trials. It is a portrait.
</P>
<P>
   For now Arnold has forsaken the abstract; he is focusing on what
is real.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
