<HEADER>
A8742 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-GOP-BLACKS01-COX     07-31 1037
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOP-BLACKS01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    GOP EXPANDING OUTREACH TO BLACKS
 &HT;    By MELANIE EVERSLEY
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ There was a time when such a scene would have
seemed surreal.
</P>
<P>
   The emcee for the luncheon laid manicured hands atop the podium
and prodded the audience to applaud for the man they all knew from
the big screen's ``Shaft,'' the black-oriented action movie from
the 1970s.
</P>
<P>
   As the mostly white, well-heeled crowd put their hands together
in the Grand Ballroom of the Philadelphia Marriott _ as if they
really had seen ``Shaft'' _ Richard Roundtree jogged onstage.
</P>
<P>
   The black actor praised the principles of self-help touted by
the Republican Party, to which he belongs. The audience of GOP
conventioneers cheered.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just feel comfortable being a Republican,'' Roundtree later
explained.
</P>
<P>
   Roundtree might not have felt so comfortable being a Republican
in the days when ``Shaft'' was popular. He may not have felt
comfortable even just five years ago.
</P>
<P>
   But convention organizers say they are kicking off a new
campaign of inclusion for America's minorities.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are a very diverse party that invites people of all
different backgrounds to this convention,'' said Andy Card,
convention co-chairman. ``Gov. Bush has reached out in Texas in
particular to bring people into the party who have not been active
heretofore.''
</P>
<P>
   Words like ``inclusion'' and ``community'' are being tossed
around, and the party is putting money behind several black
Congressional candidates, including three who addressed the
convention on Monday. One of them, Dylan Glenn, is challenging
Sanford Bishop for the seat representing the district in and around
Albany and Valdosta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   The three black Republican Congressional candidates networking,
handshaking and fund-raising here on Monday are spending a good
deal of their time getting out the message that the GOP is ready to
work with minority Americans.
</P>
<P>
   And there are people out there who clearly believe in this
message. For instance, most recent government records show Glenn
has raised more than half a million dollars and nearly as much as
Bishop. Jennifer Carroll, challenging Rep. Corrine Brown in
Florida's 3rd congressional district, has raised nearly half a
million dollars.
</P>
<P>
   Addressing the convention floor, Glenn, Carroll and third
candidate _ Joan Johnson, a black Republican woman from Long Island
seeking the seat of Republican Rep. Rick Lazio, who is running for
Senate _ all offered similar messages of how record-breaking their
posts would be if they won their seats.
</P>
<P>
   Glenn told delegates he would be the first black Republican man
in Congress since Reconstruction representing the deep South if he
won his race. Johnson said she would be the first Republican woman
from Long Island to ever be elected to Congress.
</P>
<P>
   The cornerstone of Glenn's platform is growth and employment.
The 31-year-old president of a non-profit economic development
organization that he founded says what the rural, second
Congressional district desperately needs is jobs. He believes he
can and will develop that job growth by mixing and talking
frequently with constituents and promoting economic development.
But he also said he sees the reality of the GOP'S new willingness
to welcome people like him.
</P>
<P>
   ``The news flash here is that it's not easy and it takes time,''
said Glenn, who is from Cusseta. ``It seems to be OK to be a black
Republican these days. You don't see a lot of them.''
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone is quick to believe this new GOP message. What the
party is attempting to do is take into account U.S. Census
predictions that minority Americans will shortly represent the
majority of Americans, said Dr. Ron Walters, director of the
African American Leadership Institute at the University of
Maryland. The party wants to reverse the unfriendly tone some say
was set by former House Speaker Newt Gingrich, R-Ga., Walters said.
Mostly, the party wants votes, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that people of color are being used by the Republican
party for a political obligation,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Still others claim that many African-Americans have always been
conservative in their philosophy. People making this argument point
to church-going traditions and entrepreneurship often seen in
mostly black communities around the country. They say this concept
should not be so difficult for people to grasp.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Chappell, a black Republican delegate from Atlanta, said
his turnaround came during his growing-up years in the Los Angeles
area. He had a great aunt who cleaned houses for a living, but
saved her pennies, listened to classical music, enjoyed the piano
and opera, and vacationed in Palm Springs, all things that Chappell
and the public in general did not associate with black people back
in that era. In fact, Chappell said, his family made fun of this
great aunt.
</P>
<P>
   ``As I got older and went to college, I found out she was the
one who was right,'' Chappell said.
</P>
<P>
   Chappell insists that the Republican Party has not been cruel to
minorities in its insistence at abolishing affirmative action, as
many Democrats have argued, but rather, wants people to take pride
in themselves.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you've been raised as a Democrat, all you know are the
Democratic virtues,'' Chappell said. ``Now it's about high-tech.
It's about having our own businesses.''
</P>
<P>
   Nora Reese, a black Republican alternate delegate from Warner
Robins, said the self-help message continually drummed by the GOP
is something she would like to see in her county, where poverty has
beaten down many in the African American community. She said she
would like to see her fellow African-Americans in middle Georgia
break away from their dependence on government-subsidized housing
and public assistance.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a Reagan Democrat,'' said Reese, 40. ``I switched in '86.
I felt that my community had been too dependent on big government
for social needs.''
</P>
<P>
   George Bush speaks to this, Reese said.
</P>
<P>
   ``His thing is he does not want to leave anyone behind. His
youth excites me. His message is coming from the heart,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
