<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-31 20:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8743 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-CANADA-MEDIA-ART-760(     07-31 0824
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CANADA-MEDIA-ART-760(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CANADIAN TV NETWORK BUYS MUCH OF BLACK'S NEWSPAPER EMPIRE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Canada, N.D.)  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By JAMES BROOKE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MONTREAL _ Making a bold bet on the future braiding of
television, newspapers and the Internet, Canada's second-largest
private television network announced plans Monday to buy about half
of the country's larger daily newspapers from Conrad Black, the
international press lord.
</P>
<P>
   In the largest media deal in Canadian history, CanWest Global
Communications Corp., a company that started 20 years ago with a
North Dakota television station, is to pay $2.36 billion for
dominant dailies in eight of Canada's 10 provinces. Black is to
gain a seat on the CanWest Board and to become the second-largest
shareholder, after the family of the company founder, Israel H.
Asper.
</P>
<P>
   ``The borders are gone, we have to grow,'' Asper, Global's
chairman, told a news conference Monday, comparing his acquisition
to Tribune Media's recent purchase of The Los Angeles Times. ``We
don't intend to be one of the corpses lying beside the information
highway.''
</P>
<P>
   Black said in a statement that his company, Hollinger Inc.,
``believes this intimate association with a highly successful
telecaster built by an entrepreneurial spirit compatible with
Hollinger is the best possible assurance of the strength of the
newspaper franchises.''
</P>
<P>
   In the political realm, the newspaper ownership change could
affect Canada's growing conservative movement. Black, an outspoken
press baron, placed his free-market stamp on some of the nation's
most influential editorial pages. During the recent leadership race
of the new conservative party, the Canadian Alliance, his National
Post newspaper seemed, to some readers, to be the movement's
official newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast, Asper, who runs his national television network
from his hometown of Winnipeg, Manitoba, has long been seen as a
low profile social democrat, running the provincial branch of the
Liberal Party for five years in the 1970s. Canada does not have
laws barring the ownership of newspapers and television stations in
the same media market, and the Liberal Government of Jean Chretien
is not expected to place regulatory barriers in the way of the this
merger.
</P>
<P>
   ``It looks as if the unapologetic conservative, Conrad Black,
has surrendered the reins,'' Chris Dornan, director of Carleton
University's journalism school, said Monday from Ottawa.
</P>
<P>
   Black's sale seemed to be primarily motivated by his crushing
debt load, $1.6 billion. Under the deal, CanWest will assume
responsibility for about $460 million in Hollinger debt.
</P>
<P>
   In the first half of this year, Canada's print media suffered a
psychological body blow as most of the nation's newspapers were put
up for sale, either by Black or by Kenneth R. Thomson. Thomson,
chairman of the Thomson Corp., clearly said that he wanted to
invest deeper in electronic information services. Two weeks ago,
Thomson completed the sale of his 49 American newspapers, for $2.44
billion. Thomson is trying to sell five of his Canadian newspapers
and has said he will retain ownership of the Globe and Mail of
Toronto.
</P>
<P>
   Black has sent mixed signals about newspapers. In April, he said
he wanted to sell his Canadian weeklies and smaller dailies. But
with Monday's announcement, he is selling newspapers that dominate
some of Canada's most important markets, including The Ottawa
Citizen, The Montreal Gazette, The Calgary Herald, The Edmonton Sun
and The Vancouver Province.
</P>
<P>
   If the sale goes through as expected in late September, Black,
55, will have tailored his press fiefdom to ownership of newspapers
in prestige cities that he cares about: The London Telegraph, the
Jerusalem Post and the Chicago Sun-Times.
</P>
<P>
   As for his pet Canadian project, The National Post, a
Toronto-based newspaper that in less than two years of existence
has added a muscular conservative voice to Canada's intellectual
debate, Black is to become the newspaper's chairman and Hollinger
is to retain management control. CanWest will own 50 percent of
this national newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   Monday, Black was on vacation in Europe and did not return
telephone calls left at his Toronto and New York offices. But in
his press statement, he seemed to expect criticism.
</P>
<P>
   ``There continues to be an audible body of opinion that holds
that the newspaper industry has entered a period of stagnation or
even decline,'' said Black, who is Hollinger's chairman. ``We
strenuously disagree with this and look forward to demonstrating
both the fallacy of this view and the enduring vitality of quality
newspaper assets intelligently managed and imaginatively linked
with other media.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Don Babick, The Post's publisher, declined in an interview to
predict how the marriage of electronic and print media would take
place, saying only: ``We are blending ourselves with a first-class
national telecaster.''
</P>
<P>
   The deal would greatly strengthen the news-gathering capacity of
CanWest, making it ``far and away the leading Canadian media
operation,'' said Dornan, a former television journalist. ``These
guys are going to have the robust newsrooms in every single market
in the country.''
</P>
<P>
   CanWest estimated that the combined strengths of the merged
operations could save the company up to $100 million a year.
</P>
<P>
   Little known in the United States, CanWest Global emerged in
recent years as Canada's third-largest television network, after
CBC, the government-owned network, and CTV, a privately owned
network. Bell Canada Enterprises, a major telephone company, wants
to buy CTV, largely with the idea of piping television and Internet
programs over Bell lines.
</P>
<P>
   From the small station imported 20 years ago from North Dakota,
CanWest grew by calling its collection of separately licensed
stations a ``system''rather than a ``network.'' Under Canadian
broadcasting laws, networks have to air a higher percentage of
Canadian-made programs than systems. American programs can be
bought for one-tenth the cost it takes to produce Canadian
programs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Global has been as studiously nonpolitical as possible,
producing as little Canadian content as possible and making as much
money as possible,'' said Vincent A. Carlin, chairman of the
journalism school of Ryerson Polytechnic University in Toronto.
``They were always failing the government guidelines, and always
getting a break.''
</P>
<P>
   After succeeding in Canada, Asper methodically expanded in the
industrialized English-speaking world, buying television stations
in Australia, Ireland, and New Zealand.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has taken some of the economics of a big box retailer and
applied them to small market media, where you buy American
programming in bulk and pass the savings along,'' said Paul W.
Taylor, who worked for Asper's first television station before
studying the company for a doctorate in communications. He said
Global was one of the largest buyers of American television
programming.
</P>
<P>
   Taylor predicted that with the merger, the newspapers would
strengthen television news programs, the newspapers would promote
the television entertainment shows, and that advertisers would get
larger audiences. He said: ``If you are a national advertiser, with
a single buy, you will be able to reach the eyeballs you want to
move your goods.''
</P>
<P>
   A few years ago, Global became a full network, complete with a
familiar red flash logo. Now, Asper and his son, Leonard, the
president of CanWest, may have decided that Canadian news is the
Canadian content that Canadians most want to see. By this
reasoning, Californians want to see California news, but not
necessarily California movies. Dornan said: ``News about ourselves,
journalism, current affairs programming, documentaries _ that's
what Canadians want to see.''
</P>
<P>
   The deal Monday suggested that Black might eventually play a
bigger role in Global. He has repeatedly entered companies by
holding a minority position, then has ended up wresting control. He
is to end up with 15 percent of the equity of CanWest, making him
the second-largest shareholder after the Asper family.
</P>
<P>
   But this time, Black may have to content himself with what the
deal offers: a seat on the CanWest board for himself and for
another Hollinger representative.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Asper family's control of the corporation is beyond his
reach,'' said Richard Siklos, author of ``Shades of Black: Conrad
Black and the World's Fastest Growing Press Empire'' (McClelland &AMP;
Stewart, 1995 ). ``It's an exit strategy for Black and these
newspapers. I wouldn't expect it to be a lasting partnership.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
