<P>
   POLITICAL NEWS (``p'' category)
</P>
<P>
   CVN-BUSH-STRATEGY (Columbus, Ohio) _ As the Republican National
Convention opens in Philadelphia, Karl Rove, the top strategist for
Texas Gov. George W. Bush, optimistically does his electoral
college math and concludes that Bush lacks only 44 of the 270
electoral votes needed to win the presidency in November. By
STEWART M. POWELL. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   CVN-GOP-ROUNDUP (Philadelphia) _ The first lady of Texas, Laura
Bush, and Colin Powell, the retired chairman of the Joint Chiefs of
Staff, are among the heavyhitters as the GOP showcases its interest
in children and education. Includes business on the floor. BY ALAN
BERNSTEIN.
</P>
<P>
   CVN-LAURA-BUSH (Philadelphia) _ The first lady of Texas, Laura
Bush, has been described as ``traditional,'' ``shy'' and
``reluctant.'' But after a year on the campaign trail, she's come
into her own as the candidate's wife focused on education. Despite
a small case of butterflies, she steps into the limelight as one of
the main speakers at the Republican National Convention's opening
night. By DAN FREEDMAN. (Already filed, will update.)
</P>
<P>
   CVN-POWELL (Philadelphia) _ Colin Powell, the retired chairman
of the Joint Chiefs of Staff, speaks to Republican convention
delegates about community and volunteer service. Powell, who is
widely believed to be Texas Gov. George W. Bush's choice for
secretary of state if the Republican candidate wins the fall
election, heads a national volunteer group. By ERIC ROSENBERG.
(Already filed, will update.)
</P>
<P>
   CVN-LEADERSHIP (Philadelphia) _ House Majority Leader Dick
Armey, House Majority Whip Tom DeLay and other congressional
leaders are keeping a low profile at the Republican convention.
With polls showing the congressional titans unpopular with most
Americans, the party appears to be limiting their appearances to
fund-raisers and parties for the GOP faithful. By GREG MCDONALD.
</P>
<P>
   CVN-TRASHTALK (Philadelphia) _ The Republicans have promised a
largely positive convention, even dropping the convention tradition
of devoting Tuesday night to slamming the opposition. They're
already cheating a little, of course, with occasional Democrat
bashing from the podium and lots from the floor. Still, the most
memorable moments in past conventions often have been the poison
barbs. BY JULIE MASON.
</P>
<P>
   CVN-BEDTIME (Undated)_ George W. Bush usually goes to bed at
9:30 p.m., and the most important speech of his life _ Thursday's
acceptance of his party's nomination _ is scheduled for 10 p.m. Is
he worried about his circadian rhythms? His aides addressed the
question today on the campaign trail. BY R.G. RATCLIFFE.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   PLAYBOY-GORE (Washington) _ The Catholic League urges Vice
President Al Gore to cancel a Democratic fund-raiser scheduled for
next month at the Playboy mansion in Los Angeles, saying it is
``offensive'' and ``disconcerting.'' Rep. Loretta Sanchez,
D-Calif., who Gore has tapped to be vice chairman of the Democratic
National Committee, has planned an invitation-only Aug. 15
reception during the Democratic convention for her political action
committee, Hispanic Unity, at the mansion of Playboy magazine
founder Hugh Hefner. By JUDY HOLLAND. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   CVN-MEANS-COLUMN (Philadelphia) _ Gov. George W. Bush's
convention here demonstrates the power of the southwestern branch
of the elite eastern cartel dominated by Wall Street moguls,
internationalists and the Republican country club set in which his
father and grandfather had their political roots. It is more
conservative and has a younger face, but it redirects the party
away from the social issues and toward familiar conservative
economic policy. By MARIANNE MEANS. (Already filed.)
</P>
