<SLUG> BC-GOP-DEMS-ADS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADS BY DEMOCRATS TIMED FOR GOP CONVENTION TARGET BUSH'S RECORD IN
TEXAS 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Democratic Party released two new 15-second television
commercials Monday timed to the opening of the Republican National
Convention in Philadelphia that attack the Texas record of Gov.
George W. Bush, the Republican's presidential nominee, on health
care and the environment.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCER
</P>
<P>
   Democratic Victory 2000.
</P>
<P>
   ON THE SCREEN
</P>
<P>
   Both spots open with a shot of confetti and red, white and blue
balloons floating above a convention hall. In the commercial on
health care, a map of Texas with a bandage slung around the
Panhandle appears. In the commercial on the environment, the same
map is shown, only with fumes billowing from the Panhandle as if
from an industrial smokestack. Both close with the words, ``For the
facts, visit www.texasunderbush.com.''
</P>
<P>
   THE SCRIPT
</P>
<P>
   In the spot titled ``Texas Children,'' the narrator reads:
``Tonight in Philadelphia, you'll hear a lot about `leaving no
child behind.' Meanwhile, back in Texas, George W. Bush opposed
health coverage for 200,000 more children. The state ranked second
to last in children with health insurance. Get the facts.''
</P>
<P>
   In the spot titled ``Environment,'' the narrator reads:
``Tonight in Philadelphia, you won't hear a lot about `the
environment.' Maybe that's because back in Texas, George W. Bush
appointed a chemical company lobbyist to enforce the environmental
laws. Houston is now the smog capital of the U.S. Get the facts.''
</P>
<P>
   ACCURACY
</P>
<P>
   On health care, it is true that Bush fought for a plan in 1999
that would have excluded 200,000 of the more than 400,000 children
eligible for the federal Children's Health Insurance Program. But
the Legislature insisted on the more expansive plan, and Bush
signed the bill. It is also widely accepted that Texas has more
uninsured children than any state other than Arizona. The Bush
campaign contends that the number of uninsured children is
increasing four times faster nationwide than in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   On the environment, Bush's first appointee to the Texas Natural
Resources Conservation Commission was a former Monsanto executive,
Ralph Marquez, who was also vice chairman of a chemical trade group
that did lobbying. And according to preliminary statistics from the
Environmental Protection Agency, Houston surpassed Los Angeles last
year for having the most days that exceeded the agency's smog
standards. The Bush campaign says it has significantly reduced
industrial air pollution and toxic releases since 1995.
</P>
<P>
   SCORECARD
</P>
<P>
   Polls suggest that Bush has been adept at reaching out to
centrist swing voters on education and health care, traditionally
strong issues for the Democrats. The two new advertisements are
part of a broader effort by the Democrats to stop Bush's march
toward the center by portraying Texas as suffering an array of
social maladies and the governor as beholden to the rich and
powerful. But Vice President Al Gore has been making those attacks
for several weeks, and Bush continues to receive relatively high
marks for his leadership skills and policy positions in the polls.
</P>
<P>
   _ JAMES DAO
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
