<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CVN-TRASHTALK-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOP DISCARDS VENERATED TRADITION: TUESDAY NIGHT TRASH TALK 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JULIE MASON 
c.2000 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ There's something missing from the Republican
National Convention this year, a certain venerated tradition
discarded like political dross by a kinder and gentler GOP.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday night trash talk is gone, or so convention planners
hope.
</P>
<P>
   Long a staple on the second night of the convention, highly
partisan zingers historically have provided some of the most
memorable, occasionally disastrous, moments of otherwise
forgettable political conventions.
</P>
<P>
   But this year, in a larger effort to put a new and friendlier
face on the Republican Party and its presidential ticket,
convention officials are jettisoning the smack for a more upbeat
message of unity.
</P>
<P>
   ``The delegates do enjoy the trash talk because these are your
longtime, hard-core Republican Party stalwarts,'' said Cathy
McConn, a Texas delegate and national committeewoman. ``At the same
time, I think we're getting a fresh look for the party, and one
that's more appealing.''
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday night, verbally vivisecting the other side will be
replaced as the evening's entertainment by a message on ``Strength
and security with a purpose: Safe in our homes and in the world.''
</P>
<P>
   On attack night in 1996, Republican U.S. Sen. Kay Bailey
Hutchison of Texas famously noted that President Clinton had
``high-taxing, free-spending, promise-breaking, Social
Security-taxing, health care-socializing, drug-coddling,
power-grabbing, business-busting, lawsuit-loving, U.N.-following,
FBI-abusing, IRS-increasing, $200 hair-cutting, gas-taxing,
over-regulating, bureaucracy-trusting, class-baiting,
privacy-violating, values-crushing, truth-dodging,
Medicare-forsaking, property-rights-taking, job-destroying
friends.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, partisan screeds are hardly the exclusive purview of
Republicans. Former Texas Gov. Ann Richards' best-remembered mortar
shot was delivered on savage-the-Republicans night at the 1988
Democratic National Convention.
</P>
<P>
   ``Poor George,'' Richards said of former President Bush. ``He
can't help it. He was born with a silver foot in his mouth.''
</P>
<P>
   Both those speeches were delivered on key nights before huge
national audiences. At this convention, however, what scant traces
of Democrat-bashing can be found are so far not happening on prime
time.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, on Monday some of the lesser constellations in the
Republican galaxy delivered a few pointed barbs at Democrats during
a sparsely attended afternoon convention session.
</P>
<P>
   ``After eight years of scandal, of tax increases, of
disappearing nuclear secrets, of military decline, of partial birth
abortions and of liberal federal judges, the American people want
new leadership in Washington,'' said Don Stenberg, Republican U.S.
Senate candidate from Nebraska, offering some of the day's most
heated invective.
</P>
<P>
   The party platform this year also is lightening up on the
partisan rhetoric. In 1996, the GOP platform mentioned President
Clinton 153 times.
</P>
<P>
   This year, writers were admonished to keep the focus on Bush and
his plan for America's future. As a result, the new draft includes
two mentions of Vice President Al Gore, apparently by accident.
</P>
<P>
   Texas delegates, among the most recorded and scrutinized on the
convention floor, said they like the new magnanimity. Several said
that reaching out without slashing reflects the style of Gov.
George W. Bush.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's kinder and gentler, but I think it's also designed to
show that we have the confidence to do it without resorting to the
same old parlor tricks,'' said Paul Bettencourt, the Harris County,
Texas, tax assessor-collector attending the convention as an
alternate.
</P>
<P>
   Fort Worth delegate James Borchert, absorbing the mild swats
featured in the afternoon speeches, said the party's lack of rancor
is a welcome respite from the politics of nastiness.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a good idea to keep it positive,'' Borchert said. ``It
will improve people's perception of politics.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXXXXEND OF STORY
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
