<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-CORRUPTION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SENIOR CHINESE OFFICIAL SENTENCED TO DEATH
</HEADLINE>
 By CRAIG S. SMITH   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SHANGHAI, China _ China sentenced a former central government
official to death Monday for taking almost $5 million in bribes,
the highest-profile case yet in the country's marathon
anti-corruption drive.
</P>
<P>
   The former official, Cheng Kejie, who until April was one of 19
vice chairmen of the National People's Congress under its chief, Li
Peng, would be the most senior Chinese official executed for
corruption since 1949, when the Communists took control.
</P>
<P>
   Cheng was found guilty of taking bribes while he ran the Guangxi
Zhuang Autonomous Region, a poor, mountainous province bordering
Vietnam and populated largely by ethnic minorities, including the
Zhuang people. Cheng is a Zhuang, China's largest ethnic group
after Han Chinese.
</P>
<P>
   Cheng, 67, has 10 days to appeal his sentence, but such appeals
are rarely successful. On March 8, the former vice governor of
Jiangxi Province was executed for corruption almost immediately
after losing his appeal. Executions in China are carried out by
pistol shot to the back of the head.
</P>
<P>
   The anti-corruption drive, which has been in operation for two
years, is the Communist Party's latest effort to shore up its
credibility as its ideological foundations crumble, and the
country's best and brightest abandon Marxism to make money.
</P>
<P>
   The hybrid economy, in which the state owns most assets but is
relaxing control over how those assets are used, has given
officials huge opportunities for graft. Many economists believe
that corruption is unbeatable as long as the system gives officials
the use of state assets without making them responsible for those
assets' economic viability.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem can't be solved by just punishing some people,''
said He Qinglian, an independent economist and outspoken social
critic, ``because this system itself breeds corruption.''
</P>
<P>
   In Cheng's case, he and his mistress amassed $4.7 million,
primarily from kickbacks on land deals and in return for granting
development contracts between 1992 and 1998. There is no open
bidding process for such transactions and officials like Cheng have
the power to dole out land rights or development contracts as they
see fit.
</P>
<P>
   Many Chinese are cynical about the party's drive against
corruption, which is seen as selective because graft is so endemic.
China's news media are forbidden to investigate anything more than
petty consumer-related corruption cases. Newspapers are regularly
told not to write about even well-known corruption cases, or told
to limit coverage to dispatches from the central government's New
China News Agency.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. He advocates giving the media freer rein in investigating
corruption and allowing nongovernmental organizations to act as
watchdogs. Otherwise, the government will never successfully root
out corruption from within its own ranks, she argues. Instead, the
Communist Party has tightened control of the media and punished
people like He, who was recently demoted.
</P>
<P>
   There has been almost no state media coverage, for example, of
the country's biggest ongoing corruption case, which centers on the
smuggling of hundreds of millions of dollars in firearms, cars and
crude oil through the southeastern port of Xiamen. The case has
reportedly implicated 200 people, including Xiamen police officers,
bankers and customs agents, and the former wife of a Communist
Party Politburo member. She has denied any wrongdoing.
</P>
<P>
   According to widespread rumors, the case also implicates Gen. Ji
Shengde, the former head of the army's intelligence department and
the son of one of China's most vaunted revolutionary leaders.
</P>
<P>
   Ji was identified by a Chinese-American businessman, Johnny
Chung, as the source of funds used for donations to the Democratic
National Committee in 1996. But, as with much unofficial news about
China, the reports that Ji has been arrested and is awaiting trial
come from Hong Kong news organizations, which often rely on
unsubstantiated rumor from the mainland.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
