<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-BRIEFS-$ADV06-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRAVEL NOTES AND NEWS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, August 6)  
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Virgin Atlantic Allows Incoming Cellular Calls
</P>
<P>
   Virgin Atlantic Airways says passengers can now receive calls
made to their cellular telephone number during flights.
</P>
<P>
   Passengers get a card with a magnetic strip and an
identification number from their cell phone service. Swiping the
card at the phone at the passenger's seat and entering the
identification number activates the service, which is provided by
the BT Aeronautical division of British Telecommunications.
</P>
<P>
   Callers who dial the individual's cell phone number will have
their calls routed to the telephone at the Virgin passenger's seat.
There is no extra charge to the callers, but the passenger will pay
a per-minute fee of $8 for incoming calls and $9 for outgoing
calls.
</P>
<P>
   This Skyphone Mobile Connect is available only for cell phones
using GSM, the dominant cell phone technology outside the United
States. Virgin Atlantic said that it eventually expected to expand
the service to American-style cell phones.
</P>
<P>
   Another airline, Air Canada, said that in October it will make
it possible for passengers on its Boeing 767's to use their laptops
to gain access to the Internet and get and send e-mail messages.
After six months, it will decide whether to expand the service,
which is provided by Tenzing Communications of Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   Grand Lakeside Lodge Expanded in Ontario
</P>
<P>
   Deerhurst Resort, a luxurious lakeside 425-room hotel in the
Muskoka region of Ontario, a two-and-a-half-hour drive north of
Toronto, has opened for this season after a $12.3 million
expansion.
</P>
<P>
   The new owners, Massachusetts Mutual Insurance Co., acquired the
late 19th-century resort in 1998 and spent 18 months adding a
102-room wing, a grand ballroom and a solarium-enclosed swimming
pool near Peninsula Lake. A floor-to-ceiling stone fireplace
dominates the new lobby.  &QC; In the adjoining bar, slate floors and
intricately milled, lodge-style woodwork echo the building's new
stone and timber facade. Eclipse, the newest of Deerhurst's three
restaurants, offers views of Sunset Bay from a wraparound porch.
</P>
<P>
   Summer diversions at the resort include kayaking, canoeing,
sailing and tennis; winter guests can cross-country ski on the
800-acre property. There are two 18-hole golf courses, including
Deerhurst Highlands, with dramatic shifts in terrain that include a
30-foot rock wall on one hole.
</P>
<P>
   Once the preserve of wealthy American industrialists _ one
stretch along Lake Muskoka is called Millionaire's Row _ the
Muskoka region is known as much for its cottages and lavish summer
estates as for its 1,600 lakes, sheer granite cliffs and maple
forests.
</P>
<P>
   Rooms at Deerhurst range from $88 to $225, at $1.47 Canadian to
the U.S. dollar; multiroom suites cost as much as $463. For
information and reservations, (800) 461-4393.
</P>
<P>
   Discord in Fiji Islands Alters Cruise Schedules
</P>
<P>
   As Fiji struggles to establish a new government, cruise lines
remain concerned about the safety of some of the country's ports.
Fiji has been in turmoil since mid-May, when indigenous rebels,
objecting to leadership by people of Indian descent, seized
government officials and held them hostage until July 13.
</P>
<P>
   Crystal Cruises has decided to scratch a scheduled Sept. 6 stop
at Suva, the capital of Fiji, during a 20-night voyage aboard the
Crystal Harmony that leaves San Francisco for Sydney on Aug. 22.
The ship will be at sea on the 6th and substitute a call at the
Isle of Pines in New Caledonia on Sept. 7.
</P>
<P>
   The Seabourn Sun of Seabourn Cruise Line, originally scheduled
to call at Suva on Oct. 13 during a 14-night cruise out of Sydney
that begins Oct. 3, will also bypass Fiji for now. The line will
call at Port Vila in Vanuatu instead. The Seabourn Sun, however, is
still scheduled to call at Lautoka, Fiji, on the west coast of the
main island, during a 13-night cruise from Sydney beginning Oct.
17.
</P>
<P>
   Peter Deilmann Cruises still intends to have its ship the
Deutschland call at Suva for 24 hours on Sept. 4 during an 18-night
voyage from Papeete, Tahiti, to Sydney that begins Aug. 25.
</P>
<P>
   Oakland Star Gazing
</P>
<P>
   Amateur astronomers and other sky watchers will have a new West
Coast spot to stargaze from when the Chabot Space and Science
Center, an 86,000-square-foot facility in the hills of Oakland,
Calif., opens Aug. 19. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   While the center covers a broad range of sciences, the focus is
on astronomy and space exploration. An observatory complex houses
8- and 20-inch refractor telescopes (the bigger the telescope, the
clearer the view) that were relocated from the center's former
facility. A new 36-inch reflector, one of the largest public
telescopes in the country, will be installed sometime next year. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Live and recorded star shows will be presented in a 240-seat
planetarium equipped with one of the world's most advanced star
projectors, capable of creating more than 9,000 points of light
using fiber optics. The inaugural show is ``The Soul of the
Night,'' a 35-minute presentation featuring constellations, the
Milky Way, laser graphics and a musical soundtrack. A separate
210-seat, dome-screened theater will be used for a changing
selection of 70-millimeter films.
</P>
<P>
   In the galleries, visitors can walk through full-size mockups of
International Space Station modules and learn about planetary
landscapes and meteorites. One exhibit recreates the Earth's
changing atmosphere, oceans and continents through a 3-D device
called a Hologlobe, on permanent loan from the Smithsonian
Institution.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The center is at 10000 Skyline Boulevard. Admission $8, $5.50
ages 65 and over and 4 to 12; separate planetarium or theater
tickets are $8.75, $6.50 seniors and children. Combination tickets
including either the planetarium or theater are $14.75, $11 seniors
and children; tickets including both are $19.75, $15.50 children. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   There is no charge for the telescopes, which are positioned by
staff members and are open to the public on Friday and Saturday
evenings. Information: (510) 530-3480; www.chabotspace.org.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
