<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZMAGS0801-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    'New economy' workers gain attention of political campaigns
 &HT;    By Tom Walker
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA - Democrats and Republicans are reshaping their
doctrines in this year's presidential campaign to appeal to ''new
economy'' workers, says Business Week (Aug. 7). Many of these
workers are ``economically conservative, socially tolerant swing
voters who live in suburbia.''
</P>
<P>
   Affluent ``new prosperity'' workers now account for one-third of
all registered voters _ a rapidly growing slice of the electorate.
What's more, the confluence of Information Age productivity and the
record nine-year economic expansion has transformed Campaign 2000.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tax cuts and culture wars have receded as issues,'' Business
Week says. ``Education, health care and concerns about keeping the
high-tech boom chugging along have zoomed to the top.''
</P>
<P>
   End of `dot-com' magic
</P>
<P>
   This may be the first ''new economy'' presidential campaign, but
90-year-old management guru Peter Drucker says the ``dot-com''
phenomenon that came with it probably ``is over.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Many of these Internet start-ups were not start-ups of
business, at all. They were just stock exchange gambles,'' Drucker
tells ''new economy'' magazine Business 2-0 (Aug. 22). ``If there
was a business plan, it was just to launch an IPO (initial public
offering) or be bought _ not to build a business.''
</P>
<P>
   Shocking investments
</P>
<P>
   Electric-utility stocks are surging, according to Barron's (July
31). Utilities should post strong earnings because the still-sound
economy is generating such robust demand that there are power
shortages in many areas. The outlook is particularly bright for
companies such as Atlanta-based Southern Co., the investment weekly
says.
</P>
<P>
   The downside of renewal
</P>
<P>
   Harlem, the epicenter of African-American culture, is getting
more like Mickey Mouse and Starbucks than Billie Holiday and Duke
Ellington, says Inc. Magazine (August). That's because of an
economic development boom that is bringing large, outside
corporations into the famed Manhattan neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   After years of poverty and neglect, Inc. says Harlem may now be
facing the kind of uncontrolled growth that will crowd out many
small, homegrown businesses unable to compete.
</P>
<P>
   Worth mentioning...
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  The problem with making automobiles more fuel efficient is
``the green car paradox.'' As Forbes (Aug. 7) columnist Peter Huber
explains it, the goal of fuel efficiency advocates is reduced
energy consumption. But he says ``more supply-side efficiency means
lower-cost energy, which means more consumption, not less.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Gross sales of the 100 biggest black-owned businesses in
America have risen from $473.4 million in 1972 to $16.03 billion in
1999, an increase of more than 3,000 percent, Black Enterprise
(August) says in its 30th anniversary edition.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  What'll it be if you're a small-business owner: voice mail,
e-mail, fax, phone or all of the above? Atlanta bimonthly
Competitive Edge (August) offers advice on how small firms can cope
with the options available.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ALSO INSIDE: The August issue of Esquire magazine features
female Olympic hopefuls and a profile of the owner of Southern
Voice, a regional gay newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
