<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOP-BUSH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`HONOR AND INTEGRITY' IS BUSH'S APPLAUSE LINE
</HEADLINE>
 By ALISON MITCHELL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLUMBUS, Ohio _ He rarely mentions President Clinton in his
stump speeches these days, and his aides are constantly pointing
out that the Republican convention will not be devoted to bashing
the Democrats. But as Gov. George W. Bush marches toward his
coronation in Philadelphia, it is clear that the president is not
far from his mind.
</P>
<P>
   Even as he hits the high notes about family and faith, Bush's
pointed subtext in his five-day, six-state ``Renewing America's
Purpose'' tour is President Clinton and the saga of Monica
Lewinsky. On Monday, as he does at the end of almost every speech,
he raised his hand high and made his ritual pledge.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to conclude by telling you,'' he said, ``that when I
put my hand on on the Bible that day in January of 2001, I will
swear not only to uphold the laws of the land, I will swear to
uphold the honor and integrity of the office to which I have been
elected.''
</P>
<P>
   As usual, the statement proved his biggest applause getter at a
rally Monday morning at the University of Dayton and again at the
statehouse here in the afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans have been running against Clinton's character for
years, often to see their efforts boomerang. But Bush does it more
subtly than some Republicans. And polls show that while Americans
are content with the economy, they are concerned about values and
the moral state of the nation and the Bush campaign hopes to
capitalize on that discontent.
</P>
<P>
   ``He talks about restoring the honor and integrity to the White
House,'' said Karen Hughes, Bush's spokeswoman. ``I think that's
something that the American people talk with him about at almost
every stop and he does talk about the need for that and I think
that's something people are looking for in this election.''
</P>
<P>
   She took umbrage at the idea that his words amounted to shots at
Clinton. And she disavowed the warm-up speakers at Bush's rally in
Cincinnati on Sunday who struck the same anti-Clinton themes less
subtly than Bush. A radio talk show host spoke about the ``filth
and degradation of Clinton-Gore'' while the mayor of Blue Ash,
Ohio, Jim Sumner, asked, ``Are you ready to have your daughter
serve as an intern?''
</P>
<P>
   Hughes said, ``Governor Bush hopes that the Republicans across
the country will join with him in helping to raise our political
discourse to a higher level.''
</P>
<P>
   She said that in his speech to the convention on Thursday night,
Bush ``will needle his opponents a little but he will treat them
with respect. He will not engage in the kind of trash and burn
attack style politics that we have become so sick of out of
Washington.''
</P>
<P>
   Her words illustrated a basic point and counterpoint of the
campaign. While Democrats have gone on the attack against Cheney
and his record of votes in Congress, the Bush campaign responds
with attacks against attacks, clearly hoping to reinforce the
perception of Vice President Al Gore as running a negative
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   The Gore campaign says the Republicans are counterattacking
because they are ``wrong on the issues.'' Douglas Hattaway, a
spokesman for Gore said, ``An informed voter is their worst
nightmare.''
</P>
<P>
   Hughes countered: ``Let's point out a vote where Dick Cheney
voted to increase funding for Head Start by 16 percent. Al Gore
voted no. Now, should we run an ad claiming Al Gore's against Head
Start?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-31-00 2024EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000731.0407 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-31 20:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8761 &Cx1f; tad-z
r s BC-FBC-GAFOOTBALL0801-CO     07-31 0816
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-GAFOOTBALL0801-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    16 Georgia players disciplined in phone scandal
 &HT;    By Mark Schlabach
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATHENS, Ga. - The Georgia Bulldogs on Monday suspended seven
football players one game each and nine others were disciplined for
their unauthorized use of a university long-distance access code.
</P>
<P>
   The suspended players include starting defensive tackle Richard
Seymour, defensive end Charles Grant and middle linebacker Kendrell
Bell. Reserve running back Kenny Bailey, tight end Robert Brannon,
cornerback Decory Bryant and linebacker Tony Gilbert also were
suspended one game for charging more than $50 worth of phone calls
using UGA Athletic Association code.
</P>
<P>
   Under penalties recommended by the NCAA, the players must repay
the charges and sit out one of the first two games. Georgia may
withhold four players from the Sept. 2 opener against Georgia
Southern, and then have three sit out the Sept. 9 game at South
Carolina, or vice versa.
</P>
<P>
   ``The conduct of these players was inappropriate and is a
violation of NCAA rules,'' Georgia coach Jim Donnan said in a
statement. ``We did discover the violation, promptly notified the
Southeastern Conference and the NCAA, and conducted a very thorough
investigation. The players understand their mistake and are willing
to take responsibility for it.''
</P>
<P>
   Donnan declined additional comment.
</P>
<P>
   Nine additional players also made unauthorized calls, but the
totals were less than $50. Players who made calls totaling $25 to
$50 will have to pay restitution and serve 30 hours of community
service; players with totals of less than $25 will serve one hour
of community service for every dollar charged and repay the school
for the calls.
</P>
<P>
   ``I made a mistake, but part of being a man is admitting your
mistakes, paying for the mistakes, and learning from them,'' said
Seymour, an All-America candidate this season. ``I'm prepared to do
that and, at the same time, apologize for the problems I've
caused.''
</P>
<P>
   The players could still face punishment from the university's
Student Judiciary. ``We will work with the athletic department on
this but . . . these are students first and athletes second,'' said
Owen Barber, UGA's director of Student Judicial Services.
</P>
<P>
   According to documents obtained by the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution, an athletic department employee became aware
of the charges in March while completing a routine audit. The calls
were made between July 1999 and December 1999, and were charged to
a long-distance access code that was once issued to a receptionist
at Georgia's Butts-Mehre Heritage Hall.
</P>
<P>
   When the employee was promoted to an assistant in athletics
director Vince Dooley's office, the access code was never
deactivated so part-time employees could still use it. More than
$1,700 in calls were made during that period, and Georgia's
investigation found that football players accounted for more than
$900 in calls. Most of the calls were placed from a telephone in
the team locker room.
</P>
<P>
   ``In discussing it with some of the student-athletes, we
couldn't determine where it started,'' said Hoke Wilder, Georgia's
assistant athletics director for compliance. ``But it was passed on
from athlete to athlete.''
</P>
<P>
   Wilder said that some of the athletes told him they were unaware
they were using a Athletic Association calling card.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there were some cases where the players really didn't
know what they were using,'' he said. ``They thought they were
using a calling plan.''
</P>
<P>
   Georgia reported the violations to the SEC in March. Initially,
athletics director Vince Dooley recommended the suspension of
Bailey and Brannon for the first half of the Georgia Southern game
and that the rest of players serve community service. Bailey and
Brannon were the only active players who had totals of more than
$100.
</P>
<P>
   SEC commissioner Roy Kramer agreed with those self-imposed
penalties, but the NCAA's Subcommittee on Student-Athlete
Reinstatement ruled that they weren't adequate. The committee
recommended that players with totals of more than $50 be suspended
for one game.
</P>
<P>
   On April 24, Dooley sent a letter to Julie Roe Sumner, director
of reinstatement for the NCAA. Dooley wrote that Georgia ``strongly
believes the penalty of a one-game suspension for a first-time
violation to be excessive'' for players with less than $100 in
charges.
</P>
<P>
   Dooley also asked that the suspensions be served over the first
three games, instead of two, because it ``would create a severe
hardship on the defensive unit and, of course, penalize the team.''
</P>
<P>
   But Wilder said Monday that the NCAA will no longer allow
schools to stagger the suspensions over more than one game. In the
future, suspensions will be served on the first scheduled game
after penalties are levied.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
