<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-31 20:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8762 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i BC-ISRAEL-PERES-ART-2TAK     07-31 0939
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-PERES-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN DEFEAT, PERES RETAINS REPUTATION FOR COURTLINESS
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photos _ NYT1,6 _ are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By JOHN F. BURNS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ At the moment on Monday when the announcement of the
first of the two Parliament votes for Israel's next president made
it all but certain that he had lost the last big battle of his
60-year political career, Shimon Peres, Nobel Prize laureate,
three-time prime minister and one of the most enduring
standard-bearers for Middle East peace, remained in character.
</P>
<P>
   The result, with 60 votes for Moshe Katsav, the Iranian-born
immigrant who was the eventual winner; 57 votes for Peres, and
three blank ballots, brought loud groans, slumped shoulders and
moist eyes among members of Parliament backing Peres to become
Israel's eighth president.
</P>
<P>
   But Peres himself, aware that Katsav's second-ballot victory was
a virtual certainty, merely thrust his hands in the trouser pockets
of his dark suit, leaned back against the parliamentary chamber's
rear wall, and talked studiedly with friends.
</P>
<P>
   The vote came as Prime Minister Ehud Barak survived a
no-confidence vote mounted by opponents of his peace effort.
</P>
<P>
   To those who know Peres, the 76-year-old statesman appeared on
Monday to be nursing a deep private hurt, but in his manner and
words he did nothing overt to bely his reputation for courtliness.
</P>
<P>
   The outcome cannot have been made easier by the fact that the
54-year-old Katsav was a relatively obscure figure who had never
held an office more weighty than tourism minister in the last Likud
government and whose name would almost certainly draw blanks in the
chancelleries and palaces around the world where Peres' visits have
become a fixture.
</P>
<P>
   ``At this moment, the only thing I have to say is to
congratulate Moshe Katsav on his election as president,'' Peres
told reporters who engulfed him as he left the Parliament chamber
after the second ballot had confirmed Katsav as the victor by 63
votes to 57. ``I wish him success and all the best.''
</P>
<P>
   With no further word for the clamoring throng, Peres turned and
walked away, this time almost certainly into retirement from a
political career whose glittering pinnacle was the 1993 Nobel Peace
Prize that Peres won for his role in the Oslo peace accords, along
with Yasser Arafat, the Palestinian leader, and Yitzhak Rabin, the
prime minister who was assassinated in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   For all his honors, Monday's defeat, denying Peres a five-year
term in an office with mainly ceremonial powers in a magnificent
presidential mansion in the heart of Jerusalem, will almost
certainly mark him as one of Israel's great losers.
</P>
<P>
   Even before the vote, the talk in the Parliament hallways was of
whether Peres could shake off the image he has acquired over the
last two decades by losing four of five elections for prime
minister, as well as leadership battles within the Labor Party that
relegated him to runner-up status first behind Rabin and then Ehud
Barak, the current prime minister.
</P>
<P>
   While many factors appeared to have combined to secure Katsav
his victory, including the last-minute defection of at least a half
dozen members of Parliament who had assured Peres of their support,
there was no doubt that the perennial loser tag followed him into
the vote, and may even have been what sunk him.
</P>
<P>
   ``His reputation as a loser may have been something that
influenced some Knesset members,'' said a chagrined Yosef Lapid, a
68-year-old Parliament veteran whose six-member centrist Shinui
Party supported Peres.
</P>
<P>
   The vacancy in the presidency came with the resignation three
weeks ago of Ezer Weizman, a 75-year-old stalwart of the old
political elite, who quit mid-way through a second term after state
prosecutors issued a report harshly criticizing him for financial
improprieties.
</P>
<P>
   When the day began, accounts in many of Israel's newspapers
depicted the presidential vote as a virtual formality. The papers
said Peres' election was more or less assured by his towering
reputation as a peacemaker and as a major figure in Israeli
governments since the 1960s and by his association, almost from
boyhood, with most of the major political icons of Israel's
history.
</P>
<P>
   An eve-of-vote Gallup poll in the newspaper Maariv had Peres as
the popular choice for the post, 63 percent to 20 percent for
Katsav, with 17 percent undecided. But political power in Israel
has been shifting for years from the old Ashkenazi elite with roots
in eastern Europe that the Polish-born Peres personifies, and the
newspaper forecasts appeared to have underestimated how far the
process has gone among the elected members of Parliament.
</P>
<P>
   In Katsav, whose first home in Israel was a tent, the Parliament
chose a man who is not widely known even inside Israel. His home is
in Qiryat Malakhi, about 30 miles south of Tel Aviv, one of the
working-class ``''development towns'' that many prosperous Israelis
consider deeply unfashionable.
</P>
<P>
   But precisely because of this modest background, Katsav has a
strong chance, as president, of turning himself into an icon for
many of Israel's six million people. When he is sworn in on
Tuesday, he will be the first Israeli president from the underclass
of Sephardic immigrants who flooded into the country from the
Middle East and north Africa in the 1950s. He will also be the
first successful presidential nominee from Likud, the right-wing
party with broad working-class and Sephardic support.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   In the days before the vote, Katsav campaigned aggressively
among the right-wing and ultra-Orthodox splinter parties with
strong Sephardic support that control crucial blocs of votes in the
120-seat Parliament, tapping the alienation among the have-nots of
Israeli society.
</P>
<P>
   But in victory, he struck a conciliatory note, saying he
intended to ``lock up'' his political views during his five-year
term and work as ``the loyal representative of all Israeli
citizens, of all strata, of all sections, of all classes.''
</P>
<P>
   His speech brought loud cheers from his supporters, and smiling
handshakes from several Labor Party members, including Dalia Rabin,
daughter of the assassinated prime minister and a herself a member
of Parliament.
</P>
<P>
   The big question facing Israelis after the presidential vote was
what impact it would have on the peace efforts. After the huge
gains made in Israeli-Palestinian negotiations that have been
virtually synonymous with Peres, the march to a final peace pact
faltered last week after 15 days of negotiations at Camp David.
</P>
<P>
   One theory about Peres' loss on Monday was that right-wing
lawmakers could not stomach the prospect of Peres as president,
notwithstanding the office's limited powers. Unquestionably, one
thing that drew backing for Katsav from a block of 22 right-wing
members belonging to Shas, a religious party that broke with
Barak's coalition before Camp David, and to United Torah Judaism,
another right-wing Orthodox group, was Katsav's widely-advertised
opposition to some of the concessions that Barak offered Arafat at
Camp David.
</P>
<P>
   In Knesset hallways, some wondered if the erosion of support for
Peres might have been engineered by Barak, who has had uneasy
relationship with his predecessor as Labor Party leader. But
Barak's aides said the Labor bloc had voted solidly for Peres, and
Barak himself appeared upset.
</P>
<P>
   But an even stronger factor than calculations about the peace
process appeared to have been played by the growing political power
of Sephardic parties, and of political groups that draw their
support from among the one-million Russian immigrants who have
arrived in the past two decades. Many of these groups, including
Shas, want changes that would chip away at the secular nature of
Israeli politics, and tighten religious laws and practices.
</P>
<P>
   Haim Shibi, parliamentary correspondent for Yedioth Ahronoth,
the country's most widely-circulated newspaper, said that the
country was witnessing one of its most significant political
watersheds.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are calling the shots now, whether you like it or not,''
he said, referring to Sephardic Jews.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
