<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-31 20:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8765 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-GOP-DELIGHT-NYT &LR;      07-31 0760
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOP-DELIGHT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ONLY HAPPY FACES IN THIS MAGIC KINGDOM 
</HEADLINE>
  
(Earlier skedded as GOP-INTERNET)  By RICK LYMAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Republican Party elders Monday declared on every channel that
would listen that they intended to put a new, more moderate face on
the Republican Party.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ours will be a different kind of convention for a different
kind of Republican,'' Andrew Card, co-chairman of the convention,
told Fox News.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a new GOP, it's a new time in America,'' the party
chairman, Jim Nicholson, told MSNBC.
</P>
<P>
   For the most part, they seemed to pull it off. As far as the
television cameras could find, none but happy faces inhabited the
Magic Kingdom, otherwise known as Philadelphia's First Union
Center.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're thrilled to be here and my husband and I are excited
about the future of the party,'' Cindy McCain, wife of Gov. George
W. Bush's chief primary opponent, told MSNBC. ABC had outfitted
McCain with a videocamera and was planning to regularly show
portions of her ``video diary'' during the five-day gathering. Not
surprisingly, much of the early footage featured her husband.
</P>
<P>
   Many of those who had been on the short-list to be Bush's
running mate told interviewers Monday that they were delighted _
delighted _ that the former Wyoming congressman Dick Cheney had
been chosen in their stead. As Sen. Fred Thompson of Tennessee and
others noted, Cheney was ``popular on both sides of the aisle,''
despite what he called efforts by Democrats to paint him as a
right-winger in recent days.
</P>
<P>
   Surfing is not much fun when there are not any waves.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately, several Republican candidates for the House and
Senate were given a few minutes in front of the nearly empty
chamber during the morning session (at times, it looked like the
crowd for a baseball game between two last-place teams on a drizzly
day), and a few of them seemed to have trouble sticking to
don't-bash-the-Democrats rule.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Rod Grams, running for re-election from Minnesota, told the
Republican delegates that they were part of ``the party of
opportunity, not the party of oppression.'' The party of
oppression? Lighten up, dude. Didn't he get the memo?
</P>
<P>
   The result was that reporters and commentators _ there are
15,000 journalists representing 1,700 news organizations _ were
forced to look elsewhere for drama, or to supply it in the
traditional way, by arguing among themselves. Others just tried a
different tack.
</P>
<P>
   CBS gave us a tour of the Main Line, the ritzy suburban stretch
west of the city, and said it had ``discovered'' that the district
was named for the rail line that runs through it. CNN talked about
the party scene. Apparently, the hot ticket on Sunday night was a
bash put on by the Bloomberg News Service, although another
headlined by Rep. J.C. Watts Jr., in which the Oklahoman sang with
the Temptations, was a close second. Monday night, the place to be
was the party for John McCain.
</P>
<P>
   C-SPAN hopped on a yellow school bus rented by demonstrators to
take a ``reality tour'' of Philadelphia, a visit to the tent city,
where out-of-town protesters were encamped, and through the city's
poverty-stricken neighborhoods. ``We are not experiencing a booming
economy and our poverty is getting worse every day,'' said Tazmin
Cheshire of the Kensington Welfare Rights Union, who acted as tour
guide.
</P>
<P>
   Fox News' World Wide Web site decided that the best way to cover
the demonstrators was to offer a daily ``slightly opinionated
column'' that poked fun at them, describing one group of marchers
as ``a writhing mass of several thousand malcontents.'' Not to
worry, though, America. ``It was all good fun,'' the column
decided. ``More like a carnival parade in Trinidad than a political
march.''
</P>
<P>
   On the British Broadcasting Corp.'s Web site, the Republican
gathering was not even one of the five top stories, relegated
instead to a digest at the bottom of the opening page (under
``Americas''). But it did offer a helpful guide on ``how to elect a
U.S. president.'' Done in the form of a baseball diamond, the
cheeky devils showed how a candidate must move from first base
(primaries), to second (the convention), third (campaign) and
finally home (Election Day).
</P>
<P>
   The BBC also offered a Republican convention quiz, asking when
the last time was a GOP ticket didn't include a Bush or a Dole
(1972) and when a woman first addressed a Republican convention
(1920). A score of 9 out of 10 meant ``you should get a job running
a political campaign.''
</P>
<P>
   Great. What's second prize?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
