<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-31 20:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8772 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-GOP-MESSAGE-ART-NYT &LR;      07-31 1063
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOP-MESSAGE-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
15,000 REPORTERS AND NOT A SHRED OF NEWS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo NYT13 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By PETER MARKS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ Jeff Zucker, the executive producer of NBC News'
convention coverage, wanted a live interview Monday night from the
First Union Center with one of the event's most highly sought-after
guests: George P. Bush, the telegenic, 24-year-old nephew of the
Texas governor.
</P>
<P>
   But to NBC officials' dismay, the Republicans turned down the
request, and not because young Bush is camera-shy. No, Zucker
contended, NBC was spurned because it was only covering the
proceedings in prime time Monday night on its cable channel, MSNBC,
which garners substantially lower ratings than the broadcast
network.
</P>
<P>
   The fact that ABC News was to provide a full hour and CBS News
at least 30 minutes of prime time coverage starting at 10 o'clock
Monday night knocked NBC down a few notches in the interview
pecking order, Zucker said. ``It's a game,'' he observed. ``They
have divvied out guests accordingly.''
</P>
<P>
   Later in the day, after a reporter inquired about Zucker's
complaint, the Republicans informed NBC that they could have the
young man on the air, and spokesmen for both NBC and the convention
sought to play down the episode. But the incident was instructive
about a reality of the media hierarchy here: Cable television may
provide more coverage, but the broadcast networks are still the
kings.
</P>
<P>
   That enduring truism is reflected in the way the convention
program is structured: virtually all the major speeches this week,
from those of Laura Bush and Gen. Colin L. Powell on Monday night
and continuing with Sen. John McCain and Elizabeth Dole on Tuesday,
the vice presidential nominee, Dick Cheney, on Wednesday and Gov.
George W. Bush on Thursday, are to take place between 10 p.m. and
11 p.m. That just happens to be the hour on every night that one or
more of the over-the-air networks will be covering the Philadelphia
proceedings live.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything is geared for the 10 to 11 o'clock hour,'' said Tom
Hannon, the political director of CNN. ``They're obsessed about
getting their message across in the 10 to 11 hour, and that is
their driving concern. People say that the conventions are for
cable, but as far as the parties are concerned, the conventions are
for the most eyeballs they can get.''
</P>
<P>
   The conflicting aims of the parties and the networks have led to
an odd standoff: as the conventions become ever more scripted and
ever less newsworthy in the strictest journalistic sense, the
networks become ever less interested in covering them. Yet the
conventions vie for the network cameras as vigorously as ever, and
the networks still show up in vast numbers, but with scaled back
prime-time coverage plans.
</P>
<P>
   According to Thomas E. Patterson, a Harvard professor of
government and the press, convention coverage on ABC, NBC and CBS
has declined from 50 total hours in 1976 to 12 hours in 1996, and
this year, he reported, that total may dwindle to 10 hours. He told
a conference here on Saturday, sponsored by the Harvard's Joan
Shorenstein Center on the Press, that if the networks were to
abandon the conventions altogether, the audience for the gatherings
would be cut in half. In 1976, the conventions had an average
prime-time rating of 28; by 1996 it had dropped to about 17.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Patterson did not place all the blame for the erosion of
network attention on the broadcasters. ``The parties need to loosen
up a bit, and allow for a little more conflict and spontaneity,''
he said, adding that recent polls show that ``those who might be
expected to watch said it's the lack of suspense that's keeping
them away.''
</P>
<P>
   Even keeping awake could be a problem. Zucker, who has been
detached from his normal producing duties at the ``Today'' program
to oversee the party gatherings, seemed a bit underwhelmed Monday
at the prospect of supplying four nights of coverage, principally
on MSNBC, the network's cable channel. NBC will also cover the
proceedings on its flagship channel on Wednesday and Thursday
nights.
</P>
<P>
   At a meeting Monday afternoon in an air conditioned trailer,
Zucker and Elizabeth O'Connell, the news executive producer of
special events, gave out assignments to the correspondents for the
night of cable coverage _ David Bloom was to answer viewers' e-mail
from the floor, for example _ and presented an overall theme for
the three-hour program, the ``soft side of the Republican party.''
</P>
<P>
   Reporters were to fan out and report on the conservative bent of
the delegates and try to score interviews with more coveted
Republican luminaries. (George P. is widely considered a
significant ``get,'' as are the presumptive nominee's parents, who
were to appear on MSNBC Monday night.)
</P>
<P>
   Still, the event does not exactly enthrall Zucker. ``I'm not
sure it's not a colossal waste of time and money,'' he said after
the meeting.
</P>
<P>
   Zucker is not a lone voice. Many in the news business, both in
print and broadcast, mutter to one another about the gargantuan
size of the press corps here _ 15,000 plus, or more than 7 for
every delegate _ and the puniness of the story. ``Great drama and
great TV and great journalism are built on conflict,'' Zucker said.
</P>
<P>
   The Republicans seem unfazed about the lack of drama. Their big
worry is to keep up the pace and make sure they exploit the
television moment. On the convention floor Monday, Ed Gillespie, a
Bush adviser who had been working on the convention for six weeks,
was preoccupied with the endless logistics. Between cell phone
calls placed to find one of the evening program's participants, he
explained that the schedule was merely the most rational use of
time.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of the featured speakers are in the 10 o'clock hour,'' he
said, ``and that's the point at which the most people will see the
Republican convention.''
</P>
<P>
   Hannon said that from his vantage point, Republican operatives
are not about to start worrying about filling that hour with
breaking news. ``These guys are in the business of knowing who
their audience is,'' he said, even if their focus on packaging may
be overblown. ``Bob Dole lost in '96,'' he added, ``but they still
think they had a great convention.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-31-00 2046EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
