<HEADER>
A8777 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-GOP-CONGRESS-NYT     07-31 0955
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOP-CONGRESS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
29 CONGRESSIONAL CANDIDATES MAKE THE MOST OF THEIR LUCKY MINUTE 
</HEADLINE>
  By ADAM CLYMER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ Even though many Republicans worry more about
losing the House than capturing the presidency, Gov. George W.
Bush's team has given the House campaign effort no prime time for
the week and indeed just half an hour of throw-away time at midday
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, in the feel-good atmosphere of this convention, nobody from
the congressional wing of the Republican Party could be found to
complain that Bush was putting his election ahead of theirs.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Thomas M. Davis III of Virginia, chairman of the National
Republican Campaign Committee, said the un-prime time was just
fine, even though the House Republicans hold the majority by a
margin of just 13 seats.
</P>
<P>
   ``The governor is going to be our spokesman,'' Davis said,
adding that for Republicans, ``Bush is a great brand name.''
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, 29 Republican congressional candidates made the
most of their allotted 60 seconds on stage. John Kline, challenging
a Democratic incumbent in the suburbs of St. Paul, Minn., walked
quickly onstage, promised to ``return control of our schools to the
parents of Minnesota and take it away from the bureaucrats of
Washington,'' and dashed off.
</P>
<P>
   Back home in Eagan, Minn., Kline's supporters watched carefully
as a television camera recorded their cheers at Joe Sensor's
Restaurant. It made the noon news. Kline said later, ``It was great
for those of us to be showcased, a big help.''
</P>
<P>
   The Senate, where retaining Republican control seems more
likely, despite the death of Sen. Paul Coverdell of Georgia, which
put the majority's margin at eight, also got a midday half-hour
Monday, under the control of its campaign chairman, Sen. Mitch
McConnell, R-Ky.
</P>
<P>
   Recalling his home state's Kentucky Derby, McConnell valiantly
tried to persuade the half-empty hall that there was more than a
first-place bet on Bush on the board; there was a trifecta, a wager
in which the bettor picks the first three finishers. ``Winning a
trifecta takes real skill,'' McConnell said. ``The true measure of
victory in addition to George W. Bush winning the White House is
keeping a Republican Senate and a Republican House.''
</P>
<P>
   He conceded, ``It isn't going to be easy.''
</P>
<P>
   McConnell put six candidates forward. There were two embattled
incumbents, Spencer Abraham of Michigan and Rod Grams of Minnesota,
and four competitors for open Senate seats, Reps. Bob Franks of New
Jersey and Bill McCollum of Florida, former Rep. John Ensign of
Nevada and Attorney General Don Stenberg of Nebraska.
</P>
<P>
   And McConnell alluded to one other high-profile race, the one in
New York. He said, ``We're going to elect a Republican to the
United States Senate who is actually from New York.'' But he never
said the words ``Rick Lazio.''
</P>
<P>
   Later McConnell said in an interview that Lazio had been offered
one of the five-minute speaking slots for Senate candidates but had
``turned us down.'' In New York, Lazio's staff said he had better
uses for his time. He had no public campaign schedule Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio was mentioned _ but by his would-be successor in the
House, Joan Johnson, the town clerk in Islip. N.Y., who said she
would ``follow in the footsteps of Rick Lazio.'' With an acute
sense of timing, Johnson, who is black, said, ``I will make
history.'' And as the audience expected her to predict that she
would become the first black Republican woman in Congress, she said
instead, ``I will be the first Republican woman ever elected to
Congress from Long Island.''
</P>
<P>
   Lazio's opponent was also mentioned _ by Franks, who said his
own Democratic opponent, Jon Corzine, was ``pushing Hillary Rodham
Clinton's failed health care plan.''
</P>
<P>
   Most of the candidates sought to tie themselves to Bush, none
more forcefully than Stenberg. Stenberg complained that his
argument before the U.S. Supreme Court defending his state's ban on
a particular type of abortion need not have been unsuccessful. ``If
I had one more conservative justice,'' he said, ``Nebraska's ban on
partial-birth abortion would have been upheld. President George W.
Bush can make that happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Some House candidates had highly individualistic messages _
sometimes intended to distinguish them from their district's
general assumptions about Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   Former Rep. Dick Zimmer, hoping to unseat Rep. Rush Holt in
central and western New Jersey's 12th District, cited a ``strong
Republican legacy that the environment will be protected for
generations to come.''
</P>
<P>
   Mark Kirk, contesting an open seat in the Chicago suburbs, made
a point of saying, ``I do not agree with every tenet of our
platform.'' Several hours later he explained that he disagreed with
the Republican platform's positions against abortion and
gun-control.
</P>
<P>
   Others seemed to benefit from the speechwriting assistance that
the campaign staff had offered. ``Faith, family and freedom'' was a
central message for both Dunn Lampton of Mississippi and Chuck Yob
of Michigan.
</P>
<P>
   The lucky 29 seemed thrilled. Mark Nielson, challenging Rep. Jim
Maloney in southwestern Connecticut, said, ``They say everybody has
15 minutes of fame, and so I know it was only one minute, and
therefore I still have 14 left.''
</P>
<P>
   While the senators and would-be senators were given five
minutes, the House hopefuls and Rep. James Rogan of California, the
only struggling incumbent to receive stage time, may not have been
aware of the good training they were receiving with their one
minute. House members most often speak for only a minute, though
they get to revise and extend their remarks and make them look
longer in the Congressional Record.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
