<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRAZIL-FASHION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRAZILIANS AIM TO TRANSFORM BOOM IN FASHION INTO ECONOMIC
MOMENTUM 
</HEADLINE>
   By JENNIFER L. RICH   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAO PAULO, Brazil _ When the gurus of fashion came here from all
over the world a few weeks ago for a peek at MorumbiFashion,
Brazil's biggest and most prestigious fashion show, they were
wondering if this was the industry's next international capital.
</P>
<P>
   Brazil's burgeoning textile and garment industries are hoping
the answer is yes. But in a country still known largely as an
exporter of goods made with cheap manual labor, questions remain
about whether the Brazilians can transform this new international
attention into something sustainable.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now is the time for us to show to the world that we are
offering products of high quality, competitive price, good design
and beauty, and with all the characteristics of Brazil,'' said
Paulo Skaf, the president of the Brazilian Textile Association, a
trade group.
</P>
<P>
   One thing is certain: Brazilian fashion is hot. It started with
the meteoric success of a 19-year-old supermodel, Gisele Buendchen,
who was Vogue's model of the year in 1999. In four years, Buendchen
has landed on the cover of more than 250 magazines and paraded down
1,600 catwalks, bringing international attention to the concept of
``Brazilian-ness.'' Marking the trend in the United States: Bikinis
are shrinking and the caipirinha, the country's potent
lime-and-cachaca cocktail, is the drink of choice in some Manhattan
night spots.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, such Brazilian designers as Alexandre
Herchcovitch and Icarius are gaining cachet on the world fashion
circuit. Both have been asked to participate in the ready-to-wear
fashion week in Paris in October, while Herchcovitch has already
been seen on the catwalks of London. The confluence of the Gisele
phenomenon and the growing success of Brazilian designers abroad
has been called the Brazilian Moment in this country. But the
garment industry is working to make sure that the moment never
ends.
</P>
<P>
   ``Brazil is all about the sensual, tropical Latino, Carnival,
sports, women, sex,'' said Nelson Alvarenga Filho, the founder and
president of Brazilian label Ellus. ``It's entertaining, and people
always need a little entertainment. That will never go out of
fashion.''
</P>
<P>
   One look down the local equivalent of Madison Avenue _ Rua Oscar
Freire in Sao Paulo's posh Jardins neighborhood _ would indicate
that Brazil is on the right track. Boutiques selling both Brazilian
and international fashion are springing up all along the most
exclusive 10-block stretch, and have spilled into adjacent avenues.
</P>
<P>
   But while Sao Paulo may be turning into the fashion capital of
Latin America, Brazil still has a long way to go to break out of
its mold as a source of cheap manual labor to become an
international fashion exporter. Only a handful of the most well
known Brazilian designers have landed in stores in the United
States and Europe so far, and the $18 billion industry still
remains dominated by small businesses that lack the resources to
expand and export.
</P>
<P>
   ``Exports of garments over the past years have been around $200
million, which is about zero point nothing of world trade,'' said
Leda Oliveira, the director of foreign trade at the Brazilian
Apparel Association. ``We plan to get to $1 billion by 2003 though.
Put that in writing, and I'll sign it.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the apparel association's first steps has been to
organize the country's small and medium-sized apparel businesses
into regional consortiums to attract more attention from national
and international buyers. The effort seems to be working. Aided by
a favorable exchange rate, garment exports were up 33 percent in
the first five months of the year, compared with 1999.
</P>
<P>
   The Brazilian Textile Association has sought to take advantage
of Brazilian fashion's popularity to strengthen the country's
textile industry. It has publicized plans by textile manufacturers
to spend more than $12 billion on updated machinery over the next
several years.
</P>
<P>
   The textile association is a co-sponsor of the MorumbiFashion
show, and in June it held the country's first annual Brazilian
fashion awards, with Buendchen receiving the award for model of the
year. The textile association is also organizing a show of
Brazilian designers in a not-yet-selected European city later in
the year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
