<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-31 20:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8780 &Cx1f; taf-z
s t BC-TRAVEL-OLY-SYDNEY-POR     07-31 1273
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-OLY-SYDNEY-PORTSTEPHENS-$ADV06-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AT PLAY WITH SMILING DOLPHINS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, August 6)  
(Editors: 2nd take is a 236-word box containing details about
accommodations) 
 By JOHN TIERNEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   When we headed up the Australian coast for Port Stephens, a
resort two and a half hours north of Sydney, we had expectations:
miles of lovely and empty beaches, magnificent sand dunes, famously
clean waters inhabited by trophy fish and sociable dolphins. It was
all there as promised. But there was also something not on our
list: rain.
</P>
<P>
   It did not seem to be on anyone else's list, either. The locals
never stopped professing amazement at our bad luck. No one could
remember the last time they'd had five straight days of rain. Why,
there hadn't been a drop of water in the two months before we
arrived last March. ``If only you'd come another week,'' they kept
saying. Their sympathy got more irritating every day.
</P>
<P>
   We still managed to have a good time, and that is no small
tribute to the charms of Port Stephens. Rain is the ultimate test
of a beach resort, not to mention a family's bonds. On wet days you
can't help wondering why you've spent so much time and money to
commune with nature. What exactly is so great about nature? But
there are enough other attractions to keep everyone content on the
shores of Port Stephens.
</P>
<P>
   It's a huge bay (two and a half times the size of Sydney's
harbor) with tranquil waters connected to the ocean by a narrow
opening in the headlands. The northern shore is green and largely
uninhabited. The southern shore is a peninsula that's becoming a
popular spot for resorts and retirement homes, although it is still
undeveloped compared with other coastal resorts near Sydney (or
with some on the United States Eastern Seaboard _ imagine Nags Head
a few decades ago). The attractions include a couple of tiny
amusement parks, a wildlife preserve with koalas, and a zoo where
children can pet koalas and kangaroos.
</P>
<P>
   My wife, Dana, and I and our 11-month-old son stayed at one of
the better resorts on the southern shore, the Peppers Anchorage.
The resort is a collection of well-appointed town houses
overlooking a marina, with a small beach on the bay. The placid
waters are popular for water skiing and sightseeing excursions. A
few miles away, on the ocean side of the peninsula, is a national
park with hiking trails and beaches with pounding surf.
</P>
<P>
   The most spectacular sights are the Stockton Beach Sand Dunes,
which stretch for 20 miles along the seaside coast. They extend a
half mile inland and include dunes 10 stories high. In dry weather
you could easily imagine you were in the Sahara, especially if you
were on one of the camelback tours. We chose other forms of
transportation. Dana went across the dunes on a horse and enjoyed
the challenge of the occasional sinkhole. When the inevitable rain
came, she took consolation in being fashionably wet in the long
oilskin coat provided by her guide. It billowed in classic Outback
style as she emerged from the dunes for a gallop along the deserted
beach.
</P>
<P>
   I climbed the dunes on a quad bike, which has four balloon tires
and looks like a riding mower on steroids. The instructor, Tony
Burrell, lectured on safeguarding the environment and leaving no
traces of our rides. He also demonstrated the perils of the dunes,
like driving off the edge of a sand cornice or allowing your bike
to overturn on a slope. If you didn't follow the rules, he was fond
of repeating, ``your machine will roll over and you will be
squashed.'' It was a little frightening at first _ some of the
slopes appeared just about vertical _ but once you learned to rev
your way up and brake your way down, it was utterly exhilarating to
cruise through the dunes. Lawrence of Arabia never had it so good.
</P>
<P>
   If you prefer to let someone else do the driving, there's the
Bushmobile. It carries 24 passengers and is emblazoned with the
motto of Dieter Hartmann, its German operator: ``Ve get U there
when others would not dare!'' Hartmann migrated to Australia as an
engineer and then decided to live in the bush with his wife and
another couple. They built a cabin deep and subsisted for several
years on food they hunted and gathered themselves. ``I was the
guinea pig for the plants we found,'' he says. ``I would eat it,
and if I didn't get sick, then we knew it was safe.''
</P>
<P>
   Upon returning to civilization, Hartmann applied his engineering
skills to the Bushmobile, a converted military transport vehicle
with a 20-speed transmission, enormous tires and a hydraulic winch
for extricating itself from quicksand that sometimes forms in the
dunes. Hartmann's tour included dramatic descents in the Bushmobile
as well as a chance to do some sandboarding _ the dune equivalent
of sledding. He took us into Tin City, a shantytown in the dunes.
He also conducted what he called a magic carpet ride, which
consisted of bouncing across the sand on a mat dragged behind the
Bushmobile.
</P>
<P>
   High-speed rides are something of a theme in the Port Stephens
area. You can whiz down a half-mile-long winding metal chute at
Toboggan Hill Park (your toboggan, incidentally, has a brake). You
can go out on a jet boat called Foxy that hits speeds of 40 knots
and does 180-degree turns. With a little luck, you can watch
Australian and American military pilots in action by visiting
Fighter World, a museum that's next to a working military airfield.
It was raining so hard the day we visited that no planes were
flying, but we at least got to peer into the cockpits of the
fighters on display and listen to war stories from the Australian
Air Force veterans who run the museum.
</P>
<P>
   The rain didn't deter the fishermen competing in an annual event
called the Billfish Shootout at the Peppers Anchorage marina. They
were busy hauling in sharks and marlins to be weighed on the dock.
The talk of the marina was a world-record blue marlin that had just
been caught. Even amateurs can arrange to catch their dinner (and
have it superbly cooked at the hotel) on one of the charter boats.
</P>
<P>
   Or you can merely observe the marine life in what local boosters
like to call the Dolphin Capital of Australia. About 80 dolphins
have settled in the sheltered waters of the bay, and their
performances are sustaining a small fleet of dolphin-watching
boats. Our first evening in Port Stephens we boarded an elegant
yacht, the Winifred, and sailed off in the hope of watching the sun
set over a sea of leaping dolphins. Then the clouds came. The
captain took us into a sheltered cove and assured us that we could
still see dolphins in the rain.
</P>
<P>
   ``They'll come out as long as the water's calm,'' he said, ``and
we're sheltered here from the wind in every direction except the
northwest.'' Then the wind began blowing from the northwest. No
dolphins.
</P>
<P>
   The next evening we tried a different dolphin-watching
operation, a catamaran called Imagine. It was even rainier than the
previous evening. We clutched wine glasses and stared glumly into
the murky twilight waters. Suddenly, 20 yards off starboard, there
was a fin; then 10 yards away, another one. Then a whole shining
dolphin body crested, just feet away.
</P>
<P>
   We were surrounded by at least 20 dolphins, cresting and
flipping their bottle noses, their sinuous bodies nimbly keeping
pace with the racing pontoons of the catamaran. They were playing
with us! We cheered and waved into the wet wind, and managed to
convince ourselves that they were smiling back at us. And for a
moment we convinced ourselves that the rain didn't matter, either.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   Port Stephens is about two and a half hours north of Sydney by
car. For information, contact the Port Stephens Visitor Information
Center, Post Office Box 435, Nelson Bay, 2315 Australia; (61-2)
4981 1579, fax (61-2) 4984 1855, www.portstephens.org.au.
</P>
<P>
   We stayed at what seemed to be the best lodging in the area, the
Peppers Anchorage; (61-2) 4984-2555; fax (61-2) 4984-0300
www.peppers.com.au/anchorage. Rooms start at $145 weekdays, $180
weekends (at $1.72 Australian to the U.S. dollar), with discounts
on longer stays. The sunny rooms have balconies overlooking a
marina. The staff was very helpful booking tours.
</P>
<P>
   Among boats offering dolphin cruises are the catamaran Imagine,
(61-2) 4984-9000, and the Surprise, with a veteran guide, Capt.
Pete Dawson, (61-2) 4982-0444. A two-hour trip is $11, $6 ages 4 to
12.
</P>
<P>
   Bushmobile tours ($16) depart from Anna Bay; (61) 500-55 00 66.
</P>
<P>
   For dune biking ($57), try Sand Safaris, in Williamtown; (61-2)
4965-0215.
</P>
<P>
   A 15-minute ride on the Foxy high-speed boat, Nelson Bay, costs
$16; (61-2) 4086-84421. Toboggan Hill Park, Nelson Bay, charges
$2.65 for a ride, $16.70 for six; (61-2) 4984-1022. Admission to
Fighter World, Williamtown, (61-2) 4965-1810, is $2.65, $1.75
children.
</P>
<P>
   Oakvale Farm and Fauna World, where you can pet a koala, is in
Salt Ash; (61-2) 4982-6222; $5.25, children $3. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
