<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-31 20:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8782 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-GOP-NC-ALA-YOUTHS-ART     07-31 0697
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOP-NC-ALA-YOUTHS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
  
 YOUNG DELEGATES WANT TO BE NEW FACE OF GOP  (ART ADV: Photo is
being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers can purchase
one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(Greg Retsinas is Raleigh Bureau chief for the New York Times
Regional Newspapers.) 
 By GREG RETSINAS    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ Josh Workman admits there have been times when he
would really like to go ``off the record.''
</P>
<P>
   The Banner Elk, N.C., college student is a delegate, after all,
at one of the biggest political parties of the year _ four days of
parties, dancing, night-owl concerts and schmoozing otherwise known
as the 2000 Republican National Convention.
</P>
<P>
   But Workman, at 19, is believed to be the youngest of the 2,066
delegates gathered here this week, a status that has earned him the
distinction of having an MTV camera crew follow him around day and
night for the entire convention.
</P>
<P>
   As Workman talked recently, he fiddled with a microphone clipped
to his shirt that is recording his every word.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, I went into my room and undid it,'' he said, referring
to the microphone. ``I needed to take a break.''
</P>
<P>
   He's not alone in his youthful status _ Joy Barganier, two
months older than Workman and a native of Fort Deposit, Ala., is
thought to be the next youngest delegate. The two represent an
emphasis by the GOP to put a youthful face on their party, and this
week's slate of convention festivities represent that. Nightly
parties that last into morning feature hip musical acts, and MTV is
just one of dozens of entertainment-related media outlets covering
the convention.
</P>
<P>
   For Workman, the MTV attention means special access to a host of
private parties and events that would normally cost hundreds of
dollars a ticket. He is scheduled to meet with George W. Bush when
he arrives at the convention later this week.
</P>
<P>
   Workman is now a rising senior at Lees-McRae College in Banner
Elk majoring in criminal justice and psychology. Politics is more
of a passion than a career goal, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's awesome and cool. I like to be here to show that young
conservatives exist instead of sending to Philadelphia a bunch of
50-year-old men and a bunch of millionaires who donate to the Bush
campaign,'' Workman said. ``Why not send a young guy?''
</P>
<P>
   Workman said he campaigned door-to-door for his delegate
selection, winning all but six votes of those cast in his
northwestern North Carolina district. His previous political
experience included volunteering on Lauch Faircloth's 1998 Senate
campaign and working for the N.C. College Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   Barganier is just as politically enthused as Workman, yet she's
glad that MTV is not chronicling her week. The two are about as
different as two teen-agers might be. Workman has spiked hair, an
earring and a tattoo of a maple leaf on his shoulder; Barganier is
reserved, proper and calls everyone ``Sir'' or ``Ma'am.''
</P>
<P>
   ``What's wrong with people my age is the MTV generation, the
radical, liberal propaganda that's put into their heads. Kids don't
know what's really going on, they just listen to what MTV tells
them,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike Workman, Barganier, a rising sophomore at Auburn studying
English, is a convention veteran. She has attended three as a guest
of her mother, Susan, who has been a delegate to three conventions.
</P>
<P>
   And in 1980 at the GOP convention in Detroit, Susan was pregnant
with Joy.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really neat that she can sit on the floor with me,'' said
Mrs. Barganier.
</P>
<P>
   Joy Barganier said the view is different as a participant than a
spectator. Her biggest thrill has been rubbing elbows with the
state's two U.S. senators, Jeff Sessions and Richard Shelby.
</P>
<P>
   Both Barganier and Workman said they often have to explain their
Republican affiliations to their college pals, many of whom are
apolitical. If their friends could get a taste of convention life,
they would be similarly hooked, the pair said.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of young people are not Republicans simply because their
parents are. I bet kids would agree with most of the party stuff if
they took the time to find out about it,'' Barganier said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
