<HEADER>
A8783 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-GOP-FUNDRAISING-NYT &LR;      07-31 0746
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOP-FUNDRAISING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMPANIES AID LAWMAKERS WHO WILL OVERSEE THEM 
</HEADLINE>
   By JOHN M. BRODER and DON VAN NATTA Jr.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ Reps. Michael Oxley and Billy Tauzin have brought
their cash-fueled competition for the chairmanship of the House
Commerce Committee to the Republican convention. And corporations
affected by the committee are betting on both men.
</P>
<P>
   At parties on Monday night and Tuesday financed by some of the
companies the committee regulates, Oxley of Ohio and Tauzin of
Louisiana will entertain lawmakers and lobbyists with rock 'n' roll
and zydeco music and stuff them with finger food and po' boys.
</P>
<P>
   Oxley, who leads the Subcommittee on Finance and Hazardous
Materials of the Commerce Committee, and Tauzin, who presides over
the telecommunications subcommittee, are in a race to see who can
raise the most money this year. Since the beginning of last year,
they have raised hundreds of thousands of dollars _ and given much
of it away to win the allegiance of Republican House members. The
Commerce Committee sits astride much of American industry, and its
chairman is one of the most powerful figures on Capitol Hill.
</P>
<P>
   The confluence of corporate money, political influence and
congressional power is one of the hidden motifs of this and all
modern political conventions. While the congressional leaders in
Washington are not being showcased during television prime time in
Philadelphia, their Beltway battles and intrigues have followed
them here.
</P>
<P>
   The Oxley-Tauzin contest provides the most striking example of
the phenomenon here this week, but other lawmakers are also using
the occasion to solicit special interest money, often from
industries they oversee. Scott Harshbarger, president of Common
Cause, a group that monitors campaign spending, said, ``People are
giving who have clear business before these committees.''
</P>
<P>
   Both Oxley and Tauzin have amassed enormous war chests for their
re-election campaigns this fall, and nearly all of the money comes
from corporate political action committees and individuals with
interests before the Commerce Committee, according to an analysis
provided by the Center for Responsive Politics.
</P>
<P>
   Tauzin has already raised $541,845 for his re-election bid, and
his leadership political action committee, the Bayou Leadership
PAC, has raised $49,234 since January 1999, Federal Election
Commission data shows. Tauzin has given away more than $43,000 of
his PAC's money to the election campaigns of his fellow House
members. Oxley does not have a leadership PAC.
</P>
<P>
   The receptions here span the spectrum of corporate interests.
Time Warner, Walt Disney, Universal Studios and Viacom are giving a
party for Rep. Mark Foley of Florida, chairman of the House
Entertainment Industry Task Force. It is one of the hottest tickets
this week, to be held on Wednesday at 10 p.m. at the Shampoo Night
Club.
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T bought martinis and cigars and Guinness provided the stout
for Rep. David Dreier of California, chairman of the House Rules
Committee at the Continental, a 50s-style diner jammed with so many
cigar-smoking lobbyists that 100 people who wanted to could not get
in. Limousines and town cars were double-parked outside on Market
Street.
</P>
<P>
   The Oxley and Tauzin receptions, expected to cost as much as
$500,000 each, are sponsored by companies with business before the
Commerce Committee. Oxley's party, on the old soundstage of
``American Bandstand'' and featuring entertainment by Frankie
Avalon, Chubby Checker and others, was sponsored on Monday night by
18 investment houses, insurance companies, accounting firms and
chemical industry associations.
</P>
<P>
   Tauzin's Mardi Gras event, to be held on Tuesday night, is
underwritten by ``a bunch of telecommunications and energy
companies,'' an aide to Tauzin said on Monday. The aide would not
name them.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday night, Sen. Trent Lott, the majority leader, had a
sock hop for himself and 1,500 ``friends.'' Lott and his wife,
Tricia, who wore a letter sweater and a poodle skirt, arrived in a
1959 Chevrolet convertible. Among the underwriters were AT&AMP;T,
International Paper, Union Pacific and Lockheed Martin.
</P>
<P>
   DaimlerChrylser put on a dual-purpose party, displaying its
latest models and paying tribute to Rep. J.C. Watts of Oklahoma,
chairman of the House Republican Conference. Watts joined The
Temptations on the stage of the downtown Convention Center for a
rendition of ``My Girl.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
