<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-31 20:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8784 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-LIBERIA-U.S.-NYT &LR;      07-31 1202
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LIBERIA-U.S.-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
2 AFRICAN NATIONS SAID TO BREAK U.N. DIAMOND EMBARGO 
</HEADLINE>
   By BLAINE HARDEN    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS _ American and British officials accused the
presidents of Liberia and Burkina Faso Monday of taking a personal
role in trading arms for diamonds in violation of a U.N. embargo.
The Americans and British also said the two presidents had helped
Sierra Leone rebels to continue fighting a brutal civil war.
</P>
<P>
   The American ambassador to the United Nations, Richard
Holbrooke, compared President Charles Taylor of Liberia to
President Slobodan Milosevic of Yugoslavia, who has been indicted
for war crimes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Taylor is Milosevic in Africa with diamonds,'' Holbrooke said
in an interview, contending that outsiders have been ``much too
passive'' in naming African leaders who foment war for personal
gain.
</P>
<P>
   ``Taylor is fueling the conflict in Sierra Leone for his own
benefit,'' Holbrooke said. ``He is threatening to destabilize west
Africa, and there is deep division in the region about how to deal
with him.''
</P>
<P>
   A British diplomat said Monday at a U.N. hearing on the role of
diamonds in the Sierra Leone war that that Taylor had personally
taken command of rebel forces fighting there against U.N.
peacekeepers and that he has in recent weeks sent arms to the
rebels and taken smuggled diamonds in payment.
</P>
<P>
   ``In effect, President Taylor has been directing strategy
meetings of the rebels,'' said the diplomat, Stephen Pattison.
</P>
<P>
   Pattison also made unusually specific allegations against
President Blaise Compaore of Burkina Faso, saying that in return
for diamonds Compaore has sent mercenaries from Burkina Faso to
fight with rebels in Sierra Leone against U.N. peacekeepers.
Compaore has repeatedly allowed airports in Burkina Faso to be used
for supplying the rebels with arms bought in Ukraine, Pattison
added.
</P>
<P>
   Diplomats from Liberia and Burkina Faso denied the allegations,
demanding that hard evidence be presented.
</P>
<P>
   Foreign Minister Monie Captan of Liberia categorically denied
that Taylor had been trading arms for diamonds this year, although
he acknowledged that ``in the past'' the president had dealt with
the rebels.
</P>
<P>
   Captan said Taylor was working for peace in Sierra Leone. In an
interview, he accused Holbrooke of making accusations against
Taylor to advance his campaign to become secretary of state if Vice
President Al Gore wins the presidency.
</P>
<P>
   Taylor, a former warlord who terrorized voters into electing him
in 1998, has played a singularly influential role in the making and
the unmaking of a crisis this year in Sierra Leone. Before rebels
there seized 500 U.N. troops in May and held them hostage, Taylor
was their principal ally in letting them smuggle diamonds and buy
arms. After the troops had been detained, Taylor's intervention
secured their release. The Liberian government, Captan said Monday,
had expected to receive international credit for its role in
defusing the crisis.
</P>
<P>
   But in mid-July, Thomas R. Pickering, Under Secretary of State
for Political Affairs, had a combative meeting with Taylor in
Monrovia. Pickering warned Taylor that unless his government
quickly halted its support for the Sierra Leone rebels, the United
States will invoke unilateral sanctions, including denying American
visas for Taylor and other Liberian officials and seizing their
assets in the United States, an American official said.
</P>
<P>
   At the meeting in Monrovia, Taylor acted defensively, denying
the allegations and demanding to be shown proof, the American
official said.
</P>
<P>
   That proof was not supplied, but an American official said
Monday that evidence includes photographs of trucks carrying arms
and supplies to Sierra Leone and electronic surveillance that shows
Taylor meeting with commanders of the rebels, known as the
Revolutionary United Front.
</P>
<P>
   In his testimony Monday, Pattison said Taylor recently ordered
an increase of diamond production in rebel-held areas of Sierra
Leone. ``Taylor has assured the RUF of his support and of increased
military aid, this has included supplies of arms, ammunition, fuel,
food and medicine,'' he said. ``These are regularly transported
across the Liberian border in trucks and occasionally in
helicopters.''
</P>
<P>
   After the peacekeepers were taken hostage in May, the Security
Council banned trading in Sierra Leone diamonds until a
certification regime could be set up. The diamond industry _ led by
De Beers, the world's largest trader _ has since moved to tighten
trading and toward branding diamonds to make provenance clear.
</P>
<P>
   Human rights groups have said, however, that there is no way of
knowing if the industry can police itself. In March, a scathing
U.N. report condemned the central diamond clearing house in Antwerp
for ``extremely lax controls'' in handling banned diamonds sold by
rebels in Angola.
</P>
<P>
   Holbrooke said that the Clinton administration now supports the
creation of a global certificate of origin system. It is not yet
clear how such a system would work. The U.N. embargo on diamonds
from Sierra Leone does not yet ban sales of diamonds exported from
Liberia. Industry experts say most of Liberia's diamond exports
originate in Sierra Leone. An American official said that Liberia
itself has the capacity to mine about $10 million of diamonds a
year, but that last year it exported about $300 million worth of
the stones.
</P>
<P>
   Pattison said that Burkina Faso has become a major player in the
export of smuggled stones from Sierra Leone. He said the best
recent estimate is that, in return for arms and other supplies,
about 60 percent of rebel-mined diamonds are moving from Liberia
and about 40 percent from Burkina Faso.
</P>
<P>
   Holbrooke said the Clinton administration hopes to persuade
American consumers to demand a certificate of origin that will
prove they are not taking home ``blood diamonds'' from Africa. ``I
hope that people buying a beautiful stone will start asking
questions and be sure not to buy unless they see a certificate of
origin,'' said Holbrooke.
</P>
<P>
   So far, American diamond consumers have shown little interest in
the provenance of the stones they buy, according to industry
experts and shop owners. Sales of diamond jewelry jumped 11 percent
last year, and De Beers had record worldwide sales of more than $5
billion.
</P>
<P>
   The president of Burkina Faso was also singled out in March for
violating a 1998 U.N. embargo to stop Angola rebels from using
diamonds to pay for their war. The U.N. report said Compaore sent
fuel to the rebels and received ``substantial contributions'' for
his political campaigns. A representative of Compaore's government
dismissed the charges.
</P>
<P>
   Anticipating that some African countries will respond to his
accusations as ``neo-colonialism,'' Holbrooke emphasized that he
was not making a ``universal condemnation'' of African leadership,
but only of some ``bad leaders.'' ``We should have been saying
these things a year ago,'' he said. ``We need to move past
perceptions based on race. This is not about race. This is very
difficult for the Africans because it means there has to be a
candid admission that some of the African leadership has failed its
people.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
