</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GERMAN-IMMIGRANTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GERMAN FAULTS SILENCE ABOUT ATTACKS ON IMMIGRANTS
</HEADLINE>
 By ROGER COHEN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BERLIN _ A renewed wave of anti-immigrant violence in Germany
has prompted Foreign Minister Joschka Fischer to suggest that a
silent majority may be abetting the crimes by not speaking out
against them.
</P>
<P>
   His statement, with its thinly veiled allusion to past German
passivity before the rise of rightist violence, reflected growing
concern in the government over an abrupt increase in such attacks.
Germany has more than 7 million foreigners but remains uneasy with
the idea that it is a ``land of immigration.''
</P>
<P>
   A bombing in Dusseldorf on Thursday that wounded nine
immigrants, six of them Jews, was followed by a number of attacks
over the weekend. The worst occurred in the eastern town of
Eisenach, where two African asylum-seekers were kicked, spat upon
and pursued by a group of neo-Nazi skinheads shouting ``Sieg
Heil!''
</P>
<P>
   The authorities on Saturday raided the home of a policeman in
Potsdam, near Berlin, after hate calls were traced to his number.
Officials found firearms, ammunition and anti-immigrant propaganda
similar to the cache recently discovered in the dismantling of a
rightist youth movement south of Dresden.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact that hatred of foreigners probably lies behind the
Dusseldorf attack should rouse us all,'' Fischer, a member of the
Green Party, said in a statement on Saturday. ``We have reached a
point where the majority of the population that has been silent up
to now can no longer remain silent.''
</P>
<P>
   Certainly Germany appears to face a quandary over its identity.
With great fanfare, the government on Monday handed over the first
of a planned 20,000 ``green cards,'' papers allowing skilled
foreigners to come here and work in computer jobs.
</P>
<P>
   It is the first time since Turkish ``guest workers'' were
admitted in the 1960s that Germany has formally invited immigrants
in this way, a tacit admission that it requires outside talent to
remain competitive in a global economy.
</P>
<P>
   But even as the door to legal immigration is pried open a
fraction, animosity toward foreigners seems to be rising. Heinz
Fromm, the president of the Office for the Protection of the
Constitution, a domestic intelligence service, expressed outrage
similar to Fischer's in a newspaper interview published on
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are being injured and killed,'' he was quoted as
saying. ``These groups keep blacklists, including the names of
well-known actors who are identified as Jews. Yet the population
does not seem to take all this too seriously. Society must
intervene or this development will damage the whole country.''
</P>
<P>
   The response Monday from the conservative Frankfurter Allgemeine
was furious. It published an editorial saying, ``Placing the entire
German population under suspicion is hardly the way to promote
reason.''
</P>
<P>
   Many Germans with no sympathy for rightist violence are troubled
by the large number of foreigners, particularly Turks, in the
country and by suggestions that Germany must embrace
multiculturalism. As a result, politicians have been generally
hesitant to broach the questions raised by Fischer.
</P>
<P>
   Since the fall of the Berlin Wall a decade ago, rightist
violence has become a fact of German life. It is rooted principally
in the east, where, since the collapse of the Communist state
there, youth unemployment has remained high, alienation widespread
and broad exposure to foreigners a novelty.
</P>
<P>
   ``There has been a virtually unbroken nationalist tradition in
the east of the country for decades,'' said Klaus Klott, a teacher
who worked for several years in the eastern town of Jena.
``Exposure to a multicultural society is something entirely new,
and in many instances it is violently resented.''
</P>
<P>
   What seems clear from the recent attacks is that even a decade
of German unity has not diminished this rightist and xenophobic
sentiment. In the last decade, more than 100 people have been
killed in Germany in xenophobic attacks.
</P>
<P>
   Fromm suggested that the spread of Internet sites full of racist
invective and the passivity of most Germans had in fact allowed the
anti-immigrant groups to spread their message.
</P>
<P>
   ``The perpetrators obviously think they will not face much
resistance from the community,'' he said. ``They even have the
feeling they are acting on behalf of the majority.''
</P>
<P>
   Officials close to Fischer suggested that the minister was
troubled by what he views as the post-Nazi German taboo surrounding
nationalist extremism and anti-Semitism. ``What is needed is more
open debate,'' one official said. ``An unhealthy silence has
descended.''
</P>
<P>
   The recent killing of a child by a pit bull prompted a far more
vigorous national debate over dogs than anything that emerged from
the killing on June 11 of an African immigrant, Alberto Adriano, by
a group of neo-Nazi thugs in Dessau.
</P>
<P>
   This point was made on Sunday in an unusually emotional
television debate that touched on the subject, in which Annette
Kahane, the director of a foundation that seeks to combat racist
violence, noted that no government minister appeared in Dessau
after Adriano's death or issued a statement on his behalf.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-31-00 2100EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000731.0421 </DOCNO>
