<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-31 21:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8786 &Cx1f; taf-z
s t BC-TRAVEL-OLY-SYDNEY-GUI     07-31 1433
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-OLY-SYDNEY-GUIDEBOOKS-$ADV06-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE BEST OF THE LATEST GUIDEBOOKS TO SYDNEY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, August 6)  
 By DEBBIE SEAMAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Spare me the spread of the bronzed, muscle-bound lifeguard and
show me something I may not know about before visiting Sydney, such
as the saltwater sea pools, built barely out of reach of the
breakers, at many of the city's ocean beaches.
</P>
<P>
   Guides to the host city of the 2000 Olympic Games are plentiful
at the moment, but the best go beyond being just visually
resplendent. Photos and graphics in these provide context, and are
illustrative and informative rather than merely decorative. I can
pardon the occasional close-up shot of a koala nibbling gum leaves,
for example, but it is a delight to see giraffes or elephants
against the backdrop of Sydney's skyline and harbor afforded by the
Taronga Zoo. I'm also more tempted to visit a museum by a visual
preview of a few of the works in its collection rather than a photo
of its facade.
</P>
<P>
   The Sydney guides I prefer also tell visitors intriguing things
they might miss, like what stages the Sydney Harbour Bridge was
built in and in what time spans, or tips about the different styles
of Aboriginal art. De rigueur, too, are detailed accounts of
excursions to nearby areas, like the majestic Blue Mountains about
65 miles to the west and the breathtaking juxtaposition of bush and
waterways in Ku-ring-gai Chase National Park about 19 miles to the
north.
</P>
<P>
   I'll pass altogether on the Sydney guides whose pages are
enlivened by little more than bold-face type or sporadic clumps of
color pictures.
</P>
<P>
   It's well worth spending the extra $5 to $10 for a thorough and
thoughtfully produced book.
</P>
<P>
   THE NATIONAL GEOGRAPHIC TRAVELER SYDNEY, by Evan McHugh. 271
pages. 1999. (National Geographic Society, $22.95.)
</P>
<P>
   As one would expect from the publisher, this handsome travel
guide is impeccably appointed with bold and relevant color art.
Even a relatively small photo in the Eastern Suburbs section places
picnickers not only in Nielsen Park but also under the canopy of an
outsize Moreton Bay fig tree, with the gables of Greycliffe House,
an 1852 residence that now houses the National Parks and Wildlife
Service office, visible in the background. Now, that's context! It
also has the most comprehensive section on the Olympic site as well
as an Olympic Survival Guide. (Don't forget the bottled water and
the aspirin!)
</P>
<P>
   Yet what really makes this one of the top two Sydney city books
is that Evan McHugh, a native Sydneysider, goes the extra mile to
provide the unexpected: a comprehensive section on Aboriginal art;
a section on where to view noteworthy artists' renditions of Sydney
Harbour; a short history of the area's shipwrecks.
</P>
<P>
   Toward the back there are miniportraits and profiles of Sydney's
principal wildlife _ most of the species charming, as the venomous
funnel web spider is noteworthy in its absence here. ( McHugh deals
with these and such other nasty creatures as sharks right up front
under the heading A Few Precautions.) My only disappointment is
that the hotel and restaurant listings, while succinct and
informative, could use a bit of the dazzling photographs that are
so prominent elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   DORLING KINDERSLEY TRAVEL GUIDES SYDNEY. 264 pages. 2000.
(Dorling Kindersley, $19.95.)
</P>
<P>
   I was happy to see a few interiors pictured among the
restaurants and hotels in this top-tier Sydney guide, then amazed
to see that the book's contributors were considerate enough to show
what your plate is liable to look like if you order, say,
char-grilled kangaroo fillets, Chinese Yum Cha dumplings,
freshwater crayfish or the classic Australian pavlova dessert of
meringue, cream and fruit. Likewise with beverages: It explains
with pictures as well as words the difference between a middy of
beer (10 fluid ounces) and the more daunting 15-fluid-ounce
schooner, among other gustatory guidelines.
</P>
<P>
   It's all in the details here. The segment on beaches _ and
Sydney warrants one of these _ shows the varieties of waves and the
level of swimming skills it takes to negotiate them. The
topographic map of Paddington indicates exactly where to glimpse
the terrace and gingerbread houses the neighborhood is famous for.
Close-up photographs and graphics allow readers to get accustomed
to the different currency before they arrive; sample a float from
the Gay and Lesbian Mardi Gras; look at size charts and see that an
Australian women's size 14 is equivalent to an American 12; learn
how to operate a pay phone, and how to spot an Australian
policeman. The menacing funnel web spider even makes a relatively
innocent appearance _ among the displays at the Australian Museum.
</P>
<P>
   Information about the Olympic Games, however, is relatively
scant, and I was sorry not to see Sydney's most spectacular harbor
walk, the Manly Scenic Walkway, mapped out the way it is in the
National Geographic guide. (The authors chose to focus on a less
worthy ramble around the seaside resort town of Manly itself.)
Fortunately, my other favorite, the Bondi Beach to Clovelly
cliffside walk, has two pages devoted to it.
</P>
<P>
   SYDNEY IN A WEEK, by Wendy Moore. 176 pages. 1997. (New Holland
Publishers, $24.95.)
</P>
<P>
   Wendy Moore's ``Ultimate Guide to Sydney,'' as the subtitle
proclaims, does not quite have everything you'll need. The author's
written sketches, while useful, tend to be thumbnail, and diners
are encouraged to look elsewhere if they want more than minimal
information about restaurants.
</P>
<P>
   That said, this is one of my favorite books on Sydney, and there
is a practical reason behind its somewhat impractical 8}-by-11-inch
size.
</P>
<P>
   Its seven sections on sightseeing, organized by day, are
illustrated with spectacular, full-blown color photographs. A
visitor might look at the aerial photo of the peninsula that
culminates in South Head at the entrance to Sydney Harbour, for
example _ with breakers on one side and crystalline coves on the
other _ and decide to spend the last day checking out this
landscape in the Eastern Suburbs rather than the more commercial,
less aesthetically pleasing Darling Harbour.
</P>
<P>
   I was particularly excited about the aerial vistas of different
districts of Sydney, most covering two-page spreads, in which
neighborhoods and landmarks are prominently labeled. My husband,
who is Australian, laughs at me, but these orient me much better
than conventional maps. They also show something of the character
of neighborhoods and how they fit into the grand scheme of Sydney.
In addition, there are plenty of traditional maps for people like
my husband, and a variety of special itineraries for the
adventurous, including harborside walks.
</P>
<P>
   LONELY PLANET SYDNEY (CONDENSED). 128 pages. 2000. (Lonely
Planet Publications, $9.95.)
</P>
<P>
   The best of the so-called pocket guides, although its nearly
eight-inch height makes it better suited to a purse, this slim book
should not be confused with the publisher's adequate but
unarresting full-length version, or judged by its homely front and
back covers. The covers, in fact, fold out and harbor a variety of
useful maps.
</P>
<P>
   There's too much impractical, sometimes careless artwork here _
one caption claims that beach views are a draw at a certain
restaurant, but there's nary a shore in sight in the photo, which
focuses on a wine bottle and glass. However, there is a lot to like
about this book, including an eight-page insert about the Olympic
Games. For hungry Game-goers who can't find places at the more
popular restaurants, this section offers a list of suburban streets
where the many and varied restaurants will probably have tables.
The contributors also note the Olympics events, such as the
Marathon, which can be seen free of charge.
</P>
<P>
   There is a page on Quirky Sydney here, which is good for an
entertaining read even if you don't want to visit a wig and
clothing shop for drag queens, and parents will appreciate the
facing page, which covers Sydney for Children, complete with the
name and number of an agency for reliable baby sitters and nannies.
Restaurants are listed by neighborhood. I was initially puzzled not
to be able to locate two of my favorite eating establishments _
Bathers Pavilion and Forty One _ then relieved to see them on a
separate restaurant page entitled Outstanding Views, only with no
sign of their vistas.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the basic facts for travelers are condensed in the back
of the guide, even access numbers for major servers and a list of
Internet cafes.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   SHOPPING SECRETS: SYDNEY EDITION, by Michelle Matthews. 130
pages. 1999. (Shopping Secrets, $14.95.)
</P>
<P>
   Like any international city, Sydney has a wealth of retail
outlets, but it never struck me as an intriguing shopping town
until I saw this engaging guide. Grouping stores by neighborhood,
Matthews steers buyers beyond the Benettons and other international
chains so they can make a beeline for the most unusual wares Sydney
has to offer. Complementing Matthews' snappy writing style are
crisp, almost tactile photos by Rupert Lorhaldar.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the products on offer here are indigenous to Australia.
There is an espresso bar where the handmade furniture you sit on is
for sale, and a store specializing in anything made from Australian
cotton, for example. Yet the book also tells you where to find the
best French imports, Soviet memorabilia and Swedish designs. Among
the 113 rather esoteric businesses to choose from are an upscale
sex shop; a boutique of unusual buttons; a lounge where you can go
with friends and a bottle of wine to make your own pottery; a
bottled-water purveyor with 100 varieties; and a consignment shop
for recycled designer clothes.
</P>
<P>
   Information on each store includes address, telephone and fax
numbers and hours, but does not include prices. The latter are apt
to change; besides, as in a store window, a lack of price tag can
draw you into the store to ask. For richer or, most likely, for
poorer, this fashionably slim book should accompany the acquisitive
to Sydney. It is available in the United States only at
www.amazon.com or at its own Web site, www.shoppingsecrets.com, but
it is sold in bookstores in Australia.
</P>
<P>
   IN A SUNBURNED COUNTRY, by Bill Bryson. 307 pages. 2000.
(Broadway Books, $25.)
</P>
<P>
   The flight to Sydney is long _ about 14 hours nonstop just from
Los Angeles _ but the travel writer and humorist Bill Bryson's
vastly entertaining takes on Australia should make it elapse
swiftly. The only risk is that laughing aloud may intrigue
neighboring passengers, possibly engaging them in unwanted
conversation, or simply make them irked that they're not having
fun, too.
</P>
<P>
   If there is one book with which to get oriented before departure
or en route to Australia, this is it. Bryson celebrates the quirks
_ in history, in culture, in flora and fauna _ that together give
Australia its eccentric character. He pokes gentle fun at Lachlan
Macquarie, governor of the colony in the early 19th century, after
whom lakes, streets, you-name-it are named. He mines the humor
inherent in Australia's abundance of extravagantly toxic creatures
such as the 10 most deadly poisonous snakes on the planet, box
jellyfish and the blue-ringed octopus. He takes us into the store
that sells pet supplies and pornography in a small country town.
</P>
<P>
   Bryson's droll point of view even renders past events palatable
for nonhistory buffs: I would never known that the explorer
Jean-Francois de la Perouse just missed claiming Australia for
France, thus, notes Bryson, saving the country from 200 years of
English cooking.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-31-00 2105EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000731.0423 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-31 21:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8788 &Cx1f; tad-z
r s BC-BBO-BRAVESTRADE0801-C     07-31 0506
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-BRAVESTRADE0801-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    With minutes to spare, Braves add Orioles' Surhofff
 &HT;    By Carroll Rogers
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA - Not to be caught standing still in a tornado of trades
late Monday afternoon, the Braves sealed their second deal of the
month at 3:45 p.m. With 15 minutes to spare before the trading
deadline, Braves general manager John Schuerholz acquired Orioles
left fielder B.J. Surhoff.
</P>
<P>
   Surhoff becomes the second recent addition Schuerholz has made
via trade, along with Andy Ashby, to a roster he's building for
October.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves also acquired pitcher Gabe Molina, a 25-year-old
right-handed reliever who's headed to Class AAA Richmond, while
giving up right-hander Luis Rivera, catcher Fernando Lunar and
outfielder Trenidad Hubbard.
</P>
<P>
   Just in time for their toughest road trip of the year that
includes stops in division-leading Arizona and St. Louis, the
Braves got an added boost to go along with the best record in
baseball and the expected return to health of Brian Jordan, Walt
Weiss and Andres Galarraga. Their one glaring weakness, produced by
Reggie Sanders and his .193 batting average in left field, has been
addressed.
</P>
<P>
   The 35-year-old Surhoff will join the Braves today in Phoenix,
with his .292 batting average, 13 home runs, 57 RBI and his
major-league leading consecutive games played streak at 427.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a deal we've been talking to the Orioles about for quite
some time,'' Schuerholz said. ``We felt like it improves the
offense of our club, especially in the outfield, which was one of
the important things for us to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Both Rivera and Jason Marquis have been sought after by other
clubs. The Braves might have been quicker to deal Marquis than
Rivera at the start of the season, but that changed with Marquis'
strong showing this past month.
</P>
<P>
   Working against Rivera is his injury problems. The 22-year-old
has an impressive repertoire, including a mid-to-upper 90s
fastball, but he has yet to make it through a full season without
injury. He started this season in the majors but missed more than
two months with shoulder stiffness. He missed much of his season in
Class A last year with blister problems.
</P>
<P>
   Rivera is healthy again and has been pitching in AAA.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a fine young prospect,'' Schuerholz said. ``We just felt
with our team structured the way we are and with the needs we have
and as close as we are to winning another division title and league
championship hopefully, B.J. Surhoff really adds to our chances of
doing that. He really strengthens us. You have to give up some
value, and we've demonstrated our willingness to do that all
along.''
</P>
<P>
   Surhoff, who has another year left on his contract, had mixed
emotions about the trade largely for personal reasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not that I don't want to play in Atlanta,'' Surhoff said.
``I'm going to a great situation and I know it's going to work out,
but I enjoy playing here.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
