<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-31 21:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8789 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a BC-POWER-HISTORY01-COX     07-31 0702
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POWER-HISTORY01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    FPL history marked by growth, some criticism
 &HT;    By Jeff Ostrowski
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Florida Power &AMP; Light was born 75 years
ago, and grew up with the state that bought its electricity.
</P>
<P>
   In 1925, utility conglomerate American Power &AMP; Light launched
FPL to provide transmission lines that would link the state's few
electric utilities.
</P>
<P>
   FPL set up transmission lines hooking up 58 communities from
Miami to Stuart on the East Coast and from Arcadia to Punta Gorda
on the West Coast.
</P>
<P>
   FPL, which on Monday announced a deal that would make it the
nation's largest utility, embarked on a $50 million expansion in
the 1920s.
</P>
<P>
   In 1926, FPL had 76,000 customers and generated 70 megawatts of
power. Those numbers have grown to 3.8 million customer accounts in
Florida and generating capacity of 16,000 megawatts.
</P>
<P>
   The Public Utility Holding Company Act of 1935 forced Americann
Miami, but its parent, FPL Group, gradually moved its headquarters
to Juno Beach in the 1980s and '90s to be more centrally located to
the rest of the state, FPL spokesman Bill Swank said.
</P>
<P>
   In 1972, its first nuclear plant, at Turkey Point in southern
Dade County, began producing power. FPL's nuclear plant on
Hutchinson Island in St. Lucie County opened in 1976.
</P>
<P>
   FPL's history includes two waves of diversification followed by
divestment.
</P>
<P>
   In its early days, FPL accumulated a limestone quarry,
streetcars, phone companies and water utilities, which it sold in
the 1940s and 1950s.
</P>
<P>
   FPL began to diversify again in the 1980s, buying real estate
firm W. Flagler Investment in 1981. The company formed FPL Group in
1984 as a holding company.
</P>
<P>
   FPL Group later bought Telesat Cablevision, insurance company
Colonial Penn Group and Turner Foods citrus groves.
</P>
<P>
   Diversification didn't prove profitable, and in 1990 the firm
wrote off about $750 million. FPL sold off the non-utility
divisions in the 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   FPL's latest expansion has focused on producing power. In 1997,
FPL Group created FPL Energy, which produces power outside of
Florida and sells it to other utilities.
</P>
<P>
   FPL Energy teamed up with Belgium-based Tractebel in 1998 to buy
gas-fired plants in Boston and Newark, N.J.
</P>
<P>
   FPL also built wind-power facilities in Iowa, Wisconsin and
Texas and bought 35 generating plants from Central Maine Power for
$846 million.
</P>
<P>
   This year, FPL launched FPL FiberNet, a subsidiary that leases
capacity on the company's fiber-optic communications network.
</P>
<P>
   FPL Chairman and Chief Executive James Broadhead has overseen
the expansion.
</P>
<P>
   When Broadhead took over in 1989, FPL was the first company
outside Japan to win that country's prestigious Deming Prize for
``quality control management.'' The award previously honored
Japanese companies such as Toyota and Nissan.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the award, Broadhead saw FPL as bloated and slow. He
launched a massive restructuring that eliminated thousands of jobs.
</P>
<P>
   He now sees the utility as a leader in reducing pollution from
power plants, but FPL has drawn complaints from environmentalists.
In 1995, the St. Lucie nuclear plant was fined by the U.S. Nuclear
Regulatory Commission for a series of problems.
</P>
<P>
   Environmentalists also criticized FPL for its attempts to power
a plant near Tampa Bay by burning Orimulsion, a cheap, tarlike fuel
from Venezuela. Then-Gov. Lawton Chiles and the Cabinet in 1998
rejected FPL's request to burn Orimulsion, and the company dropped
the effort.
</P>
<P>
   The Florida Public Interest Research Group has criticized some
FPL plants, including its Riviera Beach operation, for polluting
heavily.
</P>
<P>
   A recent report by the U.S. Environmental Protection Agency
called Florida the fourth-worst state for power plant pollution.
But while the report ranked four plants owned by St.
Petersburg-based Florida Power, Gulf Power and Tampa Electric among
the nation's 25 dirtiest, no FPL plant made the list.
</P>
<P>
   FPL is converting its Sanford and Fort Myers plants to
cleaner-burning natural gas, and it's installing equipment to lower
emissions at its Riviera Beach plant.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
