Florida and generating capacity of 16,000 megawatts.
</P>
<P>
   The Public Utility Holding Company Act of 1935 forced American
Power &AMP; Light to spin off FPL in 1950. The Florida utility landed a
listing on the New York Stock Exchange that year.
</P>
<P>
   FPL remains based in Miami, but its parent, FPL Group, gradually
moved its headquarters to Juno Beach in the 1980s and '90s to be
more centrally located to the rest of the state, FPL spokesman Bill
Swank said.
</P>
<P>
   In 1972, its first nuclear plant, at Turkey Point in southern
