<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-31 21:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8793 &Cx1f; tad-z
r f BC-POWER-REACTION01-COX     07-31 0836
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POWER-REACTION01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    FPL employees, community leaders pleased over merger
 &HT;    By Deborah Circelli, Amy Martinez
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   JUNO BEACH, Fla. _ FPL employees got a different sort of wake-up
call Monday morning when they walked through the lobby of their
Juno Beach headquarters.
</P>
<P>
   Banners and posters telling them to check their e-mail to learn
about a deal between ``America's premier power companies'' tipped
them off that soon they could be working for a new company.
</P>
<P>
   At 11 a.m., employees scattered throughout the building to watch
large TV monitors, on which Florida Power &AMP; Light President Paul
Evanson assured them that FPL Group's $13.9 billion deal for
Entergy Corp. of New Orleans would not lead to massive layoffs.
</P>
<P>
   If anything, Evanson said, it would provide new opportunities
for job growth.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's going to be the best power company out there,''
he told employees. ``It's a huge power company with incredible
possibilities.''
</P>
<P>
   Evanson, who will remain president of FPL's Florida Power &AMP;
Light subsidiary _ the company that provides millions of Floridians
with electric power _ and oversee the combined companies' regulated
utilities, spoke in a small room at the Juno Beach offices to about
100 employees. The broadcast was aired over the company's internal
news network to offices throughout the state.
</P>
<P>
   Evanson said some administrative jobs might be eliminated at the
corporate level, but how many has not been determined. FPL Group
and its subsidiaries have about 11,350 employees, including 3,250
in Palm Beach, Indian River, Martin and St. Lucie counties, and a
total of about 8,000 in South Florida. Wayne Ondler, a manager in
FPL's environmental services department, said some employees
obviously are worried, but many think the news is positive.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really not a surprise because we knew the company was
always engaged in looking at opportunities to increase shareholder
value,'' said Ondler, who has been with FPL for almost 17 years.
``I think more people view it as an opportunity.''
</P>
<P>
   Alan Cook, an FPL employee for 18 years and systems manager,
also said employees accepted the news positively.
</P>
<P>
   ``Over the years we've been through three restructurings and
employee reductions. Once you've been through that two or three
times, nothing fazes you,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The mood at the St. Lucie nuclear power plant on Hutchinson
Island was similar. With 630 employees, the twin-reactor plant is
one of St. Lucie County's biggest employers and accounts for 16
percent of its tax base.
</P>
<P>
   Ken Hall, a 20-year machinist who lives in Vero Beach, said he
learned of the deal in a two-page fax. He said employees at the
plant took the news in stride.
</P>
<P>
   ``In this day and age of deregulation, you can't get too
concerned. Job security is not what it once was,'' he said. ``But
at this point, it looks like everything is going to be the same.''
</P>
<P>
   Brian Thompson, who oversees 11 local International Brotherhood
of Electrical Workers unions representing 3,400 Florida Power &AMP;
Light employees, said he was surprised to learn of the deal Sunday
night.
</P>
<P>
   Thompson has been negotiating with FPL for a new union contract
after the current one expires Oct. 31. Weekly meetings resume
today. He said he's encouraged that Entergy employees are
represented by the same union.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now we don't perceive it as negative, but we can't say
what the future will bring,'' Thompson said. ``As far as we're
concerned, we are just going to press forward with the regular
negotiations.''
</P>
<P>
   Economic development officials in Palm Beach County and the
Treasure Coast so far embrace the deal. It lends the area prestige
as home to the country's largest electric utility, which would help
recruit other businesses, said Larry Pelton, president of the
Business Development Board of Palm Beach County.
</P>
<P>
   Large corporations like to know that other large companies are
nearby when choosing sites for their headquarters, Pelton said, and
knowing that companies the size of FPL and Entergy are based here
is not insignificant.
</P>
<P>
   ``This demonstrates that this is a good place to do business,''
Pelton said. ``We work with a lot of headquarters and back-office
operations of large corporations. And in their evaluations of an
area, they want to know that other companies of their magnitude are
in the area ... so that they feel comfortable.'' The merger would
have ripple effects in Martin County, where many FPL headquarters
employees live, said Ted Astolfi, executive director of the
Business Development Board in Stuart.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we can retain the jobs in Juno Beach, that's a major
success for us,'' Astolfi said. ``This has the potential of
providing additional jobs.''
</P>
<P>
   Veteran St. Lucie County Commissioner Cliff Barnes was more
subdued: ``It's exciting, but not overwhelming.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hopefully, it will have some spin off for our economy,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
