<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-31 21:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8797 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u p BC-CNV-LEADERSHIP-HNS &LR;      07-31 0944
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CNV-LEADERSHIP-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOP LEADERS BACK BUSH'S MESSAGE OF MODERATION, DIVERSITY 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By GREG McDONALD 
c.2000 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ Republican congressional leaders who are used to
calling the shots in Washington are taking a back seat during the
GOP convention to George W. Bush and his message of moderation and
diversity.
</P>
<P>
   The leaders are content with their convention roles and are
hoping any momentum from Bush's campaign will help fend off a dozen
or so strong Democratic challenges around the country that could
shift the balance of power on Capitol Hill.
</P>
<P>
   Republican officials say the strategy will work if they can keep
the Democrats from turning the November election in part into a
national referendum on the GOP-controlled Congress.
</P>
<P>
   So while the Democrats plan to showcase their congressional
leaders and their positions on a number of issues at their Los
Angeles convention in two weeks, Republicans this week are playing
down some of the more conservative positions of their leaders by
limiting their role in Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   ``The reason is that if the election becomes a national
referendum on the House, it's not good for us,'' said one senior
Republican aide, referring to public opinion polls showing a low
job approval for the GOP Congress. ``That's why we're trying to
keep the focus on individual candidates and Governor Bush.''
</P>
<P>
   Although House Majority Whip Tom DeLay might be out of the
public spotlight in Philadelphia, the Sugar Land, Texas, Republican
is spending his time entertaining delegates and lawmakers, and
matching up congressional candidates in need of money with
potential contributors.
</P>
<P>
   DeLay's own political action committee, Americans for a
Republican Majority, is hosting a number of events this week,
ranging from a golf tournament to a late night party featuring the
band Blues Traveler.
</P>
<P>
   DeLay's political action committee has been given use of five
luxuriously appointed railroad cars parked outside the convention
hall to serve as getaway chambers. When GOP lawmakers and
candidates have had enough of the convention business, they can
retire to a rail car to watch a little television, read, play some
cards or, maybe, entertain a potential contributor. All compliments
of DeLay.
</P>
<P>
   It's a mix of fun and business, says one DeLay aide, adding that
his boss is simply ``trying to take care of the members' needs.''
It's much like he does back in Washington, where his Capitol office
provides GOP lawmakers a place to hang out during late night
debates.
</P>
<P>
   ``This (convention) is a celebration of being Republican. It's
not about pushing one Republican agenda over another,'' the aide
said.
</P>
<P>
   House Speaker Dennis Hastert of Illinois, the convention's
permanent chairman, and House Majority Leader Dick Armey of Irving,
Texas, are following DeLay's lead by hosting a series of events and
festivities designed to both entertain and, when possible, connect
GOP candidates with sources of money needed to run competitive
campaigns in the fall.
</P>
<P>
   Armey, for instance, has enlisted the help of country
entertainers Brooks and Dunn to put on a show Wednesday night for
GOP delegates and congressional candidates when they finish their
official convention business of nominating Dick Cheney for vice
president.
</P>
<P>
   Neither Armey, DeLay nor Hastert, has been given a major role in
the convention. They're not even making public appearances beyond
Hastert's briefing remarks when the convention opens.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Republican congressional leaders have been called on to
help trumpet Bush's message. Three of them _ caucus Chairman J.C.
Watts of Oklahoma, and Reps. Henry Bonilla of San Antonio and
Jennifer Dunn of Washington _ were named convention co-chairs. They
can not only articulate Bush's agenda, but the put faces to the
diversity he says is a part of the new GOP.
</P>
<P>
   Watts is black and Bonilla Hispanic, and along with Dunn they
represent three groups of voters that Bush is targeting in his race
against Democrat Al Gore.
</P>
<P>
   The convention agenda, meanwhile is crammed with women and
minority speakers, as well as teachers, farmers and small business
people. Only a handful of Washington politicians will speak, and
most of them are not scheduled to appear during prime time.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to put a new face and a new voice to the Republican
Party and challenge the Republican Party to move in a new more
inclusive direction,'' Karl Rove, Bush's chief political
consultant, said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Bonilla agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we're doing this time is more accurately reflecting our
constituency out there,'' Bonilla said in a CBS News interview.
``What we're going to do is showcase what's happened out there and
some of the traditional faces you've seen at conventions over the
years won't be there.''
</P>
<P>
   Bonilla was referring most recently to the 1996 GOP convention
in San Diego where more than half the speakers were members of
Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's theme of diversity and moderation makes Republican
leaders more confident about congressional races this fall.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our guys are positioned so when there's a Bush wave they can
surf it. If not, they'll have enough gas in their engines for them
to make it on their own,'' said Tony Rudy, one of DeLay's senior
advisers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Democrats want to turn this (election) into a debate about
the Republican Congress,'' Rudy said, ``because they don't have a
consistent message of their own.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush has a message, he added, that ``seems to be connecting out
there ... and it's one that our (congressional) candidates can
embrace.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXXXXXEND OF STORY
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
