r f BC-POWER-MAIN0801-COX     07-31 0874
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POWER-MAIN0801-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Purchase makes Florida group nation's largest utility
 &HT;    By Jeff Ostrowski
 &HT;    and Deborah Circelli
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   JUNO BEACH, Fla. _ FPL Group, believing that bigger is better,
said Monday it would buy Entergy Corp. of New Orleans _ and become
the nation's largest utility.
</P>
<P>
   FPL would pay $7 billion in stock and assume $6.9 billion in
debt from Entergy. The deal would create a company with 6.3 million
customers in five states, $15 billion in annual revenue and more
than 20,000 employees.
</P>
<P>
   The reason for the marriage? Survival, said FPL Chairman James
L. Broadhead.
</P>
<P>
   Broadhead said the deal ensures that FPL will survive a wave of
consolidation in the energy industry.
</P>
<P>
   The consolidation is spurred by the possibility that electric
companies soon will have to compete for customers. Now, power
companies in most states, including Florida, are protected and
regulated monopolies.
</P>
<P>
   Broadhead predicted that only a few dominant utilities will
survive.
</P>
<P>
   ``This merger will give us the size, the scale and the scope to
make sure we're one of those companies,'' he said Monday in a
conference call with reporters.
</P>
<P>
   The deal would push FPL Group, which now has 3.8 million
customer accounts in Florida, past Ohio-based American Electric
Power and California utilities Pacific Gas and Electric and
Southern California Edison in number of customers.
</P>
<P>
   Before this combination of two Fortune 500 companies can take
effect, the deal will go to shareholders of both companies and will
be reviewed by the Securities and Exchange Commission and by
federal utility regulators, a process FPL said will take about 15
months.
</P>
<P>
   Broadhead, 64, would be chairman of the new company, which would
be headquartered at FPL's home in Juno Beach and is so far unnamed.
Broadhead, who last year announced his plans to retire within two
years, said he'd stay at FPL for a year after the marriage is
complete.
</P>
<P>
   Entergy Chief Executive J. Wayne Leonard, 49, would be president
and chief executive officer. Leonard would move to Juno Beach from
Neless debt.
</P>
<P>
   FPL shareholders would own 57 percent of the new company, while
Entergy shareholders would own 43 percent. FPL shareholders would
receive one share of the new company for each FPL share; Entergy
shareholders would get 0.585 of a share of the new company for each
Entergy share.
</P>
<P>
   The combined company's 15-member board would be made up of eight
FPL directors and seven Entergy directors.
</P>
<P>
   Broadhead said the deal stems from the friendship he struck up
with Leonard after the two met at industry conferences.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've known Wayne for some time,'' Broadhead said. ``Through
talking at industry meetings, we came to understand that we had
similar attitudes about the way our companies should be run.''
</P>
<P>
   Negotiations heated up in late May or early June and were
completed this past weekend, Broadhead said.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, FPL was the target of a possible $11 billion
bid from Iberdrola, Spain's second-largest power company.
Negotiations collapsed, however, after Iberdrola withdrew its bid
because of a lack of support from its board.
</P>
<P>
   Although FPL failed to draw a bid from Iberdrola, the market had
speculated that other foreign companies might have been interested.
</P>
<P>
   Broadhead, in an interview with Reuters, declined to comment on
whether another party might emerge to break up the Entergy deal.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement between FPL and Entergy includes a $215 million
break-up fee in case either side kills the deal. Termination fees
typically are paid when a company ends an agreement in favor of
another suitor.
</P>
<P>
   The new company expects to pay a dividend consistent with FPL's
dividend policy. FPL Group's annual dividend is $2.16 a share;
Entergy's is $1.20 a share. Entergy's shareholders would receive
$1.26 for each share of the new company, based on a conversion
formula.
</P>
<P>
   The combined utility would have one of the nation's largest
wholesale operations, which sell power to other utilities rather
than directly to consumers. The Wall Street Journal on Monday
speculated that FPL could spin off the profitable unit to form a
separate company, but Broadhead said he has no plans for such a
move.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wholesale operations are a very exciting part of this,''
Broadhead said. ``As far as spinning it off, we haven't even talked
about that.''
</P>
<P>
   Although state regulators in Florida, Arkansas, Louisiana,
Mississippi and Texas will review the deal, they do not have
authority to reject or approve it.
</P>
<P>
   Tim Devlin, director of economic regulation for the Florida
Public Service Commission, said the PSC can only verify that FPL's
rates don't rise.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we see a red flag and feel there is a detrimental effect to
customers, we will bring it to the commission's attention,'' Devlin
said. ``They have the authority to make sure inappropriate costs
are not passed on to the rate payer.''
</P>
<P>
   FPL's deal is just the latest example of consolidation in the
utility industry. Last year, Carolina Power &AMP; Light said it would
buy St. Petersburg-based Florida Progress, a deal that awaits
regulatory approval.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
