<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-31 21:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8800 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-CVN-DOLE01-1STLD-COX     07-31 0709
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CVN-DOLE01-1STLD-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    GOP COLLEAGUES PAY TRIBUTE TO ELIZABETH DOLE
 &HT;    Eds: Corrects dateline to Philadelphia.
 &HT;    310&AMP;add.
 &HT;    EUNICE MOSCOSO
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ The most famous North Carolinian in the GOP was
overcome with emotion and humility Monday after an hour-long
tribute that exalted her many accomplishments.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am simply overwhelmed,'' said Elizabeth Dole, who addresses
the convention Tuesday night. ``In no way do I feel I deserve such
a magnificent tribute. ... You had me in tears.''
</P>
<P>
   Dole, who brought much excitement to the presidential race last
year as a GOP candidate, was honored at an upbeat and moving
ceremony in a hotel ballroom during the Republican National
Convention.
</P>
<P>
   Friends and colleagues spoke of her courage, compassion and
conviction.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Jennifer Dunn, R-Wash., praised Dole's service as president
of the American Red Cross.
</P>
<P>
   ``She willingly journeyed into the face of hurricanes and
floods. And in places around the world, like Bosnia and Somalia,
she braved mine fields, civil war, and cholera epidemics to stand
with Red Cross staff and volunteers to reach out to those in the
most dire human need,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Tillie Fowler, R-Fla., who has known Dole for more than 30
years, said her personal side is even more impressive than her
career.
</P>
<P>
   ``Through all her years in Washington, no matter what the
pressures or how busy her schedule, she has always found the time
to be a friend, who never forgets a birthday or a special occasion
and who is always there when you need her,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The tribute also included video clips _ some emotional and
others humorous. The lighter side included a salute from her
husband, former Sen. Bob Dole of Kansas, and a TV clip of Jay Leno
driving her onto the ``Tonight Show'' stage on a Harley Davidson
motorcycle during her husband's failed 1996 presidential campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many people thought that was the highlight of the campaign,''
Bob Dole said. ``I can't remember that there was any highlight to
the campaign.''
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   During her long career in public service, Elizabeth Dole held
many high-ranking positions.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to heading the Red Cross, she was transportation
secretary under President Reagan and secretary of labor under
President Bush. In her role as transportation secretary, she was
responsible for the U.S. Coast Guard, becoming the first woman to
head a branch of the military.
</P>
<P>
   At Monday's tribute, Dole thanked her parents, John Van Hanford
and Mary Ella Hanford, for teaching her the value of hard work.
</P>
<P>
   Under their guidance, she showed leadership from the beginning.
</P>
<P>
   She was the first female to run for class president at Boyden
High School in Salisbury, N.C., a post that had been off-limits for
girls. Although she did not win, it marked her determination to
take on roles not previously assumed by women.
</P>
<P>
   She went on to be student body president at Duke University,
where she graduated with a political science degree. She also
obtained a master's degree in education and took the first step in
her political career that same year working for Sen. Everett Jordan
of North Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   To her Republican father's dismay, she toured the South with
Democratic vice-presidential nominee Lyndon Johnson. She later went
to Harvard Law School and was one of 24 women out of a class of 550
who graduated in 1965. She later worked for President Johnson in
the Committee for Consumer Interests and took the same executive
director position when Richard Nixon became president in 1969.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, she made a run at the GOP nomination, which she
called ``one of the greatest experiences'' of her life.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel very strongly that somewhere between the streets of San
Francisco, the cornfields of Iowa and the mountain roads of New
Hampshire, I may very well have met and talked to a woman who will
be the first female president of the United States,'' she said. ``I
believe that we have helped to pave the way.''
</P>
<P>
   Cox Washington Bureau reporter Miriam A. Garcia contributed to
this report.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
