<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Judge bans the S-word at Florida burglary trial
 &HT;    By Bill Douthat
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. - The legend of Spiderman is common
knowledge in the crime-conscious coastal communities in Palm Beach
County.
</P>
<P>
   Not the web-crawling super hero of comics fame. Most prospective
jurors filing into Judge Kenneth Marra's courtroom Monday recalled
Spiderman as the name of a balcony-scaling cat burglar who breaks
into high-rise condominiums in South Florida.
</P>
<P>
   Marra was trying to assess the public profile of ``Spiderman''
to insure a fair trial for Derrick James, who is standing trial for
allegedly committing a high-rise burglary in Tequesta.
</P>
<P>
   James, 35, was dubbed by police and news media as ``Spiderman''
after he was named a suspect in more than 100 burglaries from Miami
to Cocoa Beach. He has been convicted in Miami-Dade and Broward
counties and sentenced to 53 years in prison.
</P>
<P>
   He is accused of stealing at least $145,000 in goods in 10 Palm
Beach County burglaries. He will have two more trials, with two new
juries, after this one, prosecutors said.
</P>
<P>
   While Marra is barring the use of the S-word during the trial,
he questioned jurors one-by-one what the term Spiderman means to
them to see if they've been tainted by news coverage of James'
case.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course, the comic book hero,'' said the first juror called.
He then remembered ``the guy breaking into condos and climbing the
walls.''
</P>
<P>
   The next juror said she remembered something about a high rise
apartment and a burglar going through the window. ``I believe it
was on TV,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Another juror said he was ``very familiar'' with the case and
even recognized James, who was sitting at the defense table, from
news photographs.
</P>
<P>
   A few said the moniker meant nothing to them outside the comic
book character.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't read the paper,'' said one juror. ``The news is so
depressing.''
</P>
<P>
   Those who linked the name to burglaries were instructed that
only evidence heard inside the courtroom should be considered
during deliberations.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Alan, James' attorney, said during a recess that the
Spiderman label imposed on James is so widely known that he didn't
bother seeking a change of venue.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we would probably have to leave the state of
Florida,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Jury selection continues today.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
