<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-31 21:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8810 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-LAW-BOOTCAMP-NYT &LR;      07-31 1067
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LAW-BOOTCAMP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAW FIRM PLANS   RADICAL REVISION OF SUMMER PROGRAM FOR STUDENTS 
</HEADLINE>
   By DAVID LEONHARDT   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   It seems like an odd recruiting strategy in a tight labor
market: tell prospective employees that they can expect to work
longer hours and receive fewer perks than they would at rival
companies. That is precisely what a large Washington law firm will
announce Tuesday as it tries to redefine the summer-associate
program that virtually all firms use to woo law students.
</P>
<P>
   Howrey Simon Arnold &AMP; White, which has a roster of blue-chip
clients that includes Intel, Johnson &AMP; Johnson and Procter &AMP;
Gamble, is scrapping its traditional program _ in which law
students spend the summer doing relatively little work, going out
for expensive meals and still getting paid more than $2,000 a week.
In its place will be a ``boot camp'' in which the potential
employees will work 12 hours a day for two weeks on a mock trial,
as well as a two-week stint in one of Howrey's six offices around
the country.
</P>
<P>
   Partners at Howrey said they hoped the new program would give
young lawyers a more accurate picture of life at a law firm than a
summer of free baseball and theater tickets does. That in turn
could reduce turnover, which has been rising at most large firms as
many associates have taken advantage of the tight labor market and
have left behind law-firm work that can resemble drudgery in the
first few years for jobs at consulting firms, Internet start-ups
and big companies.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone is looking for ways to make sure people really
understand the life of an associate,'' said Janet Zagorin, the
director of practice development at Gibson, Dunn &AMP; Crutcher,
another big firm. Howrey's new summer program ``is a very, very
interesting idea; it's very different.''
</P>
<P>
   It also brings some significant risks for Howrey, the
74th-largest firm in the country, according to American Lawyer
magazine, and one that focuses on antitrust and
intellectual-property litigation. The firm is both cutting
perquisites for law students who have dozens of options in a good
economy and encouraging them to spend the majority of their summer
at another firm that will try to hire them.
</P>
<P>
   Howrey will mail letters to law students and deans Tuesday
announcing the change, lawyers at the firm said. It will take
effect next year.
</P>
<P>
   Law school officials and lawyers at other firms said they did
not know whether Howrey's idea would spread, but they called it one
of the most notable changes in years to the summer-associate
program, which is the most important recruiting tool for firms.
Each large firm hires dozens of law students, most of them entering
their third and final year of school, for two or three months.
Partners and associates then spend much of the time trying to
persuade the students to join the firm after graduation.
</P>
<P>
   Howrey's move is also one of the most dramatic illustrations of
the ways that law firms are scrambling to respond to raises given
to associates earlier this year in an effort to reduce turnover.
The pay increases _ lifting the salaries of first-year associates
at the nation's largest firms to $125,000, from $100,000 _ have
drastically raised firms' costs, causing many to consider
eliminating some practice areas or hiring less expensive outside
lawyers to do more basic work.
</P>
<P>
   Howrey's summer program will save it about $700,000 in direct
costs, and the firm plans to spend some of that money on new
training programs for associates, said Richard Ripley, a partner
who oversees the firm's recruiting committee.
</P>
<P>
   The recent pay increases have also raised the stakes for holding
onto lawyers for more than a few years. The largest increases went
to the least experienced lawyers at most firms, making fourth-year
and fifth-year associates more profitable for firms than their less
experienced colleagues with lower billing rates.
</P>
<P>
   But Howrey has had the same kind of retention problems as many
firms. In June, for example, a lawyer who had quit the firm sent an
anonymous letter to its partners and associates with a long list of
complaints. The ``associates are either leaving like rats from a
sinking ship or are grumbling about how unhappy they are,'' said
the memo, which was passed along by e-mail to dozens of lawyers at
other firms.
</P>
<P>
   With a summer program intended to mimic the kind of work more
experienced lawyers perform, Howrey partners said they hoped to cut
down on the number of associates who leave during their first or
second year, bored by the long hours and the kind of work that
occupies their time then.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem with the summer-associate programs is that the
bulk of the work that can be effectively done during this very
short period of time is library research,'' said Edward Han, a
Howrey partner. ``Beyond the first year or two of practice, our
actual associates don't do that.''
</P>
<P>
   For its two-week boot camp, Howrey will rent a corporate retreat
in Leesburg, Va., where its 50 summer associates and some lawyers
from the firm will spend two weeks. The law students will split
into two teams of opposing lawyers for the mock trial. They then
will depose ``witnesses'' _ played by Howrey employees _ receiving
critiques from the firm's actual lawyers, for example.
</P>
<P>
   During the remaining two weeks, the law students will spread out
across the country and go through a shorter version of the typical
summer-associate program.
</P>
<P>
   The students will receive $12,000 for the four-week program,
which will end in mid-June. The salary is about $500 a week more
than summer associates at other firms receive. But because many
students have large law-school debts, they are likely to spend the
rest of their summer at other firms. ``If you work for 10 weeks,
you pay for a year of law school,'' said W. Stevenson Hopson, the
career services dean at the University of Virginia School of Law,
which sent four of its graduates to Howrey this spring.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, Howrey Simon may have a lower acceptance rate than
other firms because nearly all of its summer associates will be
weighing more than one job offer, Hopson added.
</P>
<P>
   Howrey partners said they realized the risk but expected the
lawyers who did accept offers to have a solid understanding of
their new employer. ``We're thinking that by making a better fit,
we will improve our retention,'' Han said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
