u p BC-GOP-LAZIO-NYT &LR;      07-31 0797
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOP-LAZIO-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAZIO SKIPS CONVENTION TO FOCUS ON NEW YORK SENATE CAMPAIGN 
</HEADLINE>
   By ADAM NAGOURNEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ On Thursday night, Republican delegates from
across the nation will gather here to nominate George W. Bush as
their candidate for president, but one particularly prominent
Republican delegate from the state of New York has decided to skip
the climactic night of his party's nominating convention.
</P>
<P>
   The delegate _ Rep. Rick Lazio, Hillary Rodham Clinton's
opponent in this year's race for Senate in New York _ was also one
of the few prominent New York Republicans missing from an
invitation-only convention party hosted by Gov. George Pataki and
Bloomberg News Service on Sunday evening. And he turned down an
invitation from convention organizers for a brief,
way-out-of-prime-time speech Monday, instead opting for a swift
visit here on Tuesday for a fund-raiser and a speech with New York
delegates at their hotel. That might be the closest Lazio ever
makes it to the convention floor during this four-day session.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio's advisers said that he had decided to steer clear of
Philadelphia because he believed that he could more profitably
spend his time campaigning in New York. But Lazio's campaign
schedule for Monday lists not a single public campaign event _ and
his aides were unable Monday to say precisely what he will be doing
in New York on Thursday night when Bush is nominated in
Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   The question of the whereabouts of Lazio, who for many
Republicans has assumed star status in his role as the man who
might block Clinton's entry into elective office, echoed through
the throngs of revelers eating oysters and lobster salad at
Pataki's party on Sunday, and Monday emerged as one of the few
intriguing questions at a convention at which matters of suspense
have been in short supply.
</P>
<P>
   The answer seems to be that after some negotiations _ and
considerable division among Lazio's advisers, some of whom had
pushed for Lazio to get a large role at the convention _ both
Lazio's associates and organizers of the convention concluded that
it was in neither side's interest for Lazio to have the kind of
high-profile spot here that Hillary Clinton has been promised at
the Democratic convention in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   The GOP convention organizers offered Lazio a minor role in the
proceedings, speaking along with other candidates for Senate, an
offer Lazio turned down.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio's chief political strategist, Mike Murphy, said Monday
that Lazio already felt he had lost time campaigning because of his
congressional obligations, which have forced him to spend more time
in Washington than he would have liked. Congress is out of session
this week, and Murphy said Lazio decided to spend just one day
here, and take advantage of the respite to concentrate on his New
York campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to have one great day here and then get back to
work in New York,'' Murphy said, speaking in an interview on the
convention floor on Monday. He said that the demand of the campaign
was the sole factor in that decision.
</P>
<P>
   But other Republicans here suggested that other things might be
in play for Lazio. For example, at a time when Clinton has been
trying to draw the contest as an ideological
Republican-versus-Democrat, it might not be in Lazio's interest to
be associated with a gathering that is, ultimately, a celebration
of the Republican Party.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio's campaign spokesman, Dan McLagan, said that appearing in
Pennsylvania ``doesn't move the ball down the field. The campaign's
priorities are in New York _ we're not running for national
office.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Clinton's campaign moved quickly Monday to stoke the
perception that Lazio was in a bit of a predicament. Clinton's
spokesman, Howard Wolfson, said that Lazio was ``trying to run away
from his party,'' adding, ``In Washington, Rick Lazio is proud to
be a member of the Republican leadership, but in New York he tries
to hide the fact that he's a Republican at all.''
</P>
<P>
   The GOP's national co-chairman, Pat Harrison, disputed that
claim Monday night, asserting that she understood Lazio's absence
and said he would have been welcome to enjoy a larger role here.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he just has decided that he needs to be campaigning 24
hours a day,'' Harrison said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, several Republicans suggested the party might have little
interest in providing Lazio a prime position.Convention speakers
have been instructed to avoid critical remarks in general _ and
attacks on President Clinton and Hillary Rodham Clinton in
particular. Such restrictions might have proved problematic for
Lazio.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton is scheduled to speak directly before her husband on the
opening night of her own party's convention in Los Angeles.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
