<SLUG> BC-GORE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR GORE'S NO. 2, SPECULATION ON THE SAND 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: N.C., Fla., Mass., S.D.)   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WRIGHTSVILLE BEACH, N.C. _ Vice President Al Gore's list of
running mate possibilities seems to be shrinking, based on playful
sign language from his wife Monday during a stroll on the beach in
North Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   As Gore, his wife, Tipper, and daughters Karenna and Sarah
walked along the surf on Figure Eight Island for a photo
opportunity, reporters asked whether Gore had narrowed the field
and how his convention speech was coming.
</P>
<P>
   Gore said, ``We're just relaxing, concentrating on my grandson
right now,'' as he pushed a stroller with Karenna's 13-month-old
son, Wyatt.
</P>
<P>
   But Tipper Gore suggested in a gesture that the field was
narrowing, holding her hands about two feet apart, closing up the
space then expanding it again. Democrats close to the campaign also
suggested that Gore was getting closer to a final decision.
</P>
<P>
   Names still in circulation include Sen. John Edwards of North
Carolina, Sen. Bob Graham of Florida and Sen. John Kerry of
Massachusetts. Sen. Tom Daschle, the minority leader, from South
Dakota, who has visions of the Democrats' recapturing the Senate,
has asked the Gore camp not to raid any Democratic senators whose
replacements would be named by a Republican governor. Of these
three, only Edwards meets that requirement.
</P>
</TEXT>
