r a BC-FLOYD-AFTERMATH0801-C     07-31 0353
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLOYD-AFTERMATH0801-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Charges fly over possible contamination of N.C. housing site
 &HT;    By Chris Burritt
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROCKY MOUNT, N.C. _ Possible contamination of a temporary
trailer park for Hurricane Floyd's victims on Monday prompted
charges of racism against government agencies.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a racial thing that we are poor, we didn't have
anything, so you are going to have to accept whatever we give
you,'' said Vernice Lyons, 56, still living at the government
trailer park more than 10 months after Floyd destroyed her home.
</P>
<P>
   State and federal emergency relief officials denied the charges
of racism, but acknowledged Floyd's massive, still unfinished
recovery has left thousands of victims weary and angry.
</P>
<P>
   Flooding from North Carolina's worst natural disaster damaged or
destroyed about 55,000 homes, displacing hundreds of thousands of
people. Many of the 1,171 families still living in temporary state
housing are Hispanics and African-Americans, including the families
living in campers and trailers outside of Rocky Mount, at the
former Fountain Industrial Park.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clearly, there is no environmental racism,'' said Doug Boyd,
who is in charge of temporary housing for North Carolina's
Emergency Management Division.
</P>
<P>
   Hastily constructed last fall, the Fountain Industrial trailer
park is on a former coal ash dump. Toxic arsenic and mercury are
byproducts of coal ash
</P>
<P>
   Monday, the state Emergency Management Agency distributed a
letter to residents saying the site had passed an independent
environment assessment last fall, clearing the way for its use as a
housing site.
</P>
<P>
   Scientists gathered additional soil samples last week, after the
University of North Carolina School of Public Healthraised
contamination concerns.
</P>
<P>
   The results of soil testing could be available as soon as today,
Boyd said.
</P>
<P>
   The emergency housing official plans to meet Thursday with
residents who, he said, would be relocated if the samples find
evidence of contamination.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
