u p BC-GOP-DIARY-NYT     07-31 1081
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOP-DIARY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PHILADELPHIA DIARY: REPLACING MARY FISHER; CHOOSING TO LOSE GORE; A
SOMBER TEA; A NOT-SO-REPUBLICAN ALERT
</HEADLINE>
 By ALEX KUCZYNSKI and MATTHEW PURDY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Mary Fisher speech had become an fixture at Republican
conventions. She spoke passionately in 1992 and 1996 about living
with HIV and offered to do a repeat performance in Philadelphia.
The response from the Bush campaign was, well, no direct response.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, a short speech about AIDS will be delivered by Patricia
Funderburk Ware, the president of the Preserving Family Well-Being
Foundation, who favors abstinence-only sex education programs. It's
a decidedly more conservative message than the one Fisher would
have delivered. Fisher provides funds for an AIDS research and
education fund, and advocates a broader range of preventive
measures. ``I think it's more important to save lives than
virginity,'' Fisher said.
</P>
<P>
   But there's another difference. Fisher, whose father, Max, has
given sizable amounts of his auto-body fortune to the Republican
Party, is white. Ware, who worked in the administration of
President Bush, is black.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it was important that it be an African American,''
said Carl E. Schmid, a leading gay supporter of Governor Bush who
discussed the choice with party officials.
</P>
<P>
   Tim Fitzpatrick, a party spokesman, said simply that Ware ``is
reflective of Governor Bush's call for soldiers in the army of
compassion.'' Ware did not return calls.
</P>
<P>
   Fisher said she thought it would be more powerful for the
delegates to hear from someone with AIDS. ``Having someone with the
disease puts a face on it,'' Fisher said. Her past speeches were
arrestingly personal and, Fisher added, ``maybe it brings it too
close to them.''
</P>
<P>
   So Fisher stayed away from the convention, but her
non-invitation was on the minds of some at a reception Monday for
gay and lesbian Republicans. Like Fisher, they were struggling to
find their place under the big tent the party says it has pitched.
</P>
<P>
   Schmid, addressing a room of about 200, praised the party's
draft platform, which was in line with many policies favored by
gays. ``Unfortunately,'' he told the crowd, ``the very conservative
platform committee'' changed the language. `We have a long road
ahead in our own party,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   One step on that road, he said, will be a speech to the
convention by Rep. Jim Kolbe of Arizona, who will be the first
openly gay person to address a Republican convention.
</P>
<P>
   His topic? International trade policy.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, Rep. Jerry Lewis was happily anticipating the party
he was planning to give for the California delegation and
Republican congressmen at the Philadelphia Navy Yard. The theme of
the evening, which was to last until 2 a.a.: Survivor. But in this
version of the wildly popular television show, it's not bikini-clad
coeds who get kicked off the island.
</P>
<P>
   It's Al Gore.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they have booked some actors to do stuff,'' said Jim
Specht, Lewis' spokesman. ``But I don't think there's a plan to do
anything terribly official looking. I think they'll announce the
list of candidates to be kicked off and, well, Al Gore's name might
be the only one on there.''
</P>
<P>
   Republican ladies who usually do not have time for lunch _ about
200 women, including members of the House and Senate _ sat down to
an afternoon tea, hosted by Lifetime Television for Women, in honor
of Elizabeth Dole.
</P>
<P>
   But a dolorous air had settled in at the ground-floor ballroom
in the Four Seasons Hotel, over the tables, some empty, set with
crumpets, cream and crystal flutes filled with Champagne.
</P>
<P>
   After all, many women attending the tea had hoped that it would
be Dole making her acceptance speech here in Philadelphia, for
either spot on the ticket. Now, instead of being feted on the
convention floor, she was being saluted with petits fours.
</P>
<P>
   Nancy G. Brinker, the founder of the Susan Komen Breast Cancer
Foundation, stopped to pose for a photograph with Dole and said
that she was disappointed that there was no woman on the Republican
ticket. Brinker, though, remained hopeful that there would be one
in the future.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I tend to think of progress in breast-cancer terms, in
years and years, not in months,'' she said. When did she expect a
woman? ``Soon. This is an evolution, not a revolution. Politics is
about the art of the possible.''
</P>
<P>
   When asked if she was disappointed not to see Dole on the
ticket, Rep. Tillie Fowler of Florida said, ``Oh my, yes. She's
been my friend for thirty years.'' Fowler and Dole once worked
together in the Lyndon Johnson White House.
</P>
<P>
   But Rep. Jennifer Dunn of Washington, a member of the Republican
House leadership and a deputy convention co-chair, was positively
bouyant. She said that George W. Bush was strong on issues that
deal with women, citing his plans for Social Security reform as an
example.
</P>
<P>
   ``Husbands tend to die seven or eight years earlier than their
wives, so Social Security reform is beneficial for women,'' she
said. She was also a big fan of Dick Cheney, who has opposed
legislation supporting equal rights for women. ``He is married to a
powerful woman, and he knows he needs to listen to a powerful
woman.''
</P>
<P>
   The lights dimmed. Piano music tinkled over a canned soundtrack.
Images of Dole in Bosnia, in Serbia, Dole cradling a starving
African child, Dole in hurricane gear, filtered across the screen.
Carole Black, the chief executive of Lifetime, spoke about Dole's
accomplishments. Black, who is a Democrat, is also giving a party
at the Democratic convention in Los Angeles: It is for the elected
women of the Congress and the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Larry Rockefeller, an environmental lawyer, stalked the
corridors of the Republican convention Monday, spreading his
gospel, a ``Statement by Larry Rockefeller'' that warns darkly of
Republican extremism.
</P>
<P>
   Rockefeller, whose uncle Nelson A. Rockefeller was the original
Rockefeller Republican, said that he was going booth to booth, and
tent to tent, to sound an alert.
</P>
<P>
   ``We must look beyond the gauze and the haze and the happy
promises and look at Bush's record in Texas,'' he said, his leather
satchel leaking manifestoes. ``He is not, despite what some voters
think, a mainstream Republican. As a Republican, I personally feel
I ought to let voters know.'' Rockefeller, who describes himself as
a ``mainstream Republican'' contributed $2,000 to Al Gore's
campaign last year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
