<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE 
</HEADLINE>
  c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   START-UP RECRUITING
</P>
<P>
   A California start-up, DNA Sciences, is introducing a Web site
that will recruit people to donate their DNA to help find genes
that cause disease. The company hopes to get 50,000 to 100,000
people to contribute to its ``gene trust'' by appealing to their
altruism.
</P>
<P>
   The new effort reflects a big change taking place in genetics.
Studies to link genes to disease are starting to be conducted on an
unprecedented scale. While such studies promise to lead to big
medical advances, the collection of genetic data on such a wide
scale is also raising ethical and privacy issues.
</P>
<P>
   A PEARSON PURCHASE
</P>
<P>
   Pearson said that it was buying National Computer Systems, the
largest scorer of student assessment tests in the United States,
for $2.5 billion in cash. Several analysts said that while they
supported efforts by Pearson's chief executive, Marjorie Scardino,
to expand the company's role in educational publishing, they were
concerned about the structure of the deal, which offers existing
stockholders the right to buy some additional shares at a
significant discount. Shares of Pearson fell 9 percent, to 18.28
pounds, or $27.40. National Computer rose $13.75, to $71.875.
</P>
<P>
   TECHNOLOGY RALLIES
</P>
<P>
   Stock prices moved higher, led by technology issues. The Nasdaq
composite index rose 103.99 points, or 2.8 percent, to 3,766.99,
while the Dow Jones industrial average gained 10.81 points, or 0.1
percent, to 10,521.98. The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index
climbed 10.94 points, or 0.8 percent, to 1,430.83.
</P>
<P>
   MANUFACTURING SLOWS
</P>
<P>
   Manufacturing in the Midwest grew in July at the slowest pace in
18 months while more companies paid higher prices for raw
materials, an industry survey showed.
</P>
<P>
   E-TALE MOVING UP
</P>
<P>
   A week into the horror writer Stephen King's closely watched
experiment with self-publishing over the Internet, King said that
he was about to break even. In a statement on his Web site, King
estimated that readers downloaded 152,132 copies of the first
chapter of ``The Plant'' in the first seven days.
</P>
<P>
   FPL SHOPPING
</P>
<P>
   FPL Group, the parent of Florida Power and Light, agreed to
acquire Entergy for about $7 billion in stock in a deal that would
create the nation's largest electric company. But the news sent
shares of FPL lower, reducing the original value of the deal, on
disappointment that FPL was not the takeover target. Shares of FPL
fell $4.5625, to $48.25, while Entergy fell $3.1875, to $27.0625.
</P>
<P>
   DELAYED TESTIMONY
</P>
<P>
   Justice Department antitrust prosecutors investigating
Christie's and Sotheby's won a court order postponing the taking of
testimony in a civil suit against the auction houses until at least
Sept. 11.
</P>
<P>
   TAX CUTS IN RUSSIA
</P>
<P>
   Changes in the Russian tax code seek to drag enormous portions
of revenue out of hiding and onto company books by reducing the tax
burden about 20 percent. But many businesses, which pay only a
fraction of what they really owe, say that only deeper cuts and a
fairer system will induce them to pay.
</P>
<P>
   CARBIDE AHEAD
</P>
<P>
   Union Carbide said that its second-quarter profits more than
doubled, surpassing Wall Street estimates.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
