<HEADLINE>
PURDUM   
</HEADLINE>
 
FIRE IN SEQUOIA FOREST IS ONE OF 45 RAGING IN THE WEST By TODD S. c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ More than 1,500 firefighters and a fleet of
helicopters and tankers continued to battle a 63,270-acre wildfire
in the eastern Sierra Nevada on Monday, with the blaze still only
about 15 percent contained and thunderstorms and dangerous dry
lightning forecast, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The fire, which destroyed eight homes in a tiny mountain town
over the weekend, started July 22 and has burned through the
Sequoia National Forest about 120 miles north of here. It is just
one of about 45 fires burning over nearly 500,000 acres in
California, Arizona, Colorado, Idaho and Montana. Officials at the
National Interagency Fire Center in Boise, Idaho, said that hot,
dry weather, lightning without rain and a spate of new fires were
taxing firefighting capacity throughout the region. Training began
today for the Army's 3rd Battalion 16th Field Artillery from Ft.
Hood, Texas, which is being called in to assist firefighters in
Idaho.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the worst fire season we've had since 1988,'' said
Michelle Barrett, a spokeswoman at the center.
</P>
<P>
   Eight new fires in the region were reported on Monday, and
Barrett said overworked and exhausted firefighters would soon have
to be rotated off duty for rest. She said officials would also have
to be selective about where they put their stretched resources.
</P>
<P>
   ``As much as we worry about the fires, there's not a blade of
grass or a tree out there that's important as the lives of our
firefighters,'' Barrett said.
</P>
<P>
   Except for a training accident in Alaska, there have been no
firefighter fatalities in forest fires so far this year.
</P>
<P>
   In the Sequoia Forest fire, in an isolated area west of
California Route 395, nine water-spraying helicopters and eight
fixed-wing aircraft dumping flame retardant chemicals supplemented
the efforts of firefighters on the grounds, said Doug Johnston, an
engineer with the Kern County Fire Department. The cause of the
fire is unknown, and 11 firefighters have suffered minor injuries.
</P>
<P>
   ``The estimate now is that it won't be fully controlled for
about two weeks,'' Johnston said.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, the fire destroyed houses and trailers in the
isolated hamlet of Pine Creek, part of a broader area known as
Kennedy Meadows, destroying eight buildings and lodges, including
five in an abandoned Boy Scout camp. The Sequoia Forest is a
habitat area for California spotted owls.
</P>
<P>
   A few isolated structures in the area remain at risk, but at
peak summer, the entire population is about 100, according to
Johnston. He said most, if not all, residents had already been
evacuated. Firefighters were bivouacked in two temporary camps. A
total of 51 hand crews, 74 engines, 13 bulldozers and 18
water-tenders have been dispatched to the blaze, where the
firefighters have been hindered by inaccessible terrain and high
temperatures.
</P>
<P>
   Two smaller fires were also still burning in Southern and
Central California, one on the Pechanga Indian Reservation in the
Cleveland National Forest, just east of Temecula, and another in
the Los Padres National Forest, 25 miles north of Cambria on the
Central Coast, which was expected to be contained by Tuesday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-31-00 2155EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
