<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-TAXES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUSSIA'S TAX REFORMS WELCOMED, BUT BUSINESSES SAY MORE CUTS ARE
NEEDED 
</HEADLINE>
  By SABRINA TAVERNISE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ For much of the last decade, Russia's government had
promised that it would reduce the country's huge tax burden. Last
week it finally did. But the changes, business owners say, do not
go nearly far enough.
</P>
<P>
   Since the collapse of the Soviet Union in 1991, businesses have
been plagued by a tax system so complicated and burdensome that
most have chosen to keep big chunks of their revenue hidden. Armies
of bureaucrats, many of them prone to bribery, make operating even
more expensive and turn company accountants into tax negotiators.
Even losses are taxed, while slender profits can turn to losses
after taxes.
</P>
<P>
   The overhaul of the Russian tax code aims to drag enormous
portions of revenue out of hiding and onto company books by
reducing the tax burden about 20 percent. But many businesses,
which pay only a fraction of what they really owe, say only deeper
cuts and a fairer system will get them to pay.
</P>
<P>
   A payroll tax is considered one of the biggest drags on
business. Oleg Ryabov, who owns a small blouse-maker with about 50
employees in northern Moscow, says the deepest cuts in the new tax
code passed over him. His seamstresses earn an average of 5,000
rubles a month, or $180, more than double the country's average
wage. Still, that is well below the level at which sharp reductions
in the payroll tax apply. Ryabov's business is eligible for a tax
cut of only two percentage points. He said he would continue, as
before, to show only a third of his workers' wages to the tax
authorities.
</P>
<P>
   Only about 15 percent of Russians' wages are eligible for the
deepest cuts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now if we pay what we owe, we just cannot compete,'' said
Ryabov, 39, whose small company is tucked away in the back of a
former machinery factory.
</P>
<P>
   The company pays about one-sixth of what it really owes in
taxes. Any more would make his blouses more expensive than the
Chinese imports at Moscow's biggest outdoor markets. Importers of
such garments often avoid paying tariffs, and the imports come to
the consumer virtually tax-free.
</P>
<P>
   Larger businesses have a harder time trimming officially
reported wages and revenue. One of Russia's biggest cosmetics
producers, Kalina, says it cannot get away with hiding revenue. It
welcomed the tax changes, in particular a flat-rate income tax
reduction to 13 percent from a maximum of 35 percent. The company,
which employs about 2,500 people, will have to withhold far less
from workers' wages.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I say we pay taxes, people look at me as if I am crazy,''
said Aleksandr Petrov, finance director at Kalina, in the Ural
Mountains.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the tax changes so far have been welcomed by many
Russians as a good start. They allow the poorest people for the
first time to take additional write-offs for education and health
care, and reduce the revenue tax, until now 4 percent of company
income, to 1 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The Russian industrialist Kakha Bendukidze, who heads Uralmash,
a big machinery producer, called on President Vladimir Putin at a
meeting last Friday to further reduce tax rates. High taxes are the
single biggest hindrance to doing business in Russia, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Until the tax rates are lowered, every businessman is a
criminal,'' Bendukidze said after the meeting.
</P>
<P>
   The government has promised more cuts in 2002 and 2003.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-31-00 2159EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000731.0446 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-31 22:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8835 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-AD-DAY-AD-COLUMN-NYT     07-31 0758
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AD-DAY-AD-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADVERTISING: THE POPULAR INDUSTRY PARTY THAT WASN'T, AND WHY 
</HEADLINE>
  By STUART ELLIOT   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Just as the curiosity of Sherlock Holmes was piqued by the dog
that did not bark, Madison Avenue is wondering about the party that
is not being thrown.
</P>
<P>
   The party is known as Advertising New York, an annual benefit
event held since 1994 under the sponsorship of three organizations
well-known in the agency industry: the Advertising Club of New
York, Advertising Women of New York and the American Advertising
Federation. The popular event, typically held in June at
Rockefeller Center in midtown Manhattan, has drawn more than a
thousand attendees each year to buy tickets to elaborate food
tastings featuring celebrity chefs from agencies, client companies
and the media.
</P>
<P>
   Profits after expenses have been donated to the charitable and
educational programs sponsored by the foundations of the three
organizations. Typically, each event yielded an estimated profit of
$100,000, said Wally Snyder, president and chief executive of the
advertising federation in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   However, this year June has come and gone without the party
taking place _ and therefore without the money being raised. Also
missing this year was the presentation of annual honors named the
Good Egg Awards that had been awarded in connection with the event.
The awards, meant to promote corporate citizenship had been
presented since 1996.
</P>
<P>
   While there has been no shortage this year of awards or parties
in the New York advertising world, primarily because of the ad
spending boom, people became curious when there was no word about
Advertising New York, which has also gone by the name Ad Day in New
York.
</P>
<P>
   So what happened? The answer is not quite elementary, my dear
Watson, but more the result of a combination of circumstances.
</P>
<P>
   First off, it turns out that a committee formed by the three
organizations to coordinate Ad Day met in December 1999 and decided
not to hold it in 2000 and form a task force to rethink the event.
</P>
<P>
   ``The collective judgment was to step back a year and take a
breath,'' Snyder said, ``to see how it could be refocused and what
more we could be doing.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a great program and I loved it,'' he added, ``but it's
a big effort.''
</P>
<P>
   Ellen Flahive, president at the women's advertising
organization, said: ``Ad Day has always served as an important
fund-raiser, but I can't think of a recipe for a fund-raiser that
you can repeat year in and year out. Advertising is a business that
prides itself on the new, the different, the cutting edge. People
like change and new things.'' Flahive is also publisher at the
American Park Network in New York, part of the Meredith Corp.
</P>
<P>
   ``The enthusiasm has died down,'' agreed Frank Ginsberg,
chairman, chief executive and creative director at Avrett, Free &AMP;
Ginsberg in New York, who has been one of the most ardent
supporters of the event.
</P>
<P>
   One reason, Ginsberg said, is that because ``the business is
booming,'' there are ``many events where you can get together with
your peers.'' Another reason, he said, was that fewer people seemed
familiar with the purpose of the event as the years went by,
leading to perceptions that it was just another social affair or
schmooze-athon.
</P>
<P>
   ``People were asking what all the booths with food at
Rockefeller Center were there for,'' Ginsberg said. ``It wasn't
clear.'' Avrett, Free is part of the Bozell Group unit of True
North Communications.
</P>
<P>
   As enthusiasm flagged, there was also a change in the
composition of the crowds, particularly the volunteers who agreed
to be chefs. (The chefs, including this columnist, did not actually
cook food but stood by as caterers served the dishes and talked
with the attendees who bought tickets to the event.)
</P>
<P>
   ``In the beginning, we got the top people in the industry to
come,'' said Brett Caldwell, director for events and programs at
the advertising club. ``We're trying to restructure and rebuild it,
to make it the way it was.''
</P>
<P>
   Snyder at the advertising federation said that he too hoped
``there would be more CEOs'' from the agencies attending as well as
``more clients.''
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, the advertising club is planning to become the
sponsor of the Good Egg Awards. A committee has been formed,
Caldwell said, whose members anticipate resuming the presentations
in summer 2001.
</P>
<P>
   Will there be an Ad Day to accompany an awards presentation when
the Good Eggs are revived? As the saying goes, stay tuned.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
