<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-31 22:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8845 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-GOLDMAN-MARKETPLACE-A     07-31 1222
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOLDMAN-MARKETPLACE-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARKET PLACE: GOLDMAN, SACHS THROWS GUTTERBALL WITH AMF BOWLING
INVOLVEMENT 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) By PATRICK McGEEHAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   When Goldman, Sachs led a buyout of AMF Bowling in 1996, some
analysts wondered why a silk-stocking investment bank would risk
sullying its image in such a pedestrian pursuit.
</P>
<P>
   But, after four years under Goldman's control, it is AMF's image
that has suffered as the company has racked up losses and its stock
price has sunk to 75 cents a share.
</P>
<P>
   Having traded for less than $1 a share for more than 30
consecutive days, AMF _ arguably the biggest name in bowling _ is
in danger of being delisted from the New York Stock Exchange and
investors are wondering if the company will have to sort out its
financial troubles in bankruptcy court. People close to the
company, which is based in Richmond, Va., said that AMF's board
discussed a variety of revamping options, including a prepackaged
bankruptcy filing, last week in New York.
</P>
<P>
   AMF is saddled with about $1.2 billion in debt. Its bonds have
been trading for 20 percent to 30 percent of their face value.
</P>
<P>
   When the company releases its second-quarter earnings within the
next two weeks, those investors who still are paying attention will
focus less on what happened in the traditionally slower spring
season than on what the company has to say about its future plans.
After all, the earnings cannot surprise analysts because nobody on
Wall Street follows AMF's stock any more.
</P>
<P>
   Ronald Baron, chief executive of Baron Capital, once was one of
AMF's biggest boosters, predicting that the stock price would soar
to $100 by 2003. Now, with his company and its mutual funds holding
more than 11 million shares of AMF, Baron will not discuss AMF.
Through a spokesman, he denied that his funds, the biggest investor
in the company after Goldman, were among the sellers when AMF
shares dropped to a record low of 18.75 cents on June 30.
</P>
<P>
   Stephen Hare, AMF's chief financial officer, said in an
interview that ``the capital structure needs to be fixed'' but the
company has not settled on a solution. He declined to discuss the
possibility of a voluntary bankruptcy filing and said that the
company had not started negotiating with its creditors. But it is
clear that changes must be made before AMF has to start making much
bigger payments to bondholders in about a year.
</P>
<P>
   ``The meter is running,'' Hare said ``It's fair for the markets
to say, `Show us the plan.' When we have a plan that we're
comfortable with, you'll see us announce it.''
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, Hare acknowledged, the company, its industry
and its employees are all suffering. ``Just the fact that the stock
has not been successful in the last year, I don't think speaks well
for the industry,'' he said, ``We feel a certain obligation to be
successful for the industry at large.''
</P>
<P>
   Goldman officials declined to comment.
</P>
<P>
   Hare said that company officials have talked to representatives
of the New York Stock Exchange about how to get back into
compliance with the exchange's listing standards. AMF has less than
30 days to come up with a plan. One possibility: a reverse stock
split that would reduce the number of shares outstanding to push up
their price and buy management more time to formulate a solution.
</P>
<P>
   How AMF, under Goldman's control, got into such a bind is a
complicated story that involves Asian economics, American social
trends and the ways of Wall Street.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, Goldman led a leveraged buyout of AMF. A year later,
the firm took the company public again, raising $263 million by
selling shares for $19.50 each.
</P>
<P>
   The pitch for the 1997 offering was that AMF would buy bowling
alleys around the United States and capitalize on a growing craze
for bowling in China and other parts of Asia. AMF would make money
two ways: by operating a chain of bowling centers and by selling
the equipment to outfit new ones overseas.
</P>
<P>
   But while AMF was gobbling up alleys and trying to run them more
efficiently, league bowling _ the lifeblood of the bowling business
_ was dying. Leagues, which represent a predictable stream of
revenue from September through March, once accounted for as much as
80 percent of a bowling center's business, said Sandy Hansell, a
bowling consultant in Southfield, Mich. That share has dropped to
about 50 percent, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Then in the summer of 1998, an economic crisis swept across
Asia, wiping out demand for capital-intensive leisure activities
like bowling.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, Goldman was the majority owner of a heavily indebted
company in a slow-growth business. The bowling products business,
which had generated about $70 million in cash flow in 1997,
produced less than $10 million in cash flow last year, Hare said.
He said demand for bowling is still growing in some countries,
including England, but ``what we don't see right now are any
markets that have that boom potential.''
</P>
<P>
   AMF's board _ which has Richard Friedman, who runs Goldman's
merchant-banking operations, as chairman _ removed the company's
management. Last year, the directors hired Roland Smith, who
formerly ran the Arby's fast-food chain, as chief executive.
</P>
<P>
   Smith is slowing the pace of acquisitions while the company
devises a strategy for marketing its 417 bowling centers as a
national chain, Hare said. The company is spending about $10
million to gear all of its centers for what it calls Xtreme
bowling, a nighttime activity aimed at teen-agers and other
recreational bowlers, and is considering an extensive ad campaign,
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Without a big increase in revenue, the bowling centers are
profitable on an operating basis, said Hansell. And, despite its
slower growth, the bowling business is healthy, with most lane
operators making more money than they ever have, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The tough question for AMF and Goldman is how they can relieve
the company of some of its debt burden before it snuffs the life
out of bowling-center operations. It is a rare problem for Friedman
and Goldman's other merchant bankers, who have rolled their share
of strikes, most recently in having a big stake in VoiceStream
Wireless when Deutsche Telekom agreed to buy that company for a
huge premium.
</P>
<P>
   In May 1996, Goldman and its merchant-banking funds put up $260
million for a majority stake in the buyout of AMF. Two other
investment banks, Blackstone Group and Kelso &AMP; Co., bought smaller
stakes, and the company borrowed about $1 billion through bank
loans and bond sales.
</P>
<P>
   Along the way, Goldman received about $50 million in fees for
advising the company and underwriting securities, including its
initial public offering of stock. Now its 45 million shares are
worth less than that, about $34 million. Goldman officials will not
say how much the firm has lost on its AMF investment, but a person
close to the matter said the firm is feeling ``a lot of pain.''
</P>
<P>
   No matter what happens to AMF, Hansell said, the bowling
business will survive.
</P>
<P>
   ``If AMF went belly up, would it be a problem?,'' he said. ``It
would hurt, but it wouldn't be cataclysmic. The other 5,000 bowling
centers in this country would roll along.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
