<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-31 22:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8846 &Cx1f; tta-z
u p BC-GOP-PLATFORM-1STLD-WR     07-31 1255
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOP-PLATFORM-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PLATFORM STRIVES TO REACH RIGHT AND CENTER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Subs to rewrite throughout, subs byline; adds parenthetical
sentence in 5th graf that full text of platform can be found on
www.nytimes.com.)  
 By ROBIN TONER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ The Republican National Convention on Monday
approved a platform intended to both reassure the party's
conservative base and signal to the broader electorate that the
party had been transformed by Gov. George W. Bush's bid for the
center.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Tommy Thompson of Wisconsin, the chairman of the platform
committee, hailed the document's ``positive, uplifting'' tone and
described it to the delegates as a platform that ``every Republican
can be proud of, and one that will carry George Bush to the White
House.''
</P>
<P>
   But the effort to satisfy moderate and conservative
constituencies alike, and help ensure a peaceful convention,
carried political risks of its own. Democrats and their allies
quickly seized on the most conservative parts of the platform, like
its call for a ban on abortion, as evidence that little had changed
in the Republican Party beyond rhetoric and imagery.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to use the platform like we're going to use George
Bush's record in Texas and Dick Cheney's voting record _ to show
the American people that this is still the same old Republican
Party,'' said Jenny Backus, a spokeswoman for the Democratic
National Committee.
</P>
<P>
   The document approved Monday had been carefully managed by
Bush's allies, and much of it bears his unmistakable mark. It
incorporates his policy proposals, and his language, on a set of
issues at the heart of his campaign, from education to tax cuts,
from health care to immigration. In keeping with his theme of
``compassionate conservatism,'' it declares that ``for every
American, there must be a ladder of opportunity, and for those most
in need, a safety net of care.'' (For the full text of the
platform, go to www.nytimes.com.)
</P>
<P>
   Thompson and other Bush allies worked hard over weeks of private
and public meetings to ensure that the platform process was free of
the divisiveness of prior years and did not distract from the
upbeat message of the convention and the campaign.
</P>
<P>
   They chose to fight conservatives on some issues _ notably the
governor's education plan _ that they felt were imperative to
underscore the idea that Bush was ``a different kind of
Republican.'' But they removed the abortion issue from contention
early on, declaring that they did not want the plank to change,
even though Bush says his personal position is less restrictive.
</P>
<P>
   The only suspense Monday was whether Republicans who support
abortion rights would win enough support among delegates either for
a minority report or to bring the issue to the floor. They did not,
although they insisted they had come close despite heavy opposition
from the party establishment. They vowed to return to the grass
roots re-energized, and promised a stronger fight on the issue four
years from now.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, all was harmony when the platform was presented to
the convention Monday afternoon, and quickly approved on a voice
vote. Abortion was never mentioned from the podium, although many
delegates were wearing vests, handed out by the Republican National
Coalition for Life, that bore anti-abortion slogans. In the only
allusion to the division on social issues that at times had roiled
the platform committee's deliberations, Thompson declared, ``As
Republicans, there is so much more that unites us than divides
us.''
</P>
<P>
   As passed, the platform embraces Bush's call for ``bold reforms
in education,'' including a strong federal role in more
accountability and more school choice; for ``saving and
strengthening Social Security'' by allowing some private investment
of payroll taxes; for an array of tax cuts; and for a more
inclusive tone on immigration. In sharp contrast to the platform of
1996, it does not call for the abolition of a single federal
agency, and the partisan attacks are markedly diminished.
</P>
<P>
   It drops some of the most controversial elements of the 1996
immigration plank, including tough language about denying benefits
to immigrants and denying automatic citizenship to the
American-born children of illegal immigrants. The original draft,
written by Bush's allies, also sought to drop the demand that
English be officially recognized as the nation's common language,
although delegates essentially restored that provision in
subcommittee.
</P>
<P>
   But for all the repositioning, the platform also reiterates most
of the agenda of the party's social conservatives. It calls for a
constitutional ban on abortion, without exceptions, and the
appointment of judges who ``respect the sanctity of innocent human
life.'' The only change in the plank is a new denunciation of the
recent Supreme Court decision overturning state laws that banned
the procedure opponents call ``partial birth'' abortion.
</P>
<P>
   Bush has noted that he would personally allow abortion in cases
of rape, incest or danger to the life of a pregnant woman, and also
says he does not support a litmus test for judicial appointments.
But abortion rights groups say that by agreeing to the platform he
in fact embraced a litmus test, and that this is a crucial
indication of how he would make appointments to the Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will trumpet that message across the country,'' said Alice
Germond, acting president of the National Abortion and Reproductive
Rights Action League. ``On this issue, he's neither compassionate
nor kind.''
</P>
<P>
   Ari Fleischer, a spokesman for the Bush campaign, allowed
himself some distance from the platform, particularly when
responding to Democratic attacks.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're very pleased that the platform has departed
substantially from earlier platforms, notably in the areas of
education and immigration,'' he said, but added, ``Governor Bush is
going to run on his record and his views, and it's on that ground
that he'll make his stand.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush differs as well with the platform's position on gays in the
military; he supports the current ``don't ask, don't tell'' policy,
while the platform flatly declares that homosexuality is
``incompatible'' with military service. The platform also opposes
counseling on contraceptives in school-based clinics, any
recognition of ``special legal protection'' for homosexuals and any
movement to recognize same-sex marriages.
</P>
<P>
   The document that emerged was generally praised by delegates,
who were strikingly optimistic on this first convention day.
Moments after the platform's passage, as the strains of Bob Seger's
``Old Time Rock &AMP; Roll'' filled the hall, Cathie Adams, president
of the conservative Texas Eagle Forum, declared herself ``very
happy'' with it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we're going to win,'' she said. ``And I'm going to
work hard to make sure we do.''
</P>
<P>
   Former Rep. Robert L. Livingston of Louisiana, now a lobbyist,
described it as ``solidly right of center, a good, solid,
reasonable platform that George W. Bush as nominee won't have to
run away from.''
</P>
<P>
   But Backus, of the Democratic National Committee, asserted that
the platform was a mother lode of out-of-the-mainstream positions,
not only on abortion but also on the environment, school vouchers
and Medicare.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is about stripping away fluffy rhetoric and pretty photo
ops,'' Backus said. ``People want to know what a party stands for
and what a candidate stands for, and that's where the platform is
important.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
