<HEADER>
A8849 &Cx1f; tad-z
r s BC-SURHOFF-BRAVES0801-CO     07-31 0414
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SURHOFF-BRAVES0801-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Surhoff has strong ties to Baltimore community
 &HT;    By Carroll Rogers
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA - As happy as the Braves are about the acquisition of
B.J. Surhoff, it might take the 14-year-veteran some time to get
used to the idea. Surhoff has played in Baltimore since signing
there as a free agent in December 1995, and he has strong ties to
the city.
</P>
<P>
   His wife, Polly, is from Baltimore and 8-year-old son Mason, one
of their four children, is autistic. Johns Hopkins University in
Baltimore has a special program for Mason that Surhoff worries
can't be matched here.
</P>
<P>
   ``It gets much more complicated because things are important to
me not just as a player anymore,'' Surhoff said. ``If it were just
me, it would be one thing. The other side ... affects me more
deeply off the field. Hopefully I'll do a good job with it.''
</P>
<P>
   One person who understands his concerns but who also thinks
Surhoff will be a ``perfect fit'' in Atlanta is his former college
teammate at North Carolina and fellow New York native, Walt Weiss.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been friends a long time,'' Weiss said. ``I've always
held out hope we'd get a chance to play together in the big
leagues. It's been 15 years and it's finally happened.''
</P>
<P>
   Surhoff was drafted first overall in 1985 by the Milwaukee
Brewers out of Rye, N.Y. Weiss, who was picked 11th overall by the
A's in the 1985 draft, grew up 20 minutes away in Suffern, N.Y.
They played together for three years at North Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a real professional guy, a real team guy, real
dependable, plays hard,'' Weiss said. ``He's one of the more
heads-up, intelligent players in the game. He thinks like a manager
would. On top of that, he's talented.... I don't know if you could
have made a better pickup.''
</P>
<P>
   A bonus for the Braves is that Surhoff spent the first part of
his career catching and can still play there as well as first and
third base.
</P>
<P>
   Surhoff, who is making $4.1 million this season, has one more
year on his contract worth $4.5 million plus an option for 2002
worth $4.5 million, which kicks in if he plays 120 games or has 372
plate appearances in 2001. Surhoff, like any player who is traded
in the middle of a multiyear contract, can demand a trade after the
season is over.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he does, he'll be the first to have done that here,''
Braves general manager John Schuerholz said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
