<P>
   &UR; (Eds: This story also moved in the ``l'' lifestyle news
file.) &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; By LEAH GARCHIK &QC;  &LR; 
 &UR; c.2000, San Francisco Chronicle &LR;  &QC; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
ANOTHER FONDA IN THE POLITICAL RING?
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to be president,''  &UR; Peter Fonda &LR;  told the New
York Post's  &UR; Cindy Adams &LR; , ``but I would if there are such
extraordinary emergencies that our already bad infrastructure
totally breaks down. In that case, I'd not hesitate to declare
martial law. ...
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd get rid of the whole government, then replace both houses
so life continues, since mail has to be delivered, food must be
disseminated. ... I'd fire every federal judge. ... I'd keep in
place only the Supreme Court. I'd lock them into their building.
...
</P>
<P>
   ``Once I'd readied the new infrastructure and seen that we'd all
returned to the Bill of Rights, I'd go back to my ranch in Montana
and hope I get another movie.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
HE LIKES TO WATCH
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Robin Williams &LR;  went to Paris at the invitation of  &UR; Lance &LR; 
 &UR; Armstrong &LR;  to watch the final leg of the Tour de France, which he
describes to  &UR; Lillian Ross &LR;  in the latest New Yorker.
</P>
<P>
   ``So I flew right over, and the next thing I knew I got to sit
in the grandstand,'' says Williams, ``right in the middle of the
big  &LR; mishpocha &LR; , next to the finish line near the Place de la
Concorde. I felt 10 years old again! To be that close! Watching all
those amazing guys whoosh by, so fast, in a blur! It was like
waiting outside Yankee Stadium and suddenly finding  &UR; Joe &LR; 
 &UR; DiMaggio &LR; ! It gave you a big kick in the heart.''
</P>
<P>
   After the race, Williams attended a celebration dinner, where he
reverently describes meeting the U.S. postmaster general _ the
Postal Service sponsored Armstrong's team _ the team chef and
several past winners (all of whom were probably at least equally
excited to meet him).
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong gave him an autographed yellow jersey. ``I love it!''
said Williams. ``I'll never wash it! I'll frame it. I'll keep it
all my life.''
</P>
