<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-31 22:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8851 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u p BC-CVN-LAURA-BUSH-1STLD-     07-31 1219
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CVN-LAURA-BUSH-1STLD-WRITETHRU-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
LAURA BUSH STEPS INTO THE LIMELIGHT &HT;    (EDS: Complete writethru; updates with speech delivered, quotes)
 &HT;    By DAN FREEDMAN
 &HT;    c. 2000 Hearst Newspapers
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ Defying her reputation as a prim,
noncontroversial former librarian, Texas first lady Laura Bush took
a swipe at the Clinton-Gore administration Monday night, telling
delegates to the Republican National Convention that if her husband
becomes president he ``will not change with the winds of polls.''
</P>
<P>
   The wife of Gov. George W. Bush took a giant step into the
limelight on the convention's opening night by alluding to
presidential character _ an issue that regularly registers as a
high priority in public opinion surveys.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've known him through big legislative successes and a few
defeats,'' Laura Bush said. In a reference to her husband's former
ownership of the Texas Rangers baseball team, she said: ''I sat by
his side during some winning and many losing baseball seasons. But
George never loses sight of home plate.``
</P>
<P>
   Laura Bush's remarks were a veiled slap at her husband's
Democratic opponent, Vice President Al Gore, whose critics say
waffles on issues. It also is a jab at President Clinton, whose
presidency has been marked by similar accusations, as well as the
Monica Lewinsky sex scandal.
</P>
<P>
   The governor's ``core principles will not change with the winds
of polls or politics or fame or fortune or misfortune,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Drawing strong applause, Bush recalled supporters saying they
want their children ``to respect the president of the United States
of American.''
</P>
<P>
   Focusing largely on education, Bush said she and her husband had
tried to impart to their twin daughters the lessons their parents
had taught them, that ``reading is entertaining and interesting and
important. '' Her husband is running for president ``to make sure
every child in America has that same opportunity to grow up
reading.''
</P>
<P>
   Looking on were the Bush's daughters, Jenna and Barbara; Laura
Bush's mother, Jenna; and former President George Bush and his wife
Barbara Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Monday's theme at the GOP convention, ``Opportunity With a
Purpose: Leave No Child Behind,'' was an effort to flesh out Bush's
campaign mantra of ``compassionate conservatism'' by showcasing
speakers focused on improving education and conditions for young
people. Colin Powell, former chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff,
spoke about volunteer service.
</P>
<P>
   The convention platform is Laura Bush's biggest stage by far.
She agreed to marry Bush in 1977 on condition that she would never
have to deliver a political speech on his behalf.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the only political promise I ever broke,'' the governor
has told innumerable campaign crowds over the past year.
</P>
<P>
   For Laura Welch Bush, it has been something of a long, strange
trip between the tumbleweed plains of Midland, Texas, where she
cruised Agnes' drive-in for hamburgers, to potential first lady
whose family life is publicly picked over in sometimes excruciating
detail.
</P>
<P>
   In between, there were stops in Houston and Austin as a teacher
and librarian. And there was the barbecue in 1977 where she met
Bush, an encounter she had actually resisted because she did not
think she would have anything in common with someone from a
political family.
</P>
<P>
   The Bushes were married in November 1977 when Laura Bush was 31.
</P>
<P>
   Ambition, power and fame are not qualities to which Laura Bush
aspired. Monday night she described herself as being ``a little bit
overwhelmed.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet, on the campaign trail, she has grown into the role of
high-profile political spouse. She has stumped on her own, talking
about education. On the campaign plane when she is traveling with
the candidate, Laura Bush is relaxed and informal up to a point,
reminding some reporters of helpful librarians.
</P>
<P>
   Don Evans, a longtime family friend who serves as Bush's
campaign manager, described Laura Bush as ``a lady who's full of
grace'' and ``somebody America will love.''
</P>
<P>
   Has there been a campaign-trail learning curve for her? ``Well,
there is for everybody,'' Evans responded. ``But I guarantee you,
she's there.''
</P>
<P>
   Laura Bush, 53, was the only child of a Harold Welch, a home
builder, and Jenna Welch, who did bookkeeping for him and read
books to Laura aloud.
</P>
<P>
   She knew her future husband just barely in junior high school
before the Bushes moved from Midland to Houston and Bush was sent
to boarding school in Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   About the only blip on the screen of her life is when at the age
of 17, she ran a stop sign in Midland. Her car collided with a
vehicle driven by another teen-ager, a boy she knew. He was killed.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was painful, of course,'' she told one interviewer. It
was ``a very tragic time in my life.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Bush graduated from Southern Methodist University in Dallas in
1968. Like her future husband at Yale, the social turmoil and
experimentation of the 1960s passed her by.
</P>
<P>
   She spent the first part of the 1970s as an elementary school
teacher and librarian in Houston and Austin, earning a master's
degree in library science at the Austin campus of the University of
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Teaching in a predominantly minority school in Houston and not
marrying until after age 30 shows she was ``in many ways very
contemporary,'' she once told one interviewer.
</P>
<P>
   In many ways the Bushes are a classic odd couple. He is at times
a garrulous jokester who bounces off the walls; she is mostly quiet
and demure. But by all accounts, Laura Bush has been the yin to her
husband's yang.
</P>
<P>
   She has a calming effect on him and years ago helped him quit
drinking before it became a problem. But she acknowledges that he,
in turn, adds a few thrills to her life that she might not
otherwise have expected.
</P>
<P>
   Bush was not wild about the idea of her husband running for
governor of Texas in 1994. And earlier this year she told the
Associated Press, ``I was the last person on board'' when the
governor was weighing a White House bid.
</P>
<P>
   But if her service as first lady of Texas is any indication,
Bush may well warm to the role of national first lady should her
husband vanquish Gore. From the governor's mansion, Laura Bush has
raised money and lobbied fiercely for Texas libraries and programs
to teach reading to pre-school children.
</P>
<P>
   The education theme of Monday night's speech drew polite sniffs
from Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   ``The campaigns are asking the spouses to do different things,''
said Joseph Andrew, chairman of the Democratic National Committee,
who as at the Republican National Convention at the behest of
various media organizations. Gore's wife ``Tipper speaks out on
substantive issues'' such as mental health, Andrew said. ``With
Laura Bush, the (Republican) campaign has asked her to talk
non-specific generalities because they can't talk about the issues
or the record ... Texas is one of the worst places to raise
children.''
</P>
<P>
   Andew was referring to studies showing Texas ranking at the
bottom of various social indicators. In one such study earlier this
year by the nonpartisan, Baltimore-based Annie E. Casey Foundation,
Texas ranked 44th among 50 states in rates of child poverty.
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
