<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-31 22:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8852 &Cx1f; tta-z
u p BC-GDP-RDP-2TAKES-NYT     07-31 1061
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GDP-RDP-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POWELL CALLS FOR INCLUSION OF MINORITIES
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photos NYT 9,10,11,15,19,22,23,25 are being sent to NYT
photo clients. Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by
calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
 By RICHARD L. BERKE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ The Republican Party put on a newly moderate and
disciplined face at the opening of its national convention Monday
night as one of the party's most compelling figures, retired Gen.
Colin L. Powell, challenged delegates to rally behind Gov. George
W. Bush with a genuine commitment to minorities.
</P>
<P>
   Powell, the former chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff, put
aside the reference to abortion rights that roiled the convention
four years ago and instead stressed the need for inclusiveness, a
matter that also worries party officials but is considered to be
slightly less divisive.
</P>
<P>
   ``The party must follow Governor Bush's lead and reach out to
minority communities and particularly the African-American
community _ and not just during an election-year campaign,'' Powell
said pointedly in his remarks prepared for delivery to the
convention. ``It must be a sustained effort. It must be every day.
It must be for real.''
</P>
<P>
   He did not spare the party for its record on affirmative action,
saying, ``Some in our party miss no opportunity to roundly and
loudly condemn affirmative action that helped a few thousand black
kids get an education.'' But, he added, ``hardly a whimper is heard
from them over affirmative action for lobbyists who load our
federal tax codes with preferences for special interests.''
</P>
<P>
   When Bush appeared before the NAACP earlier this month, Powell
said, it was not mere window dressing. He quoted Bush's declaration
that ``the party of Lincoln has not always carried the mantle of
Lincoln.'' And he said he spoke with Bush Monday and that ``he
wants the Republican Party to wear that mantle again. But he knows
that it will take hard work.''
</P>
<P>
   The address by Powell, and a speech by Bush's wife, Laura, about
education and her husband's values, formed the centerpiece Monday
night of a tightly and painstakingly choreographed presentation by
the Bush campaign and by the Republican Party that was aimed far
beyond the First Union Center. It was intended to persuade the
public at large _ particularly women, independents and even
Democrats _ that their rightful place is in the Republican Party.
</P>
<P>
   After the Bush campaign decreed there would be no searing swipes
at Democrats, Mrs. Bush, in describing her husband, confined
herself to an implicit comparison with Bill Clinton and Al Gore,
whom the campaign often portrays as obsessed by bald political
calculations.
</P>
<P>
   ``His core principles will not change with the winds of polls or
politics or fame or fortune or misfortune,'' Mrs. Bush said of her
husband in prepared remarks. ``I know because I've known him
through big legislative successes and a few defeats. I sat by his
side during some winning and many losing baseball sessions. But
George never loses sight of home plate.''
</P>
<P>
   In a testimonial to her husband of 22 years, she went on: ``He
shares credit and doesn't cast blame. He sets a tone that's
positive and constructive, a tone that is very different from the
bitterness and division that too often characterizes Washington,
D.C.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Bush, a former teacher and librarian, extolled her
husband's commitment to education and literacy. And she said her
husband was devoted to Head Start, a subject upon which the
Republican ticket has become suddenly vulnerable because of votes
cast against it by Dick Cheney, the vice presidential candidate,
when he was a congressman.
</P>
<P>
   ``As first lady, I will make early childhood development one of
my priorities,'' she said, ``and George will strengthen Head Start
to make sure it's an early reading and early learning program.''
</P>
<P>
   While George W. Bush was still wending his way eastward to
Philadelphia as part of a six-day tour of swing states, he
dominated the convention Monday. In a play on his nickname _ and an
appeal to women _ the letter ``W'' was emblazoned big and red on
signs throughout the arena. Underneath, in smaller letters, were
the words, ``Stands for women.''
</P>
<P>
   The remarks by Powell were perhaps most striking not only for
what he said but for what he did not say. When he addressed the
Republican convention on the first night in San Diego four years
ago, he also spoke of compassion and people in need. But in that
speech, he dropped in a line that many delegates did not want to
hear: He reminded them of his support for abortion rights and said
that he had been invited to San Diego because the party wanted to
air divergent views.
</P>
<P>
   There was no such reference to abortion _ or talk of dissent _
in the prepared remarks Monday night. People close to Powell
insisted they were not pressured into excising any reference; they
said the general felt it simply did not fit the theme of the night:
``Opportunity With a Purpose. Leave No Child Behind.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush campaign officials view Powell as a powerful ally because
he is a popular national figure who exudes tolerance and inclusion.
To make the most of Powell's support, Bush has repeatedly dropped
hints that he would name him to a high-level Cabinet post, like
secretary of state _ and Powell has only encouraged the
speculation. Powell had brushed aside Bush's initial overtures
about his joining the ticket.
</P>
<P>
   But the effort by Powell to avoid saying anything that could
stoke unrest among the approximately 22,000 people who crammed into
the hall _ including 2,066 delegates and 2,066 alternates _
underscored the degree to which Republicans are united behind Bush
in their determination to win back the White House. The program ran
with such tight-fistedness that at one point it was 20 minutes
ahead of the minute-by-minute schedule.
</P>
<P>
   In his remarks, Powell focused on Bush's accomplishments in
Texas; he stressed the ``compassion'' in the governor's
``compassionate conservative'' slogan.
</P>
<P>
   ``For Texas, Governor Bush has reached out to all Texans _
white, black, Latino, Asian, native American,'' he said. ``He has
been successful in bringing more and more minorities into the tent
by responding to their deepest needs. Some call it compassionate
conservatism. To me, it's just about caring for people.''
</P>
<P>
   The 37th Republican convention opened when Erik Weihenmayer, a
blind mountain climber, led the delegates in the Pledge of
Allegiance. Throughout the day, a parade of women, blacks, Latinos
and recovered Democrats marched to the rostrum in a show that more
resembled an Up With People jamboree than a hard-driving,
calculated effort to retake the White House. Despite the
understated references to the current administration, the words
Clinton, abortion and impeachment appeared to have been banished
from the scripts Monday. Even Newt Gingrich was far removed from
the action; his role Monday night was as a commentator for Fox
News.
</P>
<P>
   That left the millions tuning in on television with a buffed
view of the Republican Party _ and Bush _ that was far more
moderate than the delegates in the hall who voted Monday for a
platform that hewed to some fiercely conservative tenets, like the
party's call for a ban on abortion. With the usual internecine
maneuvering largely absent, and Cheney already selected as the
running mate, there was little suspense. That was reflected in the
lack of enthusiasm in a roll call to make Bush's nomination
official _ the party's first three-day rolling roll call _ that
drew only the most perfunctory rounds of cheers by delegates.
</P>
<P>
   Karl Rove, Bush's chief strategist, said he did not believe
there was a contradiction between the moderate, inclusive message
and the fact that polls of the delegates show that they are notably
conservative.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think there's a gap between what Republicans believe
and what their candidate does,'' said Rove, in an interview on
``Political Points,'' the New York Times/ABC News webcast.
``Otherwise, they wouldn't have nominated him. And let me correct.
You said inclusive and moderate. What we're saying is it's
inclusive and compassionately conservative.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite all the stage-managing, convention organizers had an
easy job because delegate after delegate said the party had not
been so unified since 1984, when Ronald Reagan cruised to a second
term. On the opening night of that convention, in Detroit,
Republicans bashed Walter F. Mondale relentlessly. But Monday
night, party officials expressed such confidence with Bush's
positioning that they said they felt they could go easy on Gore.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to imagine a convention that could be more
unified,'' Butch Davis, a delegate from Houston, said.
</P>
<P>
   It was no accident that the party held its 37th convention here
this week, the first Republican gathering in Philadelphia since
Thomes E. Dewey won the nomination in 1948. The party this year was
determined to underscore its commitment to a state that is not
reliably Republican.
</P>
<P>
   In keeping with the effort to portray Bush as a leader who could
work across party lines, his name was placed in nomination by his
lieutenant governor, Rick Perry. Perry told reporters that Bush
helped persuade him to defect from the Democratic to the Republican
party more than a decade ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``I proudly place the name of the current governor of the great
state of Texas and the next president of the United States into
nomination, George W. Bush,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Breaking from tradition, the Republicans abandoned their
traditional one-night roll calls of states _ which officials said
has become too interminable for a single sitting of prime time
television _ and Monday night began a rolling state-by-state tally
that will be spread over three nights. The party was careful to
juggle which states cast its votes so that Bush would not be
officially nominated before Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   When the roll call came to Arizona, the spokeswoman for the
delegation was not that state's senior senator, John McCain, Bush's
most ardent foe in the primaries, but his wife, Cindy.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's father and mother strode into the hall at 8:40 p.m. Their
arrival was not announced. But as delegates began catching sight of
these most famous of Republicans, they rose to their feet and a
swell of applause came from the floor. When they were formally
announced moments later, they were greeted with a 30-second
standing ovation and chants of ``Bush! Bush! Bush!''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
