<HEADER>
A8860 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-ISRAEL-KATSAV-NYT &LR;      07-31 0474
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-KATSAV-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ISRAEL'S NEW PRESIDENT KNOWN FROM PARLIAMENT AS `TOLERANT AND
POLITE' 
</HEADLINE>
   By JOHN KIFNER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ Moshe Katsav, Israel's new president, is a modest,
soft-spoken man who was the country's youngest mayor at 24, and has
since soldiered loyally in the right-wing Likud's political
trenches.
</P>
<P>
   Katsav, 55, was first elected to Parliament in 1977 in Menachem
Begin's landslide and was referred to as ``the tolerant and
polite'' legislator, a certain distinction in the often rancorous
body.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the Likud leader, Ariel Sharon, is said to have chosen
him as a candidate for the largely ceremonial post because he had
so few enemies. But until the stunning vote in Parliament Monday,
not a single political pundit gave him a chance against Shimon
Peres, a Nobel laureate who was twice prime minister, although
never by election.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not easy to compete with someone like Shimon Peres,''
Katsav mused in a pre-election interview with The Jerusalem Post,
whose reporter found him ``remarkably normal.'' It was the kind of
regular-guy image he cultivated in his campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps most important for Israel's domestic politics, he is a
Sephardic Jew _ that is, a Jew of Middle Eastern origin _ a native
of Yazd, in central Iran, who came to Israel in 1951 at the age of
5. The eldest of 10 children, he grew up in a tent camp named
Qiryat Malachi, which became a working-class ``development city.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1969, when Katsav was 24, the camp's voters elected him
mayor. He had by then studied economics and history at Hebrew
University _ the first student from the town to attend university _
and worked briefly as a reporter for the newspaper Yediot Ahronot.
He still lives in Qiryat Malachi with his wife and five children.
</P>
<P>
   Katsav's military service, often a crucial social and political
distinction here, was similarly modest. In contrast to the war
heroes, fighter-pilots, paratroopers and commandos who normally
populate the upper reaches of Israeli politics, he was an ordinary
soldier, serving as a tank loader and a radio operator. He once sat
in jail for a week for refusing a command he thought was wrong.
</P>
<P>
   His strong religious connections undoubtedly helped him, winning
the key votes of the 17-member Shas Party of ultra-Orthodox
Sephardim. On Sunday, one of the Shas spiritual leaders, Rabbi
Yitzhak Kadouri, said he had had a vision that Katsav was favored
by the heavens. As a result, aides to Kadouri called legislators to
urge Katsav's election.
</P>
<P>
   ``I intend to contribute to the reduction of tensions within our
society, and I will be the representative of all classes,'' Katsav
said after his election. ``I call on Arabs of Israel, the religious
and secular, Sephardic and Ashkenazic, to see me as their
representative, their president.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-31-00 2235EDT &QL; 
