u f BC-STUDIO-EXECS-NYT &LR;      07-31 0581
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STUDIO-EXECS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEWS CORP. APPOINTS TWO EXECUTIVES TO HEAD 20TH CENTURY FOX 
</HEADLINE>
   By RICK LYMAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Two longtime executives at 20th Century Fox were
named Monday to share the job of running the movie studio,
succeeding Bill Mechanic, who resigned in June.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Gianopulos, who has been president of the studio's
international distribution division since 1994, will join Tom
Rothman, the president of the 20th Century Fox Film Group and a
longtime production executive, as co-chairmen of the movie studio,
said Peter Chernin, president of the News Corp., the studio's
parent company.
</P>
<P>
   ``These jobs are so big and so complicated right now that having
two people to share it is good for both of them,'' Chernin said.
``I did a lot of work, both inside the company and around town,
looking to fill this position and what I finally came to feel was
that I have not just one but two extraordinary individuals right
here.''
</P>
<P>
   Rothman and Gianopulos said Monday that while their studio
careers had differed in emphasis _ Rothman has more of a creative
and production background and Gianopulos more a concentration in
distribution and the business side _ they intended to fully share
the duties of running the studio.
</P>
<P>
   ``The reason Jim and I are as optimistic as we are is that we
are a neat fit in that way,'' Rothman said. ``We're both long in
the tooth in this business and between us have covered all aspects
of it, but to be honest, we do have more intensive experience in
different areas.''
</P>
<P>
   However, the two executives will not be rigid about dividing up
the duties, they said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will work together on the big decisions and share in each
other's areas as much as we can,'' Rothman said. ``But there will
be that primacy in the areas that we each have our respective
expertise in. The idea is for this to be very much of a
partnership.''
</P>
<P>
   The resignation of Mechanic, a widely respected and well-liked
executive, caught much of Hollywood by surprise in June.
</P>
<P>
   The studio had been having a sour run at the box office, from
last fall's ``Fight Club'' to ``Anna and the King'' to this
summer's animated ``Titan A.E.'' But the resignation came right
after the unexpected box office success of ``Big Momma's House''
and just before the release of ``Me, Myself and Irene'' and
``X-Men,'' which both did well.
</P>
<P>
   Rothman said he expected no significant changes. A look at the
movies the studio has released this summer is a good indication of
the kinds of films the two executives intend to release in the
future. He pointed, in particular, to alliances the studio had made
with filmmakers like George Lucas, James Cameron, Robert Zemeckis
and Tim Burton.
</P>
<P>
   ``For us, I think originality is the keyword,'' Rothman said.
</P>
<P>
   ``And diversity,'' Gianopulos added.
</P>
<P>
   The studio, they said, will continue to shy away from selling
international distribution rights to foreign companies, as many
studios do, and may even buy more foreign distribution rights to
films produced by other studios _ perhaps even DreamWorks, whose
international distribution deal with Universal Pictures is about to
expire.
</P>
<P>
   ``The two core agendas of our parent company are the hunger for
content and the ability to distribute it in many different ways on
many different platforms, and an international emphasis in
general,'' Gianopulos said. ``This creates for us a global
perspective, and those continue to be our core strategies.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-31-00 2239EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
