<DOCNO> NYT20000731.0465 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-31 22:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8865 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-GOP-NJ-NYT &LR;      07-31 0679
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOP-NJ-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEMOCRAT'S EXIT A RELIEF FOR NEW JERSEY REPUBLICANS
</HEADLINE>
  By DAVID M. HALBFINGER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHERRY HILL, N.J. _ New Jersey Republicans attending their
national convention in Philadelphia on Monday were so stunned by
Sen. Robert Torricelli's sudden withdrawal from the Democratic race
for governor that they seemed not to know whether to celebrate or
lament his exit.
</P>
<P>
   ``Going to Mass yesterday morning really helped,'' joked Donald
T. DiFrancesco, the president of the State Senate and a contender
for the Republican gubernatorial nomination, who had widely been
seen as the underdog in a contest with Torricelli.
</P>
<P>
   But DiFrancesco quickly added that James McGreevey could prove
no less formidable an opponent.After McGreevey was endorsed Monday
by the mayor of Newark, Sharpe James, and other officials,
Torricelli bowed out.
</P>
<P>
   DiFrancesco called McGreevey a ``tough candidate.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He almost beat Christie Whitman, he's been campaigning every
day for four years _ he says that openly _ he's got labor support,
he's got African-American support, he's got cities, he's got Sharpe
James,'' DiFrancesco said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Democrats' rallying around Jim McGreevey is not good for
Republicans,'' he added. ``I'd rather see them fighting _
fisticuffs, punching, scream, bite, yell, curse.''
</P>
<P>
   If Torricelli's monthlong candidacy had divided New Jersey
Democrats, it had distracted Republicans as well, overshadowing
Rep. Robert D. Franks' uphill run for the U.S. Senate and giving
party leaders reason to think twice about their field of potential
gubernatorial candidates for next year's election.
</P>
<P>
   Besides DiFrancesco, of Union County, the leading Republican
contenders are Jack Collins, the Assembly speaker, who is from
rural Salem County at the southern end of the state, and Bret
Schundler, the mayor of Jersey City. None has the statewide name
recognition that Torricelli enjoys.
</P>
<P>
   Until Monday, some Republicans were even promoting the idea of
enticing former Gov. Thomas Kean to make another run _ a notion
Kean did nothing to discourage _ as if only a popular former
governor had the electoral heft to trump a Torricelli candidacy.
</P>
<P>
   ``There did seem to be that juggernaut feeling coming at
people,'' said Robert Stears, a Republican lobbyist attending a
fund-raiser Monday night in Camden.
</P>
<P>
   Franks, the fund-raiser's beneficiary, said, ``The 800-pound
gorilla is back in his cage.''
</P>
<P>
   He had his own reasons to exult, of course. With little chance
of matching the advertising budget of his Democratic opponent in
the Senate race, the multimillionaire Jon S. Corzine, Franks is
almost wholly dependent on journalists for publicity, and the
Senate race was essentially ignored during the commotion
surrounding the Torricelli-McGreevey matchup.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm delighted that the New Jersey media will now be available
to spend more time with the Senate campaign,'' Franks said.
</P>
<P>
   Other Republicans suggested that while Torricelli's departure
would cement McGreevey's status as the presumptive nominee, it
would also deepen the fissures among New Jersey Democrats. They
noted that the rebellious faction of South Jersey Democrats led by
George E. Norcross III of Camden County had promoted Torricelli's
gubernatorial bid to compete with McGreevey's supporters in the
central and northern parts of the state.
</P>
<P>
   ``Torricelli's pulling out only makes the rift even worse,''
said Gregg Edwards, DiFrancesco's top aide in the Senate. ``Some of
these folks, particularly George Norcross, will be very bitter
people. They'll just look for one more fight to get into.''
</P>
<P>
   Collins, the Assembly speaker, emerged Monday from his hotel
room here, where the New Jersey Republican delegation is staying,
and broke into a broad smile when he was told that Torricelli had
quit the race without endorsing McGreevey.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's the man who will be the senior senator from New Jersey,
and the assumed leader of the Democratic Party, and he's not for
Jim McGreevey?'' Collins said. ``How can anything be better for
Republicans?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-31-00 2241EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000731.0466 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-31 22:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8866 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-PEARSON-NCS-NYT &LR;      07-31 0630
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PEARSON-NCS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PEARSON MAKES BID FOR NATIONAL COMPUTER
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Calif., D.C., Britain)  By GERALDINE FABRIKANT   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Pearson PLC, which has been on an acquisition tear over the last
two years, said Monday that it was buying National Computer Systems
Inc. for $2.5 billion in cash.
</P>
<P>
   The purchase of National Computer, the largest scorer of student
assessment tests in the United States, is part of Pearson's
expansion into educational publishing. National Computer had a
profit of $43 million for the fiscal year ended Jan. 29 on sales of
$630 million.
</P>
<P>
   Pearson, which also owns The Financial Times, already has
extensive education holdings, the centerpiece of which is the
textbook publisher Simon &AMP; Schuster. The addition of National
Computer would allow the company to offer a package of services
permitting schools and parents to monitor the performance of
students and organize remedial work for home and classrooms.
</P>
<P>
   Several analysts said Monday that while they supported efforts
by Pearson's chief executive, Marjorie Scardino, to expand the
company's role in textbook and educational publishing, they were
concerned about the structure of the deal. It offers existing
stockholders the right to buy some additional shares at about half
their value based on Friday's closing price.
</P>
<P>
   Pearson is paying $73 a share in cash, a 26 percent premium to
National Computer's closing price on Friday. Monday, National
Computer rose $13.75, to $71.875. Pearson is raising $2.56 billion
through a rights offering that allows shareholders to buy three new
shares of Pearson at 10 pounds, or about $15 each, for every 11
shares they already own. Shares of Pearson closed on Friday at
20.10 pounds, or $30.13.
</P>
<P>
   The American depository receipts of Pearson were unchanged
Monday at $31.50. Pearson has 625 million ADR's outstanding, and
the company has filed to issue additional shares, which it expects
to list on the New York Stock Exchange within the next several
weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts and investors were not happy with the strategy of
issuing new stock at a discount to complete the purchase. Shares of
Pearson fell 9 percent, to 18.28 pounds, or $27.40, in London
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The company said that the stock strategy would make the
acquisition price lower because it would reduce investment banking
fees. It would also reduce the amount of additional debt Pearson
would have to take on, and the company acknowledged Monday that it
was not eager to increase its debt load.
</P>
<P>
   One industry executive, who spoke on the condition of anonymity,
said he found the price Pearson was paying _ roughly four times
sales _ a high one. A spokesman for Scardino said she was not
returning phone calls because the company was in a quiet period
associated with its pending stock registration in the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   Behind the rush to expand in educational publishing and
information is increasing demand as more students enter U.S.
schools. At the same time, schools are investing more in textbooks,
in part because of swelling state coffers and in part because of
the public demand for better education. For example, California
will invest $1 billion over the next four years on education, said
Ed Atorino, who follows publishing for Wasserstein Perella.
</P>
<P>
   ``On top of that there is a technology play,'' he said.
``Schools are not only spending on textbooks, they are spending on
software and CD-ROMs. It started in high school, but it is working
its way down.''
</P>
<P>
   Pearson is not the only company determined to expand in
educational publishing. In late June, the Washington Post Co.
announced that it would buy the Quest Education Corp. for $165
million. Quest provides career-oriented education to more than
13,400 students.  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-31-00 2241EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
