<SLUG> BC-BUSH-TRAVEL-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH CAMP OUTLINES POST-CONVENTION TRAVEL PLANS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOEL CONNELLY  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ Texas Gov. George W. Bush will head for the West
Coast next week as the Republican presidential nominee, with stops
in California and possibly the Northwest designed to take the GOP
campaign into Vice President Al Gore's must-win states.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are as many electoral votes (18) in Washington and
Oregon as there are in Michigan,'' Karl Rove, Bush's chief
political strategist, said Monday in discussing Bush's
post-convention travel schedule.
</P>
<P>
   Borrowing from the 1992 playbook of Bill Clinton, who took a bus
trip through the Ohio Valley and then flew West to Spokane and
Seattle after the Democratic convention, Bush will barnstorm the
industrial Midwest after he accepts the Republican nomination here
Thursday night. He then will take a brief respite in Texas after
which he will head West.
</P>
<P>
   Rove said Bush's campaign has lately spent $400,000 on
television ads in Washington. Calling Washington a ``battleground
state,'' at least for now, he added: ``We spend money where we
think it will do us good, not where it will make them worry.''
</P>
<P>
   Joe Andrew, chairman of the Democratic National Committee,
scoffed at Bush's advertising buys in a state that has voted for
Democrats in the past three presidential elections.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have money to place TV (ads) even in places they have no
chance of winning, but want to create the impression that they
do,'' Andrew said in an interview here. ``I think in the end
(Washington) is a state we are going to win and win big. We're on
the air there, and taking nothing for granted.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush already has made five visits to Washington in the past
year, an investment of time that has paid handsome dividends. The
Texas governor scored an impressive win over Arizona Sen. John
McCain in the state's Feb. 29 primary. He raised more than $1
million for his own and Republican Party campaign coffers during a
night of fund-raisers at Seattle's Columbia Tower Club in May.
</P>
<P>
   With unusual candor for a campaign strategist, Rove on Monday
talked about how the Bush campaign is allocating its dollars and
how it is targeting states in the Nov. 7 election.
</P>
<P>
   Washington ``may or may not'' continue to enjoy high priority
with the Bush campaign, Rove said, depending on whether Bush
continues to lead in the polls and on the amount of energy and
fund-raising prowess shown by the state Republican Party. (Bush was
running four points ahead of Gore in a recent statewide poll taken
by the Mellman Group, a Democratic pollster working for Democratic
Senate hopeful Maria Cantwell.)
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a specific plan for each state,'' Rove added. A key
requirement, he said, is ``an active, energetic home-grown victory
committee in the state.'' Rove said he met with newly elected GOP
State Chairman Don Benton before the Republican National Convention
got under way, and asked: ``Are you holding up your end?''
</P>
<P>
   Tony Williams, chief of staff to GOP Sen. Slade Gorton, said
later: ``We have dramatically increased the state party budget to
reflect the presidential campaign, on the order of 75 percent.'' He
declined to give a specific dollar figure.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need them and they need us,'' Williams said. ``We know we
have to raise a lot of money in the state, and they are excited
about the prospect of winning a state that has gone Democrat.''
</P>
<P>
   ``My gut tells me Washington state remains on the battleground
list (into the fall),'' Rove said. He added that ``one of the
reasons we are doing well on the West Coast'' is that Green Party
presidential candidate Ralph Nader is siphoning off liberal
activists from Gore.
</P>
<P>
   Rove, the strategist who has masterminded GOP gubernatorial
victories in Texas for Bush and former Gov. Bill Clements, as well
as Bush's $90 million presidential juggernaut, said the candidate
will join McCain next week at the Arizona senator's Cottonwood,
Ariz., ranch ``for a day of friendship.''
</P>
<P>
   Little love was lost between the two contenders early this year,
especially in the South Carolina primary when such Bush-boosting
Christian conservatives as the Revs. Pat Robertson and Jerry
Falwell made personal attacks on McCain.
</P>
<P>
   While not visible at the podium in this year's GOP convention,
Christian conservatives are ``energized'' behind Bush, Rove added.
``The religious conservatives are a big part of the Republican
base,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
