<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    GOP BEGINS CONVENTION AIMED AT REMAKING ITS IMAGE
 &HT;    EDS: A 1stLD will move following Powell's speech.
 &HT;    By KEN HERMAN
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ George W. Bush's high-stakes effort to put a new
face on the Grand Old Party went prime time Monday as 4,132
delegates and alternates gathered here for the Republican National
Convention.
</P>
<P>
   Front and center as the makeover began a four-night, nationally
televised run were retired Gen. Colin Powell, Texas First Lady
Laura Bush and a platform custom-tailored for a compassionate
conservative.
</P>
<P>
   Powell praised Bush as a man with a ``passion for inclusion''
but criticized the GOP for opposing affirmative action, a position
shared by Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Bush said her husband is the candidate for a country in
search of a leader who reflects ``its heart and its values and its
leadership in the world.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush, who will accept the nomination here Thursday night, was
scheduled to address delegates late Monday in a remote broadcast
from Ohio, where he was campaigning.
</P>
<P>
   The Monday night session at the First Union Center began with an
excerpt from ``Fanfare for the Common Man,'' setting the tone for a
convention aimed at ending the GOP's image as the gentry's party.
Monday's theme was ``Opportunity With a Purpose: Leave No Child
Behind.''
</P>
<P>
   ``My friends, this is going to be a different kind of convention
for a different kind of Republican,'' Republican National Committee
Chairman Jim Nicholson told delegates.
</P>
<P>
   Monday night's session was different. It included Republican
delegates, overwhelmingly white, on their feet and clapping to the
raucous, up-tempo beat of a black church choir.
</P>
<P>
   Different also meant the Pledge of Allegiance delivered by a
blind mountain climber and a long agenda of blacks, Hispanics and
women on stage.
</P>
<P>
   Bush campaign officials hope the party platform, approved here
Monday in a voice vote, also documents the difference. The party's
firm opposition to abortion remains in the platform, but delegates
OK'd a more welcoming approach to minorities and immigrants.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our party is more inclusive, more diverse and more
representative of America than ever before, but we're still the
party of limited government,'' Pennsylvania Sen. Arlen Spector said
from the arena's massive stage.
</P>
<P>
   The night's tightly scripted and slickly produced program had
one of its few spontaneous moments when delegates spotted former
President George Bush and wife Barbara entering the hall
unannounced to take their seats. The delegates turned to face the
Bushes and applaud their arrival.
</P>
<P>
   A second ovation, longer and louder, roared through the building
when the former first family was introduced.
</P>
<P>
   Powell, who served as chief of staff under the elder Bush,
touted his ex-boss' son as the right man to head a renewed effort
for racial harmony.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some call it compassionate conservatism. It's just about
caring for people,'' Powell said in remarks prepared for delivery
in prime time.
</P>
<P>
   ``In pursuing educational reform, as well as in all other parts
of his agenda for Texas, Governor Bush has reached out to all
Texans _ white, black, Latino, Asian, Native American,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has been successful in bringing more and more minorities
inside the tent by responding to their deepest needs,'' Powell
added. ``He will bring to the White House that same passion of
inclusion. I know he can help bridge our racial divides.''
</P>
<P>
   Powell urged the GOP to follow Bush's lead and reach out to
minorities ``and not just during an election year campaign.''
</P>
<P>
   Four years ago, Powell drew boos at the Republican National
Convention in San Diego when he declared his support for abortion
rights and affirmative action, two issues on which he differs with
Bush.
</P>
<P>
   He did not mention abortion Monday night, but hit hard on
affirmative action.
</P>
<P>
   ``We must understand the cynicism that exists in the black
community. The kind of cynicism that is created when, for example,
some in our party miss no opportunity to roundly and loudly condemn
affirmative action that helped a few thousand black kids get an
education, but hardly a whimper is heard from them over affirmative
action for lobbyists who load our federal tax codes with
preferences for special interests,'' Powell said.
</P>
<P>
   Laura Bush, who has campaigned around the country by herself and
with her husband, used her speech to boost the Republicans'
ambitious effort to co-opt education as their issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted to teach our children what our parents had taught
us,'' she said in remarks prepared for delivery, ``that reading is
entertaining and interesting and important. And one of the major
reasons George is running for president is to make sure every child
in America has that same opportunity to grow up reading.''
</P>
<P>
   Low-key by nature and reluctant to see her husband run for
president, Mrs. Bush has grown into a full-time campaign trail
partner. The Monday night speech marked her biggest step into the
spotlight. For years, her husband has joked that when he married
Laura Welch, a former librarian and teacher, her idea of a speech
was ``Sssh.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush stopped using the line after his wife objected to its
stereotypical nature. But Bush continues to remind audiences that
when he proposed to his future wife in 1977 he promised she'd never
have to give a political speech. Months later, she was giving stump
speeches for her husband in his unsuccessful congressional race.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the only political promise I ever broke,'' Bush tells
crowds.
</P>
<P>
   Also Monday, the GOP broke from convention by beginning the
process of nominating Bush on opening night. Instead of having all
states vote on the third night, an alphabetical
</P>
</TEXT>
