<SLUG> BC-MILLERTV-0801-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Miller at ease in debut on Monday Night Football
 &HT;    By Prentis Rogers
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA - During the course of his debut on ABC's ''Monday Night
Football,'' Dennis Miller acknowledged the pace and collisions of
the game were a lot more unnerving from the booth than from his
couch at home, but the comedian didn't show any signs of stage
fright in the Hall of Fame game between the 49ers and Patriots.
</P>
<P>
   At the top of the telecast, Miller declared, ''If there's
anybody in the stadium more pumped up than me, they wouldn't pass
the league's standardized drug test.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps Miller was too pumped up with a gabby but promising
outing that included a number of eclectic references, most notably
the couple that suggested viewers will have to brush up on their
Greek mythology to keep up with him this season.
</P>
<P>
   The meaningless, one-sided nature of Monday's preseason game was
the ideal format to get a first impression of Miller with
colleagues Al Michaels and Dan Fouts, because producer Don Ohlmeyer
is hoping this new team will be able to retain the audience when
the game itself is not compelling.
</P>
<P>
   Ohlmeyer said Miller's role was not to provide stand-up comedy,
but more often than not the telecast seemed to be little more than
a stage for him to display his sharp and irreverent wit.
</P>
<P>
   And though a few fell flat, which should be expected over the
course of three hours, for the most part Miller delivered and
boosted the entertainment value of the telecast.
</P>
<P>
   Even his employer was not spared when Miller quipped of ABC,
''People on `Survivor' have a better per diem than we do. I had to
buy a BLT today with fur pelts.''
</P>
<P>
   It was apparent Monday night that Miller will have to watch
force-feeding the humor into the telecast. Not every promo or
situation warrants a wisecrack.Miller did show flashes of being
able to talk football, noting the nifty feet of Patriots running
back Kevin Faulk and that 49ers backup quarterback Giovanni
Carmazzi looked skittish. But overall, the commentary on the
football will need much more bite to offset the steady stream of
jokes.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
