</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-HEAT-HORNETS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HEAT'S RILEY GETS MASON IN DEAL FOR JONES
</HEADLINE>
 By MIKE WISE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   To the chagrin of the Chicago Bulls, Pat Riley appears to have
gotten his man.
</P>
<P>
   On the eve of the National Basketball Association free-agent
signing period, the Charlotte Hornets and the Miami Heat were on
the cusp of completing a nine-player trade that included the
Hornets' sending Eddie Jones and Anthony Mason to South Florida for
the Heat's Jamal Mashburn and P.J. Brown.
</P>
<P>
   Riley, the Heat's coach and team president, has pursued Jones
throughout the off-season. And the trade would not only reunite
Mason with Riley, his former coach with the Knicks, but also give
the Heat Jones, the athletic All-Star shooting guard they
desperately need.
</P>
<P>
   Riley has seen his team eliminated by the Knicks the past three
postseasons. He was hoping to announce the deal as early as
Tuesday, an Eastern Conference team official said on the condition
of anonymity Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   The other players involved in the trade were believed to be
Ricky Davis and Dale Ellis of Charlotte and Otis Thorpe, Rodney
Buford and Tim James of Miami. There were still contract details to
be worked out, and it was unclear whether the assortment of role
players would change.
</P>
<P>
   Monday night, a Hornets team official said the deal was ``almost
done.''
</P>
<P>
   In Miami Monday night, fans on talk shows were wondering whether
Riley had given up too much for Jones. The Heat had to acquire
Mason, the player Riley feuded with and suspended while with the
Knicks, to shore up the deal.
</P>
<P>
   It is unclear whether the Heat will pursue a deal for Lakers
small forward Glen Rice while using Mason as trade bait. But
another Eastern Conference team official would not rule out further
trades involving Miami. The Heat did not want to part with Brown,
the consummate role player Riley has often kept out of deals.
</P>
<P>
   The only news the Knicks made Monday was orally agreeing to
terms with Kurt Thomas. Thomas, a free-agent forward, will most
likely sign a multiyear extension with the club in the next two
days, a team official said.
</P>
<P>
   Jones, whom the Chicago Bulls coveted, and the rest of the 2000
free-agent class can begin signing contracts Tuesday. In a
sign-and-trade deal, Jones could earn more than $86 million over
seven seasons.
</P>
<P>
   While Orlando officially overhauls its roster Tuesday with the
signings of Grant Hill and Tracy McGrady _ two of the top five free
agents _ the Bulls are left with $19 million in salary-cap room and
not a single All-Star left to bid on.
</P>
<P>
   After Tim Thomas spurned the Bulls last month to remain in
Milwaukee, their only hope is to perhaps overpay Ron Mercer or
Rice.
</P>
<P>
   Indiana is going to re-sign Jalen Rose and is working out
contract extensions for Reggie Miller and Mark Jackson.
Philadelphia's Toni Kukoc, Seattle's Rashard Lewis and Houston's
Cuttino Mobley are also expected to sign with their current teams.
</P>
<P>
   The Magic did well, but missed out on the top prize. Tim Duncan
decided to stay in San Antonio, where he is expected to sign a
three year deal with a fourth year option for more than $45
million.
</P>
<P>
   Before most deals were signed, teams were waiting to hear from
the league office what the adjusted salary cap number would be for
next season. A league official said the salary cap would total
approximately $35.5 million _ meaning a team's aggregate annual
salaries for their 2000-1 players under contract must add up to
that number or less.
</P>
<P>
   First-year players with one to six years of experience can sign
for 25 percent of the total unadjusted salary cap.
</P>
<P>
   While several players were still undecided as to where they
would go, the Miami-Charlotte deal became the buzz of the league
Monday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   The Hornets were ecstatic to acquire Mashburn and Brown. Faced
with the possibility of losing Jones for nothing if he signed with
another team, the Hornets dramatically altered their lineup as
well.
</P>
<P>
   The only real intrigue left around the league is what is going
to happen to Portland's Brian Grant. Cleveland and the Trail
Blazers have been discussing a swap of Grant for Shawn Kemp, but it
is unclear whether Grant wants to play for the Cavaliers, a key
aspect of the deal.
</P>
<P>
   Grant has said he wants to play in New York, and the Trail
Blazers have even mentioned Patrick Ewing's name in discussions
between the teams. But it is doubtful the Knicks will part with
their center for Grant, a power forward. What is more, Ewing has a
no-trade clause, so his approval would be required for any such
deal.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
