u e BC-COLO-ARTISTS-RANCH-NY     07-31 1024
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COLO-ARTISTS-RANCH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A RANCH IN THE ROCKIES FOR FAMED ARTISTS AND NOVICES  
 ELIZABETH HEILMAN BROOKE   
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SNOWMASS VILLAGE, Colo. _ Sheep dung once was up to the windows
of what artists now call the seminar room. The seminar room's floor
is far from level, and its walls are chinked spruce and fir logs,
remnants of a late-19th-century forest fire. But this summer
William Christenberry, a photographer, used this former sheep shed
to show slides for his course called Interaction of Media:
Photography, Painting and Sculpture
</P>
<P>
   Cattle barns and sheep sheds that until 1966 were the heart of
an active ranch here now draw acclaimed and aspiring artists from
around the world. The Anderson Ranch Arts Center, a
four-and-a-half-acre campus eight miles west of Aspen, is a bucolic
center for potters, photographers, painters, printmakers,
woodworkers, sculptors, art historians and critics. From early June
through late September the studios have more than a thousand
professional and novice artists in workshops of one to two weeks on
topics as basic as Making Stuff in Clay and as lofty as The Meaning
of Mountains.
</P>
<P>
   Internationally renowned artists come to learn from one another
and from experts in technologically new fields yet to be fully
explored.
</P>
<P>
   New York has Chautauqua, New Hampshire has the MacDowell Colony,
and North Carolina has the Penland School of Crafts. With its Rocky
Mountain backdrop, its heady 8,200-foot altitude and its proximity
to Aspen, Anderson Ranch has in three decades acquired a reputation
for corralling curious artists in search of creative synergy.
</P>
<P>
   The ranch's course catalog is available in January, and half its
courses were full by mid-March. Most workshops are limited to about
a dozen participants, but because of the extensive pottery
equipment, which include a kiln yard with five gas kilns, a wood
kiln, a Japanese Anagama kiln and several electric kilns, ceramics
workshops can enroll as many as 16.
</P>
<P>
   For 15 years Doug Casebeer, a former ceramics consultant to the
United Nations, has directed the ceramics program at the ranch.
Casebeer said that artists generally recognize that their
profession can require a selfish self-absorption, but that Anderson
Ranch is an ``arena where we can all come together, leave the egos
at the door, appreciate that everybody has something to say.''
</P>
<P>
   This summer Paul Soldner, the center's first artistic director,
and a fellow ceramic artist, Peter Voulkos, will again teach A
Lifetime of Clay, a workshop that encourages ``mentorship and an
exchange of ideas.'' Late in July, Ah Leon, a Taiwanese ceramic
artist specializing in Yixing-style teapots and sculpture, will
lead The Language of Tea: Dissecting the Teapot, which the catalog
calls ``a total immersion in the tea experience.''
</P>
<P>
   Most workshops meet from 9 a.m. to 5 p.m. Monday through Friday,
with a break for lunch. Studios are open 24 hours a day. Tuition
ranges from $250 for a one-week course called Art and Mud: A Course
for Teachers, to $550 for a two-week sculpture class taught by the
sculptor Laura Thorne, to $1,295 for two weeks of John Sexton's lab
intensive photography course.
</P>
<P>
   At the cafe these days, which serves breakfast, lunch and dinner
al fresco and cappuccino and biscotti late into the night, the
Texas sculptor James Surls can often be found sitting beside a
60-year-old lawyer, accountant or business executive who has come
to try a first studio art course.
</P>
<P>
   Seven years ago at age 67, Lloyd Schermer, then chairman of Lee
Enterprises, a media company, decided to take his first drawing
course. ``Taking a course in art, for Pete's sake. I was
terrified,'' Schermer said. Since then he has taken classes in
watercolor, figure drawing, oil, acrylic, collage and monotype
(single print) and has become an enthusiastic monotype artist.
</P>
<P>
   Relying sometimes on wood type he salvaged from one of his
newspapers in Missoula, Mont., Schermer has painted and sculptured
and sold more than 100 of his works, which are in the collections
of the National Museum of American Art at the Smithsonian
Institution, the Aspen Institute, the Tribune Co. and the Hearst
Corp.
</P>
<P>
   Schermer and his wife, Betty, have been donors to the ranch and
served on its board; the meeting hall dedicated in 1999 was named
for them.
</P>
<P>
   In August performers from Jazz Aspen will fill the ranch with
music. In past years B.B. King stopped by for an impromptu
performance. Larry Rivers, the painter, once picked up his
saxophone and surprised students with an unexpected riff.
</P>
<P>
   Artists come from as far away as Nepal, Jamaica and Japan. There
are children's workshops for ages 6 through 15.
</P>
<P>
   Artists can apply for short or long residencies. Past visiting
artists have included the Japanese ceramist Takashi Nakazato, the
performance artist Laurie Anderson and the painters Red Grooms and
Jim Dine.
</P>
<P>
   The ranch, with an annual budget of $2.8 million, has 55,000
square feet of studios and housing and offers as many as 150
scholarships a year. Full-time art students and art teachers are
offered a 50 percent discount on tuition for courses in which space
is available.
</P>
<P>
   Surls, the sculptor, who has been an invited artist in residence
for two years, said that the ranch center had given him ``a
midcareer jump, a new lease on life, a second wind.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not in the same West of Remington and Russell,'' he
said. ``Today there is an incredibly complex set of references. I
think everybody conjures from his environment. The landscape here
is beautiful. The weather is great. My work has totally opened up.
This terrain change has created a head change.''
</P>
<P>
   James Baker, a photographer and 14-year veteran of the ranch who
has been its executive director for five years, said it offered the
``gift of time and space, an opportunity to blend idealism with
pragmatism.''
</P>
<P>
   Baker added: ``At a time when our economy is so strong, we've
got everything we want except what we really need. You can see that
yearning. Society needs this type of fulfillment. To be human is to
create, and people need opportunities to create.''
</P>
</TEXT>
