<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LOS-ALAMOS-DISCRIM-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FEDERAL AGENCY INVESTIGATING DISCRIMINATION COMPLAINTS AT LOS
ALAMOS LABORATORY 
</HEADLINE>
   By JAMES GLANZ   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A federal civil rights agency is investigating possible
discrimination against Asian and Asian-American employees at the
Los Alamos National Laboratory, said spokesmen for the laboratory
and the University of California, which manages it.
</P>
<P>
   Los Alamos is the second federal weapons laboratory to be
investigated by the Equal Employment Opportunity Commission for
possible discrimination. Last year, the agency began an
investigation of Lawrence Livermore National Laboratory after
claims by nine Asian-American scientists and engineers that they
were subjected to racial bias in pay and promotions.
</P>
<P>
   Some Asian and Asian-American scientists at both laboratories
also claim that they have been unfairly singled out as possible
security risks after the arrest of Wen Ho Lee, a former Los Alamos
scientist who has been charged with mishandling nuclear data. Lee
is a naturalized U.S. citizen originally from Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
   Both laboratories are managed by the university under a contract
with the Energy Department.
</P>
<P>
   Rick Malaspina, a university spokesman, confirmed the
investigation and said both the laboratory and the university would
cooperate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Needless to say, we do not tolerate discrimination or
profiling,'' Malaspina said.
</P>
<P>
   While a commission spokesman would not comment on specific
investigations, he said that in general, legal action could result
if evidence of discrimination is found, and if the institution
being investigated declines to accept the remedies that the
commission proposes.
</P>
<P>
   The legal office at Los Alamos recently sent a memorandum to
about 350 current and former Asian and Asian-American employees of
the laboratory, informing them of the investigation ``alleging
discrimination against Asian and Asian-American employees.''
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Roark, a spokesman for Los Alamos, said California law,
which governs the university's operations, required the laboratory
to inform its employees that as part of the investigation the
commission had requested information from their personnel files on
matters like their ethnicity and place of residence.
</P>
<P>
   Roark said that because the commission had not yet revealed the
specific accusations it was investigating, the laboratory could not
comment on the action.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
