<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CVN-POWELL-1STLD-WRITETHRU-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
POWELL CHIDES GOP BUT SAYS BUSH WOULD BRIDGE RACIAL DIVIDES &HT;    (EDs: Recasts lede; updates with quotes, details from speech;
pickup: Powel is perhaps)
 &HT;    By ERIC ROSENBERG
 &HT;    c.2000 Hearst Newspapers
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ Colin Powell, one of the nation's most prominent
African Americans, criticized the Republican Party Monday night for
its traditional opposition to affirmative action, asserting that
``the issue of race still casts a shadow over our society.'' But
Powell told delegates to the Republican National Convention that
Texas Gov. George W. Bush would heal racial rifts and reach out to
minorities if elected president.
</P>
<P>
   ``We must understand that cynicism exists in the black
community,'' Powell said in a prime-time address to the 2,066
delegates _ more than 90 percent of whom are white.
</P>
<P>
   It's ``the kind of cynism that is created when, for example,
some in our party miss no opportunity to roundly and loudly condemn
affirmative action that helped a few thousand black kids get an
education,'' he said. ``But hardly a whimper is heard from them
over affirmative action for lobbyists who load our federal tax
codes with prefences for special interests.''
</P>
<P>
   Powell called on Republicans to reach out to minority groups
``and not just during an election year campaign.''
</P>
<P>
   Republicans must help the poorest Americans, he said, adding
that ``the world is watching to see if all this power and wealth is
just for the well to do, the comfortable, the privileged.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush introduced the retired Army general in a live broadcast
from a school classroom in Westerville, Ohio, a Columbus suburb.
Praising Powell for years of government service, the governor
hinted that there may be a high-profile postion for Powell if Bush
is elected president. ``I hope his greatest service to America
might still lie ahead,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Powell is considered a favorite for Bush's secretary of state.
</P>
<P>
   Powell praised Bush, saying the governor ``can help bridge our
racial divides'' and ``has been successful in bringing more and
more minorities inside the tent by responding to their deepest
needs.''
</P>
<P>
   He added, ``Some call it compassionate conservatism. To me, it's
just about caring about people. He can do the same thing as
president. He will bring to the White House that same passion for
inclusion'' that he has shown as governor in reaching out ``to all
Texans _ white, black, Latino, Asian, Native American.''
</P>
<P>
   Powell, 63, the chairman of the joint Chiefs of Staff under
President George Bush, the Texas governor's father, also said that
improving the lives of American youth should be the country's top
priority.
</P>
<P>
   ``So many of the problems we worry about go back to how we raise
our children. We either build our children or we build more
jails,'' he said, adding that it is ``time to stop building
jails.''
</P>
<P>
   Powell noted that giving children ``what they need to be
successful in life ... has become the passion of my life.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, the retired general became chairman of America's
Promise, a national organization that mentors young people, using
faith-based and community organizations to help solve social ills.
</P>
<P>
   Powell did not mention abortion, a key hot-button issue on which
his views run counter to those of Bush and many of the delegates
here. Powell supports abortion rights.
</P>
<P>
   The theme of Monday's GOP convention activities was
``Opportunity With a Purpose: Leave No Child Behind.'' It was an
effort flesh out Bush's campaign mantra of ``compassionate
conservatism'' by showcasing speakers focused on improving
education and conditions for young people generally.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to Powell, Monday's speakers included Laura Bush,
wife of the Texas governor, who spoke about education.
</P>
<P>
   Powell considered running for the Republican presidential
nomination in 1996 but ultimately declined. In the current
campaign, he aggressively dissuaded Bush from considering him as a
running mate.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Powell is considered a likely contender for secretary of
state should the governor win the election. The selection would
reunite Powell with Richard Cheney, the presumptive vice
presidential nominee and secretary of defense under President Bush.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Powell is perhaps best remembered for his role as Joint Chiefs
chairman in helping plan Operation Desert Storm, the massive 1991
war effort to expel Iraqi forces from Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
   He initially opposed use of military force to turn back Iraq's
1990 invasion of the oil kingdom. But once President Bush and the
allies decided to fight, Powell helped devise a strategy of using
overwhelming force. No U.S. troops should be put into harm's way
unless they are supported by sufficient numbers to rapidly defeat
the Iraqi military, Powell reasoned, drawing a key lesson from his
Vietnam war experience.
</P>
<P>
   Powell's history with Republican presidents dates to the Richard
Nixon era. While in the Army, Powell served in 1972 as a White
House fellow, a program that exposed him to the inner workings of
the president's Cabinet. While there, he impressed Caspar
Weinberger and Frank Carlucci, both of whom later served as
secretaries of defense.
</P>
<P>
   During the Reagan administration, Powell was the top military
aide to Weinberger and later became the president's national
security adviser. In 1989, under President Bush, Powell, at 52,
became the youngest chairman of the Joint Chiefs, the nation's
highest military post. He is the only African American to have
served in the position.
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
