A8995 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-LANE-ORACLE &LR;      07-31 0470
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LANE-ORACLE </SLUG>
  
 OFFERS POUR IN FOR FORMER ORACLE EXEC
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; BY VERNE KOPYTOFF &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CHRONICLE STAFF WRITER &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; 2000 San Francisco Chronicle &LR;
</P>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Ray Lane, the former president and chief
operating officer of database software-maker Oracle Corp., said
yesterday that he will never work as a company executive again and
will instead focus on less time-consuming jobs like serving on
boards of directors.
</P>
<P>
   Since his departure, Lane says he has been recruited to be chief
executive or director for about 50 firms. He would not discuss
details about those offers, which he said are from Internet
companies and other large businesses.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now I want to be the one in control of my time,'' said
Lane, 53, and the father of a young child. ``It depends on the
quality of life you want.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't have anything else to prove,'' he added. ``If I take
another operations role, then it's just me trying to prove
something.''
</P>
<P>
   Lane's remarks came during a telephone interview in which he
announced that he is joining the board of Sheer Networks, a
Sunnyvale firm that creates software to manage telecommunications
networks. It is Lane's first new job since his high-profile
retirement from Oracle in July after Larry Ellison, the company's
chief executive, stripped him of most of his authority.
</P>
<P>
   Including the directorship at Sheer Networks, Lane now serves on
five corporate boards. He is also a director for Marimba, C-bridge
Internet Solutions, Software Technologies Corp. and Oracle.
</P>
<P>
   Lane said he joined Sheer Networks' board because it has
developed technology that could make managing telecommunications
networks much easier. He invested his own money in the company,
describing it only as a ``significant'' amount.
</P>
<P>
   Before joining Oracle, Lane led the Dallas office of business
consulting firm Booz-Allen &AMP; Hamilton. There was no word whether
Lane would begin consulting again in addition to his board
responsibilities.
</P>
<P>
   Joshua Greenbaum, an analyst for Enterprise Applications
Consulting, a software consulting company in Berkeley, was
skeptical that Lane could stay away from the executive ranks for
long.
</P>
<P>
   Greenbaum said Lane may a need a break after managing Oracle
through difficult times. But the analyst suspected that Lane would
probably find serving on a board to be less satisfying than running
a multibillion-dollar company.
</P>
<P>
   Experienced executives like Lane, Greenbaum said, are in big
demand these days. He predicted that Lane could be lured to lead
one of them if the offer is big enough.
</P>
<P>
   ``The software industry is full of second acts and deathbed
conversions,'' Greenbaum said. ``I would take Lane's announcement
with a grain of salt.''
</P>
<P>
   E-mail Verne Kopytoff at  &LR; verne &LR; (AT) &LR; sfgate.com &LR; .
</P>
