<SLUG> BC-MONEYBAG-ADVICE </SLUG>
  
 BEST ADVICE ON INVESTING _ SIT DOWN AND READ
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; COLUMN BY ARTHUR LOUIS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; 2000 San Francisco Chronicle &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Q:  &LR; I am a student, interested in investing in stocks. I have &LR; 
 &LR; about $3,000 saved up in a certificate of deposit. How do I go &LR; 
 &LR; about picking stocks? &LR;
</P>
<P>
   A: Investing is a skill like any other, only more so. It takes a
lot of time, study and application if you hope to do it right _ and
even then you may fail.
</P>
<P>
   Buy regularly _ and read thoroughly _ such investor-oriented
publications as Barron's, the Wall Street Journal and Smart Money.
Also, pay close attention to the business coverage in your friendly
local newspaper (hint, hint).
</P>
<P>
   Read all the books you can find on investing. Browse a
good-sized bookstore and pick the titles that pique your interest.
Do the same at the nearest branch library.
</P>
<P>
   Here are some books I would particularly recommend: ``A Random
Walk Down Wall Street,'' by Burton J. Malkiel; ``One up on Wall
Street,'' by Peter Lynch; ``The Intelligent Investor,'' by Benjamin
Graham, and ``The Battle for Investment Survival,'' by Gerald M.
Loeb.
</P>
<P>
   Don't slavishly follow any writer's advice. The idea is to
become familiar with the conventional wisdom, to soak up some
unconventional wisdom and to learn the jargon. Once you know how
the so-called experts think, you will be prepared to start thinking
for yourself.
</P>
<P>
   I also suggest that you open a brokerage account promptly, even
if you plan to wait a while to invest. That way you can gain access
to the broker's research archives, which allow you to explore
facts, statistics and recommendations pertaining to thousands of
stocks. Most brokers make it possible to do this online.
</P>
<P>
   I suppose I am obligated to mention that investment novices with
small amounts of money ought to at least consider investing in a
mutual fund. Mutual funds offer diversification and professional
management. The catch is that professional management isn't
necessarily worth much; most mutual funds fail to match the
performance of the stock-market averages.
</P>
<P>
   One type of mutual fund that matches the market _ precisely _ is
an index fund. The performance benchmark for most stock-oriented
mutual funds is the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500, so you might want to buy
shares in a fund that emulates that index.
</P>
<P>
   But picking your own stocks is more fun.
</P>
<P>
   One intriguing alternative would be to sign up with one of the
new online brokers that let you build your own mutual fund with
small amounts of money and at low commission costs. (See my article
about these brokers in today's Business section on Page E1.)
</P>
<P>
   Death and Taxes
</P>
<P>
   Q: I am a senior with substantial individual retirement
accounts. My daughter is the beneficiary of these accounts. After I
die, she obviously will have to pay income tax as she withdraws the
money. But what about the estate tax? Are the IRAs counted as part
of the estate for tax purposes?
</P>
<P>
   A: Internal Revenue Service spokesman Jesse Weller says IRAs
generally are included in the estate for tax purposes. There are
some arcane, complicated exceptions to that rule, however, so you
ought to touch base with a financial planner, accountant or tax
lawyer.
</P>
<P>
   Your daughter will have choices to make when it comes time to
withdraw the money from the IRAs. How she proceeds will depend on
whether you have reached the age at which you are required to make
annual withdrawals from your IRAs. The cutoff is April 1 of the
year after you reach age 701/2.
</P>
<P>
   If you die after the cutoff date, your daughter will have to
withdraw money from the IRAs at least as rapidly as you were
required to do so. Your minimum withdrawal schedule will have been
determined from age expectancy tables provided by the IRS in its
Publication 590.
</P>
<P>
   If you die before the cutoff date, then your daughter will have
two choices. She can withdraw all the money from the IRAs by the
end of the fifth year following your death. Or, she can take
withdrawals based on her own life expectancy, using the IRS tables.
Those withdrawals would have to begin before the end of the year
following your death.
</P>
<P>
   In any case, Weller notes, your daughter would not have to pay
an early-withdrawal penalty. There is no penalty because the
withdrawals are required by law.
</P>
<P>
   Post-Acquisition Math
</P>
<P>
   Q: I have some shares of Ziff-Davis and ZDNet, both of which are
being acquired by Cnet. Can you tell me how to figure out how many
shares of Cnet I will receive?
</P>
<P>
   A: You will get 0.3397 shares of Cnet for every Ziff-Davis share
you own, and 0.5932 Cnet shares for every share of ZDNet.
</P>
<P>
   Before that happens, however, Ziff-Davis will spin off shares of
its Key3Media trade-show and conference business. You will get one
share of Key3Media for every two shares you hold in Ziff-Davis. As
part of the spin-off, you also will receive a special cash dividend
of up to $2.50 per Ziff-Davis share. The precise amount hasn't been
determined.
</P>
<P>
   NOTE: In last week's column, I advised a reader that the
institutions at which he holds his IRAs will be able to tell him
what portion of the money he withdraws is taxable. I have since
been informed by institutions and other sources that this generally
is not true _ that the institutions usually do not keep the
necessary records. So you had better keep track of this yourself,
noting each year which of your IRA contributions are deductible or
non-deductible. (Check copies of your tax returns to remind
yourself what you did in past years.) If, for example, you have
$10,000 in a traditional IRA, and you made $6,000 in nondeductible
contributions, then $6 out of every $10 you withdraw will not be
taxable.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; Send questions about how to manage your money to
 &LR; moneybag &LR; sfgate.com,  &LR; or to Arthur M. Louis, Moneybag column, 901
Mission St., San Francisco, CA 94103.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
