<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NAPSTER-TRAFFIC </SLUG>
  
 COURT FIGHT DRAWS MILLIONS TO MUSIC SITE
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; BY BENNY EVANGELISTA &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CHRONICLE STAFF WRITER &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; 2000 SAN FRANCISCO CHRONICLE &LR;
</P>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ With Napster Inc.'s survival hanging in the
balance last week, traffic to its Web site exploded past some more
well-known sites like ESPN.com, Disney.com, MSNBC.com and
Priceline.com.
</P>
<P>
   According to the Web monitoring service PC Data Online,
Napster's site attracted 5.8 million visitors last week, reaching
7.3 percent of the total Web audience.
</P>
<P>
   That moved Napster into first place for the first time in PC
Data's list of top online music sites, easily pushing RealNetworks
Inc.'s Web site Real.com into second place.
</P>
<P>
   Napster's surging Internet popularity is exactly what members of
the Recording Industry Association of America hoped to stop.
Napster's popular computer software program allows its 20 million
members to share free copies of songs with each other, a practice
the record industry fears will undercut revenues for companies and
artists.
</P>
<P>
   Last Wednesday, U.S. District Court Judge Marilyn Hall Patel
issued a preliminary injunction ordering Napster to stop all
copyright infringements. But Friday, U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals
judges blocked the injunction until at least mid-September with a
last-minute stay.
</P>
<P>
   The court drama helped Napster.com traffic surge 92 percent
during the week, peaking at 849,000 unique visitors on Friday, the
day the injunction was blocked, according to another online
audience measurement service, Nielsen/NetRatings.
</P>
<P>
   The percentage of people downloading the Napster program doubled
last Friday, when the stay was issued, compared to the number on
July 25, the day before Patel's ruling, Neilsen/NetRatings said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The increase in the downloads of Napster on the heels of the
court stay is a strong indication that digital downloading has hit
critical mass among American Web consumers,'' said Allen Weiner,
vice president of analytical services at NetRatings.
</P>
<P>
   Napster's court problems also helped boost the ratings of Scour,
which operates a program that shares music and movie files. Scour,
which also has been sued for copyright infringement, ranked 10th on
PC Data's latest list in the music category with 1.29 million
visitors. It was the first time Scour cracked the top 10.
</P>
<P>
   Napster was also the top site in PC Data's entertainment
category. The San Mateo startup didn't even rank in that category
the previous week, when the site had only 1.75 million unique
users, or 2.2 percent of the total Web audience.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Napster was not that far behind overall leaders
Microsoft.com, which had 12.8 million users, and Netscape.com, with
10.4 million users.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the last several months, Napster has gravitated in the 1.8
million, sometimes 2 million unique weekly users'' range, said PC
Data Online spokesman Jim Carey. ``This clearly just sent it over
the top. It's clear there is a draw to it now because of the court
case.''
</P>
<P>
   Carey said PC Data Online records show only one jump to match
Napster's huge rise last week. That occurred last April, when
Microsoft.com saw its traffic jump from about 3 million visitors
per week to about 10 million visitors the week the U.S. Justice
Department won its landmark antitrust case against the Redmond,
Wash., software giant.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail Benny Evangelista at bennye(AT)sfgate.com.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
