<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-31 23:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8999 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-WEBAD-HOTEL &LR;      07-31 0909
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WEBAD-HOTEL </SLUG>
  
 WEB-ONLY ADS FOR W HOTEL'S ELITE CLIENTELE
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; BY CAROL EMERT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CHRONICLE STAFF WRITER &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; 2000 San Francisco Chronicle &LR;
</P>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Internet ads get a bad rap. Derided as too small
to attract a passing glance from surfers, banner ads generate
clicks from fewer than one-half of one percent of the people who
see them.
</P>
<P>
   It seems odd, then, that Web ads are the only type of mass
advertising being used to launch a chichi new W Hotel in Silicon
Valley.
</P>
<P>
   Starwood Hotels and Resorts Worldwide, owner of the ultra-hip W
Hotel chain, is eschewing traditional media in favor of a digital
campaign it believes will be a hit with the W's core customers _
wired, wealthy business travelers in their thirties and forties.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want the marketing to stand out in the same way we believe
the hotel stands out,'' said Diane Briskin, director of sales and
marketing for Starwood. ``We're taking a risk with this because if
it doesn't work, it could hamper us. But because (Silicon Valley)
is so tech-driven, we feel it's the best place to make this stab.''
</P>
<P>
   The campaign for W Suites Newark will debut next week. One
hundred of the hotel's 174 rooms opened for business last
Wednesday; the fully wired hotel, where suites go for $199 to $389
per night, will be fully operational in three weeks.
</P>
<P>
   The digital campaign could prove a bellwether in the fledgling
world of online advertising, where technologies change almost daily
and marketers are still trying to figure out how to reach customers
effectively.
</P>
<P>
   One big plus: The two-week campaign costs half as much as
Starwood would have spent in conventional media, Briskin said.
Other W Hotel launches have been advertised in magazines including
Vanity Fair and Travel &AMP; Leisure.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this campaign will be used as a model (by other
advertisers) if it's successful,'' said Mark Stephens, media
director for Lot 21, an interactive ad agency in San Francisco. If
it works, the campaign will demonstrate that the Web truly can
``syphon off money from other media,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   To achieve the most visual impact with surfers, Starwood opted  &LR; 
 &LR; against the most common form of Web advertising _ banner ads, the
small rectangles that appear at the top of Web pages. Instead, it
chose ``superstitials,'' 25-second animated ads that fill about
half the screen.
</P>
<P>
   The ad for the W Suites Newark opens with a hand planting a seed
on a map of Newark. A watering can showers the map and a sunflower
grows and blossoms. Next, text appears describing various amenities
and giving surfers the option of jumping to the W Web site to make
a reservation. Surfers may also sign up for e-mail newsletters or
e-mail copies of the ad to others.
</P>
<P>
   Superstitials, developed by Unicast Communications of New York,
are invisibly ``streamed'' onto a surfer's hard drive and play
automatically when a subsequent page comes up. The ads have a
high-quality, broadcast look and unwind at a constant speed that
does not require wide bandwidth.
</P>
<P>
   Sean Black, an executive with Grey EMedia who helped develop the
W Suites Newark campaign, points to several advantages Web
advertising has over conventional media.
</P>
<P>
   In the case of W Suites Newark, a promotion for hotel guests to
accrue bonus points can be discontinued when the promotion ends, as
opposed to magazine ads, which are static.
</P>
<P>
   The Web ads are also highly targeted. They will be shown on just
five sites, most of which have pronounced skews toward high-income,
technology-oriented business executives: InformIT.com,
Stockmaster.com, Thomasinvest.com, Edgar.com and Time.com. If any
of the sites fails to attract clicks, the ad can easily be switched
to another site.
</P>
<P>
   Even more important from a marketer's standpoint is the ability
to gather information, such as e-mail addresses, that can be used
in future marketing efforts.
</P>
<P>
   And the campaign's ``viral marketing'' component creates
publicity for the hotel at no extra cost. Viral marketing is the
practice of customers forwarding e-mailing promotions to each
other, the digital realm's version of word-of-mouth advertising.
</P>
<P>
   There are also plenty of disadvantages.
</P>
<P>
   While superstitials are becoming more accepted among Web
publishers, they are still accepted on a paltry 250 sites. That's
because superstitials require a different technology than other
types of interactive advertising, and Web site publishers worry
they might muck up their site.
</P>
<P>
   Publishers are also wary of superstitials because of their
potential to annoy users since the ads pop up unexpectedly and
interrupt the surfer's online experience.
</P>
<P>
   Black said less than 1 percent of surfers click to get rid of
Grey's superstitials. The trick is to make sure the ads reach
people who are interested in the brand by running them on highly
targeted sites, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The number who click off the ad is such a minute group of
people that we don't care because the overall results at the end of
the day are so much better'' than with banner ads, Black said.
</P>
<P>
   The number of surfers who click on Grey superstitials ranges as
high as 12 percent of those who see the ads.
</P>
<P>
   Advertisers must also be careful not to show ads too many times
to the same person. The W Suites Newark ad is designed to be shown
a maximum of three times in one day and one time per browser
session, according to Hilary Fadner of Unicast.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
