<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PROF-GIFT </SLUG>
  
 U.S. TO RECEIVE GIFT THAT KEEPS ON SEARCHING
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; BY KELLY YAMANOUCHI &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CHRONICLE STAFF WRITER &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; 2000 San Francisco Chronicle &LR;
</P>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ A University of California at Berkeley professor
plans to give an unusual gift to the federal government: a database
that will handle searches of all of the federal government's Web
pages.
</P>
<P>
   Computer science professor Eric Brewer is building the
``privately financed'' site using search-engine technology he
developed for Inktomi Corp., the Foster City company he co-founded.
</P>
<P>
   Brewer, now chief technology officer and chief scientist for
Inktomi, has formed a foundation to build the database that will be
filled with many as 100 million pages that users can search in less
than a quarter-second, according to federal officials.
</P>
<P>
   The search engine at  &LR; www.firstgov.gov &LR; , which can direct users,
for example, to Web pages such as one that allows them to track
their Social Security benefits, is scheduled to be up and running
in the fall.
</P>
<P>
   Brewer wasn't unavailable for comment but a federal official on
the board overseeing the project speculated Brewer may be doing it
for free in gratitude for the federal government's assistance in
developing Inktomi's Internet search technology.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton said Brewer ``developed one of the most
successful Internet search technologies with the help of government
grants.''
</P>
<P>
   The new Web site is part of a larger project to develop a
``high-speed, high-tech, user-friendly government,'' Clinton said
during a recent Webcast.
</P>
<P>
   The government also plans to develop more government Web pages
as part of the effort. Eventually, Clinton said, people will be
able to compete online for government grants and contracts to buy
goods and services.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail Kelly Yamanouchi at kyamanouchi(AT)sfgate.com.  &LR;
</P>
