<HEADER>
A9002 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k BC-YOUNG0802-COX     07-31 0658
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YOUNG0802-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    If it's smart, GOP won't repeat 1992 debacle
 &HT;    By John Young
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Talk about a contrast in conventions. The last time the
Republicans convened to nominate a George Bush, the Monday-night
headline was that Pat Buchanan had declared a culture war _ we
begin bombing in 5 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   This time? Laura Bush comes before the nation with the
press-stopper: Literacy good. Illiteracy bad.
</P>
<P>
   You might say, in other words, that no news from Night 1 is very
good news for the Republican Party. Or from Night 2, or Night 3.
</P>
<P>
   If George W. Bush was paying attention behind the scenes during
the 1992 convention in Houston's Astrodome, he was learning how not
to win a nation's heart.
</P>
<P>
   You don't win it by repeating the phrase ``family values'' every
other sentence, as speaker after speaker after speaker did in the
Astro-drone. They so cheapened an already two-bit phrase that when
all was said and drummed it couldn't have been weighty to an ear
mite.
</P>
<P>
   What did ``family values'' mean? Was it chastity and bottomless
wells of virtue? The opposite of Bill Clinton with his personal
flaws? One will say that with subsequent events that would cripple
Clinton's administration this litany was fair warning. Yes. And it
was unfortunate that people applauding in the Dome in '92, people
like Newt Gingrich, Bob Livingston, Dan Burton, Henry Hyde and Bob
Bahr, later would have the rhetoric come back and bite them where
it hurts, in ye olde private parts.
</P>
<P>
   Purity and reality
</P>
<P>
   Maybe, with George W.'s own playboy past as inferential fodder
we can put this type of piety aside and consider issues of
governance.
</P>
<P>
   In '92 with Buchanan setting the tone with his bellicose assault
on foreigners and homosexuals, with anti-abortion protesters trying
to shut down Houston women's clinics, the convention was as mean as
it was ponderous.
</P>
<P>
   (It's said that the Houston Astros vacated the Dome this year
because of economic issues. Another theory is that they couldn't
shake the bad vibes left by the GOP convention.)
</P>
<P>
   With the pronounced attempt to portray the party as ``family
values'' incarnate, as America most pure, the most remarkable
moment in '92 may have come when Mary Fisher, a former aide to
Gerald Ford, a mother infected with HIV, stepped to the microphone.
</P>
<P>
   ``Though I am female and contracted this disease in marriage, I
am one with the lonely gay man sheltering a flickering candle from
the cold wind of his family's rejection,'' she said, to a bare
smattering of applause. Or was it jewelry rattling?
</P>
<P>
   That was a singular pause in a gathering that, in rhetorical
texture, couldn't have been more divisive. Bush doesn't want that,
and certainly doesn't need it. His mission this week is to modulate
a media event that will try to put a fuzz-focus on his party's
dagger edges. He has succeeded in helping tone things down already
by removing from the GOP platform a call for an
English-as-official-language law and the denial of automatic
citizenship to children of illegal immigrants born on U.S. soil.
</P>
<P>
   Bush will seek to avoid entirely the abortion issue, although he
can't dodge it forever, witnessed by the unremittingly anti-choice
voting record of his running mate.
</P>
<P>
   Bush will seek to win the presidency as a voice of moderation.
In some ways, therefore, the toughest crowd he faces this week is
not the one in the nation's living rooms but the one inside
Philadelphia's First Union Center.
</P>
<P>
   Bush will be addressing a body that is heavily seasoned with the
hard-right elements that Buchanan was serenading with his ``culture
war'' speech. The Texas delegation, for instance, is teeming with
religious conservatives to whom moderation is no virtue.
</P>
<P>
   And so now, everybody in unison, one, two, three: Literacy good
. . .
</P>
<P>
   E-mail: jyoung(at)wacotrib.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
