<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOP-MRSCLINTON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON DERIDES REPUBLICANS, AND HER OPPONENT, AS EXTREMISTS 
</HEADLINE>
  By SOMINI SENGUPTA   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ As the Republican convention opened on Monday with
appeals to moderate voters, Hillary Rodham Clinton warned an
audience here not to be deceived by the GOP's ``well-scripted
show'' intended to conceal what she called the party's extremist
record.
</P>
<P>
   Mocking Gov. George W. Bush's slogan of ``compassionate
conservatism'' at the National Urban League's annual convention on
Monday in Manhattan, Clinton used especially caustic language to
criticize the Republicans for trying to promote ``political
amnesia,'' and linked her rival in the New York Senate race to
conservative policies favored at the top of the party ticket.
</P>
<P>
   Without using the name of her Republican opponent for the U.S.
Senate, Rep. Rick A. Lazio, Clinton scoffed at his efforts to
present himself as moderate. For the first time in weeks, she
linked Lazio to the reign of Newt Gingrich _ a strategy she seized
upon when Lazio entered the race but then quickly dropped.
</P>
<P>
   ``He goes around calling himself mainstream,'' she said,
mockingly stretching out both syllables. ``I guess his service as a
deputy whip to Newt Gingrich is considered mainstream.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton also reminded her audience of some items from the
Republican record, hammering at the words and deeds of both Bush
and his vice presidential choice, Dick Cheney, and attacking their
plans to keep the convention free of dissent. Republican leaders,
including Bush, have said they would not spend time criticizing
Clinton, a frequent target of some GOP members.
</P>
<P>
   But Clinton did not seem to feel the need to reciprocate.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need leaders who won't just talk the talk of equal
opportunity,'' she said, her voice noticeably hoarse from a week of
intense campaigning for the U.S. Senate seat from New York. ``We
need leaders who have, and are, and will walk the walk with all of
us.''
</P>
<P>
   She repeatedly referred to Cheney as Congressman Cheney _ and
targeted his voting record as a member of Congress in the 1980s. No
less than three times in a 30-minute speech, she noted Cheney's
1986 vote against a resolution urging freedom for Nelson Mandela,
who was in a South African prison.
</P>
<P>
   Cheney has defended his 1986 vote by saying that Mandela's
group, the African National Congress, was then considered a
terrorist organization. He has lately praised Mandela, who became
president of South Africa after the dismantling of apartheid.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton also reminded the audience of Bush's visit to Bob Jones
University _ the South Carolina campus that at the time had banned
interracial dating. And she told them that Bush has said that
Justices Antonin Scalia and Clarence Thomas were his model Supreme
Court justices.
</P>
<P>
   The last comment went far with the crowd, which responded with a
groan. Clinton nodded, pausing for effect. ``We need to make sure
everybody knows that,'' she said, drawing a roar of laughter from
the audience. ``The strategy of the other side is to induce a case
of political amnesia in every one of us,'' she added.
</P>
<P>
   Bryan Flood, a spokesman with the Lazio campaign noted that
invoking Lazio's ties to Gingrich did not work for Clinton in the
past. ``New Yorkers know the Lazio record and they know he's a
mainstream candidate,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
