</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-ARATON-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GRIFFEY'S HOMECOMING IS HALF-EMPTY 
</HEADLINE>
  By HARVEY ARATON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Maybe you can't go home again, as Ken Griffey Jr.
seemed to be suggesting Monday, but Barry Larkin was having no
second thoughts about staying home and missing his opportunity to
play shortstop for the Mets.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they had offered me a multiyear contract, I would have been
here,'' Larkin said, before slipping into his uniform, still and
perhaps forever a Cincinnati Red, to play the Mets on Monday night
at soggy Shea Stadium. ``But it worked out for me. Yes, it did.''
</P>
<P>
   On the day the major league trade deadline mercifully arrived,
sparing paper mills potential inventory depletion from servicing
baseball's rumor mill, Larkin arrived to say, hey, no hard
feelings, the Mets wound up with Mike Bordick, while he secured the
three-year contract extension he'd all but given up on.
</P>
<P>
   He got to stay home, which is all he wanted after a lifetime in
Cincinnati and 14 terrific years with the Reds and what could
possibly be wrong with that? Larkin was still booed by those
unmistakably sophisticated New York baseball fans when he batted in
the first inning, even louder than Griffey, who spurned the Mets
without so much as sleeping on it last December. Then Griffey
forced Seattle to ship him to the team in whose uniform his father
of the same name enjoyed his best days, and signed for less money,
a mere $116.5 million, than the open market would have paid.
</P>
<P>
   It was supposed to be a modern-day triumph of hometown loyalty
over greed, at least until Junior got off to a slow start, the Reds
sank under .500 and stuffed their best pitcher, Denny Neagle, into
George Steinbrenner's bottomless pocket.
</P>
<P>
   Next came the attempted trade of Larkin to the Mets, who wanted
to send him a plane full of welcoming teammates, which he called
``flattering,'' but not the point.
</P>
<P>
   Asked what Griffey had to say during the period it seemed he
might be leaving, Larkin said: ``His response was, `I didn't travel
3,000 miles to come home and play with you for one year,''' Larkin
said. ``He told me he was going, too.''
</P>
<P>
   On the subject of a threat, Griffey said one place he never went
was to the Reds' new owner, Carl Lindner. ``I didn't express that
to management,'' he said, though he also insisted: ``I wouldn't
have deferred as much money as I did to have someone sell off my
teammates. I didn't come here to lose.''
</P>
<P>
   Quite the contrast to the ebullient Larkin, Griffey seemed so
weary in the pregame clubhouse, so dour, you wanted it to all be an
act. No one with that much natural talent and grace should be as
unhappy, feel as unappreciated, as Griffey seemed when he stared
vacantly and whispered his answers as if he were on death row.
</P>
<P>
   He began the game with 32 home runs and 91 runs batted in, power
numbers that no one could quibble with. Yet he was hitting only
.241, and though the Reds had recently climbed over .500 and back
into the Central Division race, they hadn't exactly been the
Seattle Mariners. That's another rub. Junior's old team took some
of the money it saved by not keeping him to hire some pitching.
They're in first place without him and, no matter how logical
baseball minds may avoid casting this as a reflection on him, this
is an extremely sensitive soul who often sees glasses half-empty.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything that's been said this season has been negative,''
he said. ``If I go 4 for 4 and hit three home runs and didn't hit
the fourth one out, it's like I didn't do anything.''
</P>
<P>
   He doesn't recall much positive national response to his signing
with the Reds. He believes the news media has dogged him for eight
months with innuendo and outright lies. He said he has been accused
of everything from signing with the Reds only so his father, a
coach, would become manager to calling up a cable sports network to
complain that another center fielder's highlights were being shown
more than his.
</P>
<P>
   The best thing about playing baseball in Cincinnati? ``Hanging
out with my family,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   It was a good, honest response, except he never had one good
thing to say about playing baseball with the Reds, a small-market
team that, under fan fire, dug deep to keep Larkin, its longtime
linchpin, probably at the cost of future help elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   Griffey said he might have considered the Mets had he not been
given 15 minutes to make up his mind, an account that was disputed
by team officials in Seattle. At 35, the proud owner of a 1990
World Series ring, staying put made all the sense in the world for
Larkin. Junior's another story, though. He may have very well been
better off batting in front of Mike Piazza, in New York.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-31-00 2320EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
