<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-31 23:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9009 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BBN-METS-REDS-NYT     07-31 0674
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-REDS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GRIFFEY AND LARKIN SAY NO TO THE METS ONCE AGAIN 
</HEADLINE>
  By TYLER KEPNER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Two Reds who turned down deals to become Mets _ Ken
Griffey Jr. and Barry Larkin _ turned on New York again Monday
night in Cincinnati's 6-0 victory at Shea Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Griffey went two for five with two runs scored, and Larkin
singled home a run in the seventh. Dante Bichette drove in three
runs for the Reds, whose starter, Scott Williamson, blanked the
Mets for six innings before leaving with a spasm in his left
hamstring.
</P>
<P>
   The loss was the first for the Mets on this homestand, which
opened with six victories.
</P>
<P>
   Three hours before the game, Mets players knew for sure that
they had not added or lost any teammates by Monday's nonwaiver
trading deadline. This, they hope, is the group that will carry
them into the postseason.
</P>
<P>
   When they took the field, on a damp, misty night, they
encountered two Reds who could have been a part of their group.
Griffey and Larkin both vetoed potential deals to the Mets within
the last year. When Larkin struck out in the first inning, a
delighted Mets crowd jeered him for rejecting a trade to New York.
</P>
<P>
   Williamson (4-7) allowed baserunners in each of his innings, but
the Mets were 0 for 6 against him with runners in scoring position.
The right-hander gave up six hits and two walks, striking out three
and outpitching the Mets' Glendon Rusch.
</P>
<P>
   Rusch left in the seventh inning after Pokey Reese reached base
on a fielding error by third baseman Robin Ventura. Larkin singled
off Rick White to bring in the first unearned run Rusch has allowed
this year. The Mets' left-hander worked six innings, allowing four
earned runs on seven hits and a walk as his record dropped to 7-8.
</P>
<P>
   Rusch had allowed only four runs in 19 innings during the second
half of the season. But he matched that total by the third inning
Monday night, mainly because of trouble with the Reds' third and
fourth hitters _ Griffey and Dante Bichette.
</P>
<P>
   Griffey had one hit in 10 career at-bats off Rusch before this
season. But that hit was a homer, and Griffey homered again off
Rusch in April. His hits stayed in the park Monday night, but they
were no less harmful to Rusch.
</P>
<P>
   Chris Stynes led off the game with a single, and after Larkin
struck out, Griffey singled Stynes to third. When Bichette doubled
to the center-field warning track, Griffey came around to score
behind Stynes as the Reds took a 2-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   One of Griffey's few flaws as a player is that he sometimes
slides awkwardly, and he did so Monday night, starting his slide
late and knocking right knees with catcher Mike Piazza. Griffey
limped back to the dugout _ where he saw Bichette score on a
groundout to put the Reds ahead, 3-0 _ but he stayed in the game
and soon did more damage.
</P>
<P>
   With one out in the third, Griffey lined one toward the
right-field corner, good for a double. Bichette singled him home to
increase the Reds' lead to 4-0.
</P>
<P>
   Rusch was having little trouble with the rest of the Reds, and
he resumed his solid pitching immediately. Sean Casey ended the
inning with a double-play grounder, and Rusch held the Reds without
a run or a hit for the next three innings.
</P>
<P>
   But the Mets could not do much with Williamson and they failed
to convert on their chances. With one out in the first, Edgardo
Alfonzo singled to move Derek Bell to second. That brought up
Piazza and stirred the crowd, but Piazza grounded into a double
play.
</P>
<P>
   That at-bat began a string of futility for the Mets. They left
one runner in scoring position in each of the first five innings,
including the second, when Williamson issued two wild pitches that
advanced Ventura two bases. That gave Williamson a
major-league-high 19 wild pitches, matching a Reds record.
</P>
<P>
   Williamson, who was the National League's rookie of the year
last season as a reliever, also walks a lot of hitters, averaging
6.5 walks per nine innings. But he walked just two and threw no
more wild pitches after the second.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
