<SLUG> BC-GOP-CLINTON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN FLORIDA, CLINTON RAISES FUNDS FOR DEMOCRATS AND SNIPES AT GOP 
</HEADLINE>
   By CARL H. LAVIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PALM BEACH, Fla. _ President Bill Clinton took on the
Republicans and their platform Monday in a series of Florida
appearances that raised more than $1.2 million for the Democratic
party and rallied support for his plan to expand Medicare to
provide prescription drug insurance.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking to Medicare beneficiaries at a community center in
Tampa, the president continued his attack on the host of tax cuts
being passed by the Republican-controlled Congress.
</P>
<P>
   ``You may hear, if you turn on the television, the Republicans,
when they meet in Philadelphia in convention, talking about all
their tax-cut bills and how wonderful they'd be for you,'' Clinton
said. ``But what they don't say is that if you take all their
tax-cut proposals in total, it spends the entire projected surplus
of the country for the next 10 years.''
</P>
<P>
   He compared tax-cut legislation being sent to him by Congress to
the choices a diner faces at a well-stocked restaurant: ``When I go
to a cafeteria, everything I see looks good,'' he said, ``but if I
eat it all, I'll get sick.''
</P>
<P>
   Accompanied by Bill Nelson, the Florida insurance commissioner,
who is running for the Senate, Clinton also told Democratic donors
in Tampa, and later in Palm Beach, that the Republican goal was to
blur the differences between the parties on health care, the
economy, gun control, the environment and other issues that matter
to voters.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their strategy is to talk about compassion,'' and ``it's a
brilliant strategy,'' Clinton said. ``It's a pretty package, and
they're hoping if they wrap it tight enough, nobody will open it
before Christmas.''
</P>
<P>
   At a fund-raising reception here for Nelson, the president said
that the Democratic strategy should be to stay positive _ ``You
don't have to say a bad word about our opponents,'' he said _ and
to explain to voters how the parties differ.
</P>
</TEXT>
