<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-31 23:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9015 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u p BC-CMV-GOP-RDP-HNS &LR;      07-31 1470
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CMV-GOP-RDP-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAURA BUSH, POWELL INTRODUCE BUSH'S APPROACH TO EDUCATION WITH
FAMILY TOUCH 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By ALAN BERNSTEIN 
and BENNETT ROTH 
c.2000 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ Laura Bush and retired Gen. Colin Powell brocaded
Gov. George W. Bush's approach to education issues with a family
touch and the feeling of brotherhood Monday.
</P>
<P>
   But Powell, parting with Bush, also scolded his fellow
Republicans for opposing affirmative action policies.
</P>
<P>
   It was Episode One of the summer drama mini-series known as the
Republican National Convention. Fitting the party's efforts to
reach beyond the stereotype of its core supporters, neither of the
two star players was a white man.
</P>
<P>
   Laura Bush said her husband, the Texas governor who once served
as managing partner of the Texas Rangers baseball team, ``won't
lose sight of home plate'' in a crusade for student literacy and
other advancements. She said he is a purposeful man who can inspire
the nation.
</P>
<P>
   Powell, positioned for a cabinet job if Bush wins the
presidency, was introduced by the candidate in a live video feed
from the campaign trail in Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   The retired general praised Bush's ``compassionate
conservative'' message and his record on education.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know that he can help bridge our racial divides,'' said
Powell, the first black chairman of the military's Joint Chief of
Staff and a key strategizer in the Persian Gulf War.
</P>
<P>
   Briefly putting aside the evening's tender tone, though, Powell
said the party must reach out to minorities ``not just during an
election year.''
</P>
<P>
   Blacks get cynical, Powell said, when ``some in our party miss
no opportunity to roundly and loudly condemn affirmative action
that helped a few thousand black kids get an education, but you
hardly hear a whimper when it's `affirmative action' for lobbyists
who load our federal tax codes with preferences for special
interests.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush's wife, promised by her husband 23 years ago that she would
never have to give a political speech, and Powell, delivering a
kind of encore of his speech on opening night of the 1996 GOP
convention, closed an evening officially dedicated to education.
Voters have indicated that education is their top concern.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, citing improvements in Texas public school test scores,
has said he has established a record of education reform.
</P>
<P>
   But before Monday night's speakers opened their mouths,
Democratic officeholders gathered at a union hall here and said
Republicans were putting on a false front.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Sen. Tom Harkin of Iowa, a potential running mate for the
Democratic presidential contender, Vice President Al Gore, cited
the oil industry background of Bush and his ticket mate, former
Defense Secretary Dick Cheney.
</P>
<P>
   ``This Texaco ticket hears oil companies loud and clear, but
when it comes to kids who can't get a fair start to life, they
simply smile and nod and do nothing,'' Harkin said.
</P>
<P>
   New Orleans Mayor Marc Morial urged voters to look beyond ``a
wonderfully orchestrated picture of black and brown and white
faces'' at the podium and examine the delegates, who are
overwhelmingly conservative white males.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats also announced they were airing two TV commercials
criticizing Bush for resisting an expansion of a childrens' health
program in Texas and for appointing a chemical company lobbyist to
enforce environmental laws.
</P>
<P>
   Inside the sports arena that houses the convention, however, the
personal politics practiced by Laura Bush and Powell was
unbothered.
</P>
<P>
   The governor's wife, a former librarian and Houston teacher,
mentioned the couple's college-bound twin daughters, Jenna and
Barbara. The twins, generally kept out of the campaign spotlight,
watched their mother's speech from the audience.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted to teach our children what our parents taught us,
that reading is entertaining and interesting and important,'' she
said. ``And one of the major reasons George is running for
president is to make sure every child in America has that same
opportunity to grow up reading.''
</P>
<P>
   Laura Bush said she learned from watching her husband fight
state legislative battles and suffer through losing baseball
seasons that ``his core principles will not change with the winds
of politics or fame or fortune or misfortune.''
</P>
<P>
   When the governor grew up in Midland, she said, he ``developed
the strength and the consistency of conviction.''
</P>
<P>
   The governor's parents, former President George Bush and first
lady Barbara Bush, moved the family from Midland to Houston as
their eldest son turned 13.
</P>
<P>
   The former White House occupants were in the convention audience
Monday night as their daughter-in-law spoke. She said that if she
becomes first lady of the nation, she will make early childhood
development programs one of her priorities.
</P>
<P>
   Powell promoted Bush to the hilt Monday night, but he also
seemed to challenge the party's appetite for ``law and order''
stances. Bush pushed for a tougher juvenile justice system in his
campaigns for governor.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's time to stop building jails in America and get back to
the task of building our children,'' Powell said. ``Our children
are not the problem, they are our future. They are America's
promise.''
</P>
<P>
   America's Promise is the name of a children's advocacy group
headed by Powell, who has resisted Republicans' encouragement to
run for president or vice president.
</P>
<P>
   In his 1996 speech, Powell drew scattered bos and hisses from
GOP delegates when he endorsed abortion rights and affirmative
action, which are opposed by Bush and the Republican Party.
</P>
<P>
   Without the stagecraft that Republican planners are using to try
to make this year's convention entertaining, delegates adopted the
Republican Platform 2000 without debate Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   Bolstering the night's convention theme, ``Opportunity With a
Purpose: Leave No Child Behind,'' the platform rescinded the GOP's
call for abolishment of the Department of Education. The change was
brought about at Bush's behest in hearings last week.
</P>
<P>
   The platform contains an unprecedented GOP outreach to
minorities and immigrants.
</P>
<P>
   ``We offer not only a new agenda, but also a new approach _ a
vision of a welcoming society in which all have a place,'' it says.
``To all Americans, particularly immigrants and minorities, we send
a clear message: this is a party of freedom and progress, and it is
your home.''
</P>
<P>
   But the platform champions traditional GOP issues such as tax
cuts, and highlights Bush's goal of providing government aid for
charitable and religious organizations that run social programs.
The platform also sticks with Republican opposition to abortion,
gay rights and sex education.
</P>
<P>
   In another piece of official business that was overshadowed by
featured speakers, musical entertainment and a professional
wrestler, Bush's name was officially submitted Monday for the
presidential nomination.
</P>
<P>
   The deed was done by Lt. Gov. Rick Perry, who chairs the Texas
delegation and would become governor if Bush wins the Nov. 7
presidential election.
</P>
<P>
   ``I proudly place the name of the current governor of the great
state of Texas and the next president of the United States into
nomination, George W. Bush,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The gesture was uncontested, even by supporters of U.S. Sen.
John McCain of Arizona, who won seven Republican primary states
before conceding the nomination to Bush in March. McCain told his
delegates here Sunday to support Bush.
</P>
<P>
   The GOP commenced its novel ``rolling roll call'' of states
Monday night, registering the nominating votes of delegates from
Alabama to Iowa in alphabetical order. Former candidate Alan Keyes,
more conservative than Bush, got a few votes.
</P>
<P>
   The process continues piecemeal through Thursday, abandoning the
tradition of calling the roll in a single night and avoiding a
tedious process that would be ignored by edited broadcasts.
</P>
<P>
   Voter surveys made public Monday showed Bush ahead of Gore, but
not by as much as was indicated in competing polls released the day
before.
</P>
<P>
   A Los Angeles Times poll showed Bush with 44 percent and Gore
with 39 percent of the support of registered voters, less than the
10-point lead documented by the same poll in June. A new NBC-Wall
Street Journal poll showed Bush at 44 percent and Gore at 38
percent.
</P>
<P>
   Karl Rove, Bush's Austin-based political strategist, said during
a breakfast with reporters that the race would probably tighten.
</P>
<P>
   ``The election is far from over,'' Rove said. ``This race is
going to be by Labor Day single digits one way or the other ...
there are going to be points after the Democratic convention where,
in all likelihood, we're going to be behind.''
</P>
<P>
   The Democratic convention starts Aug. 14 in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
