<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-31 23:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9016 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-TV-DAILYSHOW-POLITICS     07-31 0913
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-DAILYSHOW-POLITICS-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CRITIC'S NOTEBOOK: COMEDY CENTRAL'S NEWS PARODY AT THE CONVENTION
</HEADLINE>
 By JULIE SALAMON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   When George W. Bush announced that Dick Cheney would be his
running mate, Jon Stewart drily observed:
</P>
<P>
   ``Cheney has opposed the Equal Rights Amendment, busing and
abortion, but he is in favor of prayer in schools. So he should
really help Bush open up the Republican Party to the
much-sought-after white conservative vote.''
</P>
<P>
   This week, beginning Tuesday night, the anchor of Comedy
Central's news parody, ``The Daily Show With Jon Stewart,'' is
taking his frisky brand of political commentary to the Republican
Convention. Stewart is a comedian, not a journalist, and this may
prove a distinct advantage over the network anchors, who must
report the events as they occur, no matter how dull.
</P>
<P>
   At a time when politicians have become cautious and bland,
political commentary is having a heyday, especially late at night,
with David Letterman, Jay Leno, Bill Maher and Stewart, whose show
is on at 11 p.m. (with several rebroadcasts). In recent months,
``The Daily Show'' has been attracting a lot of media attention
with its election coverage, especially since signing on Bob Dole
and Robert Reich, the former labor secretary, as convention
commentators. But for many people _ especially teen-age boys _ the
program has also become a regular source of news and a way to
deconstruct daily headlines with fashionable irony.
</P>
<P>
   The network says that its cockeyed coverage attracts about
500,000 viewers per show, or 2 million during its four-night week,
a sizable audience for cable. Though its attention is now on
politics, ``The Daily Show'' lampoons science, culture and business
as well. For example, its writers recently jumped on the megadeal
in which Nabisco, a food company, is being acquired by Philip
Morris, a food company that is also a cigarette company. With a
studied look of disbelief and using the warning label on a package
of cigarettes as a prop, Stewart described the deal as combining
Nabisco, ``the people who bring you Oreos, Ritz crackers and Cream
of Wheat,'' and Philip Morris, ``the people who bring you low birth
weight, infant mortality and, oh, the old favorite, emphysema.''
</P>
<P>
   Because ``The Daily Show'' is far more enjoyable when compared
with the traditional newscasts, it could actually encourage young
people to watch the nightly news _ if only to make fun of it.
Certainly the network news programs could use the jolt. Look what's
advertised on them: painkillers, laxatives, denture adhesives,
cholesterol medications, weedkiller and Chevrolets. ``The Daily
Show'' is sponsored by cool cars, cell phones and movies _ and its
big corporate sponsors for its ``Indecision 2000'' election
coverage include Yahoo, Volkswagen and Snapple.
</P>
<P>
   At its best, Stewart's show offers a satiric interpretation of
events that touches on larger truths and even larger fears. At its
worst, it's silly and crude (though some of the most sophomoric
bits are, admittedly, the funniest, like a recent raucous feature
on the Queen Mother).
</P>
<P>
   Compare ``The Daily Show'' coverage of the human genome project
with coverage by the network news programs. Tom Brokaw began the
NBC report like this: ``A day for the ages at the White House
today, that's how President Clinton described it.''
</P>
<P>
   Over on ABC, Kevin Newman, sitting in for Peter Jennings, said,
``It isn't often we can begin with something like this: The main
story is a day for the ages.''
</P>
<P>
   Dan Rather at CBS was more circumspect. After declaring that
``the recipe for humankind'' will ``revolutionize the diagnosis,
treatment and prevention of disease,'' he cautioned that genetic
mapping ``also raises questions about what is medically possible,
desirable and ethical.''
</P>
<P>
   Stewart, though, reacted the way many of us did upon
encountering the mysterious visuals that accompanied the genome
story on every broadcast (including ``The Daily Show'') _
indecipherable computer images, acres of test vials, weird helixes
and symbols. ``Scientists crack the human genetic code,'' he
announced, ``and yes, it will be used for pure evil.''
</P>
<P>
   Stewart, 37, doesn't have a squared-off anchor physique or an
anchor's height (he's 5-foot-7) or a deep anchor voice, but he has
fine comic timing (which includes a good repertory of eye rolls and
suppressed giggles) and lots of self-deprecating charm. He projects
no need to appear unassailable.
</P>
<P>
   Like the network anchors, however, he has a book out, and these
books flag the difference between them and him. The Big Three have
chosen portentous topics like ``The Century'' (Peter Jennings),
``The Greatest Generation'' (Tom Brokaw) and ``People of the
Century: One Hundred Men and Women Who Shaped the Last One Hundred
Years'' (Dan Rather). Stewart's book, a collection of his essays,
is called ``Naked Pictures of Famous People.''
</P>
<P>
   When Middle East peace talks broke down, Stewart announced the
news like this: ``Good news for war buffs. The Middle East peace
talks have ended in failure.'' Further into the broadcast, he
explained, ``It soon became apparent that Barak was from Mars and
Arafat was from Venus.'' Of course, Stewart is spared the gruesome
necessities that go along with being a real television journalist.
The terrible Concorde crash that dominated the network news last
week was a nonstory for ``The Daily Show.'' Some news events can't
be mocked.
nn
</P>
<P>
   Even more than its ``Saturday Night Live'' model, ``The Daily
Show'' is structured basically like a regular newscast, with a half
hour of headline news, features and commentary. The features aim to
be far more absurd than the networks _ like a segment by Vance De
Generes (comedian Ellen's brother) on ``The Blackout of 2000,''
when Manhattan's Upper East Side experienced 20 minutes of reduced
power, which actually forced some people to turn off their
air-conditioners and reset their VCRs.
</P>
<P>
   In another feature, ``The Daily Show'' used the same video that
ABC News did in its account of a Russian immigrant family in
Brooklyn that is fighting to keep custody of a pet monkey named
Cookie. (The animal is a Cercopithecus diana monkey, which is an
endangered species.) But while ABC's Bill Blakemore offered a
sympathetic yet balanced report, Stewart didn't hide his
appreciation of the situation's absurdity. ``Experts across the
board support the state's position,'' he said, ``saying Cookie is a
rare beast of the wild who deserves to live as nature intended _ in
the Detroit Zoo.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, the show's humorists are hard pressed to match the
eccentric wit of ABC's Robert Krulwich, whose excellent report on
the human genome uncovered the amazing overlap between humans and
other species _ not just chimpanzees, as expected, but cows,
roosters and baker's yeast.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Daily Show'' is also a talk show, with a live audience and
with a regular spot reserved for guests, most often actors,
musicians or writers on promotional tour. In these segments,
Stewart's humor is more piquant than acid, and he unashamedly fawns
over his sexy female guests while revealing embarrassing details
about his own childhood and dating life (or former dating life _ he
married recently). He was even nice and respectful to Joe Eszterhas
and let him read from his nasty book ``American Rhapsody.'' Still,
Stewart did greet the shaggy, overweight, unbuttoned guest with a
gentle barb. ``This looks like a parole meeting,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   It's no small feat to pull off this eclectic vision of breaking
news, which relies on film clips and graphics to tell its stories.
In addition to its crew of field reporters and commentators, ``The
Daily Show'' has a large backstage contingent of writers, producers
and technicians. The show is sending 94 people to the Philadelphia
convention. But casting Stewart, who also writes much of his own
material, as the anchor 18 months ago _ replacing Craig Kilborn _
has proved to be the crucial ingredient to the 4-year-old program's
success. Ratings have increased 43 percent since he took over.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly his convention coverage won't be predictable. On the
day of the vice presidential announcement, Stewart showed a video
clip in which Bush explained his choice of Cheney, who had been
running the vice presidential screening process.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was impressed by the thoughtful and thorough way he
approached his mission,'' Bush said emotionally, ``and then I
realized the person who was best qualified to be my vice
presidential nominee was working by my side.''
</P>
<P>
   At that Stewart turned to the camera. ``And Bush added,'' he
said earnestly, ```and once (Cheney) took off his glasses and let
his hair down, I also realized he was beautiful.''' Who knows,
maybe the Republican Convention can be fun.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-31-00 2330EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000731.0494 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-31 23:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9021 &Cx1f; tta-z
u p BC-NJ-GOVERNOR-1STLD-WRI     07-31 1051
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NJ-GOVERNOR-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TORRICELLI DROPS HIS BID FOR NEW JERSEY GOVERNOR 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: SUBS 2nd graf to change `16 of the last 20 years' to `most of
the last two decades.') 
By DAVID KOCIENIEWSKI   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. _ Just three weeks after throwing New Jersey's
Democratic Party into chaos by making a bid for governor of New
Jersey, Sen. Robert Torricelli abruptly abandoned the race Monday
after an array of prominent Democrats said they would not support
him.
</P>
<P>
   Torricelli, the chairman of the Democratic Senatorial Campaign
Committee, which is coordinating 32 Senate races across the nation,
had asserted that his national stature as a congressional power
broker gave Democrats the best chance to retake the governor's
mansion, which has been controlled by Republicans for most of the
last two decades.
</P>
<P>
   But after prominent Democrats, including Mayor Sharpe James of
Newark, announced that they would endorse his rival, Jim McGreevey,
in the election next year, Torricelli said that he was ending his
candidacy.
</P>
<P>
   Torricelli acknowledged Monday that he was ``humbled'' by his
failure to generate widespread grass-roots support, but said he
could not simultaneously run in a gubernatorial primary while
carrying out his duties heading Democratic Senate efforts.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was probably somewhat naive,'' Torricelli said of his plan
to quickly win support from party leaders and wrest the nomination
from McGreevey before the Democratic National Convention in
mid-August. ``I thought that people would put their own interests
aside to work toward the goal of something larger.''
</P>
<P>
   McGreevey, who nearly defeated Gov. Christie Whitman in 1997,
has been working ever since to build support for another attempt at
the governor's office.
</P>
<P>
   But many political experts said Torricelli himself was to blame
for his lukewarm reception by party leaders, whose support is
crucial in New Jersey primaries because they determine which
candidate's name appears on the party line. During his rapid ascent
in Washington, Torricelli's sharp tongue and hot temper have made
enemies of many Democrats who were only too eager to pay him back
by rallying behind McGreevey. Torricelli's widely publicized
investment in several private stock deals has also hurt his
standing among voters, according to recent public opinion polls.
And his 1996 Senate campaign, which is now entangled in a federal
investigation that has brought guilty pleas from six contributors,
was also a political liability, according to a private poll that
the state party conducted over the weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Clifford Zukin, a political science professor at Rutgers
University, said the decision to withdraw would seriously damage
Torricelli's standing within the party and would be at least a
temporary setback to any presidential ambitions he might harbor.
</P>
<P>
   ``For a politician as seasoned as Torricelli, this is a huge
misstep,'' Zukin said. ``He put a number of powerful Democrats into
a very difficult position by entering this thing, which means he
was going for it. So for him to drop out, this is a fundamental
miscalculation.''
</P>
<P>
   Torricelli turned New Jersey politics upside down three weeks
ago, when he began lobbying county chairmen and labor leaders to
support his quest for the party's nomination for governor in 2001.
The governor's office in New Jersey, with broad powers, is
considered one of the most powerful in the country, and the post is
considered the supreme prize in state politics.
</P>
<P>
   Although McGreevey had already gathered the support of many
Democratic leaders and raised $3.2 million for the state party in
late June, Torricelli contended that his candidacy could unite the
state's Democratic Party, which is engaged in a feud so bitter that
leaders from South Jersey now refuse to meet with their
counterparts from North Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   But McGreevey, the mayor of Woodbridge, refused to be muscled
aside. With the help of his political patrons, state Sens. John A.
Lynch and Raymond J. Lesniak, McGreevey locked up the support of
the labor leaders and party chairmen he has courted assiduously
since 1997 and prevented Torricelli from gaining endorsements from
all seven counties in South Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   Torricelli won the backing of some labor leaders and
endorsements in Camden, Morris, Bergen and Burlington counties. As
recently as last Friday, Torricelli's closest advisers predicted
that he would win the endorsement of party leaders in populous
Essex and Hudson counties early this week and gain a stranglehold
on the nomination.
</P>
<P>
   But over the weekend, the state party's polling found that
McGreevey, who has run almost nonstop for the last six years, led
Torricelli among likely primary voters by 35 percent to 31 percent.
When asked whether the controversies surrounding the senator's
personal finances and campaign fund-raising would affect their
decision, more than 20 percent of likely voters said it would make
them less likely to support Torricelli, said a party official, who
spoke on condition of anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   When James announced his endorsement Monday, along with other
Essex County leaders, including state Senate Minority Leader
Richard J. Codey, it was clear that Torricelli would face a bitter
and divisive primary. The state party chairman, Tom Giblin, said he
was grateful that Torricelli decided to withdraw rather than
further fracture the party, and said Democrats could now focus on
helping Al Gore win the state's presidential vote and electing Jon
Corzine to the U.S. Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Despite McGreevey's victory however, there were few signs that
the various factions of the party might resolve their differences
soon.
</P>
<P>
   At the news conference announcing the endorsements, McGreevey,
42, took a swipe at Torricelli.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Democratic Party is greater than any individual's
political ambitions,'' he said. When Torricelli later withdrew from
the race, McGreevey did not return repeated telephone calls seeking
comment.
</P>
<P>
   In announcing his withdrawal from the race, Torricelli was
sparing in his praise for McGreevey and refused to offer an
endorsement. Instead, the senator mentioned two U.S.
representatives who might consider seeking the nomination, Bill
Pascrell and Frank Pallone, although most party leaders now
consider that unlikely.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
