u s BC-BBO-CHASS-COLUMN-NYT     07-31 0929
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-CHASS-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: RIDING THE WAYVE IN A TRADING FRENZY
</HEADLINE>
 By MURRAY CHASS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The trade deadline is supposed to be for contenders. Does that
mean the Chicago Cubs, who traded for Rondell White, consider
themselves contenders?
</P>
<P>
   Only four games from first place when Monday night's games
began, the Cincinnati Reds suddenly appear to be contenders. Does
that mean they blundered by trading their No. 1 starter, Denny
Neagle, for four minor leaguers a few weeks ago?
</P>
<P>
   Why do the Atlanta Braves consistently make brilliant trades?
Why were they able to extract B.J. Surhoff, a solid veteran, from
Baltimore when the Yankees could not?
</P>
<P>
   The deadline passed at 4 p.m. Monday so it's safe to come up for
air, at least until later this month when contenders begin making
waiver deals in time to make players eligible for postseason
rosters. But Monday's dizzying flurry of trades that climaxed a
four-day cascade of deals was stunning.
</P>
<P>
   Teams made nine trades involving 29 players, outdoing Friday's
flurry of activity that produced six trades involving 25 players.
Adding in the weekend activity, teams traded 69 players in 20
transactions, ensuring good scorecard sales all over the country in
the coming weeks.
</P>
<P>
   The Reds did not join the list of traders Monday, though it was
not for a lack of trying. They were part of discussions that, if
concluded successfully, would have produced a four-team trade that
would have plunked Pedro Astacio into the Reds' starting rotation.
Astacio, whom the Yankees had also pursued, would have replaced
Neagle, whom the Yankees successfully pursued.
</P>
<P>
   ``We tried to sign Neagle and we couldn't so we traded him,''
said General Manager Jim Bowden of the Reds. ``Same with Larkin. We
didn't want to get stuck with draft choices who might never play in
the majors. We traded two, signed one.''
</P>
<P>
   Bowden referred to Barry Larkin, who was at Shea Stadium Monday
night as the Reds' shortstop. Had he accepted the trade the teams
made, he would have been the Mets' shortstop, but he didn't and
instead signed a contract extension, which the Reds had said they
would not give him.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were going to sign them or trade them,'' Bowden said. He
added that he was not second-guessing himself for Neagle now that
the Reds had improved their playoff chances. ``We'd do it again,''
he said. ``We know we don't have to worry about free agents
leaving. The same team can come back next year and play.''
</P>
<P>
   Bowden went after Astacio because he is signed beyond this year
and could have been traded elsewhere next winter. Besides the Reds
and the Colorado Rockies, the four-way trade would have included
Toronto and Oakland. Presumably, in a pitcher-studded transaction,
Kevin Appier would have gone from Oakland to Toronto, Chris
Carpenter from Toronto to Colorado, Astacio from Colorado to
Cincinnati and Scott Williamson from Cincinnati to Oakland.
</P>
<P>
   But that was just one of the thousands of discussions that never
reached fruition. Another was the Yankees' desire to place White in
left field. First they wanted him, then they were wary of a damaged
knee, then they were said to have made a late bid Sunday to get
him. By then, however, the Cubs had struck opportunistically.
Despite the fact that the Cubs had won 15 of their previous 19
games and had leaped from 16 1/2 games from first to 8 1/2, they
did not obtain White with the idea of contending for the National
League Central championship.
</P>
<P>
   ``We very much were focused on making ourselves as competitive
as possible for 2001 and beyond,'' said Andy MacPhail, back in the
trenches as the Cubs' acting general manager. ``While a player on
the disabled list could be a risk for a contender, it's not a risk
for us. We felt we had a unique opportunity to land a high-caliber
player who can help us be a competitive team from 2001 forward.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cubs, however, did not want to take White without working
out a contract extension. He rejected a four-year offer, but the
Cubs exercised his 2001 option for $4 million, then agreed to a
two-year, $14 million extension that White, if he has 502 plate
appearances next season, can accept or reject, which would allow
him to become a free agent.
</P>
<P>
   In last Friday's trading frenzy, the Cleveland Indians, a
distant second in their quest to win a sixth successive division
title, turned over 20 percent of their roster in a matter of hours.
The Braves, who have a solid division lead, have nevertheless
created the same ratio of change in recent weeks.
</P>
<P>
   They traded for Andy Ashby for their starting rotation, they
signed Scott Kamieniecki and Stan Belinda, who had recently been
released, for their bullpen, they claimed Paul Bako to be a backup
catcher and Monday they acquired Surhoff for the outfield position
that Reggie Sanders did not fill as they had expected.
</P>
<P>
   The Surhoff trade was just another example of the brilliant work
John Schuerholz has done as the Braves' general manager. (Part of
his work was not trading John Rocker to Cleveland, a deal that had
been reported as having been virtually done.) The Yankees wanted
Surhoff but did not satisfy the Orioles' desires or demands. The
Braves did.
</P>
<P>
   Chances are the feelings of the Baltimore owner, Peter Angelos,
toward his Yankee counterpart, George Steinbrenner, had something
to do with the Orioles' decision to send Surhoff to Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   The decision affects the Mets as much as it does the Yankees.
Surhoff's presence in the Braves' lineup will make them tougher for
the Mets to catch.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-31-00 2347EDT &QL; 
