<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-31 23:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9041 &Cx1f; tib-z
u k BC-COLLINS-COLUMN-1STLD-     07-31 0801
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COLLINS-COLUMN-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: GOP'S SUMMER OF LOVE 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: Subs 5th graf to drop `Senate' before candidates, because
house candidates also spoke; subs third to last graf, Actually,
this ... to add Powell's swipe at lobbyists.)  
By GAIL COLLINS    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ Thousands of Republican activists walked into the
maw of the Philadelphia convention Monday to begin their
reprocessing. They arrived here as well-to-do white conservatives,
a number of whom think trigger locks are unconstitutional and
Social Security is a socialist scheme. But by Thursday night they
are going to be nothing but a big, squishy bowl of inclusion that
likes big hugs all around.
</P>
<P>
   Their reorientation program, otherwise known as the Republican
National Convention, consists mainly of listening to: (a) blacks
and Latinos talking about upward mobility; (b) white women talking
about tax cuts; (c) the kinds of celebrities Bob Dole was
complaining about in 1996; and (d) single moms, people who have
overcome disabilities, people who are at least taking regular
medication.
</P>
<P>
   After an opening program that included a blind man who recited
the Pledge of Allegiance (``He has climbed four of the world's
highest mountains.''), a black woman who sang ``The Star-Spangled
Banner'' (``Gloria is a well-known and forceful advocate for the
homeless.'') and a Latino party activist who cried ``Puerto Rico I
love you!,'' the delegates settled back to wait for the evening's
big prime-time hour, which differed from what preceded in that the
people on the platform were famous women and minorities.
</P>
<P>
   In producing a convention that looks like America, George W.
Bush has manufactured one that looks nothing whatsoever like his
party. It's going to be hard to top the woman who ``won the Miss
America pageant with an insulin pump under her evening gown.''
</P>
<P>
   The convention did grudgingly provide a few minutes of
cable-only air time Monday to some of the Republican candidates
from hotly contested districts. The Senate hopefuls were hopefully
off-message _ middle-aged white men in suits complaining about
their opponents, liberal judges and Hillary Clinton's health care
plan.
</P>
<P>
   Outside of abortion and gun control, the platform has been
rewritten to cover all bases while offending no feelings. In one
stroke of genius, the framers scrapped the old, noninclusive call
for elimination of the Department of Education and the National
Endowment for the Arts in favor of: ``There are too many
departments and agencies.'' Who could argue with that? And who
could not agree with Tommy Thompson, the platform committee
chairman, who told the convention, ``Our title says it all:
Renewing America's Purpose Together.''
</P>
<P>
   In their drive to refashion themselves into nonthreatening
winners, Republicans are laying waste to anything that's left of
the English language as a meaningful political tool. As a public
speaker, Bush is naturally incoherent, and his genius is his
ability to sound both sincere and indecipherable. ``If you don't
know what you're supposed to know, we'll make sure you do early
before it's too late,'' he said the other day, discussing education
policy in Kentucky. He's still out campaigning in the heartland,
making his way slowly, slowly toward Philadelphia. The crowds are
enthusiastic, and the message is invariable: If you breathe, here's
your man.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are some people who think power resides in Washington
and that's where the most important people are,'' said Rep. Anne
Northup at a rally in Louisville. ``But the truth is, the most
important people are every American, up and down every street.
These are the people that go to work every day. They care about
their children.''
</P>
<P>
   This seems a little tough on the important people who live in
Washington. (None of whom, of course, have anything whatsoever to
do with this convention. The skyboxes are reserved solely for the
homeless.) Do high-priced lobbyists not bleed? Do they not get up
and go to work every day, and hug their children at night?
</P>
<P>
   Actually, this convention hasn't had much to say about lobbyists
_ except one really nifty swipe by Gen. Colin Powell. They've been
lumped in with the Christian right's agenda as the Reality That
Dare Not Speak Its Name.
</P>
<P>
   There are still a few people worried about John McCain's
prime-time moment Tuesday night. McCain has fallen in the tank for
the Bush campaign so often over the last few days that his suit is
shrinking. But what would happen if his evil spirit took over and
he launched into a bout of truth-telling about the relationship
between the Republican Party and big money?
</P>
<P>
   At this convention, not much. Everybody would probably start
singing ``Michael, Row the Boat Ashore,'' and drown him out.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
