<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KING-E-TALE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STEPHEN KING PROMISES TO CONTINUE E-TALE AFTER NEAR BREAK-EVEN IN
FIRST WEEK 
</HEADLINE>
   By DAVID D. KIRKPATRICK   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A week into the horror writer Stephen King's closely watched
experiment with self-publishing on the Internet, King said Monday
that he is about to break even.
</P>
<P>
   Publishers are eager to see how many people download the first
chapter of King's new electronic novel, ``The Plant,'' about a
vampiric vine's assault on a publishing house, in part because the
venture tests the proposition that marketing and distribution via
the Web can reduce authors' dependence on conventional publishers,
at least for famous writers with plenty of money and fans.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement on his Web site, King estimated that readers
downloaded 152,132 copies in the first seven days, and he promised
that he would continue writing new installments, at least for now.
</P>
<P>
   He had asked readers voluntarily to pay him a dollar for each
chapter downloaded, and had said he would stop writing if he did
not receive payments for 75 percent of them. But King reported that
116,200 had paid or promised to pay, meeting his threshold to
continue writing. He said 93,200 had already paid by credit card
through Amazon.com, which is collecting for him.
</P>
<P>
   Estimating the proportion of downloads by readers who are paying
required some finesse, said William Thornton, who operates the
site. He said that readers had downloaded a total of 227,000
copies, but some were lost to user error and had to be repeated. To
account for repeats, King adjusted his assessment down to a number
he considered ``fair,'' Thornton said.
</P>
<P>
   After just seven days, ``The Plant'' will soon be in the black.
King said he spent about $124,150 on his self-publishing effort,
including two advertisements, in Publishers Weekly and USA Today.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for Conxion Corp., a computer server company that is
handling the downloads, said each download cost less than 2 cents.
With $116,000 in payments promised, after seven days King is out
roughly $10,000. He has few additional costs, and will soon be
earning a profit on his experiment.
</P>
<P>
   On his Web site, King estimated that if he wrote 10 or 11
chapters, his readers might ultimately download 1,673,452
individual installments and pay him a dollar for each. ``Do the
math,'' he wrote. ``It's pretty good math, if people keep coming
back.''
</P>
<P>
   The next installment appears this month.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
